{"type":"text","timestamp":1777794579667,"sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","part":{"id":"prt_decd070040010AdL97DqKKcZaj","messageID":"msg_deccd529a001kpjDj5j5TMIlZh","sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","type":"text","text":"Looking at the extensive LESSONS file, I see a pattern emerging:\n- Winning hypotheses (r1s0, r4s2) either **collapse genuinely duplicated hardware** or **add a truly parallel earlier-stage path**.\n- Losing hypotheses (r4s1, r5s1, r7s1, r8s1, r9s0, r9s2) restructure already-CSE'd cones — Yosys on GW2AR has already found local optima.\n- Struct/pipeline-register edits destabilize formal (r4s0, r5s1, r5s2, r6s0, r6s1, r7s0, r7s2, r8s0).\n\nLet me look at the recent log to confirm no one has tried a forward_unit simplification:","time":{"start":1777794576388,"end":1777794579665}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777794579704,"sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_016WmYFJDyUdjQQTkubv8Q2h","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -l \"forward_unit|x0|rd.*!= 5.b0\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -5","description":"Search log for forward_unit or x0 mentions"},"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","metadata":{"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","exit":0,"description":"Search log for forward_unit or x0 mentions","truncated":false},"title":"Search log for forward_unit or x0 mentions","time":{"start":1777794579699,"end":1777794579702}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm analyzing what micro_opt hypothesis to propose for the bench core—the current best fitness is 387.98 compared to a baseline of 301.04, built on the winning JAL fast-path from the previous run. Recent attempts have all regressed, and the lessons document is clear about what approaches to avoid.\n\nLooking at the actual critical paths and what's worked before, the ALU's shared multiplier and the JAL fast-path were the big wins. I'm considering the forward_unit's priority encoder, the hazard stall logic, or the immediate generator as potential targets. The imm_gen particularly stands out—it's a 5-way case statement that could potentially be simplified since most instruction types (LOAD, OP-IMM, JALR, SYSTEM) share the same I-type pattern, while only STORE, BRANCH, LUI/AUIPC, and JAL need their own formats.\n\nThe classical approach would be to express imm_gen as bit-wise muxes driven by a few control signals from the decoder, but that risks adding wiring or requiring structural changes to id_ex_t. Another angle is the forward_unit's nested priority logic for fwd_rs1 and fwd_rs2—there might be room to optimize how those comparisons cascade.\n\nLooking at the hazard_unit's load_use_hazard check, the `id_ex_rd != 5'b0` condition is actually necessary because loads to x0 are valid but don't write, so dependents shouldn't stall. The logic is already correct here.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the forwarding path in the execute stage—the muxes selecting between AUIPC/PC and ALU operands feed into the ALU, comparator, and JALR logic, creating a combinational chain through the forwarding multiplexers. For shifts, the ALU already uses only the low 5 bits of the operand, which is minimal. I'm considering whether pre-computing the `!= 0` flags for rd addresses in the pipeline registers could help the forward_unit's priority encoder, though Yosys likely already optimizes this away. Another angle is rethinking the byte/halfword load logic with explicit mux trees per byte based on address bits, but that approach caused silent divergence on misaligned halfwords before. I'm exploring whether a dedicated shift-by-bytes multiplexer could help...\n\nActually, looking back at what's worked in previous iterations, the pattern is clear: pure Boolean or arithmetic restructuring on existing logic tends to regress because Yosys has already found a local optimum. The wins came from genuinely removing duplicated hardware—collapsing three multipliers into one—or adding a small parallel path that saves cycles, like the JAL fast-path in the ID stage. So I'm scanning the execute stage for truly duplicated hardware: the branch target computation, JALR sum, and jump target logic all reuse the `pc + imm` addition in different ways, which suggests there might be redundant adders I could consolidate.\n\nPrevious attempts at restructuring—threading `link_val = pc+4`, folding JAL into the ALU, routing branch compute through the ALU—all regressed, likely because they either broke formal verification or disrupted existing CSE optimizations. But there's a concrete opportunity I'm noticing: the `wb_w_data` wire from the writeback stage serves double duty as both the regfile write data and the MEM/WB forwarding value fed back to the execute stage, which creates unnecessary fanout and coupling.\n\nThe combinational path is long—loaded data flows through shift/sign-extend, then through the mem_to_reg mux, then back as a forwarding input to the execute stage's forward mux, then into the ALU. I considered moving the mem_to_reg mux earlier into the MEM stage so MEM/WB stores a single `wb_data` field, but r3s1 already tried this and regressed 5.66% because the shift/extend cone already has tight setup timing, and adding the mux in series with it made things worse. The current design—keeping both `read_data` and `alu_result` separate in MEM/WB with the mux post-flop in writeback—is actually the right call here.\n\nFor a minimal, safe optimization, I'm considering two ideas. First, I could separate the dmem read enable from the misalignment gating to shorten that path, though the memory stage is relatively short so this might not be critical. Second, I could gate `reg_write` to 0 in the ID stage when `rd==0` (by checking `instr[11:7]`), which would let me drop the `rd != 5'b0` checks in the forward unit and potentially simplify the forwarding logic. But I need to verify whether the forward unit's `rd != 0` check is actually on the critical path.\n\nLooking at the forwarding comparisons—the equality check on the 5-bit `rd` address and the OR reduction for the inequality—these are likely already merged by synthesis, so there's probably not much to gain there. I'm exploring more creative approaches now: eliminating the `mem_sext` control bit (though that's just a rename), skipping the shift stage for aligned loads (not worth the complexity), or registering the forwarding select signals one cycle earlier so the muxes in EX use flopped selects instead of combinational logic. The registered forwarding idea is interesting—since the forwarding decision can be made when an instruction is in ID and the producer is in EX or MEM, I could capture those select bits and use them in the next cycle.\n\nBut extending the id_ex pipeline register is risky given past formal verification issues. Looking at the hazard unit's critical path instead, I could pre-compute and register a combined signal like `id_ex_mem_read_nonzero` to save a logic level, though synthesis might already be doing this optimization. I also considered merging the WB-stage mux into the MEM-stage for the forwarding path, but that exact change was tried before and caused a 5.66% regression.\n\nThe issue was that the mux ended up in series with the load-data shift-and-extend logic rather than in parallel, adding delay to the MEM/WB flop's input. I could try adding a separate post-flop path by computing `wb_data_pre` in MEM and flopping it alongside the existing read_data and alu_result, but that would just recreate the same series problem or require extra flops to split the paths. Instead, I'm thinking about using a distributed-RAM inference-friendly register file with conditional synthesis guards. Previous attempts in r1s0, r5s0, and r6s1 explored this, and the key lesson is being careful with the macro names—specifically using `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` which is defined during formal verification but not `RISCV_FORMAL`, so I'd guard the code appropriately.\n\nThe real constraint isn't the reset behavior but the port topology: a dual-read-port regfile with write-first bypass doesn't map to Gowin SDPB/BSRAM primitives, so Yosys falls back to discrete no-reset flip-flops. However, a dual-storage variant where each storage has only one read port IS compatible with distributed SSRAM. So the plan is to use the correct macro guard, implement the dual-storage regfile (separate storage for rs1 and rs2 with broadcast writes), and preserve resets under formal—this should avoid the fallback to discrete FFs and actually work.\n\nThe guard needs to distinguish between synthesis and formal flows. The issue is that `YOSYS` is defined in both Gowin synthesis and SBY's formal flow, so it's not a reliable sentinel. The cleaner approach is to use `ifdef SYNTHESIS` (which Gowin defines but SBY doesn't) or `ifndef FORMAL`, ensuring reset-clear survives formal verification but gets elided during Gowin synthesis to enable SSRAM inference. I need to find a macro that distinguishes formal verification from FPGA synthesis—`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` is defined during formal but not FPGA, while `YOSYS` is set in both contexts. The issue is that Verilator also lacks `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`, so guarding reset with that macro would incorrectly drop it for simulation too. I'm realizing the `make fpga` flow sets `SYNTHESIS` during Yosys synthesis, which could be the actual discriminator needed here.\n\nBut even with the right guard, removing reset entirely breaks Gowin's primitive inference because the port shape no longer matches what the SSRAM expects—the fabric placement gets worse without that reset-clear hint. So instead of trying to drop reset, I should change the register file architecture itself: use dual storage with separate arrays for each read port, where writes broadcast to both but each array only has one read port, matching Gowin's single-port SSRAM constraints while keeping reset intact. infer SSRAM. This should work! The key insight is that r6s1 failed because of the guard macro name, not the dual-storage approach itself. If I correct the guard to `ifdef YOSYS && ifndef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`, formal should pass while still allowing SSRAM inference on the FPGA side.\n\nThere's a risk that r5s0's experience shows reset-drop alone worsens FF placement, but the dual-storage topology might route better than a single 2-read-port array. However, if SSRAM inference still fails and it falls back to FF, I'd be doubling the flip-flops on an already 94.8%-full fabric, which could backfire.\n\nLet me try a safer, more targeted approach instead: short-circuit the decoder's write-enable for x0-targeted writes by forcing `reg_write = 0` when `rd == 5'b0`, which simplifies the forward and hazard logic without restructuring the entire regfile.\n\nActually, the regfile already guards against x0 writes with `w_en && w_addr != 5'b0`, so this is pretty minor—maybe 2 LUT operations at best. The real bottleneck might be elsewhere. Hazard detection feeds the stall signal which affects PC enable, so that's on the critical path, but Yosys likely common-subexpression-eliminates those comparisons anyway.\n\nLet me pivot to the immediate generator instead. It uses a 5-way case statement to produce 32-bit immediates, with each output bit selected from various instruction fields depending on type. This creates deep mux trees per column that could be a timing bottleneck.\n\nOne approach would be to compute one-hot type signals from the opcode, then build each immediate bit as a small AND-OR tree across the five possible instruction sources. But Yosys's case-to-mux conversion should already find this optimization, so there's probably no real win there.\n\nI keep coming back to pre-computing `pc+4` in the fetch stage and threading it through the pipeline so JAL/JALR and branch fallthrough paths grab it from a flop instead of computing it locally in execute. But that actually regressed before because `pc+4` is already being common-subexpression-eliminated with the fetch stage's next-pc calculation.\n\nThe ALU's sign-extension operand packing—`{sext_a & a[31], a}`—looks like it could collapse a level, but that AND gate is already just one LUT, same as a mux would be. No savings there either.\n\nMaybe the real angle is fanout reduction on the stall signal itself. The hazard unit ORs together load-use detection, instruction-memory stall, and data-memory stall to drive `stall_if`, which then fans out to multiple consumers.\n\nActually, looking back at the regfile regression in r5s0: the macro guard was correct and formal verification held, but the FPGA synthesis fell back to distributed flip-flops instead of inferring block RAM because the dual-read-port topology didn't match Gowin's primitive shapes. The reset-cluster hint got lost in that fallback, which hurt placement on a nearly-full fabric.\n\nSo for dual-storage regfile to work, I need the correct macro guard like r5s0 had, keep the port shape compatible with Gowin primitives (one read port per storage), maintain write-first bypass semantics, and handle whatever else the synthesis flow needs.\n\nBut this combines two fixes at once—the macro guard from r6s1 and the port topology from r5s0—which is risky. Expected value is roughly neutral if it regresses again.\n\nLet me pivot and look at what's probably the real critical path now. After r4s2's JAL fast-path win, the bottleneck has likely shifted to the execute side. The ALU's 33-bit multiplier and divider case statement are probably the main culprits, especially the combinational divider tree for DIV/REM operations that fires every cycle regardless of whether we're actually doing division. If I can gate that computation or pipeline it differently, I might free up significant LUT area and improve timing without the regfile topology risk.\n\nThe forwarding muxes in the execute stage are currently 3:1, but I'm only using two of the three inputs. If I can merge the EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding paths into a single prioritized bus, I could reduce this to 2:1 and save a mux level.\n\nDescribing the forwarding mux logic... I'm weighing the trade-offs between collapsing the forwarding mux hierarchy versus keeping it simple—moving complexity upstream to forward_unit might save a LUT level in the critical path, but Yosys likely already optimizes this, and duplicating comparison logic would add gates without clear benefit. The safer move is a narrower optimization: collapsing the hazard_unit's stall computation by combining memory wait conditions earlier in the pipeline rather than restructuring the forwarding logic.\n\nActually, I'm settling on factoring out the x0-check into the decoder stage—forcing `reg_write` to zero when rd is x0 during the id_ex latch, so forward_unit doesn't need to check for x0 separately. But loads to x0 are legal (the memory operation still happens), so the hazard_unit still needs its x0 check for load-use detection even after this change.\n\nThe savings are marginal—maybe one LUT per forward path. Let me explore something with more impact: using a lookup table for the byte mask computation in mem_stage instead of variable shifting, or better yet, adding a parallel prefetch path for branch targets to reduce mispredict latency. But prefetching needs dual imem ports which isn't feasible. So I'm going with the byte-selector mux approach for load-data alignment in the memory stage.\n\nActually, wait—r3s1 and r6s0 both failed when I touched mem_stage. That's a real risk. And pre-flopping io_imemReady into hazard_unit changes the protocol. Let me look at the redirect_target mux at the top level instead. It's already a 2:1 priority between ex_redirect and id_jal_target from r4s2, so per the lessons from r9s2, I should leave that alone.\n\nRegistering io_imemReady would add a cycle of latency that breaks semantics since it's an input from the testbench. And computing id_ex_reg_write_nonzero in hazard_unit to avoid redundant zero-checks is a small win but worth testing.\n\nActually, I think the real pattern here is that CSE is already well-tuned—the big wins came from collapsing duplicated multipliers in r1s0 and adding the parallel JAL path in r4s2. Every tiny restructure since then has regressed. Looking at the adders scattered across the pipeline—pc+4 in if_stage, pc+j_imm in ID's JAL path, pc+imm and rs1+imm in EX, plus the link value adder—Yosys is probably already CSE'ing the ones with matching operands. But r4s1 regressed too, so I can't rely on threading to save area. The question is whether there's a multiplier or other duplicated logic I'm missing.\n\nI considered merging all the comparisons (SLT, SLTU, branches, SUB) through a single 33-bit subtractor to read carry, zero, and sign flags—that would consolidate 9 operations into one resource. But r2s0 already tried routing branch resolution through a shared ALU subtractor and it regressed by 4.10% because the carry chain serialization hurt critical path. The lesson is that sharing creates serialization, which contradicts the multiplier win. The difference is that multipliers are big DSP resources that were tripled, while subtractors are small and parallel cones don't hurt—but apparently the serialization still matters for branches.\n\nI think I've hit the limit of what I can creatively optimize here. Let me propose something conservative: using Yosys carry chain attributes on the ALU's arithmetic ops to ensure they use dedicated carry primitives instead of generic logic.\n\nActually, I'm going to commit to a different hypothesis instead: pre-registering the forward unit's producer-nonzero flags to shorten the EX-stage forwarding cone. The forward unit currently checks `ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd != 0` combinationally, but since ex_mem is already flopped, I could add pre-computed 1-bit signals that capture whether the write is enabled and the destination is nonzero. This saves the 5-bit comparison per cycle. The catch is that adding fields to ex_mem_t might destabilize formal verification like it did with id_ex_t. I could avoid struct changes by computing `ex_mem_rd_nonzero` combinationally at the top level instead—it's just duplicating what the forward unit does internally, and Yosys should CSE it away.\n\nActually, I'm settling on something simpler and safer: force the decoder to set reg_write=0 whenever rd==0, so the forward unit's priority encoder can be simplified. This stays local to decoder.sv with no struct changes, reduces the forward logic by one operand per term, and is formally safe since writes to x0 are dropped anyway. But wait—I need to think through the forwarding logic more carefully. If reg_write=0 when rd=0, then the forward check becomes just `ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs1`. When rd=0 we'd have w_en=0 so no forward happens, which is correct. But id_ex_rs1 could legitimately be 0 (reading x0), and we shouldn't forward from an x0 write anyway since that never happens.\n\nFor the load-use hazard detector, LOADs to x0 have mem_read=1 but if I force reg_write=0 for rd==0, then the hazard check `mem_read && id_ex_rd == rs1` would incorrectly stall when rd=0 and rs1=0. I'd still need to keep the `id_ex_rd != 5'b0` gate there, so only the forward unit actually gets simplified. This feels too marginal. Let me consider something with more potential upside instead.\n\nI'm weighing whether to share the ALU's signed comparators across SLT instructions and branch comparisons, but the sources are different and the logic isn't straightforward to unify without risk. After thinking through a few optimization angles, I'm going to stick with the simpler, more pragmatic approach: just have the decoder force reg_write=0 for rd==0 in the id_stage, which cleans up the forward unit logic without introducing structural complexity.\n\nActually, the decoder unconditionally sets reg_write=1 for ALU ops without knowing rd, so gating it downstream in id_stage after decoding is the cleanest move—it constrains the signal to its useful domain and lets Yosys dead-code-eliminate the redundant checks in forward_unit and regfile.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether this actually helps timing though. The rd!=0 check in forward_unit is already a 5-input NOR plus OR (a couple LUT4 levels), and moving that check upstream by one flop stage only saves about one LUT4 level on the forward path—maybe 1% Fmax at best. Low confidence win, but worth proposing modestly.\n\nLet me draft the AML entry with the hypothesis clearly stated: suppress reg_write in id_stage when rd is zero, which lets me remove the redundant rd!=0 check from forward_unit and make the critical path slightly shorter. I'll also clean up the regfile's write-enable logic to be explicit about this optimization.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decd07613001CuL4ZRHxT22W7s","sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","messageID":"msg_deccd529a001kpjDj5j5TMIlZh"}}
