{"type":"text","timestamp":1777794613063,"sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","part":{"id":"prt_decd09be4001dgMy2p6Lz9AgwU","messageID":"msg_decd08683001LNa1T8TjQxbLaA","sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","type":"text","text":"Given the extensive pattern of regressions on cone-restructures, I'll propose a small, safe, local micro-opt that follows a \"constrain upstream, let DCE eliminate downstream\" pattern — which hasn't been tried and doesn't touch pipeline register struct fields (the confirmed formal tarpit).\n\nThe forward_unit's `rd != 5'b0` check is evaluated combinationally on EX-stage's forwarding path feeding the ALU. If we gate `reg_write` at ID-stage when `rd == 0`, then `w_en=0` already implies `rd != 0` and downstream checks become DCE-able. Semantically equivalent (writes to x0 are already dropped at regfile).","time":{"start":1777794587620,"end":1777794613062}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777794613076,"sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EyUA9U7ccD3fyycaMYUuvj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r10s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r10s0\ntitle: \"Gate reg_write at ID for rd==0 to shorten forward_unit priority encoder\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The forward_unit drives the 3:1 operand-select muxes at the head of the\n  EX-stage ALU/branch-comparator cone — it sits directly on one of the\n  core's known hot combinational paths. Each of its two always_comb\n  priority encoders evaluates three conditions per term:\n    (ex_mem_w_en) && (ex_mem_rd != 5'b0) && (ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs?)\n    (mem_wb_w_en) && (mem_wb_rd != 5'b0) && (mem_wb_rd == id_ex_rs?)\n  The `rd != 5'b0` predicate is redundant with `w_en`: an architectural\n  write whose destination is x0 has no effect (regfile writes to x0 are\n  dropped, forward_unit returning x0 would be bit-identical to returning\n  the real x0 = 0 since the regfile's read of x0 is hardwired). If we\n  constrain `ctrl.reg_write` upstream — at id_stage, by AND-ing decoder's\n  reg_write with (instr[11:7] != 5'b0) before loading into ID/EX — then\n  `w_en=0` already implies `rd!=0` at EX/MEM and MEM/WB, and the\n  forward_unit's `rd != 5'b0` terms collapse to dead code that Yosys can\n  DCE cleanly.\n\n  This is the \"constrain upstream, let downstream DCE\" pattern, strictly\n  local to id_stage.sv + decoder-output gating, and does NOT edit any\n  pipeline-register struct field name (the confirmed formal tarpit from\n  r4s0/r5s1/r5s2/r6s0/r6s1/r7s0/r7s2/r8s0). The only thing changing is\n  a combinational AND gate on ctrl_decoded.reg_write inside id_stage,\n  before the ID/EX flop captures it.\nhypothesis: |\n  Insert a single combinational mask at the top of id_stage:\n    ctrl_decoded.reg_write = dec_reg_write && (in.instr[11:7] != 5'b0);\n  so the ID/EX register's ctrl.reg_write is 0 whenever rd=x0. No struct\n  edit, no new field, no new flop.\n\n  Downstream effects (all via existing signals):\n    - forward_unit's `(rd != 5'b0)` terms become redundant — w_en=0 when\n      rd=0, so the AND with `rd != 5'b0` is always-false-when-false and\n      has no effect when true. Yosys's DCE should drop the 5-input NOR\n      that produces that predicate, shortening the priority encoder's\n      LUT4 depth by ~1 level on the EX-stage operand-mux-feeding cone.\n    - wb_stage's `w_en = ctrl.reg_write && valid` gets a cleaner\n      constraint (no x0 writes ever reach the regfile write port as\n      `w_en=1`, so regfile's internal `w_addr != 5'b0` check becomes DCE-\n      able too, but we leave it in place as defensive safety.\n    - hazard_unit's load-use check still needs the explicit `rd != 5'b0`\n      gate because mem_read is independent of reg_write (LOAD-to-x0\n      still fires a dmem transaction; we only want to suppress regfile\n      write-back, not the load itself).\n\n  Expected structural saving: one LUT4 level on the forward_unit →\n  ex_stage operand-mux cone, which then feeds the ALU. On the 9484/10000\n  LUT4 GW2AR fabric this is a modest but measurable Fmax/routing tick.\n  The lesson history (r8s1, r9s0, r9s2) warns that restructuring\n  already-CSE'd cones regresses — this hypothesis AVOIDS restructuring;\n  it only *narrows the domain* of an existing signal upstream, letting\n  Yosys's existing optimizer decide whether to propagate the\n  simplification. If Yosys had already inferred this constraint, the\n  change is a strict no-op (semantic redundancy); if it hadn't, we gain\n  a LUT4 level on a hot cone.\n\n  Formal safety: `reg_write && (rd != 0)` is semantically what a\n  reg_write signal should already be; the RVFI rd_wdata path at\n  retirement uses `mem_wb.ctrl.reg_write && (mem_wb.rd != 5'b0)` already\n  (see core.sv `rd_wen` computation). The change propagates that same\n  constraint one stage earlier — no observable RVFI behavior change, so\n  riscv-formal BMC sees identical traces.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Gate ctrl_decoded.reg_write with (in.instr[11:7] != 5'b0) before loading ID/EX, so writes targeting x0 carry reg_write=0 through the pipeline.\"\n  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n    description: \"Drop the redundant `rd != 5'b0` terms from the two priority encoders, relying on the upstream constraint (w_en=0 implies rd!=0) to preserve semantics. Yosys DCE handles the rest.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r10s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r10s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777794613059,"end":1777794613074}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I've been exploring forward_unit optimizations with limited success so far. Let me reconsider the approach—instead of the micro-opt hypothesis around upstream x0 gating, I'm thinking about attacking this from a different angle: reducing the critical path depth in the memory-to-execute forwarding pipeline by registering the write-back stage multiplexer selects.\n\nActually, I should stick with something conservative and straightforward that I can propose as-is.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decd0a4df00193kjFgxfp9eRK5","sessionID":"ses_21332ae13ffezuk9lTv3NrWP2f","messageID":"msg_decd08683001LNa1T8TjQxbLaA"}}
