{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796388692,"sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01TfpSNpLJdQq1QSou5eCBQs","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/rtl/ && wc -l cores/bench/rtl/*.sv","description":"List RTL and line counts"},"output":"alu.sv\ncore_pkg.sv\ncore.sv\ndecoder.sv\nex_stage.sv\nforward_unit.sv\nhazard_unit.sv\nid_stage.sv\nif_stage.sv\nimm_gen.sv\nmem_stage.sv\nreg_file.sv\nwb_stage.sv\n     118 cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv\n     141 cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv\n     341 cores/bench/rtl/core.sv\n     233 cores/bench/rtl/decoder.sv\n     155 cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv\n      38 cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv\n      82 cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n     116 cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv\n      67 cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv\n      42 cores/bench/rtl/imm_gen.sv\n     156 cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv\n      58 cores/bench/rtl/reg_file.sv\n      27 cores/bench/rtl/wb_stage.sv\n    1574 total\n","metadata":{"output":"alu.sv\ncore_pkg.sv\ncore.sv\ndecoder.sv\nex_stage.sv\nforward_unit.sv\nhazard_unit.sv\nid_stage.sv\nif_stage.sv\nimm_gen.sv\nmem_stage.sv\nreg_file.sv\nwb_stage.sv\n     118 cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv\n     141 cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv\n     341 cores/bench/rtl/core.sv\n     233 cores/bench/rtl/decoder.sv\n     155 cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv\n      38 cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv\n      82 cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n     116 cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv\n      67 cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv\n      42 cores/bench/rtl/imm_gen.sv\n     156 cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv\n      58 cores/bench/rtl/reg_file.sv\n      27 cores/bench/rtl/wb_stage.sv\n    1574 total\n","exit":0,"description":"List RTL and line counts","truncated":false},"title":"List RTL and line counts","time":{"start":1777796388687,"end":1777796388690}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the performance data, the best result so far is 387.98 with the JAL fast-path optimization showing a 17.73% improvement, but recent attempts have been regressing. The core is hitting LUT capacity limits on GW2AR, and most micro-optimizations targeting the EX critical path are backfiring due to Yosys synthesis issues.\n\nI've identified a long list of approaches that have already failed—touching the id_ex_t struct, modifying control signal domains, editing the regfile reset logic, rewriting fetch-redirect Boolean expressions, and various other critical path manipulations all led to formal verification dead ends or synthesis problems. The successful wins came from the shared multiplier in r1s0 and the JAL fast-path in r4s2.\n\nThe key insight is that I need to find micro-optimizations that stay completely outside the problematic cones—the PC-redirect path, the EX-to-EX/MEM forwarding logic, the ALU carry chain, and the load-data cone. I should focus on internal module optimizations that don't change port shapes, like potentially factoring the write-enable condition in the regfile to avoid redundant address comparisons.\n\nI'm reconsidering the regfile write-port optimization: the regfile already internally checks `w_en && w_addr != 5'b0` before storing, so the control signal can stay as-is for RVFI compliance while the regfile itself handles the x0 write suppression. For the forward unit, I could add a precomputed field alongside the existing id_ex/ex_mem structures rather than renaming, which should avoid the formal verification issues that field edits triggered. The decoder and immediate generator are likely already off the critical path, but the MEM stage wdata precomputation might still be worth exploring.\n\nLooking at the hazard unit, byte-lane masking, and JALR alignment—these are all formal verification traps that have regressed before. The real wins came from shared logic like the multiplier and cheap unconditional bypasses like the JAL fast-path, not from restructuring existing cones. I should focus on identifying what's actually on the binding Fmax path after r4s2's improvements.\n\nThe EX forwarding mux feeding into the ALU and then the EX/MEM register is likely the critical path now, along with the fetch-redirect cone driving the PC. Rather than touching those, I'm looking for LUT-reclamation opportunities that stay off the critical path. The WB-stage mem_to_reg mux is always computed but only meaningful for loads, and the mem_wb register carries rs1_val/rs2_val purely for RVFI compliance—these are 64 bits of storage that don't affect pipeline function. Combining control bits like is_jump/is_branch/is_jalr into a 2-bit encoding would shrink id_ex_t, though that risks becoming another formal verification tarpit.\n\nThe decoder's opcode checks at ID could potentially hoist earlier, and I'm thinking about whether there's still unconditional logic that could resolve a stage sooner. LUI and AUIPC are already minimal through the ALU. But I notice the immediate-form decode is split between imm_gen and the decoder, both checking opcodes combinationally at ID—there might be a chance to consolidate that opcode decode. Also, in EX there are two separate 32-bit adders computing pc + imm for jump_target and branch_target; even though Yosys likely CSEs them already, explicit sharing via a single wire could reduce variance.\n\nLooking at the actual EX stage code, both expressions are in the same always_comb block, so CSE should work. In MEM, the shift computation `addr[1:0] * 8` is just a left-shift by 3, which Yosys probably already optimizes. For safe, cheap targets, I could narrow the storage of rs1_val/rs2_val or address fields if they're unused downstream, but those are RVFI-visible so that's risky. Another angle is optimizing the forward_unit via a parallel form instead of the current sequential if-else chain...\n\nRewriting the forward_unit logic with precomputed hit signals...\n\nThe forward_unit is already pretty minimal. I could pre-compute `rs_nz` bits to avoid the `!= 0` checks, but that requires editing id_ex_t, which gets messy. Actually, the field name change itself isn't the real blocker—it's more about whether the savings justify the churn.\n\nLooking at the EX-stage's alu_result path, that post-ALU mux selecting between jump link address and ALU output is likely already CSE'd with the if_stage's pc+4 adder, so it's a tarpit. The pc_next mux is more interesting—it's a 4-way selector handling misalign faults, jumps, branches, and sequential flow...\n\nActually, I could merge those two `in.pc + 32'd4` arms into a single default case, but that restructures a redirect-adjacent wire. Even though pc_next feeds the EX/MEM register rather than the PC-redirect cone directly, r8s0's lesson about flattening redirect logic suggests this is still risky. The safer approach is to focus on pure LUT reduction targets that are off the critical path, like the decoder's case structure or immediate generation logic.\n\nI'm noticing the fabric is already 94.8% full, so even modest LUT savings could help with congestion. The misalignment check for memory operations could theoretically be computed earlier and flopped, but that mirrors r10s1's failure pattern. Let me look for truly safe micro-optimizations that don't touch the redirect cone or pipeline boundaries. Looking at the hints about reducing duplicated combinational work and resolving earlier, I'm scanning for remaining opportunities. There's some redundant PC arithmetic in the EX stage that's likely already CSE'd by the synthesizer, and AUIPC could theoretically resolve at ID but threading it forward doesn't seem worth the complexity. The real question is whether the shared multiplier in the ALU is worth gating — it's always active even for non-MUL operations, though the synthesizer might already be optimizing away unused bits. Let me think about whether there's a practical power or area win there. Looking at the ALU's default case, it zeros the output for the 13 unused opcodes out of 32 possible values. Yosys should already optimize this away if the decoder only produces valid opcodes, but it's worth checking if we're synthesizing unnecessary logic there.\n\nThe multiplier chain looks solid — the 33x33 signed multiply correctly produces the low 32 bits for MUL and the upper 32 bits for MULH variants by adjusting the sign-extension flags. So that's not where the waste is.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the register file — we're allocating 32 flip-flops for x0 even though it's hardwired to zero and never written. We could save 32 FFs by declaring only regs[1:31] and tying x0 to ground, though that might complicate formal verification anchoring.\n\nBut here's a better angle: the EX-stage operand forwarding mux is a 4:1 multiplexer for each bit of rs1, which synthesizes to 3 LUTs per bit on LUT4 fabric. That's 96 LUTs just for the rs1 forwarding path alone, and the same for rs2. Reworking how these muxes are structured could pack them more efficiently into the available LUT resources. output. If I move the `mem_to_reg` mux to the MEM stage instead, I'd be computing `mem_wb.write_data = ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result` there and just writing it directly in WB — but that's what r3s1 tried and it actually hurt because the load-data path becomes critical. So that's a dead end.\n\nLet me explore something different: what if I share the branch-target adder with the JAL-target adder? Right now I'm computing `id_jal_target = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm` in the ID stage for the fast path, and then separately computing `in.pc + in.imm` in the EX stage for both branch targets and JALR jumps. For non-JALR jumps (JAL), the EX computation is redundant since the prediction already handled it, but for JALR I need `rs1 + in.imm` anyway.\n\nI could thread the JAL target from ID through to EX via the id_ex register, which would let me reuse it there instead of recomputing — though that adds 32 flip-flops and requires editing id_ex_t. Or I could try unifying the reset and hold logic in mem_stage to reduce per-bit muxing overhead, which is a smaller win but cleaner.\n\nActually, looking at the real EX critical path after the shared multiplier: it's the forwarding mux feeding into the ALU's massive case statement with all those multiplier arms, then into the EX/MEM register. That case mux is the bottleneck. What if I split it into pre-categorized sub-muxes — arith, logic, shift, mul, div — instead of one giant 20-way selector?\n\nOn LUT4 fabric a 20:1 mux is already 10+ levels deep, so splitting into four sub-muxes plus a final 4:1 combine would be 7 levels total and might improve Fmax, but this kind of restructuring has historically been a time sink. Let me look elsewhere instead.\n\nThe combinational divider fires every cycle and probably consumes a lot of LUTs. I could gate its inputs when we're not doing division, hoping Yosys propagates constants, but that's unlikely to help since the divider is combinational and Yosys doesn't know input patterns at synthesis time. I'd need an explicit mux, which just adds overhead.\n\nLet me try restructuring the forward_unit's priority encoding into explicit onehot form — Yosys might already do this, but the structural hint could help Gowin pack it better without affecting RVFI. Before committing though, I should check the log for what's been attempted before.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decec16ce001W0Z72C5wQgrUT0","sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","messageID":"msg_dece988c7001Jqf7lAzj9aVYFD"}}
