{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796428505,"sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Kzb1bx7Ck77ch3wkQ6RSGJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -n \"branch_taken\\|branch_target\" cores/bench/rtl/*.sv | grep -v \"_q\\.\" | grep -v \"^Binary\"","description":"Check branch_taken/target field usage"},"output":"cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv:113:    logic        branch_taken;\ncores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv:114:    logic [31:0] branch_target;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:64:  logic        branch_taken;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:65:  logic [31:0] branch_target;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:81:    branch_taken  = in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_cond;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:82:    branch_target = in.pc + in.imm;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:100:    misalign_branch = in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:101:                      && (branch_target[1:0] != 2'b00);\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:112:  assign redirect        = (branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.jal_predicted))\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:114:  assign redirect_target = in.ctrl.is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:143:                            : branch_taken      ? branch_target\ncores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv:30:  // ex_mem_t carries branch_taken / branch_target / pc_next / rs?_val\n","metadata":{"output":"cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv:113:    logic        branch_taken;\ncores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv:114:    logic [31:0] branch_target;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:64:  logic        branch_taken;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:65:  logic [31:0] branch_target;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:81:    branch_taken  = in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_cond;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:82:    branch_target = in.pc + in.imm;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:100:    misalign_branch = in.ctrl.is_branch && branch_taken\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:101:                      && (branch_target[1:0] != 2'b00);\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:112:  assign redirect        = (branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.jal_predicted))\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:114:  assign redirect_target = in.ctrl.is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target;\ncores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv:143:                            : branch_taken      ? branch_target\ncores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv:30:  // ex_mem_t carries branch_taken / branch_target / pc_next / rs?_val\n","exit":0,"description":"Check branch_taken/target field usage","truncated":false},"title":"Check branch_taken/target field usage","time":{"start":1777796428501,"end":1777796428503}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I've tried a bunch of micro-optimizations on that slot without success—multiplier worked but everything else either broke or lost performance. Now I need to dig into the existing code and find a different optimization that doesn't hit any of those same pitfalls, then figure out what's actually off the critical path.\n\nLooking at the design, the decoder at the ID stage is flopped into id_ex and probably has some headroom, same with imm_gen. The hazard_unit is combinational and feeds PC/ID controls, and RVFI is just wiring. Since we're constrained by LUT count on the Gowin GW2AR, I'm considering a few smaller tweaks: reducing the decoder's case statement to operate on just the 5 bits that matter instead of all 7, simplifying the byte_mask logic in mem_stage to avoid redundant shifts, and looking at what else might compress without breaking anything.\n\nThe real opportunity I'm seeing now is in the forwarding logic. Currently forward_unit outputs a 2-bit select that gets decoded into a 4:1 mux in the EX stage. If I switched to one-hot encoding, I could use AND-OR muxes which might pack better into LUT4s. But I'm hesitant because Yosys probably already optimized this pretty well. The cleaner angle is recognizing that when rs1_addr is zero, the forwarding predicates become redundant—the comparison ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs1 would never be true if both are checking against zero, so I could eliminate that logic entirely.\n\nLet me focus on something more concrete instead. I'm considering replacing the decoder's full 7-bit opcode case with just the upper 5 bits, since valid RISC-V instructions always have bits[1:0] set to 11. But if I drop that check from the case statement, illegal opcodes that don't follow this pattern would slip through as valid. I'd need to add an explicit validity check for those low bits and AND it with the case arm conditions to maintain the invariant that is_illegal defaults to 1 and only clears for validated instructions. The current full 7-bit case probably already gets optimized down by synthesis anyway, so this might not be worth the added complexity.\n\nLet me try a different approach. The winning patterns I've seen involve sharing combinational resources or resolving values earlier using existing signals. Within the ALU itself, I could look at the shifters, adders, or logic operations, but those attempts have mostly regressed. Sharing the multiplier's adder with something else feels too speculative. \n\nI think I should stay conservative and look for a narrow, low-risk optimization. One idea is to examine the mem_wb_t structure and identify fields that no consumer actually uses.\n\nLooking through the mem_wb_t fields and tracing their usage, every single field gets consumed somewhere—either in wb_stage or in the RVFI interface. So there's no easy cleanup there.\n\nBut I notice that branch_taken and branch_target are defined in ex_mem_t but don't appear to be read by anything downstream. Let me verify whether these fields are actually consumed.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dececb24c001e7OBg0hXTQGDHh","sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","messageID":"msg_decec3db0001N7fVsT8mUPTaPQ"}}
