{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777796452943,"sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","part":{"id":"prt_deced124c001eQ7Icvks4zLr2m","messageID":"msg_deced01d10015lrkzxeja5qcNx","sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","snapshot":"8e4779b470b1d8e60d9ff8632ea85264e2cefa38","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777796536316,"sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","part":{"id":"prt_decede36b001aQzPGmnt9oesJf","messageID":"msg_deced01d10015lrkzxeja5qcNx","sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","type":"text","text":"I've analyzed the code carefully. Notable finding: `ex_mem_t.branch_taken` (1 FF) and `ex_mem_t.branch_target` (32 FFs) are written in `ex_stage` but **never consumed** by any downstream stage or RVFI output — 33 dead flops per cycle. `reg_q.pc_next` already captures the resolved next-PC (branch_target is a subset). The comment in `mem_stage.sv:30` claiming these fields are \"for downstream RVFI use\" is stale.\n\nGiven the extensive list of tarpits (id_ex_t renames, fetch-redirect cone rewrites, regfile-reset changes, load-data cone muxes, ALU operand widening, pc+4 threading), a narrow dead-field removal in `ex_mem_t` is one of the few remaining low-risk micro-opts. Yosys *should* DCE these, but explicit removal guarantees it and may help Gowin FF packing on the 94.8%-full GW2AR fabric by reducing the ex_mem struct-flop cluster width.","time":{"start":1777796506476,"end":1777796536315}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796536330,"sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01HBCYVnBLnadie9UnuCZzVa","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r11s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r11s0\ntitle: \"Remove dead ex_mem_t.branch_taken / branch_target fields — 33 unused FFs\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  Grep confirms `ex_mem_t.branch_taken` (1 bit) and `ex_mem_t.branch_target`\n  (32 bits) are written by ex_stage into the EX/MEM register but NEVER\n  read by any downstream consumer — not by mem_stage, not by wb_stage,\n  not by the top-level RVFI logic in core.sv. The comment at\n  mem_stage.sv:30 calling them \"for downstream RVFI use\" is stale\n  (RVFI has no branch_taken/branch_target fields — only pc_wdata, which\n  is served by ex_mem_t.pc_next). These 33 FFs per cycle plus their\n  reset-mux drivers and the ex_stage combinational assigns that feed\n  them (a 33-bit adder's low-byte compare merged into misalign_fault,\n  and the pc_next 4:1 priority mux) exist purely as dead code.\n\n  Yosys *should* DCE these via struct-field liveness analysis, but two\n  structural factors make manual removal worth trying on GW2AR:\n  (1) reset-cluster grouping: ex_mem_t's `reg_q <= '0` reset line\n  covers every field uniformly — removing 33 bits from that uniform-\n  reset cluster can let Gowin pack the remaining FFs into denser slices\n  (the fabric is 94.8% full, so placement/routing is near the binding\n  constraint); (2) struct-packed register inference: Yosys's SV frontend\n  sometimes lowers a packed struct register as a single opaque word,\n  and whether its field-level DCE fires depends on whether each bit's\n  fanout-to-observable-output chain is provably empty — simpler to\n  guarantee that by removing the source than to hope synth proves it.\n\n  This fits r1s0's winning pattern (reduce silicon that contributes\n  nothing to the retirement datapath) at minimal scope, and explicitly\n  does NOT touch any of the documented tarpits: no id_ex_t struct edit\n  (r7s0), no fetch-redirect cone rewrite (r8s0/r9s2), no regfile reset\n  (r4s0/r5s0/r6s1), no load-data cone reshape (r6s0), no ALU operand\n  widening (r7s1), no ctrl.reg_write domain change (r10s0), no new\n  ex_mem_t fields threaded across stages (r10s1 regressed on FPGA but\n  passed formal — so ex_mem_t struct edits are formally safe, unlike\n  id_ex_t). Pure removal of unused writes.\nhypothesis: |\n  Delete `branch_taken` (logic) and `branch_target` (logic [31:0]) from\n  the `ex_mem_t` typedef in core_pkg.sv. Delete the two corresponding\n  `reg_q.branch_taken <= branch_taken;` / `reg_q.branch_target <= branch_target;`\n  assignments inside ex_stage's `always_ff` block. The local\n  combinational wires `branch_taken` and `branch_target` stay (they\n  feed `redirect`, `redirect_target`, `misalign_branch`, and\n  `reg_q.pc_next`'s 4:1 mux arm — all live nets). Nothing else needs\n  to change: no module port list touched, no consumer referenced these\n  fields.\n\n  Expected outcome:\n    - 33 fewer FFs in the EX/MEM register (about 1.8% of the core's\n      current 1861 FFs).\n    - LUT impact: zero or mildly positive — the combinational logic\n      feeding the removed FFs (the `branch_taken` AND, `branch_target`\n      adder) stays allocated because it feeds `redirect` and\n      `redirect_target` and pc_next, so LUT count is expected flat; FF\n      saving is the primary effect.\n    - Fmax: unchanged on the EX pre-flop critical path (this removes\n      flop D-inputs, not any combinational gate count on the existing\n      critical cone). Second-order: freed FF slices may loosen placement\n      on the 94.8%-full fabric, giving nextpnr more room on a few\n      critical nets. This is the same mechanism that makes any FF-count\n      reduction on a near-full fabric weakly Fmax-positive.\n    - Formal: should pass trivially — no invariant touches these\n      fields, no RVFI port depends on them, no riscv-formal BMC anchors\n      on an EX/MEM value other than what propagates to RVFI via\n      mem_wb_t.\n\n  Risk assessment: low. Closest tarpit analog is r7s0 (id_ex_t rename\n  tripped formal) — but r10s1 showed ex_mem_t append passes formal on\n  this flow, so ex_mem_t edits per se are not the tarpit class.\n  Removing a field whose fanout to any observable wire is empty is the\n  cleanest structural change possible on a packed struct; if it does\n  trigger a formal issue, the diagnostic will be an unambiguous \"field\n  not found\" elaboration error rather than the opaque\n  no_checks_generated BMC-pass that struck id_ex_t edits.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Remove `logic branch_taken;` and `logic [31:0] branch_target;` fields from the `ex_mem_t` typedef. Keep all other fields intact (pc_next remains as-is, since it carries the live resolved-next-PC information those two fields partially duplicated).\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Delete the two assignments `reg_q.branch_taken <= branch_taken;` and `reg_q.branch_target <= branch_target;` inside the EX/MEM register's always_ff else-branch. Keep the local combinational `logic branch_taken;` and `logic [31:0] branch_target;` declarations and their always_comb assigns — they still feed `redirect`, `redirect_target`, `misalign_branch` and `reg_q.pc_next`'s priority mux.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Update the stale header comment at line 30 that claims `ex_mem_t carries branch_taken / branch_target / pc_next / rs?_val for downstream RVFI use` — after this change the struct no longer carries branch_taken/branch_target, and the comment should reflect that pc_next is the live branch/jump-resolved next-PC path.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r11s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r11s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777796536310,"end":1777796536327}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm noticing that `ex_mem.branch_taken` and `ex_mem.branch_target` are written in the execute-memory pipeline stage but never actually read downstream—the memory stage doesn't consume them, and they're not part of the RVFI output either. These look like dead flops that should be eliminated by Yosys's dead code elimination, though I'm wondering if the struct packing in Yosys's frontend handles field-level DCE properly.\n\nThe comment in mem_stage claims these fields are carried for downstream RVFI use, but grepping the code shows no such use anywhere—that documentation is stale. RVFI doesn't even have a branch_taken field. So these 33 flip-flops are genuinely dead, and while Yosys might already be removing them, there could be small savings if it's not (especially if reset or stall logic keeps them semantically alive). This feels like a low-risk but also low-impact micro-optimization.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture though, given how fragile this codebase is, I should probably focus on something with higher confidence of passing all the formal and cocotb tests. Let me consider consolidating the two `in.pc + 32'd4` adders that appear in both the alu_result and pc_next assignments in ex_stage—that could reduce redundant hardware without touching the core pipeline logic.\n\nActually, I'm noticing something more promising in the forwarding unit. The case mux for rs1 selection has four cases but only three distinct outputs: two cases map to `in.rs1_val`, one to `fwd_ex_mem`, and one to `fwd_mem_wb`. This is a 4:1 mux synthesizing to 3 LUTs per bit, which across 32 bits and two operands adds up to 192 LUTs—that's material. Restructuring this as an explicit 3:1 mux could save area...\n\nExploring mux optimization...\n\nActually, the math doesn't work out. A 3:1 mux with the one-hot encoding I'm considering still needs two LUT4s per bit because the logic `(s0&a) | (s1&b) | (!s0&!s1&c)` requires five distinct inputs, which exceeds LUT4's capacity. The existing 4:1 mux is already two LUT4s per bit, so there's no savings here either.\n\nLet me pivot and look at the reset behavior in the ex_stage register. The current design clears everything on reset and uses enable FFs for stalls, which Yosys handles fine. But I'm wondering if the reset path for signals like branch_taken and branch_target actually needs to be cleared, or if there's a way to optimize that.\n\nThe key insight is that only the valid bit matters for pipeline correctness—the data fields are don't-care at reset since invalid entries won't propagate. However, this optimization is risky from a formal verification standpoint and would likely trigger the same tarpit issues I hit with the regfile reset experiment.\n\nGiven those constraints, I'm settling on a safer approach: removing the dead branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t entirely. This is pure dead code elimination for source cleanliness, and shrinking the struct width might help Yosys pack things better on the Gowin device if the struct gets lowered opaquely.\n\nBut wait—modifying core_pkg.sv struct definitions is formally fragile, as I learned from the id_ex_t experience. Field removals are riskier than appends, though r10s1 did add fields to ex_mem_t successfully. Rather than risk another formal tarpit, I should look for optimizations that stay within alu.sv and don't touch any struct definitions.\n\nLooking at the multiplier logic, I notice that opa_ext, opb_ext, and prod are computed unconditionally every cycle regardless of the operation, so the full 33×33 multiplier runs even when the result isn't used. The sign-extend selects are already computed before the case statement, so there's limited room to hoist them further. I'm considering whether computing div/rem results with overflow and divide-by-zero guards inside the...\n\nExtracting the pc + 4 computation into a shared intermediate signal...\n\nActually, Yosys probably already CSEs that addition across both the if_stage and ex_stage uses, so this micro-optimization might not help or could even be a wash. Let me step back and consider a different angle: removing dead writes from ex_mem_t entirely. It's low-risk since it only eliminates unused fields, and it might free up some FF allocation if Yosys didn't already DCE them. Though I'm also wondering if I should try narrowing mem_wb_t.mem_rdata or routing it combinationally—but that won't work because RVFI needs the registered load data at the retirement boundary, and we can't derive the raw mem_rdata from the sign-extended read_data anyway. So I'm going to commit to the dead-field-removal approach as the safest, most straightforward optimization.\n\nWait, one more idea just occurred to me: what if I precompute whether rd is nonzero and thread that bit through the pipeline as a parallel signal? The forward_unit could use this rd_nz bit instead of comparing rd != 0 each time. But that means appending to multiple structs, which carries some risk, and the savings are pretty minimal. The formal verification also flagged issues when I tried narrowing reg_write based on rd==0 before, so I need to be careful not to change the RVFI shadow. I think the safest move is to stick with dead-field removal and consolidating the pc+4 computation in ex_stage—both changes are isolated to ex_stage.sv and core_pkg.sv, and they're clean wins with no formal risk.\n\nActually, let me reconsider whether removing a field from ex_mem_t is even safe. Renaming caused problems in r7s0, so struct edits are risky. But removal is different—I could leave the struct definition alone and just stop writing those dead fields in ex_stage. If I delete the assignments for branch_taken and branch_target, Yosys should recognize them as unused and optimize them away anyway. That way I avoid touching the struct definition entirely.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to remove both the struct fields and the writes in one shot. If it breaks like the id_ex_t rename did, so be it—I've tried the safer options first. But before I commit to that, there's another angle worth exploring: reusing the already-computed pc_next field in ex_mem_t to drive mem_wb.pc_next directly, which follows the pattern of sharing existing wires rather than adding new ones.\n\nWait, that's already what's happening—pc_next is computed with all the branch and jump logic, and mem_wb.pc_next just propagates it forward. The branch_taken and branch_target fields are genuinely dead code. So removing them is straightforward: delete the fields and their assignments, then commit.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decedef7a001XYLA2CZh36G587","sessionID":"ses_2131677e7ffecydQ1T4r3asgUc","messageID":"msg_deced01d10015lrkzxeja5qcNx"}}
