{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777800160419,"sessionID":"ses_212de74a8ffeoP4asD6RbV8NCf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_016tttSfFboXBTwv26AYRzyZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r13s0\ntitle: \"Merge jalr_sum and branch_target adders into a single shared jump-sum adder with operand-input 2:1 mux\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  ex_stage.sv currently instantiates TWO distinct 32-bit adders on the\n  redirect cone: `jalr_sum = rs1 + in.imm` (for JALR) and\n  `branch_target = in.pc + in.imm` (for BRANCH; also reused as JAL's\n  jump_target via `in.pc + in.imm`). Unlike the pc+4 case from r4s1\n  (where Yosys can CSE two `X + 32'd4` adders because the constant-side\n  matches), these two adders have DIFFERENT a-operands (rs1 vs pc) with\n  a common b-operand (in.imm), which Yosys cannot CSE — they synthesize\n  as two independent carry chains. On the 94.8%-full GW2AR fabric\n  (9484/10000 LUT4), reclaiming one full 32-bit carry chain (~32 LUT4 +\n  ~32 carry cells) is a real area win that frees placement/routing\n  pressure without touching any of the established tarpits (id_ex_t\n  symbol table per r7s0, ctrl.reg_write activation domain per r10s0,\n  fetch-redirect cone Boolean form per r8s0, packed-struct field\n  offsets per r11s0, or the MEM-stage load-data cone per r6s0). The\n  ALU-adder-serialization failure modes (r2s0 branch-through-ALU,\n  r7s1 widened ALU-operand mux) explicitly touched the ALU's shared\n  carry chain; this proposal leaves the ALU cone untouched and only\n  merges two ex-local adders whose outputs feed the redirect_target\n  mux and pc_next, both of which are already 2:1-mux consumers of\n  these adders in the current RTL. This is the jump-target analogue\n  of the r1s0 shared-multiplier win (one 33x33 replaced three\n  32x32s), applied to the pc/rs1 + imm case.\nhypothesis: |\n  Rewrite ex_stage.sv's `jalr_sum` + `branch_target` + `jump_target`\n  computation as a single shared adder fed by an upstream 2:1 operand\n  mux:\n\n      logic [31:0] jsum_a_mux;\n      logic [31:0] jsum;\n      assign jsum_a_mux = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? rs1 : in.pc;\n      assign jsum       = jsum_a_mux + in.imm;\n      assign jump_target = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? {jsum[31:1], 1'b0} : jsum;\n      assign branch_target = jsum; // only consumed when !is_jalr\n\n  Because BRANCH and JALR are mutually exclusive at the decoder (BRANCH\n  opcode 0x63 vs JALR opcode 0x67), `branch_target` is architecturally\n  don't-care on any cycle where `is_jalr=1`, so reusing `jsum`\n  (which equals pc+imm when is_jalr=0) for branch_target is bitwise-\n  identical to the current `in.pc + in.imm` on every cycle where\n  `is_branch=1`. The `reg_q.branch_target <= branch_target` flop write\n  stays — and per r11s0's lesson we do NOT remove that struct field,\n  so the packed ex_mem_t layout is byte-for-byte preserved.\n\n  Critical-path analysis on the redirect cone:\n    Before: (rs1+imm carry chain) || (pc+imm carry chain) → 2:1 mux\n            → {jsum[31:1],0}-or-pass mux → redirect_target mux.\n    After:  2:1 input mux → (jsum carry chain) → {jsum[31:1],0}-or-pass\n            → redirect_target mux.\n\n  Both paths contain 1 carry chain + 2 LUT-level muxes on the worst arm;\n  the LUT-depth is equivalent. On GW2AR the carry chain dominates per-\n  bit delay and is identical between the two forms. The primary win is\n  area (one carry chain freed) and the secondary win is the associated\n  placement headroom on a near-full fabric.\n\n  The `jsum` adder is NOT routed through the ALU (preserving the r2s0\n  / r7s1 lessons — ALU operand mux untouched, ALU carry chain\n  unshared). ctrl.reg_write's activation set is untouched (r10s0/r12s1).\n  id_ex_t/ex_mem_t field offsets are untouched (r11s0). The Boolean\n  form of `redirect_target` and the id-side JAL fast-path from r4s2\n  are both structurally unchanged (r8s0/r9s2).\n\n  Formal safety: bitwise equivalence is mechanical. On is_jalr=1:\n    jsum_a_mux = rs1, jsum = rs1+imm, jump_target = {jsum[31:1],1'b0}\n    == old {jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}. branch_target's value is don't-care\n    this cycle (is_branch=0, flop-write still happens but ex_mem_t's\n    branch_target is a dead RVFI-invisible field per r11s0).\n  On is_jalr=0 (BRANCH or JAL):\n    jsum_a_mux = pc, jsum = pc+imm, jump_target = jsum == old\n    (in.pc+in.imm); branch_target = jsum == old (in.pc+in.imm).\n  On neither (ALU op): all jump/branch consumers gated off by\n    is_branch/is_jump, so don't-care.\n  This keeps `reg_q.pc_next`, `reg_q.branch_target`, `redirect`,\n  `redirect_target`, and `ctrl_with_trap.is_illegal` (misalign_fault)\n  bitwise identical on every retirement, so the riscv-formal shadow\n  is unchanged.\n\n  Expected gain: 0.3-3% from freed LUT area + placement room, with\n  no downside on IPC (zero-cycle semantic identity) and near-equivalent\n  Fmax path length. Low-risk structural local change; does not touch\n  any of the ~15 documented failure-mode classes.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace the dedicated `jalr_sum = rs1 + in.imm` and `branch_target = in.pc + in.imm` computations with a single shared `jsum = jsum_a_mux + in.imm` adder driven by `jsum_a_mux = is_jalr ? rs1 : in.pc`, then derive `jump_target = is_jalr ? {jsum[31:1],1'b0} : jsum` and `branch_target = jsum`. Preserve the `reg_q.branch_target <= branch_target` flop write so ex_mem_t's packed struct layout (and therefore GW2AR placement) is byte-for-byte unchanged. Leave the ALU, imm_gen, forward_unit, id_ex_t, ctrl_t, and all RVFI feeds untouched.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777800160413,"end":1777800160418}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The predictor path is clearly exhausted—all those recent runs regressed. I need to shift focus to non-predictor micro-optimization angles instead. Looking back at what's been attempted, I'm seeing a pattern of failures across different approaches: ALU micro-ops had some success early on with shared multiplication, but bit-reverse and iterative division both flopped, and various register file changes haven't panned out either.\n\nThe forward-unit restructuring, dead field removal, and multiple EX stage rewrites all failed to improve things. Even the MEM-stage load mux and link-value folding attempts didn't work. So what's left unexplored? The hazard_unit stall logic seems like a promising direction—it's been flagged as a pivot point. I haven't seen direct attempts on the immediate generator either, though the J-arm path is noted as particularly deep. The data memory cone and potential simplifications within the memory stage byte-mask handling are also worth investigating, especially since moving that logic to EX already failed.\n\nLooking at the hazard_unit more closely, the stall and flush signals are all combinational logic derived from the ID/EX control signals. There might be room to simplify or restructure how these disjunctions are computed.\n\nNow I'm examining the load_use_hazard cone itself—it's checking memory reads, destination registers, and comparing against source operand indices. The 5-bit comparisons and AND gates might not actually be on the critical path, but it's worth verifying. The real bottleneck seems to be the consumer-side forwarding logic: the selection signals feeding into those 3:1 muxes that route either the original operand, the EX/MEM forward value, or the MEM/WB forward value into the ALU. Previous attempts at pre-registering match bits failed, but what if I could eliminate one of those forward paths entirely?\n\nFor LOADs specifically, the MEM/WB forward is the only one that matters—when a dependent instruction reaches EX, a LOAD that was stalled is now in MEM/WB. The EX/MEM forward path only carries ALU results anyway, never loaded data, so it's already minimal. That leaves me thinking about other bottlenecks: the immediate generator is pure bit routing with no arithmetic, and while sign-extension from bit 31 could theoretically be shared, Yosys probably already optimizes that. The PC+4 adder appears in multiple places, but I haven't fully explored whether consolidating those paths would help.\n\nThe branch condition logic is interesting—BEQ and BNE both need equality, BLT and BGE both need signed comparison, and BLTU and BGEU both need unsigned comparison. I could restructure this to compute just three base signals and use branch_op[0] to invert when needed, which might reduce the comparator overhead.\n\nFor the hazard unit, I'm noticing that `dmem_stall` is a simple AND of whether memory isn't ready and we're doing a memory operation. The `ex_mem_mem_op` signal itself is just unpacking the control struct at the top level—I could precompute that as a bit in the ex_mem_t struct to avoid the combinational logic, though that risks touching struct layout which r11s0 warns against.\n\nAnother possibility is merging mem_write and mem_read into a single mem_op bit since they're mutually exclusive, then using that for hazard detection. But again, that changes struct layout.\n\nI'm also looking at the misalign_fault path in ex_stage's ctrl_with_trap logic...\n\nActually, let me step back and think about what's really constraining Fmax now. The shared multiplier in r1s0 was a big win, which suggests the EX combinational depth was the bottleneck. After the recent optimizations, the binding path is likely still in EX—either the ALU for multiply/shift operations, the load data cone in MEM, the new JAL fast-path adder in ID, or somewhere in the fetch and decode pipeline.\n\nThe parallel adder for PC + immediate in ID that shipped with r4s2 might have become critical itself. Earlier attempts to optimize it failed, so that's probably locked in place.\n\nLooking at the forwarding unit, I notice it's doing register comparisons across pipeline stages to detect data hazards. The current priority scheme uses cascading if-else logic. I could try flattening that into explicit priority encoding, but given that r10s0 already tried narrowing the reg_write signal and hit verification issues, I'm skeptical this path will work either. The control signals are pretty tightly constrained in this flow.\n\nLet me shift focus to the ALU itself. It's got a lot of case arms—the base arithmetic operations, multiply, divide—and I'm noticing that LUI just passes through one operand unchanged. If I could fold LUI into the ADD operation by zeroing out one input at the EX stage, I'd eliminate one case arm entirely. The trick is setting up the decoder or ID stage to mark LUI instructions with ALU_ADD instead of ALU_LUI, and ensuring the first operand gets zeroed before it reaches the ALU.\n\nThe formal verification should hold since the output stays identical. But realistically, Yosys is probably already optimizing the case statement into a mux tree, so removing one arm from twenty won't move the needle much.\n\nI should look for something with more impact. The forwarding unit has two separate comparison chains for each register—one checking ex_mem_rd against the current rs values, another checking mem_wb_rd—giving us four 5-bit equality operators total. There might be a way to share or merge those comparison cones.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the flush logic. Right now flush_if combines redirect and imem_stall to NOP the IF/ID bundle. But if imem_stall is already holding the PC steady, the same instruction keeps flowing through the decoder each cycle. The real question is whether ID/EX captures it multiple times—stall_id depends on dmem_stall and load_use_hazard, not imem_stall, so there's a potential issue where the instruction gets decoded repeatedly without being gated downstream.\n\nThis is getting into contract territory I shouldn't mess with. Let me look for safer micro-opts instead.\n\nThe ALU's sign-extension muxes are already minimal—just a single AND gate per operand. Moving sext_a/sext_b selection to an assign statement is trivial and equivalent. But here's something that might work: precomputing the auipc mux in the ID stage by overriding rs1_val with pc at ID/EX capture time, moving that 32-bit mux out of the critical EX path. Though r4s1 tried a similar ID/EX precomputation and failed because it widened the register struct and hit the same constraints as before.\n\nWait—this time we'd reuse rs1_val without expanding id_ex_t, so the bit offsets stay the same. The catch is that rs1_val feeds RVFI's rs1_rdata, which should report the actual register value, not the pc. For AUIPC that breaks the RVFI invariant, so we'd need a separate field anyway, which brings us back to the struct expansion problem.\n\nThat's a dead end. Let me try narrowing the alu_b mux instead—the 32-bit 2:1 selector between immediate and rs2 that sits inside ex_stage.\n\nActually, that can't really be eliminated either. And sharing the branch adder with the ALU has already regressed in prior attempts.\n\nWhat about simplifying the load-use hazard detection? Right now it's checking if a load in the pipeline matches either source register, plus a nonzero check on the destination. I could precompute whether the destination is nonzero and a load at the ID stage, store that as a single bit in id_ex_t, then the hazard logic just does the register comparisons. But that still adds to the struct, which is the same tarpit risk.\n\nI'm running into the same constraints everywhere—any optimization either expands id_ex_t or gets blocked by prior regressions. Let me explore something more unconventional.\n\nExamining the memory stage write and mask generation logic...\n\nGenerating load-data extraction...\n\nThe r6s0 attempt to restructure this broke formal verification due to bitwise equivalence issues on misaligned accesses, so I'll skip that approach. The key constraint is that `reg_q.read_data` loads unconditionally and becomes part of the RVFI shadow, so every bit needs to match exactly even in don't-care misaligned cases.\n\nNow looking at a more targeted optimization: the pc+imm adder is computed twice for JAL instructions — once in the id-stage for the fast-path and again in the ex-stage for the branch/jump target. The id-stage uses a separate immediate from imm_gen, while the ex-stage reuses the same immediate through the id_ex pipeline. This duplication might be worth consolidating.\n\nActually, examining the register assignments more closely, `reg_q.branch_target` feeds into the ex_mem_t field and removing it previously caused placement regressions, so that's not a clean win either.\n\nLet me focus on the hazard-unit stall logic instead. The current control signals share several common terms like dmem_stall, load_use_hazard, imem_stall, and redirect across multiple consumers. The flush_id signal in particular combines load_use_hazard and redirect with a negated dmem_stall condition — there might be room to simplify this boolean expression or reduce the number of distinct signal dependencies.\n\nLooking at how id_stage actually uses these signals: when dmem_stall is high, we hold; when load_use_hazard is high without dmem_stall, we clear; when redirect is high without dmem_stall, we clear; otherwise we capture. The logic checks out, but I'm wondering if there's a way to restructure the register update logic itself to reduce LUT usage...\n\nActually, let me step back. The real bottleneck is probably the forward_unit fanout from the pipeline registers. I could try precomputing `reg_write && (rd != 0)` inside the registers themselves, but that either changes the struct fields or breaks the reg_write signal—I already hit that wall with r10s0 and r12s1.\n\nDifferent angle: what if I split the ALU's massive case statement into separate blocks? The current 19-arm case has logarithmic mux depth, but I could carve out DIV/REM into its own sub-block and keep the common operations in the base result path.\n\nIf I derive `is_mul` and `is_divrem` category bits combinationally from the opcode, I can restructure the case into three smaller muxes feeding a final 3:1 mux. That might save a LUT level on the ALU output. The risk is touching the ctrl_t struct again, which has been a tarpit before.\n\nBut honestly, Yosys is already doing mux balancing on the current case statement, so just rewriting it in SystemVerilog probably won't help. The real win would be if I explicitly compute the multiplier output as a shared wire—muxing between the low 32 bits for MUL and the high 32 bits for MULH variants—then feed that into the final case. Yosys might not recognize that optimization on its own.\n\nActually, looking at the branch condition logic, I notice all the comparison operations can be factored down to three base signals: equality, signed less-than, and unsigned less-than. Then I can use the branch opcode bits to select which one and optionally invert it. This is cleaner and might save some logic.\n\nBut I'm realizing this is still pretty marginal. The real bottleneck I keep hitting is that moving the forwarding unit match earlier requires handling trap-gating differently, and that's what killed the r12s1 attempt.\n\nLet me step back and think about what's actually achievable here. Maybe the safest move is to simplify the trap control logic in the execute stage by precomputing which register write signals should be suppressed when a misalignment fault occurs, rather than doing all those mux operations inline.\n\nActually, looking at how the trap gating works now, it's already pretty direct—just setting illegal and clearing reg_write when a fault happens. The synthesizer probably optimizes this down already.\n\nI think my best bet is to focus on the immediate generation module. I can hoist the sign-extension of bit 31 as a shared signal that feeds into multiple immediate formats, since several types (I, S, B, J) all need that same sign-extended upper portion.\n\nBut honestly, Yosys is already doing common subexpression elimination on this kind of thing. I keep circling back to optimizations the synthesizer handles automatically.\n\nLet me step back—I've been exploring preflopping the JAL target, removing unused fields from the pipeline structs, and tightening the hazard unit's stall logic, but each one either regresses performance or is already implemented. The hazard unit in particular has already been optimized to avoid stalling on memory operations when there's nothing in flight.\n\nI think the real move here is to focus on the hazard unit's stall disjunction. When `imem_stall` is high, the `load_use_hazard` condition becomes irrelevant since we'll re-evaluate it next cycle anyway. Similarly, `dmem_stall` being high makes some of the other conditions redundant. If I can simplify that logic by recognizing these don't-care conditions, I might actually reduce gate count without sacrificing correctness.\n\nBut looking at the actual OR gates involved—three inputs on a 4-LUT fabric is already pretty tight. The `flush_id` logic is similarly constrained. These aren't going to compress much further.\n\nLet me settle on something concrete: I'll propose pre-computing the shift amount in the EX stage by combining the immediate and register paths early, so the ALU only needs to handle the actual shift operation rather than muxing between two different shift-amount sources.\n\nActually, wait—the mux between immediate and register is already happening before the ALU gets the operand, so extracting just the 5-bit shift amount from that muxed result doesn't save anything.\n\nI think the real win is decoupling the RVFI observability path from the fetch-redirect logic. Right now `pc_next` and `redirect_target` share the same jump and branch target signals, creating unnecessary fanout. If I split them so the RVFI path computes its own next-PC independently from the redirect cone, I can reduce the critical path pressure on those target signals.\n\nBut that would duplicate the adder, which probably costs more area than it saves.\n\nLet me try something concrete instead: the ALU's final mux has a wide default case that might cause Yosys to generate unnecessarily wide select logic. If I explicitly restrict the case to only legal operations and remove the default arm, I could trim some LUTs.\n\nActually, here's the move I'll go with—merge the two adders in the jump target computation. Right now JALR uses one adder for `rs1 + imm` and JAL uses another for `pc + imm`, then a mux picks between them. I can use a single adder by muxing the first operand: feed `rs1` for JALR and `pc` for JAL into one adder, then apply the alignment logic afterward.\n\nThe critical path should stay the same—both approaches have an adder plus a mux in series—but I'm worried about the pre-adder mux adding delay on the redirect cone. Previous attempts at widening the ALU operand mux regressed timing, though this is a separate dedicated adder so it shouldn't serialize with the ALU itself.\n\nLooking at the carry-chain structure on Gowin GW2AR, putting a LUT in front of the adder forces the mux-then-carry sequence, whereas the original output-side mux lets the adder finish first. Hard to predict which Yosys will prefer. The real win is area—collapsing two distinct adders into one saves roughly 32 LUTs—but on a 94.8%-full fabric, that area savings might not translate to Fmax gains, and the pre-adder mux could still hurt the redirect path.\n\nChecking against prior lessons: r2s0 routed branch comparison through the ALU's full carry chain, which is different from my jump-target consolidation. r7s1 broke CSE by widening the operand mux, but my proposal only touches the jump path, not the ALU cone. The formal verification is straightforward since jump_target remains bitwise-identical, and the Fmax impact should be neutral or slightly positive. I'm confident this is low-risk, so I'll proceed with the YAML. Let me verify that jump_target is only used in the redirect cone...\n\nChecking where jump_target is assigned...\n\nMerging the two adders into one with a mux on the first operand—using rs1 for JALR and pc for JAL—then applying the tail bit operations. This saves one adder (~32 LUTs) while keeping the redirect cone depth the same.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded2535a5001GU9GHjlcbbWPKt","sessionID":"ses_212de74a8ffeoP4asD6RbV8NCf","messageID":"msg_ded218c08001SHEuvVFjZhL3jY"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777800160423,"sessionID":"ses_212de74a8ffeoP4asD6RbV8NCf","part":{"id":"prt_ded25215c001JGay9ttWerjEJi","messageID":"msg_ded218c08001SHEuvVFjZhL3jY","sessionID":"ses_212de74a8ffeoP4asD6RbV8NCf","type":"text","text":"Looking at the extensive history, the predictor angles are conclusively exhausted (r3s2, r6s2, r7s2, r10s2, r11s2, r12s2 all regressed across 4 topologies). Many micro_opts failed due to CSE-already-done surprises (r4s1, r9s0, r9s1) or struct/cone edits breaking placement (r11s0, r12s1) or formal tarpits (r7s0, r8s0, r10s0).\n\nLet me look for an untried, structurally-local Fmax/area angle that doesn't touch id_ex_t, ctrl.reg_write domain, fetch-redirect cone form, or pre-flop RVFI shadow.\n\nOne angle I don't see in the lessons: ex_stage currently computes **two distinct 32-bit adders** — `rs1+imm` (jalr_sum) and `pc+imm` (for branch_target/JAL's jump_target). Unlike the `pc+4` case (r4s1), these have different `a`-operands so Yosys CSE cannot share them. Merging via an operand-side 2:1 on the adder input is a known-safe pattern for jump-target computation specifically, and it's separate from the ALU cone (so it avoids r2s0/r7s1's \"serialized through ALU\" failure mode).","time":{"start":1777800126812,"end":1777800160422}}}
