{"type":"text","timestamp":1777800187973,"sessionID":"ses_212de74a8ffeoP4asD6RbV8NCf","part":{"id":"prt_ded25f4fc001uThWuiU1MgDWt5","messageID":"msg_ded25a4dc00151H1m9djxA9lK1","sessionID":"ses_212de74a8ffeoP4asD6RbV8NCf","type":"text","text":"I've written the hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary of the proposal:**\n\nGiven that predictors are conclusively exhausted (4 failed topologies) and many micro_opts hit documented tarpits (struct edits, ctrl.reg_write domain, fetch-redirect cone form, packed-struct offsets, MEM load cone, ALU serialization), I picked a narrow local Fmax/area target that avoids all 15+ documented failure-mode classes:\n\n**Merge `jalr_sum = rs1+imm` and `branch_target = pc+imm` into one shared adder with an upstream 2:1 operand mux** (`jsum_a = is_jalr ? rs1 : pc; jsum = jsum_a + imm`).\n\nKey reasoning:\n- Unlike the `pc+4` case (r4s1), these two adders have **different a-operands** so Yosys cannot CSE them — they're genuinely two independent 32-bit carry chains today.\n- Mutual exclusion between BRANCH (0x63) and JALR (0x67) opcodes makes `branch_target = jsum` bitwise-identical on every cycle where is_branch=1.\n- Path depth analysis: before = (carry chain) || (carry chain) → mux → mux; after = mux → (carry chain) → mux — same LUT depth, one fewer carry chain.\n- Structurally avoids: ALU cone (r2s0/r7s1), id_ex_t symbols (r7s0), struct offsets (r11s0), reg_write domain (r10s0), redirect-cone Boolean form (r8s0/r9s2), MEM-load cone (r6s0).\n- Keeps `reg_q.branch_target <= branch_target` flop-write to preserve packed struct layout per r11s0.\n\nExpected: +2% (low confidence) — small LUT area win on 94.8%-full GW2AR with equivalent Fmax path depth.","time":{"start":1777800180988,"end":1777800187971}}}
