{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777801479312,"sessionID":"ses_212cbcc4fffebpiL6Hrcu0tTBS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_018uiHLWFPrMmbFqJa88CXML","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Verify hypotheses directory exists"},"output":"hyp-20260503-002-r14s1.yaml\nhyp-20260503-003-r14s2.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260503-002-r14s1.yaml\nhyp-20260503-003-r14s2.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"Verify hypotheses directory exists","truncated":false},"title":"Verify hypotheses directory exists","time":{"start":1777801479308,"end":1777801479311}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the immediate-value computation in core.sv, I'm seeing how the J-format instruction's immediate gets reconstructed from scattered bits across the instruction encoding—sign extension from bit 31, then the various fields reassembled in the correct order to form the full 21-bit immediate value.\n\nThe key insight is that this same immediate calculation happens in imm_gen.sv for the JAL opcode, both pulling from the same instruction wire, so Yosys might optimize away the duplication but there's no guarantee. More significantly though, the pc+immediate adder that computes the jump target only exists in core.sv and runs in parallel with imm_gen's immediate extraction at the id_stage, so there's no redundancy there.\n\nNow I'm examining the hazard unit's flush logic and how stall and flush signals interact to control the pipeline—looking at the truth table of what happens when these signals combine, and tracing through the logic to understand when bubbles actually get inserted versus when the pipeline holds or captures new instructions.\n\nAfter working through the signal combinations, I realize the flush and stall interaction isn't as simplifiable as I initially thought. Given the time constraints, I'm going to propose the J-immediate sharing idea as a modest, safe optimization: refactor imm_gen to output separate immediate \"buckets\" for each instruction type, then feed the J-immediate bucket to both the final mux in id_ex and directly to the jump target adder in core.sv, giving Yosys an explicit single source to work with.\n\nActually, the cleaner approach is to compute J-immediate once in core.sv as a named wire and pass it to id_stage as an input port, so both the JAL arm of imm_gen and the jump target adder use the same signal. It's semantically safe—just moving computation across a module boundary—but the impact is probably small, maybe 1-3% if Yosys wasn't already CSE'ing across modules well.\n\nThat feels speculative though. Let me look at the EX stage for something more substantial—the branch_cond computation is a 6-way case mux that feeds into redirect, which might have more optimization potential.\n\nRefactoring the branch condition logic to explicitly compute three shared comparators... I'm seeing that the XOR approach with a multiplexer could work structurally, but touching the branch resolution and redirect cone is risky—earlier attempts like r2s0 and r8s1 that modified this area caused regressions and formal verification issues. Given that lesson, I'll skip this refactoring and move forward with committing the ID-stage J-immediate changes instead.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded39c102001Be0pS4rsfQsumj","sessionID":"ses_212cbcc4fffebpiL6Hrcu0tTBS","messageID":"msg_ded39368c0013vheuPhgIgxgND"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777801479642,"sessionID":"ses_212cbcc4fffebpiL6Hrcu0tTBS","part":{"id":"prt_ded39b25c001zDoFuMYq4qP4dP","messageID":"msg_ded39368c0013vheuPhgIgxgND","sessionID":"ses_212cbcc4fffebpiL6Hrcu0tTBS","type":"text","text":"Given the exhaustive exploration — with 6 consecutive predictor regressions closing that space, and the formal tarpit making most PC-redirect/id_ex/RVFI-observable edits unsafe — I'll propose a narrow, formal-safe micro-opt that follows the r4s2 \"local shared wire\" template.\n\nThe observation: `core.sv` computes `id_jal_imm` as a 32-bit J-type immediate from `if_id_w.instr`, and `imm_gen.sv` (called from `id_stage`) computes the IDENTICAL J-imm expression from the same `in.instr` wire for its JAL arm. These are two separate combinational cones on the same source bits. Yosys may or may not CSE across module boundaries reliably. An explicit single-source `imm_j` wire makes the sharing structural.\n\nThis change:\n- Doesn't touch `id_ex_t` struct, RVFI ports, PC-redirect cone, or any reset path\n- Doesn't add state (no flops, no shadow bits)\n- Keeps `id_jal_aligned` gate intact (r13s2 lesson)\n- Leaves `redirect`/`redirect_target` arbitration byte-identical (r4s2 topology preserved)\n- Is a pure structural refactor across the id_stage↔core.sv boundary\n\nLet me verify the exact shape of both computations one more time, then write the hypothesis.","time":{"start":1777801474652,"end":1777801479640}}}
