{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777801508421,"sessionID":"ses_212cbcc4fffebpiL6Hrcu0tTBS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01LotbifuoLTxZjF3Hmc6AhV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r14s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r14s0\ntitle: \"Share J-immediate compute between imm_gen and id_jal_target via explicit imm_j wire\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The r4s2 JAL fast-path (current best +17.73%) added `id_jal_imm` as a\n  32-bit J-type immediate bit-permute in core.sv:\n\n    assign id_jal_imm = {{11{if_id_w.instr[31]}}, if_id_w.instr[31],\n                         if_id_w.instr[19:12],    if_id_w.instr[20],\n                         if_id_w.instr[30:21],    1'b0};\n\n  imm_gen.sv's JAL arm independently computes the IDENTICAL bit-permute\n  on the same source wire (in.instr, driven by if_id_w.instr via\n  id_stage's input port):\n\n    7'b1101111:\n      imm = {{11{instr[31]}}, instr[31], instr[19:12],\n             instr[20], instr[30:21], 1'b0};\n\n  These are two combinational cones on the same 32 source bits,\n  producing the identical 32-bit output. Yosys MAY CSE across module\n  boundaries (imm_gen is its own module, called from id_stage), but\n  this isn't guaranteed — cross-module CSE is weaker than within-module\n  CSE in most Yosys flows, especially after flatten passes when\n  placement heuristics have already bound each instance's logic to a\n  region.\n\n  The hypothesis: by making the shared J-immediate an EXPLICIT named\n  wire in core.sv (`imm_j`), exposed as a new input port on id_stage\n  (fed to imm_gen for the JAL arm) AND consumed by the id_jal_target\n  adder, we collapse the two cones into one structurally-shared signal\n  with one bit-permute network. On the 94.8%-full GW2AR fabric, even a\n  tiny reduction in duplicate combinational logic frees LUT headroom\n  and may let Gowin place the ID-side decode+JAL-target cluster more\n  favorably, similar to how r1s0's shared 33x33 multiplier unlocked\n  Fmax gains beyond the mux-width savings alone.\nhypothesis: |\n  Refactor the J-immediate computation so there is exactly one source\n  of truth shared between id_stage's imm_gen (for id_ex.imm) and\n  core.sv's id_jal_target adder (for the r4s2 fast-path). Changes:\n\n  1. core.sv: define `imm_j` as an explicit 32-bit wire computed from\n     if_id_w.instr using the standard J-type bit-permute. Remove the\n     duplicate id_jal_imm local; assign id_jal_target = if_id_w.pc +\n     imm_j directly.\n\n  2. id_stage.sv: add an input port `imm_j_in [31:0]` threaded from\n     core.sv. Pass it into imm_gen.\n\n  3. imm_gen.sv: add an input port `imm_j_in [31:0]`. For the JAL\n     opcode arm (7'b1101111), assign imm = imm_j_in rather than\n     recomputing the bit-permute locally. All other arms (I/S/B/U\n     types) keep their existing inline computation — only the JAL\n     (J-type) arm changes. This narrows imm_gen's biggest bit-permute\n     arm (J-imm has the most scrambled bit shuffle of the five imm\n     types) to a pass-through wire.\n\n  Correctness: the J-type bit-permute expression is identical in both\n  locations today (verified by reading both files — same bit slicing,\n  same sign-extension width, same imm[0]=0 constant). The refactor\n  only changes which module physically owns the bit-permute; the\n  resulting 32-bit value is unchanged cycle-by-cycle, across all\n  reachable states (including symbolic post-reset states the BMC\n  explores). No pipeline register is modified, no ctrl_t field\n  changes, id_ex_t is byte-identical, the RVFI port set is\n  untouched, the PC-redirect priority mux shape (2:1 at core.sv\n  between ex_redirect and id_jal_target) is preserved exactly as in\n  r4s2. No new state bits, no shadow flops (sidesteps r13s1),\n  no rename of any id_ex_t field (sidesteps r7s0), no alignment-check\n  deletion (sidesteps r13s2), no upstream reg_write narrowing\n  (sidesteps r10s0), no fetch-redirect Boolean restructuring\n  (sidesteps r8s0).\n\n  Expected mechanism: on the near-full GW2AR, the duplicate\n  bit-permute may currently be synthesized as two sets of wires\n  placed in different slices (imm_gen's instance placed near id_stage\n  flops; id_jal_imm placed near the PC-redirect mux in core.sv).\n  Consolidating to one explicit wire lets the router put a single\n  permute near the common consumer region, potentially shortening\n  the net fanout from if_id_w.instr to both consumers and reducing\n  LUT count by the (modest) duplication delta. Gain is expected to\n  be small (~1-4%) but with very low regression risk given the\n  refactor's structural minimality.\n\n  If fitness is flat or slightly negative, the learning is that\n  Yosys's cross-module CSE was already handling this case, which is\n  itself useful negative knowledge — it narrows future speculative\n  \"share this across modules\" hypotheses. If positive, it validates\n  explicit-sharing as a generally-productive pattern on GW2AR and\n  opens similar sharings (e.g., pc+4 adders, branch-offset computes)\n  for future micro_opt slots.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Introduce explicit imm_j wire (J-type bit-permute from if_id_w.instr), remove local id_jal_imm, wire imm_j into id_stage's new imm_j_in input port, and drive id_jal_target = if_id_w.pc + imm_j.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add imm_j_in [31:0] input port, thread it to imm_gen's new imm_j_in port. No id_ex_t changes, no reset changes, no control-flow changes.\"\n  - file: rtl/imm_gen.sv\n    description: \"Add imm_j_in [31:0] input port. In the 7'b1101111 (JAL) case arm of the imm-type case statement, replace the inline bit-permute expression with a direct assignment imm = imm_j_in. All other case arms (I/S/B/U/default) unchanged.\"\n"},