{"type":"text","timestamp":1777801516610,"sessionID":"ses_212cbcc4fffebpiL6Hrcu0tTBS","part":{"id":"prt_ded3a3d9b00138FLQ2KU2nNavD","messageID":"msg_ded3a36c7001yWKeIqQUImZlJw","sessionID":"ses_212cbcc4fffebpiL6Hrcu0tTBS","type":"text","text":"Written `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r14s0.yaml`.\n\nSummary of the proposal:\n\n**Title:** Share J-immediate compute between `imm_gen` and `id_jal_target` via explicit `imm_j` wire\n\n**Category:** micro_opt\n**Expected delta:** +2% (low confidence)\n\n**Rationale for this angle given the lesson space:**\n- Predictor space fully exhausted (r3s2/r6s2/r7s2/r10s2/r11s2/r12s2 all regressed) — pivoted away per guidance\n- Formal tarpit rules out: id_ex_t edits (r7s0), shadow flops (r13s1), PC-redirect reshaping (r8s0), reset changes (r4s0/r5s1/r6s0/r6s1), alignment-check deletion (r13s2), reg_write domain narrowing (r10s0), struct-layout edits (r11s0)\n- Shared-logic refactors have a proven-win template (r1s0's +9.47% shared 33×33 multiplier)\n- r4s2 left behind a duplicate J-imm bit-permute that sits on the ID-side of the redirect cone — an explicit-sharing refactor doesn't touch any tarpit surface\n\n**Key safety properties:** zero new state, zero struct edits, zero RVFI changes, zero PC-redirect Boolean restructuring, r4s2's 2:1 arbiter topology preserved byte-identical. Worst case is flat fitness confirming Yosys already CSEs cross-module (itself useful negative knowledge).","time":{"start":1777801510299,"end":1777801516608}}}
