{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777802635656,"sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01L53habWSxxVdS6FJHUqWGd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg \"title.*(alu|adder|carry|mul|shift)\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl -o | head -30","description":"Check ALU hypotheses attempted"},"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","metadata":{"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","exit":0,"description":"Check ALU hypotheses attempted","truncated":false},"title":"Check ALU hypotheses attempted","time":{"start":1777802635652,"end":1777802635656}},"id":"prt_ded4b6951001MRr65YEAU4WjFE","sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","messageID":"msg_ded49659900138LHIG1NFrRxEs"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777802635658,"sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01RgZfG6JQR6BoW8rBp4tQm4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -l \"hazard\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -3; echo \"---\"; rg \"hazard_unit|stall_if|stall_id\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl -c","description":"Check prior hazard_unit hypotheses"},"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\nzsh:1: command not found: rg\n---\n","metadata":{"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\nzsh:1: command not found: rg\n---\n","exit":127,"description":"Check prior hazard_unit hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"Check prior hazard_unit hypotheses","time":{"start":1777802635654,"end":1777802635657}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the fitness score of 387.98 with r4s2 JAL fast-path performing best in the micro_opt diversity slot, I'm seeing a clear pattern: predictors have completely failed across all four topologies, while structural changes to id_ex_t and fetch-redirect components are creating formal verification issues, and the shared-adder refactoring approach isn't working either.\n\nDead-field cleanups, WB-side load cone relocations, and forward-unit consumer-side restructuring have all regressed. Explicit CSE sharing yields nothing since Yosys already handles it, and multi-cycle MUL/DIV operations plus the SLL bit-reverse trick both made things worse.\n\nNow I'm looking at what hasn't been explored yet. The hazard_unit stall disjunct could be simplified beyond just adding a shadow flop, the memory stage's dmem read output is currently combinational, and there's potential in decoder and immediate generator restructuring. But the regfile write-first bypass mux seems most promising—it's sitting on the ID-stage critical path, and the current implementation uses a combinational mux to select between write-back data and the register file read, which might be where I can find real gains.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the write-first bypass might be redundant with the forward unit's MEM/WB leg. When instruction A in WB writes to x5 and instruction B in ID reads x5, the regfile gives B the new value immediately, which gets latched into the pipeline. By the time B reaches EX, A is already retired, so no forwarding is needed. But the forward unit's MEM/WB path handles a different scenario—when B is already in EX and A is still in MEM/WB. So they're actually covering different cases, and I need to think through whether both are truly necessary or if one can subsume the other.\n\nNow I'm looking at the hazard unit's flush logic and the dmem_stall gating. The redirect signal comes from ex_redirect, and dmem_stall is computed as a combinational OR of mem_read and mem_write bits from the EX/MEM register. I'm wondering if we could register that OR instead of computing it combinationally—r13s1 tried adding a shadow flop before and it broke formal verification, but that was introducing a new register. The question is whether we could replace the combinational logic itself without breaking anything.\n\nI'm hypothesizing that on GW2AR at 172 MHz, the critical path is likely in the EX stage's forwarding mux feeding into the ALU—that 3:1 mux plus the ALU case logic plus the 33-bit multiplier. The operand-B mux for the ALU is already minimal since alu_src is known at decode. But the shift amount logic is interesting: for immediate shifts (SLLI/SRLI/SRAI), shamt comes from imm[4:0], and for register shifts (SLL/SRL/SRA), it comes from rs2[4:0]. There might be room to decode shamt earlier.\n\nActually, extracting shamt with a separate 5-bit mux doesn't help—it's still just a mux. Let me consider other micro-optimizations instead. Narrowing the dmem_addr output won't work since the FPGA bench might decode those top bits. But the forward_unit priority encoder is worth examining—currently it's a cascading if-else that produces a 2-bit selector, and I'm looking at how the EX consumer uses that selector...\n\nExamining forward_unit logic... Looking at the hazard unit's stall and flush logic, I see the load-use hazard signal has wide fanout across multiple pipeline stages. I'm wondering if I could precompute this earlier—maybe register a \"next cycle will have load-use\" flag so the critical path doesn't depend on comparing `id_ex_rd` against the current operands. Alternatively, I could add a `id_ex_rd_nonzero` bit to the pipeline register to avoid the zero-check in the hazard detection itself.\n\nBut I'm running into the same issue: the load-use check inherently spans two cycles—comparing the *previous* cycle's decoded destination against the *current* cycle's source registers. There's no way around that dependency without changing the pipeline structure.\n\nI've tried several other approaches to reduce fanout or simplify the control logic. Removing redundant reset logic broke things in multiple revisions. Packing fewer bits into the pipeline registers to reuse flops creates formal verification headaches. Now I'm looking at simplifying the misalignment fault detection in the EX stage—the branch and jump target alignment checks can be compressed since the PC is always aligned, so only the immediate's lower bits matter.\n\nFor branches, the B-type immediate encoding means bit 1 comes directly from instruction bit 8, so a misaligned branch only occurs when that bit is set. But this relies on the invariant that PC[1:0] is always zero, which the formal tools haven't proven inductively, so removing this check would break verification.\n\nNow I'm looking at whether I can simplify the sign-extension logic for multiply operations. The current implementation uses a case statement to set sign-extension flags differently for MULHU and MULHSU versus other operations. I could express this more directly as boolean comparisons against the opcode, though Yosys might already optimize the case mux anyway. The real insight is that only the three M-extension multiply operations actually use these high-word results...\n\nActually, let me reconsider the whole approach. MUL only needs the low 32 bits where sign doesn't matter, while MULH needs both operands sign-extended, MULHU needs neither extended, and MULHSU needs only the first operand extended. The current code already handles this efficiently with the case statement, so there's probably no meaningful optimization here.\n\nLet me pivot to something else entirely. Looking at the EX stage, I notice that branch_target and branch_taken are being written to the EX/MEM register but never actually read downstream—they're just dead flip-flops sitting there. When r11s0 tried removing these fields, it caused a 23% regression, which suggests the struct packing changes disrupted placement and routing rather than the logic itself being wrong.\n\nThe WB stage is essentially three lines of combinational logic, so inlining it into the core wouldn't save anything structurally. For the memory stage's barrel shifter, the expression `dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0] * 8)` gets optimized to a shift by 0/8/16/24, but r6s0 showed that explicit muxing broke formal verification, and r14s1 demonstrated that MEM-to-WB relocations cause significant regressions.\n\nBoth EX and MEM stages have similar logic for handling misalignment faults—they conditionally set is_illegal and clear reg_write when a misalign_fault occurs. This cone could potentially be simplified or unified.\n\nThe ID stage's JAL fast-path opcode compare is part of the critical timing path in r4s2. Moving just the 7-bit opcode check to IF stage and registering it could help, since r8s2 showed that moving the full adder there caused setup violations due to carry chain duplication. The question is whether isolating just the opcode compare would yield timing gains without the same penalty.\n\nNow looking at the load_use_hazard logic — currently it compares the flopped id_ex_rd against the combinational if_id_rs1/rs2 fields from the current instruction. Pre-flopping those compare results in the ID stage would require capturing whether the *next* instruction's source registers match the current cycle's destination register, which is a cross-cycle dependency that complicates the pipeline.\n\nMoving on to other potential optimizations: the dmem_wen and dmem_ren gating in the MEM stage is already tied to the ALU's low bits through the misalignment check, so there's no easy win there. Replicating store data before flopping was already tried and caused a significant regression. The decoder's opcode case statement follows standard patterns without obvious simplification. The forward unit's priority mux versus one-hot mux synthesize to the same result. Now examining the immediate generator logic...\n\nStill writing imm_gen...\n\nThe sign-extension field reuses instr[31] across multiple formats, so factoring out a single sign bit computation could theoretically help, but Yosys likely already performs this optimization. The ALU's shift operations use three separate structures, and attempts to fold SLL into SRL via bit-reversal previously regressed. Even combining just SRL and SRA into one structure wouldn't gain much since Yosys already recognizes they're both right-shifts with different fill behavior. Pre-decoding alu_src into the IF/ID combinational path isn't applicable since it's already flopped in id_ex_w.ctrl.alu_src. I need to think about what genuinely small, overlooked optimizations might still be available.\n\nCollapsing branch_op encoding from 3 bits down to 2 bits plus a secondary bit is theoretically possible since only 6 of 8 values are legal, but re-encoding everything would likely yield no real benefit. Looking at the decoder's jump-related signals, JAL and JALR both set is_jump, but only JALR sets is_jalr, and only ID-path JAL sets jal_predicted. The redirect logic in EX evaluates whether a jump wasn't already predicted in ID, which happens when the fast-path stalls or the target misaligns. I'm trying to see if there's redundancy in how these signals interact that could be simplified.\n\nNow I'm reviewing the remaining optimization candidates: the shared multiplier gained 9%, the JAL fast-path gained 17.7%, and most other strategies have been ruled out. The most promising untested idea is to keep the multiplier always-signed and correct MULHU/MULHSU results afterward, avoiding the sign-extension mux overhead. But there's also a simpler angle: the write-first bypass in the register file creates a timing chain from the memory-to-writeback flop through the data mux and into the register file bypass logic, which feeds into ID stage. This path might be worth optimizing.\n\nActually, let me trace through whether removing the write-first bypass entirely would break correctness. If instruction A writes to x5 in the WB stage during cycle T, and instruction B reads x5 in ID during that same cycle, B would get the old value without bypass. By cycle T+1, B moves to EX and A retires, so the forward unit's MEM/WB leg should catch the dependency—but I need to verify whether A's write is already committed to the register file by then or if it's still in flight.\n\nAt the clock edge transitioning from T to T+1, A's write commits to the register file, but A's mem_wb register gets overwritten with the next instruction. So at T+1, the forward unit can't see A anymore—B would read stale data. The write-first bypass is actually necessary to prevent this hazard.\n\nI could try extending the pipeline so B reads one cycle later, but that's a major restructuring. Another angle: precompute the write data selection in the MEM stage instead of WB, but that just shifts the mux earlier and doesn't really help the critical path. Or I could optimize the forward unit's write-enable check by precomputing the validity signal in the EX stage to save one AND gate at the consumer, though that's a minor savings.\n\nI also considered gating `reg_write` at the decoder level when rd=0, but that broke formal verification before. Similarly, gating `mem_read` with the rd!=0 check inside ID stage would save an AND in the hazard unit, but it changes the semantics of the control signal and would likely trip formal again. Adding a new id_ex field like `load_use_check` would work but adds complexity.\n\nLet me explore a different direction: shortening the reset cone...\n\nAll registers reset synchronously, and the reset signal fans out to many flops. Some might not need reset, which could help placement in Gowin. But removing reset from the register file broke formal before, and the pipeline registers probably need their reset to anchor the BMC for riscv-formal. The branch condition logic using XNOR for BEQ/BNE is another option, but those comparators run in parallel with the ALU and likely aren't on the critical path anyway.\n\nLooking back at what's actually been proven critical: the EX forward path shows up repeatedly as a bottleneck, and the MEM pre-flop load cone is also tight. The ID→PC redirect cone had slack, so that's not where the pressure is.\n\nIn the EX stage, the forward mux is a 3:1 on 32 bits for each of rs1 and rs2, then the ALU gets a 4:1 mux for its a-input and another 4:1 for its b-input before the result fans out. The AUIPC path is already optimized—when AUIPC is selected, pc routes directly. I'm considering whether we could drop the MEM/WB forwarding leg and rely on the regfile's write-first bypass instead, but that won't work because the EX stage reads from the ID/EX register's flopped rs1_val, which was captured before the WB write happened in the same cycle. Delaying that capture would add a cycle of latency, which defeats the purpose. Let me look for a more modest optimization that's actually safe to try.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded4b69200012Je7NX4vJ6Mzgb","sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","messageID":"msg_ded49659900138LHIG1NFrRxEs"}}
