 in.imm`, identical to\\njump_target's non-JALR arm. So the outer is_jump mux is structurally\\nredundant: every non-JALR taken-redirect (both JAL and taken-BRANCH)\\nresolves to in.pc + in.imm, and the only architecturally-distinct case is\\nJALR, which picks {jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}.\\nredirect_target feeds core.sv's EX-vs-ID arbitration mux (2:1) then\\nif_stage's PC-select mux (2:1) then the PC D-input \\u2014 i.e. this net is on\\nthe fetch-redirect critical cone that has repeatedly dominated Fmax on\\nthis near-full (9484...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Flatten EX redirect cone: distribute misalign into per-arm align-check\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage `redirect` net feeds IF's PC-select mux and is on the\\nfetch-redirect critical path \\u2014 any LUT-level we can remove there\\ntranslates directly into Fmax on GW2AR's near-full fabric. Today\\nthe cone is an AND-of-OR structure: redirect = (BT || (J &&\\n!JP)) && !misalign_fault, where misalign_fault = (is_branch &&\\nBT && misalign_branch_target) || (is_jump && misalign_jump_target).\\nThe branch_taken signal appears in BOTH operands of the outer AND\\n(directly in the first OR, and transitively via misalign_branch\\nin the second OR), forcing Yosys to realize the compare-compute\\nand align-check as a serial chain feeding the `redirect` wire\\nrather than two parallel-then-combined cones. This lengthens the\\nEX\\u2192IF redirect path by ~1 LUT level on this fabric.\\n\\nSeven prior slot-1 structural attempts have all regressed or\\nbroken formal \\u2014 the survivors were those that stayed local (no\\nid_ex_t edit, no PC-mux widening, no cross-flop mux moves, no\\nnew storage). This hypothesis is chosen to satisfy ALL of those\\nconstraints simultaneously.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage `redirect` net feeds IF's PC-select mux and is on the\\nfetch-redirect critical path \\u2014 any LUT-level we can remove there\\ntranslates directly into Fmax on GW2AR's near-full fabric. Today\\nthe cone is an AND-of-OR structure: redirect = (BT || (J &&\\n!JP)) && !misalign_fault, where misalign_fault = (is_branch &&\\nBT && misalign_branch_target) || (is_jump && misalign_jump_target).\\nThe branch_taken signal appears in BOTH operands of the outer AND\\n(directly in the first OR, and transitively via misalign_branch\\nin the second OR), forcing Yosys to realize the compare-compute\\nand align-check as a serial chain feeding the `redirect` wire\\nrather than two parallel-then-combined cones. This lengthens the\\nEX\\u2192IF re...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Pre-register JAL target at IF to lift the 32-bit adder off the ID redirect cone\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the one predictor that won on this fabric\\n(+17.73%). Every subsequent predictor variant regressed because it\\nviolated at least one of the winning constraints: no new PC-mux\\ninput (r1s2), no storage+tag array pulling LUT area (r2s2), no new\\nID-side fire-term with a misprediction arm widening the EX redirect\\nmux past 2:1 (r6s2, r7s2), no id_ex_t struct rename (r7s0).\\n\\nWhat r4s2 did NOT eliminate, though, is a 32-bit adder sitting on\\nthe ID\\u2192PC-D-in combinational cone. In core.sv today:\\n\\n    id_jal_target  = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm;         // <-- 32b adder\\n    redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_target : id_jal_target;\\n    // if_stage: PC_D = redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4;\\n\\nOn each cycle where a JAL is in ID, the PC register's D-input cone\\npasses through PC_reg \\u2192 if_id_w.pc \\u2192 32-bit carry-chain add \\u2192 2:1\\nmux (ex_redirect select) \\u2192 2:1 mux (redirect select) \\u2192 PC_D. The\\ncarry chain dominates this arm. On near-full GW2AR (9484/10000\\nLUT4), congestion-amplified routing around the carry chain is\\nexactly the sort of thing that nudges Fmax down \\u2014 and r4s2's win\\nconfirms Fmax-side gains 