 \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor design space on this core is unusually constrained: r4s2's\\nzero-storage ID-stage JAL fast-path is the only predictor ever to win\\n(+17.73%), while every attempt to add a second ID-side fire term\\n(BTFN r6s2 -23%, dirty-x1 RAS r7s2 -50%, RAC r10s2 -20%, IF-side RET\\nr11s2 -26%), widen the redirect_target arbitration mux past 2:1\\n(r7s2/r10s2), or even restructure r4s2's own winning cone (r8s2/r9s2\\n-13% to -19%) has regressed on the near-full GW2AR fabric. The\\ntransferable rule from r4s2 is that a predictor only wins when it is\\n(a) architecturally unconditional (no misprediction arm) and (b)\\nreuses the existing redirect wire topology (2:1 target arbitration\\npreserved). The unexplored angle that fits both constraints is\\nBEQ rs,rs (instr[19:15] == instr[24:20] with funct3=000): this\\nencoding is architecturally unconditional-taken (x == x is always\\ntrue) exactly like JAL, has zero misprediction cost, and its target\\nis pc + B_imm computed at ID from fields already available. GCC\\noccasionally emits BEQ x0,x0 as an unconditional branch idiom for\\nloop-header jumps and long-jump trampolines; even a modest fraction\\nof such instructions converted from 2-bubble EX redirects to\\n0-bubble ID redirects contributes to CoreMark IPC without any Fmax\\ncost on the prediction side.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor design space on this core is unusually constrained: r4s2's\\nzero-storage ID-stage JAL fast-path is the only predictor ever to win\\n(+17.73%), while every attempt to add a second ID-side fire term\\n(BTFN r6s2 -23%, dirty-x1 RAS r7s2 -50%, RAC r10s2 -20%, IF-side RET\\nr11s2 -26%), widen the redirect_target arbitration mux past 2:1\\n(r7s2/r10s2), or even restructure r4s2's own winning cone (r8s2/r9s2\\n-13% to -19%) has regressed on the near-full GW2AR fa...\n  Line 38: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"Merge jalr_sum and branch_target adders into a single shared jump-sum adder with operand-input 2:1 mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"ex_stage.sv currently instantiates TWO distinct 32-bit adders on the\\nredirect cone: `jalr_sum = rs1 + in.imm` (for JALR) and\\n`branch_target = in.pc + in.imm` (for BRANCH; also reused as JAL's\\njump_target via `in.pc + in.imm`). Unlike the pc+4 case from r4s1\\n(where Yosys can CSE two `X + 32'd4` adders because the constant-side\\nmatches), these two adders have DIFFERENT a-operands (rs1 vs pc) with\\na common b-operand (in.imm), which Yosys cannot CSE \\u2014 they synthesize\\nas two independent carry chains. On the 94.8%-full GW2AR fabric\\n(9484/10000 LUT4), reclaiming one full 32-bit carry chain (~32 LUT4 +\\n~32 carry cells) is a real area win that frees placement/routing\\npressure without touching any of the established tarpits (id_ex_t\\nsymbol table per r7s0, ctrl.reg_write activation domain per r10s0,\\nfetch-redirect cone Boolean form per r8s0, packed-struct field\\noffsets per r11s0, or the MEM-stage load-data cone per r6s0). The\\nALU-adder-serialization failure modes (r2s0 branch-through-ALU,\\nr7s1 widened ALU-operand mux) explicitly touched the ALU's shared\\ncarry chain; this proposal leaves the ALU cone untouched and only\\nmerges two ex-local adders whose outputs feed the redirect_target\\nmux and pc_next, both of which are already 2:1-mux consumers of\\nthese adders in the current RTL. This is the jump-target analogue\\nof the r1s0 shared-multiplier win (one 33x33 replaced three\\n32x32s), applied to the pc/rs1 + imm case.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"ex_stage.sv currently instantiates TWO distinct 32-bit adders on the\\nredirect cone: `jalr_sum = rs1 + in.imm` (for JALR) and\\n`branch_target = in.pc + in.imm` (for BRANCH; also reused as JAL's\\njump_target via `in.pc + in.imm`). Unlike the pc+4 case from r4s1\\n(where Yosys can CSE two `X + 32'd4` adders because the constant-s...\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r13s1\", \"titl