must tar...\n  Line 40: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"JAL fast-path: delete tautological id_jal_aligned gate\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the only predictor that has scored positive\\non this core (+17.73%). All four JALR/RET predictor topologies\\n(r3s2 4-entry RAS, r7s2 dirty-x1, r10s2 RAC, r11s2 IF-side-seq-arm)\\nregressed sharply, as did BTFN (r6s2), BEQ-rs,rs (r12s2), IF-side\\nJAL predecode (r8s2), and a Boolean-equivalent rewrite of the r4s2\\ncone itself (r9s2, -18.86%). The transferable rule from r9s2 is that\\nSUBSTITUTING one expression for another on the r4s2 cone invalidates\\nYosys's CSE/placement optimum. DELETION of a provably-redundant term\\nis a structurally different operation: it leaves the remaining cone\\nin its original form (same expression tree for the surviving\\noperands), reducing the cone's fan-in rather than reshaping it.\\n\\nThe `id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)` check is a\\ntautology for this core:\\n  - PC register resets to 0 (pc[1:0]=00).\\n  - PC updates are pc+=4 (preserves pc[1:0]=00) or redirect_target.\\n  - JAL targets: pc+J_imm, and J-imm has bit 0 \\u2261 0 by encoding, and\\n    pc[1:0]=00 invariantly \\u21d2 target[1:0]=00.\\n  - JALR: clears bit 0 explicitly via `{jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0}` in\\n    ex_stage.sv:89, and ex_stage's misalign-fault gate traps any\\n    JALR target with bit 1 set (invariant #2; target[1:0]==00 check\\n    at ex_stage.sv:101-103), preventing pc[1:0]=10 from persisting.\\n  - Branch targets: also go through ex_stage's misalign-fault gate,\\n    so branch_target[1:0]!=00 traps and does NOT redirect the PC.\\nConclusion: pc[1:0]==00 is an invariant maintained by the existing\\nRTL, and hence id_jal_target[1:0]==00 is an invariant too. The gate\\nalways evaluates to 1 at runtime.\\n\\nYosys cannot statically prove this invariant without a multi-cycle\\nanalysis it does not perform on combinational expressions, so the\\n2-bit equality check remains in synthesized logic, costing ~1 LUT\\nle...\n  Line 41: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r14s0\", \"title\": \"Share J-immediate compute between imm_gen and id_jal_target via explicit imm_j wire\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path (current best +17.73%) added `id_jal_imm` as a\\n32-bit J-type immediate bit-permute in core.sv:\\n\\n  assign id_jal_imm = {{11{if_id_w.instr[31]}}, if_id_w.instr[31],\\n                       if_id_w.instr[19:12],    if_id_w.instr[20],\\n                       if_id_w.instr[30:21],    1'b0};\\n\\nimm_gen.sv's JAL arm independently computes the IDENTICAL bit-permute\\non the same source wire (in.instr, driven by if_id_w.instr via\\nid_stage's input port):\\n\\n  7'b1101111:\\n    imm = {{11{instr[31]}}, instr[31], instr[19:12],\\n           instr[20], instr[30:21], 1'b0};\\n\\nThese are two combinational cones on the same 32 source bits,\\nproducing the identical 32-bit output. Yosys MAY CSE across module\\nboundaries (imm_gen is its own module, called from id_stage), but\\nthis isn't guaranteed \\u2014 cross-module CSE is weaker than within-module\\nCSE in most Yosys flows, especially after flatten passes when\\nplacement heuristics have already bound each instance's logic to a\\nregion.\\n\\nThe hypothesis: by making the shared J-immediate an EXPLICIT named\\nwire in core.sv (`imm_j`), exposed as a new input port on id_stage\\n(fed to imm_gen for the JAL arm) AND consumed by the id_jal_target\\nadder, we collapse the two cones into one structurally-shared signal\\nwith one bit-permute network. On the 94.8%-full GW2AR fabric, even a\\ntiny reduction in duplicate combinational logic frees LUT headroom\\nand may let Gowin place the ID-side decode+JAL-target cluster more\\nfavorably, similar to how r1s0's shared 33x33 multiplier unlocked\\nFmax gains beyond the mux-width savings alone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path (current best +17.73%) added `id_jal_imm` as a\\n32-bit J-type immediate bit-permute in core.sv:\\n\\n  assign id_jal_imm = {{11{if_id_w.instr[31]}}, if_id_w.instr[31],\\n    ...\n  Line 42: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r14s1\", \"title\": \"Rebalance pipeline: hoist load-data shift/sign-extend from MEM pre-flop to WB post-flop\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"r3s1 explicitly diagnosed the MEM pre-flop load-data cone (dmem_rdata \\u2192 shift\\nby addr[1:0]*8 \\u2192 byte/halfword mux \\u2192 sign/zero-extend \\u2192 mem_wb flop D-input)\\nas the binding MEM-side Fmax limiter on this core. Every prior MEM-side\\nattempt has *added* logic to this cone:\\n  - r3s1 folded mem_to_reg mux pre-flop \\u2192 regressed (-5.66%) because the\\n    mux's load_data input IS the tip of the critical cone, so the new mux\\n    lands in series with it.\\n  - r10s1 precomputed byte_mask at EX \\u2192 regressed (-13.48%) because the\\n    byte_mask selector `alu_result[1:0]` is the ALU carry output.\\n  - r6s0 replaced the variable shifter with explicit byte muxes \\u2192 broke\\n    formal on misaligned-addr RVFI shadow.\\nThe untried direction is the *opposite* rebalance: delete the shift+extend\\nfrom the MEM pre-flop path entirely by having WB reconstruct load_data\\ncombinationally from already-flopped mem_wb_t fields. mem_wb_t already\\ncarries `mem_rdata` (raw dmem word, for RVFI), `alu_result` (its low 2 bits\\nare the byte offset), `ctrl.mem_width`, and `ctrl.mem_sext` \\u2014 every input\\nthe shift+extend needs is already post-flop. So the structural move is\\n\\\"no struct edits, just relocate the combinational cone across the\\nmem_wb boundary.\\\"\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r3s1 explicitly diagnosed the MEM pre-flop load-data cone (dmem_rdata \\u2192 shift\\nby addr[1:0]*8 \\u2192 byte/halfword mux \\u2192 sign/zero-extend \\u2192 mem_wb flop D-input)\\nas the binding MEM-side Fmax limiter on this core. Every prior MEM-side\\nattempt has *added* logic to this cone:\\n  - r3s1 folded mem_to_reg mux pre-flop \\u2192 regressed (-5.66%) because the\\n    mux's load_data input IS the tip of the critical cone, so the new mux\\n    lands in series with it.\\n  - r10s1 precomputed byte_mask at EX \\...\n  Line 43: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r14s2\", \"title\": \"Slim JAL fast-path fire gate: drop structurally redundant `& if_id_w.valid` conjunct\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"After 13 predictor-slot iterations, r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path\\n(+17.73%) remains the sole predictor win on this core. Every extension\\nregressed: second ID-side fire term (r6s2 -23%, r7s2 -50%, r10s2 -20%,\\nr11s2 -26%, r12s2 -23%), widened redirect_target arbiter past 2:1\\n(r7s2, r10s2), new IF-side predecode adder (r8s2 -13%), equivalent\\nrewrite on the winning cone (r9s2 -19%), dead-field struct shrink\\n(r11s0 -23%), and delete-tautology gates that BMC explores (r13s2\\nbroken). The predictor search space as traditionally conceived is\\nempirically exhausted on this fabric.\\n\\nThe ONE angle that has NOT been tried, and that avoids every named\\nfailure mode in the lessons, is a minimal cone-shave INSIDE the r4s2\\nwinning gate that is a pure combinational tautology (not reachable-\\nstate-dependent). Specifically, in core.sv line ~134:\\n\\n    id_is_jal = (if_id_w.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111) & if_id_w.valid;\\n\\nThe `& if_id_w.valid` conjunct is structurally redundant: if_stage\\ndrives `out.instr = flush ? 32'h0000_0013 : imem_data` and\\n`out.valid = !flush`, so whenever valid=0 the instruction is forced\\nto ADDI x0,x0,0 whose opcode[6:0]=0010011 already fails the JAL\\nopcode compare (1101111). The conjunct is a combinational identity\\ntautology on the pair (instr[6:0], flush) \\u2014 NOT a reachable-state\\ninvariant like r13s2's pc-alignment (which BMC explored and falsified\\nfrom arbitrary initial states). No SBY BMC step can construct a case\\nwhere `instr[6:0]==1101111` holds while `valid=0`: the flush-NOP is\\nhardwired by the always_comb, so the implication is unconditional at\\nevery simulated cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After 13 predictor-slot iterations, r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path\\n(+17.73%) remains the sole predictor win on this core. Every extension\\nregressed: second ID-...","metadata":{"matches":43,"truncated":false},"title":"\"title\":","time":{"start":1777802640102,"end":1777802640125}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_ded4b795b001iYuCYiKLLwyif4","sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","messageID":"msg_ded4b6b2c001UcKYN1R2tccUld"}}
