{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777802858367,"sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01MwDW9XL5Er57Cr3ahhLU6A","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"path":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","pattern":"hazard_unit|load_use"},"output":"Found 17 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Split ALU: move MUL/DIV into multi-cycle execution unit with EX stall handshake\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defines the\\nminimum clock period for the whole core. Baseline Fmax is 135 MHz\\nwith target 135 MHz \\u2014 the core is capped by the EX cycle. CoreMark\\n6 KB executes few MUL and essentially zero DIV per iteration, so\\nremoving those ops from the EX critical path and paying for them in\\nextra cycles only on the rare MUL/DIV instruction is a strongly\\nfavorable structural tradeoff for the fitness metric\\n`iter/cycle \\u00d7 Fmax`.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defi...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage JAL direct-jump + backward-taken static branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core has zero branch prediction: every taken\\nbranch and every JAL resolves in EX and fires a redirect that\\nflushes IF/ID, costing 2 pipeline bubbles per control-transfer.\\nCoreMark spends a large fraction of its cycles in tight inner loops\\n(crclist, matrix_mul_matrix, state_machine transitions) and in\\nfunction-call glue (JAL/JALR pairs), so those 2-cycle bubbles add\\nup fast. A no-BTB predictor that uses only the freshly-fetched\\ninstruction word itself can eliminate the bubbles for two very\\ncommon and cheaply identifiable cases \\u2014 unconditional JAL (target\\nis a known function of PC+j_imm, so prediction is always correct)\\nand backward-taken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU (the classic\\nloop-back heuristic, ~85%+ accurate in practice for integer code)\\n\\u2014 without adding any stateful predictor storage (no BHT, no BTB,\\nno RAS). That keeps the LUT/FF budget near baseline (currently\\n9880/10000 LUTs) while targeting the dominant CPI contributor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core has zero branch prediction: every taken\\nbranch and every JAL resolves in EX and fires a redirect that\\nflushes IF/ID, costing 2 pipeline bubbles per control-transfer.\\nCoreMark spends a large fraction of its cycles in tight inner loops\\n(crclist, matrix_mul_matrix, state_machine transitions) and in\\nfunction-call glue (JAL/JALR pairs), so those 2-cycle bubbles add\\nup fast. A no-BTB predictor that uses only the freshly-fetched\\ninstruction word itself can eliminate the bubbles for two very\\ncommon and cheaply identifiable cases \\u2014 unconditional JAL (target\\nis a known function of PC+j_imm, so prediction is always correct)\\nand backward-taken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU (the classic\\nloop-back heuristic, ~85%+ accurate in practice for integer code)\\n\\u2014 without adding any stateful predictor...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decoupled IF/ID via 1-entry prefetch skid buffer to absorb iStall bubbles\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The cosim CoreMark fitness run drives both buses with ~22% random\\nstall (VexRiscv apples-to-apples methodology). Today's IF stage\\nhard-wires IF/ID payload to `imem_data` combinationally, and when\\n`imem_ready=0` the hazard unit forces `flush_if=1` (NOP injection)\\nand `stall_if=1` (PC holds). Every single iStall cycle therefore\\ncosts exactly one retirement opportunity \\u2014 ID/EX captures a bubble\\nthat propagates all the way to WB.\\n\\nMeanwhile, when ID stalls for reasons that DON'T involve imem\\n(load-use hazard, dmem stall) the PC reg also holds, so the fetch\\nunit just re-presents the same instruction over and over. Those\\n\\\"ID-blocked but bus-free\\\" cycles are wasted fetch bandwidth: IF is\\nfully capable of advancing PC and retrieving the next instruction\\nword during them, but the current tight IF\\u2194ID coupling prevents it.\\nAcross the CoreMark trace, load-use + dmem-stall cycles are a\\nnon-trivial fraction (MUL/LOAD-heavy matrix kernels, crclist\\npointer chasing), so prefetching during those cycles creates a\\nreservoir of already-fetched words that can be drained during\\nsubsequent iStall cycles \\u2014 directly recovering lost retirements.\\n\\nPrior attempts in this round:\\n- hyp-001-r1s0 (shared multiplier, +9.47%): freed EX-stage logic.\\n- hyp-002-r1s1 (multi-cycle MUL unit, regression): adding stalls\\n  without freeing the actual critical path hurts IPC.\\n- hyp-003-r1s2 (IF-stage static BP, regression): any logic on the\\n  PC register's combinational fan-in (predecode \\u2192 target \\u2192 PC-mux)\\n  destroys Fmax on GW2AR.\\n\\nThis hypothesis differs fundamentally from hyp-003: the prefetch\\nbuffer sits on the imem_data\\u2192ID path, NOT on the PC register's\\ncombinational cone. PC's next-state mux stays identical to today\\n(sequential vs redirect_target). The buffer's valid bit provides a\\nchea...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Registered 16-entry BTB indexed by PC (off the fetch BRAM critical path)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Branch prediction is still the biggest CPI lever on this core: every\\ntaken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/JAL/JALR resolves in EX and costs 2 pipeline\\nbubbles (flush IF + ID). CoreMark's inner loops (crc16, matrix_mul,\\nstate_machine) plus function-call glue hit this tax on a large\\nfraction of cycles. The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2,\\n-11.64%) proved the IPC win is real but put the predecode+adder on\\nthe imem BRAM \\u2192 PC register combinational cone, extending the fetch\\nloop critical path enough on GW2AR to wipe out the gain. The\\nLESSONS.md takeaway is explicit: prediction logic must stay off the\\nPC register's combinational cone \\u2014 register the prediction and\\nabsorb a 1-cycle redirect. A PC-indexed BTB satisfies this: the\\nlookup is driven by the PC register (not by imem_data), and its\\noutput is flopped before reaching the PC mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Branch prediction is still the biggest CPI lever on this core: every\\ntaken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/JAL/JALR resolves in EX and costs 2 pipeline\\nbubbles (flush IF + ID). CoreMark's inner loops (crc16, matrix_mul,\\nstate_machine) plus function-call glue hit this tax on a large\\nfraction of cycles. The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2,\\n-11.64%) proved the IPC win is real but put the predecode+adder on\\nthe imem BRAM \\u2192 PC register combinational cone, extending the fetch\\nloop critical path enough on GW2AR to wipe out the gain. The\\nLESSONS.md takeaway is explicit: prediction logic must stay off the\\nPC register's combinational cone \\u2014 register the prediction and\\nabsorb a 1-cycle redirect. A PC-indexed BTB satisfies this: the\\nlookup is driven by the PC register (not by imem_data), and its\\noutput is flopped before reaching the PC mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small 16-entry direct-mapped, tagged Branch Target Buffer\\nstored in flip-flop...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Regfile as GW2AR distributed-RAM (SSRAM) \\u2014 drop reset-loop to free ~1k FFs and the 32:1 read mux cone\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Baseline uses 9905/10000 LUT4 and 1858 FF on Tang Nano 20K. The r2s2\\nlesson is explicit: \\\"on a near-full Tang Nano 20K ... reclaim area\\nelsewhere first.\\\" Prior structural/predictor hypotheses kept bumping\\ninto area-induced Fmax/routing walls. The integer register file\\n(`reg_file.sv`) is the single biggest area hog in this design that is\\nNOT on anyone's critical path:\\n\\n  - 32 \\u00d7 32b = 1024 FFs (>55% of the total 1858 FF budget)\\n  - Two combinational read ports = two 32:1 32b muxes \\u2248 hundreds of\\n    LUT4s for the read fan-in trees\\n  - A synchronous-reset foreach loop zeroing the array is the ONLY\\n    thing preventing Yosys's `memory_dff`/`memory_bram` pass from\\n    mapping this array to GW2AR LUT4-as-SSRAM (distributed RAM) on\\n    the Gowin flow.\\n\\nGW2AR LUT4s support SSRAM (SP/DP distributed RAM) \\u2014 a 32\\u00d732 two-read\\none-write configuration maps to roughly 2 rows \\u00d7 32 cols \\u00d7 2 read\\nports = ~128 LUT4s configured as memory, replacing ~1024 FFs AND the\\n32:1 read muxes. Net expected save: ~1024 FF + several hundred LUT4\\nheadroom, opening Fmax ceiling on GW2AR where routing/congestion is\\nthe dominant Fmax limiter near 99% LUT occupancy.\\n\\nFunctional behavior must stay bit-identical: x0-hardwire, write-first\\nsame-cycle bypass (ID read of a register being written by WB this\\ncycle returns the new value), and the single-write / dual-read port\\nstructure. The only change is storage inference, not semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Baseline uses 9905/10000 LUT4 and 1858 FF on Tang Nano 20K. The r2s2\\nlesson is explicit: \\\"on a near-full Tang Nano 20K ... reclaim area\\nelsewhere first.\\\" Prior structural/predictor hypotheses kept bumping\\ninto area-induced Fmax/routing walls. The integer register file\\n(`reg_file.sv`) is the single...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) with ID-stage speculative redirect\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is call/return dense \\u2014 crc16, core_bench_matrix, core_bench_state\\nall run through small leaf functions, and every `ret` (JALR x0, x1, 0)\\nin this core costs TWO bubbles today (IF/ID both squashed when EX\\nresolves the JALR redirect). Prior predictor attempts failed for two\\ndistinct reasons that point to a narrow design window:\\n  * r1s2 (static BP at IF): logic on imem_data\\u2192PC_reg cone killed Fmax.\\n  * r2s2 (16-entry BTB, ~928 FFs + ~100 LUTs): IPC win was ~7% but\\n    area congestion on the near-full GW2AR (9905/10000 LUT4) erased it.\\nLESSONS.md explicitly suggests \\\"try 8-entry or tagless variants\\\". A\\nfunction-call RAS is the most area-efficient possible predictor: the\\nhit rate on returns is ~100% in single-threaded code with matching\\ncall/ret discipline (CoreMark qualifies), it needs no tag compare, and\\nthe predicted target is a stored 32-bit word rather than an adder\\ncone. Pattern-less call/ret imbalance is rare in CoreMark's hot loops,\\nso a 4-deep stack covers nearly all dynamic returns without ever\\noverflowing across a leaf call chain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is call/return dense \\u2014 crc16, core_bench_matrix, core_bench_state\\nall run through small leaf functions, and every `ret` (JALR x0, x1, 0)\\nin this core costs TWO bubbles today (IF/ID both squashed when EX\\nresolves the JALR redirect). Prior predictor attempts failed for two\\ndistinct reasons that point to a narrow design window:\\n  * r1s2 (static BP at IF): logic on imem_data\\u2192PC_reg cone killed Fmax.\\n  * r2s2 (16-entry BTB, ~928 FFs + ~100 LUTs): IPC win was ~7% but\\n    area congestion on the near-full GW2AR (9905/10000 LUT4) erased it.\\nLESSONS.md explicitly suggests \\\"try 8-entry or tagless variants\\\". A\\nfunction-call RAS is the most area-efficient possible predictor: the\\nhit rate on ...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Pre-compute JAL/JALR link value (PC+4) in IF stage; drop EX-stage link adder\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"EX stage's EX/MEM.alu_result D-input has two parallel cones that fan into the\\nfinal 2:1 mux (`is_jump ? pc+4 : alu_result`):\\n  (a) the full ALU cone \\u2014 which includes the shared 33x33 multiplier and any\\n      forward mux on operands \\u2014 the intended critical path.\\n  (b) a dedicated 32-bit adder `in.pc + 32'd4` plus the is_jump-select mux,\\n      running in parallel off ID/EX.pc.\\nThe pc+4 value is NOT derived from EX-stage computation \\u2014 it is already\\ncomputed one cycle earlier inside if_stage as `next_pc = pc + 32'd4` (the\\nsequential-fetch path). The duplicate adder in EX is therefore pure\\nredundant silicon whose output only matters for JAL/JALR link-register\\nwriteback. On GW2AR at 148 MHz with 9905/10000 LUT4s already consumed,\\nshaving one 32-bit carry-chain adder + its LUT footprint relieves routing\\npressure near the EX/MEM register, and \\u2014 to the extent the is_jump mux's\\nnon-ALU input was even marginally close to timing \\u2014 removes a second\\ncandidate critical cone from the EX cycle. Prior structural attempts\\nregressed by adding logic depth (r1s1 MUL handshake, r2s1 skid buffer,\\nr3s1 MEM-stage pre-mux); this one STRICTLY REMOVES logic from EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"EX stage's EX/MEM.alu_result D-input has two parallel cones that fan into the\\nfinal 2:1 mux (`is_jump ? pc+4 : alu_result`):\\n  (a) the full ALU cone \\u2014 which includes the shared 33x33 multiplier and any\\n      forward mux on operands \\u2014 the intended critical path.\\n  (b) a dedicated 32-bit adder `in.pc + 32'd4` plus the is_jump-select mux,\\n      running in parallel off ID/EX.pc.\\nThe pc+4 value is NOT derived from EX-stage computation \\u2014 it is already\\ncomputed one cycle earlier inside if_stage as `next_pc = pc + 32'd4` (the\\nsequential-fetch path). The duplicate adder in EX is therefo...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Zero-storage backward-branch prediction at ID, r4s2-pattern (additive, no rename)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80-95% accurate on\\nthese CoreMark kernels, covers another ~4-6% of dynamic instructions, and\\nsaves 2 pipeline bubbles per hit.\\n\\nr5s2 attempted this concept but failed implementation: it renamed\\n`jal_predicted` to `predicted_taken`, and a missed downstream consumer\\ncascaded into SBY's \\\"Status: passed / engine_0 did not produce any traces\\\"\\nsignature + cover VCD crash (no_checks_generated). The architectural idea\\nis sound; the diff discipline was not. This hypothesis retries the concept\\nwith strict additive plumbing (no renames) to eliminate the cascade-risk\\nclass of failures entirely.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Flatten ex_stage redirect_target to a single 2:1 mux on is_jalr\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-at-ID fast-path (+17.73%, current best 387.98) added a 2:1\\nmux in front of the PC D-input: `ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target :\\nid_jal_target`. That mux sits on the PC-redirect critical path, which\\nmeans `ex_redirect_target`'s combinational cone is now directly timed\\nagainst fetch Fmax. Any LUT level shaved from `ex_redirect_target`\\nshortens the PC-redirect arm and potentially lifts Fmax without\\ntouching IPC.\\n\\nPast branch-predictor hypotheses (r1s2 static BP, r2s2 BTB, r3s2 RAS,\\nr6s2 BTFN) all regressed because they loaded the PC-select cone. The\\ninverse strategy \\u2014 structurally *simplifying* cones that already feed\\nthe PC-select \\u2014 is underexplored. r4s2's success pattern itself was\\n\\\"resolve one stage earlier and share the existing redirect net\\\"; a\\nnatural complement is \\\"make the existing redirect net's cone shallower\\nwhere structural redundancy exists\\\".\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-at-ID fast-path (+17.73%, current best 387.98) added a 2:1\\nmux in front of the PC D-input: `ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target :\\nid_jal_target`. That mux sits on the PC-redirect critical path, which\\nmeans `ex_redirect_target`'s combinational cone is now directly timed\\nagainst fetch Fmax. Any LUT level shaved from `ex_redirect_target`\\nshortens the PC-redirect arm and potentially lifts Fmax without\\ntouching IPC.\\n\\nPast branch-predictor hypotheses (r1s2 static BP, r2s2 BTB, r3s2 RAS,\\nr6s2 BTFN) all regressed because they loaded the PC-select cone. The\\ninverse strategy \\u2014 structurally *simplifying* cones that already feed\\nthe PC-select \\u2014 is underexplored. r4s2's success pattern itself was\\n\\\"resolve one stage earlier and share the existing redirect net\\\"; a\\nnatural complement is \\\"make the existing redirect net's cone shallower\\nwhere structural redundancy exists\\\".\\n\", \"h...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Pre-register JAL target at IF to lift the 32-bit adder off the ID redirect cone\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the one predictor that won on this fabric\\n(+17.73%). Every subsequent predictor variant regressed because it\\nviolated at least one of the winning constraints: no new PC-mux\\ninput (r1s2), no storage+tag array pulling LUT area (r2s2), no new\\nID-side fire-term with a misprediction arm widening the EX redirect\\nmux past 2:1 (r6s2, r7s2), no id_ex_t struct rename (r7s0).\\n\\nWhat r4s2 did NOT eliminate, though, is a 32-bit adder sitting on\\nthe ID\\u2192PC-D-in combinational cone. In core.sv today:\\n\\n    id_jal_target  = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm;         // <-- 32b adder\\n    redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_target : id_jal_target;\\n    // if_stage: PC_D = redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4;\\n\\nOn each cycle where a JAL is in ID, the PC register's D-input cone\\npasses through PC_reg \\u2192 if_id_w.pc \\u2192 32-bit carry-chain add \\u2192 2:1\\nmux (ex_redirect select) \\u2192 2:1 mux (redirect select) \\u2192 PC_D. The\\ncarry chain dominates this arm. On near-full GW2AR (9484/10000\\nLUT4), congestion-amplified routing around the carry chain is\\nexactly the sort of thing that nudges Fmax down \\u2014 and r4s2's win\\nconfirms Fmax-side gains are available on the fetch-redirect net.\\n\\nCrucially, the adder's operands both resolve to flop outputs at the\\nclock edge starting cycle N: PC_reg is already flopped; J_imm is a\\nbit-permutation of imem_data which at cycle N is the Gowin BRAM\\noutput (clock-to-Q of the BRAM, not a combinational chain). So the\\nadder can be RELOCATED to compute `jal_target_next = pc + J_imm`\\nduring cycle N-1 (when the JAL is still in IF) and registered into\\na new `jal_target_q` flop on the N-1\\u2192N edge. At cycle N the JAL is\\nin ID and `jal_target_q` is a ready flop output \\u2014 feeding the\\nredirect_target mux with ZERO adder levels in the ID\\u2192PC cone.\\n\\n...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Iterative 33-cycle DIV/REM unit (MUL stays combinational) to free LUTs and lift the divide cone off EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently synthesizes DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational\\n`$signed(a)/$signed(b)` / `a%b`. On Gowin GW2AR (Tang Nano 20K) a\\n32-bit combinational divider is a very deep carry/subtract tree\\ncosting 300-500 LUTs and presenting one of the longest paths in the\\nEX cone. The core currently sits at 9484/10000 LUT4s with Fmax\\n172.35 MHz \\u2014 area is a binding constraint and a non-trivial fraction\\nof that budget is being burned on divider logic that CoreMark's hot\\nkernels (matrix_add/sub/mul, list_join, CRC, state machine) hit\\nessentially never: inspection of CoreMark's core_portme / core_list /\\nmatrix sources shows MUL everywhere but no DIV/REM inside the\\nbracketed measurement region (DIV appears only in CRC seed setup\\nand `%` modulo reductions that fall outside start_time/stop_time).\\n\\nLesson r1s1 specifically warned against multi-cycle MUL because MUL\\ndominates CoreMark's matrix kernels \\u2014 that lesson does NOT apply to\\nDIV, which is architecturally separable in the ALU case-mux and has\\norders-of-magnitude lower dynamic density. Moving DIV/REM alone to a\\nmulti-cycle iterative unit captures the divider LUT savings and the\\ncritical-path relief without paying the MUL-density IPC tax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently synthesizes DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational\\n`$signed(a)/$signed(b)` / `a%b`. On Gowin GW2AR (Tang Nano 20K) a\\n32-bit combinational divider is a very deep carry/subtract tree\\ncosting 300-500 LUTs and presenting one of the longest paths in the\\nEX cone. The core currently sits at 9484/10000 LUT4s with Fmax\\n172.35 MHz \\u2014 area is a binding constraint and a non-trivial fraction\\nof that budget is being burned on divider logic that CoreMark's hot\\nkernels (matrix_add/sub/mul, list_join, CRC, state machine) hit\\nessentially neve...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Gate reg_write at ID for rd==0 to shorten forward_unit priority encoder\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The forward_unit drives the 3:1 operand-select muxes at the head of the\\nEX-stage ALU/branch-comparator cone \\u2014 it sits directly on one of the\\ncore's known hot combinational paths. Each of its two always_comb\\npriority encoders evaluates three conditions per term:\\n  (ex_mem_w_en) && (ex_mem_rd != 5'b0) && (ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\n  (mem_wb_w_en) && (mem_wb_rd != 5'b0) && (mem_wb_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\nThe `rd != 5'b0` predicate is redundant with `w_en`: an architectural\\nwrite whose destination is x0 has no effect (regfile writes to x0 are\\ndropped, forward_unit returning x0 would be bit-identical to returning\\nthe real x0 = 0 since the regfile's read of x0 is hardwired). If we\\nconstrain `ctrl.reg_write` upstream \\u2014 at id_stage, by AND-ing decoder's\\nreg_write with (instr[11:7] != 5'b0) before loading into ID/EX \\u2014 then\\n`w_en=0` already implies `rd!=0` at EX/MEM and MEM/WB, and the\\nforward_unit's `rd != 5'b0` terms collapse to dead code that Yosys can\\nDCE cleanly.\\n\\nThis is the \\\"constrain upstream, let downstream DCE\\\" pattern, strictly\\nlocal to id_stage.sv + decoder-output gating, and does NOT edit any\\npipeline-register struct field name (the confirmed formal tarpit from\\nr4s0/r5s1/r5s2/r6s0/r6s1/r7s0/r7s2/r8s0). The only thing changing is\\na combinational AND gate on ctrl_decoded.reg_write inside id_stage,\\nbefore the ID/EX flop captures it.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The forward_unit drives the 3:1 operand-select muxes at the head of the\\nEX-stage ALU/branch-comparator cone \\u2014 it sits directly on one of the\\ncore's known hot combinational paths. Each of its two always_comb\\npriority encoders evaluates three conditions per term:\\n  (ex_mem_w_en) && (ex_mem_rd != 5'b0) && (ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\n  (mem_wb_w_en) && (mem_wb_rd != 5'b0) && (mem_wb_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\nThe `rd != 5'b0` p...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"IF-side RET predictor via sequential-PC arm (squash-refetch off the ID redirect cone)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Every ID-side RET/JALR predictor has regressed on this fabric\\n(r3s2 4-entry RAS ~0%, r7s2 dirty-x1 RAS -50%, r10s2 1-entry RAC\\n-20%). The r10s2 lesson names the one remaining unexplored path\\nexplicitly: \\\"JALR/RET speculation on this fabric must either\\nresolve off the ID redirect cone entirely (IF-side hint +\\nsquash-refetch) or be abandoned\\\". r4s2's JAL fast-path won\\n(+17.73%) by folding onto the EXISTING redirect wire via an\\nupstream 2:1; every variant that widened the ID-side redirect\\ncone (new fire term, new upstream target mux, new target\\nregister) paid the full predictor tax regardless of downstream\\ntopology preservation. What no hypothesis has tried: fold the\\nRET prediction into the SEQUENTIAL-fetch arm of if_stage's PC\\nD-input, leaving the `redirect`/`redirect_target` cone\\nstructurally identical to the current winning r4s2 form.\\n\\nCoreMark's call/return density is ~4-6% dynamic (crc16, list_ins,\\nmatrix inner helpers, state_machine small leaves); every RET\\ncosts 2 bubbles today. Saving one bubble per correctly-predicted\\nRET recovers ~2-3% of execution cycles \\u2014 same order of magnitude\\nas r4s2's JAL-only win, but through a structurally disjoint\\nfetch path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Every ID-side RET/JALR predictor has regressed on this fabric\\n(r3s2 4-entry RAS ~0%, r7s2 dirty-x1 RAS -50%, r10s2 1-entry RAC\\n-20%). The r10s2 lesson names the one remaining unexplored path\\nexplicitly: \\\"JALR/RET speculation on this fabric must either\\nresolve off the ID redirect cone entirely (IF-side hint +\\nsquash-refetch) or be abandoned\\\". r4s2's JAL fast-path won\\n(+17.73%) by folding onto the EXISTING redirect wire via an\\nupstream 2:1; every variant that widened the ID-side redirect\\ncone (new fire term, new upstream target mux, new target\\nregister) paid the full predicto...\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"Parallel mem_op hint flop \\u2014 shorten dmem_stall fanout cone without touching ex_mem_t layout\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor search is closed (r6s2/r7s2/r10s2/r11s2/r12s2 all regressed),\\nand consumer-side forward-cone restructures are likewise negative\\n(r3s1/r11s1/r12s1). Non-predictor structural wins must target the\\nhazard/stall network, which feeds a very high-fanout set of flop enables\\n(PC reg hold, ID/EX reset, EX/MEM hold, MEM/WB valid).\\n\\nToday, `hazard_unit.dmem_stall = !dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op`, and\\n`ex_mem_mem_op` is a top-level combinational OR:\\n    assign ... = ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read | ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_write\\ni.e., the OR sits on two distinct bits of the packed ex_mem_t flop Q,\\nrouted across core.sv's top-level glue into hazard_unit, which then ANDs\\nwith !dmem_ready and fans out as `stall_if`/`stall_id`/`stall_ex_mem`/\\n`hold_mem_wb` \\u2014 i.e., into the IF PC-D mux's stall cone that r4s2 showed\\nis Fmax-binding on this fabric, plus the ID/EX reset cone and the EX/MEM\\ncapture-enable cone.\\n\\nr4s2 won by moving work ONE STAGE EARLIER onto a dedicated parallel flop\\nthat rides the existing net (the `redirect` wire) \\u2014 not by editing a\\nshared struct or reshuffling an already-optimized cone. r11s0 proved that\\nediting ex_mem_t's packed layout (even to delete dead bits) regresses via\\nplacement churn, and r12s1 proved that appending to id_ex_t + threading\\nacross stages regresses from routing/FF cost. The remaining structural\\nlever is: add a SEPARATE 1-bit flop (not a struct-member edit) whose D-\\ninput is a combinational OR of two pre-flop wires already present in\\nex_stage, and whose Q replaces the top-level OR-of-flop-Qs in core.sv.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor search is closed (r6s2/r7s2/r10s2/r11s2/r12s2 all regressed),\\nand consumer-side forward-cone restructures are likewise negative\\n(r3s1/r11s1/r12s1). Non-predictor structural wins must tar...\n  Line 40: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"JAL fast-path: delete tautological id_jal_aligned gate\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the only predictor that has scored positive\\non this core (+17.73%). All four JALR/RET predictor topologies\\n(r3s2 4-entry RAS, r7s2 dirty-x1, r10s2 RAC, r11s2 IF-side-seq-arm)\\nregressed sharply, as did BTFN (r6s2), BEQ-rs,rs (r12s2), IF-side\\nJAL predecode (r8s2), and a Boolean-equivalent rewrite of the r4s2\\ncone itself (r9s2, -18.86%). The transferable rule from r9s2 is that\\nSUBSTITUTING one expression for another on the r4s2 cone invalidates\\nYosys's CSE/placement optimum. DELETION of a provably-redundant term\\nis a structurally different operation: it leaves the remaining cone\\nin its original form (same expression tree for the surviving\\noperands), reducing the cone's fan-in rather than reshaping it.\\n\\nThe `id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)` check is a\\ntautology for this core:\\n  - PC register resets to 0 (pc[1:0]=00).\\n  - PC updates are pc+=4 (preserves pc[1:0]=00) or redirect_target.\\n  - JAL targets: pc+J_imm, and J-imm has bit 0 \\u2261 0 by encoding, and\\n    pc[1:0]=00 invariantly \\u21d2 target[1:0]=00.\\n  - JALR: clears bit 0 explicitly via `{jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0}` in\\n    ex_stage.sv:89, and ex_stage's misalign-fault gate traps any\\n    JALR target with bit 1 set (invariant #2; target[1:0]==00 check\\n    at ex_stage.sv:101-103), preventing pc[1:0]=10 from persisting.\\n  - Branch targets: also go through ex_stage's misalign-fault gate,\\n    so branch_target[1:0]!=00 traps and does NOT redirect the PC.\\nConclusion: pc[1:0]==00 is an invariant maintained by the existing\\nRTL, and hence id_jal_target[1:0]==00 is an invariant too. The gate\\nalways evaluates to 1 at runtime.\\n\\nYosys cannot statically prove this invariant without a multi-cycle\\nanalysis it does not perform on combinational expressions, so the\\n2-bit equality check remains in synthesized logic, costing ~1 LUT\\nle...\n  Line 42: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r14s1\", \"title\": \"Rebalance pipeline: hoist load-data shift/sign-extend from MEM pre-flop to WB post-flop\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"r3s1 explicitly diagnosed the MEM pre-flop load-data cone (dmem_rdata \\u2192 shift\\nby addr[1:0]*8 \\u2192 byte/halfword mux \\u2192 sign/zero-extend \\u2192 mem_wb flop D-input)\\nas the binding MEM-side Fmax limiter on this core. Every prior MEM-side\\nattempt has *added* logic to this cone:\\n  - r3s1 folded mem_to_reg mux pre-flop \\u2192 regressed (-5.66%) because the\\n    mux's load_data input IS the tip of the critical cone, so the new mux\\n    lands in series with it.\\n  - r10s1 precomputed byte_mask at EX \\u2192 regressed (-13.48%) because the\\n    byte_mask selector `alu_result[1:0]` is the ALU carry output.\\n  - r6s0 replaced the variable shifter with explicit byte muxes \\u2192 broke\\n    formal on misaligned-addr RVFI shadow.\\nThe untried direction is the *opposite* rebalance: delete the shift+extend\\nfrom the MEM pre-flop path entirely by having WB reconstruct load_data\\ncombinationally from already-flopped mem_wb_t fields. mem_wb_t already\\ncarries `mem_rdata` (raw dmem word, for RVFI), `alu_result` (its low 2 bits\\nare the byte offset), `ctrl.mem_width`, and `ctrl.mem_sext` \\u2014 every input\\nthe shift+extend needs is already post-flop. So the structural move is\\n\\\"no struct edits, just relocate the combinational cone across the\\nmem_wb boundary.\\\"\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r3s1 explicitly diagnosed the MEM pre-flop load-data cone (dmem_rdata \\u2192 shift\\nby addr[1:0]*8 \\u2192 byte/halfword mux \\u2192 sign/zero-extend \\u2192 mem_wb flop D-input)\\nas the binding MEM-side Fmax limiter on this core. Every prior MEM-side\\nattempt has *added* logic to this cone:\\n  - r3s1 folded mem_to_reg mux pre-flop \\u2192 regressed (-5.66%) because the\\n    mux's load_data input IS the tip of the critical cone, so the new mux\\n    lands in series with it.\\n  - r10s1 precomputed byte_mask at EX \\...\n  Line 43: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r14s2\", \"title\": \"Slim JAL fast-path fire gate: drop structurally redundant `& if_id_w.valid` conjunct\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"After 13 predictor-slot iterations, r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path\\n(+17.73%) remains the sole predictor win on this core. Every extension\\nregressed: second ID-side fire term (r6s2 -23%, r7s2 -50%, r10s2 -20%,\\nr11s2 -26%, r12s2 -23%), widened redirect_target arbiter past 2:1\\n(r7s2, r10s2), new IF-side predecode adder (r8s2 -13%), equivalent\\nrewrite on the winning cone (r9s2 -19%), dead-field struct shrink\\n(r11s0 -23%), and delete-tautology gates that BMC explores (r13s2\\nbroken). The predictor search space as traditionally conceived is\\nempirically exhausted on this fabric.\\n\\nThe ONE angle that has NOT been tried, and that avoids every named\\nfailure mode in the lessons, is a minimal cone-shave INSIDE the r4s2\\nwinning gate that is a pure combinational tautology (not reachable-\\nstate-dependent). Specifically, in core.sv line ~134:\\n\\n    id_is_jal = (if_id_w.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111) & if_id_w.valid;\\n\\nThe `& if_id_w.valid` conjunct is structurally redundant: if_stage\\ndrives `out.instr = flush ? 32'h0000_0013 : imem_data` and\\n`out.valid = !flush`, so whenever valid=0 the instruction is forced\\nto ADDI x0,x0,0 whose opcode[6:0]=0010011 already fails the JAL\\nopcode compare (1101111). The conjunct is a combinational identity\\ntautology on the pair (instr[6:0], flush) \\u2014 NOT a reachable-state\\ninvariant like r13s2's pc-alignment (which BMC explored and falsified\\nfrom arbitrary initial states). No SBY BMC step can construct a case\\nwhere `instr[6:0]==1101111` holds while `valid=0`: the flush-NOP is\\nhardwired by the always_comb, so the implication is unconditional at\\nevery simulated cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After 13 predictor-slot iterations, r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path\\n(+17.73%) remains the sole predictor win on this core. Every extension\\nregressed: second ID-...","metadata":{"matches":17,"truncated":false},"title":"hazard_unit|load_use","time":{"start":1777802858343,"end":1777802858364}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm narrowing down which micro-optimization angle to pursue by eliminating the approaches that have already been tried or ruled out—the forward cone restructuring, memory load-data cone optimization, and ALU operand widening all have evidence against them across multiple test runs.\n\nLooking at what's still untouched, the hazard unit's combinational depth, the decoder tree, the immediate generator structure, and the ALU's case multiplexer stand out as potential targets that haven't been systematically explored yet.\n\nOne angle I haven't tried: the hazard_unit's load_use_hazard and redirect signals feeding into flush_id, which gates the ID/EX synchronous reset. The flush expression combines load_use_hazard (checking for register dependencies on loads) with redirect, both gated by dmem_stall. Since ID/EX is a large struct, asserting flush forces the entire thing to zero, which works fine with clear-enable semantics.\n\nNow looking at mem_stage's data shifting logic — the shifted value is computed combinationally from the flopped ALU result, then sliced and muxed based on memory width for the final load data. This is where r6s0 ran into issues.\n\nI'm wondering if there's room to simplify the load_data case mux itself, or if the ALU's operation decoder might have some encoding tricks to reduce its depth. Let me trace through the ALU ops and see if there's a pattern I can exploit.\n\nLooking at the shift operations specifically, I notice that only 5 bits of the 32-bit input actually matter for the shift amount, so most of that mux is wasted. Yosys probably already optimizes this away though.\n\nLet me focus on the mem_stage's shift-and-extend pipeline instead. The current flow chains a barrel shift followed by sign extension, which adds depth. I'm thinking about whether I can move the sign-extension decision earlier to compress the critical path.\n\nActually, examining the decoder and execute stage more carefully, I see that `is_jump` flags both JAL and JALR, with `is_jalr` distinguishing between them. The redirect logic uses `is_jump` to select between jump and branch targets, but since JAL's jump_target equals its branch_target anyway, that mux is only really meaningful for JALR.\n\nr8s0 tried simplifying `redirect_target` to use `is_jalr` to pick the JALR sum instead, but that broke formal verification, so that path is closed. Looking at other angles: the mem_width encoding uses 2 bits for three cases, which creates multiple 2:4 decode muxes in the memory stage, but that's an architectural choice locked in at the decoder level. Registering the stall condition in the hazard unit would add another register that the solver can't handle. Focusing on the if_stage PC mux, it's currently structured as a conditional always_ff that could be converted to a clock-enable register where the D-input becomes a 3:1 mux selecting between redirect_target, the JAL target, or pc+4.\n\nThe actual critical path is likely the fetch loop: PC flop feeds imem_addr, which reads from BRAM, and that data flows through instruction decode to compute the JAL target, which feeds back as the redirect target to the PC's D-input. The id_jal_target itself comes from pc+J_imm, so there's a long combinational chain from the BRAM read output through decode logic back to the PC mux input. The low bits of the adder output determine alignment quickly since they're just the carry chain's bottom bits. The critical path through id_jal_target is likely the 32-bit adder feeding into two sequential 2:1 muxes, totaling around 34 LUT levels with carry chain sharing. I'm considering whether there's a way to optimize this path, but alternatives like custom carry-save structures would be too complex for Yosys to handle. Now I'm looking at how pc_next gets computed in the EX stage—it's a priority mux that selects between pc+4 and various jump/branch targets based on fault and redirect conditions, which I can simplify by factoring out the repeated pc+4 cases.\n\nThe EX/MEM forwarding unit seems critical for avoiding stalls on consecutive ALU instructions, so I can't remove it entirely. I'm examining whether I can optimize the priority encoding by merging the conditions that check for valid forwarding sources—both terms share a 5-bit OR to check if the destination register is nonzero, plus a 5-bit equality check against the source register, which adds up to several LUT levels. Previous attempts targeting this have all failed, so I need to focus on a concrete optimization strategy.\n\nLooking at the memory stage, I notice the byte mask is generated identically for both the write-enable gating and the EX/MEM register capture—Yosys should already be sharing that logic. The write data replication based on memory width is also combinational off the EX/MEM register, but that's already been explored without success. What stands out is the flush signal in the ID stage: it depends on `ex_redirect`, which is a combinational output from the execute stage that chains through the branch condition and ALU result—that's a deep critical path feeding back into the ID stage's reset logic.\n\nIf `ex_redirect` arrives late, it delays `flush_id`, which then delays the mux selector for the ID/EX flop reset, potentially limiting Fmax. The `load_use_hazard` check already correctly handles the x0 case by gating on `id_ex_rd != 0`, so there's not much to optimize there—the real bottleneck is that redirect signal propagating back into the flush cone.\n\nNow I'm examining whether I can merge the misalignment fault check with jump target computation in the execute stage. For JAL, the target's lower bits depend on the immediate, but for JALR, bit 0 is always zero by construction, so I only need to check bit 1 to detect misalignment.\n\nThe current two-bit comparison could theoretically simplify to just checking bit 1, but that breaks formal verification—BMC can initialize the program counter with bit 0 set, which would make the simplified check miss real misalignments. So I'm keeping the full comparison.\n\nLet me pivot to the hazard unit instead and see if there's room to simplify the stall logic.\n\nLooking at how the id_ex flop behaves: when there's a data memory stall, we hold; when there's a load-use hazard or redirect without a stall, we flush; otherwise we capture normally. The current code computes stall and flush separately, but I could restructure this as a unified control signal that handles all three cases—either capturing, holding, or clearing the pipeline stage. That said, the structural cost doesn't really change much either way.\n\nNow I'm considering a different optimization: `ex_mem_mem_op` is just the OR of `mem_read` and `mem_write` from the decoder, and since those are mutually exclusive (LOAD vs STORE), I could represent this as a single \"mem_op\" bit instead. The challenge is that would require editing the struct definition, or I'd need to compute it at the consumer side like the current code does. I've also been exploring whether pre-flopping this signal at the ex_stage level could help, but that either requires struct changes or breaks the mem_stage semantics. The imem_stall path is another area I haven't fully optimized yet.\n\nLooking at the imm_gen logic more carefully, it's doing a lot of bit-selection muxing across different immediate formats. Instead of having the full 7-bit opcode drive a complex mux tree for each output bit, I could encode the immediate format as just 3 bits (I/S/B/U/J/R) and decode that once, which would be more efficient than Yosys synthesizing a bank of muxes per output bit.\n\nBut honestly, Yosys is already pretty good at optimizing this kind of thing, so there's probably no clear Fmax win here.\n\nLet me focus on something concrete. I keep coming back to the ALU — LUI already just passes `b` through without any case mux overhead, so there's nothing to optimize there either. The real bottleneck might be in the multiplier input selection logic, where I'm currently using a case statement to set sign-extension flags based on the operation type. I could factor that out to reduce the mux depth feeding into the multiplier.\n\nFactoring out the sign-extension selection... Looking at the jump target alignment logic, I notice that for JALR instructions, bit 0 is always zero, so checking `jump_target[1:0] != 0` is equivalent to just testing `jump_target[1]`. For regular JAL instructions, I need to think through whether there's a way to reuse this bit extraction across the misalignment detection and other parts of the pipeline.\n\nThe current structure already handles this with a conditional mux, but I could potentially factor it differently — though the synthesizer probably optimizes this away anyway. Let me move on to something more concrete: optimizing the forwarding unit by precomputing the register equality comparisons instead of recalculating them each cycle. I'm considering pre-computing the forward-eligibility bit combinationally from existing signals in the ex_stage rather than adding a new flop, since that avoids the formal verification burden that killed the r13s1 approach. The key is deriving it from wires that are already present before the pipeline register, so there's no new state to prove invariants about. Looking at the R-type decoder's alu_op mapping, I notice that funct3 alone captures most of the arithmetic operations when funct7 is zero, and funct7 bit 5 distinguishes between ADD/SUB and SRL/SRA. The M-extension operations (MUL variants) are isolated by funct7=0000001. I could potentially encode this more efficiently by using funct7[5] and funct3 directly rather than a full 10-bit case, which might reduce the LUT footprint.\n\nBut honestly, this is what Yosys should be optimizing anyway—it's not a promising manual improvement.\n\nLet me focus on something concrete: the forward_unit is already computing `rd != 5'b0` checks in both forwarding predicates, but these checks are redundant when combined with the write-enable signal. I can precompute `reg_write_gated = ctrl.reg_write && (rd != 5'b0)` once and reuse it, eliminating duplicate OR reductions across the forwarding logic. The key insight is that both approaches—gating on `id_ex_rs1 != 0` or `ex_mem_rd != 0`—correctly handle the x0 case, but they do it differently. When rs1=0, the current check `ex_mem_rd != 0` blocks forwarding and lets the regfile return 0, which is correct. If I switch to gating on `id_ex_rs1 != 0` instead, I'd suppress the forward at the source, achieving the same result. The tradeoff is that `id_ex_rs1 != 0` can be precomputed once per register, while `ex_mem_rd != 0` must be computed per pipeline stage, though both are cheap 5-bit reductions. The key insight is that swapping the gate order doesn't change the forwarding logic's behavior—both versions correctly prevent forwarding when rs1 is zero, and both forward when there's a genuine register dependency. Since the forward_unit output only affects the data values used in execution (which flow into RVFI), and the behavior is functionally identical, the RVFI shadow state should remain unchanged. Let me verify this with a concrete edge case where instruction A writes to x0 and instruction B reads from x0—both the old and new gate configurations correctly prevent forwarding and let B read x0 from the regfile. The critical path through both the old and new forwarding logic looks roughly equivalent—both involve a 5-bit OR and comparison, so this optimization probably won't move Fmax. I'm realizing the low-hanging fruit here is mostly exhausted, so let me pivot to something with more potential impact.\n\nI'm considering hardwiring `jump_target[0]` to zero since valid jumps always produce a zero in that bit position, which would simplify the misalignment check. But that breaks the formal verification assumptions about reachable states, so it's not viable.\n\nLet me try a different angle entirely...\n\nSimplifying the `pc_next` mux in the EX stage could help. Right now it's a 4-way priority mux that checks misalignment first, then jump, then branch, then defaults to pc+4. I could flatten this into a 2-way mux by computing whether we're taking any redirect (`branch_taken || is_jump`) and gating it with `!misalign_fault`, then choosing between the target and pc+4. This reduces the mux depth and should be equivalent across all cases—when misalignment occurs, the gate forces us to pc+4; otherwise we pick the appropriate target.\n\nHowever, `pc_next` feeds into the RVFI shadow path, which is formally verified. Boolean-equivalent rewrites on the redirect cone have historically triggered the \"no_checks_generated\" tarpit in formal verification, so this optimization carries real risk despite being provably correct.\n\nLet me explore a different angle instead. The hazard unit's load-use detection currently checks if the destination register matches either source and isn't zero, all in one expression. I could optimize this by pre-computing whether either source is non-zero once, rather than embedding that check inside the full hazard condition.\n\nChecking the semantics: if the destination is zero, it can't match a non-zero source, so moving the zero-check to the source operands should preserve correctness. Let me verify the edge cases...\n\nBoth formulations are equivalent. The structural difference is that checking `if_id_rs1 != 0` on the combinational instruction bits might let me eliminate the `id_ex_rd != 0` reduction entirely from the hazard unit, since the source register checks are probably already computed elsewhere in decode logic. Whether Yosys already optimizes this away is unclear—worth testing. Though I'm second-guessing whether this counts as real sharing or just a different structural arrangement.\n\nThe hazard unit drives high-fanout control signals like `stall_if` and `flush_id` on the fetch critical path, so any LUT savings should propagate. I'm going to commit to rewriting the load-use hazard's zero-check to use `if_id_rs?` instead of `id_ex_rd`, but I suspect the impact might be minimal.\n\nActually, I just realized a better optimization: instead of tweaking the load-use logic, what if I share the `rd != 0` check within the forward unit itself? Currently it's computed separately for each destination register match—I could compute it once per destination and reuse it for both rs1 and rs2 comparisons.\n\nBut wait, Yosys's standard optimizations should already be handling that sharing, so it probably won't help. Let me think about this differently.\n\nHere's what I'm actually interested in: `stall_id` controls whether the ID/EX flop captures, and it's currently `dmem_stall || load_use_hazard`. If I could decouple load-use handling from the stall mechanism entirely and use a different approach—maybe keeping the load in EX/MEM while the dependent instruction stays in ID without stalling the whole pipeline—that might reduce the fanout on this critical signal.\n\nLooking at the hazard unit logic, when load_use_hazard is true and dmem_stall is false, both stall_id and flush_id go high, but flush_id takes priority and zeros out the ID/EX register while the PC holds. This is correct, but the combined stall/flush cone is driving both the mux and the clock enable, creating unnecessary complexity. I could simplify this: just let the flop capture unless dmem_stall is active, and handle load-use and redirects purely through flush_id. The current CE expression has redundancy that could be collapsed.\n\nLooking at how Verilog synthesizes the if-else chain into a mux tree, the flop's D-input becomes a 3-way mux: reset or flush selects 0, otherwise stall selects between holding the register or capturing new data. This is standard and Yosys will optimize it, but I'm wondering if there's a micro-optimization hiding here. The hazard unit checks if id_ex_rd matches rs1 or rs2 for load-use detection, and I could potentially factor out the zero-check on id_ex_rd as a shared wire to give the synthesizer a structural hint. Though honestly, CSE probably won't help much here either.\n\nLet me pivot to a different angle: the MULHSU sign-extension in the ALU. Currently we're computing a 33-bit signed operand times a 33-bit unsigned operand in a full 33×33 multiplier, where the sign-extension bits are anded with the MSB of each input. For MULH variants we need the high 32 bits of the product, and the sign bits matter there, but for MUL we only care about the low 32 bits where those high bits don't contribute. The synthesizer has to handle the sign-extension logic through DSP blocks or LUT partial products, which might not be optimal depending on the target.\n\nAn alternative would be to always compute unsigned multiplication and then apply a signed correction term—adding back the contributions from the sign bits—which is a classic trick that could be cheaper in some synthesis flows, though I'm not sure it'll actually win on this particular architecture.\n\nI'm going to try something concrete instead: optimizing the hazard unit's load-use detection by hoisting the zero-register check earlier in the pipeline, which removes a redundant OR reduction from the critical path. It's minimal, formally equivalent, and only touches the hazard unit module. The impact should be small—maybe 1-3% on Fmax—but it's a safe, low-risk change.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded4eccad001zGgNwIz1s6oqQn","sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","messageID":"msg_ded4b7b46001I4Sd2gsdZj4SOT"}}
