{"type":"text","timestamp":1777802923483,"sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","part":{"id":"prt_ded4fbaa00011mcIn7taftRWJT","messageID":"msg_ded4fb25f001E7CbEJDXauKJL1","sessionID":"ses_212b69b33ffepoG55mrPcavMV2","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written. Summary:\n\n**hyp-20260503-001-r15s0** — `micro_opt` targeting the one hot-network module untouched across all 14 rounds: `hazard_unit.sv`. The proposal rewrites `load_use_hazard` from its current outer-factored form `(rd==rs1 || rd==rs2) && rd!=0` to the equivalent per-rs form `(rd==rs1 && rs1!=0) || (rd==rs2 && rs2!=0)`. This is algebraically identical (proven by 4-case exhaustion on the zero-axis) but shifts the 5-bit non-zero check from the flopped `id_ex_rd` to combinational `if_id_rs?` bits — the same source bits the regfile's x0-gate and adjacent decoder/compare cones use, giving Yosys post-flatten CSE a chance to share logic it currently cannot.\n\nSafety profile avoids every documented tarpit: no struct edits (r7s0/r11s0), no RVFI shadow change (r10s0), no new state (r13s1), no fetch-redirect cone Boolean rewrite (r8s0/r9s2/r13s2), no reachable-state invariant dependence (r13s2/r14s2), no ALU/forward-cone restructure, no predictor. Conservative delta of +2% with low confidence reflecting r14s0's warning that pure-CSE hints often net zero — but downside is strictly bounded since outputs are bit-identical.","time":{"start":1777802918560,"end":1777802923482}}}
