{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777782503962,"sessionID":"ses_213e85e67ffe0SVaGLp8k2t34z","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01PCg5Pus2Som2D9xLxAepV3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r1s0\ntitle: \"Share single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current alu.sv computes three independent 64-bit products on every\n  cycle (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and a case-mux selects among them. For\n  a 5-stage in-order core whose EX stage is already on the critical path\n  (forward mux -> ALU -> branch resolve -> redirect mux), instantiating\n  three parallel 32x32 multipliers is pure waste: only one result is\n  selected per instruction, and Yosys/nextpnr on Tang Nano 20K's GW2AR\n  either burns three DSP slots or synthesises three LUT-based multipliers\n  plus a wide final mux. Both outcomes hurt Fmax (one of the two fitness\n  factors) and the LUT/DSP budget. CoreMark exercises MUL heavily in the\n  matrix kernel, so any Fmax gain here is a direct fitness gain — every\n  1 MHz at the current iter/cycle is ~2.2 CoreMark iter/s.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the three separate always-computed multipliers in alu.sv with\n  a single 33x33 signed multiplication whose operand sign-extensions are\n  selected by alu_op. The textbook sharing: zero-extend a (to 33b) for\n  MULHU / MULHSU-b, sign-extend a for MUL / MULH / MULHSU-a; zero-extend\n  b for MULHU / MULHSU, sign-extend b for MUL / MULH. The 66-bit product\n  then supplies MUL = prod[31:0] and MULH/MULHU/MULHSU = prod[63:32].\n  Division (4 ops) and the ALTOPS ifdef branch are left completely\n  untouched — ALTOPS still substitutes the XOR algebraic forms so formal\n  BMC stays tractable. Correctness is already guarded by test_alu.py's\n  30+ vectors per M-ext op and by the cosim against the Python ISS for\n  every retired MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU in the CoreMark run; both will\n  fail loudly on any sign-extension bug. The expected Fmax win comes\n  from collapsing three multiplier instances + 4:1 mux into one\n  multiplier + 2:1 high/low mux — shorter data-path and less DSP\n  pressure. LUT savings are a secondary win that relaxes placement and\n  may also nudge Fmax upward via easier routing.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su trio with a single 33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign bits are selected from alu_op. MUL reads prod[31:0]; MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read prod[63:32]. Division arms and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch are unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Add targeted MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors (INT_MIN*INT_MIN, INT_MIN*-1, 0xFFFFFFFF*0xFFFFFFFF, mixed-sign products) to catch any sign-extension regression from the multiplier-sharing refactor before cosim does.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777782503944,"end":1777782503960}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm working through the performance metrics here—the bench core shows 301.04 iterations per second at 135 MHz, which means roughly 449k cycles per iteration when I back out the math. That aligns with what I'd expect for a 6KB CoreMark.\n\nFor the micro-optimization slot, I'm looking at the RTL to find something targeted that could improve either IPC or Fmax without major structural changes. Branch prediction would help but that's a different category. The real bottleneck I'm seeing is in the EX stage—the ALU is computing all three 64-bit multipliers unconditionally every cycle, which is burning a lot of LUTs and likely hurting Fmax. My idea is to consolidate this into a single shared multiplier that handles all four multiply variants (MUL, MULH, MULHU, MULHSU) through a single 33×33 signed multiply with proper sign extension and operand selection.\n\nImplementing multiplier sharing...","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec1804b6001BayWHQm45w4BFL","sessionID":"ses_213e85e67ffe0SVaGLp8k2t34z","messageID":"msg_dec17bfbc001W13wStibLZtbRY"}}
