{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777783451094,"sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","part":{"id":"prt_dec26add2001CRTtSE14vGDCPJ","messageID":"msg_dec269f49001YC0eLxwU5sI0nr","sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","snapshot":"2912d69d5f7440c74d805edf527f06a9c967e3ed","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777783475068,"sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01SksHcAPbDZLh6G6NKhJZgf","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head","description":"Check existing hypotheses directory"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypotheses directory","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypotheses directory","time":{"start":1777783475050,"end":1777783475066}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at the current best score of 329.56 from the shared multiplier approach, which beat the baseline of 301.04 in the micro_opt category. The recent experiments show that sharing the multiplier gave a solid boost, but multi-cycle MUL/DIV and static branch prediction both caused regressions, so I need to explore different optimization angles from here.\n\nNow I'm examining what's actually on the EX critical path after the multiplier sharing. The path flows through forward muxes, ALU operand muxes, the ALU itself, and then into the EX/MEM register. The ALU is a large case statement handling all operations, and the redirect logic runs combinationally from the comparator back to the IF stage PC register—that's likely where the bottleneck is. I'm considering several micro-optimizations: splitting the shifter into a dedicated path to reduce mux depth, using a single adder with inverted operands for add/sub, simplifying the forward unit by pre-computing register matches, or restructuring the decoder's case statement to help the synthesis tool optimize better. The forward unit comparators also look like they could be a bottleneck, particularly in how they check for write enables and register matches.\n\nLooking at the highest-impact options, I'm weighing whether to optimize the forwarding comparators by pre-computing the write-enable check once, unify the ALU's adder to handle ADD/SUB/SLT/branches through a shared subtractor, move operand selection into the ID stage to shorten EX, or split the shifter out of the main ALU mux. The critical path seems to be the ID/EX register feeding through forward muxes and operand selection into the ALU (especially with multiplication), then the result going to EX/MEM. Combining SLT and branch comparisons into a shared subtractor looks like a practical win since they're currently duplicating that logic.\n\nActually, moving branch comparison entirely into the ID stage could resolve branches earlier and potentially free up EX, though it would complicate forwarding semantics. A simpler win might be pre-computing PC+4 in the IF stage so EX doesn't need a separate adder for JAL return addresses. But the real bottleneck is probably still the multiplier on the critical path—pipelining the multiplier output by adding another stage could give meaningful Fmax gains, similar to how collapsing multiple multipliers helped in the previous iteration.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether one-hot opcode decoding or a shared adder/subtractor with precomputed comparison signals would actually help synthesis, but given we've already squeezed 9.47% from multiplier consolidation, the ALU is likely no longer the critical path. The next bottleneck is probably the load-to-extend-to-register chain from memory, which is probably not critical either. I should focus on identifying what's actually on the critical path now before optimizing further.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec270a970018Zf2bSzyrlbCR7","sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","messageID":"msg_dec269f49001YC0eLxwU5sI0nr"}}
