{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777783492747,"sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","part":{"id":"prt_dec275088001grd9JninuYgmKZ","messageID":"msg_dec2744c0001UO0St1JJQwBIOb","sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","snapshot":"2912d69d5f7440c74d805edf527f06a9c967e3ed","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777783513003,"sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01MhKLgZcxu73hf9jd925PWw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r2s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r2s0\ntitle: \"Share a single 33-bit subtractor across ADD/SUB/SLT/SLTU and branch compare\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  After the shared-multiplier win (+9.47%), the next most redundant arithmetic\n  silicon in the EX cone is subtract/compare logic. The ALU currently synthesises\n  at least three distinct subtract-derived datapaths: one for SUB (a - b), one\n  for SLT ($signed(a) < $signed(b)), and one for SLTU (a < b). In parallel,\n  ex_stage.sv's branch comparator block re-implements signed and unsigned\n  less-than and equality against the same post-forward rs1/rs2 operands. On\n  GW2AR each extra subtract/compare is real LUT4/carry-chain silicon hanging\n  off the forward-mux output pins, inflating rs1/rs2 fanout and keeping the\n  EX-cone carry chain wider than necessary. The multiplier-sharing lesson\n  (r1s0) showed that collapsing redundant arithmetic units on the same\n  forward-mux fanout produces Fmax-bound CoreMark gains well above the mux\n  saving alone. The analogous consolidation for the compare units has not\n  been tried yet.\nhypothesis: |\n  Introduce a single shared 33-bit subtractor inside alu.sv driven by\n  {1'b0, a} - {1'b0, b} (for unsigned lt / eq) and {a[31], a} - {b[31], b}\n  (for signed lt) — implemented as a single 33-bit add with inverted b and\n  carry-in, with the sign-extension bits selected per-op. Expose three\n  flags — eq, lt_signed, lt_unsigned — alongside the ALU's `out` port.\n  ADD and SUB feed from the low 32 bits of the same adder (ADD with sub=0,\n  SUB with sub=1). SLT/SLTU consume lt_signed / lt_unsigned directly.\n  ex_stage.sv drops its own comparator case and derives branch_cond from\n  {eq, lt_signed, lt_unsigned} via a small funct3 mux, using the ALU\n  instance that is already being driven with the (post-forward) rs1/rs2\n  whenever ctrl.is_branch=1 (alu_src=0 for branches, so alu_b already\n  equals rs2). This collapses four independent compare units down to one\n  carry chain, reduces fanout on the forward-mux outputs, and keeps the\n  multiplier sharing untouched. Arithmetic semantics are bit-identical so\n  cocotb test_alu.py, cosim, and riscv-formal (both ALTOPS and deep) should\n  all still pass. Expected Fmax gain on GW2AR is 2-4% with negligible IPC\n  change, producing a CoreMark iter/s win directly proportional to the\n  Fmax delta.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Add unified 33-bit adder/subtractor with per-op sign-extend selects; derive ADD/SUB/SLT/SLTU from its outputs; expose eq/lt_signed/lt_unsigned flag outputs. Keep the shared 33x33 multiplier and ALTOPS branch unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace the branch-comparator case block with a funct3-indexed mux over the new ALU eq/lt_signed/lt_unsigned flags; ensure the ALU is driven with rs2 (not imm) when ctrl.is_branch to get the correct compare operands.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"If needed, widen the ALU-instance interface typedef (flags output) — keep existing ALU_* opcodes and ctrl_t layout unchanged so decoder/id_stage need no edits.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Add direct-check vectors for the new eq/lt_signed/lt_unsigned flag outputs across representative edge cases (signed/unsigned boundary, equal operands, INT_MIN vs -1) to guard the shared-subtractor behaviour; keep all existing ADD/SUB/SLT/SLTU/M-ext vectors intact.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r2s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r2s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777783512985,"end":1777783513001}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I notice the hypothesis directory is empty, so I need to develop one. My thinking is that after achieving a 9.47% gain from multiplier consolidation, the next optimization opportunity lies in eliminating redundant subtraction and comparison logic in the ALU—specifically, the ADD, SUB, SLT, and SLTU operations could potentially share circuitry with the comparison operations (BEQ, BNE, BLT, BGE, BLTU, BGEU) currently implemented separately in the execution stage.\n\nI'm proposing to build a unified 33-bit subtractor that serves all arithmetic and branch comparison needs, exporting equality and signed/unsigned less-than flags that the execution stage can consume directly. This mirrors the successful multiplier-sharing approach and should yield a 3–5% fitness improvement, though I need to be careful about timing paths, branch semantics, and the IO contract. I'll need to modify the ALU module to implement this unified logic, update the execution stage to use the exported flags, and verify the changes don't break existing arithmetic tests.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec27644d00162w2Lsg2bAooBq","sessionID":"ses_213d960fdffe1TJ09PlVYrpLXA","messageID":"msg_dec2744c0001UO0St1JJQwBIOb"}}
