{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777784914954,"sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","part":{"id":"prt_dec3d0404001EgRM7jpQxV6Y3J","messageID":"msg_dec3cf3c60013F46qXjo7KjLB5","sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","snapshot":"c62ebf2621236675137fce5ca1f65d39c0e20bfd","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777784966933,"sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","part":{"id":"prt_dec3dcdda001zGZr5Gi2sDQvCj","messageID":"msg_dec3cf3c60013F46qXjo7KjLB5","sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons:\n- Baseline LUT budget is tight (9905/10000) — BTB failed partly due to area pressure\n- The key signal: \"reclaim area elsewhere first\"\n- Shared multiplier won big by reducing EX-stage resource pressure\n- Anything touching the fetch-to-PC cone regresses\n\nThe regfile is ~1024 FFs (32×32) plus expensive 32:1 read muxes — a prime target for GW2AR distributed-RAM (SSRAM via LUT4) inference. The only thing preventing inference today is the synchronous reset loop zeroing the array.","time":{"start":1777784966618,"end":1777784966932}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777784966964,"sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015tX2ciTfq5NxTrdHbZWX9N","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List existing hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777784966953,"end":1777784966962}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the current fitness of 329.56 versus the baseline of 301.04, I'm reviewing what's worked and what hasn't in this micro-optimization category. The shared multiplier gave a solid boost, but several other approaches—multi-cycle operations, the IF-stage branch predictor, subtractor sharing, and the skid buffer—all created regressions, mostly by impacting the critical path. The BTB didn't help either despite the area pressure.\n\nNow I'm realizing we're nearly at the LUT budget ceiling at 9905/10000, which means Fmax is really the limiting factor here. Any IPC improvement that adds LUTs on the critical path is going to hurt us. So I need to find optimizations that either reduce LUTs, avoid extending critical paths, or ideally shorten them. Looking at what's likely on the critical path—the fetch pipeline through the decoder and hazard logic, the register file read through the forwarding mux into the ALU, or the PC register feeding the instruction memory address—I'm thinking the ALU and its surrounding muxing is probably the bottleneck. I've got a few angles to explore: simplifying the immediate generation logic by computing type-specific low bits and concatenating with a shared sign extension, examining the forwarding unit's 3-way muxes for potential reduction, optimizing the ALU operand muxes that currently handle AUIPC and ALU source selection, and reducing the overall muxing complexity in the EX stage where the forwarding mux feeds into the operand selection. u_src mux, then ALU. That's two mux layers before ALU. Could we merge them?\n\n5. **Remove x0 check from forwarding**: Not a big deal since it's combinational.\n\n6. **Write-first bypass in regfile**: Already done — this adds a mux. Could we remove it if we forward via forward_unit? Actually ID reads regfile, but WB writes happen. The bypass in regfile covers the ID-stage same-cycle bypass. If we remove it, we need WB-to-ID forwarding. Actually no — WB writes come out the same cycle the ID stage reads, so same-cycle write-then-read matters. The regfile bypass handles this.\n\nActually wait — let's think about this. If an instruction N is in WB stage (writing rd), and instruction N+4 is in ID stage reading the same register, the write-first bypass ensures ID sees the new value. Without the bypass, we'd need WB-to-ID forwarding at the top level. But this currently is in reg_file.sv — it's two 32-bit 2:1 muxes on the read path. Not super critical.\n\n7. **Predecode in IF stage**: Hmm, adding logic to IF increases fetch cone. Regression zone.\n\n8. **Lower-latency JAL resolution in ID instead of EX**: JAL target is PC + imm. Resolving JAL in ID would save 1 bubble per JAL. BUT we saw the static BP attempt regress. The issue there was it was on the fetch cone. If we resolve JAL in ID (not in IF), then the redirect happens 1 cycle earlier than EX-stage redirect, saving one bubble. Currently JAL in EX causes 2 flush cycles (IF/ID and ID/EX bubbled). If JAL resolved in ID, only 1 flush cycle. But ID already has the decoder and imm_gen. Adding a redirect path from ID to IF means an extra mux on the PC next path, which could hit the critical path. The previous static BP attempt failed because of the PC cone, so this would likely have the same issue.\n\n9. **Register file as distributed RAM vs flip-flops**: Currently it's LUT flops. Could use distributed RAM on Gowin (if GW2A supports). Maybe BRAM-based regfile? But that has read latency. The GW2AR has LUT4+SSRAM primitives. The regfile uses 32×32 = 1024 flip-flops (1858 FF baseline). If we inferred SSRAM instead, we'd save FFs and LUTs. The issue is reg_file.sv has a reset loop clearing all entries, which prevents Yosys from inferring RAM. Removing the reset and relying on power-on init would let it infer SSRAM instead.\n\nConverting to distributed RAM could free significant LUTs and reduce FF count substantially. A 32x32 dual-read-port regfile would use many LUTs but free all those FFs. The problem is the synchronous reset — Yosys can't infer SSRAM when there's a reset clearing all memory. If we remove the reset (relying on standard RISC-V ABI crt0 to initialize registers), Yosys infers distributed RAM. This is risky without knowing the exact crt0 behavior, but RISC-V ABI typically zeroes registers at startup, and x0 is hardwired anyway. Formal checks and cocotb tests should handle uninitialized state properly. This feels promising but risky — we'd free ~1024 FFs and possibly LUTs, but we'd need to verify it doesn't break formal verification or tests.\n\nOn Gowin, SSRAM infers via LUT4 configured as RAM16X1S/D. A dual-read-port 32x32 regfile would use about 128 LUTs configured as RAM, replacing both the 1024 FFs and the expensive 32:1 read muxes. The net savings would be roughly 384 LUTs freed, which could reduce congestion and enable higher Fmax. The write-first bypass would need careful handling since Gowin SSRAM supports write-first mode natively.\n\nMy hypothesis: convert the register file to distributed RAM by removing the reset loop. This means dropping the reset of the memory array, keeping write-first bypass externally, and using the `ram_style = \"distributed\"` attribute or relying on inference. Gowin SSRAM requires clocked writes, async reads, and no reset—which matches what we need.\n\nAlternatively, I could precompute the JAL return address (PC+4) in the ID stage rather than EX, moving it off the ALU result mux critical path. Since JAL doesn't use the immediate for ALU operations, I could carry PC+4 through the pipeline via the id_ex stage.\n\nBut working through the encoding: JAL could set alu_op to ADD with alu_a=PC and alu_b=4, computing PC+4 naturally in the ALU. This would let me remove the `is_jump ? pc+4 : alu_result` mux in EX—saving one mux layer at the ALU output. The tradeoff is adding a case to the immediate generator and extra mux logic for JAL's ALU inputs. The gain seems modest compared to the added complexity.\n\nI'm going to stick with the distributed RAM approach for the register file.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing the regfile-as-RAM strategy because of yosys_gowin inference risk—if it doesn't cleanly infer SSRAM, I'd end up with LUT-based structures and combinational feedback, which defeats the purpose. Let me explore merging the EX-stage forwarding mux with the ALU operand mux instead. The forwarding unit already selects which value (rs1, ex_mem result, or wb_data) goes to alu_a, but AUIPC bypasses rs1 entirely and uses PC directly. I could fold the forwarding into the ALU input selection, but that doesn't actually save muxes since AUIPC needs to override forwarding anyway. Alternatively, I could move forwarding earlier in the pipeline before the ID/EX register, but that won't work because forwarding depends on EX/MEM and MEM/WB signals from later cycles. Another angle is re-timing the forward select signals themselves to be registered rather than combinational, but that's getting into the weeds.\n\nLet me step back and commit to the regfile-as-SSRAM approach. The BTB lesson specifically says to reclaim area elsewhere first before adding predictor structures, and converting the regfile to distributed RAM is exactly that kind of area reclamation. Gowin BRAM/SSRAM powers up to zero by default, and since our core starts at PC=0 running crt0, any register read before write just gets zero—which is safe. Even for formal verification with riscv-formal's BMC assuming arbitrary initial states, the functional behavior is identical since we're just remapping storage; the core works correctly from any register state.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec3dcef1001zrIpzcWrCTrdAB","sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","messageID":"msg_dec3cf3c60013F46qXjo7KjLB5"}}
