{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777785054360,"sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015y99vn21eSZKWyrfnaN8f9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r3s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r3s0\ntitle: \"Regfile as GW2AR distributed-RAM (SSRAM) — drop reset-loop to free ~1k FFs and the 32:1 read mux cone\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  Baseline uses 9905/10000 LUT4 and 1858 FF on Tang Nano 20K. The r2s2\n  lesson is explicit: \"on a near-full Tang Nano 20K ... reclaim area\n  elsewhere first.\" Prior structural/predictor hypotheses kept bumping\n  into area-induced Fmax/routing walls. The integer register file\n  (`reg_file.sv`) is the single biggest area hog in this design that is\n  NOT on anyone's critical path:\n\n    - 32 × 32b = 1024 FFs (>55% of the total 1858 FF budget)\n    - Two combinational read ports = two 32:1 32b muxes ≈ hundreds of\n      LUT4s for the read fan-in trees\n    - A synchronous-reset foreach loop zeroing the array is the ONLY\n      thing preventing Yosys's `memory_dff`/`memory_bram` pass from\n      mapping this array to GW2AR LUT4-as-SSRAM (distributed RAM) on\n      the Gowin flow.\n\n  GW2AR LUT4s support SSRAM (SP/DP distributed RAM) — a 32×32 two-read\n  one-write configuration maps to roughly 2 rows × 32 cols × 2 read\n  ports = ~128 LUT4s configured as memory, replacing ~1024 FFs AND the\n  32:1 read muxes. Net expected save: ~1024 FF + several hundred LUT4\n  headroom, opening Fmax ceiling on GW2AR where routing/congestion is\n  the dominant Fmax limiter near 99% LUT occupancy.\n\n  Functional behavior must stay bit-identical: x0-hardwire, write-first\n  same-cycle bypass (ID read of a register being written by WB this\n  cycle returns the new value), and the single-write / dual-read port\n  structure. The only change is storage inference, not semantics.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure `rtl/reg_file.sv` so Yosys infers distributed SSRAM on\n  GW2AR instead of flop array:\n\n    1. Delete the `if (reset) for (i=0;i<32;i++) regs[i] <= 0;` branch.\n       Registers start at 0 via Gowin's power-up-to-zero default on\n       SSRAM, which matches the pre-reset architectural state as far\n       as any software is concerned (crt0 loads register values\n       before any meaningful use; x0 is still hardwired at read).\n       riscv-formal BMC already considers arbitrary initial register\n       state so removing the reset cannot break formal — it simply\n       removes a degenerate case.\n    2. Split the dual-read-port structure cleanly:\n         logic [31:0] regs [0:31];\n         // write port\n         always_ff @(posedge clock) if (w_en && w_addr!=0) regs[w_addr] <= w_data;\n         // read ports: pure async read of the array, with x0-zero mask\n         //             and write-first bypass as external muxes.\n         assign rs1_raw = regs[rs1_addr];\n         assign rs2_raw = regs[rs2_addr];\n       plus the existing `if (w_en && w_addr==rs?_addr) rs?_data = w_data`\n       bypass and the `rs?_addr==0 ? 0 : rs?_raw` x0 mask kept EXACTLY\n       as today but moved OUT of the inferred-RAM block. This is the\n       canonical pattern Yosys's memory passes detect as dual-read\n       SSRAM.\n    3. Add a `(* ram_style = \"distributed\" *)` (or the Gowin-specific\n       `(* syn_ramstyle = \"distributed_ram\" *)`) hint on the `regs`\n       declaration so the synthesizer commits to LUT-SSRAM rather than\n       falling back to BRAM (which would add an unwanted read latency)\n       or flops (no gain).\n    4. Preserve the top-level interface BIT-FOR-BIT: same ports, same\n       timing (async read, 1-cycle write), same write-first bypass\n       visible to `id_stage`. No changes anywhere else in the pipeline\n       are required — forward_unit, hazard_unit, and ex_stage see\n       identical values on identical cycles.\n\n  Expected wins:\n    - ~1024 FFs freed (>55% of FF budget) — directly unlocks register\n      placement freedom for the tightly-packed rest of the design.\n    - Several hundred LUT4s freed from the two 32:1 read-mux trees,\n      replaced by ~128 LUTs configured as SSRAM (net save >>0).\n    - Reduced congestion on GW2AR → nextpnr routing finds shorter\n      paths on the EX-cone critical path (alu/forward_mux/ex_mem) the\n      median Fmax reflects.\n    - No impact on IPC: behavior is functionally identical, so the\n      entire delta flows through Fmax × constant-IPC.\n\n  Risk controls:\n    - Keep the x0-zero mask and write-first bypass OUTSIDE the inferred\n      memory (combinational `always_comb`) so the RAM macro remains a\n      pure dual-read/single-write with no reset / no bypass / no port\n      muxing internally — the shape Yosys reliably recognizes.\n    - Tests under `test/test_regfile.py` (if present) and\n      `test/test_pipeline.py` are the cocotb guards; cosim diffs\n      regfile state every retirement via RVFI so any write/read\n      regression surfaces instantly. If cocotb regfile test relies on\n      post-reset registers being 0, relax it to initialize through\n      an explicit ADDI stream or drive an `initial` block in sim.\n    - If Gowin synthesis logs don't show `INFO: Inferring RAM for ...`\n      on the `regs` array, the hypothesis fails loudly (area stays\n      the same, no benefit) — no silent correctness regression.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n    description: \"Rewrite to the canonical Yosys-inferred-distributed-RAM pattern: delete reset-loop over regs; split into (a) pure async-read `regs[rs?_addr]` with `(* ram_style = \\\"distributed\\\" *)` / `(* syn_ramstyle = \\\"distributed_ram\\\" *)` attribute, (b) external x0-mask + write-first bypass in always_comb, (c) single synchronous write port gated on w_en && w_addr!=0. No port shape changes.\"\n  - file: test/test_regfile.py\n    description: \"If the existing suite asserts all-regs-zero after reset, relax it: drive a write sequence first so the test verifies write-then-read round-trip and write-first-bypass behavior (the semantics that actually matter), not the power-up state. Keep the x0-hardwire and write-first-bypass assertions unchanged.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r3s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r3s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777785054356,"end":1777785054360}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_dec3eb026001wB1vOQBbgBEzKz","sessionID":"ses_213c30d33ffeW0EWfCe6z9RYpn","messageID":"msg_dec3ded8f001ZdzfMResT7K6zg"}}
