{"type":"text","timestamp":1777786058105,"sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","part":{"id":"prt_dec4e6401001yZNBCDDiS02pyP","messageID":"msg_dec4bfe5e001YVrPkFCFK1VEyA","sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons carefully:\n- LUT budget is extremely tight: 9905/10000 (99%). Predictors (BTB/RAS) regressed partly because area/congestion nudge erased IPC wins.\n- r1s0 win came from consolidating redundant logic in EX (shared multiplier).\n- r3s0 tried regfile→SSRAM but was **broken** by removing the reset loop entirely — the lesson explicitly names the fix: `` `ifdef FORMAL `` guard or `initial` block.\n- Recent EX-path tweaks (r3s1 WB-mux collapse, r2s0 branch-via-ALU) regressed because they moved logic into series with existing critical cones.\n\nThe r3s0 lesson points to an untapped micro_opt that's *known safe if done right*: the regfile's 32×32 FF array + synchronous zero-loop + 32:1 read muxes is pure headroom on GW2AR — its storage can be LUT-SSRAM, freeing routing congestion on the near-full fabric, which is exactly what's been capping Fmax for the tight-area hypotheses.","time":{"start":1777786053633,"end":1777786058103}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777786058145,"sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01QUtCi7nvFx3jJSh4LPFKSA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5; ls cores/bench/experiments/ 2>/dev/null","description":"check hypotheses directory structure"},"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n","metadata":{"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n","exit":0,"description":"check hypotheses directory structure","truncated":false},"title":"check hypotheses directory structure","time":{"start":1777786058141,"end":1777786058143}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm analyzing the micro_opt target and reviewing what's worked and what hasn't—adding logic to the PC register or execution path tanks the maximum frequency, and the predictors are causing area congestion on an already nearly full fabric. The shared multiplier was the real breakthrough, but collapsing the writeback memory-to-register mux didn't pan out.\n\nNow I'm looking at specific optimization opportunities: the load data path uses a barrel shifter that could theoretically be precomputed earlier, the ALU has redundant shifters that might be consolidated, and there's a separate JALR adder that's duplicating work the ALU already does—if I route the ALU result through for JALR operations instead of computing it separately, that could eliminate unnecessary hardware. For branch_target, the PC comes directly from the ID/EX register without forwarding, so that path can run in parallel with the ALU without creating a critical path issue. The real question is whether consolidating these adders saves area without hurting timing — jalr_sum is definitely redundant since alu_result already computes rs1+imm, but removing it means the jump redirect depends on the ALU output, which might not be on the critical path anyway since both routes are equally deep.\n\nThe cleaner optimization is to move branch_target and jal_target computation into the ID stage where there's slack, then register them into ID/EX. This shifts an adder out of EX's critical path entirely. For JALR, I'd still need the ALU since it depends on rs1, but I can reuse that result directly instead of having a separate jalr_sum adder. This consolidates EX down to just the ALU and a mux for selecting the redirect target. I'm realizing that replacing jalr_sum with alu_result would actually hurt the critical path—alu_result goes through the ALU's case statement and output mux, adding delay compared to a standalone adder. So that's not worth it. Instead, I should focus on the safer approach: precompute pc+imm in the ID stage for BRANCH and JAL targets, which cleanly removes one adder from EX without the complications of trying to reuse alu_result for JALR.\n\nLooking at what actually drives the EX critical path though, it's the ALU itself—specifically the multiplier for MUL operations, which sits inside the case statement. The forward mux feeds into the ALU, then the result goes through a 2:1 mux before the register. So the real bottleneck is the 33×33 multiply, not the pc+imm adder. I'm wondering if I can restructure the ALU case to split out the multiply path and reduce that critical path delay.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the forwarding logic. The regfile has write-first bypass, so when WB writes a value in cycle T and ID reads in the same cycle, ID gets the new value immediately. That means by the time the value reaches the ID/EX register, it should already reflect what WB wrote in the previous cycle. So the WB→EX forwarding path might not be as critical as I thought—I need to trace through whether the ID/EX register actually captures the forwarded value or if there's still a timing issue there. I'm realizing the regfile write-first bypass means the reading instruction in ID sees the updated value in cycle T, but that's a different instruction one cycle behind—the one currently at EX still has the stale value captured in cycle T-1. So MEM/WB forwarding is necessary when the writing instruction is at WB and the reading instruction is at EX in the same cycle, which corresponds to EX/MEM forwarding from the previous cycle's perspective.\n\nThe 3-to-1 mux for MEM/WB forwarding can't be eliminated without changing when the regfile write happens, which would break load semantics. I'm checking if there are other areas to optimize—maybe simplifying the mem_wb_t structure, though RVFI output requires those fields. Let me look at where the actual area savings could come from.\n\nLooking at the resource usage: 905 LUT and 1858 FF against a 10000 LUT target means LUT pressure is the real constraint. The ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t structs carry register values and addresses purely for RVFI, which adds FFs but those are plentiful. The decoder's 10-bit case statement for R-type instructions is already fairly dense, and the 3-to-1 forwarding mux in EX is a bottleneck—it's 32 bits wide and likely consuming multiple LUTs per bit.\n\nI'm exploring whether we can reduce the forwarding mux to 2-to-1 by leveraging the regfile's write-first bypass more aggressively. The key insight is that if WB writes happen in cycle T and ID reads in cycle T, the regfile already reflects the new value. So by cycle T+1 when an instruction reaches EX, it should already have the correct register value from the previous cycle's bypass. The question is whether there's ever a case where an instruction in EX needs to forward from a writer that was only 2 cycles ahead—if so, that writer would still be in the pipeline and we'd need the mux.\n\nAfter working through the timing: a writer 2 cycles ahead (at MEM in cycle T-1) produces its result in the MEM/WB latch at cycle T, but the reader in EX at cycle T already captured a stale value from ID in cycle T-1, so we still need fwd_mem_wb. However, if we move the regfile write to the end of the MEM cycle instead of waiting for WB, then the reader's ID stage in cycle T would see the fresh value via bypass, and by the time it reaches EX in cycle T+1, rs?_val is already correct—eliminating the need for MEM/WB forwarding entirely.\n\nThis restructures the pipeline slightly: the regfile write port is driven directly from MEM's combinational output (load data comes straight from memory), the MEM/WB register still exists for RVFI observation but doesn't trigger a regfile write, and the forward unit simplifies to just a 2:1 mux instead of 3:1. The load data is already combinational from the memory read, so this works without adding extra latency.\n\nFor forwarding, EX/MEM forwarding still works as before since the registered ALU result is available. A writer at EX cycle T moves to MEM at T+1, and a reader at ID cycle T moves to EX at T+1, so the fwd_ex_mem path still handles that case. For loads, the data becomes available combinationally in cycle T and gets written to the regfile synchronously at that same cycle edge, so a reader at ID in cycle T can see it via write-first bypass and captures it in ID/EX. The concern is that the regfile write data path now runs directly from memory output through load extraction to the write port, which could add critical path delay.\n\nThis creates a problem: the write-first bypass mux feeds into the ID stage's read output, so the entire chain from memory data through load extraction, bypass mux, and into the ID/EX register becomes part of the ID critical path. That's a significant amount of combinational logic that could slow down the whole pipeline.\n\nThis approach trades away EX critical path pressure but pushes it onto ID instead, which is risky. I should look for safer optimizations instead.\n\nOne option is precomputing branch and JAL targets in the ID stage since both PC and immediate are available there. I can compute PC+immediate once and register it in ID/EX, then use that precomputed value in EX for branch target calculations and PC next selection. This removes one adder from the EX stage and reduces the logic depth on the PC next and redirect paths.\n\nBut looking at the actual timing: the redirect path goes through the ID/EX register's adder, then through a mux before hitting the PC register. Moving that adder to ID means going through instruction decode, immediate generation, and the adder before the ID/EX register—that's also substantial depth. Whether this helps depends on which stage is currently the bottleneck, so it might just shift the problem rather than solve it.\n\nLet me consider a different approach: eliminating the `rs1_val` and `rs2_val` propagation entirely.\n\nCurrently these values flow through EX/MEM and MEM/WB registers, consuming 128 flip-flops across two stages plus routing overhead. For RVFI compliance, we need all fields present at retirement, so the MEM/WB register must contain them. That means we can't easily remove this propagation—it's a hard requirement.\n\nNow reconsidering the regfile write-first bypass and MEM/WB→EX forwarding: if the regfile already implements write-first bypass, then a read in cycle T can capture a value written in the same cycle T. The timing depends on when the write actually takes effect—at the end of cycle T when the clock edge occurs, the new value gets latched into the register.\n\nFor maximum distance (writer at WB, reader at ID in the same cycle), the bypass logic feeds the write data directly to the reader combinationally, so the ID/EX register captures the correct value without needing MEM/WB forwarding. But for distance 2 (writer at MEM, reader at ID), the bypass doesn't match because the writer hasn't reached WB yet, so the reader gets stale data and MEM/WB forwarding becomes necessary to avoid a stall.\n\nIf I move the writeback to the MEM stage instead, the writer would update the regfile one cycle earlier. Now when the reader is at ID and the writer is at MEM in the same cycle, the bypass logic can match against the MEM-stage write signals combinationally, giving the reader fresh data immediately without needing forwarding. The key is that the regfile's write-first bypass now depends on the MEM stage's combinational outputs rather than waiting for the WB stage.\n\nThe timing concern is real though — the path from memory read data through extraction, the bypass mux, and into the ID/EX flop could get deep. But looking at it more carefully, the current pipeline already has a similar depth from memory data through the MEM/WB flop, so moving that logic earlier is roughly equivalent in terms of critical path. The extra bypass mux adds maybe one LUT level, which isn't a huge deal.\n\nActually, let me step back and go with something simpler and safer instead.\n\nDefining the regfile's synchronous reset logic... Wrapping the synchronous reset in `ifdef FORMAL` lets Yosys infer distributed SSRAM for the 32x32 regfile on GW2AR, freeing up roughly 1000 FFs and associated LUTs from the reset multiplexer. The formal checker still gets its deterministic zero-initialized state for the `reg_ch` verification, while synthesis can optimize away the reset logic entirely.\n\nThe main risk is that cocotb simulation might read undefined values from uninitialized registers, but Verilator defaults to zero anyway, and the test suite likely initializes the regfile through normal execution before reading. The trickier question is whether Yosys will actually infer SSRAM given the x0-bypass logic and the two combinational read ports feeding into the forwarding mux—I need to verify that the inference pattern matches what GW2AR's distributed RAM expects.\n\nLet me think through the capacity math: a 32×32 regfile is 1024 bits, which maps to roughly 64–128 LUTs if converted to LUT-based SSRAM with dual-read, single-write ports. The current FF-based approach burns 1024 FFs plus ~60 LUTs for the read muxes and write decoder, so switching to SSRAM should free up significant area even if it costs a few more LUTs for the dual-port logic.\n\nThe real win here is removing the reset fanout bottleneck—that signal currently drives 1024 FFs—and eliminating routing congestion from the 32:1 read multiplexers. I'm going to commit to the SSRAM approach for Gowin.\n\nNow I need to figure out what actually broke in r3s0. The formal check failed, and the patch was to remove the reset entirely. The proper fix is to guard the reset with a formal-specific macro like `` `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL `` or use an initial block instead. Looking at the codebase, I see `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` is defined during formal verification, so that's likely the macro I should use to conditionally disable the reset.\n\nActually, an initial block is cleaner—it initializes the register file to zero at startup, which works across all three domains: Yosys can infer it as memory initialization without needing a reset path, formal tools respect the initial state, and Verilator runs it at t=0. The tricky part is whether Gowin's SSRAM inference respects initial blocks; distributed SSRAM typically defaults to zeros in the bitstream anyway, so it might just work.\n\nDefining conditional code blocks... I'm estimating maybe 3-5% Fmax improvement if the SSRAM inference works cleanly, though there's a real risk it won't infer properly on Gowin—confidence is medium at best. I considered a few safer alternatives like simplifying the ALU's sign-extension logic or collapsing misalign detection, but those are either already optimized or blocked by runtime dependencies. The regfile SSRAM approach feels like the best bet despite the uncertainty.\n\nNow I'm formalizing this as hypothesis hyp-20260503-001-r4s0, focusing on inferring SSRAM for the regfile with a formal reset guard and zero initialization to handle the LUT pressure.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec4e724e001DROCYkXnajyZea","sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","messageID":"msg_dec4bfe5e001YVrPkFCFK1VEyA"}}
