{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777786114469,"sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","part":{"id":"prt_dec4f519f001q9paHNLX0LB5cO","messageID":"msg_dec4e7f48001w9ZQqYbsy9Vlvs","sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","snapshot":"b4e10c5ba9b96d99d8fe9ad5f454b56e5c6ad01f","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777786145928,"sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","part":{"id":"prt_dec4f5a34001TC5n38rOEKO1dL","messageID":"msg_dec4e7f48001w9ZQqYbsy9Vlvs","sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","type":"text","text":"Now I'll write the hypothesis. The cleanest pattern per r3s0's lesson is the `initial` block — respected by Verilator (cocotb), Yosys→SMT (formal/bitwuzla), and Gowin synthesis (as LUT-SSRAM init). That directly addresses the r3s0 failure mode (\"reg_ch check anchors on deterministic post-reset state\") while still enabling distributed-RAM inference.","time":{"start":1777786116660,"end":1777786145926}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777786145938,"sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01JZJNsw9Fko8PFF8KgnVW42","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r4s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r4s0\ntitle: \"Regfile distributed-SSRAM inference: replace reset-loop with initial-zero block\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current reg_file.sv stores the 32x32 integer file in an FF array\n  with a synchronous reset loop that clears all 32 words in one cycle.\n  On GW2AR this forces Yosys/nextpnr to synthesise:\n    - 1024 FFs of real flop storage (drives utilization; resets fanout\n      to every regfile FF enlarges the reset net).\n    - Two 32:1 read muxes (one per read port) — roughly 60 LUT4 each,\n      i.e. ~120 LUT4 + their routing plus the write-first-bypass muxes.\n    - A 5:32 write-address decoder.\n  This structure is the textbook reason small RISC-V cores on LUT-RAM\n  fabrics move the regfile into distributed SRAM: GW2AR LUTs can be\n  configured as 16x1 single-port SSRAM, so a 32x32x1W/2R file collapses\n  to ~64 SSRAM LUTs (one per read port, dual-read = 2x) with zero FF\n  storage — eliminating the 32:1 read-mux trees and most of the FF\n  pressure. On this project LUTs are 9905/10000 (99% full) — the r2s2\n  BTB lesson explicitly called out that predictor-style wins get erased\n  by congestion-induced Fmax loss. Reclaiming ~100 LUT4 and ~1000 FFs\n  from the regfile is a direct area win that unblocks routing freedom\n  for the existing critical cones, so Fmax should tick up without\n  touching any timing path.\n\n  Prior attempt r3s0 tried this by deleting the reset loop outright and\n  was broken: riscv-formal's per-channel `reg` check (`reg_ch*`) anchors\n  its BMC induction on a known post-reset regfile (all zeros) to diff\n  the DUT's observable rs?_rdata/rd_wdata against the ISA model. With no\n  reset clear and no init, the initial FF state is unconstrained — the\n  check fails. The r3s0 lesson explicitly names the usable pattern:\n  a synthesis-only `ifndef FORMAL` guard, *or* a ROM-init `initial`\n  block. The `initial` form is strictly better: it is accepted by\n    - Verilator (runs initial at t=0, regs start zero in cocotb),\n    - Yosys's SMT backend (bitwuzla sees the initial assignment as the\n      SMT-level initial-state constraint, so riscv-formal's reg_ch\n      induction anchor holds),\n    - Gowin P&R (initial values are bitstream-programmed into LUT-SSRAM\n      init contents — GW2AR distributed RAM supports init values),\n  and doesn't require probing which macro (RISCV_FORMAL vs our own) is\n  defined under formal.\nhypothesis: |\n  In rtl/reg_file.sv, replace the synchronous reset-loop clear of the\n  regs[] array with an `initial` block that zero-initialises regs[0..31]\n  at time 0. Remove the `if (reset)` arm from the write always_ff —\n  leaving a pure 1W2R RAM pattern Yosys can infer as GW2AR distributed\n  SSRAM (aka LUT-RAM). The combinational read side (x0 zero + write-\n  first bypass + regs[addr]) is unchanged; x0 gating stays external\n  because SSRAM has no hard-wired zero word.\n\n  Expected behaviour:\n    - Verilator/cocotb: initial zeros regs at t=0; behaviour matches\n      the old reset-loop result (cocotb tests that assume x1..x31 read\n      as 0 before first write continue to pass).\n    - Formal: Yosys translates the initial assignment into the SMT\n      initial-state constraint, satisfying riscv-formal's reg_ch\n      post-reset-zero induction anchor. Unlike r3s0's bare delete, this\n      preserves the deterministic start state the check depends on.\n    - FPGA synth: with no reset path on the memory inference, Yosys's\n      `memory_dff` / `memory_bram` passes should either match it to\n      GW2AR distributed SSRAM or collapse the 32:1 read muxes into\n      dedicated SRAM read ports. Either way, the storage leaves the\n      FF pool and routing pressure drops.\n\n  Secondary effects we don't expect to need to fix, but will watch for:\n    - Yosys may still emit FFs if it can't prove the reset-free RAM\n      pattern; in that case the `initial` zero-init still makes the\n      change correctness-neutral (no regression, no gain — the bet\n      just doesn't hit).\n    - If Yosys chooses BRAM over SSRAM, the core's BRAM footprint grows\n      by one block; that would be odd for a 1 Kbit file and should not\n      happen — the hypothesis-driven fallback is a synth pragma\n      (`(* ram_style = \"distributed\" *)`) on the regs[] array. The\n      initial implementation will check the `.rpt` file and add the\n      pragma iff Yosys picked the wrong style.\n\n  The cocotb test suite should already cover this (any ALU / pipeline\n  test reads rs? before writing it on occasion during reset). We will\n  also add a focused regfile unit test (test/test_regfile.py) that\n  asserts post-reset rs?_data == 0 for every address, locking the\n  initial-zero contract so future regressions show up there first.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n    description: \"Replace the synchronous reset-loop zero of regs[] with an initial block that zero-initialises regs[0..31]. Drop the `if (reset)` arm from the write always_ff so the write path is a clean 1W2R RAM pattern inferrable as GW2AR distributed SSRAM. Read-side combinational logic (x0 bypass, write-first bypass, regs[addr] read) is unchanged. If the synth report shows FF inference instead of SSRAM, add `(* ram_style = \\\"distributed\\\" *)` to the regs[] declaration as a directed-inference hint.\"\n  - file: test/test_regfile.py\n    description: \"Add a focused cocotb test: apply reset, then read every architectural register (x1..x31) across both read ports and assert the returned data is 0. Locks the initial-zero post-reset contract that riscv-formal's reg_ch check depends on, so future regressions surface here before hitting formal.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r4s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r4s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777786145921,"end":1777786145935}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm concerned that `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` might be used without `RISCV_FORMAL` being properly defined, so I'll switch to using an `initial` block to zero out registers instead—this approach works consistently across formal verification, simulation, and synthesis tools without relying on conditional compilation.\n\nThe `initial` block sets the post-reset state in a way that Yosys, Verilator, and Icarus all respect, and when synthesizing with Yosys on GW2AR, it gets mapped to memory initialization in LUT-SSRAM or BRAM, which aligns with the ROM-init approach from the r3s0 lesson. Now I'll write out this hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec4f5cbf0014o12chhxgx3d3m","sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","messageID":"msg_dec4e7f48001w9ZQqYbsy9Vlvs"}}
