{"type":"text","timestamp":1777786151962,"sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","part":{"id":"prt_dec4fd4b2001MQiWFzj7GhTuie","messageID":"msg_dec4fcce30019xgNDKT3BBnhPN","sessionID":"ses_213b4024fffeICcDWcEMke5wh7","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r4s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Micro-opt targeting the known tight LUT budget (9905/10000). Replace reg_file.sv's synchronous reset-loop zero of the 32×32 array with an `initial` block that zero-inits regs[0..31]. This converts the regfile's FF-array + 32:1 read-mux trees into a clean 1W2R RAM pattern that Yosys can infer as GW2AR distributed SSRAM, freeing ~1000 FFs and ~100 LUT4 worth of mux/routing.\n\n**Why this won't re-break like r3s0:** r3s0 deleted the reset entirely, leaving undefined post-reset state that broke riscv-formal's `reg_ch*` BMC induction anchor. The r3s0 lesson explicitly names the fix: `initial` block (or `` `ifdef FORMAL `` guard). `initial` is strictly better — Verilator honors it at t=0, Yosys's SMT backend translates it into the formal initial-state constraint, and Gowin programs it into SSRAM init contents. Includes a focused `test_regfile.py` to lock the post-reset-zero contract in cocotb before it can hit formal.","time":{"start":1777786148018,"end":1777786151960}}}
