{"type":"text","timestamp":1777788396965,"sessionID":"ses_21390e507ffeKuRsHBtKX02KGL","part":{"id":"prt_dec71ca710011ZOo855HTS6GVc","messageID":"msg_dec71b653001z7IM9jvhEVO8uE","sessionID":"ses_21390e507ffeKuRsHBtKX02KGL","type":"text","text":"The prior r3s1 failure explicitly identified \"shift + sign/zero extend\" as the MEM-stage pre-flop critical cone, but no hypothesis has yet tried to *shorten* that specific cone. That's my micro-opt target.","time":{"start":1777788373617,"end":1777788396964}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777788396980,"sessionID":"ses_21390e507ffeKuRsHBtKX02KGL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01ARvN52TS6uXhCvhZUDZPQK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r6s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r6s0\ntitle: \"Explicit byte/halfword select muxes in mem_stage load-data cone\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The MEM-stage pre-flop critical cone was explicitly named in the\n  r3s1 regression analysis: \"the pre-flop combinational depth (shift\n  + sign/zero extend) is already the MEM critical path\". Today that\n  cone uses a variable 32-bit right-shift:\n\n      shifted   = dmem_rdata >> (in.alu_result[1:0] * 8);\n      byte_val  = shifted[7:0];\n      hword_val = shifted[15:0];\n\n  Structurally this is a full 32-bit barrel shifter whose output\n  narrow-slices are the only consumers — only 8 bits of shifted are\n  needed for byte loads, only 16 bits for halfword loads, and the\n  word-load path (mem_width=2'd2) ignores the shifter entirely and\n  uses dmem_rdata verbatim. The `* 8` literal forces Yosys to reason\n  about a multiply before constant-folding to `{addr[1:0], 3'b0}`,\n  and the downstream bit-slice of a barrel-shifter output is a\n  structure Gowin's LUT4 mapper doesn't always collapse to the\n  minimum byte-mux depth.\n\n  On a near-full fabric (9484/10000 LUT4s at the current best), a\n  cleaner structural expression of \"pick one of four bytes\" (4:1 mux\n  on 8 bits = 2 LUT4 levels) versus an opaque variable shifter\n  frees LUTs and shortens the dmem_rdata → MEM/WB.read_data.D cone\n  that r3s1 already confirmed is on the MEM pre-flop critical path.\n  This is the dual to r3s1's failed move: rather than adding a mux\n  to the cone, shorten the existing cone by replacing an implicit\n  barrel shifter with explicit byte/halfword muxes.\n\n  Distinct from r1s0 (shared multiplier in ALU) — different cone,\n  different stage. Distinct from r3s1 (moved mem_to_reg mux into\n  MEM, regressed) — this keeps the mem_to_reg mux where it is and\n  only shortens the shift+extend sub-cone.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the `shifted = dmem_rdata >> (in.alu_result[1:0] * 8)`\n  variable shifter plus slice with two explicit muxes indexed by\n  `in.alu_result[1:0]`:\n\n    byte_val  : 4:1 mux over the four byte lanes of dmem_rdata\n    hword_val : 2:1 mux over the two aligned halfword lanes\n                ({dmem_rdata[15:0], dmem_rdata[31:16]}) gated on\n                addr[1]; misaligned halfword loads already trap\n                via mem_misalign, so the odd-addr arms are don't-care.\n\n  Word loads continue to use dmem_rdata directly (unchanged).\n\n  Effect:\n  - `byte_val` becomes a 4:1 32-bit→8-bit select ≈ 2 LUT4 levels\n    (vs. a 32-bit barrel shifter collapsed into byte-slice: 3-5\n    LUT4 levels after Yosys structural mapping).\n  - `hword_val` becomes a 2:1 32-bit→16-bit select ≈ 1 LUT4 level.\n  - The sign/zero-extend mux on top is unchanged.\n  - Word-load path unchanged — still dmem_rdata verbatim.\n\n  Semantic preservation: for every legal (non-trapping) load width\n  and address combination, the selected byte_val / hword_val are\n  identical to the variable-shift version:\n    - byte @ addr[1:0]=k → dmem_rdata[8k+7 : 8k]\n    - halfword @ addr[1:0]=0 → dmem_rdata[15:0]\n    - halfword @ addr[1:0]=2 → dmem_rdata[31:16]\n    - halfword @ addr[1:0] in {1,3} → trap (mem_misalign already set)\n  Cocotb load/store tests and cosim ISS diff will catch any slip.\n\n  Expected to shorten the MEM pre-flop cone by 1-3 LUT4 levels on\n  GW2AR and free a handful of LUTs that the current barrel shifter\n  consumes. Net: modest Fmax lift (cycle pressure on dmem_rdata →\n  MEM/WB.D) plus tiny area win, both of which compound through the\n  near-full fabric's placement/routing pressure.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace `shifted = dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0]*8)` + slice-to-byte_val/hword_val with explicit byte-lane and halfword-lane muxes on `in.alu_result[1:0]`. Keep mem_misalign, sign/zero-extend, word-load path, and MEM/WB register logic unchanged. Remove the `shifted` intermediate and its verilator UNUSEDSIGNAL pragma if no longer needed.\"\n  - file: test/test_mem_stage.py\n    description: \"Add or extend cocotb vectors exercising byte loads at all four byte-lanes (addr[1:0] ∈ {0,1,2,3}) with both signed (LB) and unsigned (LBU) extension, plus aligned halfword loads (addr[1:0] ∈ {0,2}) for LH/LHU, verifying load_data bit-exactness against the shift-then-slice reference. If test_mem_stage.py does not exist, add the coverage to the existing mem-related cocotb suite (test_pipeline.py or test_loads.py — adapt to whatever exists).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r6s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r6s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777788396960,"end":1777788396978}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I see that previous attempts modified the write-back stage multiplexer placement, which added complexity to the memory stage pipeline. My approach is different—I'm focusing on actually reducing the critical path through the shift-and-extend logic without moving the mux around. Let me formalize this as a concrete hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec71cc05001VejUa8DcVtDhT4","sessionID":"ses_21390e507ffeKuRsHBtKX02KGL","messageID":"msg_dec71b653001z7IM9jvhEVO8uE"}}
