{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777789872041,"sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","part":{"id":"prt_dec88a7a1001ArBPCsV4TU505m","messageID":"msg_dec8891f3001qBt6NKr5qw7ocE","sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","snapshot":"10ab80f7cf46f18a19d30ab4dc26f480b0faaa7c","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777789971193,"sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","part":{"id":"prt_dec8a221b001qpD2V05ryYHqrV","messageID":"msg_dec8891f3001qBt6NKr5qw7ocE","sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons and recent outcomes, I need to find a safe micro_opt that doesn't touch the formal tarpits (regfile reset, JAL/JALR link folding, MEM load-data, predictors with mispredict arms).\n\nThe r4s2 JAL fast-path winner (+17.73%) added a 2:1 mux `ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target : id_jal_target` in front of the PC D-input. This means `ex_redirect_target`'s combinational cone is now part of the PC-redirect critical path.\n\nExamining `ex_stage.sv`:\n```\nbranch_target = in.pc + in.imm;\njump_target = is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : (in.pc + in.imm);\nredirect_target = is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target;\n```\n\nThe `!is_jalr` arm of jump_target computes `pc+imm`, identical to branch_target. The cascade is a 3:1 mux-of-muxes (2 LUT4 levels), but structurally it's a 2:1 mux on `is_jalr` alone. Yosys may or may not flatten this — and even if it does, the explicit form removes any doubt and can only help.\n\nLet me also look at the `is_jump && !jal_predicted` gate on redirect — this AND of two flop outputs can be pre-computed at ID into a single ctrl bit.","time":{"start":1777789968923,"end":1777789971191}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777789971229,"sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Ez18pFCLX23waD1yENZsdb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check hypothesis directory exists"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypothesis directory exists","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypothesis directory exists","time":{"start":1777789971215,"end":1777789971227}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm working through a micro-optimization hypothesis for the cores/bench benchmark, trying to beat the current best of 387.98 from the JAL fast-path optimization. Based on what's worked and failed before, I'm noting that branch predictor designs with misprediction handling don't perform well on this architecture, distributed register file approaches create bottlenecks, and memory load refactoring tends to introduce formal verification issues—so I should focus on the link-value optimization pattern that proved successful with JAL/JALR.\n\nNow I'm examining what optimization opportunities remain untapped. The EX stage is clearly the critical bottleneck with its forwarding mux, ALU with the shared multiplier, branch comparator, and pc_next mux all competing for timing. I'm considering whether the redirect target muxing logic—currently handling both jump and branch targets—could be restructured to reduce the mux depth, particularly around the JAL target computation where there might be redundant logic I can eliminate. I'm noticing that redirect_target goes through a series of muxes on the critical path to the PC register, and I can simplify this by merging the branch and jump target logic. Since both paths ultimately compute pc+imm when not doing a JALR, I can collapse the muxing down to just checking if it's a JALR operation—if so, use the shifted rs1+imm result, otherwise use pc+imm for everything else.\n\nThe synthesizer might already optimize this away, but making it explicit as a single 2:1 mux could help. Though I should verify this actually improves timing rather than just being a cosmetic change—Yosys is usually good at common subexpression elimination on adders anyway.\n\nLet me explore a different optimization angle instead, maybe looking at the load-use hazard detection logic to see if there's slack to reclaim there. I'm realizing that for AUIPC, the rs1 field in the instruction doesn't actually represent a register dependency—it's just bits that get ignored. So instead of using a mux to select between rs1 and pc in the EX stage, I could move that selection earlier: in the ID stage, I'd pre-compute which value should feed alu_a (pc for AUIPC, rs1 for everything else) and store it in the pipeline register, eliminating the mux from the critical path.\n\nBut there's a catch with RVFI—it expects rs1_rdata to reflect what was actually read from the register file, not the pc value we'd substitute for AUIPC. If I patch rs1_val to pc at ID stage, the formal verification would fail because it would see pc instead of the register value. So I'd need to keep rs1_val untouched and route pc to alu_a through a separate path, which defeats the whole optimization.\n\nLooking at what's actually critical in the EX stage, the real bottleneck is probably the divider for DIV/REM operations—those are combinational and brutally slow. The forward mux and ALU operand selection are in the critical cone too, but the AUIPC mux is just a single LUT and unlikely to be the limiter. CoreMark uses MUL heavily, so multi-cycling those would hurt IPC, but DIV/REM are rare enough that making them multi-cycle might be worth exploring without the performance regression.\n\nI'm thinking about whether we can reduce the forward mux depth. The forward_unit outputs a 2-bit selector for a 3:1 mux in EX, which takes 2 LUT levels for 32 bits. Could we move the forwarding logic earlier to ID stage instead? We'd read the regfile and apply forwarding from EX/MEM and MEM/WB right there, so the ID/EX flop already captures the forwarded value and EX doesn't need a mux at all. This shifts the timing pressure to ID, which typically has more slack. The tradeoff is that the forwarding comparison would need to happen in ID, but that's a well-known technique.\n\nThe catch is that ID-stage forwarding can't handle the EX slot—when an older instruction is still in EX computing its result, we can't forward its value yet to an instruction in ID. We'd need to stall every time, which would kill IPC. So we'd need EX to still forward from its own EX/MEM register for that one-cycle hazard, which means we're back to needing a mux in EX anyway. The complexity is whether we can make this work without losing performance.\n\nLet me step back and try a different angle. What if I can simplify the AUIPC handling by merging it with the existing ALU operand muxes? The issue is AUIPC needs pc as one operand and imm as the other, but the current setup routes rs1 and rs2 through separate paths. Trying to reroute pc into rs1 or rs2 would break RVFI compliance, so that's not viable.\n\nFor the multiplier's sign-extension logic, I can simplify the case statement by recognizing that sext_a should be false only for MULHU, and sext_b should be false for both MULHU and MULHSU—so I can express these as simple boolean functions of the operation type rather than listing every case.\n\nNow looking at the PC redirect critical path, the bottleneck seems to be the chain from rs1 through the forwarding mux, into the JALR adder, then through the masking and jump target mux before reaching the PC input. The JALR masking step that clears the low bit could potentially be moved earlier to reduce the depth of the final redirect target mux.\n\nI notice the redirect_target mux has redundancy—both the jump and branch paths compute pc+imm, so the logic could collapse into a simpler conditional that only needs to choose between the JALR result and the pc+imm path.\n\nSimplifying redirect_target... I'm considering whether to move the forwarding mux selection logic into the forward_unit itself, so it outputs the final 32-bit value instead of just a 2-bit selector — but that doesn't actually reduce timing depth since the mux still needs to happen somewhere. Instead, I'm focusing on a concrete micro-optimization: consolidating the branch and jump target muxes in the EX stage to share the PC+immediate adder and reduce the redirect_target to a single 2:1 mux, though I'm uncertain if Yosys already does this CSE. Looking at the immediate generator as another opportunity, I notice the 6-way case statement on opcode could potentially be compressed by exploiting patterns in the opcode bits.\n\nNow examining the misalign_fault path more carefully — since immediate bit 0 is always 0 for B and J type instructions, and the PC is always aligned, branch_target[0] is guaranteed to be 0. For JAL, the same holds because imm[0]=0. Without the compressed extension, the [1:0] != 0 check effectively reduces to just checking bit [1], which is a small but concrete optimization.\n\nFor JALR though, jump_target = rs1 + imm with bit 0 cleared, so bit [1] could be anything — this is riskier to optimize away since riscv-formal might test those cases explicitly.\n\nMy best bet is to restructure the redirect_target mux: instead of cascading three options (JALR, JAL, branch), I can fold it into a 2:1 mux on is_jalr, since both the non-JALR jump case and the branch case compute pc+imm. This tells Yosys the target is one of two values rather than three, which should flatten the combinational cone better. It's semantically identical and low-risk, with a potential small Fmax win if Yosys wasn't already doing this CSE.\n\nI also considered whether moving the misalign check off the redirect path would help, but that breaks the riscv-formal requirement that the trapping instruction's pc_wdata stays as pc+4 when misaligned — so that's not viable. I'm also reconsidering whether the `!jal_predicted` gate on the redirect expression could be removed, but I need to think through the implications more carefully before committing to that change.\n\nFor now, I'm going to focus on the redirect_target simplification in the EX stage. The current mux cascades through two levels to select between jalr_masked, pc_plus_imm, and branch_target, but since branch_target equals pc_plus_imm, I can collapse this to a single 2:1 mux that just picks between jalr_masked and pc_plus_imm — saving one LUT level in the PC-redirect cone. Yosys might preserve the mux cascade if it doesn't recognize that both non-jalr branches converge to the same value, so I'll write it out explicitly. The redirect signal `branch_taken || (is_jump && !jal_predicted)` could potentially simplify, but since branch_taken and is_jump are mutually exclusive from the decoder, expressing it as `(is_branch && branch_cond) || (is_jump && !jal_predicted)` doesn't really help. Let me focus on two concrete micro-optimizations: first, collapse redirect_target to a single 2:1 mux keyed on is_jalr, and second, pre-compute `jump_needs_ex_redirect = is_jump && !jal_predicted_in` as a control bit at the ID stage. Both target the PC-redirect critical path that r4s2's JAL fast-path already operates on. Since r4s2 added a mux at the top level between ex_redirect_target and id_jal_target, if I can reduce ex_redirect_target to one LUT level, the total path becomes 2 LUT levels instead of 3.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec8a2844001eepphqKRKM6ghs","sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","messageID":"msg_dec8891f3001qBt6NKr5qw7ocE"}}
