{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777789998427,"sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01M7LPwdaosJ6nGcfhQBJdMq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r7s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r7s0\ntitle: \"Flatten ex_stage redirect_target to a single 2:1 mux on is_jalr\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The r4s2 JAL-at-ID fast-path (+17.73%, current best 387.98) added a 2:1\n  mux in front of the PC D-input: `ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target :\n  id_jal_target`. That mux sits on the PC-redirect critical path, which\n  means `ex_redirect_target`'s combinational cone is now directly timed\n  against fetch Fmax. Any LUT level shaved from `ex_redirect_target`\n  shortens the PC-redirect arm and potentially lifts Fmax without\n  touching IPC.\n\n  Past branch-predictor hypotheses (r1s2 static BP, r2s2 BTB, r3s2 RAS,\n  r6s2 BTFN) all regressed because they loaded the PC-select cone. The\n  inverse strategy — structurally *simplifying* cones that already feed\n  the PC-select — is underexplored. r4s2's success pattern itself was\n  \"resolve one stage earlier and share the existing redirect net\"; a\n  natural complement is \"make the existing redirect net's cone shallower\n  where structural redundancy exists\".\nhypothesis: |\n  Two structural simplifications local to ex_stage.sv + a 1-bit ctrl\n  bit added at id_stage — all semantically bit-for-bit identical to\n  today's RTL, so formal should pass untouched.\n\n  (1) Collapse redirect_target mux cascade.\n      Today:\n        branch_target   = in.pc + in.imm;\n        jump_target     = is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : (in.pc + in.imm);\n        redirect_target = is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target;\n      Since the `!is_jalr` arm of jump_target is `pc+imm`, identical to\n      branch_target, the three-valued cascade collapses to a strict 2:1:\n        redirect_target = is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0}\n                                  : (in.pc + in.imm);\n      This is the same pattern r4s2 exploited on the ID side (single 2:1\n      upstream of the existing PC D-input mux). On GW2AR LUT4s the 2:1\n      is 1 LUT level vs the cascade's 2 LUT levels, shaving one LUT4 off\n      the redirect cone in the unconditional-branch / taken-BRANCH /\n      JALR paths. Yosys may or may not already CSE this — being explicit\n      removes the dependency on the synthesizer doing the right thing,\n      at zero cost in expressivity.\n\n  (2) Pre-compute the \"jump needs EX redirect\" predicate at ID.\n      Today: `redirect = (branch_taken || (is_jump && !jal_predicted))\n                         && !misalign_fault;`\n      The `is_jump && !jal_predicted` AND of two id_ex flop outputs can\n      be pre-computed at id_stage into a new ctrl bit\n      `jump_needs_ex_redirect`. This saves one AND-gate level from the\n      EX-side `redirect` output, which feeds both if_stage's combined\n      `redirect` and hazard_unit's `flush_if`. The ID-side AND runs in\n      parallel with the wide IF→ID/EX combinational path, which has\n      abundant slack.\n\n  (3) No RVFI, decoder, IO, or formal-cone changes. `jal_predicted`\n      propagation through id_ex is preserved (EX may still reference\n      it for the new ctrl bit's derivation or drop it — the canonical\n      form is to replace `jal_predicted` with the precomputed bit and\n      update the one consumer in ex_stage).\n\n  The gains are each small (a LUT level here, a LUT level there), but\n  both land on the post-r4s2 critical path. Multi-percent Fmax is\n  plausible on near-full GW2AR where LUT-depth reduction on hot cones\n  reliably translates to MHz. IPC is unchanged by construction.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace the `is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target` cascade with a single 2:1 mux `is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : (in.pc + in.imm)`. Consume the new ctrl bit `jump_needs_ex_redirect` from id_ex in place of the `is_jump && !jal_predicted` AND in the `redirect` output expression. Keep pc_next logic, misalign handling, and the EX/MEM register layout otherwise unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add a `jump_needs_ex_redirect` bit to the id_ex_t struct (or reuse the jal_predicted field inverted — equivalent). Update doc comments so the contract with ex_stage is obvious.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute `jump_needs_ex_redirect = ctrl_decoded.is_jump && !jal_predicted_in` combinationally and register it into id_ex alongside the other ctrl fields. No change to regfile reads, decoder wiring, or RVFI-feeding fields.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"No functional change; the top-level wiring between id_stage, ex_stage, and hazard_unit is unaffected since jal_predicted_in is already driven by id_is_jal_fire. Only the ctrl-bit plumbing through id_ex moves from jal_predicted to the inverted jump_needs_ex_redirect form if that naming is chosen.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r7s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r7s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777789998413,"end":1777789998425}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_dec8a3b60001u5M57NSoXFiGcr","sessionID":"ses_213776ec0ffeEvzsRffxmSeYkT","messageID":"msg_dec8a35b2001wqnz9o13XqtAGO"}}
