{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777791742910,"sessionID":"ses_2135add8affeu0S6g7IlssIi6u","part":{"id":"prt_deca533b800145t8LqZrPdI8tv","messageID":"msg_deca523a2001WI8LvXYoos9wDR","sessionID":"ses_2135add8affeu0S6g7IlssIi6u","snapshot":"c5241aeb0c778405309c888ed4621bc5cac1227d","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777791802868,"sessionID":"ses_2135add8affeu0S6g7IlssIi6u","part":{"id":"prt_deca60eec001AlXfiFdU0vjv3o","messageID":"msg_deca523a2001WI8LvXYoos9wDR","sessionID":"ses_2135add8affeu0S6g7IlssIi6u","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons and recent outcomes, I need to find a micro_opt that avoids the known tarpits:\n- Don't rename/remove id_ex struct fields (r7s0)\n- Don't widen EX redirect_target past 2:1 with predictor arms (r6s2, r7s2)\n- Don't collapse parallel arithmetic cones into shared deeper ones feeding critical paths (r2s0, r7s1)\n- Don't touch regfile port shape for distributed SSRAM (r5s0, r6s1)\n- Don't refactor the mem pre-flop load-data cone (r6s0)\n\nLet me examine a concrete simplification opportunity in `ex_stage.sv`: the `redirect_target` path currently goes through a 3-way structure (jump_target itself is a 2:1 mux, then redirect_target picks jump_target vs branch_target). But `branch_target = in.pc + in.imm` and `jump_target`'s non-JALR arm is also `in.pc + in.imm` — identical. So the outer `is_jump` mux is semantically redundant.","time":{"start":1777791799020,"end":1777791802867}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777791802909,"sessionID":"ses_2135add8affeu0S6g7IlssIi6u","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_0137u3JHtMYixs3BQnNKiXS5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check hypotheses dir exists"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypotheses dir exists","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypotheses dir exists","time":{"start":1777791802893,"end":1777791802907}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at the current fitness score of 387.98 against the baseline of 301.04, and the most promising recent win was the JAL fast-path optimization that gained 17.73%. The last several attempts have all been setbacks, so I need to be more careful—I've learned that modifying the id_ex_t struct field names breaks formal verification, and I should avoid routing changes that caused previous failures.\n\nLooking at what's left to optimize, I'm noticing the branch condition logic in ex_stage has redundant comparison operations across different branch types. The equality and less-than comparisons are being computed separately for each branch variant, but I could consolidate these into shared primitives and let the synthesis tool reuse them rather than duplicating the logic.\n\nFor the memory stage, the byte-lane mask generation and load data shifting are already pretty minimal—the mask shifter handles alignment cases and the load shifter is essentially a 4-way multiplexer, both of which synthesis should handle efficiently. The aligned address computation is already just zeroing the bottom 2 bits, so there's not much room there either.\n\nLooking at the critical path, the main bottlenecks are the fetch redirect cone, the EX forward mux and ALU, and the load data extend before the MEM flop. I could try registering the branch condition earlier, but that would add pipeline stages which defeats the purpose. Precomputing something in the ID stage might help reduce EX work though.\n\nThe decoder's large case statement and the imm_gen's 7-way case could potentially be faster. The sign-extension selection in the ALU for the multiplier already uses a reasonable AND-gate approach. Looking back at what's actually worked—the shared 33x33 multiplier gave a 9.47% win and the JAL fast-path gave 17.73%—I should focus on similar structural improvements rather than gate-level tweaks.\n\nThe hazard unit's load_use_hazard check could potentially be simplified by compressing the comparison logic.\n\nI'm considering moving imm_gen partially into the IF stage to shorten the ID critical path, though this needs careful handling. For branches, the key insight is that branch_cond is really just a 6-way case on rs1 vs rs2, which could be recoded as three checks: equality, signed less-than, and unsigned less-than, with an invert bit from funct3[0]. Yosys should already optimize this though, so explicit recoding probably won't help much.\n\nThe ALU operand muxes are already minimal 2:1 muxes, so there's not much room there. For the memory stage, I could derive the write mask directly from funct3 instead of using a case statement.\n\nLooking at forwarding, the current 2-bit fwd_rs*_sel driving a 3:1 mux is probably fine as-is. The rvfi_order_q increment is already a simple 1-cycle flop. JAL prediction handling needs the jal_predicted bit to work correctly. The decoder's 7-bit opcode case should synthesize well. I'm wondering if rs1_val and rs2_val in the EX/MEM pipeline are actually necessary or if they're just stored for RVFI purposes.\n\nActually, those post-forwarded values are used by EX itself, so they can't be removed. But they do add 64 bits to the pipeline register. I could potentially add new fields without renaming existing ones, though that feels risky. The pc_next computation is a 4-way mux but it's not on the critical path since it only feeds the MEM/WB flop. The repeated `in.pc + 32'd4` might get common-subexpression eliminated by the synthesizer anyway. For redirect_target, I'm seeing that it's either the aligned JALR result, the JAL offset, or the branch offset — there might be a way to simplify how these cases are encoded.\n\nLooking at the redirect_target logic more carefully, JAL and branch both compute `in.pc + in.imm`, so I could flatten this to a simple 2:1 mux on is_jalr instead of the current 3-level structure through jump_target and is_jump. This is exactly what r7s0 tried, but it failed because it renamed a struct field. If I flatten the logic without touching any field names, just appending new fields if needed, this optimization should work. Verifying the logic of the simplified redirect_target assignment: for JALR it uses the masked sum, for everything else it computes PC plus immediate, which correctly handles both JAL and branch cases. The key insight is that this flattening removes a mux level in the combinational path without changing the actual values, and the previous regression was tied to a rename issue rather than the flattening itself. Simplifying the redirect logic...\n\nI'm collapsing the mux hierarchy by making `redirect_target` directly select between `jalr_target` and `branch_target` based on `is_jalr`, which eliminates one mux level and should reduce the critical path delay. The key insight is that `branch_target` was always just `pc + imm` anyway, so the outer `is_jump` mux was redundant. I need to verify this actually helps by checking if the redirect path is on the critical path, and I should keep the `branch_target` field in the EX/MEM struct to avoid the struct field renaming issues from the r7s0 lesson.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deca61b2a001AaORSo1awD3lzt","sessionID":"ses_2135add8affeu0S6g7IlssIi6u","messageID":"msg_deca523a2001WI8LvXYoos9wDR"}}
