{"type":"text","timestamp":1777792895428,"sessionID":"ses_2134abfcaffe4KQES1L5K9Huyy","part":{"id":"prt_decb6bd56001VT7Or5nxb4n0T5","messageID":"msg_decb540ec001aUxNgJUtbFuyZn","sessionID":"ses_2134abfcaffe4KQES1L5K9Huyy","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons, I need to avoid the well-documented tarpits:\n- id_ex_t symbol edits (r7s0)\n- redirect_target cone restructures (r8s0, r8s1)\n- MEM load-data reshuffles (r6s0)\n- Regfile reset/init changes (r3s0, r5s0, r6s1)\n- JAL/JALR link-value folding (r5s1, r4s1)\n- Predictors that add a second ID-redirect arm (r6s2, r7s2)\n\nThe fabric is 9484/10000 LUT4 (94.8% full). Area reclaim that doesn't touch hot cones seems like the untried safe-ish micro_opt. The ALU has three separate barrel shifters (SLL, SRL, SRA). SLL can be implemented as bit-reversed SRL, sharing one shifter — a classic area trick that's local to alu.sv and bit-exact.","time":{"start":1777792892246,"end":1777792895427}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777792895460,"sessionID":"ses_2134abfcaffe4KQES1L5K9Huyy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_012EhztQw7vMUKCnpf7Jr6Nv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check hypothesis dir exists"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypothesis dir exists","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypothesis dir exists","time":{"start":1777792895437,"end":1777792895458}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the performance data, the biggest breakthrough was the zero-storage JAL fast-path optimization that gained 17.73%, while most regressions came from modifying id_ex_t fields and making changes to the redirect logic and predictor. I'm identifying the formal bottlenecks—regfile reset, JAL/JALR link mux, memory load-data paths—to guide the micro_opt hypothesis for this benchmark.\n\nThe current fitness of 387.98 is well ahead of the baseline 301.04, but I'm trying to find untapped optimization opportunities that don't hit known tarpits. The shared 33x33 multiplier was already a win, and most predictor/BTB/RAS attempts have regressed. Looking at what's left: the combinational divider in the ALU is likely the critical Fmax path, and pipelining just the division operation—separate from multiplication—might be worth exploring since the full MUL/DIV pipeline attempt regressed earlier.\n\nFor remaining micro-opts, I'm considering decoder flattening to reduce ID-stage setup time, flattening the forward unit's priority chain into a truth table, or unifying the shift operations to save LUTs. The AUIPC pre-computation is tempting—moving pc+imm into the ID stage—but that would pull the immediate generator output into the EX operand mux cone, which is currently a simple 2:1 between pc and rs1. Both pc and rs1 are already flopped in the ID/EX register, so the mux depth there is already constrained.\n\nThe real bottleneck is likely the combinational divider. On an FPGA, signed division synthesizes into a massive ripple-subtractor chain—probably 32 stages deep of 32-bit compares and subtractions. That's almost certainly the longest combinational path in the ALU and the Fmax limiter. Making DIV multi-cycle would remove it from the critical path entirely. The r2s1 lesson warned that pipelining both MUL and DIV regressed CoreMark due to stall cycles, but CoreMark barely uses DIV in its hot loops. Pipelining DIV alone while keeping MUL combinational would eliminate the biggest Fmax bottleneck with minimal IPC cost.\n\nThe synthesis tool builds both the multiplier and divider combinationally inside the always_comb block, then the output mux selects between them. So the divider's delay—potentially 60+ LUT levels—plus the final mux delay determines Fmax. An FSM-based DIV pipeline could break this critical path.\n\nLooking at what else might help: the forward unit's comparison logic for detecting register hazards runs multiple comparators in parallel (checking ex_mem_rd against both id_ex_rs1 and id_ex_rs2, same for mem_wb), plus the != 5'b0 check. This could be a candidate for critical-path restructuring.\n\nI could precompute whether ex_mem_rd is nonzero as a flopped bit in the ex_mem struct to save a LUT level, though I need to be careful—the lessons flag id_ex_t edits as risky, but ex_mem_t additions seem safer since they're just additive.\n\nThe load-use hazard detector also reads imem_data combinationally (the rs1 and rs2 fields) and compares them against id_ex_rd, feeding into the stall signal. Precomputing a \"load_pending\" flop wouldn't help much though. Let me dig deeper into where the real bottleneck is.\n\nAfter the r4s2 improvement, the ID-stage JAL fast-path now dominates the fetch redirect cone—it extracts the J-immediate from imem_data, adds it to the flopped PC, and drives the redirect target directly. That's BRAM output → immediate extraction → 32-bit adder → mux → PC input, and the carry chain through that adder could be the critical path. The lesson from r8s2 showed that registering jal_target didn't help, but what if I precompute just the lower bits of the JAL target specially? Since the J-immediate has a fixed structure with bit 0 always zero and PC is always aligned, the low bits of the addition are predictable.\n\nActually, the full 32-bit add isn't that bad—there's not much to optimize there. Let me look at the ALU instead. That giant case statement with 19+ operations probably decodes to a 5-input decoder feeding a massive mux, all running combinationally from the flopped alu_op. Yosys likely already does some grouping, but I could explore splitting the ALU into functional groups and picking within each group. Or I could try using the forward unit to precompute sums and differences gated by the operation, though that's essentially the same as the ALU mux. The memory write-data replication logic that handles byte/half/word widths is also combinational and feeds both the DMEM port and the MEM/WB register, but that's a minor optimization target.\n\nThe dmem byte-mask shifter is interesting—it takes the ALU result and shifts a mask based on the address alignment, and this path feeds directly to dmem_wen as a combinational output. That's the store address-to-enable critical path for the memory bus, though it's usually not the Fmax bottleneck. There's also the ALU's multiplier sign-extend logic that uses a case statement to set sign-extension flags, then applies them with AND gates and concatenation...\n\nHandling sign-extension for multiply operations...\n\nNow I'm thinking about concrete optimizations. The fetch-redirect cone is heavily contested, id_ex_t is frozen, and MEM load-data is a bottleneck. The safer approach would be to shave LUT cost on non-critical paths or simplify EX-stage logic that doesn't touch redirect_target or pc_next. I'm wondering if I can remove the redundant x0 checks in the forward_unit—when ex_mem_rd is zero, reg_write should already be gated. But looking at wb_stage, there's no x0 check there; the regfile does the gating internally. So forward_unit does need that check. What if I precompute in the decoder with a reg_write_nonzero signal that combines reg_write with a check that rd isn't x0, then add that to ex_mem? That would eliminate the redundant check downstream, though it means expanding ex_mem slightly.\n\nLet me explore a different angle: shortening the critical path in the regfile read bypass. The current three-way priority mux (x0 check, write-first bypass, regfile read) creates a long cone from MEM load_data through the WB mux to w_data to the regfile bypass mux and into the ID/EX flop. I could split this bypass out to the EX stage instead—remove it from the regfile and add an extra forward mux in EX that selects between regfile output and mem_wb.w_data. But that's essentially what the forward_unit already does via fwd_mem_wb. The regfile bypass might actually be redundant since the forward_unit handles MEM/WB→EX forwarding, and the regfile gets written at the posedge anyway for ID-stage reads.\n\nActually, the write happens at posedge, so before that the regfile holds the old value. An instruction in ID reading combinationally would see the old value, but after the posedge the new value is there for the next cycle's read. The regfile bypass matters for same-cycle write-then-read in ID, but without it that instruction would just rely on fwd_mem_wb once it reaches EX. Removing the bypass would eliminate the 32-bit 2-port read mux (~64 LUTs), which might help routing even if it's not the main Fmax bottleneck. The forward logic and regfile bypass are computing the same thing from equivalent signals, so it should work—just need to verify the timing flow when WB writes and ID reads in the same cycle.\n\nWait, actually there's a problem. If I remove the bypass, the instruction reads the old value into id_ex, then by the time it's in EX the next cycle, mem_wb has already advanced to a different instruction. So fwd_mem_wb won't match the x5 writer anymore—it'll be looking at whatever new instruction is in WB. That means I'd need a third forwarding source to handle writes from two cycles ago, which defeats the purpose. Scratch that idea.\n\nLet me think about a different optimization: maybe I can flatten the ALU mux or use binary decoding for the 19 operations on the 5-bit opcode. Or here's a simpler one—implement SLL as bit-reversed SRL to share the shifter hardware, which is a common trick that could save around 32 LUT levels.\n\nLooking at the three shift operations, I initially thought there were three separate barrel shifters, but actually SRL and SRA probably already share hardware since they only differ in the fill bit. SLL is the odd one out since it shifts the opposite direction. The bit-reverse approach would use a single shift-right unit with input and output bit-reverse muxes for SLL, but those muxes aren't free—they'd be two 32:1 multiplexers. If I unconditionally reverse for SLL, the logic becomes selecting whether to reverse the input and output based on the operation type.\n\nThe math works out to saving roughly one full barrel shifter (~90 LUT4s) while adding about 64 LUT4s of mux logic, netting maybe 30 LUT4s saved overall. That adds one LUT level to the critical path, but since SLL isn't timing-critical and the shifter isn't the bottleneck anyway, this is area-positive and Fmax-neutral. At 95% fabric utilization, even 0.3% savings could help with routing.\n\nNow I'm reviewing what micro-optimizations have actually been attempted across the design iterations to see what's left unexplored.\n\nLooking at the untried options, dedicated DIV pipelining stands out as higher-impact since DIV is often the actual critical path. The tradeoff is that moving to an FSM removes the combinational divider (big Fmax win) but makes DIV take 32+ cycles instead of 1. CoreMark doesn't use DIV heavily though, so if it's rare enough, the latency gets hidden and the Fmax improvement could outweigh the per-DIV cost.\n\nBut integrating that into the hazard_unit is risky given the earlier regressions. Instead, I'm going to go with barrel shifter unification—implementing SLL via bit-reverse of SRL/SRA. It's a genuinely local ALU optimization that avoids touching the redirect cone, id_ex_t, memory load-data, or regfile reset (all the problematic areas). It should reduce LUT count modestly, and since shifts aren't typically Fmax-critical, the extra LUT level is acceptable.\n\nRecalculating: saving 30–50 LUTs on a 9484-LUT design that's already lost ~500 LUTs of headroom could actually help place-and-route succeed. Low-to-medium confidence, but structurally safe enough to try.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decb6c6d7001qR1mZcigwWMjVF","sessionID":"ses_2134abfcaffe4KQES1L5K9Huyy","messageID":"msg_decb540ec001aUxNgJUtbFuyZn"}}
