{"type":"text","timestamp":1777794525001,"sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","part":{"id":"prt_deccfa2aa001qu9q9RbB0forPL","messageID":"msg_deccd53610015nrJ2H6XvnADZj","sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons carefully, I need to find a structural angle that:\n- Avoids known tarpits (fetch-redirect cone, id_ex_t field renames, regfile reset, load-data mux, JAL fast-path rewrites)\n- Isn't \"Yosys already CSE'd it\" territory\n- Doesn't add fan-in to the PC-redirect mux\n\nLet me check past experiments briefly and look at what structural options haven't been tried.","time":{"start":1777794523818,"end":1777794524999}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777794525024,"sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01NcMyNyrRSQKtzMcBDJfsz9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -o '\"title\":\"[^\"]*\"' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | tail -40","description":"List titles of past experiments"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List titles of past experiments","truncated":false},"title":"List titles of past experiments","time":{"start":1777794525007,"end":1777794525022}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the performance data, the zero-storage JAL fast-path in r4s2 delivered the only significant improvement at +17.73%, while most other modifications caused regressions. The current design is pushing up against fabric limits at 94.8% utilization with 9484 LUT4s and 1861 flip-flops, so I need to focus on architectural changes that improve efficiency rather than adding more logic.\n\nI'm considering several structural approaches that haven't been fully explored: registered regfile reads to enable BRAM inference, pipelining the multiplier (though r1s1 suggests this won't help), eliminating redundant fields in the EX/MEM register, or potentially removing the WB stage entirely since it's already combinational. Another angle is moving the decoder into the IF stage with a registered control path, or splitting the divider into a dedicated pipelined unit while keeping the result path clean to avoid the always-on mux overhead that's been hurting other attempts.\n\nNow I'm noticing something in the register structures—the ex_mem_t has both `write_data` and `rs2_val` storing the same post-forward value, and mem_wb_t carries multiple redundant 32-bit fields like `alu_result`, `branch_target`, and `pc_next`. The real issue is that RVFI outputs must be driven at the top level, but on the FPGA bench they likely get tied off during synthesis, so Yosys can't DCE those duplicate fields even though they're only consumed by formal verification.\n\nThe structural ideas I haven't fully explored yet: moving the regfile write to the end of the MEM stage so non-load ALU results are written earlier, which would collapse the forwarding sources from two (ex_mem and mem_wb) down to just one for most operations. Or merging EX and MEM into a single stage to eliminate that register entirely—making it a 4-stage pipeline with simpler forwarding, though the longer critical path might hurt Fmax. The tradeoff is whether reducing forwarding complexity outweighs the potential timing hit.\n\nLooking at the register file storage itself, I notice ex_mem_t stores both write_data and rs2_val, but they're actually the same value—the post-forward rs2 captured at the same clock edge. Removing write_data would save 32 FFs. Similarly, mem_addr and the mask fields in mem_wb_t are derivable from alu_result, so they're only there for RVFI observability. The real win would be eliminating write_data redundancy since mem_stage can just use rs2_val for byte replication instead.\n\nThat's roughly a 1.7% FF reduction on the current 1861-FF fabric with no critical path impact, though it's borderline between structural and micro-optimization. For something more solidly structural, I'm considering moving load sign/zero-extension from MEM into WB stage—pushing the extension logic past the MEM/WB register flop would shorten the pre-flop cone feeding that register. But the extension result feeds the forwarding path through wb_w_data, so adding that combinational logic there could hurt the forwarding mux timing instead.\n\nI'm exploring a few other structural angles: splitting the regfile write so ALU ops bypass MEM entirely (EX→WB) while loads go through MEM→WB, which would halve ALU forwarding latency but introduces WAW hazards. Or I could pre-compute forwarding selects one cycle earlier—instead of computing which source to forward in the ex_stage operand mux combinationally, I'd register the select bits into ID/EX after comparing rs1/rs2 against what's about to be written, moving that comparator cone from the ex-stage critical path into ID's setup time.\n\nThe timing doesn't quite work though—the forwarding decision depends on what lands in EX/MEM next cycle, which is the current id_ex.rd, so checking at ID-time is off by one. Another option is making regfile reads synchronous with registered outputs to help Yosys infer BRAM, but the regfile is only 32×32 bits so that's not practical. Looking back at r4s2's winning pattern—resolving unconditional cases one stage earlier and reusing the redirect net—I could try resolving branches in ID when both operands are already available (not in any pipeline register), since most branches sit at loop ends where the operands were computed cycles ago. An ID-stage branch comparator gated on \"neither rs1 nor rs2 is being written in EX/MEM\" would save one bubble per taken branch, though it adds a comparator with forwarding fan-in and puts another redirect on the PC-mux critical path.\n\nLet me commit to something concrete: removing the redundant write_data field from ex_mem_t and using rs2_val directly in mem_stage instead. The EX stage writes the same value to both write_data and rs2_val, so write_data is pure FF waste—mem_stage can just substitute rs2_val for write_data in the wdata_rep assignment. I should verify rs1_val isn't used in MEM either, but it looks like mem_stage only propagates it downstream to mem_wb for RVFI, so that one has to stay.\n\nThis is a solid structural change with real impact: on a 94.8%-full fabric, cutting 32 FFs reduces routing congestion and improves Fmax. Looking more carefully at ex_mem_t, I can also flatten pc_next since it already encodes the branch decision, and branch_target appears unused by mem_stage—it's not even passed to mem_wb_t. Let me trace through what mem_stage actually consumes to confirm which fields are truly redundant. Verilator flagged unused signals in the mem_stage input bundle, so branch_taken and branch_target are likely dead code that Yosys will eliminate anyway. The real question is what structural changes actually reduce FFs post-synthesis—pipelined multipliers with scoreboards regressed, splitting ID/EX into separate stages adds branch mispredict cost, and the BRAM approach failed on this architecture. I should focus on what r4s2 did right: resolving operations one stage earlier and reusing existing paths.\n\nLooking at candidates like LUI/AUIPC writeback computed in ID, regfile write-port conflict detection, or moving the wb_w_data mux into MEM's combinational output—but r3s1 already regressed on that last one. The most promising angle is a dedicated 2-stage pipelined multiplier that removes the 33×33 signed multiply from the EX critical path entirely, treating MUL results as arriving one cycle late like load-use hazards, without adding handshake logic. This trades a few extra FFs for the multiplier result register against cleaner timing, though it requires new stall detection and forwarding logic in the hazard unit.\n\nThe risk is that r1s1 regressed when we added handshake overhead, and r9s1 (iterative DIV) also regressed by 4.52%, suggesting the multiplier might not actually be the Fmax limiter—the bottleneck could be the EX redirect cone, the ALU case-mux feeding into the EX/MEM flop, or the IF PC-mux for branches. If that's true, pipelining the multiplier won't unlock frequency gains. Another angle worth exploring is moving dmem byte-replication, byte-mask computation, and address alignment into the EX stage as registered values, flattening the MEM-stage pre-flop cone down to just mux selects and registers, though Yosys may have already balanced this.\n\nI could also try pushing the load data shift and sign-extension into the WB stage instead of MEM, storing raw dmem_rdata and addr bits in mem_wb first, but that adds the extension logic to the forwarding path and r6s0 already showed that refactoring the shift becomes a formal verification nightmare. A safer structural bet might be splitting the EX stage register so the forward-visible path (ALU result, write data, rd) sits on a tighter flop with shorter fan-out, or moving the forward_unit computation into the ID stage so forwarding selects are precomputed and registered into ID/EX, shortening the EX operand mux critical path—though the forwarding source values (ex_mem.alu_result, wb_w_data) are one cycle ahead when we compute the selects, which creates a timing dependency I need to think through.\n\nActually, I can make this work by comparing ID's rs1/rs2 against id_ex.rd (which becomes EX/MEM next cycle) and ex_mem.rd (which becomes MEM/WB next cycle), then registering those compare results as fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel into id_ex—this moves the forward comparators from EX's pre-flop cone into ID's pre-flop cone and might balance pipeline depths. But this is a known optimization with real tradeoffs: it adds fanout on id_ex.rd and ex_mem.rd, costs 4 extra FFs in the ID/EX register, reshapes the forward_unit's input graph, and might not actually move the critical path if the comparators weren't the bottleneck to begin with.\n\nLet me just pick something concrete. I could eliminate the redundant ex_mem_t.write_data field to shave 32 FFs, but I'm skeptical Yosys hasn't already dead-code-eliminated it. Instead, I'm going to try adding an explicit IF/ID pipeline register—currently if_id_t is combinational, so the path runs imem BRAM read → decoder → id_ex register all in one cycle. Splitting it with a registered IF/ID stage would create two shorter paths instead of one long one, which could improve Fmax significantly. This adds 65 FFs (32 for instr, 32 for pc, 1 for valid) and costs one extra cycle of branch mispredict penalty, but it's a cleaner structural change than the early forwarding optimization.\n\nActually, wait—Fmax is already 172 MHz versus a 135 MHz target, so we're well above spec. Adding a pipeline stage to improve Fmax when we're already well above target just trades IPC loss for a gain we don't need. That's not going to help fitness. And all my pure FF-reduction ideas are probably already handled by synthesis anyway. I think I need to go with something more ambitious like structural dual-issue support, even though that's risky to implement in one hypothesis. The extra mispredict bubble costs about 7.5% of cycles, so I'd need an Fmax gain above 8% to break even—pushing from 172 MHz to 190+ would do it. But this is a risky structural change, and the pattern that's worked before favors minimal tweaks. I'm torn between the high-upside pipeline split and the safer approach of just removing the redundant write_data field from ex_mem_t to free up some flops on the congested fabric. Actually, splitting ex_mem_t into separate hot and RVFI-only structs might let the synthesizer cluster the critical fields better and ease routing pressure without the complexity of a full pipeline stage split. Though that's speculative too.\n\nLet me settle on something concrete: a pipelined multiplier with pass-through for non-MUL ops, where MUL results are delayed one cycle and dependent instructions stall—but I know r1s1 already tried this and hit neutral. So instead I'll go with the simpler structural fix: drop the unused write_data, branch_target, and branch_taken fields from ex_mem_t and have mem_stage consume rs2_val directly. It's a pure register-layout change with no behavioral risk, though I'm wary that Yosys may have already dead-code-eliminated these fields, making the RTL-level removal a wash or even counterproductive.\n\nActually, let me try something more novel: add a fast write-back path from EX that lets ALU ops (ADD, SUB, logic, shift, MUL) write the regfile directly without waiting for MEM stage, while memory ops stay on the current path. This shortens forwarding depth and gets results into the regfile faster, but it's risky because I'd need to preserve RVFI retirement order, handle dual regfile write ports, and rework the hazard logic—too much complexity and formal risk for one shot.\n\nSo I'm going minimal and structural: move the byte-replication and byte-mask computation from MEM stage up into EX, registering them into ex_mem_t.\n\nThis flattens MEM's combinational cone by precomputing wdata_rep and wmask in EX where alu_result is available anyway. The tradeoff is adding 36 bits to the pipeline register (wdata_rep + wmask) while dropping the 32-bit write_data field, so it's a net +4 bits—worse for area. Alternatively, I could move it down or drop mem_width from the control path, but that doesn't really help. I'm overthinking this and need to just commit to a direction.\n\nActually, the safer bet is simpler: just drop the redundant write_data field entirely since it's identical to rs2_val in EX—both get assigned from the same rs2 wire every cycle. This is a minimal, low-risk structural win that either saves a few FFs if Yosys didn't already optimize it away, or is neutral if it did. Let me verify the assignment and then write this up as the final hypothesis.\n\nBut wait—I'm second-guessing myself because r7s0 hit formal issues when editing id_ex, and removing a field from ex_mem_t might trigger similar problems. Plus, every minor refactor lately (r4s1, r5s1, r8s1, r9s0, r9s2) has regressed due to Yosys already doing the optimization, so the risk-reward here is getting thin.\n\nLet me steer clear of the known problem zones—fetch redirect, forward mux, load-data mux, regfile reset, pipeline struct names—and look for something genuinely untried. Reshuffling mem_wb_t fields or gating the hazard_unit differently won't actually change anything meaningful. I need a real structural angle that's both safe and novel.\n\nMoving the decoder to the IF stage would rebalance the pipeline cones, but it adds complexity with a new if_id_t struct and grows the IF stage. That's too risky. Instead, let me focus on removing the dead fields in ex_mem_t—write_data, branch_taken, branch_target—which account for about 65 FFs or 3.5% of the pipeline register count. Even if Yosys already folded some of this, there's a reasonable chance of a small gain here without touching the known tarpit zones.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deccfa3c0001L0EyRmjbS7AvWu","sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","messageID":"msg_deccd53610015nrJ2H6XvnADZj"}}
