{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777794527635,"sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01GNtmUWK9g7NXmL1grt23yU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"head -3 cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","description":"Check log.jsonl structure"},"output":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-46e45dd\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 301.04, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.21, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9880, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [121.29, 135.21, 136.07], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T04:27:39.271470Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Share single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three independent 64-bit products on every\\ncycle (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and a case-mux selects among them. For\\na 5-stage in-order core whose EX stage is already on the critical path\\n(forward mux -> ALU -> branch resolve -> redirect mux), instantiating\\nthree parallel 32x32 multipliers is pure waste: only one result is\\nselected per instruction, and Yosys/nextpnr on Tang Nano 20K's GW2AR\\neither burns three DSP slots or synthesises three LUT-based multipliers\\nplus a wide final mux. Both outcomes hurt Fmax (one of the two fitness\\nfactors) and the LUT/DSP budget. CoreMark exercises MUL heavily in the\\nmatrix kernel, so any Fmax gain here is a direct fitness gain \\u2014 every\\n1 MHz at the current iter/cycle is ~2.2 CoreMark iter/s.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three independent 64-bit products on every\\ncycle (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and a case-mux selects among them. For\\na 5-stage in-order core whose EX stage is already on the critical path\\n(forward mux -> ALU -> branch resolve -> redirect mux), instantiating\\nthree parallel 32x32 multipliers is pure waste: only one result is\\nselected per instruction, and Yosys/nextpnr on Tang Nano 20K's GW2AR\\neither burns three DSP slots or synthesises three LUT-based multipliers\\nplus a wide final mux. Both outcomes hurt Fmax (one of the two fitness\\nfactors) and the LUT/DSP budget. CoreMark exercises MUL heavily in the\\nmatrix kernel, so any Fmax gain here is a direct fitness gain \\u2014 every\\n1 MHz at the current iter/cycle is ~2.2 CoreMark iter/s.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three separate always-computed multipliers in alu.sv with\\na single 33x33 signed multiplication whose operand sign-extensions are\\nselected by alu_op. The textbook sharing: zero-extend a (to 33b) for\\nMULHU / MULHSU-b, sign-extend a for MUL / MULH / MULHSU-a; zero-extend\\nb for MULHU / MULHSU, sign-extend b for MUL / MULH. The 66-bit product\\nthen supplies MUL = prod[31:0] and MULH/MULHU/MULHSU = prod[63:32].\\nDivision (4 ops) and the ALTOPS ifdef branch are left completely\\nuntouched \\u2014 ALTOPS still substitutes the XOR algebraic forms so formal\\nBMC stays tractable. Correctness is already guarded by test_alu.py's\\n30+ vectors per M-ext op and by the cosim against the Python ISS for\\nevery retired MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU in the CoreMark run; both will\\nfail loudly on any sign-extension bug. The expected Fmax win comes\\nfrom collapsing three multiplier instances + 4:1 mux into one\\nmultiplier + 2:1 high/low mux \\u2014 shorter data-path and less DSP\\npressure. LUT savings are a secondary win that relaxes placement and\\nmay also nudge Fmax upward via easier routing.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su trio with a single 33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign bits are selected from alu_op. MUL reads prod[31:0]; MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read prod[63:32]. Division arms and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch are unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Add targeted MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors (INT_MIN*INT_MIN, INT_MIN*-1, 0xFFFFFFFF*0xFFFFFFFF, mixed-sign products) to catch any sign-extension regression from the multiplier-sharing refactor before cosim does.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su trio with a single 33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign bits are selected from alu_op. MUL reads prod[31:0]; MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read prod[63:32]. Division arms and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch are unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Add targeted MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors (INT_MIN*INT_MIN, INT_MIN*-1, 0xFFFFFFFF*0xFFFFFFFF, mixed-sign products) to catch any sign-extension regression from the multiplier-sharing refactor before cosim does.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 329.56, \"delta_pct\": 9.47, \"vs_baseline\": 9.47, \"fmax_mhz\": 148.02, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9905, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [148.02, 146.48, 151.88], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T04:36:28.396928Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-03 hyp-20260503-001-r1s0 (improvement, +9.47%): Collapsing three always-computed 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier with per-op sign-extend selects shortens the EX critical path and frees DSP/LUT pressure on GW2AR, yielding Fmax-bound CoreMark gains far above the mux-width savings alone would suggest.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Split ALU: move MUL/DIV into multi-cycle execution unit with EX stall handshake\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defines the\\nminimum clock period for the whole core. Baseline Fmax is 135 MHz\\nwith target 135 MHz \\u2014 the core is capped by the EX cycle. CoreMark\\n6 KB executes few MUL and essentially zero DIV per iteration, so\\nremoving those ops from the EX critical path and paying for them in\\nextra cycles only on the rare MUL/DIV instruction is a strongly\\nfavorable structural tradeoff for the fitness metric\\n`iter/cycle \\u00d7 Fmax`.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defines the\\nminimum clock period for the whole core. Baseline Fmax is 135 MHz\\nwith target 135 MHz \\u2014 the core is capped by the EX cycle. CoreMark\\n6 KB executes few MUL and essentially zero DIV per iteration, so\\nremoving those ops from the EX critical path and paying for them in\\nextra cycles only on the rare MUL/DIV instruction is a strongly\\nfavorable structural tradeoff for the fitness metric\\n`iter/cycle \\u00d7 Fmax`.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the EX execute element into two units:\\n\\n  1. A fast single-cycle ALU that only handles the RV32I ops\\n     (ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SLT/SLTU/SLL/SRL/SRA/LUI) plus the\\n     branch comparator. No 32x32 multiplier, no divider \\u2014 the\\n     critical path collapses to an adder + shifter + mux, which\\n     on GW2A should close around 160\\u2013180 MHz.\\n\\n  2. A separate mul_div unit with a `start` / `busy` / `done`\\n     handshake. Multiplier is a 2-cycle pipelined 32x32 (registered\\n     Booth/DSP) producing a 64-bit product. Divider is a 33-cycle\\n     non-restoring iterative divider (one bit per cycle for the\\n     signed 32-bit quotient + fixup). When EX dispatches a MUL/DIV,\\n     the mul_div unit asserts `busy`; `ex_stage` presents a new\\n     `stall_mul_div` that feeds the existing hazard_unit to freeze\\n     IF, ID/EX, and to inject MEM/WB bubbles until the result is\\n     ready. The result is then forwarded from the mul_div output\\n     through the normal EX\\u2192MEM path, so RVFI retirement and the\\n     forwarding network stay textbook.\\n\\nCritical-path consequence: the EX cycle's combinational work drops\\nto (2:1 operand fwd mux) -> (adder | shifter | logic | slt) ->\\nEX/MEM flop. That is the same critical path as a classic RV32I\\nsingle-issue 5-stage, whose textbook synthesis on GW2A sits well\\nabove 150 MHz. Target: Fmax >=155 MHz (+15%).\\n\\nCoreMark IPC cost: for ITERATIONS=10 the CoreMark kernel issues on\\nthe order of a few hundred multiplies (matrix kernel) and no divides\\nat all. A 2-cycle pipelined MUL costs 1 extra stall cycle vs. the\\ncurrent 0-cycle path; over ~4.49M cycles this is well under 0.1%\\nIPC loss. Net fitness: ~(1.15 * 0.999) = +14%.\\n\\nCorrectness: unchanged. The decoder still emits ALU_MUL..ALU_REMU\\nas 5-bit op codes; the ex_stage routes those to the mul_div unit\\nrather than the fast ALU; the ALTOPS substitution path stays in the\\nmul_div unit under the same `ifdef` so riscv-formal's per-iteration\\nBMC pass keeps its XOR-of-add shortcut (solver stays tractable),\\nwhile the real hardware path is exercised by `test_alu.py` and the\\ncosim diff against reference.py for every retired MUL/DIV/REM.\\nhazard_unit already owns the stall infrastructure (dmem_stall is\\nthe same shape); mul_div stall slots into the same OR tree.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU/DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational ALU. On those opcodes drive `out = 32'b0`; the ex_stage will source the real result from the new mul_div unit. Keep ALTOPS cases as-is for the formal path so riscv-formal's BMC solver still sees XOR-of-adds.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mul_div.sv\", \"description\": \"NEW module: 2-cycle pipelined 32x32 multiplier (produces 64-bit product, selects low/high per MULH*/MUL) plus 33-cycle iterative non-restoring divider with RV32M sign/zero/div-by-zero/INT_MIN-overflow fixup. Ports: clock, reset, start, op[4:0], a[31:0], b[31:0], busy, done, result[31:0]. Under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the unit becomes single-cycle with the XOR-of-add substitution mirrored from alu.sv so formal still closes.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate mul_div alongside alu. Detect MUL/DIV class opcodes (alu_op >= ALU_MUL). On first cycle: pulse `mul_div.start`, assert new output `stall_mul_div` until `done`. Final result mux between alu_result and mul_div.result drives EX/MEM.alu_result. Preserve forwarding \\u2014 mul_div.result feeds fwd_ex_mem once the op has landed in EX/MEM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add input `mul_div_busy`. OR it into stall_if / stall_id (freeze IF and hold ID/EX register) and clear flush_id while busy (don't insert a load-use-style bubble). stall_ex_mem stays 0 (EX/MEM captures on `done`). hold_mem_wb asserts while busy so the prior retirement's MEM/WB forwarding payload stays alive.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_stage's `stall_mul_div` into hazard_unit's new `mul_div_busy` input. No change to IO or RVFI ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update the ALU cocotb harness: MUL/DIV vectors now test the new `mul_div` DUT separately (2-cycle MUL latency, 33-cycle DIV latency). Add a stall-handshake test that verifies `busy` stays high for the entire operation and `done` pulses exactly once. Keep coverage for all 8 M-ext ops with the existing 30+ vectors each.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a test that inserts a MUL followed by a dependent ADD and verifies IF/ID are frozen for the expected 2 cycles, then ADD retires with the correct rd_wdata. Add a DIV-by-zero + DIV by -1 of INT_MIN + generic signed DIV trio and verify rvfi_rd_wdata matches RV32M semantics field-by-field.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU/DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational ALU. On those opcodes drive `out = 32'b0`; the ex_stage will source the real result from the new mul_div unit. Keep ALTOPS cases as-is for the formal path so riscv-formal's BMC solver still sees XOR-of-adds.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mul_div.sv\", \"description\": \"NEW module: 2-cycle pipelined 32x32 multiplier (produces 64-bit product, selects low/high per MULH*/MUL) plus 33-cycle iterative non-restoring divider with RV32M sign/zero/div-by-zero/INT_MIN-overflow fixup. Ports: clock, reset, start, op[4:0], a[31:0], b[31:0], busy, done, result[31:0]. Under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the unit becomes single-cycle with the XOR-of-add substitution mirrored from alu.sv so formal still closes.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate mul_div alongside alu. Detect MUL/DIV class opcodes (alu_op >= ALU_MUL). On first cycle: pulse `mul_div.start`, assert new output `stall_mul_div` until `done`. Final result mux between alu_result and mul_div.result drives EX/MEM.alu_result. Preserve forwarding \\u2014 mul_div.result feeds fwd_ex_mem once the op has landed in EX/MEM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add input `mul_div_busy`. OR it into stall_if / stall_id (freeze IF and hold ID/EX register) and clear flush_id while busy (don't insert a load-use-style bubble). stall_ex_mem stays 0 (EX/MEM captures on `done`). hold_mem_wb asserts while busy so the prior retirement's MEM/WB forwarding payload stays alive.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_stage's `stall_mul_div` into hazard_unit's new `mul_div_busy` input. No change to IO or RVFI ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update the ALU cocotb harness: MUL/DIV vectors now test the new `mul_div` DUT separately (2-cycle MUL latency, 33-cycle DIV latency). Add a stall-handshake test that verifies `busy` stays high for the entire operation and `done` pulses exactly once. Keep coverage for all 8 M-ext ops with the existing 30+ vectors each.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a test that inserts a MUL followed by a dependent ADD and verifies IF/ID are frozen for the expected 2 cycles, then ADD retires with the correct rd_wdata. Add a DIV-by-zero + DIV by -1 of INT_MIN + generic signed DIV trio and verify rvfi_rd_wdata matches RV32M semantics field-by-field.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 301.04, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.21, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9880, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [121.29, 135.21, 136.07], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T04:42:59.919457Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-03 hyp-20260503-002-r1s1 (regression, +0.00%): Once the shared 33x33 multiplier already sits off the EX forward-mux critical path, moving MUL/DIV into a multi-cycle handshake unit adds stall logic in hazard_unit and a new busy/done path without freeing Fmax, so CoreMark's matrix-kernel MUL density turns the extra stall cycles into a net IPC loss \\u2014 pipelining MUL/DIV only pays when the combinational multiplier is provably the critical path, otherwise measure first.\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-46e45dd\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 301.04, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.21, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9880, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [121.29, 135.21, 136.07], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T04:27:39.271470Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Share single 33x33 signed multiplier across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three independent 64-bit products on every\\ncycle (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and a case-mux selects among them. For\\na 5-stage in-order core whose EX stage is already on the critical path\\n(forward mux -> ALU -> branch resolve -> redirect mux), instantiating\\nthree parallel 32x32 multipliers is pure waste: only one result is\\nselected per instruction, and Yosys/nextpnr on Tang Nano 20K's GW2AR\\neither burns three DSP slots or synthesises three LUT-based multipliers\\nplus a wide final mux. Both outcomes hurt Fmax (one of the two fitness\\nfactors) and the LUT/DSP budget. CoreMark exercises MUL heavily in the\\nmatrix kernel, so any Fmax gain here is a direct fitness gain \\u2014 every\\n1 MHz at the current iter/cycle is ~2.2 CoreMark iter/s.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three independent 64-bit products on every\\ncycle (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and a case-mux selects among them. For\\na 5-stage in-order core whose EX stage is already on the critical path\\n(forward mux -> ALU -> branch resolve -> redirect mux), instantiating\\nthree parallel 32x32 multipliers is pure waste: only one result is\\nselected per instruction, and Yosys/nextpnr on Tang Nano 20K's GW2AR\\neither burns three DSP slots or synthesises three LUT-based multipliers\\nplus a wide final mux. Both outcomes hurt Fmax (one of the two fitness\\nfactors) and the LUT/DSP budget. CoreMark exercises MUL heavily in the\\nmatrix kernel, so any Fmax gain here is a direct fitness gain \\u2014 every\\n1 MHz at the current iter/cycle is ~2.2 CoreMark iter/s.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three separate always-computed multipliers in alu.sv with\\na single 33x33 signed multiplication whose operand sign-extensions are\\nselected by alu_op. The textbook sharing: zero-extend a (to 33b) for\\nMULHU / MULHSU-b, sign-extend a for MUL / MULH / MULHSU-a; zero-extend\\nb for MULHU / MULHSU, sign-extend b for MUL / MULH. The 66-bit product\\nthen supplies MUL = prod[31:0] and MULH/MULHU/MULHSU = prod[63:32].\\nDivision (4 ops) and the ALTOPS ifdef branch are left completely\\nuntouched \\u2014 ALTOPS still substitutes the XOR algebraic forms so formal\\nBMC stays tractable. Correctness is already guarded by test_alu.py's\\n30+ vectors per M-ext op and by the cosim against the Python ISS for\\nevery retired MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU in the CoreMark run; both will\\nfail loudly on any sign-extension bug. The expected Fmax win comes\\nfrom collapsing three multiplier instances + 4:1 mux into one\\nmultiplier + 2:1 high/low mux \\u2014 shorter data-path and less DSP\\npressure. LUT savings are a secondary win that relaxes placement and\\nmay also nudge Fmax upward via easier routing.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su trio with a single 33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign bits are selected from alu_op. MUL reads prod[31:0]; MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read prod[63:32]. Division arms and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch are unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Add targeted MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors (INT_MIN*INT_MIN, INT_MIN*-1, 0xFFFFFFFF*0xFFFFFFFF, mixed-sign products) to catch any sign-extension regression from the multiplier-sharing refactor before cosim does.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace mul_ss/mul_uu/mul_su trio with a single 33x33 signed multiplier whose operand sign bits are selected from alu_op. MUL reads prod[31:0]; MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read prod[63:32]. Division arms and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch are unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Add targeted MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors (INT_MIN*INT_MIN, INT_MIN*-1, 0xFFFFFFFF*0xFFFFFFFF, mixed-sign products) to catch any sign-extension regression from the multiplier-sharing refactor before cosim does.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 329.56, \"delta_pct\": 9.47, \"vs_baseline\": 9.47, \"fmax_mhz\": 148.02, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9905, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [148.02, 146.48, 151.88], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T04:36:28.396928Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-03 hyp-20260503-001-r1s0 (improvement, +9.47%): Collapsing three always-computed 32x32 multipliers into one shared 33x33 signed multiplier with per-op sign-extend selects shortens the EX critical path and frees DSP/LUT pressure on GW2AR, yielding Fmax-bound CoreMark gains far above the mux-width savings alone would suggest.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Split ALU: move MUL/DIV into multi-cycle execution unit with EX stall handshake\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defines the\\nminimum clock period for the whole core. Baseline Fmax is 135 MHz\\nwith target 135 MHz \\u2014 the core is capped by the EX cycle. CoreMark\\n6 KB executes few MUL and essentially zero DIV per iteration, so\\nremoving those ops from the EX critical path and paying for them in\\nextra cycles only on the rare MUL/DIV instruction is a strongly\\nfavorable structural tradeoff for the fitness metric\\n`iter/cycle \\u00d7 Fmax`.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defines the\\nminimum clock period for the whole core. Baseline Fmax is 135 MHz\\nwith target 135 MHz \\u2014 the core is capped by the EX cycle. CoreMark\\n6 KB executes few MUL and essentially zero DIV per iteration, so\\nremoving those ops from the EX critical path and paying for them in\\nextra cycles only on the rare MUL/DIV instruction is a strongly\\nfavorable structural tradeoff for the fitness metric\\n`iter/cycle \\u00d7 Fmax`.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the EX execute element into two units:\\n\\n  1. A fast single-cycle ALU that only handles the RV32I ops\\n     (ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SLT/SLTU/SLL/SRL/SRA/LUI) plus the\\n     branch comparator. No 32x32 multiplier, no divider \\u2014 the\\n     critical path collapses to an adder + shifter + mux, which\\n     on GW2A should close around 160\\u2013180 MHz.\\n\\n  2. A separate mul_div unit with a `start` / `busy` / `done`\\n     handshake. Multiplier is a 2-cycle pipelined 32x32 (registered\\n     Booth/DSP) producing a 64-bit product. Divider is a 33-cycle\\n     non-restoring iterative divider (one bit per cycle for the\\n     signed 32-bit quotient + fixup). When EX dispatches a MUL/DIV,\\n     the mul_div unit asserts `busy`; `ex_stage` presents a new\\n     `stall_mul_div` that feeds the existing hazard_unit to freeze\\n     IF, ID/EX, and to inject MEM/WB bubbles until the result is\\n     ready. The result is then forwarded from the mul_div output\\n     through the normal EX\\u2192MEM path, so RVFI retirement and the\\n     forwarding network stay textbook.\\n\\nCritical-path consequence: the EX cycle