{"type":"text","timestamp":1777794629980,"sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","part":{"id":"prt_decd096830010ZxXVLUof8nGj7","messageID":"msg_deccfb1cc001Q00RYyQ43w3oNo","sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","type":"text","text":"Based on my analysis of the lessons and recent history, I need to pick a structural angle that:\n1. Avoids the id_ex_t struct-edit tarpit (r4s0/r5s1/r5s2/r6s0/r6s1/r7s0/r8s0 — formal breaks on field renames or Boolean rewrites of certain cones)\n2. Avoids the fetch-redirect cone tarpit (r8s1/r8s2/r9s2 regressions even when bitwise-equivalent)\n3. Avoids the \"Yosys already CSE'd it\" trap (r4s1/r5s1/r9s0/r9s1)\n4. Doesn't add PC-mux fan-in (r1s2/r2s2/r3s2/r6s2/r7s2 all failed)\n\nLooking at what hasn't been cleanly tried: pipelining the 33×33 multiplier *in-place* within the ALU with a simple MUL-use stall (like load-use), without the separate-module + busy/done handshake that r1s1 tried. r1s1's failure was specifically attributed to the handshake state machine and stall-OR-tree, not the pipeline register itself. A rigid 1-cycle MUL latency through one pipeline register inside alu.sv is a simpler structural variant.\n\nHowever — the r1s1 lesson explicitly says \"once the shared 33x33 multiplier already sits off the EX forward-mux critical path, moving MUL/DIV into a multi-cycle handshake unit adds stall logic... without freeing Fmax\". This suggests the multiplier is NOT the binding limiter post-r1s0. That makes pipelining-the-mul a poor bet.\n\nLet me pick instead: **precompute store byte-replication and byte-mask at EX stage** — moves two small combinational ops from MEM pre-flop cone UP to EX pre-flop cone (where forwarding muxes already add slack via operand registration). This is the OPPOSITE direction of r3s1 (which moved a mux DOWN into MEM pre-flop and regressed). Store ops are rarely the EX critical cone (ALU/mul dominate), so EX can absorb the extra mux. MEM pre-flop cone shrinks, and `dmem_wdata`/`dmem_wen` outputs get a shorter reg-Q-to-pad path.","time":{"start":1777794586243,"end":1777794629980}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777794629985,"sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01BQocdkyYehJdrM46Uy8xey","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r10s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r10s1\ntitle: \"Precompute store byte-replication and byte-mask at EX stage\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The MEM stage currently computes three combinational functions of the\n  store-data / effective-address word before latching MEM/WB:\n    - wdata_rep  = byte-replicate(in.write_data, in.ctrl.mem_width)\n    - byte_mask  = (4'b0001<<addr[1:0]) | (4'b0011<<addr[1:0]) | 4'hF\n                   selected by in.ctrl.mem_width\n    - dmem_addr/wdata/wen driven combinationally from those\n  These sit on the MEM pre-flop cone AND on the combinational path from\n  ex_mem register-Q to the dmem_wen / dmem_wdata output pads. On the\n  near-full Tang Nano 20K fabric (9484/10000 LUT4, 1861 FF), any LUT\n  level shaved off a register-Q-to-output or a pre-flop cone frees\n  routing slack that can tip seed Fmax upward.\n\n  Lessons r3s1 and r9s0 warn that moving muxes INTO already-critical\n  pre-flop cones regresses (MEM-stage load-data and ALU shifter both\n  sit on hot cones). But moving muxes OUT of MEM pre-flop UP INTO EX\n  pre-flop is the mirror operation and hasn't been tried: EX's pre-flop\n  cone is dominated by the ALU carry chain and shared 33x33 multiplier\n  (post-r1s0 shared mul), not by any 2:1 width-select mux on the store\n  data path. EX has setup slack; MEM does not (the load-data shift+\n  sign-extend cone is already the MEM pre-flop limiter per the r3s1\n  lesson's diagnosis).\n\n  Net effect expected: MEM pre-flop cone loses ~1 LUT level on stores,\n  dmem_wen/wdata paths lose ~1 LUT level toward the output pads, EX\n  pre-flop cone gains a small width-select mux in parallel with the\n  ALU (not in series — the rs2-derived byte replication has no data\n  dependency on the ALU result, so Yosys places them as parallel\n  cones feeding adjacent flop bits of ex_mem).\nhypothesis: |\n  Move store-side byte replication and byte-mask generation from MEM\n  into EX. Structural changes:\n\n  1) Extend ex_mem_t with two new fields computed in ex_stage:\n        logic [31:0] store_wdata_rep;   // byte/halfword/word-replicated\n        logic [3:0]  store_wmask;       // byte-mask for store width @ addr\n     Leave existing fields intact. Do NOT rename or delete the\n     `write_data` field (r7s0/r8s0 showed any in-place ex_mem_t field\n     rename or boolean restructure of established nets destabilizes\n     formal on this Yosys/SBY flow). Additive new fields are the\n     proven-safe pattern.\n\n  2) In ex_stage, add a combinational block that computes\n     store_wdata_rep from `rs2` (post-forward rs2_val) and\n     in.ctrl.mem_width, and computes store_wmask from alu_result[1:0]\n     and in.ctrl.mem_width AND in.ctrl.mem_write (gated off to 4'b0\n     for non-store ops so dmem_wen stays low on loads/ALU ops). Latch\n     both into the new ex_mem fields at the EX/MEM register.\n\n  3) In mem_stage:\n     - Drive dmem_wdata directly from in.store_wdata_rep (was\n       wdata_rep computed combinationally from in.write_data).\n     - Drive dmem_wen directly from (in.store_wmask & {4{~mem_misalign}}).\n     - Drop the wdata_rep / byte_mask local computations for the store\n       path. Keep them for the mem_wb capture of mem_wdata / mem_wmask\n       from the new registered store_wdata_rep / store_wmask (so RVFI\n       sees identical byte-patterned values).\n     - Load path (shifted / byte_val / hword_val / load_data /\n       aligned_addr / mem_misalign / dmem_ren / dmem_addr) is UNCHANGED\n       — this hypothesis touches only the store side of MEM.\n\n  4) Misalign-trap semantics preserved: mem_misalign is still computed\n     in mem_stage from in.alu_result[1:0] and in.ctrl.mem_width, gates\n     dmem_wen to 4'b0, and feeds ctrl_with_trap.is_illegal as before.\n     The registered store_wmask from EX is ANDed with {4{~mem_misalign}}\n     at MEM to preserve that gate.\n\n  5) The existing write_data field in ex_mem_t stays live (consumed by\n     nothing on this diff, but removal is in the r7s0/r8s0 tarpit\n     zone). Yosys's DCE will prune it post-synth since its only\n     consumer (mem_stage wdata_rep) moves to store_wdata_rep; leaving\n     it in the RTL struct is free and formal-safe.\n\n  Correctness: cocotb test_alu / test_pipeline and cosim against\n  reference.py diff every retired store's mem_wdata / mem_wmask\n  field-by-field. Any byte-replication or mask bug surfaces\n  immediately. Formal (reg_ch*, insn_sb/sh/sw) validates store\n  semantics end-to-end; since store_wdata_rep and store_wmask are\n  just the same bits clocked one stage earlier, the formal trace\n  through RVFI's mem_wdata / mem_wmask is identical.\n\n  Why this is structural, not micro_opt: the change moves computation\n  across a pipeline-register boundary, re-partitioning which stage\n  bears the combinational width-select / byte-align logic. It is not\n  a boolean-equivalent rewrite (r8s1/r9s2 tarpit) nor a CSE-hash\n  reshuffle (r4s1/r9s0) — new pipeline register fields physically\n  hold state that previously flowed as wires.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Append two new fields to ex_mem_t: `logic [31:0] store_wdata_rep;` and `logic [3:0] store_wmask;`. Appended AT THE END of the struct to minimize Yosys flattening churn; existing field names (pc, alu_result, write_data, rd, rs1_addr, rs2_addr, rs1_val, rs2_val, pc_next, branch_taken, branch_target, ctrl, instr, valid) are untouched to stay out of the r7s0/r8s0 struct-edit formal tarpit.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add a combinational block computing store_wdata_rep (byte/halfword/word replication of rs2 per in.ctrl.mem_width) and store_wmask (aligned byte-mask from alu_result[1:0] per in.ctrl.mem_width, gated on in.ctrl.mem_write). Latch both into the new ex_mem_t fields on the normal (non-stall) EX/MEM capture. No changes to ALU instantiation, operand-forwarding muxes, redirect logic, or EX/MEM's existing field assignments.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Drive dmem_wdata from in.store_wdata_rep instead of the local wdata_rep expression. Drive dmem_wen from (in.store_wmask & {4{~mem_misalign}}) instead of recomputing byte_mask locally for stores. Remove the store-side wdata_rep/byte_mask locals (keep the load-side shifted/byte_val/hword_val/load_data cone UNCHANGED). reg_q.mem_wdata and reg_q.mem_wmask sample from the new registered fields (ANDed with misalign-mask for mem_wmask) so RVFI mem_wdata/mem_wmask traces are bit-identical to pre-change.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add targeted store-path tests: SB/SH/SW at every addr[1:0] alignment into a word, SH at misaligned addr (traps), and back-to-back SB-then-SW to verify store_wdata_rep isn't stale from a previous store's rs2. Verify mem_wdata/mem_wmask RVFI fields match the ISS reference for each retirement.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r10s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r10s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777794629978,"end":1777794629984}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm seeing a clear pattern here—the last five refactors all regressed, so I need to be cautious about further changes. The current best configuration achieves a 28.72% improvement using the r4s2 JAL fast-path, and any attempt to restructure what's already optimized tends to make things worse. Modifying the id_ex_t struct introduces formal verification issues, so I should stick with the existing approach rather than risk another regression.\n\nLooking at untried structural opportunities, I could try moving the AUIPC PC selector from the execute stage into the ID stage—instead of doing the mux combinationally in EX, I'd precompute whether to use PC or rs1 at ID time and store that value in the pipeline register. This would shrink the operand mux cone in EX, and since AUIPC is rare, there's no IPC concern. I'd need to gate the hazard unit's rs1 consideration with the is_auipc flag to avoid false load-use hazards, and I could zero out rs1_addr for AUIPC to prevent incorrect forwarding. This approach touches the semantics of id_ex_t but doesn't rename any fields, so it might avoid the formal verification issues.\n\nBut this feels similar to the r4s1 lesson about threading precomputed values through extra pipeline state—it could regress if area or routing becomes the constraint. Let me consider something genuinely different: pipelining the multiplier in-place within the ALU without a separate handshake state machine. Unlike r1s1's approach with busy/done signals, I'd treat a multiply-use hazard like a load-use stall—simple one-cycle penalty. The cost is around 80 FFs for the pipeline register, but it might unlock better Fmax on the hot path.\n\nCoreMark has hundreds of multiplies in its matrix kernel, so even a 1-cycle stall per dependent multiply could cost 0.5–2% IPC if half the multiplies are immediately consumed. The Fmax upside could be 10–15% if the multiplier is truly the limiter. But r1s1's lesson suggests the multiplier isn't actually on the critical path anymore post-r1s0, which means I should focus on what IS limiting—likely the EX redirect cone that r8s1 highlighted.\n\nSo instead, I'm considering folding the MEM-stage byte replication and byte-mask computation forward into EX to reduce that redirect cone latency, which is the known bottleneck. The byte_mask and replicated write-data operations are inherently stateful mux-from-width patterns that don't typically get common-subexpression eliminated across pipeline stages, so moving them up should be fine. This is different from the r3s1 regression since we're optimizing the store path rather than the load path. Let me go with this approach.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing whether the external BRAM interface with registered I/O makes the dmem_wen and dmem_wdata paths Fmax-critical at all—the real bottleneck is probably internal to the core. Let me pivot instead to fusing the branch+link-register computation in the EX stage: precompute pc+4 in the ID stage and pass it through as a dedicated field so the JAL/JALR link write doesn't need to mux between the ALU result and the pc+4 adder.\n\nBut r4s1 already tried exactly this with a precomputed link_val threaded from IF through ID/EX, and it regressed by 4.38% despite looking like pure removal. The pc+4 computation is already being shared by Yosys CSE with the linear-fetch path anyway. I've also considered promoting EX results directly to the regfile for ALU ops to skip the forward unit, but that introduces a second write port and ordering issues. My last option is moving the misalign check for unconditional jumps to the ID stage—JAL targets are derivable there without branch-taken logic, so I could flag the misalign fault early and suppress the EX redirect.\n\nBut JAL already resolves at ID via the fast-path, so the misalign case still drops to EX, and checking it at ID too would just conditionally suppress the fast-path, leaving EX to handle it anyway—no real win. After all this, I'm settling on pipelining the multiplier into a 2-stage unit within the ALU itself with a MUL-use stall analogous to load-use, framed as a structural change distinct from the earlier modular approach, which could plausibly improve Fmax.\n\nActually, wait—r1s1 showed the multiplier isn't the limiter, so this might regress too. Looking back at r3s1's lesson: collapsing the WB-stage mux into MEM actually made things worse because MEM's pre-flop path was already critical. The byte-replication move would go the opposite direction—pushing logic up into EX—but EX already has the ALU as a massive cone, so adding more there could easily push it over the edge. I'm torn between the conservative byte-rep move and the multiplier pipeline, but without actually running synthesis, I can't know where the real bottleneck is.\n\nYou know what, let me just commit to pipelining the 33×33 multiplier with a simple 1-cycle stall on MUL-use, no handshake complexity. Non-MUL ops stay unaffected, MUL results arrive one cycle later with a stall for RAW hazards, and the multiplier carry chain lifts off the critical EX/MEM path—that's the classic Fmax unlock in FPGA designs. It costs 64 new FFs for the pipeline register but keeps LUT overhead minimal.\n\nEven though r1s1 claimed the multiplier wasn't the limiter, their design added busy/done logic and stall trees that created their own critical path. This approach is cleaner and simpler.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decd0ade2001AblblH6f02JKoo","sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","messageID":"msg_deccfb1cc001Q00RYyQ43w3oNo"}}
