{"type":"text","timestamp":1777794637341,"sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","part":{"id":"prt_decd147b40014WTm9TcJLRk4M3","messageID":"msg_decd14197001ZUOpYI0M38gRH8","sessionID":"ses_21332ad4dffeXdWVjP6a45RONf","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r10s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Structural move of store-side byte-replication and byte-mask generation from MEM stage (pre-flop) up to EX stage (pre-flop). Mirror of the r3s1 regression direction — r3s1 moved a mux DOWN into the already-critical MEM pre-flop load-data cone and lost; this moves store muxes UP into EX's slack area, parallel to the ALU carry chain (no data dependency — byte replication uses rs2 directly, byte mask uses alu_result[1:0] only).\n\nAdditive-field design (new `store_wdata_rep`/`store_wmask` in ex_mem_t, leaving `write_data` in place for Yosys DCE) specifically avoids the r7s0/r8s0 struct-edit formal tarpit. Load path untouched to avoid the r6s0 byte-lane formal tarpit. No touch to the fetch-redirect cone (r8s1/r8s2/r9s2 tarpit) or JAL fast-path (r9s2 tarpit). No PC-mux fan-in growth (r1s2/r2s2/r3s2/r6s2/r7s2 predictor tarpits).\n\nExpected: +3%, low confidence — depends on whether MEM pre-flop or dmem_wen/wdata output path is currently a binding routing constraint on the 94.8%-full fabric.","time":{"start":1777794631604,"end":1777794637339}}}
