{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777796225999,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"id":"prt_dece99bca001e7yaUW1Pw3dbk7","messageID":"msg_dece9897f001QSISPJGeSUJc10","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","snapshot":"8e4779b470b1d8e60d9ff8632ea85264e2cefa38","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796544023,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01CkSqtT8rvNqE7PMNDmjGmH","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -i \"mem.wb.forward|early.write|write.first|regfile.write\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -20","description":"Search prior hypotheses for MEM/WB forwarding topics"},"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","metadata":{"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","exit":0,"description":"Search prior hypotheses for MEM/WB forwarding topics","truncated":false},"title":"Search prior hypotheses for MEM/WB forwarding topics","time":{"start":1777796544020,"end":1777796544022}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what worked and what didn't from previous optimization attempts—the JAL fast-path was clearly the biggest win, but most predictor changes and micro-optimizations on the fetch-redirect path didn't pan out, and I keep running into issues with the id_ex_t structure. Now I need to think about a different structural approach to push the CoreMark performance beyond the current 387.98.\n\nThe recent attempts all regressed, so I'm looking at genuine pipeline topology changes rather than incremental tweaks. Dual-issue execution is a natural candidate since the NRET=2 contract is already there to support it, and I could explore register file write forwarding simplification or restructuring how the MEM stage fits into the pipeline. The current single-issue setup is hitting around 1 IPC with stalls on a 5-stage pipeline, and while Fmax is well above the 135 MHz target at 172.35 MHz, there's still room to improve throughput. The real bottleneck seems to be in the EX stage—it's packed with the forwarding mux, ALU operand selection, the ALU itself, branch logic, and misalignment checks all compressed into one cycle, so I should look at whether I can decompose or pipeline some of that work.\n\nI'm considering several structural approaches: splitting EX into separate ALU and branch resolution stages would help but adds branch penalty cycles; moving regfile reads earlier or adding an IF/ID flop to decouple instruction fetch from decode could relieve pressure but again introduces branch mispredict overhead; or I could try a forwarding path from WB back to ID to eliminate the write-first bypass requirement in the register file itself.\n\nThe more promising direction is collapsing the pipeline from 5 stages down to 4 by merging EX and WB — since the data memory is combinational, I could compute the load address, fetch data, and write the result all in one cycle. This would dramatically reduce branch mispredict bubbles and eliminate load-use stalls, though it means cramming a lot of logic (ALU, memory addressing, data shifting/extension, and regfile write) into a single stage, which would hurt clock frequency.\n\nLooking at what's been attempted in the structural category, most attempts have focused on branch prediction — static BP, BTB, RAS, JAL fast-paths, backward-branch predictors, and various RAS tweaks — and they've all regressed except for the JAL fast-path. Since predictors keep failing, I should explore non-predictor structural changes instead.\n\nThe key insight is that fusing EX and MEM into a single stage would let LOAD results feed directly to the next instruction via forwarding without any stall, eliminating the hazard unit's load-use logic entirely. The tradeoff is that the combined EX/MEM critical path becomes very tight.\n\nThe real bottleneck is that when a LOAD's data comes back from memory, the dependent instruction is still in ID, so we need a 1-cycle stall to get it into EX where it can use the forwarded value. I'm exploring whether there's a way to bypass this — maybe by having the regfile write happen earlier in the cycle so dependent instructions in ID can read the new value immediately, or by splitting the multiplier path to reduce critical path pressure elsewhere.\n\nLooking at the ALU implementation, the 33x33 multiplier is always computing its result even for non-multiply operations, which wastes power and potentially impacts timing. I'm considering pipelining just the multiplier — compute it in EX, capture the result in the EX/MEM register, and treat MUL as a 2-cycle operation like LOAD. This would remove the 66-bit multiply result from the ALU's case mux, which is currently one of the deepest combinational cones. The hazard unit would then stall for 1 cycle on MUL-dependent instructions, similar to load-use stalls.\n\nBut r2s1 already tried multi-cycle MUL/DIV and regressed, so this structural change alone won't help. I'm now considering a more radical approach: dual-issue superscalar execution with NRET=2, where two independent instructions can retire per cycle. This would dramatically improve IPC, though it would likely hurt Fmax and explode area and complexity.\n\nEven a restricted dual-issue—like issuing a memory or ALU op in slot 0 and an ALU-only op with no dependency on slot 1—would be a major architectural pivot, but I'm already at 9484 of 10k LUTs, so there's barely any room. I'm also considering pipelining the divider separately or splitting the memory stage, but the real constraint is that EX's pre-flop cone is what's binding Fmax, so I should focus on shortening that path—maybe by moving branch resolution to the ID stage with a dedicated comparator.\n\nThe catch is that branches need rs1/rs2 values which come from forwarding in EX/MEM, so I'd need forwarding at ID to make that work. I could precompute pc_next in the ID/EX register for non-branches and known-not-taken branches, but EX still has to resolve the actual condition anyway. Another angle is moving the misalign check for branch/jump targets to MEM, but looking at the code, the misalign_fault for redirects is already computed in EX based on whether the target's low 2 bits are nonzero—and since instructions are 4-byte aligned, that's the only misalignment case that matters.\n\nActually, B-type immediates have a hardcoded 0 LSB, and PC is always 4-aligned, so branch_target[1] depends on whether imm[1] (which comes from instr[8]) is set. Same with J-type immediates where bit [1] comes from instr[21]. So misalign faults can fire when targeting 2-byte-aligned-but-not-4-byte-aligned addresses. The problem is that gating the redirect signal with misalign_fault puts it on the critical path, which hurts timing. I'm thinking about removing the misalign check from the redirect signal entirely and instead converting the trap to NOP-like behavior downstream at MEM, letting the redirect happen without the fault blocking it.\n\nBut that's risky—redirecting to a misaligned PC would break the 4-byte alignment invariant that the imem bus expects. I could force redirect_target[1:0] to 2'b00 and still trap, but that feels like it's skirting the formal verification requirements around architectural traps. Given the lessons learned about destabilizing formal proofs with structural changes, this approach is too dangerous.\n\nLooking at this more systematically, I'm considering a dual-issue ALU-only approach where two ALU instructions can execute simultaneously if there's no dependency—that would be genuinely structural and give a real IPC boost. The downside is area impact, and we're already at 9484/10000 LUT4s, so fitting this is risky. Another angle is combinational writeback to the register file, which would eliminate the M-stage latency.\n\nActually, the WB stage is just a mux selecting between memory data and ALU results before writing to the regfile. If I collapse it and write directly from MEM, the regfile still captures synchronously on the clock edge, so it's effectively the same timing as having that combinational stage between the MEM/WB flop and the regfile. The real question is whether removing that register stage actually saves anything or just shifts the problem.\n\nI've been exploring structural changes but keep hitting diminishing returns. The r4s2 JAL fast-path worked because it resolved one stage earlier with minimal overhead—just a redirect mux and a flag bit. Let me look for similar opportunities: AUIPC and LUI could compute their results in ID since they don't depend on rs1, but that means modifying id_ex which is already a pain point. Another angle is whether I actually need the MEM/WB forwarding path at all if the regfile already has write-first bypass semantics.\n\nLooking at the regfile implementation, write-first bypass is there—if an instruction in WB writes to rd on cycle N and another instruction in ID reads that same register on cycle N, the bypass mux gives it the new value combinationally. So instruction Y in ID gets the correct rs1 value even though X is still in WB. That means Y's id_ex.rs1_val should already capture the right data, which would eliminate the need for MEM/WB forwarding entirely.\n\nThe real gap MEM/WB forwarding addresses is when instruction Z enters EX on the same cycle X reaches WB—Z was in ID one cycle earlier when X was still in MEM, so Z's regfile read missed X's value and needs it forwarded into the EX stage operand. The question is whether there's a way to restructure the pipeline to avoid needing that forwarding path. So MEM/WB forwarding is definitely necessary—without it, instructions two cycles behind miss their operands since the regfile hasn't been updated yet. I'm exploring a few optimization angles: moving decode earlier in the pipeline, adding a small instruction cache to hide fetch stalls, or narrowing the MEM/WB forward path to only handle loads instead of all writeback data. The last idea is interesting because EX/MEM already covers ALU results within one cycle, so maybe MEM/WB could be specialized.\n\nI'm also considering whether I can shrink the EX/MEM register itself by computing some fields inline rather than storing them—things like rs1_val that are only needed for RVFI verification. But that's risky since it could break formal properties. Another angle is pipelining the forward unit's select signals themselves rather than computing them combinationally each cycle, though I need to think through whether that actually saves anything or just shifts the problem.\n\nThe core issue I keep running into is the load-use hazard: when a LOAD is in EX and a dependent instruction is in ID, the dependent's register values are stale because the regfile hasn't been updated yet. Even if I forward from EX/MEM at the next cycle, the dependent's id_ex.rs1_val was already captured during ID and doesn't reflect the LOAD's result.\n\nI'm considering a direct forwarding path from the MEM stage's memory output straight to the dependent instruction's operand input—this would bypass the register file entirely and eliminate the stall. The challenge is that this creates a long combinational path: address generation, memory access, data alignment/extension, operand muxing, and then the ALU operation all in one cycle. It's a significant timing risk, but if the Fmax penalty is small, the IPC gain from eliminating the load-use bubble could make it worthwhile.\n\nLooking at the safer structural options, I should avoid changes that add high-fanout wires or touch the critical load-data path. Instead, I could move the byte/halfword alignment logic earlier—computing the aligned values at the EX stage in parallel with the ALU, then having MEM just select the right one based on the address low bits. This would shorten MEM's combinational cone without introducing new forwarding complexity.\n\nWait, but I need to reconsider the dmem timing. The memory is combinational—dmem_rdata comes back the same cycle dmem_addr is driven—so if I move the dmem access into EX itself, loads become a 2-stage operation instead of 3, eliminating the load-use stall. The tradeoff is that stall handling shifts from the EX/MEM boundary to the EX stage itself, which could complicate the pipeline control.\n\nActually, looking at the current design more carefully, the dmem access already happens at the EX-to-MEM boundary combinationally—EX computes the address, and it feeds directly to dmem_addr in the MEM stage. Moving it fully into EX would extend EX's critical path with the dmem round-trip, which isn't worth it.\n\nLet me step back and look at the actual numbers: we're at 172 MHz with a target of 135 MHz, so we actually have Fmax headroom. The real constraint is IPC, not frequency. That changes what I should optimize for.\n\nGiven that headroom, I can afford some Fmax hit if it improves IPC. A restricted dual-issue approach—where the second slot only executes simple immediate-only ops like LUI, AUIPC, or ADDI without reading rs1—could work within our area budget of ~500 LUTs remaining.\n\nBut looking at the complexity and CoreMark's instruction mix, this might not be worth the risk. A safer bet is to move branch target and condition computation earlier into the ID stage, shortening the critical path in EX—though I'd need forwarding logic to resolve register values at decode time, which gets complicated.\n\nActually, let me focus on something more concrete: eliminating the load-use bubble by adding a direct forwarding path from the MEM stage's loaded data straight to EX's operand mux. Since loads are frequent in CoreMark and often followed by dependent instructions, this zero-latency forward path would save a cycle per load-use pair without requiring major structural changes.\n\nThe implementation is straightforward—remove the load-use hazard detection from the hazard unit, add a third forward select in the forward unit for MEM load data, and wire the already-aligned/extended load data from MEM directly into EX's mux. The risk is that this path (dmem_rdata through shift, extend, and into the ALU cone) becomes deep and could hurt Fmax significantly, potentially offsetting the 5-10% IPC gain. Let me explore a safer alternative instead: moving the shift/extend logic earlier so the load data is flopped at the EX/MEM boundary rather than computed combinationally in MEM, though I need to verify whether dmem_rdata is actually available combinationally in the same cycle as the address.\n\nActually, dmem_rdata does respond combinationally in the same cycle MEM asserts dmem_addr, so the current MEM pre-flop cone (alu_result → dmem_addr → dmem_rdata → shift/extend → MEM/WB.read_data) is already flop-to-flop bounded and hard to shorten. Another option is to defer the sign-extension to the WB stage—store the raw dmem_rdata plus metadata in MEM/WB and compute the final value at WB—but that just shifts the critical path to the regfile write port rather than shortening it overall. The real question is whether moving the shift/extend to WB breaks the forwarding path that currently feeds EX from MEM/WB.\n\nread_data, though since fwd_mem_wb is combinational anyway, it should be fine either way.\n\nGiven all these trade-offs and the structural constraints, I'm narrowing down the realistic options: dual-issue is too risky and large, a 5→4 stage collapse risks Fmax, a 5→6 stage pipeline adds branch penalty, direct dmem→EX forwarding is risky, moving sign-extend to WB is likely neutral, and cache is out of budget. The pattern of regressions suggests a restrained structural change might be the honest move—maybe absorbing the WB stage into MEM.\n\nThe idea would be to collapse MEM/WB into a direct combinational regfile write path, eliminating one stage of latency for writeback and reducing forwarding from two sources to one. I'd remove the MEM/WB register and have the MEM stage drive write signals directly to the regfile, though I'd still need a pipeline register for RVFI to maintain the retirement boundary. Actually, I could keep the MEM/WB register for RVFI while also driving regfile writes combinationally from MEM stage outputs—the load_data and write value are already computed on the MEM pre-flop cone, so sharing that data for a same-cycle regfile write wouldn't add much. If an instruction in MEM writes to the regfile at the end of cycle N, a reader would see the new value by cycle N+1, which should help with load-use latency.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the forwarding implications. With write-first bypass on the regfile, an instruction in ID at cycle N could see a write from MEM at cycle N directly, which would eliminate the need for MEM/WB forwarding. The EX/MEM forward would still be necessary for the truly adjacent case where one instruction is in EX and the dependent instruction is in ID at the same cycle, but the MEM/WB forward could potentially be removed. Y's id_ex.rs1_val ends up stale since the regfile write happens at the end of cycle N. But the EX/MEM forwarding path can supply X's result directly. However, if X is a LOAD, I need to reconsider: X computes the address in EX at cycle N, then accesses memory in MEM at N+1 where the loaded data becomes available. If Y is in ID at N and reads the regfile with write-first bypass, it actually captures X's new value before Y moves to EX at N+1—so no bubble is needed. But this contradicts the hazard detection logic, which would insert a stall when it sees a LOAD in the EX stage with a dependent instruction in ID. Without the stall, Y would enter EX at N+1 with stale data from the regfile read at cycle N, before X's write completes.\n\nForwarding from EX/MEM won't help because that stage only has the address, not the loaded data. MEM/WB forwarding is too late since X is still in MEM. I'd need direct forwarding from the MEM stage's combinational load_data output, which feels risky. I'm reconsidering the approach—maybe moving the regfile read into the EX stage so reads happen after forwarding is resolved, but that expands the critical path on the EX pre-flop cone, which the r2s2 BTB experience showed hurts timing on this fabric. I'm abandoning that idea too.\n\nWhat if I write the regfile earlier—at the MEM cycle instead of WB? That eliminates the MEM/WB forwarding path since ID-stage reads would see writes via write-first bypass at the end of MEM. But this still requires the load-use stall because Y in EX at N+1 would otherwise get stale data from the regfile, and forwarding from EX/MEM only gives the address. The real issue is that the regfile doesn't have the loaded data until the end of cycle N+4 in the current design, so any reader in ID at N+3 needs MEM/WB forwarding to get the right value.\n\nWith the change, the regfile write happens at the end of N+3, so a reader Y that's 3 cycles behind X gets the data via bypass. Even a 2-cycle-behind reader works the same way. But a 1-cycle-behind reader still needs the stall—Y in ID at N+2 can't see X's data yet, and when Y reaches EX at N+3, X is in MEM but the forwarding path only carries the address, not the load result. So I still need to insert the bubble to let Y stall until X writes the regfile at the end of N+3.\n\nThe key benefit is simplifying the EX forwarding muxes from 3:1 to 2:1 by removing the MEM/WB forward case, which saves area and likely improves Fmax on the EX critical path. The tradeoff is that RVFI's rd_wdata timing becomes tricky—the instruction retires at the MEM/WB boundary, but the actual write value is captured one cycle earlier in the MEM stage, so I need to make sure RVFI reports the correct data without creating a timing violation. at MEM/WB boundary. If regfile write happens at MEM cycle, but RVFI fires at MEM/WB (1 cycle later), the write happens BEFORE retirement. Hmm - RVFI expects rd_wdata to be the value written at the retirement cycle. If write happens earlier, RVFI is still correct (reports the same value).\n\nActually I think this change would be correct. But it's a structural change that touches multiple modules.\n\nWait, concern: write-first bypass on the regfile. If we write at MEM cycle, and ID reads at same MEM cycle — but ID reads based on w_addr/w_en which are now driven combinationally from MEM's mem_wb register? No, from MEM stage itself combinationally.\n\nActually the regfile's read ports see w_en/w_addr/w_data from the write port driver. If that driver is now mem_stage (from EX/MEM.rd + MEM's combinational gate), that's fine.\n\nLet me think about potential formal issues. The lesson r10s0 said modifying ctrl.reg_write's activation set destabilizes formal. This hypothesis doesn't modify reg_write — we still retire via MEM/WB. But we add regfile writes to happen 1 cycle earlier structurally.\n\nConcerns:\n- The regfile's write port now receives signals from MEM stage, not WB. The value written is identical (same instruction, same rd, same data). But the timing is 1 cycle earlier.\n- RVFI's view: instruction retires at MEM/WB, at which point regfile already has the value. RVFI reports rd_wdata = value = consistent with the commit order.\n\nNow I'm realizing the subtle issue: the regfile state at any cycle could reflect instructions that haven't retired in RVFI's view yet. The formal checker compares the DUT's regfile against a shadow copy maintained from RVFI's rd_addr/rd_wdata stream, so if writes happen early but RVFI reports them later, the checker might see a mismatch when it samples the regfile before RVFI has reported that write.\n\nThe reg_check compares RVFI's reported rs1/rs2 values against a shadow regfile. If the DUT's regfile is updated early but RVFI reports the write later, the shadow lags behind the DUT. When RVFI finally reports the write, the shadow catches up. But if the checker samples between those two events, it could fail.\n\nActually, the reg_check samples rvfi_rs1_rdata and compares it to the shadow's value for that register. If RVFI reports rs1_rdata correctly (based on the regfile state at retirement), and the shadow is updated when RVFI reports the write, they should stay in sync.\n\nLet me trace through: instruction X writes rd=5 at MEM cycle N (regfile updated immediately), retires at cycle N+1 (RVFI reports rd_wdata=V1). Instruction Y reads rs1=5 at ID cycle N+2, captures rs1_val=V1 via write-first bypass. Y retires at cycle N+3, RVFI reports rs1_rdata=V1. The shadow regfile is updated at cycle N+1 when X retires, so by cycle N+3 the shadow has V1 for register 5. Consistent.\n\nSo the change should be formally sound. The key is that RVFI's reported values come from the regfile state at retirement time, and the shadow is updated in lockstep with RVFI reports. Early writes don't break this as long as the values are correct.\n\nI could keep the MEM/WB forwarding path for safety and just add the combinational regfile write from MEM stage, or simplify by removing MEM/WB forwarding entirely if the regfile write-first bypass is solid.\n\nEliminating MEM/WB forwarding would save the 3:1 mux in EX (reducing it to 2:1), the forward_unit's mem_wb logic, and the fwd_mem_wb wire—shortening the pre-flop path. The cost is that MEM stage now drives the regfile write port combinationally, adding load to an already-busy stage. The write signals (w_en, w_addr, w_data) come from the EX/MEM register, which are already combinational outputs.\n\nFor w_data specifically, I'd mux between the combinational load_data (from dmem_rdata through shift/extend) and the flopped alu_result at MEM stage pre-flop instead of post-flop. This makes loads a single MEM+WB operation—the data arrives from memory and gets written to the regfile in the same cycle. The regfile write port now has additional fanout from the load_data cone, but since the regfile already has a write port mux, the Fmax impact is likely minimal.\n\nActually, reconsidering: the current regfile write path is short (MEM/WB flopped data through a mux to the regfile flop D-input). Moving to pre-flop load_data creates a much deeper path—dmem_rdata flows through shift, extend, the mux, then to the regfile flop. That's a significant combinational depth increase for load operations, which would hurt Fmax.\n\nThat's not ideal. Let me step back and look at what's actually working. The current best fitness is 387.98 versus a baseline of 301.04—that's a 29% improvement. The champion is r4s2 (JAL fast-path variant) at 172.35 MHz. Since r4s2 is leading, many recent hypotheses have been exploring similar structural variations, particularly in the forwarding mux topology.\n\nInstead of chasing more predictor tweaks, I should try something orthogonal. Looking at the hazard_unit, the critical paths are `flush_if` driving the instruction mux and `redirect` driving the PC mux in IF stage. The redirect path is especially tight since it depends on the branch condition from EX. But I notice something: PC+4 is being computed in two places—once in IF and again in EX for non-branch cases. What if I compute it once at IF and propagate it through the pipeline instead?\n\nActually, someone already tried that approach and it regressed, so that's a dead end. Let me think about a different structural change: moving regfile writes to happen at the MEM stage instead of WB, using write-first bypass to maintain correctness. This would shrink the EX pre-flop cone by eliminating the MEM/WB forward path, reducing the operand mux from 3:1 to 2:1. The tradeoff is that LOAD data would need to route to the regfile write port at MEM, which could be problematic.\n\nFor non-LOAD ops, the write comes from the already-flopped EX/MEM result, keeping the cone short. For LOADs, I'd add a 2:1 mux to select between load data and ALU result before driving the regfile port. The write enable needs to gate on valid and account for traps—using `mem_stage.ctrl_with_trap.reg_write && ex_mem.valid` to prevent flushed instructions from writing. This should work if the load data path doesn't balloon the pre-flop cone too much. Let me draft the YAML for this.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the load-use hazard behavior stays the same either way. With the MEM-stage write, a dependent instruction stalled in ID will read the regfile at the next cycle and see the load result immediately, so no forwarding is needed. Without the change, the dependent instruction would have to wait one more cycle for the WB-stage write, but the hazard unit already accounts for that stall. Either approach works from a correctness standpoint. At N+2, Y reaches EX with stale rs1_val since X hasn't written back yet, but the MEM/WB forwarding path captures X's load_data from the previous cycle, which correctly resolves the hazard. My proposed change would work the same way—injecting a bubble via flush_id achieves the same one-cycle stall that the current load-use detection does.\n\nHowever, there's a critical timing issue: if I write from the MEM stage at N+1, Y's ID stage at N+1 would need to read through the regfile's write-first bypass combinationally, which means the load_data cone gets pulled directly into the id_ex flop's D-input path. This extends the critical path at the ID stage rather than keeping it downstream at EX, which could actually be worse than the existing MEM/WB forward approach. Without synthesis data, it's hard to know if this timing hit outweighs the benefit of eliminating the MEM/WB forward logic, so I'm going to commit this with low confidence and document the hypothesis.\n\nActually, let me step back and consider some alternatives. A fused dual-muxed regfile port would reduce bypass logic but introduces a stall on dual reads—not worth it. Moving regfile reads to an early EX substage is too risky and ventures into territory I've already seen fail. Decoder refactoring or splitting EX into separate ALU and MUL paths are also high-risk given the formal sensitivity around regfile and datapath timing. I think I'll stick with documenting the early-write hypothesis and move forward.\n\nWait, I'm overthinking this. The real insight is pipelining the multiplier itself—register its output at the end of EX so MUL becomes a 2-cycle operation like loads, with writeback happening in MEM. This shortens EX's critical path by removing the 33x33 multiplier from the combinational cone, and the hazard unit just needs to stall on immediate MUL-use like it does for load-use. r2s1 tried a handshake version and concluded it added unnecessary stall logic, but a simpler fixed 2-cycle approach might be cleaner. the multiplier sits OFF the critical path. So pipelining it won't help.\n\nBUT: r2s1 was the SECOND iteration right after r1s0 (shared-mult improvement). Now many iterations later, r10s1 said EX pre-flop cone is binding. Has the mult moved onto the critical path?\n\nLooking at alu.sv, `prod = opa_ext * opb_ext` is computed every cycle. Then the case mux picks `prod[31:0]` or `prod[63:32]` for MUL ops. For non-MUL ops, prod's result is ignored but the multiplier was still computed. In synthesis, Yosys might tree-shake prod for non-MUL, but Yosys doesn't know at compile time which op fires each cycle. So the multiplier exists structurally.\n\nThe critical path: is it through the multiplier? Actually the multiplier output is one arm of a big case mux. The case mux takes the MUL output plus all ALU outputs. Whichever arm is longest determines the pre-flop path.\n\n33x33 multiply + sign-ext + ALU case mux is likely the longest arm. If so, pipelining MUL helps.\n\nBut r2s1 added handshake complexity which itself added cost. A simpler pipelined-mul idea would be to register the multiplier output at the EX/MEM boundary, making MUL a 2-cycle operation that treats it like a LOAD for hazard detection. But that's getting complex, and r2s1 already failed.\n\nLet me step back. I keep circling risky ideas — extending JAL fast-paths, retirement FIFOs, all of it. Instead, what if I just skip the id_ex register for NOPs by collapsing bubbles through control fields going straight to zero?\n\nActually, that's already how it works.\n\nOK, final idea: eliminate the MEM/WB forward path by pre-writing results. It's structural, targets the binding cone, and is plausible.\n\nWait, let me trace the forward_unit critical path. The comparators check if ex_mem.rd or mem_wb.rd match id_ex.rs1, then a 3:1 mux selects the operand. The MEM/WB forward arm pulls from the WB-stage combinational result (either memory read data or ALU result), which itself comes from a 2:1 mux. That whole path — flop outputs, comparators, muxes, then into the ALU — is part of the EX pre-flop cone.\n\nIf I eliminate MEM/WB forwarding, the forward mux drops to 2:1, saving maybe one LUT4 level on a 32-bit mux. The WB mux still exists but only drives regfile writes. If that's the binding path, it's worth doing.\n\nCommitting to this approach. But I need to check whether modifying regfile write timing will destabilize formal verification. The lesson notes mention that regfile reset changes broke formal, but my change only shifts when writes happen, not the reset logic.\n\nActually, there's a subtlety here: if regfile writes happen in MEM instead of WB, and a subsequent instruction reads in ID, the write-first bypass at the regfile could pick up the new value combinationally. That means MEM/WB forwarding gets replaced by regfile write-first bypass, which pulls the load data cone into the ID stage's read path. I need to think through whether that timing is actually better or if it just moves the problem.\n\nThe current ID pre-flop path is already fairly deep with regfile read and decode, but the write-first bypass only sees WB-stage data (flop-to-flop), so it's relatively contained. If I move the write to MEM, the bypass mux now sees the full load data combinational path—address decode, memory read, shift, extend—all feeding into ID's read logic before the flop. That's a significant cone extension that could make ID the new critical path and tank Fmax.\n\nThis is getting risky. Let me step back and consider a simpler approach instead.\n\nThe real issue is that the 33×33 multiplier is likely the deepest arm in the ALU's case mux, making it the Fmax bottleneck. If I pipeline it by registering the product at the end of EX and treating MUL as a 2-cycle operation like LOAD, the ALU case mux gets shorter and the hazard unit just detects MUL-use stalls the same way it does load-use. The trade-off is a small IPC hit from stalls, but CoreMark doesn't have dense MUL usage, so it might be worth it for the Fmax gain.\n\nBut wait—r2s1 already noted that the shared multiplier sits off the EX forward-mux critical path, so pipelining it might not help. Yet r10s1 said the EX pre-flop became binding after the shared-mul change. So what else is on that cone besides the multiplier? The forward mux, the ALU case mux, and all the ALU operations—shifter, subtractor, everything. The deepest arm determines the depth, so I need to figure out whether the multiplier is actually the deepest or if something else is.\n\nWithout synthesis data, I'm guessing. Let me commit to the pipelined multiplier approach with medium confidence.\n\nActually, there's another angle: the retirement boundary. The wb_stage currently has a 2:1 mux selecting between memory data and ALU result, then feeds that to the regfile write port. If I move that mux earlier—into the mem_stage, before the MEM/WB register—then MEM/WB stores the already-muxed value and the regfile write becomes a direct flop-to-port connection, saving one mux level. But r3s1 already tried something similar.\n\nWait, I'm reading the notes more carefully. r2s1 says pipelining MUL/DIV adds stall logic without actually freeing Fmax—the multiplier isn't the binding critical path. So that's a dead end; it'd just add IPC loss from extra stalls.\n\nThe real binding cone is probably the ALU's adder or subtractor carry chain. r2s0 mentions that branch resolution routes through the shared 33-bit subtractor, serializing the flush path. r7s1 talks about ALU carry chain sharing. So the adder/subtractor is likely where the critical path actually lives.\n\nI could try splitting the ALU adder from non-adder ops to shorten the case mux, but that's just basic synthesis—Yosys already does that.\n\nI'm going to propose moving the regfile write into the MEM stage instead of WB. It's a legitimate topology restructure: the regfile gets written early via a write-first bypass, eliminating the MEM/WB forwarding path entirely. The RVFI retirement cycle stays the same, but the physical write happens one cycle earlier, so MEM/WB forwarding becomes a no-op. It's risky, but it's a real structural change. I'll mark confidence as low and write it up in YAML.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decee7020001ASGF4tJh4M4ijQ","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","messageID":"msg_dece9897f001QSISPJGeSUJc10"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777796544040,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"id":"prt_decee6d64001zgbdW5cl8EaEFA","messageID":"msg_dece9897f001QSISPJGeSUJc10","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","type":"text","text":"Looking at this carefully. The category is **structural**, current best is r4s2 (JAL fast-path, +17.73%). The lessons show:\n\n1. Predictors on ID-side redirect cone have repeatedly failed (r1s2, r2s2, r3s2, r6s2, r7s2, r10s2)\n2. EX pre-flop cone is the post-r1s0 binding cone (r10s1 lesson)\n3. id_ex_t symbol edits destabilize formal (r7s0)\n4. Regfile reset/init changes break formal (r3s0/r4s0/r5s0/r6s1)\n5. Writeback-mux movement to pre-MEM/WB tried and regressed (r3s1)\n6. Pipelining MUL/DIV regressed (r2s1 — mult not on critical path)\n\nLet me look at log.jsonl briefly to confirm nothing similar tried:","time":{"start":1777796541796,"end":1777796544040}}}
