{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796547033,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01MeqWNBu8E44FyKqePfRACg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"mem.wb.forward|early.write|write.first|regfile.write|3.1.mux|MEM/WB forward","path":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 8 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Split ALU: move MUL/DIV into multi-cycle execution unit with EX stall handshake\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defines the\\nminimum clock period for the whole core. Baseline Fmax is 135 MHz\\nwith target 135 MHz \\u2014 the core is capped by the EX cycle. CoreMark\\n6 KB executes few MUL and essentially zero DIV per iteration, so\\nremoving those ops from the EX critical path and paying for them in\\nextra cycles only on the rare MUL/DIV instruction is a strongly\\nfavorable structural tradeoff for the fitness metric\\n`iter/cycle \\u00d7 Fmax`.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\\nthe real (non-formal) synthesis paths \\u2014 cosim, yosys, nextpnr \\u2014 map\\nthe `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\\na 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\\nalu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\\nmultiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\\nrange and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\\nsits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\\nmux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defi...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Regfile as GW2AR distributed-RAM (SSRAM) \\u2014 drop reset-loop to free ~1k FFs and the 32:1 read mux cone\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Baseline uses 9905/10000 LUT4 and 1858 FF on Tang Nano 20K. The r2s2\\nlesson is explicit: \\\"on a near-full Tang Nano 20K ... reclaim area\\nelsewhere first.\\\" Prior structural/predictor hypotheses kept bumping\\ninto area-induced Fmax/routing walls. The integer register file\\n(`reg_file.sv`) is the single biggest area hog in this design that is\\nNOT on anyone's critical path:\\n\\n  - 32 \\u00d7 32b = 1024 FFs (>55% of the total 1858 FF budget)\\n  - Two combinational read ports = two 32:1 32b muxes \\u2248 hundreds of\\n    LUT4s for the read fan-in trees\\n  - A synchronous-reset foreach loop zeroing the array is the ONLY\\n    thing preventing Yosys's `memory_dff`/`memory_bram` pass from\\n    mapping this array to GW2AR LUT4-as-SSRAM (distributed RAM) on\\n    the Gowin flow.\\n\\nGW2AR LUT4s support SSRAM (SP/DP distributed RAM) \\u2014 a 32\\u00d732 two-read\\none-write configuration maps to roughly 2 rows \\u00d7 32 cols \\u00d7 2 read\\nports = ~128 LUT4s configured as memory, replacing ~1024 FFs AND the\\n32:1 read muxes. Net expected save: ~1024 FF + several hundred LUT4\\nheadroom, opening Fmax ceiling on GW2AR where routing/congestion is\\nthe dominant Fmax limiter near 99% LUT occupancy.\\n\\nFunctional behavior must stay bit-identical: x0-hardwire, write-first\\nsame-cycle bypass (ID read of a register being written by WB this\\ncycle returns the new value), and the single-write / dual-read port\\nstructure. The only change is storage inference, not semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Baseline uses 9905/10000 LUT4 and 1858 FF on Tang Nano 20K. The r2s2\\nlesson is explicit: \\\"on a near-full Tang Nano 20K ... reclaim area\\nelsewhere first.\\\" Prior structural/predictor hypotheses kept bumping\\ninto area-induced Fmax/routing walls. The integer register file\\n(`reg_file.sv`) is the single...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Pre-mux write-back value in MEM stage: collapse WB's mem_to_reg mux into MEM/WB register\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The EX forwarding path is a prime Fmax suspect on this core. Today\\nfwd_mem_wb equals wb_stage's output, which itself is a 2:1 mux\\n(mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result) sitting AFTER the MEM/WB flop.\\nEX's operand network is therefore: MEM/WB flop \\u2192 2:1 mem_to_reg mux \\u2192\\n3:1 fwd mux (with fwd_ex_mem and rs?_val) \\u2192 2:1 alu_src / AUIPC mux \\u2192\\nALU. That extra 2:1 on the forwarding tail is pure combinational delay\\npiled onto a path that already fans into the ALU cone. Lesson from\\nr1s0 (+9.47%): shaving layers off the EX combinational cone is the\\nsingle most reliable Fmax lever on GW2AR at this LUT envelope\\n(9905/10000). Recent structural regressions (r2s0 shared-subtractor,\\nr2s1 skid-buffer, r2s2 BTB) all lost by *adding* logic to a critical\\ncone; the dual is to *remove* logic from the same family of cones.\\nThe WB-stage 2:1 mux is a clean removal candidate \\u2014 it does no work\\nthat couldn't happen one cycle earlier inside MEM stage, before the\\nflop, where the pre-flop combinational depth (shift + sign/zero\\nextend) is already the MEM critical path and a 2:1 32-bit mux sits\\ncomfortably in its shadow.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX forwarding path is a prime Fmax suspect on this core. Today\\nfwd_mem_wb equals wb_stage's output, which itself is a 2:1 mux\\n(mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result) sitting AFTER the MEM/WB flop.\\nEX's operand network is therefore: MEM/WB flop \\u2192 2:1 mem_to_reg mux \\u2192\\n3:1 fwd mux (with fwd_ex_mem and rs?_val) \\u2192 2:1 alu_src / AUIPC mux \\u2192\\nALU. That extra 2:1 on the forwarding tail is pure combinational delay\\npiled onto a path that already fans into the ALU cone. Lesson from\\nr1s0 (+9.47%): shaving layers off the EX combinational cone is the\\nsingle most reliable Fmax lever on GW2AR at this LUT envelope\\n(9905/10000...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Regfile distributed-SSRAM inference: replace reset-loop with initial-zero block\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current reg_file.sv stores the 32x32 integer file in an FF array\\nwith a synchronous reset loop that clears all 32 words in one cycle.\\nOn GW2AR this forces Yosys/nextpnr to synthesise:\\n  - 1024 FFs of real flop storage (drives utilization; resets fanout\\n    to every regfile FF enlarges the reset net).\\n  - Two 32:1 read muxes (one per read port) \\u2014 roughly 60 LUT4 each,\\n    i.e. ~120 LUT4 + their routing plus the write-first-bypass muxes.\\n  - A 5:32 write-address decoder.\\nThis structure is the textbook reason small RISC-V cores on LUT-RAM\\nfabrics move the regfile into distributed SRAM: GW2AR LUTs can be\\nconfigured as 16x1 single-port SSRAM, so a 32x32x1W/2R file collapses\\nto ~64 SSRAM LUTs (one per read port, dual-read = 2x) with zero FF\\nstorage \\u2014 eliminating the 32:1 read-mux trees and most of the FF\\npressure. On this project LUTs are 9905/10000 (99% full) \\u2014 the r2s2\\nBTB lesson explicitly called out that predictor-style wins get erased\\nby congestion-induced Fmax loss. Reclaiming ~100 LUT4 and ~1000 FFs\\nfrom the regfile is a direct area win that unblocks routing freedom\\nfor the existing critical cones, so Fmax should tick up without\\ntouching any timing path.\\n\\nPrior attempt r3s0 tried this by deleting the reset loop outright and\\nwas broken: riscv-formal's per-channel `reg` check (`reg_ch*`) anchors\\nits BMC induction on a known post-reset regfile (all zeros) to diff\\nthe DUT's observable rs?_rdata/rd_wdata against the ISA model. With no\\nreset clear and no init, the initial FF state is unconstrained \\u2014 the\\ncheck fails. The r3s0 lesson explicitly names the usable pattern:\\na synthesis-only `ifndef FORMAL` guard, *or* a ROM-init `initial`\\nblock. The `initial` form is strictly better: it is accepted by\\n  - Verilator (runs initial at t=0, regs start zero in cocotb),\\...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Regfile reset-loop guarded by (YOSYS && !RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS) to enable Gowin distributed-SSRAM inference for FPGA synth only\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Lesson r4s0 explicitly names this as \\\"the remaining viable path\\\" after\\nr3s0 (no-reset for SSRAM inference, broke reg_ch* formal check) and\\nr4s0 (initial-block init, broke SBY with empty traces). The current\\nregfile's synchronous 32-entry reset-to-zero loop forces Yosys to\\ninfer 32x32=1024 FFs + a 32-way one-hot reset mux network, which on\\nGW2AR blocks distributed-SSRAM inference. Area is the binding\\nconstraint on this fabric (9484/10000 LUT4, with predictor-class\\nhypotheses like r2s2 and r3s2 regressing purely on LUT headroom /\\nrouting congestion). Freeing ~1024 FFs + the reset distribution\\nnetwork would materially reduce routing pressure and likely lift\\nFmax via reduced congestion, on top of direct LUT/FF area savings.\\n\\nThe prior failures were both \\\"all-or-nothing\\\" rewrites: dropping\\nreset globally broke formal's reg_ch* BMC (which anchors induction on\\na deterministic all-zero post-reset regfile state), and `initial` was\\nlifted into an SMT universal initial-state constraint by Yosys's SMT\\nbackend that made SBY's per-instruction checks return vacuous\\npasses. The untested path is a macro-guarded version that preserves\\nthe reset loop for Verilator (cocotb tests) AND formal (reg_ch* BMC\\nanchor) but drops it only for the Gowin FPGA yosys synth pass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Lesson r4s0 explicitly names this as \\\"the remaining viable path\\\" after\\nr3s0 (no-reset for SSRAM inference, broke reg_ch* formal check) and\\nr4s0 (initial-block init, broke SBY with empty traces). The current\\nregfile's synchronous 32-entry reset-to-zero loop forces Yosys to\\ninfer 32x32=1024 FFs + a 32-way one-hot reset mux network, which on\\nGW2AR blocks distributed-SSRAM inference. Area is the binding\\nconstraint on this fabric (9484/10000 LUT4, with predict...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Dual-storage regfile with YOSYS-guarded reset for GW2AR distributed RAM\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The regfile currently synthesizes to 1024 discrete FFs plus a dense\\nread-mux tree. On a near-full fabric (9484/10000 LUT4s, 1861 FFs),\\nreclaiming 1000+ FFs and a chunk of LUT area is the biggest\\narea-unblock available short of superscalar.\\n\\nPrior attempts at distributed-SSRAM inference (r3s0, r4s0, r5s0) each\\nidentified one of the two blocking conditions but not both at once:\\n(a) r5s0 diagnosed the port-shape mismatch \\u2014 2 async read ports +\\n1 sync write does not match any single Gowin LUT-RAM primitive;\\n(b) r3s0/r4s0 diagnosed the reset-loop blocking no-reset SSRAM\\ninference, with `ifdef YOSYS` guard the remaining viable pattern\\nafter `initial` was shown to poison formal via universal SMT\\ninitial-state constraints.\\n\\nThe canonical FPGA workaround for (a) is to duplicate the storage\\narray so each read port owns its own single-read-port RAM. Writes\\nbroadcast to both copies. This is structural: it splits one module's\\nstorage topology into two parallel instances. Combined with (b), it\\nremoves both blockers simultaneously.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The regfile currently synthesizes to 1024 discrete FFs plus a dense\\nread-mux tree. On a near-full fabric (9484/10000 LUT4s, 1861 FFs),\\nreclaiming 1000+ FFs and a chunk of LUT area is the biggest\\narea-unblock available short of superscalar.\\n\\nPrior attempts at distributed-SSRAM inference (r3s0, r4s0, r5s0) each\\nidentified one of the two blocking conditions but not both at once:\\n(a) r5s0 diagnosed the port-shape mismatch \\u2014 2 async read ports +\\n1 sync write does not match any single Gowin LUT-RAM primitive;\\n(b) r3s0/r4s0 diagnosed the reset-loop blocking no-reset SSRAM\\ninference, with `ifdef YOSYS` guard the remaining viable pattern\\nafter `initial` was shown to poison formal via universal SMT\\ninitial-state constraints.\\n\\nThe cano...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Zero-storage backward-branch prediction at ID, r4s2-pattern (additive, no rename)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80-95% accurate on\\nthese CoreMark kernels, covers another ~4-6% of dynamic instructions, and\\nsaves 2 pipeline bubbles per hit.\\n\\nr5s2 attempted this concept but failed implementation: it renamed\\n`jal_predicted` to `predicted_taken`, and a missed downstream consumer\\ncascaded into SBY's \\\"Status: passed / engine_0 did not produce any traces\\\"\\nsignature + cover VCD crash (no_checks_generated). The architectural idea\\nis sound; the diff discipline was not. This hypothesis retries the concept\\nwith strict additive plumbing (no renames) to eliminate the cascade-risk\\nclass of failures entirely.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Gate reg_write at ID for rd==0 to shorten forward_unit priority encoder\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The forward_unit drives the 3:1 operand-select muxes at the head of the\\nEX-stage ALU/branch-comparator cone \\u2014 it sits directly on one of the\\ncore's known hot combinational paths. Each of its two always_comb\\npriority encoders evaluates three conditions per term:\\n  (ex_mem_w_en) && (ex_mem_rd != 5'b0) && (ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\n  (mem_wb_w_en) && (mem_wb_rd != 5'b0) && (mem_wb_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\nThe `rd != 5'b0` predicate is redundant with `w_en`: an architectural\\nwrite whose destination is x0 has no effect (regfile writes to x0 are\\ndropped, forward_unit returning x0 would be bit-identical to returning\\nthe real x0 = 0 since the regfile's read of x0 is hardwired). If we\\nconstrain `ctrl.reg_write` upstream \\u2014 at id_stage, by AND-ing decoder's\\nreg_write with (instr[11:7] != 5'b0) before loading into ID/EX \\u2014 then\\n`w_en=0` already implies `rd!=0` at EX/MEM and MEM/WB, and the\\nforward_unit's `rd != 5'b0` terms collapse to dead code that Yosys can\\nDCE cleanly.\\n\\nThis is the \\\"constrain upstream, let downstream DCE\\\" pattern, strictly\\nlocal to id_stage.sv + decoder-output gating, and does NOT edit any\\npipeline-register struct field name (the confirmed formal tarpit from\\nr4s0/r5s1/r5s2/r6s0/r6s1/r7s0/r7s2/r8s0). The only thing changing is\\na combinational AND gate on ctrl_decoded.reg_write inside id_stage,\\nbefore the ID/EX flop captures it.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The forward_unit drives the 3:1 operand-select muxes at the head of the\\nEX-stage ALU/branch-comparator cone \\u2014 it sits directly on one of the\\ncore's known hot combinational paths. Each of its two always_comb\\npriority encoders evaluates three conditions per term:\\n  (ex_mem_w_en) && (ex_mem_rd != 5'b0) && (ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\n  (mem_wb_w_en) && (mem_wb_rd != 5'b0) && (mem_wb_rd == id_ex_rs?)\\nThe `rd != 5'b0` p...","metadata":{"matches":8,"truncated":false},"title":"mem.wb.forward|early.write|write.first|regfile.write|3.1.mux|MEM/WB forward","time":{"start":1777796547005,"end":1777796547031}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_decee7e69001GWaJYBXfmw05NA","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","messageID":"msg_decee7654001z45IJQX5VKfGqN"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1777796547074,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"id":"prt_decee81d9001ryvh7Xj4aSN9Lc","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"8e4779b470b1d8e60d9ff8632ea85264e2cefa38","messageID":"msg_decee7654001z45IJQX5VKfGqN","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":103585,"input":1,"output":137,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":79082,"read":24365}},"cost":0.509875}}
