{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796680171,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01RzG2XZReSLusRU5oXX2GdX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r11s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r11s1\ntitle: \"Split-origin regfile commit: ALU writes from EX/MEM, loads from MEM/WB, shrinking the forward mux tree\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The EX pre-flop cone is the post-r1s0 binding Fmax cone (r10s1\n  lesson). Sitting at the head of that cone is forward_unit's 3:1\n  operand mux whose mem_wb input is itself the output of a *second*\n  2:1 mux (wb_stage's `ctrl.mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result`),\n  i.e. two serial mux levels of flop-to-mux depth before the ALU\n  even sees its operand. r3s1 tried to collapse the inner 2:1 into\n  MEM-stage pre-flop and regressed because the load_data cone\n  (dmem_rdata -> shift -> sign/zero-extend) was already the MEM\n  critical path — moving the mux ahead of the flop put it in\n  series with that cone. So the 2:1 cannot just be pulled back a\n  stage without hurting MEM.\n\n  But the lesson also says something useful: the mem_to_reg mux's\n  `alu_result` input is a *flopped* signal one cycle earlier than\n  MEM/WB's mem_to_reg evaluation. That is, for every non-LOAD\n  writer in the pipeline, the final architectural rd value is\n  ALREADY sitting in EX/MEM.alu_result one full cycle before\n  wb_stage evaluates the mux. Holding those values hostage in\n  MEM/WB for an extra cycle, then re-selecting them through a 2:1\n  mux, is pure structural waste: the mux branch is dead for ~70%+\n  of retirements (non-LOADs), and the one cycle of extra latency\n  is the *entire reason* MEM/WB forwarding exists.\n\n  CoreMark's instruction mix is roughly 65-75% non-LOADs on this\n  core — ADD/OR/XOR/shifts/LUI/AUIPC/JAL/JALR/branches. Every one\n  of those has its rd value ready at the end of EX stage. They\n  only *physically* write the regfile two cycles later (WB) for\n  architectural simplicity, not because the data isn't ready.\n  r4s2 established the winning pattern on this fabric: \"resolve\n  one stage earlier and share the existing net.\" The regfile\n  write port is the existing net. The structural move is to\n  commit non-LOAD writes one stage earlier — from EX/MEM, not WB.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split regfile commit by operation class, single write port, no\n  new struct fields, no id_ex_t edits (avoiding the r7s0/r10s0\n  formal tarpit):\n\n    Non-LOAD commits (ALU/JAL/JALR/LUI/AUIPC, identified by\n    `!ctrl.mem_to_reg` at EX/MEM): fire the regfile write port at\n    end of MEM-cycle using EX/MEM.alu_result as w_data. These are\n    already flopped signals — the write-port driver sees\n    flop-Q -> priority-mux -> regfile flop-D, a SHORT pre-flop\n    cone that does not touch the load_data cone r3s1 tripped on.\n\n    LOAD commits (`ctrl.mem_to_reg=1`, identified by\n    MEM/WB.ctrl.mem_to_reg at WB cycle): fire the regfile write\n    port from MEM/WB.read_data as today. Load_data cone stays\n    where it is.\n\n    Write-port arbitration: non-LOAD at EX/MEM and LOAD at MEM/WB\n    are separated by one pipeline cycle by construction (a LOAD\n    in WB was in MEM last cycle and in EX the cycle before that;\n    whatever is in EX/MEM *right now* is a different instruction,\n    one cycle younger). So if a non-LOAD is committing this cycle\n    from EX/MEM, the oldest instruction (in MEM/WB) was either a\n    LOAD (committing simultaneously — conflict, solved by the\n    priority mux below) or a non-LOAD (already committed last\n    cycle at its own EX/MEM stage — MEM/WB.reg_write stays 0 so\n    no conflict).\n\n    Priority: LOAD-in-MEM/WB wins when both are valid (keeps the\n    architecturally-older retirement's write canonical). Non-LOAD\n    at EX/MEM only fires when MEM/WB isn't writing. The non-LOAD\n    write is speculatively armed every EX/MEM cycle with\n    `reg_write && !mem_to_reg && !misalign && valid && !pending_load_in_mem_wb`.\n\n  Forward-unit consequence — the structural payoff: with non-LOAD\n  values landing in regfile one cycle earlier, a consumer 2 cycles\n  behind a non-LOAD writer reads the correct value via regfile\n  write-first bypass (already exists in reg_file.sv). The\n  MEM/WB forward path in forward_unit becomes LOAD-only — it fires\n  only when MEM/WB contains a LOAD writeback. Its data source\n  becomes MEM/WB.read_data directly (no mem_to_reg mux needed\n  since always LOAD). The wb_stage's 2:1 `mem_to_reg ? read_data\n  : alu_result` mux is eliminated entirely — w_data is wired\n  per-source (alu_result from EX/MEM Q, read_data from MEM/WB Q).\n  That removes ONE LUT level from the EX-stage forward cone's\n  mem_wb leg, which is exactly the leg identified as binding.\n\n  r4s2-pattern conformance: no id_ex_t field added/renamed\n  (formal tarpit avoided per r7s0/r10s0), no new predictor-style\n  storage (avoids r2s2/r3s2/r6s2/r7s2/r10s2 LUT/Fmax class), no\n  changes to fetch-redirect cone (avoids r4s0/r5s1/r8s0), no\n  changes to regfile reset semantics (avoids r3s0/r4s0/r5s0/\n  r6s1). The one touchpoint on the MEM load_data cone is\n  subtractive (fwd_mem_wb no longer ORs a mem_to_reg mux into the\n  pre-flop tail), NOT additive like r3s1.\n\n  Correctness sketch: RVFI retirement boundary stays at MEM/WB.\n  rvfi_order increments when MEM/WB.valid rises (unchanged).\n  rd_wdata reported at retirement is the *same value* the\n  regfile now holds (for non-LOADs the architectural value is\n  already in regfile one cycle earlier, but the RVFI observation\n  occurs when MEM/WB.valid fires — the shadow regfile the formal\n  check maintains via RVFI's rd stream then matches the DUT's\n  physical regfile after both have updated). rs1/rs2_rdata in\n  RVFI are sampled from MEM/WB register fields which are\n  captured at ID-cycle via write-first bypass — bypass path\n  unchanged.\n\n  Hazard unit stays identical: load-use hazard still requires a\n  1-cycle bubble (LOAD's load_data isn't ready until its own MEM\n  cycle, regardless of commit source). stall_*/flush_* semantics\n  untouched.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Rewire the regfile write port from wb_stage's single driver to a priority-muxed driver (LOAD-at-MEM/WB wins, non-LOAD-at-EX/MEM fires when MEM/WB has no pending LOAD commit). Pass EX/MEM.rd / EX/MEM.alu_result / EX/MEM.ctrl.reg_write / EX/MEM.ctrl.mem_to_reg / EX/MEM.valid to the reg_file's write port along with the existing WB-path signals. No changes to imem/dmem IO or RVFI port set.\"\n  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n    description: \"Simplify: wb_stage's output now drives only the LOAD-commit path. Replace `w_data = mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result` with `w_data = read_data` (wb_stage now only fires for LOADs). w_en gating tightens to `ctrl.reg_write && ctrl.mem_to_reg && valid` — non-LOAD writes are handled upstream. This eliminates one LUT level off the wb_w_data cone that feeds fwd_mem_wb.\"\n  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n    description: \"Tighten the mem_wb forward arm: only fire when the MEM/WB instruction is a LOAD committing this cycle. The w_en signal fed to forward_unit from the top level now reflects the WB path's LOAD-only gating, so fwd_rs?=2'd2 (mem_wb-source) activates less often — for non-LOAD writers the rs value is already in regfile via bypass, so the forward mux can default to the ID/EX register-read path (2'd0) without staleness. No structural change to the mux encoding — just a semantic narrowing of when 2'd2 fires.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Hook the fwd_mem_wb input to the new LOAD-only WB path. Data source for fwd_mem_wb becomes MEM/WB.read_data directly (no more mem_to_reg mux in the combinational pre-ALU cone). The 3:1 operand forward mux becomes *effectively* 2:1 for non-LOAD-heavy workloads (the 2'd2 arm fires less, Yosys may opt-merge), and the mem_wb leg loses one LUT level of depth regardless.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Cocotb smoke test: verify that an ADD followed 2 cycles later by a dependent ADD retires with the correct rd value (exercises the EX/MEM-origin commit path and the regfile write-first bypass at the ID stage). Verify that a LOAD followed 2 cycles later by a dependent ADD still retires correctly (exercises the MEM/WB-origin commit path, unchanged). Verify write-port priority: a LOAD at MEM/WB and a non-LOAD at EX/MEM on the same cycle — LOAD wins, non-LOAD commits on the following cycle when MEM/WB is clear (or more precisely: because the non-LOAD would have been at EX/MEM the prior cycle too in the normal flow, this case is actually architecturally impossible to hit at steady state; add an assertion that `mem_wb_commit && ex_mem_commit && same_addr` never fires).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r11s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r11s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777796680150,"end":1777796680170}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm realizing the early regfile write approach hasn't been explored in quite this way before, though r3s1 did some pre-muxing at the MEM stage—but that's a different mechanism. Now I need to weigh whether this actually solves the depth problem or if the write-first bypass feeding back into the ID stage creates new issues.\n\nLet me step back and consider safer alternatives. One option is to do the early write without changing the forward unit—keeping both paths active means MEM/WB forwarding becomes redundant, which gains nothing in performance and just adds area. Another angle is to keep writes at WB but add a separate forward path from MEM's combinational load data directly to EX's operands, specifically to eliminate the load-use stall. This feels structurally similar to what worked in r4s2—moving something earlier to cover more cases. The key insight is sourcing the MEM-stage forward from the pre-flop combinational signals rather than the flop outputs, so EX reads MEM's currently-computing data instead of last cycle's result. This zero-load-use-stall path would let a load's data forward immediately to the next instruction without the bubble.\n\nBut the concern is real: the load_data combinational cone is already deep—it runs from the ALU result through address decode, memory roundtrip, shift, extend, then through the forward mux and back into the ALU before hitting the flop. That's a massive path, and adding it to the critical loop would likely kill Fmax. Even a conditional version where the mux selects load_data only when MEM holds a LOAD instruction doesn't help, because the selector itself is a flop output and the data input is still that full cone. After working through all these angles, I think the most conservative move is to accept that the structural changes needed here are too risky for the timing margin we have. and 5-stage for LOAD/MUL — but that's too complex and risky. Let me stick with the original approach: early regfile write from MEM stage to cut the MEM/WB forwarding path. Actually, rereading the lesson from r3s1, I see the trap now — moving the mem_to_reg mux before the MEM/WB flop puts it in series with the load_data critical path, which is already the bottleneck in MEM. My idea does the same thing structurally, so it'll hit the same wall.\n\nWhat if I only do early writes for non-load instructions? Or split the load_data computation into separate pipelines? These feel half-baked. Let me think differently — given the structural constraint and the RVFI channel 1 port sitting unused, what if I dual-issue immediate-only instructions like LUI, AUIPC, and JAL? They need no register reads and produce results from just the PC and immediate, so they could execute in parallel and retire through the second RVFI channel. But that requires peeking ahead in the instruction stream and managing two write ports, which introduces its own complexity.\n\nThe area cost is steep and risky on a nearly full fabric, but it could genuinely double IPC for sequences heavy in these immediates — maybe 3-7% overall gain if they're 5-10% of CoreMark. The real constraint is that I need to fetch two instructions per cycle and handle the hazard detection carefully, especially around redirects. Still, it's a bold structural change that hasn't been explored yet, and if I restrict slot 0 to fetch at PC and slot 1 to fetch at PC+4, the logic becomes more tractable.\n\nBut wait — the imem interface is 32-bit with only one read port per cycle, so I can't actually fetch two instructions simultaneously without restructuring the memory. I'd need either a 64-bit imem or a prefetch buffer that survives redirects. That means true dual-issue is fundamentally bandwidth-limited here; even if I buffer the previous cycle's instruction, I'm still stuck at one fetch per cycle on average, so there's no steady-state IPC gain. The only way to exploit this would be during stall cycles, but that doesn't actually help since I'm only fetching one instruction at a time anyway.\n\nGiven all these constraints, structural changes are genuinely hard on this core. Let me pivot to something more tractable: collapsing the MEM/WB data-preservation path by forwarding directly from the MEM stage when a dmem stall occurs, which would eliminate the need for the hold_wb register and free up area.\n\nActually, thinking through the forwarding edge case — when a LOAD stalls in EX/MEM and a dependent instruction like BNE is waiting in ID/EX for the load data via fwd_mem_wb, I'd need to preserve that data somehow. But if I keep the LOAD stalled in EX/MEM and invalidate MEM/WB, there's nothing to forward from anyway since the previous instruction already retired. This is a specific edge case that complicates simplification.\n\nLet me try a different angle: macro-op fusion of LUI+ADDI for the load-32-bit-immediate idiom, collapsing both into a single retirement cycle since RV32I doesn't have a direct load-imm32 instruction.\n\nI'd need to peek at PC+4 during the ID stage of LUI to check if the next instruction is a matching ADDI, then fuse them and retire both via separate RVFI channels in the same cycle. But this requires a prefetch buffer, which adds complexity and regressed before.\n\nAnother structural idea: using both clock edges of a single-port SSRAM to read rs1 and rs2 sequentially per cycle, halving regfile area. But that doubles the clock load on the regfile and likely kills Fmax.\n\nI think I'll go with the MEM-stage early regfile write with eliminated MEM/WB forwarding — it's risky but a legitimate structural proposal.\n\nActually, reconsidering: what if I place a second write port driven from EX/MEM.alu_result for non-LOAD ops, writing one cycle earlier? LOADs still use the WB path, so MEM/WB forwarding is only needed for loads. Or simpler: add an early-commit path specifically for JAL/JALR instructions, since their rd value (PC+4) is known at EX and they're frequent in call-heavy code (~5-10% of CoreMark).\n\nThe JAL/JALR approach is minimal—just a mux at the regfile write-data input, with the value already available from in.pc in ID/EX. But adding a second write port means area overhead, and a priority mux on a single port creates a conflict: if a JAL is in EX and another instruction is in WB the same cycle, both try to write simultaneously. I'd need a second port to avoid that, or stick with single-port writes from WB—which is already how it works, since the JAL result is pre-computed in EX and stored in EX/MEM.alu_result anyway.\n\nSo that's a dead end. Instead, I'm going to propose writing the regfile from the MEM stage to eliminate the MEM/WB forward path, but I need to be careful: I'll only drive the write-data from EX/MEM.alu_result for non-LOAD operations, leaving LOADs to commit normally at WB. This keeps the load_data cone off the bypass critical path. The tradeoff is arbitrating between MEM and WB stage writes to the same port—each cycle, only one instruction can write, so I need to prioritize which stage gets the port.\n\nThe solution is to split the write responsibility: MEM stage commits non-LOAD results directly from EX/MEM.alu_result, while WB stage commits LOAD results from MEM/WB.read_data. Since these are different instruction types flowing through different cycles, there's no actual conflict on the single write port. The forward unit still needs MEM/WB forwarding for LOAD results, but now it can be simplified to only activate when MEM/WB contains a LOAD write.\n\nHowever, implementing this with a single muxed write port (gating writes based on instruction type and stage) adds mux logic that might offset the Fmax gains from removing the WB-stage mux. The added complexity and LUT cost could wash out the benefit, so I'm reconsidering whether a simpler structural approach might be better.\n\nI'm exploring a few other angles—like parallelizing the forward unit's comparison logic or speculating dmem access earlier in the pipeline—but each has its own drawbacks. After weighing the tradeoffs, I'm settling on the dual-write-port scheme as my final proposal: it's structural, targets the MEM/WB forward path directly, and while risky, it offers a concrete Fmax improvement if the regfile can support it.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decefe4010019tC0KIU1U1c58p","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","messageID":"msg_decee8219001DgcPr80jsYQtFI"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777796680172,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"id":"prt_decefd2d5001HH0dmWbZZlfPPE","messageID":"msg_decee8219001DgcPr80jsYQtFI","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","type":"text","text":"Given the lessons and my analysis, I see that structural predictor attempts have repeatedly failed (r1s2, r2s2, r3s2, r6s2, r7s2, r10s2). The EX pre-flop cone is the known binding path (r10s1 lesson). The key winning pattern (r4s2) was \"commit something one stage earlier via the existing redirect net.\" Let me apply that pattern to register writeback.\n\nCurrently, the MEM/WB forwarding path feeds a 3:1 forward mux at EX's head: `fwd_mem_wb = wb_w_data` = `ctrl.mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result` (a 2:1 mux sitting on MEM/WB flop output, which then feeds a 3:1 forward mux in EX). This serializes 2 mux levels on a hot operand path.\n\nThe structural insight: for **non-LOAD** writers (ALU / JAL / JALR / LUI / AUIPC — i.e. `!mem_to_reg`), the alu_result is ALREADY flopped in EX/MEM one cycle earlier. If we commit those writes to the regfile from EX/MEM (not WB), they land in the regfile one cycle sooner. Write-first bypass in ID then delivers the value to readers two-behind, making the MEM/WB forward path redundant for non-LOAD values. LOAD writes still go through the normal WB path (since their data only becomes available in MEM).","time":{"start":1777796633301,"end":1777796680172}}}
