{"type":"text","timestamp":1777796688652,"sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","part":{"id":"prt_decf09354001wUYrSThjPesT0t","messageID":"msg_decf08a67001sWPqJWPuUjPP22","sessionID":"ses_213167788ffeQx47yhBw8fe9sB","type":"text","text":"I've written the hypothesis. Summary of the structural proposal:\n\n**Split-origin regfile commit** — non-LOAD writers (ALU/JAL/JALR/LUI/AUIPC, ~65-75% of CoreMark instructions) commit to the regfile from the EX/MEM boundary, one cycle earlier than today. LOADs continue to commit at WB as now.\n\n**Why it should help:**\n- Eliminates `wb_stage`'s 2:1 `mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result` mux from the EX-stage forward mux tail (the `fwd_mem_wb` leg), removing one LUT level from the known-binding EX pre-flop cone (r10s1 lesson).\n- Non-LOAD values reach the regfile one cycle earlier, so the MEM/WB forward path becomes LOAD-only and its data source simplifies to `MEM/WB.read_data` directly.\n- Applies the r4s2-winning pattern (\"commit one stage earlier, share the existing net\") to the regfile commit path.\n\n**Why it avoids known tarpits:**\n- No `id_ex_t` field add/rename (r7s0/r10s0 formal tarpit).\n- No changes to fetch-redirect cone (r4s0/r5s1/r8s0).\n- No regfile reset/init changes (r3s0/r4s0/r5s0/r6s1).\n- No new predictor storage (r2s2/r3s2/r6s2/r7s2/r10s2).\n- Unlike r3s1, the new mux is NOT inserted into the load_data cone — the non-LOAD write arm uses the already-flopped `EX/MEM.alu_result`.\n\nConfidence set to **low** given the density of recent structural regressions and the subtlety of write-port arbitration; expected delta +4%.","time":{"start":1777796682580,"end":1777796688651}}}
