{"type":"text","timestamp":1777798546583,"sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","part":{"id":"prt_ded0cf925001XshOrCyUko47O4","messageID":"msg_ded086c8b001RBWTbsrxnOcVvV","sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","type":"text","text":"Looking at the recent outcomes and LESSONS, I need to propose a **structural** hypothesis that avoids the predictor tarpit (r3s2/r7s2/r10s2/r11s2 all regressed), avoids id_ex struct field renames (r7s0), avoids \"struct-field deletion causes placement churn\" (r11s0), and avoids the EX/PC redirect cone's placement optimum (r8s0/r9s2).\n\nThe LESSONS at r11s2 explicitly suggest pivoting toward non-predictor Fmax/area wins. Let me grep for any forward-unit prior attempts before committing.","time":{"start":1777798543653,"end":1777798546582}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777798546623,"sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01AdT6t5EuXdCgzayK1G5vp5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -c \"forward\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null || echo \"no log\"","description":"Search for prior forward_unit attempts"},"output":"19\n","metadata":{"output":"19\n","exit":0,"description":"Search for prior forward_unit attempts","truncated":false},"title":"Search for prior forward_unit attempts","time":{"start":1777798546617,"end":1777798546620}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the structural category, I'm seeing a clear pattern where all the predictor-based attempts have hit dead ends. The micro-optimizations on critical paths keep causing regressions, so the guidance is pointing me toward abandoning the predictor approach entirely and focusing instead on non-predictor solutions for Fmax or area improvements in the slot-2 diversity work.\n\nThe most promising untried angles are hazard-unit stall-disjunct simplification, ALU micro-opts that haven't been explored yet, and dmem-related optimizations. I'm also noticing the decoder's case statement structure—with its deep combinational logic and the is_illegal default that gets cleared in each arm—could be a bottleneck feeding into the id_stage and hazard_unit. Restructuring it to compute is_illegal in parallel using direct bit patterns might shorten the critical path feeding into the stall logic.\n\nLooking at the load-use hazard detection, the rs1/rs2 fields come directly from instruction bits, so they're already off the decoder cone. The real constraint is the MEM stage's load-data shift-and-sign-extend path, which r3s1 identified as the critical bottleneck. I'm considering whether we can pre-compute or partially extract the byte-select logic earlier, perhaps at the EX stage using address bits, to move some of that work off the MEM critical path.\n\nThe current barrel shifter approach might not be optimizing as well as expected, and while an explicit 4-way byte mux could help, r6s0 showed that naive implementations break on misaligned accesses. I need to find a structural change that maintains bit-exact equivalence across all address alignments without adding risky modifications to the ex_mem_t struct, which has caused regressions before.\n\nLooking at the hazard_unit, it's already fairly lean—the load-use detection is just a 5-bit compare on register indices plus a memory-read flag, and the stall logic checks dmem_ready against flopped control signals. The RVFI path is purely combinational muxes from the mem_wb register, so that's minimal too. The imm_gen does a lot of bit permutation for J and B immediates, but r8s2 showed that duplicating the J-imm adder at the IF stage caused regressions. I'm considering whether merging the decoder with imm_gen in the id_stage could help, since both operate on the instruction and feed into the id_ex register anyway.\n\nThe ALU's 19 cases are a potential target—I could split it into logical groups like arithmetic, logic, shift, multiply, and divide, each as a small combinational block, then mux the results by opcode bits. But r9s0's experience warns that restructuring Yosys-CSE'd cones often backfires. Moving the regfile to dual-port BRAM doesn't work well on GW2AR based on past attempts. The dmem write-mask computation is already mostly handled—mem_width is in the control struct, and r10s1 showed that moving wdata_rep to the EX stage caused regressions due to structural churn. I've also seen split-origin regfile commits fail. One angle I haven't fully explored yet is flattening the ctrl_t struct into discrete signals throughout the pipeline, though that's a larger refactor with uncertain payoff.\n\nLooking at what's likely the new critical path after the JAL fast-path: probably the EX redirect feeding the PC register, which chains through branch comparison, ALU subtraction, the redirect signal, and into the PC mux. Or there's the forwarding loop—ALU result flopped into EX/MEM, then through the forward_unit's match logic and operand mux back into the ALU, then flopped again. The forward_unit currently does ID/EX and EX/MEM address matching combinationally to select which forwarded value to use. I'm wondering if I could pre-decode at the ID stage which forward path will be needed, but that's tricky since we don't know what EX/MEM.rd will be until the current ID instruction reaches EX. I'm realizing the forward unit actually compares the current EX instruction's source registers against the rd values of instructions already in MEM and WB stages. If I shift this comparison one stage earlier to the ID cycle, I can pre-compute the forward select signals using id_ex.rd and ex_mem.rd, then register those 2-bit selects into the id_ex pipeline stage to use during EX. This moves the compare logic out of the critical EX path—leaving just the mux and ALU—but risks extending ID's setup time and growing the id_ex struct, so I need to check if the timing trade-off actually helps on this design.\n\nThe real complication is that stalls and flushes break the assumption: during a load-use stall, id_ex holds for a cycle making the pre-computed selects stale, and data memory stalls shift the pipeline structure entirely. This optimization is cleaner in theory than in practice, so I should explore a simpler approach instead.\n\nWhat if I fuse the writeback mux into the MEM stage itself — compute mem_to_reg combinationally there and store just the selected result in the MEM/WB register instead of both alu_result and read_data? That saves 32 bits in the register, but the problem is the mux input (load_data) sits on the critical path of the load-data shift/sign-extend cone feeding into the MEM/WB flop, so this regresses timing. I could try other structural angles like inlining the hazard unit's load-use detection or adding a skid register in the dmem write path, but these either don't help or add complexity.\n\nSplitting EX into two stages would require reworking the entire forward/hazard network. Registering regfile reads to make it synchronous would add a cycle and create formal issues. Removing the forward_unit module entirely by inlining it into ex_stage doesn't help since Yosys flattens anyway. The IF-stage redirect FIFO was already tried and regressed. So I'm looking for genuinely new structural moves — maybe something like moving the MEM-stage load alignment (byte shift and sign-extend) to arrive combinationally with dmem_rdata and then writing it directly to the regfile through a bypass path, completely skipping the MEM/WB register for loads.\n\nBut that's too exotic. The MEM/WB register could theoretically be eliminated for non-load instructions, letting ALU results write directly from EX/MEM to the regfile, but that's essentially what r11s1 tried with split-origin commit and it regressed.\n\nThe lessons mention \"hazard-unit stall-disjunct simplification\" as a concrete direction. Looking at the hazard unit logic, I notice the stall and flush signals have some redundancy — stall_id includes both dmem_stall and load_use_hazard, while flush_id gates those same conditions differently depending on whether dmem_stall is active. There might be an opportunity to simplify these disjunctions and reduce the logic depth. The simplified form `next = dmem_stall ? reg_q : (load_use || redirect ? 0 : new)` is structurally equivalent to the priority-based approach—both are optimal 3-state muxes. But looking at the PC-CE cone, I notice `load_use_hazard` pulls in combinational register select bits directly from the instruction memory output, which puts it on the critical path from imem-read through hazard detection to the PC clock enable. On GW2AR, the CE path might actually be the bottleneck since Yosys converts CE gating into a mux on the D input rather than using the flop's native CE, so reducing signals on that cone could help timing.\n\nThe `id_ex_rd != 5'b0` check is necessary though—removing it would cause spurious stalls on loads to x0, which are semantically valid prefetches. The hazard unit itself doesn't have much room to simplify further. I'm considering whether decoupling the instruction memory from the PC register with a small FIFO could absorb stalls, but that's essentially a regression to an earlier design. Pipelining the hazard outputs would break correctness. Let me shift focus to the data memory path instead—the memory stage computes the address combinationally from the ALU result in the EX/MEM register.\n\nNow I'm looking at the load extraction pipeline: the data arrives from memory, gets shifted by the byte offset, then sign-extended based on the load width. That's about 3 LUT levels of depth. I could optimize this by precomputing byte selects in the execute stage so the memory stage just does a 4:1 byte mux and 2:1 halfword mux, trading the barrel shifter for simpler multiplexing. But the formal verification from earlier showed that touching this path causes divergence on misaligned addresses, even when gated. To preserve equivalence, I'd need to use byte-addressable muxing that produces the exact same shifted values.\n\nThe right shift `dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0]*8)` with zero fill isn't a rotation—it's a specific shift that zeros out the upper bits. For a 32-bit word with shift amounts of 0, 8, 16, or 24, this gives predictable results. A naive byte/halfword mux approach breaks on misaligned accesses like addr[1:0]=1 or 3, where the halfword selection would try to read beyond the word boundary. To match the original behavior exactly, I'd need generalized byte-level shifting that handles these edge cases, but that gets complicated when the requested data spans beyond available bits.\n\nThe simpler approach is what the current code already does: compute the full shifted value once, then extract the byte and halfword lanes from it. Yosys should synthesize this efficiently, so there's probably nothing to optimize here.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture, the WB stage is essentially just wiring data through—it could be combined with the regfile write since they're already tightly coupled. For structural improvements, I'm considering reorganizing the MEM stage to register the address earlier and remove rarely-used fields from the ex_mem_t struct, but prior attempts at struct removal caused regressions. Other ideas like an early-commit path for move instructions or relocating immediate generation into decode don't seem viable given the single-issue pipeline constraints.\n\nStepping back at what's actually worked: r1s0 won by collapsing three multipliers into one, and r4s2 won by resolving unconditional JAL earlier. Most predictor tweaks and micro-optimizations have either regressed or broken formal verification. I've already ruled out collapsing the branch comparator into the ALU (r2s0 tried it), folding JALR into the ALU path (r5s1 broke), and pipeline register elimination for non-loads.\n\nNow I'm exploring whether the forwarding unit could be restructured to produce operand values directly instead of select signals—replacing the current select-to-mux chain with a combinational OR/AND tree that outputs the live register value. This is structurally equivalent but might have different LUT organization that Yosys could optimize differently.\n\nI'm also considering moving the load alignment sign-extend mux to run in parallel with the shift rather than serially after it, computing all possible shifted and extended values at once then muxing by funct3—trades area for potentially shallower logic depth.\n\nNow looking at the hazard unit's stall and flush logic more carefully. The flush_id signal combines load-use hazards with redirects, and I'm tracing through how stall_id and flush_id interact across different scenarios to see if there's redundancy or a simpler formulation that could reduce gate count.\n\nAnalyzing the register update logic...\n\nthe two control signals—flush_id and stall_id—each require about two LUT levels to compute, and the mux itself adds another two levels. I could try rephrasing this with freeze, fire_bubble, and fire_capture signals, but Yosys would likely synthesize to the same depth anyway, so there's probably no real gain there.\n\nMerging the IF and ID stages into one module wouldn't help either since there's no actual register between them—the payload flows combinationally, so the tools would flatten it anyway.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a structural change worth exploring: what if I moved the JAL target computation to the IF side, pre-registering it with the new PC after a redirect? But r8s2 already tried that approach and it actually made things worse.\n\nLet me focus on what's not critical right now and could be rearranged to shorten the actual critical path. The EX redirect feeding back to the PC is looking like the main bottleneck.\n\nI'm seeing five candidate paths competing for criticality: the EX redirect through branch condition logic, the ID-side JAL prediction through opcode decode and immediate addition, instruction decode feeding into the ID/EX flop, the ALU result into the EX/MEM flop, and the data memory read into the MEM/WB flop. After r4s2, the EX redirect and instruction decode paths are fighting for the PC redirect slot while the JAL path runs alongside them.\n\nOne idea is splitting EX into a dedicated branch-resolve stage and a separate ALU stage, but that adds a pipeline stage and increases mispredict penalty—probably a net loss. Another angle: pre-compute whether a branch is taken at the ID stage using the stale register values plus forwarding, so by the time we reach EX the decision is already registered. The catch is that rs1 and rs2 aren't fully resolved at ID without forwarding from later stages, so I'd either need to add forwarding at ID or compute branch_taken at EX but using the previous cycle's inputs.\n\nI'm exploring whether to restructure the EX stage's redirect output with a parallel comparator for branch-taken and dedicated adders for the target, but that feels like micro-optimization. Pipelining the multiplier/divider behind a handshake didn't help before. Removing the rs1_val and rs2_val fields from ex_mem_t by recomputing them adds complexity rather than saving it. Looking at the actual struct sizes, ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t carry a lot of RVFI-tracking fields, and past attempts to strip branch_taken and branch_target caused placement churn. Now I'm considering whether to eliminate the MEM/WB register entirely and commit directly to the regfile from EX/MEM.\n\nThis would collapse the pipeline from 5 stages to 4 by muxing ALU result versus loaded data in the MEM cycle, with load forwarding handled in-cycle. Branch misprediction penalty drops by 1, potentially improving CoreMark IPC by 5-10%, but the MEM stage now does combinational load-data plus regfile write, which likely reduces Fmax. Load-use hazards still cause 1 bubble, and r3s1 and r11s1 showed that moving write-commit earlier regresses. Actually, a 4-stage pipeline wouldn't reduce branch bubble count—a taken branch still flushes everything younger—so the only savings is 1 cycle of pipeline length, which doesn't translate to fewer bubbles. Since r4s2's JAL fast-path already eliminates the JAL bubble, regular branches and JALR still cause 2-bubble flushes. I'm now looking at a simpler angle: merging the MEM and WB pipeline registers into a single stage, though they're already mostly separate with combinational write-data paths.\n\nThe lessons suggest focusing on dmem cone, untried ALU micro-opts, and hazard-unit simplification. The dmem critical path through load-data is hard to shorten—r3s1 failed on the pre-flop mux series, r6s0 on byte-mux divergence. For ALU micro-opts, I've tried bit-reverse SLL, branch-through-sub, and iterative DIV, all of which regressed. What I haven't explored is reducing the 19-case ALU statement into fewer hierarchical tiers or splitting the ALU into independent sub-units like arithmetic, logic, and shift operations.\n\nBut looking at the actual code, Yosys already compiles each case arm independently with a shared mux—there's no structural gain from reorganizing. Pre-computing results and muxing by op is already happening. The one angle I'm considering is moving LUI outside the ALU entirely since it just passes the immediate through, but that would require rerouting the immediate generation and might not save anything meaningful.\n\nActually, I'm realizing that trying to eliminate the LUI case by forcing alu_a to zero or using a different ALU operation just trades one control bit for another—no real win. Even dropping it to the writeback stage would need a new mux and control signal.\n\nLet me step back and try something genuinely different: what if I introduce a second retirement channel for specific instruction pairs, like piggybacking register-register ALU operations on top of load instructions when there's no data dependency? That would be actual superscalar behavior.\n\nBut that's risky and massive in scope. Let me consider a different angle instead: restructuring the pipeline to eliminate redundant forwarding in the store path. I'm noticing that write_data and rs2_val are both storing the same post-forwarded rs2 value—they're duplicate 32-bit fields that could potentially be collapsed. Though I remember from r11s0 that removing redundant fields caused regressions, so this is tricky. Let me trace through the code more carefully to see if they're truly identical or if there's a subtle difference I'm missing.\n\nActually, looking at the semantics, they are the same post-forward rs2. Yosys should already merge them if they're driven by the same net. But given the placement churn risk from before, leaving them alone is probably the safer call.\n\nSo let me focus on something genuinely low-risk: pipelining the dmem access by splitting MEM into a request stage that drives the memory ports and a response stage that captures the read data. This would give the BRAM more time and potentially increase Fmax since the load-data critical path would span two cycles instead of one. The tradeoff is deeper pipeline, longer load-use hazard, and needing more forwarding paths, but the io_dmemReady contract should still hold.\n\nThough honestly, this would likely tank CoreMark IPC with 2-cycle load-use stalls on every load-use pair. That's probably not worth it.\n\nLet me consider something more targeted instead: gating the dmem address generation behind a valid signal so we only drive addresses on actual LOAD/STORE cycles instead of every cycle. Currently dmem_addr is always driven by alu_result, which might be creating unnecessary switching activity or timing pressure. Or maybe try re-encoding the ALU op field to a more compact representation that simplifies the case mux, though Yosys should already be optimizing that anyway.\n\nActually, I think the real angle here is to register the forward_unit's select outputs into the ID/EX stage to shorten the operand mux cone in EX. That's only 4 FFs versus the 32 that link_val would've needed, so the area cost is much lower. The tricky part is handling stalls correctly and not violating the rule about only appending to id_ex_t.\n\nLet me trace through the timing: at cycle C-1 during ID, I can compare the incoming instruction's rs1 against both the rd that's about to enter EX/MEM and the rd currently in MEM/WB, then flop those select signals into id_ex. By cycle C when that instruction reaches EX, the selects are already computed and ready to drive the mux, which moves the critical path earlier in the pipeline. The stall behavior should work out because when dmem_stall holds id_ex, ex_mem also holds, keeping the forwarding logic consistent. When a dmem stall holds the pipeline, the pre-computed forwarding selects from two cycles ago remain valid because the register destinations stay constant in the held stages—ex_mem.rd and mem_wb.rd don't change, so they match what the selector was computed against. An EX redirect at the previous cycle would...\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to move the forwarding logic entirely into the ID stage as combinational logic, comparing the current instruction's source registers against the flopped destination registers from id_ex and ex_mem, rather than keeping a separate forward_unit in the EX stage. This avoids the threading complexity and keeps the select signals tightly coupled to where they're needed.\n\nThe trade-off is that id_stage now needs visibility into id_ex.rd and id_ex.ctrl.reg_write (and their ex_mem counterparts) to compute the selects, which means plumbing the id_ex_t struct type back into id_stage. But the payoff is cleaner: I register just the 2-bit select signals into id_ex, then use those flopped selects in the EX-stage operand mux instead of the combinational forward_unit output, shortening the critical path from compare→select→mux→ALU down to just mux→ALU.\n\nThe risks are real though—ID setup time grows with the compare logic, I'm adding 4 flops, and I need to trace through all the stall and flush scenarios to make sure the registered selects stay coherent. If the EX operand cone wasn't actually the bottleneck, this buys nothing.\n\nBut looking at the actual critical path: the forward select comes from comparing three flopped address signals through 1-2 LUT levels, feeding into the 3:1 mux. Moving those compares into the ID stage shifts the logic from the EX cone (compare → mux → ALU → flop) into the ID cone (decoder → flop), and ID has more slack than EX. The ALU path is still in series with the mux, so if I can shorten the mux select computation, I free up time for the ALU and flop setup.\n\nThe key question is whether this actually helps—I need to verify that EX is binding and ID has room. At cycle C-1, I'm computing the forward select for instruction I using its rs1_addr from the current instruction, while id_ex holds I-1's destination and ex_mem holds I-2's destination, so the data is available when I need it.\n\nOne catch: I also need to check the reg_write enable bits to avoid forwarding from instructions that don't write, so I'd need to route id_ex.ctrl.reg_write and ex_mem.ctrl.reg_write into the ID stage along with the register addresses. The implementation would add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel to the id_ex struct, pass those select signals through to EX, and remove the forward_unit from the critical path.\n\nBut there's a timing risk I need to think through — if the pipeline stalls or flushes between ID and EX, the ex_mem register state could change, making my pre-computed select signals invalid.\n\nLet me trace through the cases: normally when instruction I reaches EX, I-1 is in MEM, so I compare I's source registers against I-1's destination. But if ex_mem stalls while id_ex advances (or vice versa), the instruction in the MEM stage shifts, and my select bits computed from the old ex_mem state no longer match what's actually there.\n\nActually, wait — if dmem_stall holds ex_mem, it also holds id_ex, so I and I-1 stay in their respective stages. The select was computed from id_ex.rd at the previous cycle, but now ex_mem.rd is stale. That's the mismatch I need to resolve. I need to step back and think about this more carefully. The key insight is that the forwarding unit needs to produce the correct output at cycle C, and my pre-computed select should match what a combinational unit would compute at that exact moment. Let me trace through what's actually available at cycle C: the rs address from the flopped id_ex register and the rd signals from ex_mem, then verify this matches my pre-computation from the prior cycle.\n\nThe problem is that all three inputs to the comparator depend on stall signals from C-1, so to pre-compute the result at C-1, I'd need to predict which stall conditions will hold and compute both possible outcomes, then mux them. But that's actually adding more logic rather than saving it—I'm duplicating the stall logic just to move the comparison earlier. The simpler approach might be to only pre-compute for the normal case and fall back to combinational forwarding when stalls occur, though that's also more complex. I'm realizing the current combinational forwarding unit is already giving me exactly what I need at cycle C, and trying to move it earlier just creates more overhead.\n\nLet me step back and try a completely different structural approach. What if I add a dedicated commit register between the WB stage and the regfile to decouple the write? No, that adds a cycle of latency. Or what about making regfile writes gate-free by always writing, with waddr='0 when not needed? That doesn't really help either, and it goes against the principle of keeping the write domain narrow.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the RVFI constraint is the real blocker here. If I always write but gate the address to 0, RVFI still sees the same effective writes because it's driven from mem_wb.ctrl.reg_write, not the regfile's internal w_en signal. So that might avoid a gate at the flop level, though Yosys probably already CSEs this anyway.\n\nLet me just commit to something concrete: the simplest untried structural change is to replace the 2:1 mux for redirect targets at the core level by moving the muxing logic directly into the control path.\n\nActually, I keep circling back to the same problem. Let me try a different angle: flattening the id_ex_t struct fields into individual flops at the core-top level instead of keeping them packed. It's a pure refactor that shouldn't change behavior, but it might help Yosys avoid the bit-offset sensitivity issues I saw earlier. Risky because formal flows can be sensitive to struct ordering, but it could improve placement.\n\nThe real insight I'm having now is about the forward-select pre-registration: at any cycle, I want fwd_rs1_sel to compare the current id_ex.rs1 against ex_mem.rd and mem_wb.rd. The field gets flopped through id_ex, so I need to handle stalls carefully—when id_ex holds, the forwarding selector should also hold, and only update on normal advance.\n\nWhen stall_id is asserted without a flush, id_ex.fwd_rs1_sel stays frozen at its previous value. The question is whether that frozen value remains correct. If the stall is due to dmem_stall, then ex_mem also holds, so ex_mem.rd and mem_wb.rd don't change—meaning the held forwarding selector is still valid for the current cycle. The comparison targets haven't moved, so the old decision still applies. fwd_sel@C-1. That was based on the state at C-2 when I was about to enter EX.\n- Hmm. Let me unroll.\n\nSuppose I enters EX at cycle C0 (normal). id_ex.fwd_sel@C0 was computed at C0-1 based on if_id.rs@C0-1 (= I's rs addr) and id_ex.rd@C0-1 (= I-1's rd), ex_mem.rd@C0-1 (= I-2's rd).\n\nAt C0, ex_mem.rd@C0 = I-1's rd (normal capture at C0 edge = id_ex.rd@C0-1). mem_wb.rd@C0 = I-2's rd (= ex_mem.rd@C0-1). So pre-computed select matches correctly.\n\nNow at C0, a dmem_stall starts (because I-1 is a LOAD waiting on bus). id_ex@C0+1 = id_ex@C0 = I. ex_mem@C0+1 = ex_mem@C0 = I-1. mem_wb partial-held with mem_wb.rd = ex_mem.rd@C0 = I-2.\n\nAt C0+1, we want fwd_sel vs (ex_mem.rd@C0+1 = I-1's rd, mem_wb.rd@C0+1 = I-2's rd). The held fwd_sel from C0 was computed against (I-1, I-2). Still matches! ✓\n\nAt C0+1 during stall: if we pre-compute new fwd_sel, it'd be based on I's rs compared against I-1's rd and I-2's rd—which is exactly what we need. The key insight is that fwd_sel should always compare the instruction entering EX against the current MEM and WB occupants, so at the C-1 side we compute using if_id.rs@C-1 (the incoming instruction's source) versus id_ex.rd@C-1 and ex_mem.rd@C-1 (the current pipeline stages that will shift forward at the clock edge). During a stall, id_ex holds I and the pre-computed select remains valid since I's operands haven't changed. When the load-use stall inserts a bubble into id_ex, I need to recompute the forwarding selector for the actual instruction when it arrives next cycle. At that point, the bubble occupies EX while the load moves to MEM, so comparing the instruction's source register against ex_mem.rd (the load's destination) produces a match, correctly selecting the EX_MEM forward path. By the next cycle, this forwarding selector is valid for the instruction now in id_ex, directing it to pull its source value from the load result in ex_mem.\n\nrd. The pre-computation approach holds up—I should move forward with implementing it.\n\nActually, I need to trace through the redirect case more carefully. When an EX redirect fires at cycle C-1, the flush happens at the C edge, so id_ex captures a bubble while the next instruction enters the pipeline. For that next instruction's forwarding computation at cycle C, I need to verify what's actually in ex_mem.rd at that moment—it should still contain the previous instruction's register destination before the flush takes effect. B's info flows into ex_mem at C, and I+1 enters ID at the same cycle. When computing forwarding for I+1's rs1, the mem_wb stage will have B's rd available, so if they match and B writes to a register, forwarding selects the mem_wb path correctly. I'm also verifying the edge cases—at reset, all forwarding signals compute to zero safely, and the mem_wb data path uses the combinational output from the write-back mux, which is clean. Let me also pre-compute the mem_wb forwarding prediction based on what's currently in ex_mem before it advances.\n\nNow I'm settling on the implementation details: I'll add two fields to the id_ex pipeline register for the forwarding selects, compute them in the ID stage using ex_mem's control signals (which I'll wire in), consume them in the EX stage, and remove the separate forward_unit module entirely.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded0cffe2001QBjpYAsNGkllco","sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","messageID":"msg_ded086c8b001RBWTbsrxnOcVvV"}}
