{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777798654190,"sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_012TQLBuCjtv1vTYtLauWpXX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r12s1\ntitle: \"Pre-register forward_unit selects into id_ex to shorten EX operand-mux cone\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  After r1s0 landed the shared 33x33 multiplier, the EX-stage operand\n  cone is the next plausible Fmax limiter on a cycle where a MUL/MULH\n  is in EX: `forward_unit compare -> 3:1 operand mux -> ALU -> EX/MEM\n  flop D`. The forward_unit's 5-bit rd-vs-rs compare plus the 2-bit\n  priority encode adds ~1-2 LUT levels in series with the 3:1 data\n  mux that feeds alu_a/alu_b. LESSONS explicitly direct slot-2\n  diversity work away from predictors (r3s2/r7s2/r10s2/r11s2 all\n  regressed) toward non-predictor Fmax wins; the forward-mux cone\n  has never been directly targeted on the consumer side (r11s1 tried\n  producer-side split-origin commit, which LESSONS noted does not\n  shorten the consumer cone). This targets the consumer side.\nhypothesis: |\n  Move the forward_unit comparators from EX-cycle combinational to ID-\n  cycle combinational, registering the resulting 2-bit rs1/rs2 selects\n  through id_ex. At ID cycle C-1 the pipeline-register state\n  (id_ex.rd@C-1, id_ex.ctrl.reg_write@C-1, ex_mem.rd@C-1,\n  ex_mem.ctrl.reg_write@C-1) is exactly what will become\n  (ex_mem.rd@C, ex_mem.reg_write@C, mem_wb.rd@C, mem_wb.reg_write@C)\n  under normal advance or under dmem_stall (both id_ex and ex_mem\n  hold together, so the held fwd_sel remains valid). Load-use and\n  EX-redirect trigger flush_id, which zeros id_ex including the new\n  fwd_sel fields — the bubble's rs_addr=0/rs_val=0 make the zeroed\n  select correct. Concretely:\n    1. core_pkg.sv: APPEND fwd_rs1_sel[1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel[1:0] to\n       the END of id_ex_t (per r7s0: append, never rename/reorder).\n    2. id_stage.sv: accept four new inputs (id_ex_rd, id_ex_rw,\n       ex_mem_rd, ex_mem_rw) wired from core.sv's existing id_ex_w\n       and ex_mem_w signals. Compute fwd_sel combinationally on\n       if_id.instr[19:15] / [24:20] and those inputs with the same\n       priority (EX_MEM > MEM_WB > none) the current forward_unit\n       uses, and flop into id_ex alongside the existing fields.\n    3. ex_stage.sv: remove the fwd_rs1_sel / fwd_rs2_sel ports, and\n       consume in.fwd_rs1_sel / in.fwd_rs2_sel from the id_ex struct\n       directly in the existing 3:1 operand mux. The EX operand cone\n       becomes just `flopped-select -> 3:1 mux -> ALU`, eliminating\n       the compare+priority-encode levels.\n    4. core.sv: remove the forward_unit instance and its wires;\n       route id_ex_w.rd, id_ex_w.ctrl.reg_write, ex_mem_w.rd,\n       ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into u_id.\n    5. forward_unit.sv: delete the file (or leave empty — Yosys will\n       elide an unused module).\n  Appending 4 bits to id_ex_t (vs r4s1's 32 bits) is an order of\n  magnitude smaller flop/routing burden, and the new wires into\n  u_id (4 flopped signals, each short-reach from the existing top-\n  level nets) are routing-cheap on GW2AR. The cone this shortens is\n  genuinely in-series (compare feeds the 3:1 select, which is the\n  gate that commits data-mux output to alu_a/b), so the LUT-level\n  reclaim is real — unlike r9s0's bit-reverse SLL fold where the\n  \"redundant\" cone was already Yosys-CSE'd.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"APPEND fwd_rs1_sel[1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel[1:0] fields to the END of id_ex_t (never renaming/reordering existing fields). Total id_ex_t width grows by 4 bits.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add four new inputs (id_ex_rd[4:0], id_ex_rw, ex_mem_rd[4:0], ex_mem_rw). Compute fwd_rs1_sel / fwd_rs2_sel combinationally with the same EX_MEM>MEM_WB>none priority the current forward_unit uses, keyed on if_id.instr[19:15]/[24:20]. Flop the two 2-bit selects into id_ex alongside the existing fields.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Remove fwd_rs1_sel / fwd_rs2_sel input ports. The existing 3:1 operand mux now indexes from in.fwd_rs1_sel / in.fwd_rs2_sel read directly from the id_ex struct (already flopped a cycle earlier). No change to the ALU or EX/MEM capture logic.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Remove the u_fwd (forward_unit) instance and its wiring. Add four wires from the existing id_ex_w and ex_mem_w signals (id_ex_w.rd, id_ex_w.ctrl.reg_write, ex_mem_w.rd, ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write) into u_id's new inputs. Remove the fwd_rs?_sel port connections from u_ex.\"\n  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n    description: \"Delete the file (Yosys will not see it after core.sv drops the instance). Alternatively leave the module in place with no instantiation; DCE is automatic.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"If the existing cocotb test probes forward_unit signals by name, update the probe names to the new id_ex.fwd_rs?_sel path; otherwise no change required. RVFI port set and retirement semantics are untouched.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777798654174,"end":1777798654189}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm exploring whether pre-registering the forward_unit selects into the id_ex stage could work—this approach hasn't been tried before, and it's promising because it only adds 4 bits to id_ex (much smaller than the 32-bit failure in r4s1) while safely appending fields rather than renaming them.\n\nThe key insight is that this targets the EX operand mux cone on the consumer side, avoiding the problematic fetch-redirect and MEM load-data paths that have been tarpit zones. The routing concern is real—moving the address comparison into id_stage means bringing id_ex.rd, id_ex.ctrl.reg_write, ex_mem.rd, and ex_mem.ctrl.reg_write into id_stage—but these signals already exist as inputs to the hazard_unit and top-level RVFI, so the wires are already there. The select line routing is a small burden compared to the data-path widening that hurt r4s1. I think this is worth implementing.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded0e461a001yF9TRRhzJzVWse","sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","messageID":"msg_ded0d3505001MOK6WfHTP7yoIS"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777798654191,"sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","part":{"id":"prt_ded0e4376001YtAX2egINirTsU","messageID":"msg_ded0d3505001MOK6WfHTP7yoIS","sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","type":"text","text":"No one has tried pre-registering the forward_unit selects. Given:\n- LESSONS explicitly suggest non-predictor Fmax wins\n- r11s1's split-origin commit touched the producer side (didn't help EX cone); this targets the consumer side\n- r4s1 regressed threading 32 bits through id_ex; this threads only 4 bits\n- r7s0's append-only rule is preserved\n- Stays off the fetch-redirect cone (r8s0/r9s2 tarpit) and the MEM load-data cone (r3s1/r6s0 tarpit)\n\nI'll propose pre-registering the forward_unit's 2-bit selects into id_ex, shortening the EX operand mux's combinational cone.","time":{"start":1777798628214,"end":1777798654191}}}
