{"type":"text","timestamp":1777798663166,"sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","part":{"id":"prt_ded0eb3b4001UidcZtb9GAa9ZS","messageID":"msg_ded0ea9690018XPiJzrVsh1M2R","sessionID":"ses_212f7942affeOT4DsTKU0nvmZ9","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml`.\n\nSummary of the structural angle:\n- **Pre-register forward_unit selects into id_ex** — move the rd-vs-rs comparators from EX-cycle combinational to ID-cycle, flopping the resulting 2-bit selects through id_ex.\n- Shortens the EX operand-mux cone from `compare → priority-encode → 3:1 mux → ALU` to just `flopped-select → 3:1 mux → ALU`.\n- Targets the consumer side (unlike r11s1's producer-side split-origin commit, which LESSONS explicitly called out as not shortening the consumer cone).\n- Appends only 4 bits to id_ex_t (vs r4s1's 32-bit thread that regressed), per r7s0's append-never-rename rule.\n- Stays entirely off the fetch-redirect cone (r8s0/r9s2 tarpit) and the MEM load-data cone (r3s1/r6s0 tarpit), and is not a predictor (avoids the -50% r7s2 class).\n- Correctness verified across stall/flush cases: dmem_stall holds id_ex and ex_mem together (held fwd_sel stays consistent); load-use and redirect flush id_ex to bubble (zeroed fwd_sel is correct for the zero'd rs_addr).\n\nConfidence set to `low` — forward-cone Fmax gains depend on whether the EX operand mux is genuinely binding after r1s0's shared multiplier landed, which can't be confirmed without a post-synth timing report.","time":{"start":1777798656948,"end":1777798663164}}}
