{"type":"text","timestamp":1777799995062,"sessionID":"ses_212de744bffe9Ru5mmX5gKrnXs","part":{"id":"prt_ded228eca0016LNMhhNOHEgUkX","messageID":"msg_ded218c6d001VLAdZHwRe0KkNW","sessionID":"ses_212de744bffe9Ru5mmX5gKrnXs","type":"text","text":"Looking at the situation, I need to find a structural angle that hasn't been tried. The lessons make clear:\n\n- All predictor angles (r1s2, r2s2, r3s2, r7s2, r10s2, r11s2, r12s2) regressed\n- Consumer-side forward-cone restructures (r3s1, r11s1, r12s1) regressed\n- Dead-field removal (r11s0) regressed via placement churn\n- Struct renames / fetch-redirect cone edits are formal tarpits\n- Parallel-to-serial cone collapses regressed (r2s0, r7s1, r8s1, r9s0)\n\nThe winning recipe (r4s2, r1s0) is: **remove work from a critical cone by moving it to a dedicated parallel flop, without touching formal-sensitive surfaces**.\n\nOne untouched structural target: the `ex_mem_mem_op = ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read | ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_write` OR gate computed at core.sv top-level feeds hazard_unit's `dmem_stall` path, which fans out to `stall_if`, `stall_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, `hold_mem_wb` — i.e., to the PC register, ID/EX reset, EX/MEM hold enable, and MEM/WB valid. Precomputing this bit as a dedicated parallel flop in ex_stage removes a LUT level from that high-fanout cone without touching ex_mem_t's packed layout.","time":{"start":1777799958218,"end":1777799995060}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777799995079,"sessionID":"ses_212de744bffe9Ru5mmX5gKrnXs","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01TCX2hawVhTBJT7HNkHscVh","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r13s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r13s1\ntitle: \"Parallel mem_op hint flop — shorten dmem_stall fanout cone without touching ex_mem_t layout\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The predictor search is closed (r6s2/r7s2/r10s2/r11s2/r12s2 all regressed),\n  and consumer-side forward-cone restructures are likewise negative\n  (r3s1/r11s1/r12s1). Non-predictor structural wins must target the\n  hazard/stall network, which feeds a very high-fanout set of flop enables\n  (PC reg hold, ID/EX reset, EX/MEM hold, MEM/WB valid).\n\n  Today, `hazard_unit.dmem_stall = !dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op`, and\n  `ex_mem_mem_op` is a top-level combinational OR:\n      assign ... = ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read | ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_write\n  i.e., the OR sits on two distinct bits of the packed ex_mem_t flop Q,\n  routed across core.sv's top-level glue into hazard_unit, which then ANDs\n  with !dmem_ready and fans out as `stall_if`/`stall_id`/`stall_ex_mem`/\n  `hold_mem_wb` — i.e., into the IF PC-D mux's stall cone that r4s2 showed\n  is Fmax-binding on this fabric, plus the ID/EX reset cone and the EX/MEM\n  capture-enable cone.\n\n  r4s2 won by moving work ONE STAGE EARLIER onto a dedicated parallel flop\n  that rides the existing net (the `redirect` wire) — not by editing a\n  shared struct or reshuffling an already-optimized cone. r11s0 proved that\n  editing ex_mem_t's packed layout (even to delete dead bits) regresses via\n  placement churn, and r12s1 proved that appending to id_ex_t + threading\n  across stages regresses from routing/FF cost. The remaining structural\n  lever is: add a SEPARATE 1-bit flop (not a struct-member edit) whose D-\n  input is a combinational OR of two pre-flop wires already present in\n  ex_stage, and whose Q replaces the top-level OR-of-flop-Qs in core.sv.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  In ex_stage.sv, add a dedicated parallel 1-bit register\n  `ex_mem_mem_op_q` clocked synchronously with (and gated by the same\n  stall/reset as) the existing ex_mem_t flop:\n\n      D-input: (in.ctrl.mem_read | in.ctrl.mem_write) & in.valid & !stall_equiv_kill\n\n  More precisely, mirror the exact enable/reset semantics of reg_q's\n  capture in ex_stage (reset → 0, stall → hold, otherwise capture from\n  `in.ctrl.mem_read | in.ctrl.mem_write`), so the new flop Q equals\n  exactly what `ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read | ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_write` would\n  yield each cycle. Expose `ex_mem_mem_op_q` as a module output\n  (new port; additive).\n\n  In core.sv, replace the top-level combinational\n      assign ... = ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read | ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_write\n  with a direct wire to the new `u_ex.ex_mem_mem_op_q` port. The hazard_unit\n  input `ex_mem_mem_op` keeps its existing name and meaning — only the\n  driver changes from \"OR of two flop bits\" to \"one dedicated flop bit.\"\n\n  Why this should win:\n  1. Removes one LUT level (the 2-input OR) from the dmem_stall fanout\n     cone. The cone currently is:\n        ex_mem_t.ctrl.mem_read Q  ─┐\n                                   OR ── AND (!dmem_ready) ── fanout to\n        ex_mem_t.ctrl.mem_write Q ─┘                          stall_if / stall_id /\n                                                              stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb\n     After:\n        ex_mem_mem_op_q  ──────── AND (!dmem_ready) ── same fanout.\n  2. The new flop is placed inside ex_stage, co-located with the existing\n     ex_mem_t flop cluster, shortening the route to hazard_unit (no\n     top-level glue OR to traverse).\n  3. No ex_mem_t layout change — avoids r11s0's placement-churn class of\n     regression (the packed struct is untouched; the new register is a\n     separate named `logic` bit).\n  4. No id_ex_t edit — avoids r7s0's formal-destabilization class.\n  5. No fetch-redirect cone edit — avoids r4s0/r5s1/r5s2/r6s0/r8s0's\n     formal tarpit.\n  6. No RVFI surface edit — reg_write/rd_wen/rvfi_trap semantics are\n     unchanged; rvfi_order/insn/mem_* are untouched. reg_ch0 BMC anchors\n     (r5s0/r6s1/r10s0 class) are preserved bit-for-bit.\n  7. Adds exactly 1 FF to a 1861-FF fabric (~0.05% FF growth) — well\n     below the r10s1 (36 FF) and r10s2 (33 FF) thresholds that tipped\n     placement/routing.\n\n  Invariant preservation (all explicit):\n  - CLAUDE.md #1 (RVFI 2-channel): untouched — new flop is a hazard-unit\n    input only.\n  - #2 (rvfi_trap iff illegal): unchanged — no decoder/ctrl edit.\n  - #3 (EBREAK-only SYSTEM): unchanged.\n  - #4 (rvfi_order monotonic): untouched — MEM/WB valid logic is unchanged\n    (dmem_stall → hold_mem_wb is bit-identical before/after).\n  - #5 (liveness): preserved — the hold_wb / stall_ex_mem conditions\n    produced by hazard_unit are functionally identical, just one LUT\n    level shallower to evaluate.\n  - #6 (mem bounds): dmem gating at mem_stage is unchanged.\n  - #10 (decoder default illegal): unchanged.\n\n  Scope: exactly two files touched — ex_stage.sv (add output port +\n  parallel 1-bit flop) and core.sv (replace one `assign` with a port\n  wire to u_ex). No struct edits, no cocotb changes required (the ex_mem\n  observable behavior at RVFI retirement is unchanged), no formal config\n  edits.\n\n  Why this has not been attempted: the prior 12 rounds focused on major\n  restructures (predictors, forward-cone, link-value plumbing) or on\n  same-cone mux rewrites. This hypothesis is pure cone-depth reduction\n  on a high-fanout wire (dmem_stall → 4 downstream stall enables) via\n  the r4s2-style parallel-flop pattern, applied to the hazard/stall\n  network rather than the PC-redirect network.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add a new 1-bit output port `ex_mem_mem_op_q`. Instantiate a parallel `logic ex_mem_mem_op_reg` flop with identical reset/stall/capture enables as the existing reg_q (reset→0, stall→hold, otherwise capture `in.ctrl.mem_read | in.ctrl.mem_write`). Drive the new output from this flop. Do NOT edit ex_mem_t, do NOT touch reg_q's field layout, do NOT touch the redirect cone, branch resolve, ALU input muxes, or forwarding muxes.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire the new `u_ex.ex_mem_mem_op_q` output to the hazard_unit's `ex_mem_mem_op` input. Delete the existing top-level combinational `ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read | ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_write` expression that drives this port. No other edits — ex_mem_t remains untouched, no RVFI port edits, no changes to any other stage instantiation, no struct-member edits, no wire renames.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r13s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r13s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777799995056,"end":1777799995076}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm working through what went wrong with different structural changes to the bench core. The predictors didn't help across any topology, restructuring attempts on both the producer and critical path sides failed, and even simpler changes like renaming fields or removing dead code caused regressions through placement instability. I need to find an approach that doesn't trigger these cascading issues.\n\nLooking at what's still viable, the hazard-unit stall logic seems like a candidate—those simple OR gates feeding the stall signals don't have much room for optimization. I'm also considering whether I can restructure the load-use hazard path itself, maybe by moving the sign/zero-extension work earlier or parallelizing the forwarding select computation across pipeline stages. The challenge is that any change risks the same placement churn that killed previous attempts, so I need to be surgical about where I make modifications. The load data path currently flows through multiple mux stages—from MEM/WB through the wb_stage mux, then into the forward mux at EX—which adds latency. Moving the extraction to WB would shorten the MEM cone but would add a LUT level to the regfile write and forwarding path, likely making things worse. I've already explored registering forwarding decisions earlier and restructuring the byte-mask generation, both of which regressed. Let me think about what structural changes haven't been attempted yet.\n\nI could merge WB into MEM to eliminate the stage, but that just moves the mem_to_reg mux before the flop—that's what r3s1 tried and it regressed. Adding an extra IF stage would help Fmax by breaking the BRAM→PC cone but adds branch latency. Merging ID and EX is risky since decode already runs in parallel with regfile read. I'm going to try a narrower fix: register a dedicated 1-bit `ex_mem_mem_op` signal inside ex_stage that captures the OR of mem_read and mem_write before the flop, so the hazard_unit's dmem_stall path doesn't have to OR two flop outputs together.\n\nActually, that's pretty marginal. The bigger idea is moving load extraction—the shift and sign/zero-extend logic—from MEM to WB. Right now MEM reads the raw dmem data and extracts it combinationally before flopping into MEM/WB; if I push that extraction into WB instead, I free up the MEM pre-flop cone and let Fmax breathe. The RVFI output is identical since it observes the final retired value anyway, but r3s1 already tried a similar move and regressed, so I need to be careful here.\n\nThe problem is the MEM→EX forwarding path: currently it takes the already-extracted read_data from the MEM/WB flop, but if extraction moves to WB, the forward leg would have to take the raw word, extract it, then feed it to the ALU—that's worse. So moving the whole extraction is a net loss. But what if I split it: keep the address-based shift in MEM, move only the sign-extension mux to WB? That way MEM's cone shrinks to just the shift, and WB handles the final sext decision, changing what lands on each flop boundary.\n\nNow I'm thinking about IF-stage Fmax wins instead. The PC+4 computation is currently a 32-bit adder feeding the PC register, but what if I register both PC and PC+4 separately? Then next-PC becomes just a 2:1 mux between redirect_target and the pre-computed pc_plus4_q, with the adder working in parallel to compute the next PC+4. The catch is handling redirects correctly—when redirecting to a target, I need pc_plus4_q to hold target+4 for the next cycle, which means I still need an adder for the redirect case, and the carry chain doesn't really shrink.\n\nLet me step back and try something more concrete. I could split the EX/MEM pipeline register into smaller independent flop clusters by purpose—alu_result, control signals, rd, PC—so the place-and-route tool treats each as a separate unit rather than one atomic packed vector. But r11s0 showed that changing packed-struct layouts can cause placement churn and regress timing anyway.\n\nA different angle: hoist the redirect OR-gate from core.sv into if_stage.sv, so the OR combining ex_redirect and id_is_jal_fire lives at the if_stage boundary instead of at the top level. This removes one inter-module wire and lets the tool place the OR closer to where it's actually used.\n\nThat's probably too small to matter. The real bottleneck is likely the EX-stage ALU and forward muxes feeding into the EX/MEM flop. But I notice branch resolution doesn't actually need the full ALU output—it just compares rs1 and rs2 post-forward directly. The ALU input muxes (is_auipc, alu_src) are irrelevant for branches, so the branch-taken signal is already on a parallel path. The misalign fault cone tried distribution before and regressed. I think the move is to restructure the hazard unit's stall and flush logic by precomputing key terms into narrow registered signals.\n\nSpecifically, I can move the `mem_op` computation (mem_read OR mem_write) into ex_stage as a dedicated flop bit instead of computing it at the top level. That removes one OR gate from the dmem_stall cone feeding hazard_unit—small but clean. I could also consider merging hazard_unit and forward_unit, but they don't share many inputs, so there's not much CSE opportunity. The safer move is just to register the mem_op bit in ex_stage as a new appended field, which follows the existing rule about not modifying struct fields. The dmem_stall signal propagates to multiple stall and hold points across the pipeline, so trimming its critical path should ease timing pressure on the PC register, ID/EX reset, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB valid signals. This structural reshaping is low-risk and could yield a modest 1-3% improvement. Let me implement it.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded229c270017XghyjW5J5zeJX","sessionID":"ses_212de744bffe9Ru5mmX5gKrnXs","messageID":"msg_ded218c6d001VLAdZHwRe0KkNW"}}
