{"type":"text","timestamp":1777800002023,"sessionID":"ses_212de744bffe9Ru5mmX5gKrnXs","part":{"id":"prt_ded232637001l3vNcTiD8XJdW1","messageID":"msg_ded231f04001OBUkZ0CSwvO8d6","sessionID":"ses_212de744bffe9Ru5mmX5gKrnXs","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written: `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r13s1.yaml`\n\n**Summary**: Structural, low-risk cone-depth reduction on the hazard/stall network. Replaces the top-level OR-of-flop-Qs (`ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read | ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_write`) with a dedicated parallel 1-bit flop in ex_stage, riding the same clock/reset/stall enables as the existing ex_mem_t register. This shortens the `dmem_stall` fanout cone — which feeds `stall_if` (PC reg hold), `stall_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` — by one LUT level, co-locates the driver with the ex_stage flop cluster, and touches exactly two files (+1 FF on a 1861-FF fabric).\n\nKey safety properties from prior lessons:\n- **No ex_mem_t layout edit** (avoids r11s0's placement-churn class)\n- **No id_ex_t field rename/append** (avoids r7s0 formal destabilization)\n- **No fetch-redirect cone edit** (avoids r4s0/r5s1/r6s0/r8s0 formal tarpit)\n- **No RVFI surface edit** (avoids r5s0/r10s0 reg_ch0 BMC class)\n- **Applies r4s2's \"dedicated parallel flop riding existing net\" pattern** to the stall network instead of the PC-redirect network\n\nExpected: +2%, low confidence — the stall-disjunct simplification angle was explicitly called out as viable in lesson r11s2's closing note.","time":{"start":1777799996983,"end":1777800002020}}}
