{"type":"text","timestamp":1777801424893,"sessionID":"ses_212cbcd14ffe5GBlfRaJVpNC73","part":{"id":"prt_ded38d567001wElAzcGWiL2EHt","messageID":"msg_ded3886af001m97oHx4xUdO7Xi","sessionID":"ses_212cbcd14ffe5GBlfRaJVpNC73","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis `hyp-20260503-002-r14s1` to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r14s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Structural stage-rebalance that relocates the load-data shift+sign/zero-extend combinational cone from MEM pre-flop (the binding Fmax limiter per r3s1) to WB post-flop. All inputs needed (raw `mem_rdata`, `alu_result[1:0]`, `ctrl.mem_width`, `ctrl.mem_sext`) already exist as flopped fields in `mem_wb_t`, so no struct edits are required — just delete the cone from `mem_stage` (zeroing the now-dead `read_data` flop for Yosys DCE) and reconstruct it byte-for-byte in `wb_stage` feeding the existing `mem_to_reg` mux.\n\n**Why this angle, given the exhaustive failure history**:\n- r3s1 identified MEM pre-flop as binding but moved the wrong way (mux pre-flop → series with critical cone). This moves the *opposite* direction (cone post-flop).\n- r6s0 broke formal by rewriting the shifter on misaligned addrs. This preserves the exact formula, just relocated.\n- Avoids every named tarpit: no struct edits (r7s0/r11s0), no mirror state (r13s1), no fetch-redirect cone touches (r8s0 class), no predictor, no regfile edit.\n- Net bet: MEM pre-flop cone is always-active on LOADs (binding); WB→forward leg is sometimes-active. Trading an always-critical for a sometimes-critical cone is the structural rebalance.\n\nConfidence low because the WB→forward leg could become the new binding limiter, but the framing makes the tradeoff explicit and the diff is minimal.","time":{"start":1777801418087,"end":1777801424892}}}
