{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777802713334,"sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01B2iB32Wkm8iNXVW5L3LZgM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -l \"hazard\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -1","description":"Check for hazard-unit hypotheses in log"},"output":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n","metadata":{"output":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n","exit":0,"description":"Check for hazard-unit hypotheses in log","truncated":false},"title":"Check for hazard-unit hypotheses in log","time":{"start":1777802713330,"end":1777802713333}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what we've learned from the optimization attempts—the predictors have hit their limits across multiple runs, micro-optimizations haven't panned out, but the JAL fast-path showed real promise with that significant gain. Given that architectural changes like shared adders and parallel flops have all failed, I need to think about a fundamentally different structural approach for the bench core.\n\nLooking at what's still on the table: the hazard unit simplification that was flagged as remaining work, the data memory cone, and potential pipeline restructuring. The key insight is that most of these attempts have been incremental tweaks, so I should consider more radical changes—either collapsing pipeline stages like merging writeback into memory, or rethinking how forwarding and hazard detection work together. The hazard unit's complex stall logic around memory operations seems like a natural place to investigate, since it fans out to multiple pipeline stages and might be creating unnecessary bubbles. The critical path for fetch runs deep: PC register through instruction memory BRAM, decoder, immediate generator, and JAL fast-path all the way to the ID/EX register input. Adding a real IF/ID pipeline register would split this into two stages but would cost an extra cycle on branch mispredicts and JAL/JALR instructions. I'm also considering whether simplifying the hazard unit's stall logic or decoupling the mem_op fanout could help, though the mem_op approach in r13s1 broke the design when attempted.\n\nI'm exploring whether relocating the regfile read or pre-registering decoder outputs could reduce the combinational depth, but these essentially add pipeline stages. I'm also reconsidering whether moving the mem_to_reg mux earlier in the memory stage could help, though r3s1 showed this regressed when the mux ended up in series with the load cone.\n\nLet me look at some genuinely different structural approaches: splitting the write port between ALU and load operations would require significant regfile changes, or I could try optimizing the forward_unit's comparison logic with one-hot encoding to trade area for shallower logic. I've also considered moving the JAL adder output earlier or flattening the hazard_unit's priority logic, but these feel like micro-optimizations rather than structural changes.\n\nGiven what's already been tried, the remaining structural options are limited—I could add a bypass directly from the EX result back into the next cycle's EX input, or explore other major topology changes, but I need to think carefully about what's actually feasible.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether adding a field to the EX/MEM struct itself (rather than a parallel shadow flop) might help reduce hazard_unit's fanout by caching the mem_op bit, since the formal issues in r13s1 were specifically about parallel shadow flops, not about extending the existing struct.\n\nI could also try merging the immediate generator into the decoder to share funct3 case logic, though that's mostly combinational reshuffling that the synthesizer might optimize away anyway. Another structural idea is moving the decoder from the ID stage into the IF stage combinationally—it wouldn't change the actual netlist since it's operating on the same imem_data input, just a different module location. The real question is identifying where the critical path actually lives now that the multiplier is no longer the bottleneck; it's likely the IF→ID cone from memory through decode and register file reads into the ID/EX flop.\n\nThe most promising approach seems to be flopping the register file read outputs. Currently the path chains from imem through the register file address decode to the actual register values, all combinationally feeding into the ID/EX register. If I moved the register file read to after the ID/EX flop instead—using the already-flopped rs1_addr and rs2_addr fields to drive the read—then the register values would arrive at the EX stage combinationally. This changes the pipeline topology though, since the register read now happens in EX rather than ID, which means the ID/EX register would need to drop the rs1_val and rs2_val fields entirely and...\n\nActually, this is worth exploring more carefully. The forwarding logic would still work the same way—prioritizing ex_mem and mem_wb over the fresh regfile read—but the critical path in cycle N+1 would be: ID/EX flop output driving the regfile address, then through the 5-to-32 decoder, the 32-to-1 mux, the write-first bypass mux, and finally the 3-to-1 forward mux before reaching the ALU. That's quite deep compared to the current cycle N path where imem feeds directly into the regfile address. I need to actually measure whether breaking up the combinational chain this way helps or just shifts the bottleneck.\n\nLet me step back and think about a different angle: what if I cache the write-first bypass logic inside the forward_unit itself? The regfile's write-first bypass and the MEM/WB forward mux are technically serving different purposes—one handles the case where an instruction is being written to the regfile this cycle and read by an ID-stage instruction three cycles later, while the other handles forwarding from MEM/WB to EX—so they don't actually overlap. But maybe there's a way to simplify the overall forwarding structure.\n\nActually, what if I eliminate the MEM/WB forward leg entirely by writing to the regfile earlier—during the MEM cycle for non-load operations instead of waiting for WB? That would satisfy 2-ahead dependencies through the regfile read itself. The downside is that's essentially split-origin writes, which was tried before and caused regressions.\n\nAnother thought: what if the forward_unit outputs feed back into the regfile instead of sitting at EX? That would merge forwarding into the regfile read itself, but the regfile reads happen in ID, a cycle earlier than EX, so I'd need the addresses available then—which they are. The forward paths would need to check if rd matches rs in the next few stages, but that's EX-stage information.\n\nI'm going in circles here. Let me focus on what genuinely hasn't been attempted yet: eliminating WB entirely by merging the write mux into the regfile write port, or trying a single-port regfile with muxed read addresses that alternate between rs1 and rs2. Or maybe inferring distributed SSRAM with a different port configuration.\n\nActually, r5s0 flagged something specific: Gowin primitives need the regfile to have either a single read port or registered reads—not 2 async read ports. So what if I add a 1-cycle latency to the regfile reads? ID would capture rs1_addr and rs2_addr into ID/EX instead of the values themselves, and the regfile output would arrive at EX. I'd need write-first bypass logic to handle cases where the previous cycle wrote to the address being read now. This structural change could enable SSRAM inference and saves about 64 FFs by removing rs1_val/rs2_val from id_ex_t, though it causes placement churn and r5s0 already mentioned some concerns.\n\nBut trying this has multiple risks: layout churn from field removal, formal verification issues around regfile reset state, and the forward unit needs to adapt to the new timing. That's pretty ambitious. Let me explore less risky options instead.\n\nI could fold the decoder into if_stage to eliminate the IF/ID boundary, but that's just a module reorganization—the netlist stays the same. Or add a 2-entry instruction buffer in ID to hide stalls, but r2s1 tried that and it regressed hard. Early-committing NOPs at ID would bypass EX entirely, but that's complex with minimal payoff.\n\nWhat about removing unused fields from ex_mem_t? The pc field only propagates through mem_stage, and rs1_addr, rs2_addr, rs1_val, rs2_val are RVFI-only—but r11s0 showed field removal causes placement churn, so that's risky too.\n\nActually, here's an idea: create a shadow pipeline just for RVFI metadata—a parallel shift register holding the address and value fields separate from the functional pipeline. This could cluster RVFI flip-flops together and help placement, though it's a lot of work and struct edits have proven risky.\n\nLooking at the actual constraints: tang-nano-20k with a 135MHz target, but we're at 172.35MHz and 9484/10000 LUTs—area is the real bottleneck. Merging hazard_unit and forward_unit might help since they share inputs, but CSE should already handle that. Same with combining imm_gen and decoder—they both decode the opcode, so maybe Yosys isn't CSE-ing across module boundaries even with flatten enabled.\n\nThe most promising angle seems to be inlining hazard_unit's logic directly where each signal is consumed rather than routing those long nets across the chip, or splitting it into per-stage local hazard evaluators to reduce fanout and localize the routing. Though I'm not fully confident either is net-positive without more restructuring.\n\nAnother option: pre-compute the write-data mux inside the MEM stage instead of deferring it to WB. This would eliminate a LUT level from the forwarding unit's mem_wb path by storing the final w_data in the pipeline register. The mux would combine the shifted/extended load data with the ALU result before the flop, using the mem_to_reg control signal that's already flopped down from ID/EX. But this is essentially what r3s1 attempted, and it regressed because the mux ended up serialized with the load data path.\n\nI'm also considering splitting the ALU result forwarding into separate low and high half networks to reduce fanout on each mux, but that's mostly a structural reorganization that Yosys would likely see through without explicit inlining directives. Moving branch comparison earlier to the ID stage could save a bubble, but it would require regfile reads and heavy forwarding into ID, adding depth to an already congested stage.\n\nI'm going to commit to a genuinely structural approach here. I'm considering a direct forwarding path from the EX/MEM stage for ALU results, bypassing the MEM/WB flop entirely—loads would still route through the normal path, but ALU operations two cycles ahead could grab their result earlier from EX/MEM, avoiding the extra flop delay.\n\nBut that doesn't actually help since the 2-ahead position is already MEM/WB, and 1-ahead is already handled by the existing EX/MEM forward path.\n\nI'm also exploring whether folding the decoder and immediate generator into a single module might help Yosys detect shared expressions more aggressively within one compilation unit, but previous results showed that cross-module CSE already collapses identical bit-permute cones after flattening, so this is likely a dead end too.\n\nLet me step back and look at what's actually driving the improvement—the current best is 387.98 versus the baseline of 301.04.\n\nNow I'm examining the actual constraints: Fmax is 172.35 MHz against a 135 MHz target, but area is the real bottleneck at 9484 out of 10000 LUT4s. Since I'm area-bound, I need genuine structural reductions rather than just removing fields, which tends to cause placement churn. The key insight is that rs1_val and rs2_val in the mem_wb_t register are only carried for RVFI compliance, so I could eliminate them and recover the values from regfile-side logic instead. A more promising structural change would be to redesign the regfile for distributed SSRAM synthesis by making reads registered with a one-cycle latency and moving the write-first bypass logic to a combinational mux on the consumer side in id_stage, which would eliminate the rs1_val and rs2_val fields entirely from the id_ex_t struct.\n\nBut that approach carries significant risks—it requires modifying id_ex_t (affecting r7s0 and r11s0), rewiring the forward_unit, and handling formal regfile-reset requirements. Given the complexity, I'm reconsidering simpler options like merging if_stage directly into core.sv to eliminate module-boundary crossings, though that feels incremental and unlikely to yield meaningful gains. The real opportunity I haven't explored yet is changing pipeline depth itself—I could split the fetch stage into IF1 and IF2, making it a two-stage fetch pipeline instead of the current single stage.\n\nIF1 would compute the PC while IF2 handles the BRAM read, potentially relieving the imem-to-decode setup path. The tradeoff is clear though: each misprediction adds an extra bubble, and with CoreMark's branch density around 15-20%, that's roughly a 3-5% IPC hit. Since Fmax is already at 172MHz (well above the 135MHz target), adding a stage probably won't improve frequency enough to compensate for the IPC loss. But fitness is actually the product of both—Fmax and IPC together—so if either one improves significantly, it could still be worth it.\n\nThe real question is whether splitting the fetch into two stages would actually gain 10%+ in Fmax. The BRAM read itself is only 3-5ns on this process, and the current cycle is already 5.8ns, so the binding constraint is likely elsewhere. I'm reconsidering the approach entirely—maybe instead of adding pipeline depth, I should look at the hazard unit simplification that was flagged as viable. That's a more localized change that could tighten up the stall and flush logic without the pipeline penalty.\n\nThe hazard unit currently gates dmem_stall on whether there's actually a pending memory operation, but if I remove that gate and just use dmem_ready directly, the logic simplifies significantly. On the FPGA where dmem_ready is always 1, this has zero effect. In the cosim mode with random stalls, it would cause unnecessary stalls when no memory op is pending, but that's just a comparison mode—the actual fitness metric is what matters, and I need to clarify whether the fitness run itself includes those stalls or if it's running zero-wait.\n\nLooking at the fitness definition more carefully: CoreMark runs in cosim with the 22% stall profile, so iter/cycle is definitely measured under stalls. That means simplifying away the ex_mem_mem_op gate would hurt the fitness number significantly, so that approach isn't viable.\n\nInstead, I could add mem_op_any as a precomputed field directly in ex_mem_t—computed in the EX stage as the OR of mem_read and mem_write, then flopped alongside the existing control bits. This follows the pattern from earlier iterations where appending a new logic field to the struct avoids the formal verification issues that came up with shadow flops.\n\nThe hazard unit would then read ex_mem.mem_op_any directly, saving one LUT level in the dmem_stall cone, though the gain is probably marginal.\n\nGiven the structural category and the need for something ambitious, I'm considering a 2-cycle load path restructure—forwarding the in-flight load's data directly to the next instruction's EX operand mux to eliminate the load-use bubble. But the load extension logic is already long, and putting it in the forward path would likely regress timing.\n\nSo I'm settling on something lower-risk: eliminating the redundant hold_mem_wb signal by making the mem stage self-aware of its stall condition, since hold_mem_wb is just a duplicate of the dmem_stall logic anyway.\n\nActually, a cleaner structural refactor would be moving all the hazard unit's stall computations into the stages themselves—if_stage owns stall_if, id_stage owns stall_id, and so on. It's a pure module boundary change with no netlist impact, but might improve placement locality.\n\nI also considered the dual-bank regfile approach, but r6s1 already tried that and hit formal verification issues. Looking back at r14s1's load-data regression, the WB cone doesn't just feed the regfile write port—it also feeds the forward unit's mem_wb leg, which fans into the EX operand mux, so any attempt to relocate that path creates new critical paths elsewhere.\n\nThe real constraint is that dmem_rdata isn't available until MEM stage, so I can't pre-shift in EX even though the shift amount (alu_result[1:0]) is trivial to compute there.\n\nLet me pivot to a structural idea: what if I move the forwarding mux logic directly into the regfile read ports? Instead of having a separate forward_unit at EX stage, the regfile itself would check for ex_mem and mem_wb matches and return the forwarded value with priority. This collapses three separate forwarding paths into one priority network at the regfile, though it would fire one cycle earlier than the current design since it'd operate at ID stage rather than EX stage.\n\nBut that timing shift breaks things — at ID time, ex_mem holds the instruction two cycles ahead, not one, so the forwarding semantics change. I'd need to recalibrate which pipeline stages feed into the priority logic.\n\nLet me settle on a concrete hypothesis: append a pre-computed one-hot rd-enable mask to both ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t, so the forward_unit can do a simple mux selection instead of recomputing the 5-bit rd comparison every cycle.\n\nActually, that trades a small AND-OR network for a 32:1 mux, which is probably deeper in LUT levels — likely a regression. I keep going in circles here.\n\nLet me just commit to something: replace the pipeline-wide `valid` propagation chain with a single counter that tracks flush depth and decrements each cycle.  This saves a few FFs and simplifies bubble injection, but it's risky because `valid` feeds RVFI directly and the semantics change.\n\nOr maybe collapse `mem_to_reg` by pre-computing the write data in MEM's pre-flop mux — select between load data and ALU result before the flop, then store only the final result in `mem_wb_t`. The mux selector is already available, and this moves the deep load-data cone into series with the mux rather than parallel.\n\nActually, here's a cleaner angle: pre-register the shift amount for load data in EX so MEM's pre-flop only handles the extend operation, not the full shift-and-extend cone.\n\nLooking at the critical path more carefully — BRAM output feeds through byte selection, then extend, then the flop. That's three LUT levels. What if I split this by moving the extend to the WB stage instead? Keep the shift pre-flop, but store the shifted word in `mem_wb_t` and let WB handle the extend combinationally. This trades one LUT level off the MEM pre-flop path for one added to the WB forward path, but it might help if the WB path has more slack.\n\nThe tradeoff is: MEM pre-flop gets shallower (shift only, no extend), but WB post-flop gets deeper (flop-Q → extend → mux → w_data instead of just flop-Q → mux). Given that r14s1 failed when moving the entire load cone post-flop, this middle ground might work if neither path is overwhelmingly critical.\n\nActually, I realize I can't extend without shifting first to get the right byte, so that alternative doesn't work. Instead, I'm going to try a different structural approach: inlining the hazard unit by distributing its logic directly into each pipeline stage. Each stage computes its own stall and flush signals locally from the signals it sees, rather than routing everything through a central hazard_unit module. This keeps the inter-stage signals the same but eliminates the module as a distinct entity. The netlist might end up identical, but the placement locality could help with routing congestion on a full fabric.\n\nI'm estimating this gives maybe a 5% improvement with low to medium confidence.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded4c9498001O5scZa6MyM5GsN","sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","messageID":"msg_ded4964d00013hE30QKXPqEge4"}}
