{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777802896387,"sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01UYCeKg2SXmp9ocPpdYgQen","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -oiE '\"title\":\"[^\"]*(alu|split|bank)[^\"]*\"' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -30","description":"Find ALU-related hypothesis titles in log"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Find ALU-related hypothesis titles in log","truncated":false},"title":"Find ALU-related hypothesis titles in log","time":{"start":1777802896349,"end":1777802896385}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reconsidering the pipeline structure more carefully—the r11s2 lesson pointed toward simplifying hazard-unit stall logic rather than a full restructure, but now I'm exploring whether there's a genuine architectural change worth trying. Looking at how the pipeline stages propagate their valid signals independently across id_ex, ex_mem, and mem_wb, I'm wondering if consolidating this could reduce complexity.\n\nThe real bottleneck is likely one of three paths: the fetch-redirect chain through the PC and instruction memory into the decoder, the execute stage with its operand forwarding mux feeding into the multiplier, or the memory stage's load data path with shifting and sign extension before the final flop. All three are quite deep. I'm now considering moving the NOP injection logic from the if_stage output into the id_stage instead—currently the mux sits directly on the decoder's input, forcing it to process every cycle including flushes, but if I kept the raw instruction data flowing through and handled the NOP selection later, that might reduce the critical path at the fetch-decode boundary.\n\nThe tricky part is that the NOP injection at IF exists specifically to prevent the hazard unit from seeing wrong-path register addresses and triggering spurious load-use stalls after a branch, not just for the id_stage capture logic which already has its own flush guard. So removing that mux would require ensuring the hazard unit doesn't misfire on flushed instructions.\n\nI could move the 2:1 mux from the decoder's input to the hazard unit's output—gating the stall signal with a flush override instead. This trades off shortening the decoder/regfile paths against potentially lengthening the PC control path, and the net benefit depends on which path is actually critical. Let me map out the timing: removing the mux from imem_data saves a stage on the decoder and regfile read paths, but adds a mux to the stall_if signal that feeds back to the PC's clock enable. Since the decoder and regfile chains are likely deeper than the hazard unit's output, this swap probably wins overall.\n\nThe tricky part is ensuring correctness when wrong-path instructions reach the decoder. The flush guard in id_stage zeros out their control signals before they hit the ID/EX register, so RVFI shouldn't see them propagate. But the hazard unit's load-use detection now fires on raw imem_data bits from potentially wrong-path instructions, so I need to gate that logic with !flush_if to prevent spurious stalls. Since flush_if depends only on external inputs like ex_redirect and imem_ready, not on load_use_hazard itself, there's no combinational loop. The real question is whether a stall triggered by a wrong-path instruction matters—the PC has already been redirected, so holding it one more cycle shouldn't break anything. So when redirect fires, the NOP injection clears the instruction to zero, which means the hazard unit sees all-zero register fields and can't trigger a spurious load-use stall. Without the NOP, the wrong-path instruction would still be visible, potentially causing a false hazard signal—but that signal gets masked downstream anyway since redirect already forces a flush. The NOP injection is technically redundant for correctness, though it does eliminate an unnecessary combinational path from the wrong-path instruction to the hazard detection logic. Now I need to check whether removing it would break the JAL fast-path, which depends on if_id_w.valid being driven correctly. The ex stage would capture the NOP's decoded signals with valid=0, which is fine. Without NOP injection, load_use might fire on the stale instruction data and flush id_ex to zero instead—same end result but potentially cleaner. This refactor should be functionally equivalent while saving a logic level on the binding paths. I'm thinking of this as a structural change since it removes the if_stage's NOP injection mux and reshapes the inter-module wiring. One concern though: the hazard unit and regfile already read raw addresses from if_id, so removing NOP injection means they'd see real imem_data on flush cycles. The regfile's async reads wouldn't hurt timing, and the decoder would just process whatever valid instruction data appears—but I need to think through whether that creates any correctness issues.\n\nLooking at the actual optimization gains: removing the 2:1 mux between imem_data and the decoder saves one LUT level, same mux removal benefits the regfile address path, and the valid bit mux is marginal. The cost is minimal since spurious hazard fires get absorbed downstream. But I'm realizing Yosys might have already optimized the mux logic pretty aggressively—the NOP pattern creates bit-specific simplifications that could mean the path isn't actually longer with the mux in place.\n\nNow I'm concerned about the BMC implications. Removing the NOP injection exposes raw imem_data to the hazard unit and regfile on wrong-path cycles, which is different from before. The RVFI-observable state (id_ex register) should stay the same because id_stage's flush guard zeros it on flush cycles, but in BMC's symbolic initial states, if_id_w.instr becomes raw imem_data instead of NOP when flush is low, and I need to verify this doesn't create a verification gap.\n\nThe key insight is that id_is_jal is still gated by if_id_w.valid (unchanged), so it stays 0 on flush cycles. The regfile outputs only matter when captured into id_ex, which is also gated by flush. The hazard unit's load_use_hazard might fire differently on wrong-path data, but that just triggers flush_id, which still zeros id_ex—same observable result whether the NOP was injected or not. Even the corner case where load_use_hazard fires on wrong-path rs1/rs2 after a redirect resolves cleanly: the cycle after redirect, imem_data holds the correct target instruction, so there's no stale wrong-path data to worry about.\n\nNow I'm verifying the id_jal_target path: it's computed combinationally from if_id_w.pc and imem_data bits, but only feeds redirect_target when id_is_jal_fire is true, which requires valid=1. On flush cycles, valid=0, so id_is_jal_fire=0 and id_jal_target doesn't affect the redirect mux. The redirect_target arbitration between ex_redirect and id_jal_target is safe because the id_jal path is effectively disabled when valid=0.\n\nI should also verify that removing the NOP mux doesn't break the JAL fast-path's Fmax optimization. Currently id_is_jal depends on if_id_w.instr[6:0] (through the NOP mux) ANDed with !flush. With my change, it becomes (imem_data[6:0] == JAL) & !flush. Since the NOP instruction (0x13) has opcode bits that don't match JAL, the flush case already forces id_is_jal to 0 anyway, so the signal structure should remain equivalent and the routing optimization should hold.\n\nThere's still some risk that removing the NOP mux changes how Yosys places the JAL compare logic, but the upstream change is less direct than previous attempts that failed. The concrete benefit of eliminating a 32-bit mux from multiple paths outweighs the uncertainty, so I'll proceed with medium confidence and note a moderate fitness delta.\n\nNow I'm tracing through what happens during imem_stall cycles without NOP injection—the decoder sees stale instruction data, but the valid bit gets cleared by the flush logic, so id_ex captures control signals with valid=0, which means RVFI won't report it and downstream stages ignore it anyway.\n\nBut there's a critical issue: the forward_unit checks ex_mem.ctrl.reg_write directly without gating on the valid bit, so if a stale instruction happens to have reg_write=1, it could incorrectly forward garbage results even though the instruction shouldn't be retiring. The NOP injection currently prevents this by ensuring reg_write=0 during stall cycles, so removing it would actually introduce a forwarding bug.\n\nI could fix this by AND'ing the valid bit into every w_en signal that feeds the forward_unit, but that adds gates everywhere. Alternatively, I could zero out the control signals in id_stage when valid=0 to prevent spurious forwarding, though I need to verify what the NOP decode actually produces for reg_write.\n\nLooking at the NOP (ADDI x0,x0,0), it has reg_write=1 but rd=0, so the forward_unit's rd!=0 gate already blocks it. The real issue is that without NOP injection, stale imem_data during imem_stall could have a real instruction's rd!=0 and reg_write=1, causing spurious forwarding.\n\nThe key insight is that flush on redirect already zeros id_ex, so the problem only occurs during imem_stall when id_ex captures with valid=0. I could keep NOP injection just for imem_stall and remove it for redirect cases, but the current if_stage logic conflates both paths.\n\nIf I change the logic to only NOP during imem_stall, during redirect cycles the wrong-path imem_data feeds downstream—but id_stage's flush_id=1 zeros id_ex and propagates ctrl.reg_write=0, preventing spurious forwards. The concern about id_is_jal firing on wrong-path data is moot because if_id_w.valid=0 on redirect, so id_is_jal never fires. So during imem_stall, the stale instruction gets captured with valid=0, which prevents it from executing downstream, but the decoder still produces control signals including reg_write=1 for whatever stale instruction was fetched. The forwarding unit then sees a non-zero rd from that stale instruction and could spuriously forward its result to later consumers. The current code avoids this by injecting NOPs during stall, since a NOP has rd=0, which the forwarding gate filters out. So removing NOP injection unconditionally would break the forwarding safety during memory stalls.\n\nOption (b) gates both the reg_write signal and the rd field at the id_ex capture point when in.valid=0, forcing them to zero regardless of what the stale instruction decodes to. This is a minimal hardware cost—just an AND gate and a small mux—and it achieves the same safety as NOP injection without needing the 32-bit instruction mux in the fetch stage. After one cycle, the forwarding unit sees reg_write=0 and won't forward, and the same holds for the next stage.\n\nBut I'm realizing this restructures how bubbles flow through the pipeline: instead of injecting them as NOP bit patterns at IF, I'd be injecting them as control-bit masking at ID. That's a meaningful shift in the pipeline's bubble discipline, and the formal verification flow has been built around the old NOP-injection approach for a long time. Changing the valid/ctrl state relationship during stalls could break the induction invariants that the formal tools rely on—exactly the kind of tarpit the r14s2 lesson warned about.\n\nSo this approach carries the same formal risk as removing NOP injection outright. I need to think of something simpler and more localized that doesn't touch the valid/instr pairing.\n\nWhat if I just consolidate the control struct instead? Or better yet, precompute the memory operation gating logic—extract `mem_write_active = ctrl.mem_write && !mem_misalign` and `mem_read_active = ctrl.mem_read && !mem_misalign` as local signals in the mem stage and reuse them throughout instead of computing them inline in multiple places. It's straightforward CSE that should save area without restructuring the pipeline's core discipline.\n\nActually, I'm overthinking this. Let me commit to the NOP-injection relocation hypothesis—it's genuinely structural and has a clear rationale for improving Fmax, even if there's risk. I'll be conservative with the fitness estimate.\n\nWait, one more angle: what if I flatten the forward_unit's priority logic into a flat OR tree instead of sequential if-else chains? That could reduce the critical path depth...\n\nGenerating priority logic...\n\nNo, Yosys already generates similar structures anyway. That won't help.\n\nAlright, final call: I'm going with the hazard_unit refactor where I distribute stall and flush computation to each stage locally instead of centralizing it in one module. It's genuinely structural and should improve placement locality, though the Fmax gain is probably minimal.\n\nActually, I can only submit one idea. Let me think about the risk profile here—we're at 94.8% LUT utilization, so adding area is dangerous. The NOP-injection removal would add area through compensating control logic at the decode stage. What if I go for something that actually reduces area instead?\n\nI could eliminate the writeback stage module entirely by inlining its mux logic directly into the core, which would shrink the netlist without topology risk.\n\nBut wait, I need to reconsider the NOP-injection approach more carefully. There are three real risks: the formal verification could get stuck on invariant checking (like what happened before with if_id_w pairs), the Fmax gain might disappear once I add compensating gates, and the JAL fast-path could break. Given those hazards, maybe I should go with something more conservative instead.\n\nActually, I keep circling back to the same issue—any change that touches if_id_w.instr could trigger that formal verification tarpit I hit before. That's a real blocker.\n\nLet me pivot to splitting the ALU into two sub-modules: one for fast operations (add, subtract, logical, shift, compare) and another for multiply/divide. The EX stage just muxes between them. This keeps the interface the same but gives the place-and-route tool more flexibility to spread them across the fabric and reduce congestion. The shared multiplier stays intact within the M-ext sub-module, so no functional change after flattening. The risk is low since I'm not touching pipeline registers or the fetch-redirect logic, though the actual placement benefit is uncertain.\n\nActually, I keep flip-flopping. Let me just commit to the NOP-injection hypothesis—it has the clearest potential win.\n\nWait, no. I should go with the ALU split. It's genuinely low-risk and could help with routing. But then I realize Yosys flattens submodules by default unless I mark them with `keep_hierarchy`, so the split might not even survive synthesis. Without that attribute, the netlist ends up identical anyway, so there's probably no real gain.\n\nLet me try restructuring the op encoding instead—precompute all possible outputs in parallel and mux at the end. But that's what the case statement already does implicitly, so Yosys probably won't improve on it.\n\nI keep circling back to the same dead ends. The real issue is I don't have enough visibility into what's actually causing the congestion. Let me just commit to the NOP-injection hypothesis—it's structural, has real rationale, and the risk is acceptable.\n\nActually, one more idea: split if_id_w into separate wires for data-dependent signals versus decode-dependent signals, so each consumer only sees what it needs. But that's too abstract and I don't see a clear win there either.\n\nI need to stop second-guessing and just write the NOP-injection hypothesis.\n\nWait, I think I've got it. The real issue is that NOP injection happens unconditionally on every redirect cycle, forcing a 32-bit mux on the imem_data path. But during redirects, the id_stage flush guard already zeros the control signals, so spurious forwarding can't happen. The actual problem is during imem_stall when flush_id=0—stale imem_data gets decoded with valid=0, but if rd is non-zero and reg_write=1, it could still trigger a spurious forward. So the fix is to inject NOP only during imem_stall, not on every redirect, which eliminates the mux overhead on the critical redirect path.\n\nBut wait—changing the mux selector from flush_if to imem_stall doesn't actually remove the mux hardware itself. The LUT structure stays the same, just with a different control signal. The critical path through those mux LUTs is still there every cycle, so there's no real Fmax gain. Removing the mux entirely would require gating at the id_stage level, which introduces formal verification risks and isn't a clean solution.\n\nI'm going to step back from this approach. Instead, let me explore splitting the regfile into independent banks for rs1 and rs2 reads—that's a fundamentally different structural change that might actually help.\n\nThe r6s1 attempt failed because of a macro naming mismatch between RISCV_FORMAL and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, but that's fixable. The real blocker was that without the reset-clear loop, the regfile doesn't initialize to all-zeros after reset, which breaks the formal BMC checks. Keeping the reset-clear loop in both banks would fix that, but r5s0 showed that Gowin's SSRAM inference doesn't work with reset-clear loops on 2-read-port regfiles anyway. So that path is closed.\n\nMerging if_stage with the core-level redirect arbitration is another option, but Yosys flattening makes it structurally equivalent to what we have now. I'm going to commit to the ALU split instead—it's genuinely structural, gives a placement locality hint to the synthesizer, has low formal risk, and even if it doesn't help Fmax, it's a reasonable decomposition.\n\nNow I'll implement it.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded4f5e7a001hyLUa47ytGd2W5","sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","messageID":"msg_ded4cab59001gJXNQGhweP5Ta8"}}
