{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777802937484,"sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_0132HoZBcoBr3VVvNi2FejYr","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\nids = ['r1s0','r1s1','r2s1','r3s1','r4s2']\nwith open('cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl') as f:\n    for line in f:\n        try:\n            d = json.loads(line)\n            i = d.get('hypothesis',{}).get('id','')\n            for x in ids:\n                if x in i:\n                    print(i, '|', d.get('hypothesis',{}).get('title','')[:100], '|', d.get('outcome',''))\n        except: pass\n\"","description":"Review key prior ALU/structural hypotheses"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Review key prior ALU/structural hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"Review key prior ALU/structural hypotheses","time":{"start":1777802937467,"end":1777802937484}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm realizing that while the previous ALU split into a multi-cycle MUL/DIV unit didn't work out, there's a different architectural approach worth exploring — keeping the fast operations (add, subtract, shift, logical, compare, load upper immediate) separate from the multiply/divide operations as parallel combinational sub-ALUs with a multiplexed output, rather than serializing them.\n\nThe original rationale about module hierarchy giving placement hints is probably too optimistic since Yosys flattens away those boundaries anyway. But what might actually help is extracting the shift operations into their own dedicated barrel-shift unit instantiated in parallel with the main ALU in the execute stage, since shifters tend to be the deepest combinational paths in RISC designs. Though I suspect Yosys would optimize this identically, and the extra post-ALU mux could end up serializing the critical path anyway.\n\nI'm going to commit to proposing the split-ALU approach—separating I-extension from M-extension operations as parallel sub-modules—framed as a placement-locality hypothesis for the GW2AR fabric, even though my confidence is low and the expected improvement is modest.\n\nActually, let me reconsider whether moving the branch comparator out of ex_stage into its own module would help. But it's already running in parallel with the ALU, so extracting it wouldn't change the actual topology. Same issue with the shift unit—it's already integrated into the ALU, and pulling it out as a sibling module wouldn't inherently improve anything.\n\nI need to think about this more fundamentally. The bottleneck is Fmax at 172MHz, which is tied to IPC around 0.45 per cycle, but I'm realizing the actual performance calculation doesn't quite add up.\n\nTo improve fitness, I need either higher Fmax or lower cycles-per-iteration. The obvious bubble source is load-use dependencies—CoreMark has many loads—but reducing those bubbles requires early regfile writes, which already regressed in r11s1. The critical path on GW2AR is likely either the fetch-decode cone or the MEM pre-flop load cone. What if I propose a late-forwarding path that lets MEM-stage results forward directly to EX operands in the same cycle the load retires, rather than waiting until writeback? This would be an additional forwarding stage beyond the current EX/MEM and MEM/WB paths.\n\nThe problem is that adding a MEM-stage load forward pulls the load-data shift-and-extend cone into EX's combinational path, which almost certainly regresses Fmax—r14s1 already showed that any cone feeding the mem_wb forward leg becomes the critical path. But the shift-and-extend might be short enough to work: the shift is just a 4:1 byte-mux controlled by addr[1:0], and the extend is a 2:1 mux, so the total combinational depth from the flopped address through both muxes to the EX forward mux is potentially manageable.\n\nHowever, the math doesn't work out: adding this path extends the EX forward cone from ~3 LUT levels to ~5 levels, which is a clear Fmax hit. Even though eliminating load-use stalls could give ~10% IPC improvement (CoreMark has roughly 10% load-use stalls), a 5-7% Fmax regression nets only +3-5% overall—and r3s1/r14s1 showed this kind of MEM-to-EX cone relocation is brittle on this fabric anyway. After considering that r11s1 already tried early-load optimizations and regressed, I'm going to propose the structural ALU split with I-ext and M-ext sub-modules as parallel combinational units instead—it's genuinely structural and distinct from prior attempts.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded4fffe2001Kn6wLL2TkygW6X","sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","messageID":"msg_ded4f7524001n00rRTlqn7z7HZ"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777802937511,"sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","part":{"id":"prt_ded4fffe0001YiQS2apW7p2RXf","messageID":"msg_ded4f7524001n00rRTlqn7z7HZ","sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","type":"text","text":"I see that r1s1 tried multi-cycle M-ext (adding stall/busy handshake) and regressed, but a purely combinational structural ALU decomposition has NOT been tried. Let me look at the current ALU cone structure to confirm:","time":{"start":1777802936288,"end":1777802937510}}}
