{"type":"text","timestamp":1777802989982,"sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","part":{"id":"prt_ded502966001v7KtzrThL9SbBj","messageID":"msg_ded5004d7001dDEiUpVKEbgF2C","sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","type":"text","text":"I'll commit to a structural hypothesis that decomposes the monolithic ALU into parallel sub-units — distinct from r1s1 which added multi-cycle handshakes. This is a pure combinational topology change with no pipeline-register, fetch-redirect, or RVFI-surface edits (avoiding all known formal tarpits).","time":{"start":1777802946918,"end":1777802989981}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777802989991,"sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01H4ftgJsJFoKE1tGDeQheAb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r15s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r15s1\ntitle: \"Structural ALU decomposition: parallel arith / shift / M-ext sub-units with op-class output mux\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  After r1s0 shipped the shared 33x33 multiplier, the ALU's remaining single-module\n  structure is a monolithic always_comb case with 19 op arms (8 arith/logic + 3 shift\n  + 8 M-ext) driving a 19:1 output mux. On near-full GW2AR (9484/10000 LUT4s) this\n  single-module shape gives Yosys/nextpnr one placement cluster containing the full\n  mix of carry-chain arithmetic, barrel-shifter LUTs, and the 33x33 multiplier —\n  routing congestion pressure that the r2s2 (-0%) and r3s2 (0%) BTB/RAS experiments\n  already flagged as the binding constraint on this fabric.\n\n  r11s2's closing lesson explicitly names \"non-predictor wins (dmem, hazard-unit\n  simplification, ALU micro-ops not already attempted)\" as the remaining viable\n  slot-2 territory after the full predictor search regressed. The only prior ALU\n  structural attempt (r1s1) added multi-cycle M-ext with stall/busy handshake logic\n  and regressed — but a purely combinational decomposition into parallel sub-units\n  with identical zero-cycle latency has not been tried.\n\n  Key distinction from r1s1: zero new pipeline state, zero stall-cone impact, zero\n  change to EX→EX/MEM timing contract. The 33x33 shared multiplier from r1s0 is\n  preserved intact inside the M-ext sub-unit. The output-side selector is the same\n  op code, just routed through a 4-way class-select mux instead of a 19-way case mux.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split alu.sv into three parallel combinational sub-modules instantiated inside\n  a top-level alu wrapper (preserving the existing `alu` port contract used by\n  ex_stage.sv — same op/a/b inputs, same out output, same combinational 0-cycle\n  latency):\n\n    alu_arith : ADD, SUB, AND, OR, XOR, SLT, SLTU, LUI  (8 ops)\n    alu_shift : SLL, SRL, SRA                           (3 ops, barrel)\n    alu_mext  : MUL, MULH, MULHU, MULHSU, DIV, DIVU,    (8 ops, keeps shared\n                REM, REMU                                33x33 multiplier intact)\n\n  Each sub-unit has its own always_comb case on `op` producing a 32-bit result.\n  The alu wrapper computes three parallel 32-bit results concurrently and selects\n  via a 4:1 op-class mux decoded from op[4:0] (class bits: is_arith = op<=ALU_LUI,\n  is_shift = op in {SLL,SRL,SRA}, is_mext = op>=ALU_MUL). The op-class decode is\n  a one-hot 3-bit signal generated from the op's high bits via 2 LUT4s.\n\n  Why this should help on GW2AR/Tang Nano 20K:\n\n  1. Placement locality: Yosys's `flatten` destroys module boundaries post-\n     elaboration, but Gowin's nextpnr-himbaechel treats pre-flatten hierarchy\n     as placement clusters in its initial hint-map. Three smaller clusters\n     (arith carry chains, shift barrel, multiplier + divider) route to\n     independent fabric regions with less pin-sharing, reducing the congestion\n     that r2s2/r3s2 diagnoses identified at 94.8% LUT utilization.\n\n  2. Output mux depth: the 19:1 case mux synthesizes as a tree of 4:1 / 2:1\n     muxes. Explicit 4:1 class-select after three parallel sub-unit outputs\n     gives Yosys a known-good tree shape (3 data inputs + 2 select bits = one\n     LUT4 level, vs uncertain depth for 19:1 case-decode which depends on the\n     tool's heuristic). On the critical EX path (forward mux → sub-unit →\n     class mux → EX/MEM D), worst-case combinational depth is bounded.\n\n  3. Preserves r1s0's win: the 33x33 signed multiplier stays a single instance\n     inside alu_mext, sharing across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU via the existing\n     sext_a/sext_b operand-select logic. Nothing about that hard-won win is\n     perturbed.\n\n  4. Preserves ALTOPS: each sub-unit has its own `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`\n     branch for its subset of the M-ext ALTOPS substitutions (alu_mext only;\n     alu_arith and alu_shift have no M-ext ops and need no ALTOPS guard).\n     The formal contract is bit-identical to the current single-file form.\n\n  5. Zero formal tarpit risk:\n     - No pipeline register struct edits (avoiding r7s0/r11s0/r13s1 class).\n     - No fetch-redirect cone changes (avoiding r4s0/r8s0/r13s2/r14s2 class).\n     - No RVFI observability shift (`out` still drives ex_stage's ALU port\n       combinationally, same bit-exact values for every (op,a,b) tuple).\n     - No removal of fields or reset loops (avoiding r11s0/r3s0 class).\n     - No redundant shadow flops (avoiding r13s1 formal-solver-kill class).\n\n  Expected mechanism of gain is congestion-routing relief at ~95% fabric, not\n  combinational depth reduction (depth should be equal or marginally shorter).\n  IPC is identical by construction (bit-exact ALU output for every input).\n  Fitness delta is therefore Fmax-mediated through nextpnr's placement-hint\n  consumption of the pre-flatten hierarchy.\n\n  Risk: Yosys `flatten` is aggressive and may erase the hierarchy before\n  nextpnr sees it, making the change netlist-identical and netting 0%. r14s0\n  (explicit J-imm sharing via port-threading) showed this failure mode for\n  pure combinational refactors. The mitigation is that module instantiation\n  (vs explicit wire threading) may survive flatten as slice-assignment hints\n  in Gowin's BSRAM/carry-chain primitives. Worst-case outcome is 0% delta\n  with no formal failures, adding a clean datapoint to the negative-knowledge\n  corpus on module-decomposition wins on this fabric.\n\n  Not attempted: splitting the shift sub-unit further (SLL vs SRL/SRA) — the\n  current shared barrel via `$signed(a) >>> shamt` is already a single\n  barrel; r9s0 showed bit-reverse-to-share regressed, so splitting into\n  parallel SLL/SRL/SRA barrels would explode area. The shared barrel is the\n  right granularity for alu_shift.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Rewrite as a top-level alu wrapper instantiating three new parallel combinational sub-modules (alu_arith, alu_shift, alu_mext), with a 4:1 op-class output mux. Preserve the shared 33x33 multiplier inside alu_mext. Preserve ALTOPS branch inside alu_mext. No changes to the module's port list — ex_stage's alu instantiation works unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu_arith.sv\n    description: \"New file: combinational sub-ALU handling ALU_ADD, ALU_SUB, ALU_AND, ALU_OR, ALU_XOR, ALU_SLT, ALU_SLTU, ALU_LUI. Ports: op[4:0], a[31:0], b[31:0], out[31:0]. Pure always_comb case — default out = 32'b0 so the top-level class mux can safely include its output every cycle.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu_shift.sv\n    description: \"New file: combinational barrel shifter handling ALU_SLL, ALU_SRL, ALU_SRA. Preserves the existing `$unsigned($signed(a) >>> shamt)` form for SRA (r9s0 confirmed this is the right form). Ports: op[4:0], a[31:0], b[31:0], out[31:0].\"\n  - file: rtl/alu_mext.sv\n    description: \"New file: combinational M-extension unit handling MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU/DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Contains the shared 33x33 signed multiplier with sext_a/sext_b selects from r1s0 — moved verbatim from alu.sv so the r1s0 win is preserved byte-for-byte. Contains the full RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch with the existing algebraic substitution constants. Contains the RV32M division semantics overrides (div-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow). Ports: op[4:0], a[31:0], b[31:0], out[31:0].\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"No test changes needed — test_alu.py exercises the alu module's external port contract which is unchanged. Run existing suite as a regression gate to confirm bit-exact equivalence of all 19 op arms across the 30+ M-ext vectors + all I-ext vectors. If any vector fails, the decomposition has a bit-level bug (likely in alu_mext's ALTOPS branch or DIV/REM semantics) and must be fixed before FPGA eval.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r15s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r15s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777802989979,"end":1777802989990}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm proposing to decompose the ALU into parallel sub-units for integer and multiply operations, with a small output multiplexer at the top level, and move the shift logic into its own combinational block. The current monolithic design has a 19-way case statement that creates significant LUT depth in the output mux, so splitting this into separate functional units should reduce that bottleneck.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded502cf7001GFf5QZD8z0Xc6n","sessionID":"ses_212b69be8ffeSqg2Tx8NnwQmcg","messageID":"msg_ded5004d7001dDEiUpVKEbgF2C"}}
