{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777782486925,"sessionID":"ses_213e85df8ffeWjUe01k6OURnJ6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01PGddPTsprydcooof1Hquwp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/CORE_PHILOSOPHY.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/CORE_PHILOSOPHY.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n\n\n(End of file - total 0 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/CORE_PHILOSOPHY.md","time":{"start":1777782486910,"end":1777782486924}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the philosophy document to identify structural improvements, I'm examining the current CoreMark fitness calculation where the baseline sits at 301.04, and I need to find ways to boost instructions per cycle to drive better performance gains.\n\nThe 5-stage pipeline has several bottlenecks I'm analyzing: load-use stalls create 1-cycle bubbles, branches incur a 2-cycle penalty from the flush, but the real issue is the combinational multiplier and divider sitting in the ALU—that's almost certainly the critical path limiting Fmax on the Tang Nano 20K. If I pipeline the multiplier into 2 stages and add a stall for division, I could dramatically increase clock frequency with minimal IPC impact since multiply and divide instructions are relatively rare. The structural change I'm proposing is splitting the ALU into a fast single-cycle unit and a separate pipelined multiply unit to remove that critical path constraint.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec17f40b001bdBrXRb5fyG1LI","sessionID":"ses_213e85df8ffeWjUe01k6OURnJ6","messageID":"msg_dec17c12500169GoK1sigXaOyB"}}
