{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777782523350,"sessionID":"ses_213e85df8ffeWjUe01k6OURnJ6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01PyZ2kjhrzuvLzxBfHWdkwx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r1s1\ntitle: \"Split ALU: move MUL/DIV into multi-cycle execution unit with EX stall handshake\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current ex_stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU. Under\n  `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the MUL/DIV ops degenerate to XOR-of-adds, but\n  the real (non-formal) synthesis paths — cosim, yosys, nextpnr — map\n  the `$signed(a)*$signed(b)` and `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` operators to\n  a 32x32 combinational multiplier and a divider sitting in the same\n  alu.sv `always_comb`. On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) the 32x32 signed\n  multiplier built from DSP blocks + carry chains is in the multi-ns\n  range and the combinational divider is worse still. Because the ALU\n  sits on the EX stage's forwarding-fed critical path (rs1/rs2 forward\n  mux -> ALU op -> EX/MEM flop) the multiplier/divider defines the\n  minimum clock period for the whole core. Baseline Fmax is 135 MHz\n  with target 135 MHz — the core is capped by the EX cycle. CoreMark\n  6 KB executes few MUL and essentially zero DIV per iteration, so\n  removing those ops from the EX critical path and paying for them in\n  extra cycles only on the rare MUL/DIV instruction is a strongly\n  favorable structural tradeoff for the fitness metric\n  `iter/cycle × Fmax`.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split the EX execute element into two units:\n\n    1. A fast single-cycle ALU that only handles the RV32I ops\n       (ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SLT/SLTU/SLL/SRL/SRA/LUI) plus the\n       branch comparator. No 32x32 multiplier, no divider — the\n       critical path collapses to an adder + shifter + mux, which\n       on GW2A should close around 160–180 MHz.\n\n    2. A separate mul_div unit with a `start` / `busy` / `done`\n       handshake. Multiplier is a 2-cycle pipelined 32x32 (registered\n       Booth/DSP) producing a 64-bit product. Divider is a 33-cycle\n       non-restoring iterative divider (one bit per cycle for the\n       signed 32-bit quotient + fixup). When EX dispatches a MUL/DIV,\n       the mul_div unit asserts `busy`; `ex_stage` presents a new\n       `stall_mul_div` that feeds the existing hazard_unit to freeze\n       IF, ID/EX, and to inject MEM/WB bubbles until the result is\n       ready. The result is then forwarded from the mul_div output\n       through the normal EX→MEM path, so RVFI retirement and the\n       forwarding network stay textbook.\n\n  Critical-path consequence: the EX cycle's combinational work drops\n  to (2:1 operand fwd mux) -> (adder | shifter | logic | slt) ->\n  EX/MEM flop. That is the same critical path as a classic RV32I\n  single-issue 5-stage, whose textbook synthesis on GW2A sits well\n  above 150 MHz. Target: Fmax >=155 MHz (+15%).\n\n  CoreMark IPC cost: for ITERATIONS=10 the CoreMark kernel issues on\n  the order of a few hundred multiplies (matrix kernel) and no divides\n  at all. A 2-cycle pipelined MUL costs 1 extra stall cycle vs. the\n  current 0-cycle path; over ~4.49M cycles this is well under 0.1%\n  IPC loss. Net fitness: ~(1.15 * 0.999) = +14%.\n\n  Correctness: unchanged. The decoder still emits ALU_MUL..ALU_REMU\n  as 5-bit op codes; the ex_stage routes those to the mul_div unit\n  rather than the fast ALU; the ALTOPS substitution path stays in the\n  mul_div unit under the same `ifdef` so riscv-formal's per-iteration\n  BMC pass keeps its XOR-of-add shortcut (solver stays tractable),\n  while the real hardware path is exercised by `test_alu.py` and the\n  cosim diff against reference.py for every retired MUL/DIV/REM.\n  hazard_unit already owns the stall infrastructure (dmem_stall is\n  the same shape); mul_div stall slots into the same OR tree.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 12\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Remove MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU/DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational ALU. On those opcodes drive `out = 32'b0`; the ex_stage will source the real result from the new mul_div unit. Keep ALTOPS cases as-is for the formal path so riscv-formal's BMC solver still sees XOR-of-adds.\"\n  - file: rtl/mul_div.sv\n    description: \"NEW module: 2-cycle pipelined 32x32 multiplier (produces 64-bit product, selects low/high per MULH*/MUL) plus 33-cycle iterative non-restoring divider with RV32M sign/zero/div-by-zero/INT_MIN-overflow fixup. Ports: clock, reset, start, op[4:0], a[31:0], b[31:0], busy, done, result[31:0]. Under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the unit becomes single-cycle with the XOR-of-add substitution mirrored from alu.sv so formal still closes.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate mul_div alongside alu. Detect MUL/DIV class opcodes (alu_op >= ALU_MUL). On first cycle: pulse `mul_div.start`, assert new output `stall_mul_div` until `done`. Final result mux between alu_result and mul_div.result drives EX/MEM.alu_result. Preserve forwarding — mul_div.result feeds fwd_ex_mem once the op has landed in EX/MEM.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add input `mul_div_busy`. OR it into stall_if / stall_id (freeze IF and hold ID/EX register) and clear flush_id while busy (don't insert a load-use-style bubble). stall_ex_mem stays 0 (EX/MEM captures on `done`). hold_mem_wb asserts while busy so the prior retirement's MEM/WB forwarding payload stays alive.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire ex_stage's `stall_mul_div` into hazard_unit's new `mul_div_busy` input. No change to IO or RVFI ports.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Update the ALU cocotb harness: MUL/DIV vectors now test the new `mul_div` DUT separately (2-cycle MUL latency, 33-cycle DIV latency). Add a stall-handshake test that verifies `busy` stays high for the entire operation and `done` pulses exactly once. Keep coverage for all 8 M-ext ops with the existing 30+ vectors each.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a test that inserts a MUL followed by a dependent ADD and verifies IF/ID are frozen for the expected 2 cycles, then ADD retires with the correct rd_wdata. Add a DIV-by-zero + DIV by -1 of INT_MIN + generic signed DIV trio and verify rvfi_rd_wdata matches RV32M semantics field-by-field.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777782523335,"end":1777782523348}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm identifying the combinational multiplier in the ALU critical path as the main bottleneck—moving it to a multi-cycle or pipelined approach could significantly improve the maximum frequency. Now I'll document this hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec180667001zqmmaUcClxgBq1","sessionID":"ses_213e85df8ffeWjUe01k6OURnJ6","messageID":"msg_dec17f7cf001rrPgwZJFu8AFMC"}}
