{"type":"text","timestamp":1777782579282,"sessionID":"ses_213e85df8ffeWjUe01k6OURnJ6","part":{"id":"prt_dec194ad2001q6vYrU2jCDNNzQ","messageID":"msg_dec18860f001PppIJ0ePlBE2PG","sessionID":"ses_213e85df8ffeWjUe01k6OURnJ6","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml`.\n\n**Structural angle:** split the EX execute element. The combinational 32×32 signed multiplier and divider currently sit in `alu.sv`'s `always_comb` directly on the EX critical path (forward-mux → ALU → EX/MEM flop). On GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) that path defines Fmax at 135 MHz.\n\n**Proposed change:** move MUL/DIV into a new `mul_div` unit with a start/busy/done handshake:\n- 2-cycle pipelined 32×32 multiplier (DSP-friendly)\n- 33-cycle iterative non-restoring signed divider with RV32M fixups (÷0, INT_MIN/−1)\n- EX drives a new `stall_mul_div` into `hazard_unit`; IF + ID/EX freeze while busy, MEM/WB forwarding payload held alive\n- ALTOPS path mirrored inside `mul_div` so `riscv-formal` BMC stays tractable\n\n**Expected tradeoff:** EX critical path collapses to adder+shifter+logic → target Fmax ≥ 155 MHz (+15%). CoreMark 6 KB issues only a small number of muls and no divs per iteration, so IPC cost is well under 0.1% → net fitness ≈ +12%.\n\n**Contract safety:** top-level `core` IO unchanged; RVFI 2-channel NRET=2 port set unchanged; all hard invariants (1–10, 5b) preserved. Don't-touch list not touched.","time":{"start":1777782573778,"end":1777782579281}}}
