{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777783451743,"sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","part":{"id":"prt_dec26b05a001yJhi7sDHUZT0ZE","messageID":"msg_dec269fb5001IHg7KUGXBh0kIY","sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","snapshot":"2912d69d5f7440c74d805edf527f06a9c967e3ed","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777783589406,"sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_017RhjTuquemzthFC63DT7PK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -l -i \"prefetch|decoupl|skid|fifo|fetch.buffer\" cores/bench/experiments/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Search for prior prefetch/decoupled fetch attempts"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Search for prior prefetch/decoupled fetch attempts","truncated":false},"title":"Search for prior prefetch/decoupled fetch attempts","time":{"start":1777783589391,"end":1777783589404}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the performance data, the current best configuration scores 329.56 after implementing a shared multiplier optimization that boosted results by 9.47%, but recent attempts at multi-cycle MUL/DIV units and static branch prediction both regressed due to added overhead in stall logic and fetch loops.\n\nThe key constraint is that Fmax on GW2AR is sensitive to critical path additions, and the EX stage's forward-mux already contains the shared multiplier, while prediction logic must stay clear of the PC register's combinational cone. I'm considering several structural approaches: splitting branch comparison into the ID stage to reduce EX pressure, merging MEM and WB stages to shorten the pipeline, or implementing early branch resolution in ID to cut the misprediction penalty from 2 instructions down to 1, though that would add complexity to ID's critical path. There's also potential in decoupling IF and ID stages or using registered redirects with predict-not-taken to absorb branch penalties differently.\n\nThe most promising angle seems to be moving the branch/JAL/JALR adder computation earlier—either into ID for immediate resolution, or using a registered predecode stage that produces the predicted target one cycle early. However, moving to ID creates conflicts with forwarding from EX, and I need to verify whether the load-data extractor in the MEM stage is actually on the critical path or if it's already properly registered into the MEM/WB boundary. efits:\n- Branch misprediction penalty: 2 bubbles → 2 bubbles (unchanged, branch is at EX → IF/ID and ID/EX cleared)\n- Load-use hazard: still 1 cycle (load data ready at end of MEM, forward MEM/WB → EX)\n- Actually if we collapse MEM and WB, we shorten pipeline but lose a potential forwarding level.\n- This could let forward_unit be simpler: only EX/MEM forwarding.\n\nActually wait - currently the load's data becomes available at end of MEM (captured in MEM/WB register). After MEM/WB reg, WB mux drives the regfile. The write-first bypass in reg_file + MEM/WB register means a dependent can use forwarding.\n\nIf we collapse MEM+WB: EX/MEM register captures results → WB logic muxes directly to regfile write → forward_unit only needs EX/MEM forwarding (not MEM/WB). This saves a forwarding level in EX.\n\nBut the load_data path: dmem_rdata → shift/sext → regfile write port. That's combinational through the WB mux. Too much logic — probably hurts Fmax.\n\nAlternative: keep MEM/WB register but bypass WB's mux combinationally.\n\nHmm, what about:\n\n**Option J: Precompute the load_data extract in EX stage using the dmem address's low bits, then dmem_rdata only feeds the final mux in MEM.** This doesn't really help.\n\n**Option K: Split MEM's load\n\nCollapsing MEM and WB would simplify forwarding to just EX/MEM, but the load data path becomes combinationally long through the write mux, likely hurting timing. I could keep the MEM/WB register and bypass the write mux combinationally instead, or precompute load extraction earlier, but neither seems to gain much.\n\nLooking at the critical path with Fmax already at 148 MHz, a structural win would be removing the write-first bypass mux in the regfile's read path. Currently it's a big combinational mux that detects same-cycle writes and forwards the new value. Since the forward_unit already handles MEM/WB forwarding to EX, I could make regfile writes fully synchronous and rely entirely on forwarding for hazards. This shortens the read path, though it means ID reads the old value when WB writes the same cycle—but forward_unit should catch that at the EX stage next cycle.\n\nActually, wait—if ID latches the old value into ID/EX at cycle N without the bypass, then at cycle N+1 when forward_unit checks for a match, WB has already moved past that instruction. The forwarding window is lost. So the bypass is functionally necessary and can't just be removed. I'd need to extend forward_unit to check for WB→ID forwarding, but that's essentially reimplementing what the regfile bypass already does. Another angle: maybe dual-issue superscalar with channel_1, but that's a massive change with unclear payoff. Or forward directly from the WB mux output to EX, bypassing the regfile entirely for certain paths.\n\nActually, here's a different structural idea: merge IF and ID into a single stage to reduce the branch penalty from 2 cycles to 1, since currently both IF/ID and ID/EX get flushed on a redirect.\n\nThe tradeoff is that combining instruction fetch with combinational decode would push the critical path significantly longer in that cycle.\n\nI could also try moving load sign/zero extension from MEM to WB, which might free up timing in the memory stage, though it would add a small combinational delay to the forwarding path for loads.\n\nOr I could pipeline the ALU itself for longer operations like shifts and multiplies by splitting EX into two stages.\n\nActually, the 33x33 multiplier is a DSP block on the GW2AR, which has optional pipeline registers built in. If I register the multiplier output, I could boost Fmax significantly for MUL operations, but that makes MUL take 2 cycles and introduces stall complexity — the same problem hyp-002 ran into.\n\nA cleaner approach might be to restructure hazard detection by moving load-use detection into EX rather than ID, using the ID/EX register's read addresses to check against the current instruction combinationally.\n\nBut looking at the actual critical path, the real bottleneck is the redirect signal flowing from EX back to IF's PC mux — that's a long cross-stage path through the forward mux, comparator, and PC logic. Registering the redirect signal would add a cycle to branch resolution (3 bubbles instead of 2), but could significantly improve Fmax. The tradeoff is whether the clock speed gain outweighs the extra misprediction penalty.\n\nAlternatively, I could move branch resolution earlier to the ID stage to save a bubble on mispredicts, but that requires operand forwarding at ID and adds critical logic there. The practical issue is that ID would need to stall whenever branch operands come from EX or MEM stages, which might not be too common in CoreMark but still adds complexity. And given that hyp-003 already hurt Fmax by adding logic to IF, pushing more computation into ID could have similar issues.\n\nLet me think about a different angle: decoupled fetch with a small prefetch buffer. The fitness metric actually includes 22% memory stalls in the cosim measurement, so absorbing those stalls would directly improve IPC. A 2-entry FIFO between IF and ID could let the fetch stage pull ahead when memory is ready, then ID pulls from the buffer during stalls instead of blocking. This would hide a meaningful fraction of the imem stalls without adding critical path logic to the main pipeline.\n\nBut I should also consider moving the load data alignment and sign extension into the writeback stage instead of the memory stage. That would free up the MEM/WB register to just capture the raw data and metadata, letting WB do the combinational extension work afterward.\n\nThe catch is that forwarding paths would get longer—the extended value now has to flow through more combinational logic before reaching dependent instructions, which could hurt the critical path more than it helps. And the regfile read could be split into its own pipeline stage, but that adds a stage and breaks more hazards without clear IPC gains.\n\nGiven the stall context and the need to avoid extending critical paths, the IF→ID skid buffer feels like the most straightforward structural improvement. It directly addresses instruction fetch stalls without adding logic to timing-critical paths.\n\nWith a 2-entry FIFO between IF and ID, whenever imem stalls, the buffer can supply cached instructions to ID instead of inserting bubbles—and with 22% stall rate, the queue should stay populated most of the time. I'd expect a realistic 5-10% IPC gain, since not all stalls are imem-related (redirects flush the FIFO, dmem stalls still block ID, load-use hazards are independent). The FIFO itself shouldn't extend the critical path since it sits between two pipeline stages.\n\nLet me finalize this as the proposal and check if there's any history of prefetch attempts in the log.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the imem interface more carefully. The current design has IF drive the address combinationally (io_imemAddr = pc), and when imem_ready is low, IF stalls and ID gets a bubble. To truly prefetch, I'd need to decouple the fetch PC from the decode PC—letting IF request the next instruction while ID is still consuming the current one. That means maintaining separate fetch and decode pointers, and only one address can go out per cycle anyway. A minimal approach would be a 1-entry buffer: when data arrives but ID isn't ready, hold it; next cycle ID drains it while fetch moves ahead. But this is getting complicated, so I'll propose the simple version and let the implementation handle the details.\n\nI'm also weighing whether to add a separate MEM stage for loads (making them 2-cycle in MEM while other ops stay 1-cycle), but that'd increase load-use latency and is probably a net loss. And there's an interesting angle from hyp-003: keeping prediction logic off the PC's combinational path. If I detect JAL in IF, compute the target combinationally, register it, then feed that registered prediction to the PC mux next cycle, I could save a bubble compared to the current 2-bubble JAL penalty—the register adds latency but the prediction is already stable when PC needs it.\n\nThe timeline works out: JAL appears at cycle N, target gets computed and stored, PC updates to sequential (pc0+4) at the cycle boundary, then at N+1 I redirect from the registered prediction and invalidate the sequential fetch—that's 1 bubble instead of 2. The mux itself is small and shouldn't hurt Fmax since the heavy lifting (decode + immediate extraction + PC addition) is done combinationally in IF but the result is registered before hitting the PC D-input.\n\nThough I'm realizing this is really a predictor, not structural—the prompt wants structural focus. Let me stick with the skid buffer / decoupled fetch idea instead. But before I finalize, I should check the critical paths again: the EX forwarding mux feeding the ALU, the IF-to-ID decode chain through regfile reads, the cross-stage redirect back to PC, and the MEM stage. The MUL consolidation already showed +9.47% just from LUT optimization, so similar wins might be hiding in other paths.\n\nNow looking at the data path from memory read through byte shifting, sign extension, and into the MEM/WB register—at 148 MHz, the ALU with the multiplier is almost certainly the bottleneck. I could move the multiplier into an early pipeline register to split it into a 2-cycle operation with automatic bubble insertion, similar to an earlier hypothesis but cleaner. Actually, wait—I should reconsider the pipeline structure itself. The WB stage is just combinational muxing, so really there are only 4 registered stages. What if I merged EX and MEM into a single cycle, packing the ALU and memory access together? That would keep the branch penalty the same but simplify the datapath significantly.\n\nNo, that won't work—combining ALU and memory access in one cycle creates a critical path that's too long and kills Fmax. And adding registers between MEM and the data memory output just adds latency and handshake complexity.\n\nSo I'm settling on a decoupled IF/ID stage with a prefetch buffer. The idea is to add a 1-entry buffer in the IF stage that catches instruction data when the ID stage is stalled, so when the pipeline unstalls, ID can read from the buffer while IF issues a fresh request. Though actually, during an imem stall when the memory isn't ready, there's nothing to buffer in the first place—the prefetch buffer only helps when the pipeline is stalled downstream, not when the fetch itself is blocked.\n\nThe real benefit comes during ID stalls like load-use hazards or data memory stalls. Right now, when ID stalls, the PC holds and IF can't fetch ahead. But with a prefetch buffer, the PC can advance during those stall cycles, fetching the next instruction into the buffer. When ID resumes, it has fresh work ready immediately, and IF continues fetching further. This could give us maybe 5% IPC improvement by keeping the fetch pipeline active during the 5-10% of cycles lost to load-use and data memory stalls.\n\nThe structural change is straightforward: add a 1-entry prefetch buffer to the IF stage that lets PC advance independently when the buffer has space and imem is ready. When ID unstalls, it reads from the buffer first, then the buffer absorbs the next instruction from memory. The risks are moderate—adding FIFO logic could extend the critical path, and PC management gets trickier since we need to track both the commit PC and the fetch PC separately. Redirect flushes just need to clear a valid bit though.\n\nI'm moderately confident on this approach, but I should also consider whether a simpler alternative like merging ID and EX stages might be better.\n\nMerging ID and EX would reduce the branch penalty by one cycle since only one instruction gets killed on redirect, but cramming decode, regfile read, forwarding mux, and ALU into a single cycle would likely kill the maximum frequency. Splitting WB into its own stage doesn't help either. Other options like collapsing the flush and stall logic into forwarding, or removing the MEM/WB register entirely, either don't address the core issue or create new problems—load data only becomes available after the memory access completes, so we still need a register to hold it.\n\nThe prefetch buffer seems like the right call. Let me write this up.\n\nActually, wait—I should think through whether a 4-stage design (merging MEM and WB combinationally) could work. The EX/MEM register would hold the ALU result and memory address, then WB would combinationally read from DMEM, extend the data, mux it, and write to the regfile in the same cycle. This saves flops and simplifies the forwarding network since there's no MEM/WB→EX path anymore. But the combinational path from DMEM read through load extension, regfile write, and back to the forwarding mux could become the new critical path. Plus it changes the RVFI retirement boundary, which is a bigger structural shift than I want to tackle right now.\n\nI'm going to stick with the prefetch buffer proposal.\n\nActually, there's a simpler optimization I keep circling back to: move the regfile's write-first bypass out of the read path and into the forwarding network. Right now the regfile has a combinational bypass mux that checks if WB is writing to the same address we're reading—that mux sits in the critical path. I could move this detection to the ID/EX register capture stage and add a WB→ID forwarding case instead. But honestly, this just rearranges the logic without eliminating it, so it probably won't help Fmax. I'm overthinking this. Let me finalize the prefetch buffer idea—a simple 1-entry IF→ID skid buffer.\n\nNow I'm writing up the YAML specification.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec28c566001ct3Wa86NDDjSUx","sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","messageID":"msg_dec269fb5001IHg7KUGXBh0kIY"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777783589456,"sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","part":{"id":"prt_dec28c431001p1pi7yO3zMYyzD","messageID":"msg_dec269fb5001IHg7KUGXBh0kIY","sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","type":"text","text":"Looking at the recent outcomes and lessons:\n- **hyp-001** won big (+9.47%) by consolidating the multiplier (Fmax + LUT win)\n- **hyp-002** failed because adding stall logic to MUL/DIV didn't free Fmax\n- **hyp-003** failed because prediction logic landed in the PC combinational cone\n\nKey lesson: structural changes must avoid extending the PC/ALU-forwarding critical paths, and must not introduce new stall sources that cancel IPC gains.\n\nLet me check prior experiments for any prefetch/decoupled-fetch attempts before proposing.","time":{"start":1777783587889,"end":1777783589454}}}
