{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777783669152,"sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","part":{"id":"prt_dec2a019d001IwDGjv5NZg3SHk","messageID":"msg_dec29f3e8001e4invp3JPEeZEe","sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","snapshot":"2912d69d5f7440c74d805edf527f06a9c967e3ed","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777783710582,"sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","part":{"id":"prt_dec2a217e001oOZN6ICHYPGxsL","messageID":"msg_dec29f3e8001e4invp3JPEeZEe","sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","type":"text","text":"I have enough context. The imem-stall path specifically loses one retirement per iStall cycle (flush_if forces NOP when imem_ready=0). Under ~22% iStall, this is a large fraction of cycles.\n\nThe structural angle: **decouple IF from ID with a 1-entry prefetch/skid buffer**, so IF can advance PC and fetch ahead while ID is stalled (load-use or dStall), then ID can drain the buffer during iStall cycles. Key contrast with hyp-003: the buffer sits ON the imem-data path to ID, not on the PC register's combinational fan-in — it's a purely structural decoupling, no prediction, so hyp-003's Fmax pitfall doesn't apply.","time":{"start":1777783677310,"end":1777783710580}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777783710590,"sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01FXvcUb5uF5sT367aCek9xD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r2s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r2s1\ntitle: \"Decoupled IF/ID via 1-entry prefetch skid buffer to absorb iStall bubbles\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The cosim CoreMark fitness run drives both buses with ~22% random\n  stall (VexRiscv apples-to-apples methodology). Today's IF stage\n  hard-wires IF/ID payload to `imem_data` combinationally, and when\n  `imem_ready=0` the hazard unit forces `flush_if=1` (NOP injection)\n  and `stall_if=1` (PC holds). Every single iStall cycle therefore\n  costs exactly one retirement opportunity — ID/EX captures a bubble\n  that propagates all the way to WB.\n\n  Meanwhile, when ID stalls for reasons that DON'T involve imem\n  (load-use hazard, dmem stall) the PC reg also holds, so the fetch\n  unit just re-presents the same instruction over and over. Those\n  \"ID-blocked but bus-free\" cycles are wasted fetch bandwidth: IF is\n  fully capable of advancing PC and retrieving the next instruction\n  word during them, but the current tight IF↔ID coupling prevents it.\n  Across the CoreMark trace, load-use + dmem-stall cycles are a\n  non-trivial fraction (MUL/LOAD-heavy matrix kernels, crclist\n  pointer chasing), so prefetching during those cycles creates a\n  reservoir of already-fetched words that can be drained during\n  subsequent iStall cycles — directly recovering lost retirements.\n\n  Prior attempts in this round:\n  - hyp-001-r1s0 (shared multiplier, +9.47%): freed EX-stage logic.\n  - hyp-002-r1s1 (multi-cycle MUL unit, regression): adding stalls\n    without freeing the actual critical path hurts IPC.\n  - hyp-003-r1s2 (IF-stage static BP, regression): any logic on the\n    PC register's combinational fan-in (predecode → target → PC-mux)\n    destroys Fmax on GW2AR.\n\n  This hypothesis differs fundamentally from hyp-003: the prefetch\n  buffer sits on the imem_data→ID path, NOT on the PC register's\n  combinational cone. PC's next-state mux stays identical to today\n  (sequential vs redirect_target). The buffer's valid bit provides a\n  cheap 1-bit enable for the \"drain buffer vs use live imem_data\"\n  mux at the IF/ID output boundary. No new combinational path is\n  added to either the PC flop or the EX→IF redirect network.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure the IF stage into a lightweight decoupled-fetch unit\n  with a 1-entry prefetch skid buffer. Core idea:\n\n  1. Split the PC register logically into:\n     - `fetch_pc`: the address IF requests from imem this cycle.\n     - `commit_pc`: the PC of the instruction currently presented at\n       IF/ID's combinational output.\n     In the common case (buffer empty) these coincide. When prefetch\n     is active they differ by 4 bytes.\n\n  2. Add a 1-entry buffer {valid, pc, instr}. Fill rule:\n     - On a cycle where `imem_ready=1`, IF received a valid\n       instruction for `fetch_pc`, AND ID cannot consume this cycle\n       (load_use_hazard || dmem_stall), latch {valid=1, pc=fetch_pc,\n       instr=imem_data} into the buffer and advance `fetch_pc` by 4\n       next cycle. This captures the \"fetch bandwidth we would have\n       wasted holding PC\" as useful prefetch.\n\n  3. Drain rule:\n     - When `buffer.valid=1`, IF/ID combinational output is drawn\n       from the buffer (not from live imem_data). Its `pc` field\n       comes from `buffer.pc`; `instr` from `buffer.instr`.\n     - When ID consumes (no stall), the buffer is invalidated and\n       `commit_pc` advances to `fetch_pc` (the address IF is\n       currently requesting, which becomes the next retirement's\n       pc).\n     - Under iStall (imem_ready=0) while buffer.valid=1, ID CAN\n       consume the buffered instruction (this is the win): flush_if\n       no longer forces NOP — it only forces NOP when the buffer is\n       empty AND imem_ready=0.\n\n  4. Redirect handling: on EX redirect, the buffer is invalidated\n     unconditionally (its contents are wrong-path), fetch_pc and\n     commit_pc are overwritten with redirect_target, and IF resumes\n     normal single-PC operation. This preserves hyp-003's hard-won\n     lesson: redirect_target → PC mux path is untouched.\n\n  5. imem_addr driving: `io_imemAddr = fetch_pc` (unchanged\n     width/semantics). The FPGA BRAM wrapper sees exactly the same\n     bus protocol.\n\n  Implementation is entirely inside `rtl/if_stage.sv` plus small\n  tweaks to `rtl/hazard_unit.sv` (flush_if gate no longer asserts\n  on imem_stall when buffer.valid=1) and `rtl/core.sv` (no port\n  changes — only if_stage internals). No RVFI port changes, no\n  decoder/ALU changes. Single-issue contract preserved: channel 1\n  stays tied off.\n\n  Expected fitness gain comes from recovered iStall cycles. Under\n  22% iStall × ~15% ID-stall cycles × 1-entry buffer fill/drain\n  statistics, ~3–5% more retirements per cycle under the cosim\n  measurement. Fmax should be neutral: the added logic is a\n  registered 1-entry buffer, a small 2:1 mux at IF/ID output, and\n  simple control — none of which extend the PC flop's combinational\n  cone or the EX→IF redirect path.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Restructure into decoupled-fetch form. Add fetch_pc/commit_pc split, add 1-entry {valid,pc,instr} prefetch buffer with fill-when-id-stalled and drain-when-id-ready semantics. Keep imem_addr=fetch_pc and the redirect override path untouched (redirect invalidates buffer, resets both PCs to redirect_target). IF/ID output mux: buffer.valid ? buffer.{pc,instr} : {fetch_pc, imem_data}. valid bit feeds the new 'fetchable_this_cycle' signal to hazard_unit.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add a new input `if_buffer_valid` from if_stage. Refine flush_if: previously `redirect || imem_stall` → now `redirect || (imem_stall && !if_buffer_valid)`. The buffer can service ID during iStall, so we must not force NOP in that case. stall_if similarly gated: PC-reg (fetch_pc) still holds on imem_stall, but the buffer provides the instruction. Load-use and dmem-stall behavior unchanged except they now also enable buffer-fill when imem_ready=1.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire the new `if_buffer_valid` signal from u_if to u_hazard. No other top-level changes (no port changes, no new modules at top level, RVFI wiring unchanged).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add cocotb tests that exercise the prefetch buffer: (a) steady-state no-stall should still retire 1/cycle with buffer always empty; (b) load-use stall followed by iStall cycle should retire the buffered instruction during iStall (proving the win); (c) EX redirect must invalidate any buffered instruction (no wrong-path retirement); (d) back-to-back iStall bursts with empty buffer still behave identically to baseline (no regression). Each test checks rvfi_order monotonicity (invariant 4) and buffered-instruction correctness against expected PC sequence.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r2s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r2s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777783710573,"end":1777783710588}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm working through the pipeline stall mechanics: instruction memory stalls flush the IF/ID stage to NOP and lose the retirement, while load-use hazards stall and flush the ID stage but preserve the fetched instruction since the PC holds steady. The dSt case appears to be cut off, but I'm tracking how each scenario handles the fetch and decode stages differently.\n\nOnly the iStall cycles (22% of the time) actually lose a fetch opportunity, so I'm considering a prefetch buffer scheme—while ID is stalled on load-use or data stalls, I'd use those idle cycles to speculatively fetch PC+4 into a single-entry buffer, then use that buffered instruction when iStall hits. The math gets complex with the probabilities, but the core idea is decoupling PC management from the stall conditions.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there might be a more direct win: instead of chasing prefetch buffers, I should look at shortening the branch redirect path itself. Right now the redirect is combinational—forwarded operands feed into the comparator, which signals branch_taken, which triggers the PC mux—all in one cycle. If I register the branch target in the EX/MEM stage and have the PC mux pull from that registered value in the next cycle, I could reduce the critical path and potentially improve timing or reduce the redirect latency.\n\nBut that trades off an extra bubble per branch, which without a predictor is just worse overall. So I'm going to stick with the prefetch buffer approach—it's structural, has moderate upside, and doesn't add pipeline depth.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec2a23d9001aoJU0Gg0KIxSD1","sessionID":"ses_213d960adffeY7h4S9ndBjAhb5","messageID":"msg_dec29f3e8001e4invp3JPEeZEe"}}
