{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777784915109,"sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","part":{"id":"prt_dec3d04a1001iGNvPIkeJyp0mX","messageID":"msg_dec3cf4300011cVtBmHterw7Ei","sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","snapshot":"c62ebf2621236675137fce5ca1f65d39c0e20bfd","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777784958441,"sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01F3NaJAdckNigYKGaFMbU4F","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check existing hypotheses directory"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypotheses directory","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypotheses directory","time":{"start":1777784958428,"end":1777784958439}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm working through the structural category for cores/bench/, reviewing what's worked and what hasn't. The shared multiplier was a win, but several critical path optimizations failed—the static branch predictor on the fetch path, the shared subtractor for branches, the skid buffer on decode, and the 16-entry BTB all came up short, so I need to find a different angle that doesn't bottleneck these key stages.\n\nLooking at the current state: fitness is 329.56 versus a baseline of 301.04, with Fmax at 148 MHz but the iteration rate is suspiciously low. The real constraint is LUT budget—I'm at 9905 out of ~10000, leaving only 95 LUTs to work with. The critical path appears to be either in the execute stage around ALU forwarding or in the instruction fetch to PC update. Given these tight margins, I'm considering structural changes like pre-decoding in the fetch stage, pipelining the ALU output paths further, registering branch resolution to shorten timing, or merging the memory and writeback stages to reduce forwarding complexity—though each of these trades off cycle count or adds pipeline depth in ways that could hurt overall performance.\n\nOne promising idea: moving the sign and zero extension of loaded data from the memory stage to the writeback stage. Currently the memory stage handles the shift based on address bits, then the sign/zero extension, all combinationally before the MEM/WB flop—this shift-and-extend path is likely contributing to the critical path, especially since the shift amount varies by 0/8/16/24 bits. If I push this logic into the writeback stage instead, the MEM/WB register just latches the raw data along with the width and sign flags, then WB does the shift and extend combinationally. The forwarding path from MEM/WB would still carry the final extended value since it comes from the writeback mux, so the forwarding latency stays the same while the MEM stage path gets shorter.\n\nBut I need to think through the timing more carefully. Moving work from before a flop to after it shifts where the combinational delay lands—currently it's between the BRAM output and the MEM/WB flop, but if I move it, the delay becomes between the MEM/WB flop and the forwarding mux that feeds into the ALU in the execute stage. If the BRAM output itself has tight timing, the current approach might actually be better since it overlaps the extend logic with the flop delay, whereas the new approach would serialize it after the flop.\n\nI'm also considering whether merging MEM and WB into a single cycle would help, but that would actually make the load-use hazard worse and wouldn't improve branch penalties since they still resolve in EX. A more promising angle is registering the ALU forwarding muxes earlier—computing the forwarded operand values at the end of ID rather than combinationally in EX would shorten the critical path in the execute stage, though I need to verify how that interacts with the forwarding signals themselves. b is only known at WB stage. It's a timing issue - the forwarding decision depends on what's in EX/MEM and MEM/WB at EX cycle.\n\nLet me think about pre-registering operand select signals in ID/EX rather than computing forwarding combinationally in EX. But the forwarding values themselves arrive from registers already, so they're registered - the mux just selects between them.\n\nThe ALU critical path in EX runs through the forwarding mux, then the AUIPC and alu_src muxes, then the ALU itself including the shared multiplier. Moving the forwarding mux into id_ex_t would latch the forwarded operand, but forwarding depends on the current ex_mem rd which only solidifies that cycle, creating a timing issue.\n\nLet me look at actually doable structural optimizations instead. I could remove the branch/jump trap misalignment check from EX since RV32I without C requires 4-byte aligned targets and immediate generation guarantees bit 0=0 for B/J - only JALR can be misaligned. Or I could bypass the MEM/WB register for ALU ops so results write to the regfile in 4 cycles instead of 5, though this complicates RVFI ordering.\n\nFor a targeted approach that works on small FPGAs: I could promote the regfile to true dual-port BRAM with 1R1W, moving write-first bypass logic out of the read path. But on GW2A, regfiles typically use distributed LUTs which is more efficient than burning a whole 9Kb BRAM.\n\nA better idea is relocating WB's regfile write mux into MEM stage - running the mem_to_reg selection combinationally there so MEM/WB just stores the final write value. This makes WB pure wiring and shortens the regfile write path, plus it compresses the forwarding path from MEM/WB. The critical path improvement comes from eliminating that 2:1 mux in the WB stage—by doing the mem_to_reg selection before the MEM/WB flop instead of after, the forwarding path shortens by one mux delay (roughly 1-2 LUT levels). I can also consolidate read_data and alu_result into a single wb_data field in the MEM/WB register, cutting 32 bits of flop overhead. This is a clean structural change that should improve Fmax without affecting IPC.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec3dadb2001rtG4w9RBLHQ0Rs","sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","messageID":"msg_dec3cf4300011cVtBmHterw7Ei"}}
