{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777784993361,"sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_0117QmhsgovK51opYoQpb1Gs","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r3s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r3s1\ntitle: \"Pre-mux write-back value in MEM stage: collapse WB's mem_to_reg mux into MEM/WB register\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The EX forwarding path is a prime Fmax suspect on this core. Today\n  fwd_mem_wb equals wb_stage's output, which itself is a 2:1 mux\n  (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result) sitting AFTER the MEM/WB flop.\n  EX's operand network is therefore: MEM/WB flop → 2:1 mem_to_reg mux →\n  3:1 fwd mux (with fwd_ex_mem and rs?_val) → 2:1 alu_src / AUIPC mux →\n  ALU. That extra 2:1 on the forwarding tail is pure combinational delay\n  piled onto a path that already fans into the ALU cone. Lesson from\n  r1s0 (+9.47%): shaving layers off the EX combinational cone is the\n  single most reliable Fmax lever on GW2AR at this LUT envelope\n  (9905/10000). Recent structural regressions (r2s0 shared-subtractor,\n  r2s1 skid-buffer, r2s2 BTB) all lost by *adding* logic to a critical\n  cone; the dual is to *remove* logic from the same family of cones.\n  The WB-stage 2:1 mux is a clean removal candidate — it does no work\n  that couldn't happen one cycle earlier inside MEM stage, before the\n  flop, where the pre-flop combinational depth (shift + sign/zero\n  extend) is already the MEM critical path and a 2:1 32-bit mux sits\n  comfortably in its shadow.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure the MEM/WB pipeline register: replace the separate\n  `read_data` and `alu_result` fields in mem_wb_t with a single\n  pre-muxed `wb_data` field. mem_stage selects `ctrl.mem_to_reg ?\n  load_data : in.alu_result` combinationally and flops the result\n  once. wb_stage becomes a thin pass-through that just drives\n  `w_en = ctrl.reg_write & valid`, `w_addr = rd`, `w_data = wb_data`.\n  core.sv's fwd_mem_wb port (today wired to wb_w_data, i.e. the\n  mem_to_reg mux output) becomes wired to mem_wb_w.wb_data directly —\n  a register bit, no intervening mux. EX's fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 muxes\n  therefore see one fewer LUT level of combinational delay on the\n  MEM/WB forwarding leg. RVFI's rd_wdata_0 uses mem_wb_w.wb_data\n  unchanged in semantics but with the same one-level-shorter path.\n  The MEM-side premux sits in parallel with the existing shift+extend\n  and ctrl_with_trap logic, not in series with them (both feed\n  distinct bits of the MEM/WB register D-input), so the MEM→flop\n  critical path is unchanged. Net effect: −1 level on the EX\n  forwarding cone, ~32 FFs saved (one of read_data/alu_result collapses\n  into wb_data; the other is gone because RVFI's rd_wdata_0 now uses\n  wb_data and there's no separate \"ALU result for RVFI\" requirement).\n  LUT count should drop slightly too (the WB-stage 2:1 mux is\n  eliminated, the MEM-stage 2:1 mux is added, net zero from muxes;\n  MEM/WB width shrinks by 32 bits → fewer flops to clock and drive).\n  This is the inverse of the r2s0 / r2s1 / r2s2 pattern: remove a mux\n  layer from a critical cone rather than add structure to it.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Replace `read_data` and `alu_result` fields in mem_wb_t with a single `wb_data [31:0]` field. Keep all other mem_wb_t fields (pc, rd, rs?_addr, rs?_val, pc_next, mem_addr, mem_rdata, mem_wdata, mem_wmask, mem_rmask, ctrl, instr, valid) unchanged so RVFI wiring is byte-for-byte identical.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute `wb_data_d = ctrl_with_trap.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result` combinationally (2:1, 32-bit), in parallel with the existing shift+extend and misalign-trap paths. Flop `wb_data_d` into `reg_q.wb_data`. Drop the separate `read_data` and `alu_result` fields in the always_ff block. Hold-wb path still clears valid only, preserving wb_data for the MEM/WB→EX forwarding leg during dmem stalls exactly as today.\"\n  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n    description: \"Remove the mem_to_reg mux. wb_stage becomes a trivial pass-through: `w_en = ctrl.reg_write & valid; w_addr = rd; w_data = in.wb_data`. Update the /* verilator lint_off UNUSEDSIGNAL */ note to reflect that read_data/alu_result no longer exist.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Rewire fwd_mem_wb input of u_ex from `wb_w_data` to `mem_wb_w.wb_data` — the forwarding value is now a direct register output with no intervening mux. Update the RVFI rd_wdata_0 expression to use `mem_wb_w.wb_data` (semantically identical; wb_w_data is still functionally the same after the wb_stage change, but the shorter wire name documents the intent). Add a brief comment explaining the mem_to_reg-premux restructure so future readers don't re-introduce the WB-side mux.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"If any existing probe reads `mem_wb.read_data` or `mem_wb.alu_result` (cocotb hierarchical signal), replace with `mem_wb.wb_data`. Add one directed test: LOAD followed by dependent ALU op (forwarding via MEM/WB→EX) produces the correct operand, proving the new forwarding wiring matches prior semantics. If no such probes exist, this file need not change — leave as a no-op entry.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r3s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r3s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777784993344,"end":1777784993359}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm starting fresh here and need to formulate my approach to this problem.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec3dd33c001zlge7C0oic7YQ0","sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","messageID":"msg_dec3dcb77001wcIpUV5jJc7TaG"}}
