{"type":"text","timestamp":1777784998463,"sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","part":{"id":"prt_dec3e3bef001kztbmNZwYvzvVm","messageID":"msg_dec3e369b001YDXc6zHyQg8vkG","sessionID":"ses_213c30cbeffeBD8l2ED0dpsMo8","type":"text","text":"Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r3s1.yaml`.\n\n**Hypothesis summary (structural):** Collapse the WB-stage `mem_to_reg` 2:1 mux by pre-muxing in MEM stage. Replace `mem_wb_t`'s separate `read_data` / `alu_result` fields with a single `wb_data` field selected before the MEM/WB flop. This removes one LUT level from the EX forwarding cone (MEM/WB flop → fwd mux → ALU), since `fwd_mem_wb` becomes a direct register output instead of the WB-stage mux output. The new MEM-side mux sits in parallel with (not series with) the existing shift/extend/trap logic that already dominates the MEM→flop path, so MEM critical path is unchanged. Also shrinks MEM/WB register width by 32 bits.\n\n**Why this avoids the recent-regression pattern:** r2s0 (shared subtractor), r2s1 (skid buffer), r2s2 (BTB) all lost by *adding* logic to critical cones. This is the inverse — removing a mux layer from the same EX-forwarding cone that r1s0 proved is the Fmax lever on GW2AR.","time":{"start":1777784994799,"end":1777784998460}}}
