{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777785901185,"sessionID":"ses_213b401fbffeeZdL7EzK147fQT","part":{"id":"prt_dec4c107b001IyhZCSPvVzUATW","messageID":"msg_dec4bfec6001qTKMnEyJQL7kHB","sessionID":"ses_213b401fbffeeZdL7EzK147fQT","snapshot":"b4e10c5ba9b96d99d8fe9ad5f454b56e5c6ad01f","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777786101502,"sessionID":"ses_213b401fbffeeZdL7EzK147fQT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EhPnghykfNEmxhqB8pY5HT","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"List existing hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777786101485,"end":1777786101500}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what structural changes have been attempted on the bench core and noticing a pattern—most modifications either regressed performance or had neutral effects. The main culprits seem to be LUT pressure on the fabric when it's nearly full, critical path issues with certain buffer designs, and serialization bottlenecks when merging components. I need to find an approach that hasn't been explored yet.\n\nLooking at the untried angles, I'm particularly drawn to option #6—restructuring how the memory stage handles byte extraction. Currently the critical path runs through data memory output, shifts it based on address bits, then extends it before the register flop. If I move that extraction logic into the writeback stage instead, the memory register would just capture raw data, and the extraction happens combinationally when feeding both the register file and the forwarding path. This trades off some complexity in the forwarding logic but potentially shortens the memory stage's critical path. I'm starting to examine the EX/MEM register structure to see what fields might be redundant or could be optimized. ), branch_target (32), alu_result (32), write_data (32), rs1_val (32), rs2_val (32), rs1_addr (5), rs2_addr (5), rd (5), ctrl (~20), instr (32), valid (1), branch_taken (1), pc (32). That's ~290 bits.\n\nMany of these are RVFI-only (rs1_val, rs2_val, rs1_addr, rs2_addr, instr after certain point, pc, branch_target). Reducing RVFI-only carriers might save FFs but not Fmax much.\n\nWhat about collapsing MEM+WB into a single stage? Then the pipeline becomes IF-ID-EX-MEM, loads return earlier so fewer load-use stalls, and forwarding paths simplify. But dmem_rdata has to feed back through byte-extract and mux to the regfile within one cycle, which could become the critical path.\n\nActually, thinking through the timing more carefully: the load-use bubble exists because dmem is inherently 1-cycle, not because of an extra WB stage. Even if I merge MEM and WB, the LOAD's data still arrives at the end of cycle N+1, and the dependent instruction in EX can't use it until cycle N+2 — same stall. Merging saves one register stage and reduces forwarding mux depth, but doesn't improve IPC.\n\nI'm exploring a few other angles: moving byte-extraction to after the MEM/WB flop to reduce MEM-stage logic, or fusing the PC+4 path used for JAL with the IF-stage adder, though they're in different pipeline stages so that's tricky.\n\nThe byte-extract timing is interesting—if BRAM read latency dominates, pushing extraction to WB could free up MEM slack, but it would lengthen WB's combinational path through the forwarding mux into EX's ALU, so the benefit is unclear. I'm also considering whether pre-registering the forward selects at the end of ID could break the critical path in EX, computing which forwarding source to use before the mux itself runs.\n\nLooking at the actual bottleneck with the 33×33 multiplier at 148 MHz on this FPGA, the critical path likely runs through either the multiplier in EX, the BRAM read plus byte-extraction in MEM, or the regfile read in ID. I'm thinking about issuing the dmem address earlier from the end of EX so the BRAM gets it at the start of the next cycle, rather than waiting for the EX/MEM flop to settle.\n\nCurrently the flow is tight: EX/MEM holds the ALU result, which combinationally drives the dmem address during MEM, BRAM reads and returns data the same cycle, then we extract and flop into MEM/WB. If I issue dmem directly from EX, the address goes out combinationally while EX is computing, so BRAM reads during that same cycle—but this doesn't actually save load-use latency since the data still arrives at the same point.\n\nAnother angle: the regfile has a write-first bypass that adds mux depth to the ID read path. Removing that and relying on explicit WB forwarding instead could shorten the critical path through ID, though it would require careful handling of same-cycle writes.\n\nThe problem is that without the regfile bypass, a dependent instruction reading in ID during the same cycle as a write would get the old value, then move to EX with stale data. By the time EX sees the write, it's already retired and the forward unit won't catch it. So I'd need explicit ID-stage forwarding from WB, which is essentially the same mux I'm trying to remove.\n\nNow I'm exploring whether moving to a BRAM-backed regfile with explicit WB→ID forwarding could work, though that requires dropping the reset loop constraint.  The formal verification issue is that BMC induction needs deterministic reset state — maybe Gowin's ROM-init blocks could set registers to zero without synchronous reset, but that's risky and Yosys might still block inference.\n\nI'm also reconsidering whether I can reduce the EX/MEM register fields that are RVFI-only, but rs1_val and rs2_val are post-forward values that RVFI requires at retirement, so dropping them would break compliance. Similarly, capturing RVFI before forwarding would give stale values instead of the architecturally-visible ones, which also violates the spec.\n\nLet me step back and think about other structural approaches — maybe splitting the decoder into smaller per-opcode-class decoders, or simplifying the data memory response path.\n\nFor the load data extraction, I could pre-register the shift amount and extend select signals in EX/MEM so MEM does a simpler mux, but that's already happening with alu_result and control signals. Converting the barrel shifter to a pre-registered one-hot byte select would probably have similar logic depth anyway.\n\nI'm wondering if moving the reg_write decision earlier to reduce WB fanout would help, or if flattening the pipeline control signals could improve timing.\n\nActually, the more promising angle is bypassing the ID/EX register for ALU operands—I could move the forwarding mux from EX back to the ID/EX boundary by resolving forwarding one cycle earlier in ID, pre-selecting the operand value directly. This removes the forward mux from the EX critical path, though it requires predicting which registers will be available for forwarding during the next cycle based on what's currently in the pipeline. The key insight is moving the bypass mux from the EX stage to the ID stage—shifting it to where there's timing slack. This changes the critical path from regfile read + ID/EX flop + bypass mux + ALU + EX/MEM flop down to just regfile read + bypass mux + ID/EX flop in ID, then ALU + EX/MEM flop in EX. On an FPGA, this might fit within a single LUT level anyway, but the architectural win is clear if EX was the bottleneck. Now I'm working through the timing of when forwarded values become available. At each cycle boundary, instruction A moves from EX into the EX/MEM register with its ALU result, B moves from ID into ID/EX, and C enters the IF stage. By the next cycle, B is in EX and needs forwarding from A (now in EX/MEM) or earlier stages. The key insight is that the ALU result from A gets registered at the end of the current cycle, so it's available as a forwarding source in the next cycle when B executes.\n\nFor ID-stage bypassing, I could forward the combinational ALU output from the current EX cycle, but that creates a long combinational path. Alternatively, I could just forward from MEM/WB (the instruction two cycles ahead) combinationally, which is simpler. But actually, the regfile already handles WB-to-ID bypassing through its write-enable logic—when a write happens to the same address being read, it returns the new data immediately. So the forward_unit really only needs to handle EX-to-EX and MEM-to-EX forwarding, which are the 1-cycle and 2-cycle-ahead cases.\n\nI'm considering whether I can convert the MEM/WB-to-EX forward into a MEM-to-ID bypass instead, checking during ID decode if a LOAD in the MEM stage will write to a register we need. But this is getting complicated. Let me focus on something more concrete and lower-risk.\n\nI'm thinking about collapsing the MEM/WB register to separate RVFI metadata (which only matters at retirement) from the forwarding-critical fields like reg_write, rd, and result. The RVFI fields could live in a shift register or shadow path that doesn't need reset, saving flip-flops. But that's also getting complex. A simpler micro-optimization would be to eliminate rs1_val and rs2_val from the MEM/WB register entirely and route them through a separate pipeline that doesn't require reset, which could trim a few flip-flops without major restructuring.\n\nActually, the real insight is that the MEM/WB register already IS the retirement boundary—the WB stage is just combinational muxing of mem_to_reg that drives the regfile write port. I could merge WB into MEM by doing that mux before the MEM/WB flop, but that exact idea already regressed by 5.66% because the mem_to_reg mux's input (the shift+extend cone from memory reads) extended MEM's critical path when moved earlier. So that's a dead end.\n\nLet me try moving the branch comparator from EX to ID instead, so branches resolve earlier in the pipeline. write_data is redundant with rs2_val, so I can drop it from the EX/MEM register and use rs2_val directly in the MEM stage's write data replication logic—saves 32 flip-flops with minimal complexity. The bigger opportunity though is collapsing EX and MEM into a single stage by issuing the memory address combinationally and using a synchronous BRAM read, which would shrink the pipeline to four stages and cut the branch mispredict penalty in half.\n\nBut wait—the BRAM on the Tang Nano is synchronous only, so the data comes back a cycle later anyway, meaning I can't actually merge those stages without switching to asynchronous reads, which isn't available. Splitting the multiplier across two execute stages also regressed before. The real win might be moving the register file write-first bypass logic out of the regfile itself and into an explicit forwarding path from WB back to ID, which would reduce the combinational depth inside the regfile storage and let me optimize the read port muxing separately.\n\nActually, the core issue is that the combinational bypass might be blocking BRAM inference in the first place. If I keep the regfile as pure synchronous read/write without the bypass mux embedded in it, Gowin might infer BRAM—but that's the same path that broke formal verification before due to the reset loop. I could try vendor pragmas to force BRAM despite the reset loop, but that's risky.\n\nLet me just commit to something concrete: removing the redundant write_data field from the EX/MEM register, since it's just a copy of rs2_val anyway, and feed rs2_val directly into the memory stage's byte replication logic instead. It's straightforward area savings of about 32 flip-flops with minimal impact on timing.\n\nBut that's pretty small. A better angle might be collapsing the three branch control signals into a single 2-bit field—encoding none, branch, jump, and jalr—which saves a bit across the pipeline and simplifies the branch-target mux.\n\nFor something more substantial, I'm considering dual-issue superscalar since channel 1 is currently unused, though that would likely bloat LUT usage on an already-full fabric. Alternatively, moving some decoder logic into the IF stage as predecode could trim the ID critical path, but earlier attempts at similar optimizations regressed. I could also add a dedicated compare unit for branches, though looking at the ex_stage code more carefully, it already has its own branch condition logic separate from the ALU.\n\nActually, here's a concrete idea: eliminate the WB→EX forwarding path entirely by relying on the regfile's write-first bypass, which already handles same-cycle WB writes visible to ID. The key insight is that when an instruction reaches EX, its operands were already captured in ID with the bypass value, so the MEM/WB→EX forward path becomes redundant—but I need to trace through a specific hazard scenario to confirm this actually works.\n\nLet me think through the timing: if instruction I1 writes rd in WB at cycle N, and I3 is in EX at cycle N, then I3's operand was captured when I3 was in ID at cycle N-2. At that earlier cycle, I1 was in MEM, not WB, so the regfile read got the stale value. That means I3 in EX does need the MEM/WB→EX forward to get I1's result—so I can't drop that path after all.\n\nLet me try a different angle: move the forwarding mux into the ID stage itself, so the operand gets pre-registered into the ID/EX boundary. This shortens the EX critical path from [flop → forward mux → ALU → flop] down to just [flop → ALU → flop], since the mux now sits in ID where it has more time to settle before the ID/EX flop. The forward mux would still have three sources—regfile read with bypass, EX/MEM result, and MEM/WB write data—but now it feeds directly into the ID/EX register instead of sitting in the EX datapath.\n\nThe tricky part is getting the timing right: when instruction I_n is in ID at cycle N, I need to forward based on comparing I_n's source registers against the destination registers of the instructions currently in EX (I_{n-1}) and MEM (I_{n-2}), then capture the forwarded value into ID/EX so it's ready when I_n enters EX at cycle N+1.\n\nThe challenge is that if I try to pre-compute the forward mux in ID cycle, I'd need to reach into EX cycle's combinational ALU output, creating a long path from regfile read through the mux to the ID/EX flop. But that doesn't actually help timing—the critical path is still bounded by EX's ALU, just now it's part of the ID cycle instead of the EX cycle. Moving where the flop sits doesn't shorten the total combinational cone between flops. The forwarding sources available at the end of ID cycle N are the EX/MEM and MEM/WB values from cycle N+1, which means I'm tapping the ALU output from the current EX stage and the WB stage output—but this creates a critical path problem since the ALU output arrives at the end of cycle N, and feeding it into the ID/EX flop (which also closes at cycle N's end) makes the path very tight. The real bottleneck is that the pre-forward mux in ID needs to include the combinational ALU output as an input, so the critical path now runs through EX's ALU result feeding the mux and then into the ID/EX flop. The pre-forward mux and ID/EX flop setup need to fit in the same cycle. Looking at the old path—ID/EX flop feeding through a mux before the ALU, then to the EX/MEM flop—versus the new path where the ALU output feeds a mux in the ID cycle before hitting the ID/EX flop, the combinational depth is roughly equivalent, so there's no clear timing win. I'm going in circles here. Let me step back and try a different approach: reducing the load-use hazard by forwarding data directly from the MEM stage instead of waiting for it to reach the WB register.\n\nThe idea is to grab the load data combinationally from the memory output (before the MEM/WB register captures it) and feed it straight into the EX stage's forward mux. This eliminates the one-cycle bubble that normally occurs when a dependent instruction needs the load result. The catch is that the Tang Nano's BRAM has synchronous reads with one-cycle latency, so the data arriving in cycle N+1 is actually the result of the address issued in cycle N. The MEM stage will have the address stable from the EX/MEM register and can drive it to the BRAM, but I need to figure out whether the data is available combinationally during that same cycle or only at the cycle's end. same cycle. NO load-use bubble. But that creates a massive critical path: memory address flows through the BRAM read, extraction logic, forward mux, and into the ALU all within one cycle—likely a Fmax killer on this FPGA. Classical MIPS designs keep the load-use bubble for this reason, and given the fabric is already near full and timing-sensitive, this optimization would probably cause a regression. So I'll skip it.\n\nInstead, I'm considering a narrower approach: issue the memory address from the EX stage combinationally to start the read one cycle earlier. But thinking through it, if the BRAM is synchronous (address latched at the clock edge, data valid next cycle), this doesn't actually help—the timing stays the same. And if the BRAM is combinational, I'd still be trying to read and forward the data in the same cycle, which brings back the critical path problem.\n\nThe real issue is that moving MEM work into EX creates a combined EX+MEM stage with a huge combinational cone: operand forwarding and address calculation feeding the memory, then extraction and shifting feeding back into the pipeline. That's essentially a 4-stage pipeline pretending to be 5 stages, and it failed before when I tried dropping the WB stage. So I'm ruling this out too.\n\nGiven all these constraints, I'm thinking about a more modest change: pre-decode the operand selection in the ID stage by computing alu_a and alu_b (including the is_auipc and alu_src muxes) and registering them into ID/EX. This moves mux depth out of the critical EX path. The catch is that forwarding still needs to override these pre-muxed values, so I'd need to apply forwarding after the muxes in EX—but that might actually work if I'm careful about the ordering.\n\nActually, wait. The is_auipc mux happens after forwarding currently, so pre-muxing in ID doesn't help; EX would still need to bypass the pre-mux when forwarding is active. That's no real win.\n\nLet me go with something cleaner: generate the link value (PC+4) for JAL/JALR directly in the IF/ID stage and carry it through as a separate signal, so the EX stage doesn't need a mux between the ALU result and the link value. Right now EX has a 2:1 mux plus a 32-bit adder just for this, which adds unnecessary fan-in and delay to the result path.\n\nThe idea is to compute PC+4 from the current instruction's PC in the ID stage (where timing is looser) and register it into ID/EX, then in EX just select between the ALU result and this pre-computed link value. The adder moves out of the critical path, potentially gaining 5-10% Fmax on a tight fabric like GW2AR, since ID stage isn't currently the bottleneck.\n\nBut I'm realizing the adder for PC+4 runs in parallel with the ALU during EX—it's a separate cone. If the ALU path is already longer (especially with multipliers), removing the adder won't help much. And the 2:1 mux at the end still exists either way, so the savings might be just one adder depth, which is hard to quantify without synthesis.\n\nStill, it's a clean structural change with minimal regression risk, so I'll go with it. Actually, an even simpler approach just occurred to me: compute link_val (PC+4) in the IF/ID stage and...\n\nWait, that's it—IF already computes `pc + 4` for `next_pc` when there's no redirect. I can tap that directly into IF/ID as `link_val`, then register it through to ID/EX, eliminating the duplicate adder in EX entirely. This shrinks the is_jump cone from [pc → +4 → mux → flop] down to just [link_val → mux → flop], saving one adder stage. It's a modest but clean win if that path was near-critical, probably worth 2–4% on Fmax.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec4f1ebf001mn5jh0n3EDGefG","sessionID":"ses_213b401fbffeeZdL7EzK147fQT","messageID":"msg_dec4bfec6001qTKMnEyJQL7kHB"}}
