{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777786202133,"sessionID":"ses_213b401fbffeeZdL7EzK147fQT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01BtTJnzzqumJrBegP1D9RDF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r4s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r4s1\ntitle: \"Pre-compute JAL/JALR link value (PC+4) in IF stage; drop EX-stage link adder\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  EX stage's EX/MEM.alu_result D-input has two parallel cones that fan into the\n  final 2:1 mux (`is_jump ? pc+4 : alu_result`):\n    (a) the full ALU cone — which includes the shared 33x33 multiplier and any\n        forward mux on operands — the intended critical path.\n    (b) a dedicated 32-bit adder `in.pc + 32'd4` plus the is_jump-select mux,\n        running in parallel off ID/EX.pc.\n  The pc+4 value is NOT derived from EX-stage computation — it is already\n  computed one cycle earlier inside if_stage as `next_pc = pc + 32'd4` (the\n  sequential-fetch path). The duplicate adder in EX is therefore pure\n  redundant silicon whose output only matters for JAL/JALR link-register\n  writeback. On GW2AR at 148 MHz with 9905/10000 LUT4s already consumed,\n  shaving one 32-bit carry-chain adder + its LUT footprint relieves routing\n  pressure near the EX/MEM register, and — to the extent the is_jump mux's\n  non-ALU input was even marginally close to timing — removes a second\n  candidate critical cone from the EX cycle. Prior structural attempts\n  regressed by adding logic depth (r1s1 MUL handshake, r2s1 skid buffer,\n  r3s1 MEM-stage pre-mux); this one STRICTLY REMOVES logic from EX.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Thread a new 32-bit field `link_val` through IF/ID and ID/EX, populated in\n  if_stage from the already-existing `pc + 32'd4` expression (the sequential\n  next_pc, reused at zero marginal cost since that adder sits on an independent\n  PC-register D-input cone that is nowhere near critical). In ex_stage, the\n  EX/MEM register's alu_result assignment changes from\n\n      reg_q.alu_result <= in.ctrl.is_jump ? (in.pc + 32'd4) : alu_result;\n\n  to\n\n      reg_q.alu_result <= in.ctrl.is_jump ? in.link_val     : alu_result;\n\n  dropping the EX-stage 32-bit adder entirely. The `in.pc + 32'd4` expression\n  is deleted; `in.pc` is still consumed by the AUIPC operand path\n  (`alu_a = is_auipc ? in.pc : rs1`), so the pc field stays in ID/EX.\n\n  Expected effects:\n  - LUT: ~30–35 LUT4s reclaimed (one 32-bit carry-chain adder). On 9905/10000\n    utilization this directly relieves routing congestion and may nudge Fmax\n    via placement quality — the same mechanism that punished r2s2 (BTB) and\n    r3s2 (RAS) going the other way.\n  - FF: +32 FFs added (link_val carried through IF/ID's combinational bundle\n    into ID/EX register). Net FF ≈ +32 (well within headroom; current FF=1858).\n    Note: link_val is only present in the ID/EX struct; IF/ID is combinational\n    and imm_gen-equivalent, so no IF/ID flop bump.\n  - Fmax: small positive from removing the parallel adder cone feeding the\n    alu_result mux, conditional on EX-cycle routing being a factor. If the\n    multiplier cone dominates exclusively, Fmax is unchanged and only LUT\n    count moves — still a net area win.\n  - IPC: exactly unchanged. JAL/JALR still write PC+4 to rd, same cycle,\n    same value. No pipeline restructuring, no new stalls, no new bubbles.\n  - RVFI: rd_wdata for JAL/JALR = link_val = pc+4, identical bit-for-bit to\n    the pre-change value. rvfi_pc_wdata continues to be driven from\n    pc_next (the redirect_target/branch_target path), unaffected.\n  - Formal: the structural invariants (is_illegal default, 2-channel RVFI,\n    order monotonic, liveness, memory bounds) are untouched. ALTOPS-mode\n    ALU operations unchanged.\n\n  Risk register:\n  - The alu_result mux is FF-DFF-setup bound; if `in.pc + 32'd4` wasn't\n    actually on a near-critical path, the LUT win is the only lever and\n    Fmax may be flat. Delta could be 0 to +3%, rarely higher.\n  - Gowin synthesis may have already CSE'd the pc+4 adder with the IF-stage\n    next_pc adder if they share a clock domain (unlikely across module\n    boundaries, but possible). In that case the LUT reclaim is smaller.\n  - link_val widens the if_id_t struct by 32 bits (combinational). The\n    decoder/hazard_unit read instr/rs?_addr only; link_val is a tag-along.\n    No fan-out change on the decoder critical path.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\n\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `logic [31:0] link_val` field to both if_id_t and id_ex_t structs. Field carries IF-stage's pc+4 value downstream for JAL/JALR link-register writeback.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Drive `out.link_val = pc + 32'd4` combinationally (reusing the same adder the sequential next_pc path already instantiates; Yosys/synplify should share the carry chain). On flush/redirect, link_val is don't-care (only consumed when is_jump fires, which implies a non-flushed instruction).\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend ID/EX register capture to propagate `in.link_val` into `reg_q.link_val` on the same non-stall/non-flush path as pc/instr/ctrl. Reset clears link_val to '0 like other fields.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace `in.ctrl.is_jump ? (in.pc + 32'd4) : alu_result` with `in.ctrl.is_jump ? in.link_val : alu_result` in the EX/MEM reg_q.alu_result assignment. Delete the now-unused local pc+4 expression. `in.pc` remains used by the AUIPC alu_a mux — do not remove it.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Extend existing JAL/JALR retirement checks to assert rvfi_rd_wdata_0 == pc_rdata_0 + 4 across a handful of directed JAL/JALR sequences (already implied by cosim; this is an explicit cocotb guard against the link_val plumbing dropping the carry into stage flops).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r4s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r4s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777786202128,"end":1777786202133}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing why previous approaches to optimize the pipeline regressed—the multi-cycle stall logic hurt throughput, the prefetch buffer added decoder complexity, and moving the write-back mux created a critical path issue. My new idea is to compute PC+4 earlier for jump instructions rather than waiting until later stages.\n\nThe key insight is that IF already has a PC+4 adder for the next instruction, so I can reuse that for the link register value instead of computing it again in EX. This removes a 32-bit adder from the execution stage's critical path to the EX/MEM register. Even if the ALU multiplier dominates timing, freeing up LUTs in a nearly full fabric could help routing and indirectly improve frequency. The cleanest approach is to move just the link-value pre-compute into IF/ID, reusing existing hardware without cascading complications like trying to also pre-mux the AUIPC operand path, which would still need forwarding logic in EX anyway.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec50412a001NwAAwfBY7FLAJ2","sessionID":"ses_213b401fbffeeZdL7EzK147fQT","messageID":"msg_dec5016b2001V5CBjJkKyXzMzT"}}
