{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777787146397,"sessionID":"ses_213a0ffceffe6YVWFPqTuEDSSK","part":{"id":"prt_dec5f1096001qNM2RjQ2UvvK6n","messageID":"msg_dec5f00ea001CRnYCaxUzGbgSv","sessionID":"ses_213a0ffceffe6YVWFPqTuEDSSK","snapshot":"07bf915b2ac67f76e1cd709f612043f9d88a82cc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777787353182,"sessionID":"ses_213a0ffceffe6YVWFPqTuEDSSK","part":{"id":"prt_dec61d590001ubSuMSIp4X0yx2","messageID":"msg_dec5f00ea001CRnYCaxUzGbgSv","sessionID":"ses_213a0ffceffe6YVWFPqTuEDSSK","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons, the biggest recent win was r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%). Key patterns from successes/failures:\n\n1. Structural refactors that **share existing wires/adders** win (r4s2, r1s0)\n2. Threading pre-computed values **through pipeline registers** loses (r4s1: link_val threading regressed)\n3. **Post-ALU muxes on forwarding path** are expensive on GW2AR\n\nLet me examine ex_stage.sv closely: for JAL/JALR, the ALU computes garbage (rs1+rs2 or rs1+imm), then a **post-ALU 2:1 mux** `is_jump ? (in.pc + 32'd4) : alu_result` selects pc+4 before flopping into EX/MEM.alu_result — which is the forward_ex_mem source. That mux + dedicated +4 adder sits **directly on the EX-forwarding critical path**.\n\nObservation: decoder leaves alu_op=ALU_ADD for JAL/JALR. If I change the EX-stage **pre-ALU** muxes to select `(pc, 4)` when is_jump, the ALU itself computes pc+4 via its existing carry chain. The post-ALU 2:1 mux + dedicated +4 adder both disappear. The pre-ALU muxes only widen from 2:1 to 3:1 (still one LUT4 level). JALR target computation stays on the separate `jalr_sum` path (unchanged).\n\nNet: one LUT level off forward_ex_mem critical cone + ~60 LUTs reclaimed, with zero FF threading. Unlike r4s1 this is purely local to EX — nothing plumbs through pipeline registers.","time":{"start":1777787327888,"end":1777787353181}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777787353191,"sessionID":"ses_213a0ffceffe6YVWFPqTuEDSSK","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01QyLBnnFWpJAqEVuBMzbU12","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r5s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r5s1\ntitle: \"ALU-integrated JAL/JALR link: fold pc+4 into pre-ALU operand muxes, delete post-ALU link mux and dedicated +4 adder from EX forwarding path\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  EX-stage's critical forwarding path today is: forward-mux -> ALU adder ->\n  `is_jump ? (in.pc + 32'd4) : alu_result` 2:1 mux -> EX/MEM.alu_result D.\n  That tail-end 2:1 mux plus its dedicated 32-bit `+4` adder sit directly\n  on fwd_ex_mem, which is the fan-in to the very next instruction's EX\n  operand mux. On GW2AR's near-full fabric (9484/10000 LUT4, lesson\n  r2s2/r3s2 both saw routing-induced Fmax loss well below the LUT cap),\n  shaving one LUT level off that cone and reclaiming ~60 LUTs is a clean\n  Fmax/area win.\n\n  Lesson r4s1 showed threading a pre-computed `link_val = pc+4` *through*\n  ID/EX regressed because it widened pipeline registers and spanned a\n  flop boundary. Lesson r4s2 showed the winning pattern: fold the new\n  behavior onto an *existing* wire with zero new state. This hypothesis\n  applies that pattern — no new FFs, no new pipeline-register fields,\n  the ALU's own adder and its existing carry chain compute pc+4.\nhypothesis: |\n  The decoder already leaves `alu_op = ALU_ADD` for JAL and JALR (the\n  defaults are never overridden for these opcodes). The ALU's output\n  for jump instructions is currently *discarded* — its real role for\n  JAL/JALR is just to hold any 32-bit ADD while branch/jump-target\n  logic runs in parallel. I will repurpose that idle ADD to compute\n  the link value directly:\n\n    always_comb begin\n      if (in.ctrl.is_jump) begin\n        alu_a = in.pc;       // steal the pre-ALU mux\n        alu_b = 32'd4;\n      end else begin\n        alu_a = in.ctrl.is_auipc ? in.pc : rs1;\n        alu_b = in.ctrl.alu_src  ? in.imm : rs2;\n      end\n    end\n\n    // EX/MEM register capture — drop the post-ALU link mux:\n    reg_q.alu_result <= alu_result;   // was: is_jump ? (in.pc+4) : alu_result\n\n  Consequences:\n   - The pre-ALU alu_a mux widens from 2:1 (is_auipc) to 3:1 (is_jump,\n     is_auipc, default) — still fits in a single LUT4 per bit on GW2AR,\n     no depth change.\n   - Same for alu_b: 3:1 {32'd4, imm, rs2}. One LUT4 per bit.\n   - The dedicated `in.pc + 32'd4` adder vanishes — its carry chain is\n     replaced by the ALU's own carry chain, which was idle for jumps.\n   - The post-ALU 2:1 mux (32 LUT4 at one LUT level) is GONE. That is\n     the LUT-level saving on fwd_ex_mem's feeder cone.\n   - JALR target is unaffected: `jump_target = jalr_sum` (= rs1+imm)\n     is already computed on the *separate* jalr_sum adder in ex_stage\n     and is not routed through the ALU — so changing ALU operands for\n     is_jump does not perturb branch-redirect semantics.\n   - JAL target is also unaffected: `jump_target = in.pc + in.imm` is\n     computed on its own adder (shared with branch_target via CSE),\n     separate from the ALU.\n   - Misalign-trap path unchanged: ctrl.reg_write is cleared by\n     ctrl_with_trap on misalign_fault, so the link value is not written\n     even though alu_result now carries pc+4 on a misaligned JAL.\n   - WB stage is unchanged: mem_to_reg=0 for jumps, writes alu_result\n     (= pc+4) to rd. Identical architectural behavior.\n   - Forwarding fwd_ex_mem for a post-JAL dependent (rare but real —\n     e.g. `jal x1, fn; nop` where downstream reads x1) still delivers\n     pc+4, because that value now lives natively in alu_result rather\n     than being mux-selected into it.\n   - RVFI: rd_wdata is driven via WB stage from alu_result; unchanged\n     semantically, value-equivalent to the current design.\n\n  This is structurally a \"merge two adders (ALU-ADD + pc+4) into one,\n  by routing pc+4 through the ALU's idle-for-jumps adder\". It follows\n  exactly the r1s0 shared-multiplier win pattern and the r4s2 share-\n  existing-wire pattern.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend alu_a/alu_b pre-mux to include is_jump case selecting (in.pc, 32'd4). Remove the `is_jump ? (in.pc + 32'd4) : alu_result` selector on the EX/MEM.alu_result D-input; capture alu_result directly. Keep jump_target/jalr_sum/branch_target unchanged. Verify misalign_fault path unaffected.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add (or extend) a test case that issues a JAL followed by an ADDI that consumes rd (x1), confirming the forwarded link value = pc+4 matches the pre-change behavior under zero-wait and under 22% stall.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r5s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r5s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777787353168,"end":1777787353187}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm analyzing the recent winning design—a zero-storage JAL fast-path that gained 17.73%—and reviewing the key constraints that emerged: predictors on near-full fabric degrade fitness, Fmax is the bottleneck for GW2AR, and local recomputation outperforms threading through pipeline registers. The winning approach resolved something one stage earlier using existing wires, so I'm exploring structural optimizations along similar lines.\n\nI'm considering several candidates: early JALR resolution in ID (though this pulls the regfile into the redirect cone), merging MEM and WB stages to cut pipeline depth and flip-flops at a potential Fmax cost, moving branch comparison to ID with early regfile reads, splitting dmem operations, or collapsing load-extend into EX. The pattern that worked best was unconditional resolution on existing wires, so I'm focusing on early branch resolution for register-zero comparisons—these are frequent in CoreMark but would expand ID's redirect cone. I'm also weighing whether to eliminate the MEM/WB register's read_data field through direct forwarding, trim ID/EX register width by removing redundant fields like rs1_addr and rs2_addr that already exist in the instruction encoding, or optimize per-byte dmem writes, though each trade-off risks either critical path impact or forwarding complexity.\n\nNow I'm exploring moving load data extraction into the WB stage instead of keeping it in MEM's combinational path—this would shorten MEM's critical path by flopping raw dmem data and doing shift-extend later, but the extracted value feeds the forwarding mux that drives EX, so it could hurt Fmax. I'm also considering PC+4 adder sharing via carry chains, splitting EX/MEM into an intermediate AGEN stage to shorten the critical path at the cost of deeper pipeline hazards, or collapsing WB's mem-to-reg mux by pre-multiplexing in MEM, though that caused regressions before. I'm leaning toward something safe and structural—possibly early byte-lane shift-extend in EX to prepare load data before it reaches MEM.\n\nLooking at the actual design, branch_target and jump_target both compute `pc + imm` and should already be CSE'd by synthesis. I could also shrink the MEM/WB register by removing unused RVFI fields like rs1_val and pc_next, though synthesis might already optimize those away if they're tied off in the FPGA wrapper. Adding an IF/ID register to pre-decode control bits would introduce an extra pipeline stage with more flushes and bubbles, so that's risky. The most promising structural idea is early branch resolution in the ID stage on existing wires.\n\nFor same-register BEQ/BNE comparisons, I can detect when rs1 and rs2 have the same register number at decode time—BEQ with identical regs is always taken, BNE is never taken—and fold this into the existing redirect mux without needing a regfile read. However, this pattern is rare in CoreMark since compilers prefer JAL for unconditional jumps and beqz is typically `beq rs, x0` with different registers. Exploring lower-level optimizations like carry chain sharing in the EX adder or funct3-based unconditional branch detection doesn't yield much since standard RV32 doesn't have such patterns.\n\nThe more promising angle is reducing LUT levels in the PC-select path. Currently it's a 3-input mux choosing between ex_redirect_target, id_jal_target, or pc+4, which synthesis implements as a priority mux with stall logic—already near-optimal. Moving mem_width control generation earlier to ID-stage won't help since it depends on alu_result[1:0] computed in EX. I'm considering whether extracting the LUI case from the ALU—since LUI just passes the immediate through—could free up resources.\n\nLooking at the actual metrics: Fmax is already at 172 MHz against a 135 MHz target, and LUT usage is at 9484/10000, so I'm hitting real constraints. The CoreMark numbers look corrupted (showing 0.0 per MHz), but fitness is 387.98 somehow. I should focus on reducing LUT pressure to improve routing and timing margin rather than adding complexity. One option is merging the illegal/reg_write suppression from the misalign_fault trap into a single control overlay register. Another is checking whether branch_target and branch_taken fields in the ex_mem_t register are actually dead code—they're set in EX but I need to verify if they're used downstream or if they're just redundant copies.\n\nThe most promising structural idea is moving load alignment (the shift and sign/zero extend operations) from the MEM stage into the WB stage, which would shorten the critical path through the memory pipeline and reduce the combinational depth feeding the MEM-stage flops.\n\nBut there's a catch: the WB stage's forwarding path already feeds back to EX for data forwarding, and adding shift+extend logic there would add multiple LUT levels to that critical path, likely hurting overall timing more than it helps. The real question is whether the MEM-stage load extraction is actually the bottleneck or if the WB forwarding path is already constraining Fmax.\n\nLet me explore a different structural approach: splitting the write-back data path so that ALU results and load results take separate routes through forwarding.\n\nActually, that doesn't work either—loads still need MEM/WB forwarding after the stall bubble, and merging the mux into the MEM stage register just recreates the same critical path problem I already hit with r3s1.\n\nLet me step back and look at what CoreMark is actually telling me. The benchmark runs at 2.25 CoreMark/MHz, which is on target for a 5-stage pipeline, but the 22% instruction and data stall overhead is killing IPC. The real bottleneck is fetch stalls—I'm currently flushing the IF/ID register to NOP whenever there's a stall, but I could instead let imem_data latch through even when stall_id is high, accepting new instructions during stalls rather than blocking fetch entirely.\n\nThe load-use bubbles already provide some natural overlap with istall recovery, but since these are independent random events, that overlap is rare. For LUT reduction, I'm looking at consolidating the decoder's opcode checks and fusing the forward unit's comparators—specifically combining the rs1 and rs2 address comparisons against both the EX/MEM and MEM/WB register destinations into fewer comparator blocks.\n\nThe most promising candidates are dropping dead fields like `branch_target` and `branch_taken` from EX/MEM, and collapsing the ID/EX `rs1_addr`/`rs2_addr` fields by deriving them directly from the instruction bits already stored in the pipeline register—that saves about 30 FFs across the three pipeline stages, though synthesis might already be doing this optimization. An even stronger move would be eliminating the `pc_next` field from EX/MEM since it's only used for RVFI and could be reconstructed.\n\nI'm also considering whether ID-stage early resolution of backward-taken branches when both operands are x0 is worth it, but that's too rare in practice. A more realistic angle is folding the EX-stage misalignment check into the decoder for BRANCH and JAL instructions, since their target alignment is statically determined at decode time—only JALR needs the EX-stage check since it depends on rs1.\n\nThe real structural win might be simplifying the PC mux hierarchy: currently the next_pc combinational path redundantly checks the redirect condition that the PC register's priority mux already handles, so removing that redundancy in next_pc could save a few LUTs without changing functionality.\n\nBut a more substantial optimization would be merging the MEM and WB pipeline stages into one—eliminating the mem_wb_t register (~200 FFs) and its associated forwarding logic. The load result would feed combinationally to the regfile write port, which synchronously captures it; this keeps the same-cycle write-before-read bypass working and doesn't change the load-use bubble behavior, though it does simplify the forwarding path for ALU operations.\n\nThe real concern is that this moves the critical path: instead of the regfile D-input being fed by the WB mux (relatively fast), it now comes directly from the memory read data through shift and extend logic, which is longer. On a fabric that's already 95% LUT-utilized, the tradeoff is whether freeing ~200 FFs and some LUTs outweighs the potential Fmax hit from that longer combinational path.\n\nGiven we're at 9484/10000 LUTs and the previous BTB iteration hit real congestion at 9905, the risk feels high. I should go with something safer.\n\nThe best low-risk option is eliminating the redundant `rs1_addr` and `rs2_addr` fields from the pipeline registers—they're just copies of instruction bits that can be extracted at the point of use. That saves 30 FFs across three stages with essentially no LUT impact, and it might free up just enough routing resources without touching any critical paths. It's modest but safe, probably a 0-2% gain.\n\nI also considered consolidating the misalign detection logic between EX and MEM stages, but they're actually detecting different fault types, so that won't work. The real win is shrinking the EX/MEM register itself since it's the widest one on an already-full fabric. I can drop the dead `branch_target` and `branch_taken` fields, collapse the address fields into instruction bit slices, and remove the redundant PC. The forward_unit and RVFI logic will just read directly from the instruction encoding instead of separate fields. It's a straightforward refactor with high confidence it won't regress.\n\nBut wait — I'm realizing Yosys probably already deduplicates those address flops since they're sourced from the same instruction bits. The synthesis tool sees that `rs1_addr` and `instr[19:15]` both capture the same data at the clock edge, so it might merge them automatically. That means my \"savings\" could be phantom.\n\nLet me pivot to something bolder — the JAL fast-path was the real winner, so what if I extend that to JALR? When `rs1` is `x0` or when the value is already available from forwarding at decode, I could compute the target early and bypass the normal pipeline. The tricky case is JALR with `rs1 = x1` (the return instruction), where I'd need to check if `x1` is being modified downstream and handle forwarding accordingly.\n\nActually, that's too risky — pulling forwarding logic into the ID-stage redirect path would add a 4-way mux, an adder, and alignment checks that'd likely blow past the timing budget.\n\nA safer JALR angle: detect `JALR` with `rs1 = x0` purely from the opcode and register address, then treat it like a JAL using the existing fast-path net. But that's vanishingly rare in real code — compilers don't use `x0` for indirect calls.\n\nI could also try early branch resolution by checking if both operands are available post-forward at ID entry, but that brings a comparator into the ID cone and gets complex fast.\n\nI'm going to commit to a cleaner hypothesis: strip out dead fields from the pipeline registers and any register fields that are just copies of instruction bits, then use that reclaimed headroom to improve routing on the nearly-full fabric.\n\nActually, wait — one more angle: push AUIPC computation to ID since it's just `PC + imm` with no register dependencies. I could pre-compute it there and bypass the ALU in EX. But the ALU's adder is shared across many operations, so removing one use doesn't actually free up hardware.\n\nLet me lock in my real plan. Given the tournament pressure and that IPC is the biggest lever, I'm going after a structural dual-path for JAL link-address bypass — eliminate the mux in EX that selects between `PC + 4` for jumps versus the ALU result by pre-selecting at the ID/EX boundary using a predicted jump bit.\n\nThe current code has a 2:1 mux that picks `PC + 4` for jumps...\n\nActually, I need to trace through the decoder more carefully. For JAL, the control signals default to `ALU_ADD` with `alu_src = 0`, which means the ALU would compute `rs1 + rs2`. But that doesn't match what I expect for JAL's target computation.\n\nLooking at the EX stage, I see that `jump_target` is computed separately from the ALU—for JAL it's `pc + imm`, and for JALR it's the masked sum. The actual `alu_result` that gets written to the regfile is forced to `pc + 4` via a mux when `is_jump` is true. So the ALU is computing garbage for these instructions, and we're using an external 2:1 mux on the critical path to select `pc + 4` instead.\n\nThe idea is to route the link value through the ALU itself by giving JAL/JALR a dedicated ALU operation that computes `operand_a + 4`, eliminating that external mux. This was attempted before as a pre-computation in the IF stage, but it caused a regression.\n\nThe key insight is that threading a pre-computed value through the pipeline stages is what hurt performance, but computing it *within* the ALU using existing operands should be different. The `pc` is already flopped in the ID/EX register, and we just need a `+4` adder, so we could make the ALU handle this directly.\n\nAlternatively, I could push the MEM and WB stages together into a single stage using write-first regfile bypass to maintain same-cycle forwarding—a cleaner structural change, though it carries some risks.\n\nLooking at the critical paths if we merge MEM and WB: the load-extend path through the data memory (shift, extend) plus the mux to select between load data and ALU result feeds directly into the regfile write, eliminating the MEM/WB register entirely. This saves the register itself and simplifies the forwarding logic—loads would incur one bubble for the load-use hazard, then the dependent instruction reads from the regfile after it's been written. The forward unit shrinks since we no longer need MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding, and RVFI retires at the merged boundary instead.\n\nBut RVFI needs a flopped boundary for riscv-formal to observe valid post-writeback state. Collapsing MEM and WB means retirement happens during MEM execution, so we'd have to register RVFI outputs separately—which recreates the register we were trying to eliminate. On FPGA, if the bench doesn't use RVFI outputs, synthesis might drop those flops anyway, but without knowing the bench behavior, this is too speculative. I'm going to step back and focus on a simpler, lower-risk optimization instead.\n\nThe clearest win is trimming dead fields from the EX/MEM register: `branch_taken`, `branch_target`, `rs1_addr`, `rs2_addr`, and the register values are either unused downstream or already captured elsewhere in the pipeline. Removing these frees up register width for routing pressure without touching the critical path or RVFI requirements. I'm exploring whether moving the JAL-link mux off the critical path could improve Fmax—specifically, by separating it from the ALU forwarding chain and handling the pc+4 selection during write-back instead, keeping the regfile write path clean.\n\nBut the tradeoff is real: forwarding stays faster but I'd need extra FFs in mem_wb to carry the link value, and for JAL instructions where the dependent instruction immediately uses x1, I can't skip putting pc+4 in the forward path anyway. Adding a separate mux on the forwarding path doesn't save anything.\n\nI'm settling on the safer approach of just trimming dead fields from ex_mem_t, even though the upside is modest—at least it's honest and won't break anything.\n\nActually, let me try one more angle: instead of muxing after the ALU computes the result, what if I steer the ALU inputs themselves? For JAL/JALR, I'd set alu_a to pc and alu_b to 4, letting the ALU compute pc+4 directly. This moves the 2:1 mux from post-ALU to pre-ALU on the input operands. The mux depth stays the same, but placing it before the ALU might get it off the critical path. The pre-ALU muxes would become 3:1 instead of 2:1, but that still fits in a single LUT per bit with no extra delay.\n\nThe real win is removing that post-ALU mux that sat after the 32-bit adder—that was costing me one LUT level plus the carry chain plus another LUT level. Now it's just the pre-mux LUT plus the carry chain, saving one LUT level overall. And I'm not adding any flip-flops.\n\nThe tricky part is making sure the decoder sets things up correctly: JAL needs is_jump=1 to force the ALU operands to pc and 4, while JALR still computes its target separately via the jalr_sum logic. For non-jump instructions, the muxes behave normally. I'm removing that `is_jump ? (in.pc + 32'd4) : alu_result` post-ALU mux entirely, but wait—that pc+4 adder itself...\n\nActually, it's not a separate adder anymore. The ALU itself becomes the pc+4 adder when is_jump is asserted. So I'm saving roughly 60 LUTs from the mux and the carry chain, plus shaving a LUT level off the forwarding path. This is definitely worth doing.\n\nModifying the operand mux logic in ex_stage to check is_jump and force alu_a and alu_b to pc and 4 respectively, then removing the post-ALU mux and the separate pc+4 expression from the register capture.\n\nFor JALR, the decoder sets alu_src=1 anyway, so the ALU gets fed imm as alu_b, but we don't care about that output since the actual target comes from jalr_sum. And nothing else depends on the ALU result for jumps — branches don't use it, memory operations don't touch it, and writeback just gets alu_result which is now pc+4. Even the misalign fault case is clean since reg_write gets cleared on trap, so the link value doesn't matter.\n\nThis is a solid structural optimization: folding the pc+4 link computation into the ALU input muxes removes the post-ALU mux and dedicated adder from the critical path, saving about 5-8% with minimal risk since it's a clean architectural change.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec61e2ec001mPdTQRUTDE34o7","sessionID":"ses_213a0ffceffe6YVWFPqTuEDSSK","messageID":"msg_dec5f00ea001CRnYCaxUzGbgSv"}}
