{"type":"text","timestamp":1777788352684,"sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","part":{"id":"prt_dec7169bf001tufTyWg03bLtBB","messageID":"msg_dec6f1b55001qY94pyTrvDtUH7","sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","type":"text","text":"Looking at the history, I need to pick a structural angle that learns from the recent wins and failures:\n- r4s2 won (+17.73%) by sharing the existing redirect net rather than adding new muxes\n- r5s0 regressed because regfile port-shape doesn't match Gowin distributed-SSRAM primitives (dual async read + reset-loop blocks inference)\n- r4s0 established that `` `ifdef YOSYS `` (not `initial`) is the formal-safe way to drop the reset-loop in synth\n- Area is the binding constraint (9484/10000 LUT4s)\n\nThe unfinished business is clear: r5o0's failure was diagnosed as \"port shape incompatible.\" The canonical FPGA trick for this — duplicate storage, one array per read port — directly addresses the diagnosed failure mode. This is structural (splits a module's internal topology) rather than micro-opt.","time":{"start":1777788348863,"end":1777788352682}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777788352719,"sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01LGU5JaJytSAnSzrbrUcJcT","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check hypotheses directory exists"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypotheses directory exists","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypotheses directory exists","time":{"start":1777788352705,"end":1777788352717}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what worked and what didn't with previous CPU design attempts—the JAL fast-path optimization gave us the best gains so far, while branch prediction and multi-cycle operations consistently underperformed. Now I need to figure out what structural change might push performance further without repeating those failed approaches.\n\nThe core constraint is tight on area and frequency, so any topology change has to be surgical. I'm considering whether moving the regfile read operation from the ID stage to EX could work—essentially making it a synchronous read that happens later in the pipeline, which might enable BRAM inference and change how forwarding flows through the design.\n\nBut actually, the regfile read is already combinational from the address signals that come out of IF/ID, so that's not really a win. The real question is whether I can eliminate the MEM/WB register for non-load operations to shorten the pipeline, or merge WB into MEM entirely since the write-back stage is mostly just a mux and register driver. The earlier attempt at moving the mem_to_reg mux before the flop regressed though, so that direction seems blocked. A combined EX+MEM stage would just push the critical path problem elsewhere by combining ALU and memory access in one cycle.\n\nWhat I should focus on instead is the regfile itself — using synchronous reads with registered outputs to enable BRAM inference on the GW2AR, though that would shift the timing significantly since the ID/EX stage would see flopped outputs instead of combinational reads. Given that I'm already at 9484/9000 LUTs and 172 MHz (well above the 135 MHz target), the real bottleneck is likely the write-first bypass logic in the regfile creating a combinational path from the WB write signals through to the ID/EX inputs. If I move that bypass logic out of the regfile and into the ID stage or rely more heavily on the existing EX-stage forwarding unit, I could shorten that critical path.\n\nLooking at the forwarding structure, the EX stage already handles MEM/WB forwarding through the forward_unit, which checks the mem_wb_rd tag and selects the write data from the WB stage's output mux. That's actually the same case the regfile's write-first bypass is catching — when a WB-stage instruction writes to a register that ID is reading in the same cycle. So the bypass logic appears redundant, and removing it would both simplify the regfile read cone and allow BRAM inference. The risk is that without the bypass, the ID/EX register would capture the flopped regfile output instead of the combinational forwarded value, but the EX-stage forwarding should still catch the dependency before it matters.\n\nSo the optimization is clear: drop the write-first bypass and rely entirely on EX-stage forwarding. But that's more of a micro-optimization than a structural change. I'm considering bigger architectural moves — converting the regfile to Gowin distributed SSRAM, flattening pipeline stages, or even dual-issue superscalar — but most of these either won't fit in the remaining LUT budget or are too cosmetic. The more interesting angle is eliminating the ID/EX register's rs1_val and rs2_val fields entirely and re-reading the regfile in the EX stage using the registered address fields instead.\n\nBut that would lengthen the critical path: the regfile read would now happen in EX rather than ID, pushing it through the forwarding mux and into the ALU path. The current design already has the values flopped in ID/EX, so moving the read later is a step backward. I could try pre-fetching the regfile read earlier, but that doesn't really help either. What's more promising is compressing the MEM/WB register itself — it's over 400 bits wide with many fields that only feed RVFI (instruction, register addresses, values, memory data, masks, PC). If I split it into a critical path part (rd, write data, write enable, valid) and a separate RVFI shadow register that's read once per retirement, the synthesizer might place them more efficiently without changing the core architecture.\n\nActually, I'm thinking about a more direct structural fix: collapsing the WB stage entirely by moving the regfile write to the end of the MEM stage. This would merge MEM/WB retirement into a single flop, reducing five stages to four. The regfile write happens at the MEM clock edge, and RVFI fires at MEM output. Load-use hazards stay the same (one bubble), but forwarding simplifies — I'd only need EX→MEM forwarding since the MEM result is already in the regfile the next cycle. The \"two-ago\" forward path disappears because that data is now readable through normal regfile reads. This is more invasive structurally, but it could be cleaner overall.\n\nOr here's another angle: split the EX stage's ALU and branch comparator from the redirect-target adder. Right now EX computes the branch condition, branch target (pc+imm), jump target (pc+imm or rs1+imm), and muxes them all together — that's a long critical path. If I move the branch target calculation to ID stage...\n\nWait, that doesn't actually help. The pc+imm is already computed in parallel with the ALU in EX, so moving it upstream doesn't shorten the critical path. The real bottleneck in EX is the forwarded operands flowing through the comparator or ALU, then into the redirect target mux. The actual critical path is (forwarded rs1/rs2) → (comparator or ALU) → redirect target mux, and that's where I need to focus.\n\nLooking at what's actually in EX: forward muxes, the ALU with its carry chain and shifter, the branch comparator running in parallel per the earlier lesson, the redirect target mux, and misalign detection. The multiplier or shifter is probably the longest combinational chain. Maybe I should pipeline just the multiplier into its own stage for M-extension operations, but that just adds another stage without really solving the problem.\n\nLet me try a different angle: move the regfile write-first bypass logic out of the regfile module and into the ID stage as an explicit WB→ID forwarding mux. This would shorten the regfile read path and might let Yosys infer distributed SSRAM for the registers, though the asynchronous reads and reset loop might still prevent inference. But at least it's a clean structural change that doesn't touch EX's critical path.\n\nActually, the next thinking suggests resolving branches at the end of ID by forwarding rs1/rs2 values there, but that requires adding forwarding paths into ID itself, which hits the same PC cone pattern that's been failing. The distinction is that r5s2 was speculative prediction, whereas actually resolving branches at ID needs the forwarded operand values before the ID/EX boundary—that's a new mux that adds delay to the PC path.\n\nGiven the tight LUT budget, I should pick something well-scoped. Collapsing IF and ID into a single fetch+decode stage is tempting since IF already emits a combinational bundle that ID consumes and registers into ID/EX, so they're effectively already coupled.\n\nWait, that means IF+ID is already one cycle—the pipeline is really IF/ID, EX, MEM, WB (four register boundaries), not five. So that structural change is already done.\n\nLet me commit to a concrete hypothesis: duplicating the register file using Gowin distributed SSRAM blocks, where each read port gets its own RAM instance with the same data, plus simultaneous writes to both copies. This sidesteps the dual-read-port limitation and makes the port shape compatible with Gowin primitives.\n\nThe area cost is 2x regfile storage, but distributed RAM could actually save LUTs and FFs compared to flip-flops. The formal reset-loop still works fine—the issue is purely synthesis-side port shape compatibility on Gowin. But here's the catch: with the reset-clear loop preserved, Yosys won't infer distributed RAM anyway because Gowin distributed SSRAM has no reset. So I need both the port duplication AND a synthesis-only guard to drop the reset-clear, using `` `ifdef SYNTHESIS `` rather than `initial` to avoid breaking formal verification.\n\nThis is getting tangled. Let me step back and propose something cleaner: hoist the write-first bypass mux out of the regfile entirely and move it to the ID/EX pipeline as a forwarding mux, then split the regfile into two single-read-port instances—one for rs1, one for rs2—with writes going to both. This shortens the read critical path, matches Gowin's port shape requirements, and keeps the formal reset loop intact. Or if I want to be even more robust, I could drop the rs1_val and rs2_val fields from the MEM/WB and EX/MEM pipeline stages entirely to reduce area pressure.\n\nActually, the cleaner move is to push the load data shift and sign-extend logic downstream: store raw dmem_rdata plus the address low bits and metadata in MEM/WB, then do the shift and extend combinationally in the WB stage right before the regfile write. This cuts the critical path into the MEM/WB flop's D-input by removing the shift-extend cone, though it costs a few extra bits in the pipeline register.\n\nBut wait—mem_sext and mem_width are already in the control signals that flow through MEM/WB, and alu_result is already there too, so I don't actually need new fields. The tradeoff is that this lengthens the WB-stage's w_data path to both the regfile and the EX forwarding mux, which reintroduces the shift-extend into the forward path. That's a regression like the earlier r3s1 pattern.\n\nSo instead I'm going to restructure the regfile itself: split it into two independent single-read-port arrays to enable Gowin's distributed SSRAM inference, and move the WB-to-ID forwarding bypass out of the regfile module into a dedicated mux in the ID stage. This is a cleaner structural change that shortens the regfile read cone without pushing latency elsewhere.\n\nI'll guard the reset logic with a `ifdef SYNTHESIS` directive so formal verification still sees the reset-loop but synthesis can infer no-reset distributed RAM. The key insight from the earlier r4s0 lesson is that `initial` blocks break formal by lifting to universal constraints, so the ifdef guard is the right pattern here.\n\nActually, I need to verify whether Yosys automatically defines `SYNTHESIS` — it turns out the build scripts would need to pass `-DSYNTHESIS` explicitly, which I can't modify. But Yosys does always define `` `ifdef YOSYS `` when using its read_verilog frontend, so I'll use that guard instead. This combines the viable macro strategy from r5s0 with the dual-port register file split to match Gowin's distributed SSRAM primitives.\n\nLet me verify the current regfile port shape — it has 2 async read ports and 1 sync write port, and I need to check whether Gowin's LUT-based distributed RAM can handle this configuration.\n\nLooking at Yosys's Gowin support, the distributed RAM primitives like SDPB are limited to clocked ports, and LUT-based inference depends on rule matching. The safest approach is splitting into two independent single-read-port arrays that both receive writes, which should reliably trigger inference regardless of which primitive Yosys picks.\n\nSo I'm going with a dual-storage register file where writes broadcast to both arrays, guarded with the `ifdef YOSYS` macro, keeping async reads per port and the write-first bypass logic.\n\nBut stepping back, I'm wondering if there's a more impactful structural change here. I could add a second execute slot for simple ALU ops to get true dual-issue capability, but that's prohibitive at 516 LUTs remaining. Bypassing the MEM stage for non-memory ops doesn't actually save cycles since the EX/MEM flop still exists. Collapsing MEM for ALU ops would reduce pipeline depth from 4 to 3 stages, but it adds arbitration complexity between MEM and WB writebacks.\n\nThe dual-storage regfile is cleaner and addresses a real inference bottleneck. But I'm also considering pipelining the multiplier output with an extra flop between the 33x33 multiplier and the ALU mux, creating a pseudo-EX2 stage that could improve timing without major area cost.\n\nActually, that won't work — r1s1 already tried multi-cycle MUL/DIV and it regressed. The lesson was clear: pipelining only helps if the multiplier is provably the critical path, and I don't have fresh timing data to confirm that.\n\nLet me refocus on what actually worked before. The r4s2 win came from reusing the existing redirect network rather than adding new PC-select inputs, and r5s2 failed because extending the fast-path doubled the pipeline-register consumers. So what if I try a JALR fast-path at ID that only fires when rs1 doesn't need forwarding — using the ID-stage regfile read directly and redirecting early, with a fallback to EX resolution if forwarding is required? This adds a lightweight dependency detector at ID and a conditional mux, which is much simpler than the previous attempts.\n\nThat could save the EX bubble for maybe 5% of dynamic JALRs, mostly function returns. But it's starting to feel like predictor territory rather than pure structure, and the redirect arbitration gets messier.\n\nI think I should just commit to the dual-storage regfile — it's well-scoped, learned from r5s0, and fits the structural category cleanly. Or maybe try splitting the EX/MEM register's control bundle into a critical subset for actual execution and an RVFI-only subset for debugging, which would reduce register pressure and pipeline width without adding new logic.\n\nActually, the more compelling idea is collapsing the WB stage into MEM entirely — make the regfile write happen at the MEM clock edge instead of WB, keeping mem_wb as a shadow register just for RVFI. This simplifies the forwarding unit since we'd only need one forward level instead of two, and it genuinely changes the pipeline depth and hazard structure.\n\nThe load-use hazard stays the same (still needs a 1-cycle bubble), but the key insight is that the 2-ago forwarding path gets absorbed into the regfile's write-first bypass behavior, so we can eliminate the MEM_WB forwarding mux in EX and save LUT levels.\n\nFor RVFI, we'd decouple retirement from the regfile write — the MEM/WB flop would only drive RVFI while the actual write happens at the MEM clock edge. This works as long as we capture rvfi_rd_wdata at write time in the flop, though it does risk breaking rvfi_order monotonicity if not careful. The real concern is whether this shortens the EX forward cone enough to improve Fmax, especially since moving load-data routing pre-flop has historically caused regressions.\n\nIf I collapse the WB stage and write the regfile combinationally from MEM outputs, writes shift earlier by one cycle — but load-use hazards still require a bubble since the consumer can't read the written value until the next cycle anyway.\n\nActually, wait. With write-first bypass checking w_en and w_addr combinationally during the same cycle, if I drive w_en directly from MEM-stage logic (not the mem_wb flop), then during the cycle a LOAD is in MEM, w_en is already asserted with the load data available combinationally. A consumer in ID that cycle could bypass directly to that value, potentially eliminating the load-use bubble entirely — a significant IPC improvement.\n\nBut load_data is...\n\nHmm, the path from memory read through shift, extend, the write-back mux, and into the bypass logic feeding back to ID is extremely long combinationally. That critical path would almost certainly violate timing at 172 MHz.\n\nSo the IPC win isn't worth the Fmax hit. Better to accept the load-use bubble but optimize non-load writes: move ALU results to regfile at the end of the MEM cycle instead of waiting for WB, while keeping LOADs writing at their current WB timing. But now I need to clarify the exact cycle boundaries — when an instruction in MEM writes versus when it transitions to WB.\n\nActually, trying to split the write paths between ALU and LOAD creates too much complexity with arbitration. I'm going to commit to the dual-storage regfile approach instead, which should let the synthesis tool infer distributed RAM properly on the GW2AR.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec71749200107NPnCBaqJe5oC","sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","messageID":"msg_dec6f1b55001qY94pyTrvDtUH7"}}
