{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777788380293,"sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_012MLHNWSCCdjUU19FR4bxWe","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r6s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r6s1\ntitle: \"Dual-storage regfile with YOSYS-guarded reset for GW2AR distributed RAM\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The regfile currently synthesizes to 1024 discrete FFs plus a dense\n  read-mux tree. On a near-full fabric (9484/10000 LUT4s, 1861 FFs),\n  reclaiming 1000+ FFs and a chunk of LUT area is the biggest\n  area-unblock available short of superscalar.\n\n  Prior attempts at distributed-SSRAM inference (r3s0, r4s0, r5s0) each\n  identified one of the two blocking conditions but not both at once:\n  (a) r5s0 diagnosed the port-shape mismatch — 2 async read ports +\n  1 sync write does not match any single Gowin LUT-RAM primitive;\n  (b) r3s0/r4s0 diagnosed the reset-loop blocking no-reset SSRAM\n  inference, with `ifdef YOSYS` guard the remaining viable pattern\n  after `initial` was shown to poison formal via universal SMT\n  initial-state constraints.\n\n  The canonical FPGA workaround for (a) is to duplicate the storage\n  array so each read port owns its own single-read-port RAM. Writes\n  broadcast to both copies. This is structural: it splits one module's\n  storage topology into two parallel instances. Combined with (b), it\n  removes both blockers simultaneously.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure `rtl/reg_file.sv` into two independent storage arrays,\n  `regs_a[0:31]` and `regs_b[0:31]`, each holding an identical copy of\n  the architectural register state. `rs1_data` reads only from\n  `regs_a`; `rs2_data` reads only from `regs_b`. Writes on `w_en`\n  broadcast to both arrays at the same clock edge.\n\n  Each storage array is now a 32x32 memory with exactly one async read\n  port and one sync write port — the shape Yosys's memlib pattern-matches\n  to Gowin distributed LUT-RAM (SDPX / RAM16SDP-style primitives on\n  GW2AR). The 32-deep 32-wide geometry maps to 8 LUT4-RAM16 columns per\n  copy (small compared to 1024 FFs).\n\n  Guard the reset-clear loop with `ifdef YOSYS` so Yosys/synth sees\n  no reset (enabling no-reset distributed-RAM inference on Gowin) while\n  Verilator, cocotb, and SBY/riscv-formal flows still see the explicit\n  reset-to-zero (preserving the `reg_ch*` formal check's deterministic\n  post-reset anchor that r3s0 broke).\n\n  Keep the write-first bypass combinational logic as-is on both arrays\n  — it catches the same-cycle WB→ID case and is redundant with EX's\n  `fwd_mem_wb` path but is cheap (one 2:1 mux per read port) and\n  shortens one edge case.\n\n  Expected area effect on GW2AR: ~900–1000 FFs freed (both regfile\n  copies inferring as distributed LUT-RAM rather than 1024 FFs), modest\n  LUT-RAM cost (~64 LUT4s for 2 copies of 32x32 SDPX), net LUT4/FF\n  headroom recovered. Net Fmax effect: slightly positive to neutral\n  (looser placement on a less-full fabric; async-read-port cone\n  unchanged in structural terms). Net IPC: unchanged (architecturally\n  identical regfile from the pipeline's perspective — both copies hold\n  identical state every cycle).\n\n  Formal correctness: both arrays reset to zero under the non-YOSYS\n  path, so `reg_ch*` BMC still anchors on all-zero initial state.\n  Under ALTOPS (riscv-formal) the `ifdef YOSYS` branch is irrelevant\n  because formal is driven by sby + yosys → bitwuzla, which does see\n  YOSYS defined — so we add `ifndef RISCV_FORMAL` as a secondary guard\n  to keep formal on the resetting path. Concretely:\n      `ifdef YOSYS\n      `ifndef RISCV_FORMAL\n      // synth-only: no reset, enables distributed RAM\n      `define REGFILE_NO_RESET\n      `endif\n      `endif\n  The reset-clear loop then lives under `ifndef REGFILE_NO_RESET`.\n  riscv-formal's flow always defines RISCV_FORMAL (checks.cfg), so it\n  takes the reset-preserving path; cocotb/Verilator don't define YOSYS,\n  so they also preserve the reset; only the Gowin synth flow hits the\n  no-reset path.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n    description: \"Split `regs` into two independent single-read-port arrays `regs_a` (drives rs1_data) and `regs_b` (drives rs2_data). Writes broadcast to both on the same w_en. Guard the reset-clear for-loop with `ifdef YOSYS` + `ifndef RISCV_FORMAL` so synth sees no-reset (enabling Gowin distributed LUT-RAM inference) while Verilator/cocotb/SBY still see the deterministic reset-to-zero that riscv-formal's reg_ch* check anchors on. Preserve write-first bypass muxes per-port.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a sanity test that writes a pattern to x5..x10 and immediately reads back via two successive instructions to exercise both read ports — asserts both ports see the same committed state. Serves as a regression guard that the dual-array broadcast stays in sync.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r6s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r6s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777788380273,"end":1777788380290}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_dec718673001ObRkW5OBf6XTXy","sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","messageID":"msg_dec718131001Esn6lq2V7pkOZW"}}
