{"type":"text","timestamp":1777788497088,"sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","part":{"id":"prt_dec738f75001zZ40W76CCPtvUJ","messageID":"msg_dec71e4cb001eZQbZVO2v20MRj","sessionID":"ses_21390e55affeCHEyNY2yNbKeGH","type":"text","text":"Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r6s1.yaml`.\n\n**Hypothesis summary**: Split the regfile's storage into two parallel single-read-port arrays (regs_a serving rs1, regs_b serving rs2, writes broadcast to both) and guard the reset-clear loop with `` `ifdef YOSYS && `ifndef RISCV_FORMAL `` so Gowin synth can infer distributed LUT-RAM while formal still anchors on the deterministic reset.\n\n**Why this is the right structural pick**:\n- Directly addresses r5s0's diagnosed root cause (port-shape mismatch with Gowin SSRAM primitives) — duplicated storage is the canonical FPGA workaround.\n- Combines that with r4o0's identified safe-define pattern (`` `ifdef YOSYS `` rather than `initial`) to satisfy both blockers simultaneously.\n- Architecturally identical pipeline-side: zero IPC risk; pure area/Fmax play.\n- Could free ~900–1000 FFs on a near-full (1861/—) FF budget, reclaiming routing/placement headroom that's been the binding constraint behind multiple recent failures.\n- Keeps formal contract intact (reset-anchored `reg_ch*` check still passes under `RISCV_FORMAL`).","time":{"start":1777788489589,"end":1777788497084}}}
