{"type":"text","timestamp":1777789989778,"sessionID":"ses_213776dfdffecrYqQbMmcvyfjT","part":{"id":"prt_dec8a6551001a5NkhrcWWtM15Y","messageID":"msg_dec8892bb001a1L92Yxl0qLPad","sessionID":"ses_213776dfdffecrYqQbMmcvyfjT","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons carefully:\n- Winning structural patterns: share a single expensive cell across opcodes (r1s0 shared multiplier: +9.47%)\n- Avoid: predictors that add PC-mux fanin, formal tarpits (regfile reset, link-value folding, MEM-stage refactors)\n- r4s2 (JAL fast-path) already harvested the zero-storage-one-stage-earlier win on the unconditional case\n\nLooking at ex_stage.sv there's a structural CSE opportunity: three parallel adders compute the same class of sums (pc+imm / rs1+imm) that the ALU's internal adder already computes for AUIPC/JALR. `branch_target = in.pc + in.imm` and `jalr_sum = rs1 + in.imm` are unnamed-but-structurally-independent duplicates of the ALU's ADD cone because the ALU's operand muxes don't cover BRANCH/JAL. Unifying this is similar in character to r1s0's shared 33-bit multiplier win — one shared cell, shorter net of critical cones, no RVFI change, no formal state-space change.","time":{"start":1777789986129,"end":1777789989777}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777789989808,"sessionID":"ses_213776dfdffecrYqQbMmcvyfjT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01L4KksKuumCpo8dmKsSLbk9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head","description":"List existing hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777789989793,"end":1777789989806}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what worked and what didn't—the JAL fast-path optimization succeeded by handling jumps earlier in the pipeline, while most other predictor attempts hit resource constraints or timing issues. The key insight is that simple, early-stage optimizations that avoid adding complexity tend to win over more sophisticated approaches that strain the design.\n\nNow I'm considering structural changes to the pipeline itself. Moving the misaligned-trap check from EX to MEM could reduce the combinational logic in the execute stage, though the real win might come from reconsidering where branch resolution happens—pushing it earlier to ID stage could cut the misprediction penalty, but I need to verify whether that's actually feasible given the current decode logic.\n\nThe more promising angle is collapsing MEM and WB into a single stage: it eliminates the MEM/WB register and saves flip-flops, and while it doesn't improve load-use hazards (still one bubble since the data isn't available until the end of MEM), it does simplify the forwarding paths. The critical path concern is real though—combining load extraction with writeback might lengthen the cycle time.\n\nI've also considered moving the sign/zero-extend logic around, but r3s1 already tried shifting the mem_to_reg mux earlier and it regressed performance, so that's risky territory. Registered forwarding muxes or splitting the EX/MEM register would just add complexity without real gains.\n\nLooking at what's actually on the critical path: the decode side (imem_data through decoder to hazard unit), the EX side (forwarding muxes through ALU to redirect logic), and the MEM side (dmem_rdata through shift and sign/zero-extend). The branch comparator is already separate, but the real bottleneck is the chain from forwarding through the compare to the PC mux in IF. Static branch prediction with predicted-not-taken is what we're already doing, so that's not a lever either.\n\nWhat's interesting is that r4s2 won by moving JAL resolution from EX to ID with zero storage overhead. I'm wondering if JALR target computation could move to ID too, but that requires forwarding since JALR can use a recently-written register—and adding a forwarding mux on the ID register read path would just shift the critical path problem. The async register file read is already combinational anyway.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the pipeline is already effectively four stages (IF→ID→EX→MEM) with WB just being register-file writes and RVFI retirement from the MEM/WB register. So combining IF and ID into a single stage—letting decode happen in the same cycle as instruction fetch—might be worth exploring.\n\nBut wait, looking at the code structure, IF and ID are already combinational! The IF/ID transition has no register; the PC sits in the IF stage and the instruction flows combinationally into ID. The first actual flop boundary is ID/EX. So when a branch mispredicts and the hazard unit sets both flush_if and flush_id, it's squashing two instructions: the one in the combinational IF/ID path and the one about to capture into the ID/EX register. That's still a 2-cycle penalty.\n\nActually, let me trace through the timing more carefully. When the branch resolves at EX, a fall-through instruction would already be in ID and capture into ID/EX the next cycle, reaching EX the cycle after that. With a redirect, ID gets a bubble instead, IF fetches the new PC, and the redirected instruction doesn't reach EX until 3 cycles later—so that's 1 bubble of penalty on top of the base latency.\n\nNow, could we move JAL resolution earlier to ID to eliminate that penalty? And what about the forwarding paths—specifically, can we simplify the MEM/WB forwarding by leveraging the regfile's write-first bypass so that ID reads the updated value directly when WB writes the same cycle?\n\nThe regfile's write-first behavior means if ID reads rs1 while WB is writing to the same register, ID gets the new value immediately. But the forwarding mux currently handles cases where the writer is one or two cycles ahead of the current instruction. Let me trace the timing to see if write-first bypass alone is sufficient or if we still need the forwarding logic. I'm exploring whether we can optimize the forwarding path itself. The MEM/WB→EX forward currently requires a mux to select between the ALU result and memory read data, which sits in the critical path. I considered pre-computing the write data at the MEM stage and storing it directly in MEM/WB to avoid this mux, but earlier attempts like r3s1 showed this doesn't help—moving the mux before the flop just makes it serial with the shift-and-extend logic instead. I'm thinking through whether there's a different structural approach that could actually reduce latency.\n\nLooking at what's worked before, I notice that zero-storage solutions and shared hardware (like the 33-bit multiplier) have paid off, while adding extra muxes or LUTs tends to hurt. So I'm now considering whether there are simplifications in the decoder's control encoding or the hazard unit's priority logic that could free up resources, or if there's a way to optimize the EX stage itself.\n\nActually, I'm spotting something concrete: the EX stage has a separate JALR adder that duplicates work the main ALU already does. For JALR instructions, the ALU is already configured to compute rs1+imm, but then ex_stage computes jalr_sum independently as another addition. If I route the ALU's result directly instead of maintaining this duplicate adder, I could eliminate hardware without changing the datapath timing.\n\nThe same issue exists for branches — the ALU computes rs1+rs2 (which gets discarded), while a separate adder computes pc+imm for the branch target. I could unify this by having the ALU compute the branch target directly when needed, though the compare logic is already separate and working fine.\n\nThe real win here is eliminating the redundant `jalr_sum` adder since the ALU already computes rs1+imm for JALR instructions. Yosys might already be combining these through common subexpression elimination, but if not, I can explicitly reuse the ALU result for the jump target calculation.\n\nReusing alu_result for JALR... I'm realizing the ALU operand muxes could be extended to handle branches and jumps—routing pc and immediate through the ALU instead of using separate adders. This would eliminate the redundant branch_target and jalr_sum adders, potentially saving ~64 LUTs. The tricky part is that for JAL/JALR, the link address (pc+4) needs to go to the register file while the computed target goes to pc_next, so I need to preserve both values or rethink the datapath slightly.\n\nRefining the approach: I'll make alu_result always compute the right value for each opcode—pc+imm for branches/JAL, rs1+imm for JALR, rs1±rs2 for arithmetic—then use alu_result directly as branch_target and jump_target. For branches, the comparison still uses rs1 and rs2 separately, which is fine since alu_result goes unused anyway. The ALU operand selection logic gets a bit more complex...\n\nAdjusting the mux controls... Looking at the actual ex_stage.sv implementation, I can see the operand muxes are already set up for PC or rs1 on alu_a, and imm or rs2 on alu_b. To route branch and JAL targets through the ALU, I'd just add the extra select conditions to both muxes, then feed alu_result directly to branch_target and jump_target—eliminating those two separate 32-bit adders and saving roughly 64 LUTs. The critical path concern is whether routing through the full ALU adds latency compared to the dedicated fast adders, but since both paths involve operand wiring plus a 32-bit add, the depth should be similar.\n\nHowever, the ALU's case mux that selects between ADD/SUB/SLL and other operations could become the bottleneck for branch targets. To avoid that overhead, I can extract the raw adder output as a separate wire before the case mux, then feed branch_target and jump_target directly from that intermediate result—this way we share the adder hardware without paying the case-mux depth penalty.\n\nThe real win here is consolidating what are currently three separate adders into one. Yosys might already CSE some of them, but the operand muxes differ between the ALU's adder (which handles both pc+imm and rs1+imm depending on control signals) and the standalone branch/JALR adders, so Yosys likely can't unify them automatically. By explicitly routing PC and immediate through the ALU's operand muxes for branch operations, I force a single shared adder and eliminate the redundancy.\n\nI should also note that pc+4 gets computed twice in the pc_next logic, so there's another small win in sharing that as well. The hypothesis is solid—let me write this up as a proposal to unify the target-address computation through the ALU's existing adder path.\n\nOne thing I'm being careful about: the r5s1 lesson showed that folding JAL's link-value (pc+4) into the ALU via pre-ALU muxes caused formal verification issues. But my proposal doesn't fold pc+4; it folds branch_target and jalr_sum, which are already computations the ALU performs. The link-value stays separate, so I should avoid those formal issues. I'm routing the ALU's operand muxes so that pc feeds into the adder for AUIPC/BRANCH/JAL, and rs1 for JALR/LOAD/STORE/other instructions, then exposing the raw adder output as a shared wire to feed both branch and jump target paths — this eliminates the duplicate branch and JALR adders and should save 40-80 LUTs without affecting critical path depth. The decoder and RVFI fields stay unchanged, though there's a risk Yosys already CSE'd these adders, making the optimization a no-op.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec8a70950010hFacI1anjnifx","sessionID":"ses_213776dfdffecrYqQbMmcvyfjT","messageID":"msg_dec8892bb001a1L92Yxl0qLPad"}}
