{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777791934944,"sessionID":"ses_2135addceffe4De8hDdLDQJTTs","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015UeA91hdcKYPrPrmjg2SBQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r8s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r8s1\ntitle: \"Flatten EX redirect cone: distribute misalign into per-arm align-check\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The EX-stage `redirect` net feeds IF's PC-select mux and is on the\n  fetch-redirect critical path — any LUT-level we can remove there\n  translates directly into Fmax on GW2AR's near-full fabric. Today\n  the cone is an AND-of-OR structure: redirect = (BT || (J &&\n  !JP)) && !misalign_fault, where misalign_fault = (is_branch &&\n  BT && misalign_branch_target) || (is_jump && misalign_jump_target).\n  The branch_taken signal appears in BOTH operands of the outer AND\n  (directly in the first OR, and transitively via misalign_branch\n  in the second OR), forcing Yosys to realize the compare-compute\n  and align-check as a serial chain feeding the `redirect` wire\n  rather than two parallel-then-combined cones. This lengthens the\n  EX→IF redirect path by ~1 LUT level on this fabric.\n\n  Seven prior slot-1 structural attempts have all regressed or\n  broken formal — the survivors were those that stayed local (no\n  id_ex_t edit, no PC-mux widening, no cross-flop mux moves, no\n  new storage). This hypothesis is chosen to satisfy ALL of those\n  constraints simultaneously.\nhypothesis: |\n  Reorganize ex_stage.sv's `redirect` expression from AND-of-OR\n  (current form) to OR-of-AND (distributed form), folding the\n  misalign detection into each branch/jump arm independently:\n\n    branch_target_aligned = (branch_target[1:0] == 2'b00);\n    jump_target_aligned   = (jump_target[1:0]   == 2'b00);\n    redirect = (branch_taken && branch_target_aligned)\n            || (is_jump && !jal_predicted && jump_target_aligned);\n\n  The trap-side `ctrl_with_trap` and `pc_next` muxes stay unchanged\n  (same misalign_fault definition drives them, so RVFI trap\n  semantics are bit-identical). Only the `redirect` wire's cone is\n  reshaped. Equivalence: the current AND-of-OR form requires BOTH\n  (taken or jumping) AND (no misalign on whichever arm fires); the\n  distributed form checks (taken-and-aligned) OR (jumping-and-aligned),\n  which is the same boolean function because a taken branch and a\n  jump are mutually exclusive in any single instruction (is_branch\n  and is_jump are disjoint decoder outputs).\n\n  Why this should win on GW2AR: the `redirect` wire drives if_stage's\n  PC-register D-input mux (via the core.sv arbitration with\n  id_is_jal_fire). In the current form, `redirect`'s cone is\n  (compare-result → AND with align-check-of-a-pc+imm-adder), serial,\n  through two LUT4 levels. In the distributed form, each arm is\n  (compare AND align-check) computed independently, then OR'd —\n  Yosys can pack each arm into a single LUT4 (3-input AND) and the\n  final OR into a second LUT4, but critically the align-check runs\n  concurrently with the compare inside each arm rather than after,\n  because branch_target_aligned = (pc+imm)[1:0]==0 depends only on\n  the low 2 bits of the adder which resolve in LUT0 of the carry\n  chain while the compare resolves at the carry chain's head.\n\n  This is the mirror-image of r2s0's lesson (\"merging parallel cones\n  into one deeper serial cone trades area for Fmax in the wrong\n  direction\") applied in reverse: unmerging a serial cone into\n  parallel arms trades nothing for Fmax in the RIGHT direction. It's\n  also local to ex_stage.sv — no id_ex_t edit (r7s0, r5s2, r6s0\n  tarpit), no PC-select widening (r6s2), no cross-flop mux move\n  (r3s1, r4s1).\n\n  Expected gain: ~1 LUT level off the EX→IF redirect path on the\n  near-full GW2AR fabric, contributing +2–4% Fmax. IPC unchanged\n  (bit-equivalent redirect semantics). No new storage, no struct\n  edits, no formal contract touch.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Reorganize redirect assignment from AND-of-OR to OR-of-AND. Compute branch_target_aligned and jump_target_aligned as explicit signals; rewrite assign redirect = (branch_taken && branch_target_aligned) || (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.jal_predicted && jump_target_aligned). Leave misalign_fault / ctrl_with_trap / reg_q.pc_next untouched (they still gate trap + linear-next-pc bit-identically). Redirect_target mux stays 2:1 (is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target) unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb assertion (if not already present) that a taken BRANCH with misaligned target produces rvfi_trap=1 on the retiring instruction and does NOT cause a PC redirect (next retirement's pc_rdata = trapping_pc + 4). Similarly for misaligned JAL and JALR. Ensures the distributed form preserves the trap-suppresses-redirect invariant.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r8s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r8s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777791934940,"end":1777791934943}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I've tried seven different structural approaches on slot 1, and they all regressed or broke the core—the issue seems to be that any modification touching pipeline registers, serializing parallel logic cones, or repositioning multiplexers across flip-flop boundaries causes problems. Let me explore what structural changes haven't been attempted yet. Looking at the redirect cone in ex_stage.sv, I'm examining how the branch and jump logic combines...\n\nThe branch_taken signal feeds into both the redirect condition and the misalign_fault detection, which creates a nested AND-of-OR structure that's wider than necessary. I can factor this into an OR-of-AND form instead—redirect fires when either a taken branch has an aligned target, or a non-predicted jump has an aligned target. This factorization should reduce the logic depth of the redirect net by roughly one LUT level without touching pipeline fields, widening the PC mux, adding storage, or crossing flop boundaries. Since redirect feeds directly into the IF-stage PC-select mux, shaving a level here could be the key to fixing the timing without destabilizing the core.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deca7c7e3001OFD9vaDq6SA88B","sessionID":"ses_2135addceffe4De8hDdLDQJTTs","messageID":"msg_deca793780018IMvOQOqjPmjSF"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777791934951,"sessionID":"ses_2135addceffe4De8hDdLDQJTTs","part":{"id":"prt_deca7bd4d001SXwnOupoeL1Eu1","messageID":"msg_deca793780018IMvOQOqjPmjSF","sessionID":"ses_2135addceffe4De8hDdLDQJTTs","type":"text","text":"All 7 prior slot-1 structural attempts regressed. The pattern: edits that touch pipeline register fields, serialize parallel cones, or move muxes across flop boundaries. I need something that stays entirely within one module, doesn't touch id_ex_t, doesn't widen the PC-mux, and flattens (not deepens) the critical cone.\n\nLooking at ex_stage.sv, the redirect cone has a nested AND-of-OR structure:\n```\nredirect = (branch_taken || (is_jump && !jal_predicted)) && !misalign_fault\nmisalign_fault = (is_branch && branch_taken && misalign_branch_tgt) || (is_jump && misalign_jump_tgt)\n```\n\nThe `branch_taken` signal appears in BOTH operands of the outer AND (directly and through misalign_fault). This forces Yosys to serialize misalign detection with the compare + redirect, feeding a wider cone into the fetch-redirect path. A distributed form factors misalign into each branch's own arm:\n```\nredirect = (branch_taken && branch_target_aligned) || (is_jump && !jal_predicted && jump_target_aligned)\n```\n\nThis is bit-equivalent, stays off id_ex_t, doesn't add PC-mux inputs, and is purely local to ex_stage. Aligned check is `target[1:0]==2'b00` — cheap, and the compare and alignment-check cones run in parallel.","time":{"start":1777791909197,"end":1777791934950}}}
