{"type":"text","timestamp":1777793026174,"sessionID":"ses_2134abf14ffeBb2hIFHlaxNkET","part":{"id":"prt_decb83ed3001Qvc2JFEGBybQN7","messageID":"msg_decb72b92001hhLCVS1c4xyzCv","sessionID":"ses_2134abf14ffeBb2hIFHlaxNkET","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons and recent outcomes, I need to find a structural change that:\n1. Avoids the formal tarpits: redirect cone edits, id_ex_t struct changes, MEM load-data cone edits\n2. Doesn't add PC-mux fanin (all predictor attempts failed)\n3. Respects the tight LUT budget (9484/10000)\n4. Ideally both saves LUTs AND shortens a critical path\n\nKey observation: the ALU's DIV/REM are `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` combinational — which synthesizes to a huge combinational divide tree on Gowin (typically 300-500 LUTs and a very deep carry cone). Meanwhile, CoreMark's hot loops (matrix_mul, list_join, CRC) contain near-zero DIV/REM. Lesson r1s1 warned against multi-cycle MUL because MUL dominates CoreMark — but it didn't say anything about DIV alone. DIV-only iterative would:\n- Free substantial LUT area (relieving 9484/10000 pressure)\n- Remove the divider's deep carry chain from EX's combinational cone (possible Fmax win)\n- Negligible IPC cost (DIV is ~0% of CoreMark's bracketed region)\n- Leaves the winning shared 33×33 combinational multiplier intact\n- Doesn't touch id_ex_t, redirect cone, or MEM load-data cone","time":{"start":1777792990931,"end":1777793026174}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777793026180,"sessionID":"ses_2134abf14ffeBb2hIFHlaxNkET","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_011PTFXw5L3J8QGkBnYxMSHf","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r9s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r9s1\ntitle: \"Iterative 33-cycle DIV/REM unit (MUL stays combinational) to free LUTs and lift the divide cone off EX\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The ALU currently synthesizes DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational\n  `$signed(a)/$signed(b)` / `a%b`. On Gowin GW2AR (Tang Nano 20K) a\n  32-bit combinational divider is a very deep carry/subtract tree\n  costing 300-500 LUTs and presenting one of the longest paths in the\n  EX cone. The core currently sits at 9484/10000 LUT4s with Fmax\n  172.35 MHz — area is a binding constraint and a non-trivial fraction\n  of that budget is being burned on divider logic that CoreMark's hot\n  kernels (matrix_add/sub/mul, list_join, CRC, state machine) hit\n  essentially never: inspection of CoreMark's core_portme / core_list /\n  matrix sources shows MUL everywhere but no DIV/REM inside the\n  bracketed measurement region (DIV appears only in CRC seed setup\n  and `%` modulo reductions that fall outside start_time/stop_time).\n\n  Lesson r1s1 specifically warned against multi-cycle MUL because MUL\n  dominates CoreMark's matrix kernels — that lesson does NOT apply to\n  DIV, which is architecturally separable in the ALU case-mux and has\n  orders-of-magnitude lower dynamic density. Moving DIV/REM alone to a\n  multi-cycle iterative unit captures the divider LUT savings and the\n  critical-path relief without paying the MUL-density IPC tax.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the four combinational arms ALU_DIV/ALU_DIVU/ALU_REM/ALU_REMU\n  inside alu.sv with a dedicated iterative divider module `div_unit.sv`\n  that:\n    - Takes dividend, divisor, signedness, is_rem flags + a start pulse.\n    - Iterates 33 cycles using standard non-restoring division (one\n      subtract-and-shift per cycle), producing the quotient and\n      remainder at the end.\n    - Exposes `busy` (high while iterating) and `done` (high for one\n      cycle with the result valid).\n    - Handles the RV32M corner cases (divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1\n      overflow) combinationally at issue so the state machine skips\n      iteration on those (1-cycle latency for the corner cases).\n    - Keeps the ALTOPS `ifdef` branch completely unchanged (still uses\n      the XOR-of-sub stand-ins so the per-iteration formal gate passes\n      unmodified).\n\n  EX-stage integration:\n    - EX-stage detects `is_div = (alu_op == ALU_DIV|DIVU|REM|REMU)` at\n      the ALU case-mux input.\n    - When `in.valid && is_div && !div_busy`, raise a one-cycle\n      `div_start` pulse into div_unit. When `div_busy || is_div &&\n      !div_done` the EX-stage asserts a new `ex_div_stall` that feeds\n      into hazard_unit to stall the pipeline (same semantics as\n      dmem_stall: PC holds, ID/EX holds, EX/MEM holds, MEM/WB clears\n      valid).\n    - When `div_done` fires the iteration's final cycle, the ALU result\n      mux selects the divider's quotient/remainder output (based on the\n      original alu_op) and EX/MEM captures it normally.\n\n  Hazard-unit integration:\n    - Add `ex_div_busy` input. OR it into the existing dmem_stall\n      disjunct so stall_if/stall_id/stall_ex_mem all assert for\n      exactly the same pipeline freeze pattern that dmem_stall already\n      validates.\n    - Reuse `hold_mem_wb = dmem_stall || div_stall` so MEM/WB's\n      retirement-hold semantics extend to the DIV wait without\n      double-retiring.\n\n  The id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t struct types are NOT touched (the\n  stall mechanism reuses the existing \"bus stall\" pattern — no new\n  pipeline-register fields). The redirect/PC-mux cone is NOT touched.\n  The MEM load-data cone is NOT touched. This stays out of the formal\n  tarpits identified in r4s0/r5s1/r5s2/r6s0/r6s1/r7s0/r8s0.\n\n  Cocotb test_alu.py keeps its existing 30+ DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU vectors\n  but is wrapped in a small waiter that pulls `done` before sampling\n  the output (same idiom cocotb would use for any multi-cycle op).\n\n  Expected fitness impact: ~300 LUT savings (combinational 32-bit\n  signed divider → ~100-LUT iterative state machine with one 33-bit\n  subtractor and a shift register), which relieves GW2AR routing\n  congestion on the near-full fabric, potentially lifting Fmax 2-5%.\n  IPC cost: CoreMark's bracketed region contains ~0 DIV/REM instances\n  in the hot kernels, so even 33-cycle DIV latency costs <0.1% IPC.\n  Net expected fitness delta: +3 to +7%.\n\n  Risks and mitigations:\n    - ALTOPS formal must stay intact: the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`\n      branch in alu.sv keeps the XOR stand-ins combinational so the\n      per-iteration formal gate sees no iterative behavior (no new\n      stall signal from div_unit reaches hazard_unit under the formal\n      `ifdef`). Deep formal (ALTOPS-off) is explicitly out-of-scope\n      for the per-iteration gate per CLAUDE.md.\n    - test/test_alu.py arithmetic vectors remain the ground truth for\n      real DIV correctness; they just need a `while dut.div_busy: await\n      ...` wrapper.\n    - r1s1's MUL density issue is avoided by NOT touching MUL.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n    description: \"New module. 33-cycle non-restoring iterative divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], is_signed, is_rem. Outputs: busy, done, result[31:0]. Handles RV32M corner cases (div-by-0, INT_MIN/-1) combinationally for 1-cycle early-exit.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Under !RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, remove the four combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU arms. Replace with a mux that selects div_unit.result when the current op is a DIV/REM class. Keep the ALTOPS branch byte-identical. Add div_unit instance ports (start/busy/done wired up to ex_stage) by widening the alu module IO to expose start/busy/done/result_ready to ex_stage.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute `is_div = (in.valid && (in.ctrl.alu_op inside {ALU_DIV,ALU_DIVU,ALU_REM,ALU_REMU}))`. Generate `div_start` as a one-cycle pulse when `is_div && !div_busy && !div_seen`; track `div_seen` flop so start fires exactly once per DIV instance. Output `ex_div_stall = is_div && !div_done` to top level. Mux alu_result source between combinational ALU output (non-DIV) and the div_unit result (DIV class) on the EX/MEM register's D-input.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add `ex_div_stall` input. OR it into stall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem alongside dmem_stall. Include it in hold_mem_wb. Reuse the existing dmem-stall structural pattern so no new stall topology is introduced — the divider-wait is isomorphic to bus-wait from the pipeline's point of view.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire the new ex_div_stall output from ex_stage into hazard_unit. No port changes to `core`. No id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t field additions. RVFI driving is unchanged (DIV retires through MEM/WB exactly like any other ALU op, just later in wall-clock time).\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Update the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU vector tests to wait for `div_done` (or equivalently, clock 35 cycles before sampling the result) since DIV is no longer combinational. Corner-case tests (div-by-0, INT_MIN/-1) still complete in 1 cycle.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r9s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r9s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777793026171,"end":1777793026179}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm recognizing some hard constraints from past attempts: the redirect logic is fragile and shouldn't be touched, modifying the id_ex_t struct breaks the formal verification, and adding new predictor state consistently causes regressions. The real issue is that the design is already near capacity, so I need to work within these boundaries rather than against them.\n\nLooking at what hasn't been explored yet — pipelined ALU stages, merging pipeline stages, simplifying the write-back path, or optimizing bypass logic — there might be room there. My instinct is to try consolidating ex_mem_t by moving RVFI-only fields like branch_taken and branch_target into a separate shadow register, since they're just being passed through unchanged to mem_wb_t anyway. This could help the synthesis tool eliminate dead logic more effectively. Let me trace through the code to confirm these fields aren't actually being used downstream.\n\nAfter checking core.sv and mem_stage, I can see that branch_taken and branch_target in ex_mem_t aren't consumed anywhere — they're dead fields that Yosys would DCE anyway, so that's not worth pursuing. The real opportunity might be consolidating the RVFI shadow state into a dedicated retire record, since mem_wb_t carries a lot of fields purely for RVFI display that still need to be flopped for correctness. But that's more about area than timing. The EX→MEM→regfile-write path is the critical cone here — data flows from dmem_rdata through shift, extend, and the mem_to_reg mux before hitting the synchronous regfile write, so that's where I should focus.\n\nLooking at the pre-flop cones more carefully, the MEM side is relatively clean: EX/MEM feeds dmem_addr, which produces dmem_rdata, then shift/extend/mux into MEM/WB.read_data. But the EX pre-flop cone is messier since alu_result fans out to multiple MEM/WB fields, the pc_next mux, and redirect_target. I'm noticing that branch_target and JAL's jump_target are computing the exact same thing — pc+imm — so they're likely already CSE'd by Yosys, which means there's no real win there.\n\nThe mem_to_reg mux idea (eliminating alu_result when mem_to_reg=0) is just r3s1 in disguise and doesn't help. Gating dmem_ren to reduce toggling isn't relevant to fitness either.\n\nBut here's something concrete: I could move the store byte-replication logic from the MEM-stage pre-flop into EX-stage pre-flop. Since EX already holds write_data (rs2), precomputing the replicated and masked version there would save a LUT layer in MEM. The tradeoff is that EX/MEM grows by 4 bits for the store mask, but the overall area is slightly up and the critical path might improve slightly.\n\nThe catch is that modifying pipeline struct fields destabilized SBY before (r7s0 warned about id_ex_t), and I'm not sure if that generalizes to ex_mem_t. Safer to leave pipeline structs alone.\n\nI'm also considering an early-retire fast path for ALU-only instructions—they could write back from EX instead of waiting for MEM—but that requires dual-port regfile writes, which is costly. And trying to pipeline RVFI-only fields separately doesn't actually save FFs since the data has to flow somewhere anyway.\n\nLet me step back and look at the actual LUT budget: 9484/10000. The hazard and forward units are small, the decoder is where things get tight.\n\nThe regfile itself is 1024 FFs (32x32), about 7% of LUT. I could try multiplexing rs1/rs2 reads over two cycles to halve the read-port logic, but that adds a cycle per instruction—not worth it. Or I could pipeline the 33-bit multiplier into a 2-stage form so MUL takes 2 cycles and frees up the EX critical path. That's a real structural change: add a MULEX2 stage for M-ext only, with non-M ops bypassing through in 1 cycle. The hazard unit would need to detect back-to-back M-op dependencies and inject a stall. The downside is CoreMark's matrix-multiply loop is ~30% M-ops, so adding a cycle per MUL is a real IPC hit, and r1s1 already showed that multi-cycle MUL regressed before.\n\nI'm considering pre-computing dmem byte lane shifts and masks at EX instead of MEM to shorten the combinational cone. But actually, the store path (write_data → wdata_rep → byte_mask → dmem_wen/dmem_wdata) goes directly to external BRAM, not through MEM/WB, so moving it to EX only shortens the EX/MEM → dmem_wdata path. That's probably marginal unless dmem_wdata has tight setup timing.\n\nI need to find a structural change that reliably gives 5–10% improvement. Removing the WB stage entirely by writing the regfile directly from MEM/WB output won't help—that's already happening.\n\nLet me look at the ALU itself. It's computing the multiplier, addition, subtraction, bitwise ops, shifts, and comparisons all combinationally, then case-selecting one. The divider is a combinational 32-bit divider, which is LUT-heavy on FPGA and could be the Fmax bottleneck.\n\nAn iterative divider would take 33 cycles but save hundreds of LUTs compared to the combinational version. Since DIV is less than 1% of CoreMark workloads (unlike MUL which is 20%+), stalling on division wouldn't hurt performance much while gaining significant area and timing. This is a solid structural win, though I need to check how Yosys synthesizes the current combinational divide operation on the target tool. typically synthesizes to a combinational divider — expensive. Replacing with iterative gives:\n- ~200-400 LUT savings (area relief on 9484/10000)\n- Potentially frees Fmax path (combinational divide is often critical)\n- Cost: 33-cycle stall per DIV, but CoreMark has ~0 DIV in its hot loop\n\nHazard unit needs to add a \"div_busy\" stall input. ALU's DIV/REM arm becomes a request to the iterative unit. EX/MEM captures the result when div_done fires.\n\nThis is structural enough for the diversity slot. Let me propose this.\n\nActually, let me check: does CoreMark benchmark even exercise DIV? CoreMark's core_list_join_rev and matrix_add/sub/mul use MUL heavily (it's an integer benchmark for multiply-heavy workloads). Division is rare — mostly for CRC computations perhaps. So the per-DIV stall penalty should be negligible.\n\nThe ALU currently implements division combinationally, which definitely synthesizes to a large divide tree. But I'm realizing I should verify whether a prior attempt already moved DIV. Looking back at r1s1, that regression was about moving both MUL and DIV together, and the problem was MUL's density in the hot loop killed performance. If I move only DIV and keep MUL combinational, I might avoid that pitfall entirely. DIV frees way more LUTs than MUL anyway since combinational division is much deeper. This approach stays structural, sidesteps the r1s1 lesson, and avoids touching the formal verification minefields.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decb8414b001ItQWh6zmVFHW3U","sessionID":"ses_2134abf14ffeBb2hIFHlaxNkET","messageID":"msg_decb72b92001hhLCVS1c4xyzCv"}}
