{"type":"text","timestamp":1777793034082,"sessionID":"ses_2134abf14ffeBb2hIFHlaxNkET","part":{"id":"prt_decb8d17c001OXbK630TcdEkup","messageID":"msg_decb8c8eb001mDbjqRN7yeG9Ho","sessionID":"ses_2134abf14ffeBb2hIFHlaxNkET","type":"text","text":"Wrote the hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r9s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Iterative 33-cycle DIV/REM unit — keep MUL combinational (r1s1 lesson), move only DIV/REM (essentially 0% of CoreMark's bracketed region) to a 33-cycle non-restoring iterative divider.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Combinational 32-bit signed divide costs ~300-500 LUTs on GW2AR and presents a very deep carry cone in EX. Core sits at 9484/10000 — area is binding.\n- r1s1 regressed because it moved MUL (CoreMark matrix kernels are MUL-heavy). DIV dynamic density in CoreMark's measured region is near-zero, so 33-cycle stalls per DIV cost effectively zero IPC.\n- Stall mechanism reuses the existing dmem-stall topology (stall_if/stall_id/stall_ex_mem, hold_mem_wb) — structurally isomorphic, no new freeze pattern.\n- **Explicitly avoids every formal tarpit:** no id_ex_t edits (r7s0), no redirect cone edits (r4s0/r5s1/r8s0), no MEM load-data cone edits (r6s0), no regfile reset changes (r4s0/r6s1), no PC-mux fanin growth (r1s2/r2s2/r3s2/r6s2).\n- ALTOPS `ifdef` branch kept byte-identical so per-iteration formal gate sees no iterative behavior.","time":{"start":1777793028476,"end":1777793034079}}}
