{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777794381050,"sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","part":{"id":"prt_deccd74f3001yeNSHud4L2Y79M","messageID":"msg_deccd52fd0017z7F6QP5TE1fQQ","sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","snapshot":"5b5635f42b65d7fd4f387589328cd58ab6434569","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777794533717,"sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","part":{"id":"prt_deccfb5ac001WpzkFww7a4SLTd","messageID":"msg_deccd52fd0017z7F6QP5TE1fQQ","sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons carefully, I see a very clear pattern in the predictor category:\n\n- **r4s2 JAL fast-path WON (+17.73%)**: zero-storage, kept redirect_target as 2:1, appended to id_ex_t\n- **Every other predictor FAILED**: r1s2 (BP on PC cone), r2s2 (16-entry BTB), r3s2 (4-entry RAS), r5s2/r6s2 (branches extended), r7s2 (implicit RAS, -50%!), r8s2 (IF-predecode relocate), r9s2 (bit-trick on JAL cone)\n\nThe r7s2 lesson explicitly calls out: \"any predictor that adds a second ID-side fire term, widens redirect_target past 2:1, *or* appends to id_ex_t pays the full predictor tax.\" But r4s2 itself appended to id_ex_t successfully — so the tax isn't the append alone, it's the **combination** of (second fire term + 3:1 mux + append) in r7s2.\n\nThe remaining untried predictor angle: a **1-entry Return Address Cache** that strictly preserves the r4s2 topology by **keeping the existing `ex_redirect ? ... : ...` mux at 2:1** and placing the ret-vs-jal selection in a separate **upstream 2:1 mux** (not a 3:1 widening). CoreMark's `ret` density is ~4-6% per iteration, single-entry hit rate in leaf-heavy code is high.\n\nLet me check log.jsonl for the exact r7s2 topology to verify my understanding differs.","time":{"start":1777794528685,"end":1777794533715}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777794533739,"sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_016tkbCu1fR12EDMnewtyd5f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -l \"r7s2|implicit.*RAS|dirty.x1\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -3","description":"Find r7s2 details in log"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Find r7s2 details in log","truncated":false},"title":"Find r7s2 details in log","time":{"start":1777794533726,"end":1777794533736}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at what made the fast-path predictor work so well for JAL instructions — it leveraged existing hardware without adding storage or complexity, just comparing opcodes and using the immediate adder. The static branch predictor approach failed because it created timing issues on the PC path, and I'm starting to see the pattern in what works versus what doesn't for this benchmark.\n\nThe JAL fast-path is already resolving in the ID stage, saving a cycle when it hits, and CoreMark probably has enough JAL density to matter. The critical path runs from instruction memory through immediate extraction and a 32-bit add, feeding directly into the redirect multiplexer that drives the PC. I'm wondering if there's still room to optimize this path without generalizing to other branch types, which keeps breaking things.\n\nEvery attempt to add storage or extra fanin to the PC multiplexer has failed on the full GW2AR fabric. Maybe the answer isn't adding a predictor at all—maybe it's removing overhead by detecting patterns that don't need prediction, or focusing on the load-use hazards that the hazard unit is already inserting bubbles for anyway.\n\nThe only successful approach (r4s2's +17.73%) resolved branches at ID stage, reused the existing redirect wire without adding a new PC-mux input, and kept the logic minimal. So I should look for predictors that follow that same constraint: resolve early, don't expand the mux, add minimal logic. ed by JALR with rs1 matching the LUI destination, I could compute the target at ID stage without waiting for the register file — but CoreMark's 6KB binary fits entirely within JAL's range, so this fusion pattern rarely triggers. Compiler-encoded branch hints would help, but RISC-V doesn't support those natively. A micro-BTB with just 2 entries stored directly in flops might be worth exploring since the 16-entry version showed neutral results; the smaller footprint could tip it positive, though prior small predictors like the 4-entry RAS also netted zero.\n\nLooking at what's actually feasible without major datapath changes, I need to reconsider the branch prediction angle. Computing the target combinationally at ID is straightforward (pc + imm_b), but predicting whether to take it requires either always predicting not-taken (no hardware cost) or adding a new PC-mux input and an EX unpredict path. CoreMark's dominant patterns are backward branches in inner loops and conditionals in list traversals, not the JAL-based function calls. The real constraint is that BEQ prediction can't follow the zero-storage pattern without widening the EX redirect mux — unless I defer the actual PC redirect until later in the pipeline, decoupling the prediction from the immediate mux width.\n\nThe core insight from the r4s2 analysis is that JAL works because it's unconditional; any predictor with a misprediction arm pays the cost of both a wider EX mux and a wider ID-side cone. JALR is conditional on rs1, so it doesn't fit that pattern. But what if I could predict specific JALR patterns — particularly returns — by maintaining a shadow register in the IF stage that tracks the current return address whenever JAL x1 fires? Detecting a ret instruction (jalr x0, x1, 0) at ID would then redirect to this shadow value, essentially a 1-entry return address stack fed directly off the JAL fast-path infrastructure.\n\nBut r7s2 already tried this with \"dirty-x1\" tracking and regressed 50% because it widened the redirect_target mux to 3:1 and added state to id_ex_t. The lesson is clear: don't expand the mux, don't bloat the pipeline registers. So the question becomes whether I can route RET predictions through the existing 2:1 redirect pathway by sharing it with JAL — when RET fires and JAL doesn't, feed link_q through the JAL target wire. The problem is that still requires a 3:1 mux on redirect_target (ex_redirect, JAL target, or RET target), unless... since JAL and RET can't decode in the same cycle, I could use a 2:1 mux on the ID side to select between them before feeding into the existing ex_redirect mux.\n\nThis keeps redirect_target at 2:1 and adds only one small upstream mux on the ID side, matching r4s2's pattern. I'd need a tiny FSM to track link_q and avoid touching id_ex_t — but the EX stage still needs to know when to suppress its redirect for a correctly-predicted RET, since JALR always fires unconditionally. The option is to detect RET at EX instead of relying on pipeline state.\n\nI'm considering whether a separate sideband flop for `ret_was_predicted_in_id` could work without regressing, but that's still adding storage like the RAS attempts that failed before. The core insight is that r4s2 succeeds because it's zero-storage, so any prediction state becomes problematic.\n\nLet me think about other angles: recognizing BEQ/BNE with matching operands as unconditional branches in the ID fast-path, or exploring whether suppressing load-use stalls for instructions consumed by JAL could help — though JAL doesn't actually read registers, so that's a dead end.\n\nGiven how many approaches have failed, I need a predictor that stays within tight constraints: no changes to id_ex_t, no widening of EX's redirect mux, no new PC-mux inputs, minimal logic (~10-20 LUTs), and a clear unconditional trigger. A 1-entry BTB would require new flops and a PC comparator, plus it can't unpredict without widening the EX mux. But what if I detect JAL opcodes directly in the IF stage by predecoding the instruction and computing the J-immediate target from the current PC?\n\nFlopping that target for one cycle and injecting it back as the next PC would work in theory, but r8s2 already tried this and regressed 13.25% because it duplicated the J-immediate carry chain. I'm realizing the real bottleneck: the decoder already computes J-immediate in imm_gen, but the JAL fast-path at the top level computes it independently with its own bit-permute logic. If I could consolidate these two paths through if_id_w, I'd avoid the duplication—but imm_gen is combinational in id_stage, and Yosys CSE probably already optimized away redundant logic anyway. Previous attempts like r9s2 (tightening the aligned check) and r8s2 (relocating to IF) both regressed, and r5s2/r6s2 tried extending to branches but hit similar walls.\n\nI'm going to try something different: resolving BEQ/BNE at ID when both operands are x0, since beq x0, x0 is always taken and bne x0, x0 is always not taken. These patterns are rare in typical compiler output, but CoreMark might have a few, and resolving them one cycle earlier could help.\n\nThe approach would add a B-immediate adder in parallel with the existing J-immediate adder, then multiplex between JAL and BEQ x0,x0 targets upstream of the redirect logic. But realistically, CoreMark has almost no \"beq x0,x0\" instances, so this optimization is probably pointless.\n\nLet me pivot to exploring unconditional jumps via x5 as an alternate link register...\n\nActually, I'm going in circles here. Every predictor variant beyond r4s2 has failed, so let me focus on the tightest possible tweak to the existing JAL fast-path. Since PC is always 4-byte-aligned and the J-immediate encoding has bit 0 implicit, the target's bit 1 is determined entirely by instruction bit 21. The current check for `id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00` is equivalent to just checking `!instr[21]`, which is what r9s2 tried—but it regressed, so I should leave this cone alone.\n\nLet me look at optimizing the if_stage PC computation instead... I'm realizing the constraint: I need to implement a zero-storage implicit RAS without expanding the id_ex_t struct or widening redirect_target to 3:1. The trick is to detect RET (jalr x0, x1, 0) at ID and feed it through the existing 2:1 mux alongside the JAL fast-path, using a dedicated link_q flop to hold the return address. The challenge is suppressing EX's redirect when the RET prediction is correct and x1 matches link_q.\n\nBut this requires tracking whether the instruction in EX was a predicted RET via a sideband flop, and invalidating link_q whenever x1 is written by a non-JAL instruction—which is essentially what r7s2 attempted and it regressed heavily. I'm going in circles here, so let me pivot to exploring other prediction angles like JAL chain prediction or IF-stage pre-decoding to catch JALs earlier.\n\nThe core blocker is that I can't pre-detect JALs at fetch without either a cache, RAM predecode, or BRAM sideband bits—all outside the scope. So I'm considering a narrower win: widening the ID-stage fast-path to also fire on unconditional branches like `beq x0, x0` or `beq rs, rs`, which adds a small parallel cone for the B-immediate adder but likely has zero impact on CoreMark. Another angle is predicting indirect tail calls via `jalr x0, rs1, 0`, though the thinking cuts off there.\n\nMy pragmatic final move is to add a single-entry Return Address Cache: store the link address when a JAL with `rd=x1` fires in ID, then detect the return pattern (`jalr x0, x1, 0`) and redirect to the cached link address, reusing the existing redirect mux with an upstream 2:1 selector.\n\nNow I'm weighing how to handle the EX-stage redirect suppression without modifying `id_ex_t` itself—I could add a separate sideband flop `ex_ret_predicted_q` that tracks whether ID predicted a return, so EX doesn't fire a redundant redirect on correct predictions. The risk is that appending to `id_ex_t` caused regressions before, but adding a parallel flop outside the type definition might be safer.\n\nLooking back at what worked and failed: r4s2 added `jal_predicted` directly to `id_ex_t` and passed, while r7s2 failed with multiple changes stacked together—the opcode compare, the wider mux, and the append. So maybe just the append alone is fine, or I should keep it minimal and use the sideband approach instead.\n\nLet me propose a tighter structure: extend the JAL fast-path with a simple 1-entry Return Address Cache using a 2:1 mux upstream of the existing redirect logic. I'd add link and link_valid flops in core.sv, update them when JAL fires with rd=x1, and detect RET at ID by checking for JALR with funct3=0 and rd=0. The tricky part is invalidating the cached link when x1 gets written elsewhere, but I can simplify by clearing it whenever any ID-captured instruction writes to x1 that isn't the JAL-call itself.\n\nThe real problem emerges at EX: I need to verify the prediction, but that requires threading link_q all the way to the execute stage or doing an extra comparison. The safest approach is to invalidate link_valid eagerly whenever there's a pending x1 writer in the pipeline, so I only predict when I'm confident, and always let EX redirect fire for JALR—using ret_predicted as a signal to suppress the redirect if it matches.\n\nLooking back at the results, r7s2 crashed with -50% and r4s2 gained +17.7%, both using similar patterns but r7s2 had that problematic 3:1 mux. The lesson is clear: JALR returns need a fundamentally different structural approach. Moving the prediction earlier to IF with link_q—predecoding for RET patterns and setting next_pc combinationally—would save cycles, but r3s2 tried RAS at IF and got 0%, and r8s2's IF-stage predecode regressed too. I'm circling back to the same dead ends. Rather than chase more structural variations, I should just commit to building a predictor and see what the data shows.\n\nGiven the fabric's sensitivity to pipeline changes, I'll propose a minimal 1-entry Return Address Cache that mirrors r4s2's structure exactly—no new pipeline register inputs, just a 2:1 mux upstream of redirect_target, with RET suppression handled by an external flop synchronized to id_ex valid instead of modifying the id_ex_t struct itself. This avoids the symbol table edit trap that sank r7s0. The design uses a link_q and link_valid_q for storage, a small combinational RET detector, and the mux to select between the cached return and the normal redirect target. I'm realizing the staged 2:1 muxes create a logical 3:1 that's deeper than r4s2's approach, so it might not gain enough to justify the risk. Given how many predictor variants have failed, I think the safest bet is a minimal 1-entry RAS that stays close to r4s2's proven topology—keeping the existing redirect mux, appending ret_predicted to id_ex_t cleanly, and using a simple RET detection gate. Confidence is low and upside modest, but it avoids the compound mechanisms that tripped up r7s2. Let me draft this now.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deccfc544001AFbul1vneBkzj8","sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","messageID":"msg_deccd52fd0017z7F6QP5TE1fQQ"}}
