{"type":"text","timestamp":1777794595606,"sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","part":{"id":"prt_decd0436a001Ruyng21cl2Ange","messageID":"msg_deccff6d2001oKjjFoyiB4Q2Rm","sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","type":"text","text":"Given the constrained space (most predictor patterns already tried/failed), I'll propose a **1-entry RAC** that explicitly avoids r7s2's failure modes by staging the target selection across *two* sequential 2:1 muxes (preserving the existing 2:1 `ex_redirect` arbiter exactly as r4s2 shipped it), and by appending to id_ex_t rather than renaming (the pattern that worked in r4s2).","time":{"start":1777794564970,"end":1777794595605}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777794595617,"sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015DRVcsK5epU8zM2JGQcV3q","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r10s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r10s2\ntitle: \"1-entry Return Address Cache via staged 2:1 muxes (preserves r4s2's exact arbiter topology)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The r4s2 zero-storage JAL fast-path remains the only predictor that has\n  improved fitness on this fabric (+17.73%). Every generalization attempt\n  has regressed: r5s2/r6s2 (backward branches), r7s2 (implicit RAS via\n  dirty-x1, -50.45%), r8s2 (IF predecode relocate, -13.25%). Reading r7s2's\n  failure carefully: the -50% came from a *compound* diff — (a) a second\n  opcode-compare arm on the ID redirect cone, (b) widening the arbiter\n  `redirect_target` mux from 2:1 to 3:1, AND (c) appending `ret_predicted`\n  to id_ex_t all at once. r4s2's own diff proves (c) alone is safe (it\n  appended `jal_predicted`). The lethal element is most plausibly (b): the\n  arbiter mux that feeds if_stage's PC D-input growing from 2:1 to 3:1\n  changes the fan-in the tool placed favorably for r4s2. JALR-ret density\n  in CoreMark is ~4–6% and single-entry RAC hit rate in leaf-call-heavy\n  inner loops (CoreMark's list_ins / crc / matrix innerloops) is near 100%\n  because calls nest shallowly — a 1-cycle saving per ret equates to\n  ~3–4% IPC headroom if the structural cost can be held near zero.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 1-entry Return Address Cache (RAC) consisting of a single 32-bit\n  `link_q` flop and a 1-bit `link_valid_q` flop. Update `link_q` on the\n  cycle the existing JAL fast-path fires with rd==x1 (i.e. a CALL);\n  capture pc+4 from if_id_w.pc + 4 (the adder already exists in if_stage\n  as next_pc's +4 — we reuse its output wire via a named net, no new\n  carry chain). Invalidate `link_valid_q` when any ID-captured instruction\n  writes x1 that ISN'T the JAL-call itself (detected at ID via\n  if_id_w.instr[11:7]==5'd1 && !id_is_jal_call).\n\n  At ID, detect RET: opcode==1100111 && funct3==0 && rd==x0 && rs1==x1 &&\n  imm[11:0]==0 — exactly the canonical `jalr x0, x1, 0` encoding. Gate\n  with `!stall_id && link_valid_q` to form `id_is_ret_fire`.\n\n  CRITICAL topology rule — to avoid r7s2's -50%: the existing core.sv\n  arbiter mux `redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target :\n  id_jal_target` STAYS A STRICT 2:1. We introduce the ret-vs-jal target\n  selection as a SEPARATE upstream 2:1 mux:\n\n      id_pred_target = id_is_ret_fire ? link_q : id_jal_target;\n      id_pred_fire   = id_is_ret_fire | id_is_jal_fire;\n      redirect        = ex_redirect | id_pred_fire;\n      redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target : id_pred_target;\n\n  This keeps the tool-critical arbiter mux byte-identical to r4s2's\n  shipping form (same fan-in, same select signal, same pinout). The new\n  2:1 sits upstream in parallel with the existing `id_jal_target` adder\n  — one LUT4 level added on the predicted-redirect path, zero change on\n  the ex_redirect path. Net LUT delta: ~40 (link_q flops + RET decoder\n  + upstream 2:1 target mux + x1-writer invalidate gate).\n\n  For EX suppression: append `ret_predicted` to id_ex_t alongside the\n  existing `jal_predicted` (this is r4s2's validated pattern — APPEND not\n  rename; r7s0's rename tarpit is avoided). In ex_stage, suppress the\n  JALR redirect when `in.ctrl.is_jalr && in.ret_predicted`. Correctness\n  is guaranteed because link_valid_q is invalidated on ANY x1 writer that\n  isn't the captured JAL-call — so by the time a predicted RET reaches\n  EX, we only suppress when rs1 was confirmed to still equal link_q at\n  capture time. If rs1 value changed via forwarding between capture and\n  EX, the invalidate-on-x1-writer check will have fired first and the\n  RET wouldn't have predicted.\n\n  Fallback safety: if the RET resolves at EX to a different target than\n  link_q (e.g. a NMI-style overwrite we didn't catch), EX would still fire\n  its redirect normally. To handle this we add a 32-bit compare at EX\n  (`in.ret_predicted && (jalr_target != in.rac_hint)`) — but since the\n  simpler invariant (link_valid_q is conservatively cleared on any x1\n  writer) already guarantees correctness at the capture point, we can\n  start WITHOUT the EX verification and just trust link_valid_q. If this\n  proves incorrect in cocotb, add the EX verification.\n\n  Expected IPC: ~4–5% reduction in CoreMark cycle count assuming ~5% ret\n  density × 90% hit rate × 1 cycle saved per hit. Structural cost is\n  explicitly budgeted to not touch the Fmax-critical arbiter mux that\n  r4s2 left in its winning topology.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: low\n\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Add link_q (32b) + link_valid_q (1b) flops. Add RET detector (opcode+funct3+rd+rs1+imm[11:0] compare). Introduce id_is_ret_fire, id_pred_target upstream 2:1 mux, id_pred_fire. Existing ex_redirect arbiter 2:1 stays byte-identical. x1-writer invalidate gate cleared link_valid_q on non-call x1 writes captured at ID. Thread ret_predicted wire into id_stage.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Append 1-bit ret_predicted field to id_ex_t (placed after existing jal_predicted; no renames). Reset-value zero. Zero other downstream consumers beyond ex_stage.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add ret_predicted_in input port; flop into reg_q.ret_predicted with identical stall/flush semantics as jal_predicted.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend redirect suppression: was `!in.jal_predicted` for is_jump; extend to also suppress JALR redirect when in.ret_predicted is asserted. Keep ex_redirect wire topology unchanged (only the gating term broadens).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add cocotb test_rac_ret_hit (call+ret sequence saves one cycle vs. baseline) and test_rac_invalidate (x1-clobber between call and ret forces EX-resolved path).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r10s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r10s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777794595602,"end":1777794595615}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The hypothesis files haven't been generated yet, so I'll work with what's in the log.jsonl entries—they have titles but might not include the hypothesis field explicitly. I'm going to move forward and draft the hypothesis myself, proposing a single-entry Return Address Cache design that sidesteps the specific issues r7s2 ran into by keeping the existing redirect logic as a strict 2:1 ratio without modifications.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the structural tradeoffs between cascading two 2:1 multiplexers versus using a single 3:1 mux. On LUT4-based FPGAs, a 3:1 mux typically fits in one LUT level per bit, whereas cascaded 2:1s would require two serialized LUT levels—so the cascade might actually be worse for timing. The r4s2 approach with a small upstream 2:1 worked because JAL is unconditional and never mispredicts, which is a fundamentally different case than what I'm trying to solve here.\n\nGiven that predictors have failed five times versus one success, I'm starting to think they're just a hard fit for this fabric. But since the mandate requires a predictor, let me explore some alternatives. A decoder flag for unconditional redirects would just be a refactoring with no real gain. An IF-stage prefetch hint for hot loops would need cache support. What if instead I pre-compute the branch target at the ID stage—computing `pc + imm_b` in parallel with the main datapath, then threading it through to EX so the execute stage only needs to select between `pc+4` and the pre-computed target rather than computing the target itself?\n\nThe issue is that `imm_gen` already produces the sign-extended B-immediate for branches, and EX computes the target by adding `pc` and `imm` from the id_ex pipeline registers. If I move that addition earlier to ID as a combinational path, then flop the result into id_ex as a new field, EX's adder becomes just a mux—shortening the critical path to redirect. But pushing an adder into ID likely congests that stage further, similar to the r8s2 problem. I think I need to commit to the RAS proposal and write it up carefully.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decd04376001JYsSAEPE9Wv043","sessionID":"ses_21332adc6ffe0qJHPeAj1dM2xU","messageID":"msg_deccff6d2001oKjjFoyiB4Q2Rm"}}
