{"type":"text","timestamp":1777796378489,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"id":"prt_decebe360001W0LfDmzD0NdmmI","messageID":"msg_dece989ea001uVVMtGPjG9S6YE","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","type":"text","text":"Looking at the predictor category and the lessons, I need to avoid a long list of failure modes:\n\n1. r1s2/r3s2/r8s2: new PC-mux input → Fmax hit\n2. r5s2/r6s2/r7s2/r10s2: new ID-redirect fire term → Fmax hit\n3. r6s2/r7s2: widened EX redirect-target mux (3:1) → Fmax hit\n4. r4s2 **won** with: zero storage, shares existing redirect wire, unconditional case only\n\nThe explicit guidance from r7s2/r10s2 lessons is: \"JALR/RET speculation must resolve off the ID redirect cone entirely (IF-side hint + squash-refetch)\". Let me check prior RET attempts in the log to make sure I'm not duplicating.","time":{"start":1777796375392,"end":1777796378489}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796378506,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EY3WNp2iUwdbiqaqJsovgM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ | head -40","description":"List prior hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List prior hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List prior hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777796378497,"end":1777796378505}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what went wrong with the previous predictor designs—the static branch predictor added unnecessary complexity to the PC path, the BTB and RAS didn't improve performance enough to justify their area overhead, and the JAL extension attempt was cut short. Let me reconsider what might actually work given these constraints.\n\nThe real breakthrough was r4s2, which solved JAL prediction with zero storage by leveraging the existing redirect infrastructure at ID stage. But every other attempt failed because adding new logic to the ID-redirect cone or PC-select mux created timing problems. The pattern is clear: I can't add prediction logic on the critical path without regressing performance significantly.\n\nThe lessons point toward two viable directions—either move prediction hints to the IF stage and handle misspeculation through squash-refetch, or abandon the predictor entirely and accelerate JALR returns through a different structural approach. Now I'm wondering if there's a completely different angle I haven't explored yet.\n\nLooking at the actual stall breakdown, unpredicted taken branches are a major cost—CoreMark has lots of loop branches that are taken 87% of the time, and each unpredicted taken branch costs 2 cycles since the IF stage just fetches linearly. Load-use stalls and JALR also contribute significantly. The question is whether I can predict branch outcomes or fetch patterns without touching the PC-select mux or ID-redirect cone.\n\nThe r4s2 win worked because it kept the PC D-input mux structurally unchanged (still 2:1), just added an upstream target mux and a single `jal_predicted` bit to mask EX's redirect—no new storage, no mispredict case. I'm wondering if I can apply a similar pattern to JALR, especially the return case where x1 holds the return address. If I add a dedicated shadow register for x1 that updates alongside the main regfile, I could compute the JALR target at ID without pulling the full regfile+forward unit into the critical path.\n\nBut r7s2 already tried this with a shadow x1 and regressed -50% due to the second fire term and invalidate gate complexity. Even r10s2, which preserved the arbiter and added the upstream mux, still regressed -20%. So ID-side JALR prediction seems like a dead end.\n\nI'm considering an IF-side approach instead: register the predicted target from the shadow x1 flop, and when IF detects the RET pattern (JALR with rs1=x1, rd=x0, imm=0) in the instruction, assert a redirect next cycle. But that still requires driving PC somehow, so it's essentially the same problem. Maybe I should look at whether I can reduce the branch mispredict penalty by narrowing the flush window instead—the branch resolves at EX, so there's potential there.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if there's a simpler angle: what if I detect when a backward branch is taken (the typical loop case) and predict it taken? Currently the core predicts not-taken for all branches, so a backward branch that's taken costs 2 cycles. But predicting it taken would save those 2 cycles when correct and cost 2 when wrong—and if mispredicted, I'd need to redirect back, which is what caused r6s2's regression. I'm also exploring whether I can detect a JAL that writes x1 in IF/ID, then when the matching RET appears later, predict it jumps back to the JAL's target without delay.\n\nBut that's essentially what a return address stack does, which r7s2/r10s2 already tried. I'm also considering whether the IF stage could prefetch both paths as a hint without actually redirecting the PC, but that's a huge area cost. Other angles I'm turning over: predictive forwarding to skip load-use bubbles (too speculative), detecting writes to x0 to free up forwarding slots, or finding a way to change fetch behavior based on a trivial signal that bypasses the PC mux entirely. I'm circling back to an early BEQ fast-path idea... I'm circling back to the core constraint: I need a predictor that reuses the existing redirect network without adding new PC-select inputs. For CoreMark's tight loops with backward branches, the dominant cost is misprediction penalty, not the predictor itself. I'm considering whether an instruction-fusion predictor could detect common loop patterns early in the fetch stage, but I keep hitting the same wall—any new prediction mechanism either requires additional redirect logic or can't resolve branch conditions cheaply enough at ID.\n\nLet me try a different angle: a minimal 1-entry BTB that records the last resolved branch target in a shadow register, then compares the current fetch PC against it to provide a prefetch hint. The trick would be making this hint feed into the next cycle's fetch without adding a new mux input to the PC directly, though I'm not yet sure how to avoid that constraint.\n\nActually, I think the most practical approach given the repeated predictor failures is to focus on something simpler that doesn't require storage—maybe detecting when a load-use hazard triggers a flush and the next instruction in the pipeline is something we can handle specially to eliminate a bubble cycle.\n\nBut that's really just hazard detection, not a predictor. Since the category demands a predictor, let me settle on something concrete: a static predict-taken for the specific pattern `BEQ x0, x0, offset`, which is an unconditional branch encoded as a conditional instruction. It's rare in typical code, but if it appears, we can predict it taken just by checking the opcode and register fields without needing operand values. The real question is whether this pattern shows up enough in CoreMark to matter, and honestly it probably doesn't.\n\nBackward BEQ with rs2==0 is more common—the loop pattern `beq rs1, x0, .loop`—and we could predict it taken statically based on direction alone, but that's essentially what r6s2 already does and it regressed performance by 23%.\n\nSo I'm pivoting to something structurally different: recognize JAL instructions at decode and cache the return address (pc+4) in a dedicated flop when it's a CALL (JAL writing to x1). Then, when we see a JALR x0, 0(x1) pattern at the IF stage, we can redirect the fetch to that cached return address one cycle earlier than waiting for EX resolution. The trick is whether we can inject this redirect into the IF stage without disrupting the existing ID redirect logic.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to modify the sequential PC calculation: instead of always computing pc+4 for the next fetch, we conditionally use the cached link address if IF detects the RET pattern. This adds just a 2:1 mux on the sequential path rather than widening the main PC mux to 4 inputs. The RET detection itself is a few opcode equality checks to match the JALR x1 encoding, plus a valid bit.\n\nTo handle the case where IF predicts RET but EX's JALR resolution disagrees, we pass a `ret_predicted` flag through the ID-EX pipeline so EX can suppress its normal redirect when the target matches our prediction. This keeps the ID-stage redirect logic completely untouched—the prediction only affects the sequential fetch path and adds a suppression signal downstream. The main concern is whether that extra mux level on the pc+4 path adds critical delay to the fetch loop.\n\nLooking back at the lesson chain, similar attempts to add predictor logic have consistently regressed performance, even when the changes seemed localized. The r10s2 approach was architecturally similar—staged muxes on the redirect side—and still lost 20%. My proposal avoids touching the redirect cone entirely, but it still introduces new FF storage and a mux on the sequential PC path, which on a nearly-full fabric could become a bottleneck. Given that r4s2 appears to be at a local optimum, I'm starting to wonder if the predictor slot itself is fundamentally constrained. But stepping back, there's another angle worth exploring: what if we tackle the load-use bubble instead by predicting late-forward paths?\n\n—though that's complex with new comparators and state. Or a trivial JAL-target combining scheme, but that needs dedicated memory ports. After weighing the options, the cleanest remaining approach is embedding RET prediction directly in the sequential-fetch mux rather than the redirect path, keeping the ID cone untouched. It's structurally distinct from prior attempts, even if confidence is low.\n\nActually, let me step back. The r4s2 win was folding the redirect onto an existing wire one stage earlier via a target mux. What if there's another candidate with that exact shape—something unconditional-at-ID that doesn't need operand resolution? JAL works, JALR needs rs1, branches are conditional. What about encoding an unconditional branch as BEQ x0, x0? It's rare but technically valid. Or BEQ rs, rs—always taken since rs equals itself. That's a point solution: any register compared to itself in an equality check is always taken, no operand dependency needed.\n\nBut this pattern barely appears in real code, so it won't help fitness. I'm running out of novel high-confidence angles here. Let me commit to the IF-side RET predictor with sequential-PC mux—it's fundamentally different from prior attempts since they all placed RET prediction on the ID-redirect cone. The lesson is clear: JALR/RET speculation on this fabric must either resolve off the ID redirect cone entirely via IF-side hints and squash-refetch, or it fails. So I need to design the squash-refetch path carefully.\n\nThe idea is that IF fetches linearly at pc+4, but when RET is detected in IF/ID, the next cycle's fetch redirects to link_q instead of continuing sequentially. I can fold this into the sequential +4 path without adding a new PC-mux input. This saves two cycles per RET compared to waiting for EX's redirect—IF stays on the wrong path for one cycle, ID flushes it on the second, but with early prediction at IF we're already fetching the correct target. Let me draft this approach and see if there's one more angle I haven't explored yet, like speculative early write-back.\n\nActually, I'm overthinking this. Looking back at what worked versus what failed, the winning design avoided adding PC-mux inputs, new ID-redirect logic, and EX target mux widening. My RET prediction proposal checks all those boxes—it folds into the existing sequential arm without structural changes, doesn't touch the ID-redirect cone, and doesn't widen the EX mux. This is the most plausible hypothesis given the constraints.\n\nBut now I'm hitting the same append-to-id_ex risk that sank r7s0. I need the ret_predicted bit to suppress EX's redirect when the prediction succeeds, otherwise EX fires a redirect to the same PC we already fetched, which flushes the correct instruction. The real problem is that without suppressing the redirect signal, we gain nothing—the flush still happens. So I either append the bit to id_ex (risky) or find another way to signal it downstream.\n\nActually, looking back at the formal history: r4s2 appended jal_predicted to id_ex_t and passed, and r10s2 appended ret_predicted and also passed formal—it only regressed on FPGA Fmax. The key lesson from r7s0 is that RENAME breaks formal, but APPEND is safe. So appending should work.\n\nLet me sketch out the actual implementation: I'll add ret_predicted as a new field in id_ex_t right after jal_predicted, then in if_stage I'll track the return address in a flop (link_q) that updates whenever a CALL retires, and detect the RET pattern in the fetched instruction to set the prediction signal.\n\nThe tricky part is timing the link_q update—I could update it at WB when the JAL retires, but that's 3-4 cycles stale by the time the RET reaches IF. Better to update link_q directly in IF when we see a JAL with rd==x1, since the return address (pc+4) is already known there. Invalidating link_q gets messy though because I'd need to track every instruction that writes x1, which is a lot of opcodes.\n\nSimpler approach: just mirror x1 writes at the WB stage—whenever the regfile writes x1, link_q gets that value too. If a RET comes before the CALL has written back, link_q will be stale and we'll mispredict, but that's rare and costs the same as no prediction anyway. In the common case where the function body runs for a while, link_q is fresh and prediction works perfectly.\n\nSo the final design adds a ret_predicted bit to the pipeline and updates link_q to shadow x1 writes at WB...\n\nImplementing the misprediction check: I need EX to compare the actual jump target against what IF predicted, and only suppress the redirect if they match. If they don't match, the redirect fires normally. This means threading the predicted target through the pipeline so EX can validate it. The cleanest path forward is threading the predicted target through the id_ex pipeline—it costs 32 flip-flops but saves two cycles on correct predictions. Alternatively, I could suppress RET prediction entirely when link_q might be stale (by checking for in-flight x1 writers in the ID/EX/MEM stages), which eliminates misprediction risk but reduces coverage. Given how many predictor variants have already failed in this slot, I'm leaning toward a simplified approach rather than over-engineering the solution.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decebec63001ZK9zrhxBFQwwqK","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","messageID":"msg_dece989ea001uVVMtGPjG9S6YE"}}
