{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796387952,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01TnHPQPPWdKrnPZPqQFDpG5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"path":"cores/bench/experiments","pattern":"predictor"},"output":"Found 15 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage JAL direct-jump + backward-taken static branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core has zero branch prediction: every taken\\nbranch and every JAL resolves in EX and fires a redirect that\\nflushes IF/ID, costing 2 pipeline bubbles per control-transfer.\\nCoreMark spends a large fraction of its cycles in tight inner loops\\n(crclist, matrix_mul_matrix, state_machine transitions) and in\\nfunction-call glue (JAL/JALR pairs), so those 2-cycle bubbles add\\nup fast. A no-BTB predictor that uses only the freshly-fetched\\ninstruction word itself can eliminate the bubbles for two very\\ncommon and cheaply identifiable cases \\u2014 unconditional JAL (target\\nis a known function of PC+j_imm, so prediction is always correct)\\nand backward-taken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU (the classic\\nloop-back heuristic, ~85%+ accurate in practice for integer code)\\n\\u2014 without adding any stateful predictor storage (no BHT, no BTB,\\nno RAS). That keeps the LUT/FF budget near baseline (currently\\n9880/10000 LUTs) while targeting the dominant CPI contributor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core has zero branch prediction: every taken\\nbranch and every JAL resolves in EX and fires a redirect that\\nflushes IF/ID, costing 2 pipeline bubbles per control-transfer.\\nCoreMark spends a large fraction of its cycles in tight inner loops\\n(crclist, matrix_mul_matrix, state_machine transitions) and in\\nfunction-call glue (JAL/JALR pairs), so those 2-cycle bubbles add\\nup fast. A no-BTB predictor that uses only the freshly-fetched\\ninstruction word itself can eliminate the bubbles for two very\\ncommon and cheaply identifiable cases \\u2014 unconditional JAL (target\\nis a known function of PC+j_imm, so prediction is always correct)\\nand backward-taken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU (the classic\\nloop-back heuristic, ~85%+ accurate in practice for integer code)\\n\\u2014 without adding any stateful predictor...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Registered 16-entry BTB indexed by PC (off the fetch BRAM critical path)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Branch prediction is still the biggest CPI lever on this core: every\\ntaken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/JAL/JALR resolves in EX and costs 2 pipeline\\nbubbles (flush IF + ID). CoreMark's inner loops (crc16, matrix_mul,\\nstate_machine) plus function-call glue hit this tax on a large\\nfraction of cycles. The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2,\\n-11.64%) proved the IPC win is real but put the predecode+adder on\\nthe imem BRAM \\u2192 PC register combinational cone, extending the fetch\\nloop critical path enough on GW2AR to wipe out the gain. The\\nLESSONS.md takeaway is explicit: prediction logic must stay off the\\nPC register's combinational cone \\u2014 register the prediction and\\nabsorb a 1-cycle redirect. A PC-indexed BTB satisfies this: the\\nlookup is driven by the PC register (not by imem_data), and its\\noutput is flopped before reaching the PC mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Branch prediction is still the biggest CPI lever on this core: every\\ntaken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/JAL/JALR resolves in EX and costs 2 pipeline\\nbubbles (flush IF + ID). CoreMark's inner loops (crc16, matrix_mul,\\nstate_machine) plus function-call glue hit this tax on a large\\nfraction of cycles. The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2,\\n-11.64%) proved the IPC win is real but put the predecode+adder on\\nthe imem BRAM \\u2192 PC register combinational cone, extending the fetch\\nloop critical path enough on GW2AR to wipe out the gain. The\\nLESSONS.md takeaway is explicit: prediction logic must stay off the\\nPC register's combinational cone \\u2014 register the prediction and\\nabsorb a 1-cycle redirect. A PC-indexed BTB satisfies this: the\\nlookup is driven by the PC register (not by imem_data), and its\\noutput is flopped before reaching the PC mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small 16-entry direct-mapped, tagged Branch Target Buffer\\nstored in flip-flop...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Regfile as GW2AR distributed-RAM (SSRAM) \\u2014 drop reset-loop to free ~1k FFs and the 32:1 read mux cone\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Baseline uses 9905/10000 LUT4 and 1858 FF on Tang Nano 20K. The r2s2\\nlesson is explicit: \\\"on a near-full Tang Nano 20K ... reclaim area\\nelsewhere first.\\\" Prior structural/predictor hypotheses kept bumping\\ninto area-induced Fmax/routing walls. The integer register file\\n(`reg_file.sv`) is the single biggest area hog in this design that is\\nNOT on anyone's critical path:\\n\\n  - 32 \\u00d7 32b = 1024 FFs (>55% of the total 1858 FF budget)\\n  - Two combinational read ports = two 32:1 32b muxes \\u2248 hundreds of\\n    LUT4s for the read fan-in trees\\n  - A synchronous-reset foreach loop zeroing the array is the ONLY\\n    thing preventing Yosys's `memory_dff`/`memory_bram` pass from\\n    mapping this array to GW2AR LUT4-as-SSRAM (distributed RAM) on\\n    the Gowin flow.\\n\\nGW2AR LUT4s support SSRAM (SP/DP distributed RAM) \\u2014 a 32\\u00d732 two-read\\none-write configuration maps to roughly 2 rows \\u00d7 32 cols \\u00d7 2 read\\nports = ~128 LUT4s configured as memory, replacing ~1024 FFs AND the\\n32:1 read muxes. Net expected save: ~1024 FF + several hundred LUT4\\nheadroom, opening Fmax ceiling on GW2AR where routing/congestion is\\nthe dominant Fmax limiter near 99% LUT occupancy.\\n\\nFunctional behavior must stay bit-identical: x0-hardwire, write-first\\nsame-cycle bypass (ID read of a register being written by WB this\\ncycle returns the new value), and the single-write / dual-read port\\nstructure. The only change is storage inference, not semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Baseline uses 9905/10000 LUT4 and 1858 FF on Tang Nano 20K. The r2s2\\nlesson is explicit: \\\"on a near-full Tang Nano 20K ... reclaim area\\nelsewhere first.\\\" Prior structural/predictor hypotheses kept bumping\\ninto area-induced Fmax/routing walls. The integer register file\\n(`reg_file.sv`) is the single...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) with ID-stage speculative redirect\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is call/return dense \\u2014 crc16, core_bench_matrix, core_bench_state\\nall run through small leaf functions, and every `ret` (JALR x0, x1, 0)\\nin this core costs TWO bubbles today (IF/ID both squashed when EX\\nresolves the JALR redirect). Prior predictor attempts failed for two\\ndistinct reasons that point to a narrow design window:\\n  * r1s2 (static BP at IF): logic on imem_data\\u2192PC_reg cone killed Fmax.\\n  * r2s2 (16-entry BTB, ~928 FFs + ~100 LUTs): IPC win was ~7% but\\n    area congestion on the near-full GW2AR (9905/10000 LUT4) erased it.\\nLESSONS.md explicitly suggests \\\"try 8-entry or tagless variants\\\". A\\nfunction-call RAS is the most area-efficient possible predictor: the\\nhit rate on returns is ~100% in single-threaded code with matching\\ncall/ret discipline (CoreMark qualifies), it needs no tag compare, and\\nthe predicted target is a stored 32-bit word rather than an adder\\ncone. Pattern-less call/ret imbalance is rare in CoreMark's hot loops,\\nso a 4-deep stack covers nearly all dynamic returns without ever\\noverflowing across a leaf call chain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is call/return dense \\u2014 crc16, core_bench_matrix, core_bench_state\\nall run through small leaf functions, and every `ret` (JALR x0, x1, 0)\\nin this core costs TWO bubbles today (IF/ID both squashed when EX\\nresolves the JALR redirect). Prior predictor attempts failed for two\\ndistinct reasons that point to a narrow design window:\\n  * r1s2 (static BP at IF): logic on imem_data\\u2192PC_reg cone killed Fmax.\\n  * r2s2 (16-entry BTB, ~928 FFs + ~100 LUTs): IPC win was ~7% but\\n    area congestion on the near-full GW2AR (9905/10000 LUT4) erased it.\\nLESSONS.md explicitly suggests \\\"try 8-entry or tagless variants\\\". A\\nfunction-call RAS is the most area-efficient possible predictor: the\\nhit rate on ...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Regfile distributed-SSRAM inference: replace reset-loop with initial-zero block\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current reg_file.sv stores the 32x32 integer file in an FF array\\nwith a synchronous reset loop that clears all 32 words in one cycle.\\nOn GW2AR this forces Yosys/nextpnr to synthesise:\\n  - 1024 FFs of real flop storage (drives utilization; resets fanout\\n    to every regfile FF enlarges the reset net).\\n  - Two 32:1 read muxes (one per read port) \\u2014 roughly 60 LUT4 each,\\n    i.e. ~120 LUT4 + their routing plus the write-first-bypass muxes.\\n  - A 5:32 write-address decoder.\\nThis structure is the textbook reason small RISC-V cores on LUT-RAM\\nfabrics move the regfile into distributed SRAM: GW2AR LUTs can be\\nconfigured as 16x1 single-port SSRAM, so a 32x32x1W/2R file collapses\\nto ~64 SSRAM LUTs (one per read port, dual-read = 2x) with zero FF\\nstorage \\u2014 eliminating the 32:1 read-mux trees and most of the FF\\npressure. On this project LUTs are 9905/10000 (99% full) \\u2014 the r2s2\\nBTB lesson explicitly called out that predictor-style wins get erased\\nby congestion-induced Fmax loss. Reclaiming ~100 LUT4 and ~1000 FFs\\nfrom the regfile is a direct area win that unblocks routing freedom\\nfor the existing critical cones, so Fmax should tick up without\\ntouching any timing path.\\n\\nPrior attempt r3s0 tried this by deleting the reset loop outright and\\nwas broken: riscv-formal's per-channel `reg` check (`reg_ch*`) anchors\\nits BMC induction on a known post-reset regfile (all zeros) to diff\\nthe DUT's observable rs?_rdata/rd_wdata against the ISA model. With no\\nreset clear and no init, the initial FF state is unconstrained \\u2014 the\\ncheck fails. The r3s0 lesson explicitly names the usable pattern:\\na synthesis-only `ifndef FORMAL` guard, *or* a ROM-init `initial`\\nblock. The `initial` form is strictly better: it is accepted by\\n  - Verilator (runs initial at t=0, regs start zero in cocotb),\\...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Zero-storage JAL fast-path: resolve JAL redirect in ID via shared redirect wire\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"JAL is unconditional and fully determined at decode time \\u2014 target = PC +\\nimm_j, no rs dependency, no branch condition. Today the pipeline pays\\nthe full 2-cycle EX redirect penalty on every JAL (same cost as a\\nmispredicted branch): IF/ID is flushed, ID/EX is bubbled, PC reloads\\nfrom EX's redirect_target three cycles after the JAL's fetch.\\nCoreMark's call/return structure (list_ins/core_list_find/core_bench_*)\\nhas ~3\\u20135% dynamic JAL density; saving one cycle per JAL by resolving\\nthe redirect in the ID stage \\u2014 one cycle earlier than EX \\u2014 recovers\\n~3\\u20135% of total execution cycles at effectively zero storage cost.\\nPrior predictor attempts (r1s2 JAL/backward-BEQ at IF, r2s2 16-entry\\nBTB, r3s2 4-entry RAS) all failed \\u2014 either on the PC-register D-input\\ncritical path (r1s2), on LUT budget on the near-full GW2AR fabric\\n(r2s2, 928 FFs), or on PC-select fanin growth combined with\\nsnapshot/rollback state (r3s2). This hypothesis deliberately avoids\\nall three failure modes by adding ZERO storage (JAL is unconditional,\\nno rollback needed, no prediction table, no tag compare) and by\\nrouting the ID-stage redirect through the EXISTING redirect wire via\\na small priority mux \\u2014 NOT by adding a new input to if_stage's PC\\nselect. The decoder already produces is_jump (combinational); imm_gen\\nalready produces imm_j (combinational). The new logic is just a\\n1-bit AND + a 32-bit adder + a 2:1 mux at the top-level redirect fan-in.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JAL is unconditional and fully determined at decode time \\u2014 target = PC +\\nimm_j, no rs dependency, no branch condition. Today the pipeline pays\\nthe full 2-cycle EX redirect penalty on every JAL (same cost as a\\nmispredicted branch): IF/ID is flushed, ID/EX is bubbled, PC reloads\\nfrom EX's redirect_target three cycl...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Regfile reset-loop guarded by (YOSYS && !RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS) to enable Gowin distributed-SSRAM inference for FPGA synth only\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Lesson r4s0 explicitly names this as \\\"the remaining viable path\\\" after\\nr3s0 (no-reset for SSRAM inference, broke reg_ch* formal check) and\\nr4s0 (initial-block init, broke SBY with empty traces). The current\\nregfile's synchronous 32-entry reset-to-zero loop forces Yosys to\\ninfer 32x32=1024 FFs + a 32-way one-hot reset mux network, which on\\nGW2AR blocks distributed-SSRAM inference. Area is the binding\\nconstraint on this fabric (9484/10000 LUT4, with predictor-class\\nhypotheses like r2s2 and r3s2 regressing purely on LUT headroom /\\nrouting congestion). Freeing ~1024 FFs + the reset distribution\\nnetwork would materially reduce routing pressure and likely lift\\nFmax via reduced congestion, on top of direct LUT/FF area savings.\\n\\nThe prior failures were both \\\"all-or-nothing\\\" rewrites: dropping\\nreset globally broke formal's reg_ch* BMC (which anchors induction on\\na deterministic all-zero post-reset regfile state), and `initial` was\\nlifted into an SMT universal initial-state constraint by Yosys's SMT\\nbackend that made SBY's per-instruction checks return vacuous\\npasses. The untested path is a macro-guarded version that preserves\\nthe reset loop for Verilator (cocotb tests) AND formal (reg_ch* BMC\\nanchor) but drops it only for the Gowin FPGA yosys synth pass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Lesson r4s0 explicitly names this as \\\"the remaining viable path\\\" after\\nr3s0 (no-reset for SSRAM inference, broke reg_ch* formal check) and\\nr4s0 (initial-block init, broke SBY with empty traces). The current\\nregfile's synchronous 32-entry reset-to-zero loop forces Yosys to\\ninfer 32x32=1024 FFs + a 32-way one-hot reset mux network, which on\\nGW2AR blocks distributed-SSRAM inference. Area is the binding\\nconstraint on this fabric (9484/10000 LUT4, with predict...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Zero-storage backward-branch fast-path predictor at ID stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core (r4s2) won +17.73% by resolving JAL one stage\\nearlier than EX via a zero-storage fast-path at ID that folds onto the\\nexisting `redirect`/`redirect_target` net. JAL dynamic density in\\nCoreMark is only ~3-5%, yet the single-cycle bubble it saves per JAL\\ncleared the Fmax noise floor. CoreMark's inner loops (crcu8, core_bench_*,\\nmatrix_mul_const) are dominated by conditional backward branches\\n(BEQ/BNE), which we currently still pay 1 bubble for on every taken\\nloop iteration (EX-resolved). Dynamic backward-branch density is\\nroughly 10-15% in CoreMark with ~85-90% taken-rate on loop back-edges,\\nso a correctly-implemented static backward-taken predictor at ID can\\nsave ~1.5-3x as many pipeline bubbles as JAL-only, with the same\\nzero-storage cost profile.\\n\\nThe three prior predictor failures teach us exactly what to avoid:\\n  - r1s2 static BP at IF: loaded the PC-reg D-input cone with\\n    predecode + adder + 3-way mux. FAIL.\\n  - r2s2 16-entry BTB: ~928 FF + ~100 LUT on a 9905/10000 near-full\\n    fabric, area/congestion erased IPC win. FAIL.\\n  - r3s2 4-entry RAS: still added a 3rd input to the PC-select\\n    priority mux for id_redirect. FAIL.\\n  - r4s2 JAL fast-path: zero storage, fold onto existing redirect\\n    net, PC mux stays 2:1. WIN (+17.73%).\\n\\nThe r4s2 pattern generalizes cleanly to conditional branches IF we\\nensure (a) the PC mux stays 2:1, (b) no new storage is added, and\\n(c) the misprediction-recovery wire lands on EX's existing\\nredirect path (not a new one). This hypothesis tests that.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core (r4s2) won +17.73% by resolving JAL one stage\\nearlier than EX via a zero-storage fast-path at ID that folds onto the\\nexisting `redirect`/`redirect_target` net. JAL dynamic density in\\nCoreMark is only ~3-5%, yet the single-cycle bubble it s...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Zero-storage backward-branch prediction at ID, r4s2-pattern (additive, no rename)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80-95% accurate on\\nthese CoreMark kernels, covers another ~4-6% of dynamic instructions, and\\nsaves 2 pipeline bubbles per hit.\\n\\nr5s2 attempted this concept but failed implementation: it renamed\\n`jal_predicted` to `predicted_taken`, and a missed downstream consumer\\ncascaded into SBY's \\\"Status: passed / engine_0 did not produce any traces\\\"\\nsignature + cover VCD crash (no_checks_generated). The architectural idea\\nis sound; the diff discipline was not. This hypothesis retries the concept\\nwith strict additive plumbing (no renames) to eliminate the cascade-risk\\nclass of failures entirely.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Flatten ex_stage redirect_target to a single 2:1 mux on is_jalr\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-at-ID fast-path (+17.73%, current best 387.98) added a 2:1\\nmux in front of the PC D-input: `ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target :\\nid_jal_target`. That mux sits on the PC-redirect critical path, which\\nmeans `ex_redirect_target`'s combinational cone is now directly timed\\nagainst fetch Fmax. Any LUT level shaved from `ex_redirect_target`\\nshortens the PC-redirect arm and potentially lifts Fmax without\\ntouching IPC.\\n\\nPast branch-predictor hypotheses (r1s2 static BP, r2s2 BTB, r3s2 RAS,\\nr6s2 BTFN) all regressed because they loaded the PC-select cone. The\\ninverse strategy \\u2014 structurally *simplifying* cones that already feed\\nthe PC-select \\u2014 is underexplored. r4s2's success pattern itself was\\n\\\"resolve one stage earlier and share the existing redirect net\\\"; a\\nnatural complement is \\\"make the existing redirect net's cone shallower\\nwhere structural redundancy exists\\\".\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-at-ID fast-path (+17.73%, current best 387.98) added a 2:1\\nmux in front of the PC D-input: `ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target :\\nid_jal_target`. That mux sits on the PC-redirect critical path, which\\nmeans `ex_redirect_target`'s combinational cone is now directly timed\\nagainst fetch Fmax. Any LUT level shaved from `ex_redirect_target`\\nshortens the PC-redirect arm and potentially lifts Fmax without\\ntouching IPC.\\n\\nPast branch-predictor hypotheses (r1s2 static BP, r2s2 BTB, r3s2 RAS,\\nr6s2 BTFN) all regressed because they loaded the PC-select cone. The\\ninverse strategy \\u2014 structurally *simplifying* cones that already feed\\nthe PC-select \\u2014 is underexplored. r4s2's success pattern itself was\\n\\\"resolve one stage earlier and share the existing redirect net\\\"; a\\nnatural complement is \\\"make the existing redirect net's cone shallower\\nwhere structural redundancy exists\\\".\\n\", \"h...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Implicit 1-entry RAS via dirty-x1 tracking: cone-free JALR-ret fast-path\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-only ID fast-path won (+17.73%) by folding the redirect onto the existing\\n`redirect`/`redirect_target` wire \\u2014 zero storage, no new PC-mux input, no new EX\\ntarget-mux arm. Subsequent predictor extensions (r5s2/r6s2 backward-branch BTFN,\\nr3s2 4-entry RAS) regressed because each added either a mispredict arm to EX\\n(widening the 2:1 target mux to 3:1) or a new id_redirect input to the PC-select\\npriority mux. CoreMark has ~8\\u201312% return-instruction density via `jalr x0, x1, 0`\\nthat the JAL-only path does not accelerate \\u2014 each return still eats 2 bubbles.\\n\\nThe key insight: if we can prove at prediction time that the predicted target\\nEQUALS the actual JALR target, EX-redirect suppression becomes unconditional (like\\njal_predicted), eliminating the need for a 32-bit target compare in EX's redirect\\ncone. That proof is available for free via a \\\"dirty x1\\\" tracker that invalidates\\nthe cached link whenever any non-fast-path writer targets x1.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-only ID fast-path won (+17.73%) by folding the redirect onto the existing\\n`redirect`/`redirect_target` wire \\u2014 zero storage, no new PC-mux input, no new EX\\ntarget-mux arm. Subsequent predictor extensions (r5s2/r6s2 backward-branch BTFN,\\nr3s2 4-entry RAS) regressed because each added either a mispredict arm to EX\\n(widening the 2:1 target mux to 3:1) or a new id_redirect input to the PC-select\\npriority mux. CoreMark has ~8\\u201312% return-instruction density via `jalr x0, x1, 0`\\nthat the JAL-only path does not accelerate \\u2014 each return still eats 2 bubbles.\\n\\nThe key insight: if we can prove at prediction time that the predicted target\\nEQUALS the actual JALR target, EX-redirect suppression becomes unconditional (like\\njal_predicted), eliminating the need for a 32-bit target compare in EX...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Flatten ex_stage redirect_target to a single is_jalr 2:1 mux (no struct edits)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage redirect_target cone currently has two mux levels stacked:\\nfirst jump_target picks between {jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0} and (in.pc + in.imm)\\non is_jalr, then redirect_target picks between jump_target and branch_target\\non is_jump. But branch_target is literally `in.pc + in.imm`, identical to\\njump_target's non-JALR arm. So the outer is_jump mux is structurally\\nredundant: every non-JALR taken-redirect (both JAL and taken-BRANCH)\\nresolves to in.pc + in.imm, and the only architecturally-distinct case is\\nJALR, which picks {jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}.\\nredirect_target feeds core.sv's EX-vs-ID arbitration mux (2:1) then\\nif_stage's PC-select mux (2:1) then the PC D-input \\u2014 i.e. this net is on\\nthe fetch-redirect critical cone that has repeatedly dominated Fmax on\\nthis near-full (9484 / 10000 LUT4) GW2AR fabric. Shaving one LUT-level\\nhere is the micro-opt version of r4s2's \\\"resolve earlier / share the\\nexisting redirect wire\\\" recipe, with zero new storage and no new predictor\\narm.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage redirect_target cone currently has two mux levels stacked:\\nfirst jump_target picks between {jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0} and (in.pc + in.imm)\\non is_jalr, then redirect_target picks between jump_target and branch_target\\non is_jump. But branch_target is literally `in.pc + in.imm`, identical to\\njump_target's non-JALR arm. So the outer is_jump mux is structurally\\nredundant: every non-JALR taken-redirect (both JAL and taken-BRANCH)\\nresolves to in.pc + in.imm, and the only architecturally-distinct case is\\nJALR, which picks {jalr_sum[31:1],1'b0}.\\nredirect_target feeds core.sv's EX-vs-ID arbitration mux (2:1) then\\nif_stage's PC-select mux (2:1) then the PC D-input \\u2014 i.e. this net is on\\nthe fetch-redirect critical cone that has repeatedly dominated Fmax on\\nthis near-full (9484...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Pre-register JAL target at IF to lift the 32-bit adder off the ID redirect cone\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the one predictor that won on this fabric\\n(+17.73%). Every subsequent predictor variant regressed because it\\nviolated at least one of the winning constraints: no new PC-mux\\ninput (r1s2), no storage+tag array pulling LUT area (r2s2), no new\\nID-side fire-term with a misprediction arm widening the EX redirect\\nmux past 2:1 (r6s2, r7s2), no id_ex_t struct rename (r7s0).\\n\\nWhat r4s2 did NOT eliminate, though, is a 32-bit adder sitting on\\nthe ID\\u2192PC-D-in combinational cone. In core.sv today:\\n\\n    id_jal_target  = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm;         // <-- 32b adder\\n    redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_target : id_jal_target;\\n    // if_stage: PC_D = redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4;\\n\\nOn each cycle where a JAL is in ID, the PC register's D-input cone\\npasses through PC_reg \\u2192 if_id_w.pc \\u2192 32-bit carry-chain add \\u2192 2:1\\nmux (ex_redirect select) \\u2192 2:1 mux (redirect select) \\u2192 PC_D. The\\ncarry chain dominates this arm. On near-full GW2AR (9484/10000\\nLUT4), congestion-amplified routing around the carry chain is\\nexactly the sort of thing that nudges Fmax down \\u2014 and r4s2's win\\nconfirms Fmax-side gains are available on the fetch-redirect net.\\n\\nCrucially, the adder's operands both resolve to flop outputs at the\\nclock edge starting cycle N: PC_reg is already flopped; J_imm is a\\nbit-permutation of imem_data which at cycle N is the Gowin BRAM\\noutput (clock-to-Q of the BRAM, not a combinational chain). So the\\nadder can be RELOCATED to compute `jal_target_next = pc + J_imm`\\nduring cycle N-1 (when the JAL is still in IF) and registered into\\na new `jal_target_q` flop on the N-1\\u2192N edge. At cycle N the JAL is\\nin ID and `jal_target_q` is a ready flop output \\u2014 feeding the\\nredirect_target mux with ZERO adder levels in the ID\\u2192PC cone.\\n\\n...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Strip JAL-target adder from redirect-select cone via direct instr[21] alignment test\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path (+17.73%) is the only predictor move that has\\never won on this core. Every attempted extension has regressed (r5s2\\nBEQ-backward broken, r6s2 BTFN -23.5%, r7s2 RAS -50%, r8s2 IF-stage\\npredecode -13.25%) because each adds either a second ID-side predictor\\narm, a widened redirect_target mux, or an extra IF-side carry chain.\\nThe remaining lever is NOT \\\"extend the predictor to more opcodes\\\" but\\n\\\"tighten the existing winning cone\\\". On GW2AR the r4s2 cone feeds two\\nconsumers off the same id_jal_target 32-bit adder: (a) id_jal_target\\nitself drives the redirect_target 2:1 data mux (necessary), and (b)\\nid_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00) drives the redirect\\nSELECT gate via id_is_jal_fire. Consumer (b) is the PC-register\\nD-input select cone, which on a near-full fabric (9484/10000 LUT4)\\nsits close to Fmax-critical; forcing a 32-bit adder's low-output\\ncomparison into the select cone stacks carry-chain latency onto a\\nsignal that should be pure combinational opcode+stall gating.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path (+17.73%) is the only predictor move that has\\never won on this core. Every attempted extension has regressed (r5s2\\nBEQ-backward broken, r6s2 BTFN -23.5%, r7s2 RAS -50%, r8s2 IF-stage\\npredecode -13.25%) because each adds either a second ID-side predictor\\narm, a widened redirect_target mux, or an extra IF-side carry chain.\\nThe remaining lever is NOT \\\"extend the predictor to more opcodes\\\" but\\n\\\"tighten the existing winning cone\\\". On GW2AR the r4s2 cone feeds two\\nconsumers off the same id_jal_target 32-bit adder: (a) id_jal_target\\nitself drives the redirect_target 2:1 data mux (necessary), and (b)\\nid_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00) drives the redirect\\nSELECT gate via id_is_jal_fire. Consumer (b) is the PC-regist...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"1-entry Return Address Cache via staged 2:1 muxes (preserves r4s2's exact arbiter topology)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 zero-storage JAL fast-path remains the only predictor that has\\nimproved fitness on this fabric (+17.73%). Every generalization attempt\\nhas regressed: r5s2/r6s2 (backward branches), r7s2 (implicit RAS via\\ndirty-x1, -50.45%), r8s2 (IF predecode relocate, -13.25%). Reading r7s2's\\nfailure carefully: the -50% came from a *compound* diff \\u2014 (a) a second\\nopcode-compare arm on the ID redirect cone, (b) widening the arbiter\\n`redirect_target` mux from 2:1 to 3:1, AND (c) appending `ret_predicted`\\nto id_ex_t all at once. r4s2's own diff proves (c) alone is safe (it\\nappended `jal_predicted`). The lethal element is most plausibly (b): the\\narbiter mux that feeds if_stage's PC D-input growing from 2:1 to 3:1\\nchanges the fan-in the tool placed favorably for r4s2. JALR-ret density\\nin CoreMark is ~4\\u20136% and single-entry RAC hit rate in leaf-call-heavy\\ninner loops (CoreMark's list_ins / crc / matrix innerloops) is near 100%\\nbecause calls nest shallowly \\u2014 a 1-cycle saving per ret equates to\\n~3\\u20134% IPC headroom if the structural cost can be held near zero.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4s2 zero-storage JAL fast-path remains the only predictor that has\\nimproved fitness on this fabric (+17.73%). Every generalization attempt\\nhas regressed: r5s2/r6s2 (backward branches), r7s2 (implicit RAS via\\ndirty-x1, -50.45%), r8s2 (IF predecode relocate, -13.25%). Reading r7s2's\\nfailure carefully: the -50% came from a *compound* diff \\u2014 (a) a second\\nopcode-compare arm on the ID redirect cone, (b) widening the arbiter\\n`redirect_target` mux from 2:1 to 3:1, AND (c) appending `ret_predicted`\\nto id_ex_t all at once. r4s2's own diff proves (c) alone is safe (it\\nappended `jal_predicted`). The lethal element is most plausibly (b): the\\narbiter mux that feeds if_stage's PC D-in...","metadata":{"matches":15,"truncated":false},"title":"predictor","time":{"start":1777796387926,"end":1777796387950}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_decec136f001uyBIGrloGRuxwV","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","messageID":"msg_decec0d74001ERIjwWu1FlLc6p"}}
