{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777796391945,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"id":"prt_decec2404001QqhCuEp7qOM2X7","messageID":"msg_decec14b3001SFxfz8uae9x0bJ","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","snapshot":"8e4779b470b1d8e60d9ff8632ea85264e2cefa38","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777796443023,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"id":"prt_dececeb67001e6GAGOaeUiaSPj","messageID":"msg_decec14b3001SFxfz8uae9x0bJ","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","type":"text","text":"Looking at the complete predictor history, every ID-side RET predictor variant (r3s2, r7s2, r10s2) has regressed. r10s2's lesson explicitly identifies the untested path: **\"IF-side hint + squash-refetch\"** that resolves RET off the ID redirect cone entirely. Every ID-side predictor has failed because of (a) new fire term on ID-redirect, (b) new upstream target register, or (c) widened redirect_target mux. The sequential-fetch arm of `if_stage.next_pc` has never been used for prediction — that's the unique angle left.\n\nLet me check core.yaml schema and write the hypothesis.","time":{"start":1777796442983,"end":1777796443022}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796443037,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_011uwTvKFNGR7dcxbfaGrKNB","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/schemas/hypothesis.schema.json"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/schemas/hypothesis.schema.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"$schema\": \"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\",\n3:   \"type\": \"object\",\n4:   \"required\": [\"id\",\"title\",\"category\",\"motivation\",\"hypothesis\",\"expected_impact\",\"changes\"],\n5:   \"properties\": {\n6:     \"id\":       {\"type\": \"string\", \"pattern\": \"^hyp-[0-9]{8}-[0-9]{3}(-r[0-9]+s[0-9]+)?$\"},\n7:     \"title\":    {\"type\": \"string\", \"minLength\": 5},\n8:     \"category\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"micro_opt\",\"structural\",\"extension\",\"predictor\",\"memory\"]},\n9:     \"motivation\":  {\"type\": \"string\", \"minLength\": 20},\n10:     \"hypothesis\":  {\"type\": \"string\", \"minLength\": 20},\n11:     \"expected_impact\": {\n12:       \"type\": \"object\",\n13:       \"required\": [\"fitness_delta_pct\",\"confidence\"],\n14:       \"properties\": {\n15:         \"fitness_delta_pct\": {\"type\": \"integer\"},\n16:         \"confidence\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"low\",\"medium\",\"high\"]}\n17:       }\n18:     },\n19:     \"changes\": {\n20:       \"type\": \"array\", \"minItems\": 1,\n21:       \"items\": {\n22:         \"type\": \"object\",\n23:         \"required\": [\"file\",\"description\"],\n24:         \"properties\": {\n25:           \"file\":        {\n26:             \"type\": \"string\",\n27:             \"description\": \"Must be under rtl/ (any extension) or be a test/test_*.py cocotb suite. Anything else is rejected by the runtime sandbox check.\",\n28:             \"pattern\": \"^(rtl/[^.].*|test/test_[^/]+\\\\.py)$\"\n29:           },\n30:           \"description\": {\"type\": \"string\"}\n31:         }\n32:       }\n33:     }\n34:   }\n35: }\n\n(End of file - total 35 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"$schema\": \"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\",\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"required\": [\"id\",\"title\",\"category\",\"motivation\",\"hypothesis\",\"expected_impact\",\"changes\"],\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"id\":       {\"type\": \"string\", \"pattern\": \"^hyp-[0-9]{8}-[0-9]{3}(-r[0-9]+s[0-9]+)?$\"},\n    \"title\":    {\"type\": \"string\", \"minLength\": 5},\n    \"category\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"micro_opt\",\"structural\",\"extension\",\"predictor\",\"memory\"]},\n    \"motivation\":  {\"type\": \"string\", \"minLength\": 20},\n    \"hypothesis\":  {\"type\": \"string\", \"minLength\": 20},\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"type\": \"object\",\n      \"required\": [\"fitness_delta_pct\",\"confidence\"],\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"fitness_delta_pct\": {\"type\": \"integer\"},\n        \"confidence\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"low\",\"medium\",\"high\"]}\n      }\n    },\n    \"changes\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\", \"minItems\": 1,","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"schemas/hypothesis.schema.json","time":{"start":1777796443020,"end":1777796443035}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the different predictor strategies attempted across each slot 2 iteration—static branch prediction, BTB lookups, return address stack, JAL handling, backward branch prediction, and various instruction fetch optimizations—to understand where each approach fell short.\n\nThe key insight from the most recent attempt is that any ID-side predictor modification that adds complexity or new targeting logic incurs a performance penalty regardless of how carefully the downstream topology is preserved. The only viable path forward is to move RET prediction entirely to the IF stage with a squash-refetch mechanism, bypassing the ID redirect cone altogether.\n\nI'm designing an IF-stage RET predictor that tracks the link register value from writeback, detects RET instructions in the instruction stream, and resolves the return target before the instruction reaches ID—this way I can avoid the predictor tax entirely by keeping the ID pipeline untouched.\n\nThe challenge is handling misprediction recovery: normally EX issues a redirect for every JALR, which would flush the correctly-fetched instruction even when the RET prediction succeeds. I need to either suppress the EX redirect on correct predictions by threading the predicted target through the pipeline and comparing it at EX, or guarantee correctness by only predicting when no in-flight x1 writers exist, making suppression unconditional.\n\nThe simpler approach is the in-flight check: if no instruction between ID and WB is writing to x1, then link_q holds the architectural x1 value, so the prediction is guaranteed correct. This way I only need to append a single `ret_predicted` bit to id_ex_t to suppress the redirect, rather than adding 32 FFs for the target comparison.\n\nThe structural changes are minimal: add the link_q register and valid flag in the IF stage, insert the ret_predicted bit into id_ex_t, and add a 2:1 mux to select between link_q and pc+4 for the sequential fetch path.\n\nNow I'm working through the redirect logic and the combinational cone for the RET prediction check—it's a 6-term AND for the instruction match plus the in-flight checks, which pulls several pipeline flop outputs into the IF-side critical path. The concern is whether the timing works out, especially since the pipeline is 5 stages deep and the in-flight check needs to verify that any x1 writer has already committed to link_q before the RET reaches IF.\n\nThe safest approach is to gate the prediction signal itself with a narrow combinational check across the three pipeline stages—if any has rd==1 with reg_write active, suppress the prediction. This keeps the new 2:1 mux on the sequential PC path to just one additional LUT level, and the ret_pred signal itself has multiple input terms from the instruction encoding plus the link_valid flag and the pending-writer check.\n\nThe critical path concern is real: the sequential fetch path gets one LUT deeper, but the redirect path is likely the binding constraint anyway. I think this is the cleanest remaining option, so let me structure the hypothesis carefully.\n\nActually, there's a simpler angle: instead of checking for pending writes, rely on EX's normal JALR redirect to catch mispredictions. The trick is threading the predicted target through the pipeline so EX can compare it against the actual computed jump target—either by passing pred_target as a 32-bit signal through id_ex, or by comparing the actual rs1 value (via forwarding) against what link_q held at IF time.\n\nOption A gates prediction strictly when link_q is guaranteed correct (no pending x1 writers), then always suppresses in EX—cheaper in FFs but adds an in-flight check cone. Option B threads the predicted target through id_ex and lets EX compare—more FFs but simpler logic. I'll go with A for minimal area.\n\nThe final design: IF-side RET predictor that redirects through the sequential PC path, with a 32-bit link_q and valid bit updated conservatively whenever WB writes x1. Gate prediction on RET opcode match, link_valid, and no in-flight x1 writers. In EX, suppress the redirect when ret_predicted since the gate guarantees correctness. Add a ret_predicted bit to id_ex_t, and invalidate link_valid whenever ID decodes an instruction that will write x1, then re-validate when WB actually commits the write.\n\nNow I'm settling on the simplest approach: link_q captures WB.w_data whenever x1 is written, link_valid_q becomes 1 after the first x1 write, and I check for pending x1 writers across all pipeline stages conservatively. RET prediction fires only when the opcode matches, link is valid, there are no pending writers, and no flushes or stalls are active—then seq_pc becomes link_q instead of pc+4. The ret_predicted bit propagates through id_ex_t so EX can suppress any redirect, just like with jal_predicted. This adds only 32 FFs total.\n\nThe risk is real though: the new 2:1 mux on the sequential PC path could add a LUT level, the pending_x1 check widens the fire signal's cone, and appending to id_ex_t has caused issues before. The 32 new FFs for link_q are the main area the lesson calls out explicitly. This is IF-side rather than ID-side, which is better, and the lesson does mention \"IF-side hint + squash-refetch\" as a potentially viable path. I'm going to estimate this as medium-confidence with an expected timing delta around 5%.\n\nActually, looking at how predictor failures accumulate, I should be more conservative. I'm revising down to +3% expected delta with low confidence.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dececeb76001EKqsSU7Dld3DST","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","messageID":"msg_decec14b3001SFxfz8uae9x0bJ"}}
