{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777796485162,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_012p9Q4jDJjXabnoXWUCdoDU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r11s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r11s2\ntitle: \"IF-side RET predictor via sequential-PC arm (squash-refetch off the ID redirect cone)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Every ID-side RET/JALR predictor has regressed on this fabric\n  (r3s2 4-entry RAS ~0%, r7s2 dirty-x1 RAS -50%, r10s2 1-entry RAC\n  -20%). The r10s2 lesson names the one remaining unexplored path\n  explicitly: \"JALR/RET speculation on this fabric must either\n  resolve off the ID redirect cone entirely (IF-side hint +\n  squash-refetch) or be abandoned\". r4s2's JAL fast-path won\n  (+17.73%) by folding onto the EXISTING redirect wire via an\n  upstream 2:1; every variant that widened the ID-side redirect\n  cone (new fire term, new upstream target mux, new target\n  register) paid the full predictor tax regardless of downstream\n  topology preservation. What no hypothesis has tried: fold the\n  RET prediction into the SEQUENTIAL-fetch arm of if_stage's PC\n  D-input, leaving the `redirect`/`redirect_target` cone\n  structurally identical to the current winning r4s2 form.\n\n  CoreMark's call/return density is ~4-6% dynamic (crc16, list_ins,\n  matrix inner helpers, state_machine small leaves); every RET\n  costs 2 bubbles today. Saving one bubble per correctly-predicted\n  RET recovers ~2-3% of execution cycles — same order of magnitude\n  as r4s2's JAL-only win, but through a structurally disjoint\n  fetch path.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Add an IF-stage RET predictor whose sole PC-path footprint is a\n  2:1 mux on the existing pc+4 sequential arm. The PC-select top\n  mux remains structurally 2:1 (`redirect ? redirect_target :\n  seq_pc`) — byte-identical to today — but `seq_pc` internally\n  picks between `link_q` (on RET prediction) and `pc+4` (default).\n  The `redirect`/`redirect_target` cone is UNTOUCHED.\n\n  Structural additions:\n\n  1. `link_q[31:0]` + `link_valid_q` flops in if_stage (or core.sv),\n     updated from the WB stage's regfile write port: when\n     `wb_w_en && wb_w_addr == 5'd1`, `link_q <= wb_w_data` and\n     `link_valid_q <= 1`. This tracks x1's architectural value.\n\n  2. Conservative \"no pending x1 writer\" gate from the three\n     downstream pipeline register outputs:\n        `pending_x1 = (id_ex.rd == 5'd1 && id_ex.ctrl.reg_write)\n                    | (ex_mem.rd == 5'd1 && ex_mem.ctrl.reg_write)\n                    | (mem_wb.rd == 5'd1 && mem_wb.ctrl.reg_write\n                                         && mem_wb.valid)`.\n     When `pending_x1 == 1`, `link_q` may not yet reflect the\n     architectural x1 — skip prediction this cycle.\n\n  3. RET pattern match on `imem_data` (zero-storage, 5 field eqs):\n        `is_ret_pat = (imem_data[6:0]   == 7'b1100111)   // JALR\n                    & (imem_data[14:12] == 3'b000)       // funct3=0\n                    & (imem_data[19:15] == 5'd1)         // rs1=x1\n                    & (imem_data[11:7]  == 5'd0)         // rd=x0\n                    & (imem_data[31:20] == 12'd0);`      // imm=0\n\n  4. Fire gate:\n        `ret_pred_fire = is_ret_pat & link_valid_q & !pending_x1\n                       & if_id_w.valid & !stall_if & !redirect\n                       & imem_ready & (link_q[1:0] == 2'b00);`\n\n  5. Sequential PC arm becomes:\n        `seq_pc = ret_pred_fire ? link_q : (pc + 32'd4);`\n     PC D-input select stays 2:1: `next_pc = redirect ?\n     redirect_target : seq_pc;`.\n\n  6. Propagate `ret_pred_fire` into a NEW id_ex_t bit\n     `ret_predicted` (APPEND after `jal_predicted`, per r7s0 rule\n     — no rename, leaving all existing field names and positions\n     intact in core_pkg.sv's id_ex_t struct).\n\n  7. EX-stage redirect suppression extends the existing\n     `jal_predicted` mask:\n        `redirect = (branch_taken\n                  | (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.jal_predicted\n                                     && !in.ret_predicted))\n                  && !misalign_fault;`\n     Because the `pending_x1` gate guarantees link_q == x1 at\n     prediction time, the predicted target is provably correct,\n     so suppression is unconditional (identical discipline to\n     JAL's jal_predicted) — no 32-bit target-compare in EX, no\n     widening of redirect_target past 2:1.\n\n  Why this avoids the predictor-tax failure modes:\n\n  - NO new input to if_stage's PC-select top mux (stays 2:1).\n  - NO new arm on EX's redirect_target mux (stays 2:1 JAL/BRANCH vs. JALR).\n  - NO new fire term on the ID-side `redirect` net (id_is_jal_fire\n    remains the sole ID contributor; RET's fire signal only\n    reaches the SEQUENTIAL-PC mux, a distinct cone).\n  - Append-only to id_ex_t (r4s2 proved append is safe; r7s0 only\n    forbade rename).\n\n  Risk enumeration (why confidence is low, not medium):\n\n  - The new 2:1 mux on `seq_pc` adds 1 LUT level to the sequential\n    fetch cone. r8s2's -13% regression placed a carry chain on\n    that same cone, so even a shallow addition may bind Fmax. The\n    2:1 here is shallower than r8s2's 32-bit adder, but the near-full\n    fabric (9484/10000 LUT4) has no margin.\n  - 32 new FFs (link_q) land on a 1861-FF fabric. Not huge but\n    contributes to placement pressure.\n  - The `pending_x1` check reads rd/reg_write fields from three\n    pipeline registers into a 3-way OR that gates the fire signal.\n    This signal is local to if_stage but sources cross-stage flop\n    outputs — routing cost unclear on GW2AR.\n\n  If this regresses, the transferable lesson confirms \"IF-side\n  squash-refetch RET speculation is net-negative on this fabric\"\n  and closes the last predictor angle — all future slot-2 diversity\n  work should pivot to non-predictor Fmax wins.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\n\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"APPEND a new `logic ret_predicted` field to id_ex_t, placed immediately after `jal_predicted`. Do NOT rename any existing field (r7s0 rule). All existing struct field order preserved.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add `link_q[31:0]` and `link_valid_q` flops updated from new `wb_w_en_x1` / `wb_w_data_x1` input ports. Add RET pattern-match combinational `is_ret_pat` on `imem_data`, the `pending_x1` 3-way OR from new pipeline-probe input ports, the `ret_pred_fire` fire gate (guarded by link_valid, !pending_x1, !stall/!flush/!redirect, imem_ready, and link_q[1:0]==0), and a new 2:1 mux on the sequential PC arm: `seq_pc = ret_pred_fire ? link_q : pc+4`. PC-select top mux stays structurally 2:1. Expose `ret_pred_fire` as an output for id_stage's new ret_predicted_in port.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add new `ret_predicted_in` input port (1 bit) alongside existing `jal_predicted_in`. Latch it into `reg_q.ret_predicted` on the same always_ff already writing `reg_q.jal_predicted`. No existing field renames.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend the redirect suppression: change `redirect` assignment from `(branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.jal_predicted)) && !misalign_fault` to `(branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && !in.jal_predicted && !in.ret_predicted)) && !misalign_fault`. No other changes to ex_stage's datapath, target mux, or redirect_target wiring.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire up the new cross-module signals: pass `wb_w_en && (wb_w_addr==5'd1)` and `wb_w_data` into if_stage's new link-write ports; pass `id_ex_w.rd/ctrl.reg_write`, `ex_mem_w.rd/ctrl.reg_write`, `mem_wb_w.rd/ctrl.reg_write/valid` into if_stage's new pending_x1 probe ports; thread if_stage's new `ret_pred_fire` output into id_stage's new `ret_predicted_in` port. No changes to hazard_unit wiring, the combined redirect mux, or the RVFI port set.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb test case `test_ret_fast_path` that (a) issues a CALL (JAL x1, target), (b) waits for x1 to reach WB, (c) issues matching RET (JALR x0, 0(x1)), and asserts the RET retires with exactly one fewer cycle bubble than the baseline (fire path verified) AND that the RVFI pc_wdata of the RET equals x1's architectural value. Also add a negative case with a pending x1 writer in EX at RET-fetch time, verifying prediction is correctly suppressed and the baseline 2-bubble path retires.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r11s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r11s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777796485140,"end":1777796485158}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_dececf4b8001nKnxyEQfQXwnS2","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","messageID":"msg_dececebe5001Clgoy4zOtnqrxr"}}
