{"type":"text","timestamp":1777796493314,"sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","part":{"id":"prt_deced96d6001b5ui3JhJTYkXCf","messageID":"msg_deced906b001dj3q436IXkHP9K","sessionID":"ses_21316770fffeZjXh7ULGb7HFFe","type":"text","text":"Written `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r11s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Proposed an IF-side RET predictor that resolves `jalr x0, 0(x1)` via the **sequential-fetch arm** of `if_stage.next_pc` rather than the redirect cone. This is the one predictor angle no prior iteration has tried — r10s2's lesson explicitly named \"IF-side hint + squash-refetch\" as the last untested path after three failed ID-side RAS variants.\n\n**Topology preservation**:\n- PC-select top mux stays structurally 2:1 (r1s2/r8s2 failure mode avoided)\n- `redirect_target` stays 2:1 (r6s2/r7s2 failure mode avoided)\n- No new fire term on the ID redirect cone (r6s2/r7s2/r10s2 failure mode avoided)\n- `id_ex_t.ret_predicted` is APPENDED (r7s0 rule — no rename)\n\n**Mechanism**: `link_q` mirrors x1 via WB write port; `pending_x1` OR of three pipeline registers' `rd==1 & reg_write` gates prediction so link_q is provably correct when fired, allowing unconditional EX suppression (no 32-bit compare, no misprediction arm).\n\n**Confidence: low** (expected +3%). The risks are (a) the new 2:1 mux on the sequential PC arm and (b) the cross-stage `pending_x1` probe's routing cost on the 94.8%-full fabric. If it regresses, this closes the last predictor angle and informs all future slot-2 work to pivot away from predictors.","time":{"start":1777796486870,"end":1777796493311}}}
