{"type":"text","timestamp":1777798358409,"sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","part":{"id":"prt_ded0a1ade0012VA45M5fnoJilZ","messageID":"msg_ded086c25001T2yMo0fQ6LJIud","sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","type":"text","text":"Looking at the extensive predictor-failure log, I need to find an angle that hasn't been exhausted. Key lessons:\n- r4s2 JAL fast-path (only winner): zero storage, resolves unconditional case one stage earlier, shares existing redirect wire\n- Every other predictor (static BP, BTB, RAS variants, BTFN, RAC, IF-side RET) regressed\n- r6s2 specifically: adding ANY second ID-side fire term with a misprediction arm taxes the redirect cone\n- r8s2: IF-side flopping of adders adds parallel-cone setup cost\n\nThe one **genuinely unexplored** predictor angle: extending r4s2's fast-path to cover architecturally-unconditional BRANCH instructions (BEQ rs,rs where rs1==rs2 in encoding — taken with certainty, no misprediction arm). This broadens r4s2's trigger set without introducing a new predictor arm on the redirect cone.","time":{"start":1777798355678,"end":1777798358408}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777798358434,"sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Wdh8fTqBvrSu8iuvkDsUSA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check hypotheses directory exists"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypotheses directory exists","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypotheses directory exists","time":{"start":1777798358418,"end":1777798358431}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at the bench core predictor slot, and the lessons are pretty clear that predictor approaches have mostly failed—except for r4s2's JAL fast-path optimization. The guidance says to pivot away from predictors entirely for slot-2 diversity work, but since this slot is specifically designated for a predictor, I need to propose one anyway despite the track record of regressions.\n\nScanning through what's already been attempted—static predictors, BTB variants, RAS configurations, predecode optimizations, and various JAL/RET strategies—they've all underperformed except that one win. The pattern suggests I should look for something fundamentally different rather than iterating on existing approaches. I'm considering JALR prediction by resolving indirect jumps earlier through direct regfile reads, avoiding the forwarding delay that typically constrains these predictions. (no hazard on rs1), then we know the target at end of ID. This is a zero-storage approach similar to r4s2.\n\nWait — r7s2 tried JALR prediction and failed hard with link_q storage, but a pure \"compute JALR target at ID when rs1 has no hazard\" is structurally different. The catch is that rs1 might need forwarding, so we'd only fire when rs1 has no hazard (not in id_ex.rd, ex_mem.rd, or pending), which lets us resolve at ID. But the lessons show that even predictor taxes like the ID-side fire term and target mux fanin are expensive.\n\nI've been cycling through options — predict JAL return addresses, gshare BHT lookups, BTFN, prefetch into skid buffers — but r2s1 showed skid buffers regress, and r4s2 made clear that any predictor with a misprediction arm pays for both the widened EX target mux and the wider ID-side cone. Given the constraints, maybe the answer is a tiny next-line predictor with just a 1-bit \"is-JAL-or-taken-backward-branch\" flag tagged by PC bits in a 2–4 entry table, fired only on backward branches with loop signatures. Or possibly the real win is simpler: predict branches not-taken at ID and only absorb the bubble when they're actually taken, which is closer to what we already do. I'm circling back to the constraint that the user wants a predictor, even though the lessons suggest moving away from them entirely. The most honest approach is something that doesn't regress the current r4s2 design—maybe extending the JAL fast-path to narrow the EX redirect gate for JAL instructions, though that's already handled by the `!jal_predicted` logic. I keep hitting dead ends with regfile write ordering and other complications, so let me consider a simpler angle: a small 4-entry direct-mapped hint table indexed by PC bits that tracks whether backward branches at specific addresses tend to be taken, with combinational lookup and the target already available from the immediate field.\n\nStill examining the redirect logic in the EX stage...\n\nActually, I think the real win here is simpler: **BEQ x0,x0 is how GCC emits unconditional branches, so if I fuse that pattern into a JAL at the decoder level, it gets caught by the existing JAL fast-path without any new hardware or state overhead.** This reuses the r4s2 predictor infrastructure that's already working well.\n\nThe tricky part is that the decoder would need to recognize BEQ where both operands are the same register and reclassify it as a jump, but then the immediate generation and id_is_jal matching logic would need to handle this pseudo-jump without breaking the opcode-based dispatch — which is where the current approach hits a wall since BEQ's opcode won't match JAL's.\n\nI'm cycling through simpler angles now: maybe a minimal predictor that just pre-computes the branch direction sign bit to shave off a carry chain, or extending the JAL fast-path to prefetch the target instruction, but both of those either don't really solve the core problem or run into port conflicts with the memory system.\n\nLet me try a completely different tack and focus on explicitly addressing one of the known failure modes...\n\nActually, I'm realizing most of these ideas either don't move the needle or are structurally infeasible. I think the safest bet is to extend the existing r4s2 JAL fast-path to handle misaligned targets by firing the redirect at ID and passing the misalign fault bit through the pipeline, which avoids redundant work in EX even though misaligned JALs are vanishingly rare in practice.\n\nBut I'm going to commit to something more novel: fusing AUIPC and JALR at the decoder level when they appear in sequence, since that's a common call-site pattern that could benefit from tighter coupling. I'm reconsidering whether there's actually a fetch bubble when the JAL fast-path redirects — looking at the IF stage logic, when redirect fires it flushes to NOP, but the next cycle the PC is already at the target and imem should deliver the instruction, so valid goes high immediately without losing a cycle. Let me trace through the exact timing to confirm whether this optimization is even necessary.\n\nActually, I think the better bet is extending the r4s2 fast-path to handle BEQ x0,x0 as an unconditional branch pattern — since both source registers are hardwired to zero, the comparison always succeeds and there's no misprediction risk, making it architecturally safe to redirect without speculation.\n\nBut that's probably too rare in CoreMark since the compiler just emits JAL for unconditional jumps anyway.\n\nThe more promising angle is an ID-stage branch-compare fast-path for patterns like BEQZ (BEQ with rs2=x0), which are common in CoreMark. The catch is that rs1 needs to be valid at ID to resolve the comparison early, but forwarding isn't available until EX — so I'd need to restrict this to cases where there's no hazard on rs1 and the regfile delivers the committed value directly.\n\nThat would require adding a hazard-check cone, a comparator, and a fire term at ID, which r6s2 already showed causes regressions.\n\nGiven how many optimizations have failed, I'm settling on the least risky approach: an IF-side JAL predecoded flop that moves the JAL-target adder out of the ID redirect cone entirely by replacing it rather than duplicating it. The ID stage would read the registered target and fire the redirect from that flop, avoiding any critical-path extension.\n\nBut there's a timing issue — if the predecode flop captures during cycle N when the instruction fetches, the ID stage doesn't see it until N+1, yet JAL is already in ID at cycle N since IF/ID is combinational. Holding JAL in IF for an extra cycle to sync with the flopped target adds a cycle per JAL, which is unacceptable.\n\nI keep circling back to the same constraints, so I'm committing to a small BHT for conditional branches, sized down aggressively and placed off the PC select cone. The lookup happens at ID, drives an id_ex bit, and EX's redirect gate gets an additional arm for predicted-taken misfires that's negligibly deep — though honestly this has the same fundamental problems as everything else I've tried.\n\nLet me pivot to something different: a decoder-level rewrite that converts architecturally-unconditional branch patterns like BEQ rs,rs into JAL-like instructions so I can reuse the r4s2 fast-path. When the decoder spots these patterns, it sets is_jump=1, is_branch=0, and routes the branch immediate through a small multiplexer in the target adder to handle the different immediate encoding, letting the existing JAL fast-path fire for the taken case. I'm weighing the trade-offs between adding a mux on the critical path versus duplicating the adder logic — the mux adds one LUT level which could trigger the same regression we saw before, while parallel adders would cost more area. Given how conservatively r4s2 performed and the clear lesson from r6s2 that any branch prediction on the ID cone hurts, I'm going to keep this minimal and propose a decoder-level rewrite, then let the orchestrator decide if it's worth the risk.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded0a22ae001NkmvrxmPW2I1a3","sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","messageID":"msg_ded086c25001T2yMo0fQ6LJIud"}}
