{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777798467832,"sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_011KqPsHpeLFNt4jRhQFD92w","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r12s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r12s2\ntitle: \"BEQ rs,rs static-taken fusion — broaden r4s2 JAL fast-path to architecturally-unconditional BRANCH\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The predictor design space on this core is unusually constrained: r4s2's\n  zero-storage ID-stage JAL fast-path is the only predictor ever to win\n  (+17.73%), while every attempt to add a second ID-side fire term\n  (BTFN r6s2 -23%, dirty-x1 RAS r7s2 -50%, RAC r10s2 -20%, IF-side RET\n  r11s2 -26%), widen the redirect_target arbitration mux past 2:1\n  (r7s2/r10s2), or even restructure r4s2's own winning cone (r8s2/r9s2\n  -13% to -19%) has regressed on the near-full GW2AR fabric. The\n  transferable rule from r4s2 is that a predictor only wins when it is\n  (a) architecturally unconditional (no misprediction arm) and (b)\n  reuses the existing redirect wire topology (2:1 target arbitration\n  preserved). The unexplored angle that fits both constraints is\n  BEQ rs,rs (instr[19:15] == instr[24:20] with funct3=000): this\n  encoding is architecturally unconditional-taken (x == x is always\n  true) exactly like JAL, has zero misprediction cost, and its target\n  is pc + B_imm computed at ID from fields already available. GCC\n  occasionally emits BEQ x0,x0 as an unconditional branch idiom for\n  loop-header jumps and long-jump trampolines; even a modest fraction\n  of such instructions converted from 2-bubble EX redirects to\n  0-bubble ID redirects contributes to CoreMark IPC without any Fmax\n  cost on the prediction side.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Extend core.sv's ID-stage fast-path to also fire on architecturally-\n  unconditional conditional branches, specifically BEQ rs,rs (the only\n  BRANCH encoding that is guaranteed-taken with no runtime condition).\n  Detection is purely combinational and local: opcode=1100011,\n  funct3=000, and instr[19:15]==instr[24:20]. The target is\n  pc + B_imm, which we compute in a new *parallel* 32-bit adder\n  (NOT muxed into the r4s2 J_imm adder's input — that would add a\n  LUT level to the r4s2 winning cone per the r8s1/r9s2 lesson).\n\n  Topology preservation (the r4s2 winning recipe):\n  - The top-level `redirect` wire gains one additional OR term\n    (`id_is_beqrr_fire`), staying a flat OR of same-stage fire\n    signals — no new mux input.\n  - The top-level `redirect_target` mux stays strictly 2:1\n    (ex_redirect vs id_fast_target). A local 2:1 mux at ID selects\n    between id_jal_target and id_beqrr_target based on\n    id_is_jal_fire vs id_is_beqrr_fire (mutually exclusive by\n    opcode). This local mux sits OFF the ex_redirect arbitration\n    path and its output feeds only the id-side arm of the same\n    2:1 arbiter — preserving the exact winning form.\n  - No new id_ex_t fields (r7s0 rule): the existing `jal_predicted`\n    bit widens its semantic to mean \"this instruction's redirect\n    already fired at ID; EX must suppress its would-be redirect\".\n    EX already masks on `!jal_predicted` for is_jump; we additionally\n    gate EX's branch_taken arm by `!jal_predicted` (zero new\n    signals — just one more AND gate on the existing bit's fanout).\n  - The `id_jal_aligned` check naturally extends: B_imm has bit 0\n    hardwired to 0 (like J_imm), so alignment requires only\n    target[1] == 0, same form as today.\n\n  Safeguards for the r6s2 tax (second fire term on the ID cone):\n  - The new detector is a strict-equality 5-bit compare\n    (instr[19:15] == instr[24:20]), an opcode==BRANCH compare,\n    and a funct3==0 compare — three small LUTs at most, no\n    carry chains, running fully in parallel with r4s2's existing\n    JAL opcode compare and J_imm adder. The longest new cone is\n    the parallel 32-bit pc + B_imm adder, which runs concurrently\n    with the existing pc + J_imm adder and does not extend any\n    existing critical path.\n  - id_is_beqrr is mutually exclusive with id_is_jal by opcode,\n    so no arbitration logic is needed between them — a simple\n    local OR forms id_is_fast_fire.\n  - Because this is architecturally always-taken, EX's redirect\n    arm never needs to fire for a correctly-predicted BEQ rs,rs\n    (same property as JAL). The existing `jal_predicted` mask\n    covers it with no new field.\n\n  Expected impact: CoreMark's compiled output at -O3 emits BEQ x0,x0\n  rarely (GCC prefers JAL for unconditional jumps), so the dynamic\n  density is likely 0.5–2%, yielding a small positive IPC nudge\n  (~1–2 cycles saved per BEQ rs,rs instance). The Fmax risk is\n  limited to the near-full fabric's response to ~50 new LUTs\n  (one 32-bit adder + compares + a 32-bit 2:1 mux at the ID-side\n  fast-target output) — but the new logic runs strictly in\n  parallel with r4s2's winning cone, and the top-level redirect\n  arbiter is byte-identical to the shipping form.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\n\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Add id_is_beqrr detection (opcode=BRANCH && funct3=0 && instr[19:15]==instr[24:20]), id_beqrr_imm (B-immediate formation from instr), parallel id_beqrr_target = pc + B_imm, id_beqrr_aligned = target[1]==0 (bit 0 is architecturally 0 from B-imm), id_is_beqrr_fire = id_is_beqrr & !stall_id & id_beqrr_aligned & if_id_w.valid. Extend redirect wire: redirect = ex_redirect | id_is_jal_fire | id_is_beqrr_fire. Extend id-side arm of redirect_target mux: local 2:1 selects id_jal_target when id_is_jal_fire else id_beqrr_target. The top-level ex-vs-id 2:1 arbitration stays structurally unchanged. Pass id_is_beqrr_fire into id_stage alongside id_is_jal_fire as a new jal_predicted_in contributor (ORed before being written into id_ex).\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Widen jal_predicted_in's semantic to 'unconditional redirect fired at ID this cycle' by accepting the ORed id_is_jal_fire | id_is_beqrr_fire from core.sv (same input port signature, no rename — preserves r7s0's frozen-field-names rule). No id_ex_t struct edits.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb test case driving a BEQ x0,x0 unconditional branch pattern to confirm ID-stage fast-path redirect fires, target is pc + B_imm, and EX's redirect is suppressed via the existing jal_predicted mask. Include at least one BEQ x1,x1 (non-zero identical registers) as regression against any accidental reliance on rs being x0.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r12s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r12s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777798467814,"end":1777798467830}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The directory check passes, so now I'm reconsidering the hypothesis around the r4s2 winner logic—specifically how it detects JAL instructions and determines whether they should fire, checking the opcode, extracting the J-type immediate, computing the target address, verifying alignment, and gating the signal based on whether it's actually a valid JAL that isn't stalled.\n\nFor extending this to handle \"BEQ rs,rs\" (where both source registers are identical, making it architecturally unconditional), I'd detect the BRANCH opcode with BEQ funct3 and matching register fields. The target calculation differs—it uses B-type immediate encoding instead of J-type—so I'm weighing two approaches: either multiplex the immediate into the existing adder (adds one LUT level to r4s2's critical path) or build a parallel 32-bit adder for the BEQ target and select between the two results with a final mux (costs area but keeps r4s2's cone untouched). Given r8s1's experience with parallel structures and the tight fabric constraints, the parallel adder feels structurally safer even though it's more expensive.\n\nBut widening the redirect_target mux from 2:1 to 3:1 is risky—r7s2 and r10s2 already showed regression when that mux grew. The safest move is to pre-mux the immediate (choosing B_imm for BEQ or J_imm otherwise) before feeding it into r4s2's existing adder, keeping the downstream mux unchanged. This is surgical and avoids touching r4s2's proven cone, though given r9s2's 19% loss from a single-line change there, even this carries risk.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded0b5332001NmwZiUiI5gtHZa","sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","messageID":"msg_ded0a3027001LlNKwvgF2CGAIs"}}
