{"type":"text","timestamp":1777798476477,"sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","part":{"id":"prt_ded0bdc6b001bzb30yKHsb6zGC","messageID":"msg_ded0bd142001QlyT3cbggMKsWm","sessionID":"ses_212f79491ffedS3EmZeXEwy1gY","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written. Summary:\n\n**hyp-20260503-003-r12s2**: BEQ rs,rs static-taken fusion — extends r4s2's JAL fast-path to cover architecturally-unconditional BRANCH instructions (BEQ where rs1==rs2 encoding-wise is always taken, zero misprediction arm).\n\nKey design choices aimed at avoiding known failure modes:\n- **No new id_ex_t fields** (r7s0 rule): reuses existing `jal_predicted` bit with widened semantic\n- **2:1 arbiter preserved** (r7s2/r10s2 rule): ex-vs-id-fast arbitration stays byte-identical; the new BEQ-rr target is selected by a local 2:1 upstream of the arbiter (mutually exclusive by opcode with JAL)\n- **No mux on r4s2's winning adder input** (r8s1/r9s2 rule): B_imm adder runs in parallel to the existing J_imm adder, not muxed into it\n- **Zero misprediction arm** (r6s2 rule): BEQ rs,rs is architecturally guaranteed-taken, so no EX misprediction path needed\n\nConfidence: low. The predictor design space on this core has been extensively explored with only r4s2 succeeding; even topology-preserving extensions (r10s2) have regressed. Dynamic density of BEQ x0,x0 in GCC -O3 CoreMark output is likely modest (GCC prefers JAL), so the IPC ceiling is small. The bet is that the broadened trigger pays more than ~50 LUTs of new parallel logic costs on the near-full fabric.","time":{"start":1777798470763,"end":1777798476475}}}
