{"type":"text","timestamp":1777800059025,"sessionID":"ses_212de73dfffe6fU0mVsdmO9O5O","part":{"id":"prt_ded23854d001KCO7A0mC8gYigN","messageID":"msg_ded218cd3001noHnTeSltS5Wsf","sessionID":"ses_212de73dfffe6fU0mVsdmO9O5O","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons, the predictor category has been exhaustively explored with a stark pattern: **every predictor angle regresses except r4s2's JAL fast-path (+17.73%)**. Four JALR/RET predictor topologies (r3s2 RAS, r7s2 dirty-x1, r10s2 RAC, r11s2 IF-side) all failed. BTFN (r6s2), BEQ-rs,rs (r12s2), IF-predecode-JAL (r8s2), and even a cone-equivalent rewrite of r4s2 itself (r9s2) all regressed.\n\nThe consistent negative pattern: **any predictor with a second ID-side fire term, new upstream/downstream target mux, id_ex_t append, or flop on the fetch-redirect cone pays a GW2AR Fmax tax that exceeds IPC wins** — because the fabric is 94.8% full and the r4s2 cone is already at a CSE/placement optimum.\n\nOne angle remains genuinely untested: **widening the JAL fast-path to the sibling unconditional opcode — `JAL x0, +offset` hoists from the rd=x0 no-link arm being already covered by the existing path, so the real untested sibling is a predictor-style early-retire for the JAL link write itself**. But all such variants have the same structural cost.\n\nGiven the overwhelming negative evidence, I'll propose the most minimal, lowest-risk predictor concept — eliminating the tautological `id_jal_aligned` gate *by deletion* (not substitution, distinguishing from r9s2's cone-rewrite). Since PC[1:0]≡00 (reset=0, pc+=4, JALR clears bit 0, branch-target misalign trapped) and J-imm[1:0]≡00, the check is architecturally dead. Deleting it removes a LUT level from `id_is_jal_fire` without introducing new logic.","time":{"start":1777800021325,"end":1777800059025}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777800059039,"sessionID":"ses_212de73dfffe6fU0mVsdmO9O5O","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01WWJJ7J5EwW3fQigqMMSZok","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r13s2\ntitle: \"JAL fast-path: delete tautological id_jal_aligned gate\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the only predictor that has scored positive\n  on this core (+17.73%). All four JALR/RET predictor topologies\n  (r3s2 4-entry RAS, r7s2 dirty-x1, r10s2 RAC, r11s2 IF-side-seq-arm)\n  regressed sharply, as did BTFN (r6s2), BEQ-rs,rs (r12s2), IF-side\n  JAL predecode (r8s2), and a Boolean-equivalent rewrite of the r4s2\n  cone itself (r9s2, -18.86%). The transferable rule from r9s2 is that\n  SUBSTITUTING one expression for another on the r4s2 cone invalidates\n  Yosys's CSE/placement optimum. DELETION of a provably-redundant term\n  is a structurally different operation: it leaves the remaining cone\n  in its original form (same expression tree for the surviving\n  operands), reducing the cone's fan-in rather than reshaping it.\n\n  The `id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)` check is a\n  tautology for this core:\n    - PC register resets to 0 (pc[1:0]=00).\n    - PC updates are pc+=4 (preserves pc[1:0]=00) or redirect_target.\n    - JAL targets: pc+J_imm, and J-imm has bit 0 ≡ 0 by encoding, and\n      pc[1:0]=00 invariantly ⇒ target[1:0]=00.\n    - JALR: clears bit 0 explicitly via `{jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0}` in\n      ex_stage.sv:89, and ex_stage's misalign-fault gate traps any\n      JALR target with bit 1 set (invariant #2; target[1:0]==00 check\n      at ex_stage.sv:101-103), preventing pc[1:0]=10 from persisting.\n    - Branch targets: also go through ex_stage's misalign-fault gate,\n      so branch_target[1:0]!=00 traps and does NOT redirect the PC.\n  Conclusion: pc[1:0]==00 is an invariant maintained by the existing\n  RTL, and hence id_jal_target[1:0]==00 is an invariant too. The gate\n  always evaluates to 1 at runtime.\n\n  Yosys cannot statically prove this invariant without a multi-cycle\n  analysis it does not perform on combinational expressions, so the\n  2-bit equality check remains in synthesized logic, costing ~1 LUT\n  level in series with `id_is_jal & !stall_id` on the redirect OR.\nhypothesis: |\n  Delete the `id_jal_aligned` signal and its use in `id_is_jal_fire`,\n  simplifying:\n    assign id_is_jal_fire = id_is_jal & !stall_id & id_jal_aligned;\n  to:\n    assign id_is_jal_fire = id_is_jal & !stall_id;\n  Also delete the `id_jal_aligned` wire declaration.\n\n  This is NOT a cone rewrite in the r9s2 sense. r9s2 SUBSTITUTED\n  `(id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)` with `!if_id_w.instr[21]` —\n  changing the set of nets entering the fire gate and forcing Yosys\n  to re-solve the placement. This hypothesis DELETES the entire\n  align-check leg of the AND, leaving the surviving terms\n  (`id_is_jal` — itself an opcode-compare on instr[6:0], and\n  `!stall_id` — a hazard_unit output) structurally identical to how\n  they appear in the current r4s2 cone. Yosys's CSE for those two\n  nets is unaffected. The only change is that the 2-bit equality\n  check and its AND input disappear from the fire gate's fanin.\n\n  The `id_jal_target` wire is still computed (it feeds\n  `redirect_target` via the arbiter mux), so the 32-bit pc+J_imm\n  adder stays — no adder placement change, no carry-chain re-route.\n  What disappears is a 2-input AND plus a 2-bit equality comparator\n  fanning into that AND: ~2 LUTs on the ID-side redirect fire cone,\n  and one LUT level of depth.\n\n  Risk assessment honest-to-the-lessons:\n    - r9s2 regressed -18.86% on a cone substitution. This is a\n      deletion, not a substitution. The distinction is structural:\n      deleting an AND-arm leaves the remaining arms' nets unchanged,\n      while substitution changes a net (e.g. swapping an adder-low-\n      bit net for an instr-bit net) that Yosys has already placed.\n      The r9s2 lesson explicitly calls out \"the *specific form* of\n      the expression\" as what matters; form-preservation via deletion\n      is exactly the mitigation r9s2 validates negatively (by showing\n      non-preservation regresses).\n    - r11s0 showed that REMOVING dead RTL from a packed struct hurts\n      via layout churn. This hypothesis does NOT touch any packed\n      struct — `id_jal_aligned` is a top-level wire in core.sv, not\n      an id_ex_t field. Deleting it does not re-pack any register.\n    - Formal: the trap discipline for misaligned JAL is unchanged.\n      The existing EX-stage misalign-fault cone (ex_stage.sv:101-105)\n      still fires rvfi_trap=1 for any is_jump with target[1:0]!=00.\n      The `id_jal_aligned` gate was defensive, not primary — removing\n      it does not weaken invariant #2 because EX still traps any\n      misaligned target that slips through. Since pc[1:0]==00 is\n      maintained, no misaligned JAL target actually reaches EX in\n      practice, and the invariant continues to be trivially upheld.\n    - CoreMark: zero IPC change expected. The gate always evaluated\n      to 1 for all CoreMark-generated JAL sequences, so dropping it\n      does not enable new redirects.\n    - Fmax: small positive or flat. The savings are ~2 LUTs and one\n      cone level on the ID-side redirect OR, which on a 94.8%-full\n      fabric may relieve a routing pressure point adjacent to the\n      r4s2-winning cone. Confidence is low because all recent Fmax\n      micro-opts on this cone have regressed — but deletion-without-\n      substitution is a structurally distinct operation that has not\n      yet been tested, and it's the smallest-surface predictor edit\n      physically possible.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Delete the `id_jal_aligned` signal declaration and its use in the `id_is_jal_fire` assignment. Change `assign id_is_jal_fire = id_is_jal & !stall_id & id_jal_aligned;` to `assign id_is_jal_fire = id_is_jal & !stall_id;`. Remove the `assign id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00);` line. Leave `id_jal_target`, `id_is_jal`, `id_jal_imm`, the arbiter mux, and all other r4s2 fast-path wires byte-identical. Update the comment block above the fast-path to document that alignment is guaranteed by the pc[1:0]==00 invariant (reset + pc+=4 + JALR bit-0-clear + ex_stage misalign-trap on any JALR/branch with target[1]=1) and that EX's existing misalign-fault gate remains the correctness backstop.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777800059021,"end":1777800059036}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the predictor approaches that have already been tested for cores/bench—essentially everything has been exhausted except for r4s2's JAL fast-path optimization which gained 17.73%. The lessons make it clear that slot-2 diversity work with predictors is done and needs to shift toward non-predictor solutions, but since I'm constrained to the predictor category, I need to identify an untested predictor angle that could still work.\n\nLooking at what's been tried and failed, I'm considering whether I can widen the JAL fast-path's reach without extending the critical path—specifically by removing the misalignment check in the ID-stage JAL predictor, since compiler-generated JALs are practically always aligned anyway and that check just adds unnecessary logic to the adder output. I've explored a few other angles—an IF-stage squash-refetch predictor (which r8s2 already tried and regressed), compressing the JAL fast-path by predicting from fewer bits, a convergence predictor that caches repeated targets (essentially a BTB that failed), and even preventing predicted JALs from traveling the pipeline entirely. The core constraint is that every predictor angle I've considered either adds storage, shares the redirect cone, or introduces new flops in the PC path—all of which have historically regressed.\n\nThe most promising remaining angle is removing the JAL fast-path's alignment guard entirely, since JAL's J-imm encoding has bit 0 implicitly zero and PC is always 4-aligned, making the target inherently aligned. But then I realize JALR can set bit 1 of the PC, so a subsequent JAL could produce a misaligned target—and r9s2 already tried folding this check differently and regressed. I'm also considering whether backward branches (negative immediates) could be predicted taken via a simple heuristic, though that's closer to traditional branch prediction territory. I'm pipelining the JAL target computation into IF so it arrives earlier, latching it into a dedicated register and consuming it in ID—but this approach (r8s2) added significant overhead and regressed performance. Given that every predictor angle has failed and the evidence points away from predictors entirely, I should propose something minimal: maybe simplifying the JAL fast-path's consume side by having EX read the opcode directly instead of propagating it through id_ex, though I'm running out of credible options here. I'm circling back to a simpler approach: an IF-stage predictor that uses a registered prediction bit, decoupled from the main redirect path — structurally cleaner than previous attempts, though I'm realizing this echoes earlier exploration around this same shape. I've cycled through several predictor angles—JAL CSE sharing, sticky IF-stage detection, JALR-with-known-link patterns—but each either requires structural changes that regress or duplicates failed approaches like the IF-side RET predictor that lost 26%. I'm settling on proposing a hypothesis that acknowledges these prior failures and offers something with explicit risk analysis rather than another speculative optimization. I'm exploring whether a branch outcome predictor based on register state could work, but I keep running into the same constraint: any useful predictor needs to redirect the PC, which puts it directly in the cone I'm trying to avoid. The simpler ideas—like using the JAL fast-path as a prefetch hint for tail chains, or a late-firing BHT that only squashes without redirecting—either regress performance or don't actually help. I'm hitting diminishing returns on this optimization angle. I've exhausted the viable predictor angles—every modification either regresses or risks destabilizing the Yosys-placed cone. My last resort is proposing a zero-cost metadata bit derived from the decoder's opcode match to give the JAL fast-path a shorthand signal, though I'm aware this is essentially disguising a non-predictor as one. I'm cycling through predictor ideas and hitting dead ends — each one either replicates existing logic unsafely, adds critical-path routing, or regresses performance like the prefetch-ahead approach did. I'm realizing I need to stop chasing optimizations and instead propose something honest that acknowledges the constraints: a predictor grounded entirely in the fetch cone that doesn't touch the toxic fast-path logic. I'm ruling out the more exotic approaches—tail-call fusion is too risky, and modifying the existing JAL fast-path cone risks the same placement regressions that hurt r9s2. I've also dismissed AUIPC+JALR prediction and forwarding-based JALR as too complex or too likely to penalize the ID redirect cone based on past lessons. I'm settling on exploring a JAL-chain fast-path extension where the IF stage detects consecutive JALs and chains them together, staying within the spirit of r4s2 but genuinely untested.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering—that doesn't gain anything since the current JAL fast-path already fires at ID. The real angle I haven't explored is a negative predictor: branches default to not-taken, so when EX resolves them as not-taken, we don't need to flush IF at all. Looking at the current redirect logic, non-taken branches already don't trigger a flush, so this might already be happening.\n\nThe actual bottleneck is taken branches, which cost 2 bubbles. I could propose dropping the `id_jal_aligned` check as a cone simplification, or removing the forward_unit's memory-writeback leg for JAL/JALR since their PC+4 writes rarely feed immediate dependencies in CoreMark. But I'm leaning toward something more concrete: detecting JALR instructions where the source register was just written by a LUI or AUIPC, pattern-matching the constant through forwarding to predict the call target in ID and fire the redirect early.\n\nThe problem is this adds a 32-bit adder on the ID side, requires cross-instruction state tracking, and introduces a new redirect term—all the previous regressions suggest this will hurt. After working through the arbiter logic, I realize JAL is always younger than any EX redirect, so firing both doesn't help. The write to x1 propagates through the pipeline regardless of the fetch redirect anyway, so there's no real optimization there either. I'm settling on the least-invasive predictor approach instead.\n\nI've considered several options: pre-registering the JAL opcode check to save one LUT level (but that's still cone-editing), adding a tag bit to id_ex (toxic), flushing wrong-path work via an early comparator hint from EX (just reordering logic), and finally gating id_is_jal_fire on imem_ready explicitly to let the synthesis tool optimize the redirect fan-in earlier. That last one seems like the safest bet—it's cone-editing but low-risk, and might give Yosys a better optimization opportunity.\n\nI'll go with that hypothesis and write it up, though I'm not confident it'll help.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded239ff90014JsmEeLTzVPP10","sessionID":"ses_212de73dfffe6fU0mVsdmO9O5O","messageID":"msg_ded218cd3001noHnTeSltS5Wsf"}}
