{"type":"text","timestamp":1777800066360,"sessionID":"ses_212de73dfffe6fU0mVsdmO9O5O","part":{"id":"prt_ded242242001ZeYvP0JXYjkZu4","messageID":"msg_ded2418d70016WIboUIbGPBnGZ","sessionID":"ses_212de73dfffe6fU0mVsdmO9O5O","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Given that every predictor angle except r4s2's JAL fast-path has regressed (including r9s2's cone-equivalent rewrite at -18.86%), I proposed the minimum-surface predictor edit physically possible: **deleting** the tautological `id_jal_aligned` gate from r4s2's fire cone.\n\nKey distinction from r9s2: that hypothesis *substituted* `(target[1:0]==00)` with `!instr[21]`, swapping nets entering the AND and forcing Yosys to re-solve placement. This hypothesis *deletes* the whole align-check leg, leaving the two surviving terms (`id_is_jal`, `!stall_id`) structurally identical — preserving Yosys's existing CSE/placement optimum.\n\nCorrectness backstop: EX-stage's existing misalign-fault gate already traps any `is_jump && target[1:0]!=00`, so invariant #2 is unweakened. pc[1:0]≡00 is invariant (reset=0, pc+=4 preserves, JALR clears bit 0, misalign traps), making the ID-side alignment check architecturally dead.\n\nConfidence is low — the r4s2 cone is a known Fmax tarpit — but this is the one cone-level simplification topology (pure deletion of a redundant AND-arm, no struct edits, no new nets, no flops) that has not yet been tested in 30+ iterations.","time":{"start":1777800061506,"end":1777800066357}}}
