{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777801180768,"sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","part":{"id":"prt_ded35365b001ptdw80Vl2AI0WF","messageID":"msg_ded3434130015d70NQxVnZ5fYX","sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","snapshot":"b370943f0f67c47f594507c112736d897df2d651","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777801333493,"sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01KaiATB7m3ssuTGurAxKeod","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -i \"if_id_w.valid|valid conjunct|redundant valid|slim fire\" /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -30","description":"Check if valid-conjunct removal attempted"},"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","metadata":{"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","exit":0,"description":"Check if valid-conjunct removal attempted","truncated":false},"title":"Check if valid-conjunct removal attempted","time":{"start":1777801333489,"end":1777801333492}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the predictor results for cores/bench/, I see that most attempts have failed to improve performance—only the JAL fast-path optimization gained ground with a 17.73% improvement. The other approaches I've tried, including static branch prediction, BTB expansion, and RAS implementation, either regressed or showed no measurable benefit, so I need to find a different angle that might actually move the needle.\n\nGiven the constraint to focus on predictors this round, I'm considering whether I can extend the successful JAL fast-path to handle JALR instructions when the source register is x1 (return address) with zero offset, though that would require RAS storage. I'm also wondering if there's a completely different structural approach—something beyond ID-side fast-paths or IF-side table lookups—that could work better. The current JAL optimization computes the target at ID stage using the PC and immediate, so I'm thinking about whether resolving the target earlier or through a different mechanism might unlock further gains. the ID redirect side is this 32-bit adder.\n\nWhat if we precompute the JAL target earlier — but the r8s2 attempt already tried that at IF-stage predecode and it regressed. Let me think about predictors that shorten the critical path at IF instead of speculating.\n\nActually, what about a pipelined JAL fast-path? We already predict JAL at ID, so could we issue two JALs back-to-back more efficiently?\n\nOr here's another thought: what if we keep the `jal_predicted` bit to mask the EX-stage redirect cone? Right now EX's redirect gate includes `!in.jal_predicted`, which adds a LUT level; without it, JAL's EX redirect would fire redundantly but harmlessly since the PC is already correct. Except it would fire again on the next JAL instruction and flush the already-correctly-fetched next instruction.\n\nIf we remove `jal_predicted` entirely and let EX fire a redundant redirect, here's what happens: JAL at IF-ID fires and PC redirects to the target on the next cycle. When JAL reaches EX, we'd redirect again to the same target, but IF is now at target+4, so the redirect would reset it back to target — re-fetching the instruction we already have. So the `jal_predicted` bit is actually necessary.\n\nLet me look at this from another angle. What if we use a predictor that doesn't feed the PC mux at all but instead feeds the next cycle's speculation through a registered hint? The key insight from r4s2 is \"zero-storage, share existing redirect net, resolve one stage earlier, mask EX redirect via a single bit.\" The only remaining unconditional instruction like JAL would be JALR with rs1=x0, which is rare in compiled code.\n\nWhat about auipc-then-jalr sequences for far calls? Those use rs1=ra from a previous auipc for PLT entries, but they're not common in CoreMark.\n\nLet me approach this differently: what if we implement a zero-storage JALR fast-path when rs1 is available in the regfile without forwarding? ering covered by load-use normally, but only for LOAD; ALU-producer-consumer uses forwarding but ONLY in EX)\n- else if (ex_mem.rd == rs1 && ex_mem.reg_write): would need to forward ex_mem.alu_result, which means target depends on that signal\n\nSo conservative fire condition: no rs1 hazard in id_ex OR ex_mem.\n\nThis is actually quite complex. The cone would be:\n- Opcode compare: `(instr[6:0] == 7'b1100111) & (instr[14:12] == 3'b0) & if_id_w.valid`\n- rs1 clear of hazard: `(~id_ex.reg_write | id_ex.rd != rs1) & (~ex_mem.reg_write | ex_mem.rd != rs1) & (rs1 != 0)`\n  - Or actually rs1=0 is also allowed since rs1_data would be 0, fine.\n- JALR target: `(rs1_data + imm_i) & ~1`\n- Fire: opcode_match & rs1_clear\n\nThen arbitrate with existing id_is_jal_fire (mutex by opcode so no arbitration needed).\n\nBut: 32-bit add + align-mask is comparable to the JAL cone. Plus hazard-detect adds maybe 2 LUTs.\n\nHowever lessons r3s2/r7s2/r10s2/r11s2 ALL say predictors that add a new fire term OR widen the ID cone regress. The r12s2 lesson explicitly says \"slot-\n\nI need to detect whether rs1 has a hazard from the in-flight instructions—if id_ex or ex_mem are writing to rs1, I can't use the regfile value directly. The fast-path would check the opcode, verify no hazard on rs1, then compute the target as rs1_data plus the immediate, masked to align. But this adds logic to the ID stage, and past results show that widening the ID cone or adding new fire conditions tends to cause regressions, so I'm weighing whether the complexity is worth it. I'm exploring whether I can move the JAL opcode detection earlier to IF-stage using a cheap predecode bit, which would eliminate a LUT level from the critical path without duplicating hardware like r8s2 attempted.\n\nBut actually, the PC+imm add still dominates at ID, so this doesn't meaningfully reduce cone depth. Let me reconsider the EX mask path instead—if I can eliminate the `!in.jal_predicted` mask without breaking correctness, I might simplify the redirect logic. The key insight is that the EX JAL's redundant redirect would just re-assert the same target, causing a 1-cycle bubble rather than wrong-path fetches, since the flush clears the stale IF output before the next fetch.\n\nSo `jal_predicted` is actually necessary to avoid that regression. I'm running low on safe predictor ideas, but here's something untested: a \"squash predictor\" for JALR returns that detects the pattern in IF-stage and masks the next two fetches without touching the PC mux—though that still leaves the bubble in place, just repositioned.\n\nLet me try narrowing the JAL fire gate by dropping the `& if_id_w.valid` check, since the flush-NOP has opcode 0010011 (ADDI), not 1101111 (JAL), so the opcode comparison already filters it out and the valid bit is redundant.\n\nRemoving that AND gate saves a LUT level, but I need to be careful—formal BMC from arbitrary initial states can break on \"provably redundant\" gates. During reset with symbolic imem_data, the valid bit could matter. Actually, looking at the logic: `out.instr = flush ? NOP : imem_data` and `out.valid = !flush`, so the condition `instr[6:0] == 1101111` is structurally equivalent to `valid && imem_data_is_jal`. The `& valid` is genuinely redundant, but as r13s2 showed, formal tools can still fail on this kind of optimization from arbitrary initial states.\n\nWait—this is purely combinational, not a flopped state invariant. The equivalence holds on the same cycle under all conditions, so BMC should see the same function. But r9s2 taught me that even bitwise-equivalent simplifications can regress because Yosys already found a placement optimum. This might not actually win.\n\nLet me think about a different angle: a dual-JAL chained fast-path that predicts both the current JAL and a fetched JAL back-to-back, saving 2 bubbles instead of 1. But that needs a second adder on the IF→PC cone, which is too risky given r8s2's regression. Given the strong signal that predictor slot 2 is done, I should propose something genuinely novel but lowest-risk—maybe a conditional-move-like predictor that doesn't touch fetch at all.\n\nActually, looking back at r4s2, the key insight is that the ID cone is shallower than EX's redirect cone. What if I replace EX's branch logic with something shallower instead? That's more of a micro-optimization than a predictor, but it affects prediction indirectly. Let me settle on extending the JAL fast-path to handle short immediates with a parallel 12-bit adder path, but that adds a mux in series, which regresses like r13s0. Or I could cache the last JAL target and skip the adder on repeat fires, but that requires a 32-bit compare on the ID cone, which probably regresses too. I need something small and incremental with a clear win.\n\nThe best angle is probably a micro-opt to restructure `id_jal_imm` to share the bit-permute with imm_gen, but Yosys likely already does this CSE. So let me propose something with low confidence: extend the JAL fast-path to handle JALR with rs1==x0 (indirect jumps from trampolines), where the target is just a sign-extended 12-bit immediate—no big adder needed. It's rare in compiler output but might appear in CoreMark, and it's zero-storage, same shape as r4s2, genuinely unconditional for this case.\n\nThe fire condition would OR into `id_is_jal_fire`, and the target is just a permute with no adder. But widening `redirect_target` to 3:1 kills Fmax based on prior runs, so I'd need to collapse `jalr_x0_target` and `jal_target` into a single upstream mux—still 2:1 at the arbiter. However, JALR with rs1=x0 has essentially zero density in CoreMark, so there's no real IPC win.\n\nActually, the safest move is just to eliminate the `& if_id_w.valid` conjunct from `id_is_jal`—it's structurally redundant since flush forces the opcode to a non-JAL value anyway.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the reset behavior: `flush = redirect || imem_stall`, and on reset `ex_redirect=0` (the EX stage drives redirect combinationally from a zeroed pipeline register). If `imem_ready=1` during reset, then `flush=0` and `out.valid=1`. If the instruction happens to be a JAL, `id_is_jal` would fire regardless of the valid bit. The fire condition also depends on `stall_id` and alignment, both of which are zero on reset, so the behavior is the same with or without the valid conjunct.\n\nDuring reset, `pc` is forced to `RESET_PC` by the synchronous logic, so any redirect computed that cycle doesn't take effect until the next cycle. This is getting too deep into edge cases. I'm going to step back and propose something safer: instead of tweaking the existing predictor logic, extend the JAL fast-path to handle misaligned targets by trapping at the ID stage, which would let me remove the `id_jal_aligned` gate entirely and simplify the whole path.\n\nBut r13s2 showed this breaks formal verification because the BMC explores arbitrary initial PC states. If I try to handle misalignment by redirecting to an aligned target and trapping at EX instead, that adds too much complexity. Registering the JAL target early to break the ID→IF cone would introduce a bubble, defeating the purpose.\n\nSo here's my final modest proposal: add a static zero-offset JALR-to-x0 fast-path for cases where `rs1=x0` and the immediate is small. This requires zero storage, has no mispredict arm since the target is architecturally determined by the immediate alone, and uses a bit-permute instead of an adder, giving shallower depth than even r4s2's JAL cone.\n\nI'd fold this into the existing 2:1 target arbiter with an upstream mux that's mutually exclusive by opcode, but I'm setting confidence low given how many similar proposals have failed. Actually, wait—I just realized I haven't tried predicting branch direction at ID using instruction encoding alone (BTFN-style) while discarding the target prediction to keep the cone narrow. No, r6s2 already tried that with backward-BEQ.\n\nLet me try one more angle: a micro-RAS that stores only the return-PC bits [11:2] (10 bits) instead of a full 32-bit link register, exploiting the fact that CoreMark's code fits in 6KB so all return addresses share high bits with the current PC. I'd reconstruct the target by concatenating the high bits from the current PC with the stored 10 bits and two zero bits, then detect RET (JALR x0, 0(x1)) at ID and use this reconstructed target. This needs just 11 FFs total, invalidates on any x1 write, and the ID redirect target mux becomes a simple conditional assembly...\n\nStill writing micro-RAS logic...\n\nActually, this has all the same problems r7s2 through r12s2 identified—a second fire term on the ID cone and a new upstream mux. JALR/RET speculation has regressed across every topology I've tried, so I'm giving up on finding a novel predictor angle that isn't obviously doomed.\n\nLet me propose something simpler and be honest about the low confidence: slim the r4s2 JAL fast-path fire gate by removing the `& if_id_w.valid` conjunct, which is structurally redundant because the IF-stage's flush NOP already fails the JAL opcode compare. This removes one LUT-level AND from the ID redirect cone. I'm verifying this is safe for formal by checking that the equivalence holds under both flush and non-flush conditions—under flush the instruction becomes a NOP with a different opcode, so both sides evaluate to zero, and under normal operation valid is always 1.\n\nThis is a pure combinational tautology, not state-dependent, so it should be safe for formal unlike r13s2. The impact is minimal—Yosys's logic minimizer might already see the redundancy, making this a no-op at synthesis, but if not we save one LUT level and slightly reduce area. Low confidence, low impact, but also low risk, so I'll propose it.\n\nI'm also reconsidering what predictor angles are genuinely novel. I've seen JAL fast-paths and various IF/ID-side predictors fail, but I haven't explored WB/commit-side predictors, prediction fusion across retires, or branch pre-resolution running in parallel with decode. The branch early-resolve idea is tempting—precomputing the condition at ID before forwarding applies—but it adds a new conditional fire term with a misprediction case on forward hazards, which mirrors the r6s2 BTFN regression. So I'm sticking with the `& if_id_w.valid` removal as my final proposal: genuinely novel, formally safe, and low risk.\n\nNow I'm re-examining the r4s2 code to verify the redundancy. The `valid` signal is `!flush`, and when flush is asserted (during redirect or imem stall), the instruction is forced to 0x13 (ADDI), which can't match the JAL opcode. So the `& valid` conjunct is indeed redundant—the opcode check alone handles both cases. During redirect, flush_if=1 kills the instruction anyway. During imem_stall, the same thing happens. Without `& valid`, id_is_jal would still evaluate correctly because the forced opcode prevents a false match.\n\nFor the second optimization, I'm considering whether we can compute the JAL alignment check more efficiently. The target alignment `id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00` is theoretically always true in correct execution (PC is 4-aligned, imm[0]=0), but formal verification with arbitrary initial states requires the check. I'm exploring whether we can replace it with a shallower expression like checking `pc[1:0]` and `imm[1]` directly. Since imm[0]=0, there's no carry into bit 1, so `id_jal_target[1] = pc[1] ⊕ imm[1]`. This might give us a path to preserve formal correctness while reducing gate depth.\n\nHowever, I'm skeptical this will actually help—Yosys likely already recognizes this optimization, and past experience shows that bitwise-equivalent simplifications often regress due to placement churn. So I'm settling on just removing the redundant `& valid` from the fire gate as the final proposal—a clean, one-line change with clear formal justification.\n\nI'm cycling through other angles: canonical NOP prediction, dual-JAL handling, MUL shortcuts, JALR target prediction via RAS—but none of them feel like genuine wins. Even the load-use hazard detection simplification isn't really a predictor. The slim JAL fast-path with the `& valid` removal is the most defensible move, though I'm only moderately confident it'll move the needle.\n\nNow I'm worried the change might be a no-op after Yosys optimization or could even regress due to placement churn. Let me try something with more substance: broadening the JAL fast-path by checking `instr[21]` directly to reduce the alignment cone, but keeping the `id_jal_aligned` gate structure intact so formal verification still covers the full mis-alignment logic. The key insight is that target bit 0 always equals pc[0] (since the immediate's bit 0 is zero), and target bit 1 is just pc[1] XOR imm[1] with no carry-in from bit 0, so I can express alignment more cheaply...\n\nDeriving the alignment condition...\n\nActually, this is just a combinational tautology—formally safe but likely to regress placement the same way the r9s2 rewrite did. So I'm going with the simpler approach of just removing the `& valid` conjunct instead.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_ded3783ba001gIf8arR3RX2jln","sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","messageID":"msg_ded3434130015d70NQxVnZ5fYX"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777801333537,"sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","part":{"id":"prt_ded37772f001cn7pB1zHMYN4su","messageID":"msg_ded3434130015d70NQxVnZ5fYX","sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","type":"text","text":"Looking at this carefully: the lessons explicitly state \"slot-2 diversity work is conclusively done with predictors\" after 12+ failed predictor attempts. Only r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path won (+17.73%). Every extension/alternative has regressed:\n- ID-side 2nd fire term (r6s2, r7s2, r10s2, r11s2, r12s2)\n- 3:1 redirect_target mux (r6s2, r7s2)\n- IF-side predecode flop (r8s2)\n- Deleting align gate (r13s2 — formal failure)\n- Equivalent rewrites on winning cone (r9s2 — placement churn)\n\nGiven the mandate to stay in \"predictor\" category, the *only* remaining safe angle is a truly minimal structural simplification INSIDE the r4s2 winning cone that avoids ALL the failure modes above: no new fire term, no widened arbiter, no storage, no new adder, no opcode-match logic change, no alignment-gate deletion.\n\nLet me grep log.jsonl to confirm nothing like this was tried:","time":{"start":1777801328431,"end":1777801333535}}}
