{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777801339574,"sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_013hffViaZc2jPcUaqs1j68j","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"if_id_w.valid|valid conjunct|redundant valid","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 6 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Zero-storage JAL fast-path: resolve JAL redirect in ID via shared redirect wire\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"JAL is unconditional and fully determined at decode time \\u2014 target = PC +\\nimm_j, no rs dependency, no branch condition. Today the pipeline pays\\nthe full 2-cycle EX redirect penalty on every JAL (same cost as a\\nmispredicted branch): IF/ID is flushed, ID/EX is bubbled, PC reloads\\nfrom EX's redirect_target three cycles after the JAL's fetch.\\nCoreMark's call/return structure (list_ins/core_list_find/core_bench_*)\\nhas ~3\\u20135% dynamic JAL density; saving one cycle per JAL by resolving\\nthe redirect in the ID stage \\u2014 one cycle earlier than EX \\u2014 recovers\\n~3\\u20135% of total execution cycles at effectively zero storage cost.\\nPrior predictor attempts (r1s2 JAL/backward-BEQ at IF, r2s2 16-entry\\nBTB, r3s2 4-entry RAS) all failed \\u2014 either on the PC-register D-input\\ncritical path (r1s2), on LUT budget on the near-full GW2AR fabric\\n(r2s2, 928 FFs), or on PC-select fanin growth combined with\\nsnapshot/rollback state (r3s2). This hypothesis deliberately avoids\\nall three failure modes by adding ZERO storage (JAL is unconditional,\\nno rollback needed, no prediction table, no tag compare) and by\\nrouting the ID-stage redirect through the EXISTING redirect wire via\\na small priority mux \\u2014 NOT by adding a new input to if_stage's PC\\nselect. The decoder already produces is_jump (combinational); imm_gen\\nalready produces imm_j (combinational). The new logic is just a\\n1-bit AND + a 32-bit adder + a 2:1 mux at the top-level redirect fan-in.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JAL is unconditional and fully determined at decode time \\u2014 target = PC +\\nimm_j, no rs dependency, no branch condition. Today the pipeline pays\\nthe full 2-cycle EX redirect penalty on every JAL (same cost as a\\nmispredicted branch): IF/ID is flushed, ID/EX is bubbled, PC reloads\\nfrom EX's redirect_target three cycl...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Zero-storage backward-branch prediction at ID, r4s2-pattern (additive, no rename)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80-95% accurate on\\nthese CoreMark kernels, covers another ~4-6% of dynamic instructions, and\\nsaves 2 pipeline bubbles per hit.\\n\\nr5s2 attempted this concept but failed implementation: it renamed\\n`jal_predicted` to `predicted_taken`, and a missed downstream consumer\\ncascaded into SBY's \\\"Status: passed / engine_0 did not produce any traces\\\"\\nsignature + cover VCD crash (no_checks_generated). The architectural idea\\nis sound; the diff discipline was not. This hypothesis retries the concept\\nwith strict additive plumbing (no renames) to eliminate the cascade-risk\\nclass of failures entirely.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\\npattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\\nEX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\\nstorage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\\ninstructions.\\n\\nThe next natural target is backward conditional branches \\u2014 CoreMark's hot\\npaths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\\ndominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\\nbackward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Implicit 1-entry RAS via dirty-x1 tracking: cone-free JALR-ret fast-path\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-only ID fast-path won (+17.73%) by folding the redirect onto the existing\\n`redirect`/`redirect_target` wire \\u2014 zero storage, no new PC-mux input, no new EX\\ntarget-mux arm. Subsequent predictor extensions (r5s2/r6s2 backward-branch BTFN,\\nr3s2 4-entry RAS) regressed because each added either a mispredict arm to EX\\n(widening the 2:1 target mux to 3:1) or a new id_redirect input to the PC-select\\npriority mux. CoreMark has ~8\\u201312% return-instruction density via `jalr x0, x1, 0`\\nthat the JAL-only path does not accelerate \\u2014 each return still eats 2 bubbles.\\n\\nThe key insight: if we can prove at prediction time that the predicted target\\nEQUALS the actual JALR target, EX-redirect suppression becomes unconditional (like\\njal_predicted), eliminating the need for a 32-bit target compare in EX's redirect\\ncone. That proof is available for free via a \\\"dirty x1\\\" tracker that invalidates\\nthe cached link whenever any non-fast-path writer targets x1.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL-only ID fast-path won (+17.73%) by folding the redirect onto the existing\\n`redirect`/`redirect_target` wire \\u2014 zero storage, no new PC-mux input, no new EX\\ntarget-mux arm. Subsequent predictor extensions (r5s2/r6s2 backward-branch BTFN,\\nr3s2 4-entry RAS) regressed because each added either a mispredict arm to EX\\n(widening the 2:1 target mux to 3:1) or a new id_redirect input to the PC-select\\npriority mux. CoreMark has ~8\\u201312% return-instruction density via `jalr x0, x1, 0`\\nthat the JAL-only path does not accelerate \\u2014 each return still eats 2 bubbles.\\n\\nThe key insight: if we can prove at prediction time that the predicted target\\nEQUALS the actual JALR target, EX-redirect suppression becomes unconditional (like\\njal_predicted), eliminating the need for a 32-bit target compare in EX...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Pre-register JAL target at IF to lift the 32-bit adder off the ID redirect cone\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the one predictor that won on this fabric\\n(+17.73%). Every subsequent predictor variant regressed because it\\nviolated at least one of the winning constraints: no new PC-mux\\ninput (r1s2), no storage+tag array pulling LUT area (r2s2), no new\\nID-side fire-term with a misprediction arm widening the EX redirect\\nmux past 2:1 (r6s2, r7s2), no id_ex_t struct rename (r7s0).\\n\\nWhat r4s2 did NOT eliminate, though, is a 32-bit adder sitting on\\nthe ID\\u2192PC-D-in combinational cone. In core.sv today:\\n\\n    id_jal_target  = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm;         // <-- 32b adder\\n    redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_target : id_jal_target;\\n    // if_stage: PC_D = redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4;\\n\\nOn each cycle where a JAL is in ID, the PC register's D-input cone\\npasses through PC_reg \\u2192 if_id_w.pc \\u2192 32-bit carry-chain add \\u2192 2:1\\nmux (ex_redirect select) \\u2192 2:1 mux (redirect select) \\u2192 PC_D. The\\ncarry chain dominates this arm. On near-full GW2AR (9484/10000\\nLUT4), congestion-amplified routing around the carry chain is\\nexactly the sort of thing that nudges Fmax down \\u2014 and r4s2's win\\nconfirms Fmax-side gains are available on the fetch-redirect net.\\n\\nCrucially, the adder's operands both resolve to flop outputs at the\\nclock edge starting cycle N: PC_reg is already flopped; J_imm is a\\nbit-permutation of imem_data which at cycle N is the Gowin BRAM\\noutput (clock-to-Q of the BRAM, not a combinational chain). So the\\nadder can be RELOCATED to compute `jal_target_next = pc + J_imm`\\nduring cycle N-1 (when the JAL is still in IF) and registered into\\na new `jal_target_q` flop on the N-1\\u2192N edge. At cycle N the JAL is\\nin ID and `jal_target_q` is a ready flop output \\u2014 feeding the\\nredirect_target mux with ZERO adder levels in the ID\\u2192PC cone.\\n\\n...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"IF-side RET predictor via sequential-PC arm (squash-refetch off the ID redirect cone)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Every ID-side RET/JALR predictor has regressed on this fabric\\n(r3s2 4-entry RAS ~0%, r7s2 dirty-x1 RAS -50%, r10s2 1-entry RAC\\n-20%). The r10s2 lesson names the one remaining unexplored path\\nexplicitly: \\\"JALR/RET speculation on this fabric must either\\nresolve off the ID redirect cone entirely (IF-side hint +\\nsquash-refetch) or be abandoned\\\". r4s2's JAL fast-path won\\n(+17.73%) by folding onto the EXISTING redirect wire via an\\nupstream 2:1; every variant that widened the ID-side redirect\\ncone (new fire term, new upstream target mux, new target\\nregister) paid the full predictor tax regardless of downstream\\ntopology preservation. What no hypothesis has tried: fold the\\nRET prediction into the SEQUENTIAL-fetch arm of if_stage's PC\\nD-input, leaving the `redirect`/`redirect_target` cone\\nstructurally identical to the current winning r4s2 form.\\n\\nCoreMark's call/return density is ~4-6% dynamic (crc16, list_ins,\\nmatrix inner helpers, state_machine small leaves); every RET\\ncosts 2 bubbles today. Saving one bubble per correctly-predicted\\nRET recovers ~2-3% of execution cycles \\u2014 same order of magnitude\\nas r4s2's JAL-only win, but through a structurally disjoint\\nfetch path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Every ID-side RET/JALR predictor has regressed on this fabric\\n(r3s2 4-entry RAS ~0%, r7s2 dirty-x1 RAS -50%, r10s2 1-entry RAC\\n-20%). The r10s2 lesson names the one remaining unexplored path\\nexplicitly: \\\"JALR/RET speculation on this fabric must either\\nresolve off the ID redirect cone entirely (IF-side hint +\\nsquash-refetch) or be abandoned\\\". r4s2's JAL fast-path won\\n(+17.73%) by folding onto the EXISTING redirect wire via an\\nupstream 2:1; every variant that widened the ID-side redirect\\ncone (new fire term, new upstream target mux, new target\\nregister) paid the full predicto...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"BEQ rs,rs static-taken fusion \\u2014 broaden r4s2 JAL fast-path to architecturally-unconditional BRANCH\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor design space on this core is unusually constrained: r4s2's\\nzero-storage ID-stage JAL fast-path is the only predictor ever to win\\n(+17.73%), while every attempt to add a second ID-side fire term\\n(BTFN r6s2 -23%, dirty-x1 RAS r7s2 -50%, RAC r10s2 -20%, IF-side RET\\nr11s2 -26%), widen the redirect_target arbitration mux past 2:1\\n(r7s2/r10s2), or even restructure r4s2's own winning cone (r8s2/r9s2\\n-13% to -19%) has regressed on the near-full GW2AR fabric. The\\ntransferable rule from r4s2 is that a predictor only wins when it is\\n(a) architecturally unconditional (no misprediction arm) and (b)\\nreuses the existing redirect wire topology (2:1 target arbitration\\npreserved). The unexplored angle that fits both constraints is\\nBEQ rs,rs (instr[19:15] == instr[24:20] with funct3=000): this\\nencoding is architecturally unconditional-taken (x == x is always\\ntrue) exactly like JAL, has zero misprediction cost, and its target\\nis pc + B_imm computed at ID from fields already available. GCC\\noccasionally emits BEQ x0,x0 as an unconditional branch idiom for\\nloop-header jumps and long-jump trampolines; even a modest fraction\\nof such instructions converted from 2-bubble EX redirects to\\n0-bubble ID redirects contributes to CoreMark IPC without any Fmax\\ncost on the prediction side.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor design space on this core is unusually constrained: r4s2's\\nzero-storage ID-stage JAL fast-path is the only predictor ever to win\\n(+17.73%), while every attempt to add a second ID-side fire term\\n(BTFN r6s2 -23%, dirty-x1 RAS r7s2 -50%, RAC r10s2 -20%, IF-side RET\\nr11s2 -26%), widen the redirect_target arbitration mux past 2:1\\n(r7s2/r10s2), or even restructure r4s2's own winning cone (r8s2/r9s2\\n-13% to -19%) has regressed on the near-full GW2AR fa...","metadata":{"matches":6,"truncated":false},"title":"if_id_w.valid|valid conjunct|redundant valid","time":{"start":1777801339549,"end":1777801339573}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_ded37a067001lIkSaFSEo5wBAx","sessionID":"ses_212cbccc7ffeh3dFaPYyREhAzM","messageID":"msg_ded378b5f0018HAI4xpBZwBJiM"}}
