{"type":"text","timestamp":1777802776014,"sessionID":"ses_212b69ba1ffeqXcA0oGF7Pu8rl","part":{"id":"prt_ded4d7b99001JUWvCjq61oH7Yu","messageID":"msg_ded4d7427001dxMuIt8xfKZMsD","sessionID":"ses_212b69ba1ffeqXcA0oGF7Pu8rl","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis `hyp-20260503-003-r15s2.yaml` (cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/).\n\nKey points of the proposal:\n\n**Category**: predictor (diversity slot)\n\n**Angle**: A strictly-additive one-conjunct narrowing of ex_stage's `misalign_jump` to exclude JAL cases where r4s2's ID-stage fast-path already certified alignment. Exploits that `in.jal_predicted` is already routed into ex_stage (consumed by the redirect gate) so no new wires, no flop adds, no struct edits, no id_ex_t changes.\n\n**Formal safety rationale**:\n- r13s2's lesson: `id_jal_aligned` gate is load-bearing — we leave it in place at ID\n- r14s2's lesson: don't remove gates from the ID fast-path — we don't\n- r11s0's lesson: no packed-struct layout change — ex_mem_t unchanged\n- r8s0's lesson: no redirect-cone reshape — redirect assignment untouched\n- JALR (jal_predicted always 0) still runs the full misalign check\n- Fall-through JAL (misaligned, jal_predicted=0) still traps via EX\n\n**Risk/reward**: Low confidence (+2%). The predictor search is extremely exhausted and most wins here would require a structurally different approach that this slot cannot legally make. This is the minimal formal-safe predictor extension I can identify that hasn't been explicitly tried.","time":{"start":1777802771353,"end":1777802776012}}}
