{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777782495874,"sessionID":"ses_213e85f83ffeM04gWO9MsDQGrV","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01KTGgCm1oPRVgsg6AbGaMbQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/rtl/ cores/bench/test/ 2>&1","description":"List RTL and test directories"},"output":"cores/bench/rtl/:\nalu.sv\ncore_pkg.sv\ncore.sv\ndecoder.sv\nex_stage.sv\nforward_unit.sv\nhazard_unit.sv\nid_stage.sv\nif_stage.sv\nimm_gen.sv\nmem_stage.sv\nreg_file.sv\nwb_stage.sv\n\ncores/bench/test/:\n_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","metadata":{"output":"cores/bench/rtl/:\nalu.sv\ncore_pkg.sv\ncore.sv\ndecoder.sv\nex_stage.sv\nforward_unit.sv\nhazard_unit.sv\nid_stage.sv\nif_stage.sv\nimm_gen.sv\nmem_stage.sv\nreg_file.sv\nwb_stage.sv\n\ncores/bench/test/:\n_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","exit":0,"description":"List RTL and test directories","truncated":false},"title":"List RTL and test directories","time":{"start":1777782495867,"end":1777782495870}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm starting fresh with branch prediction for this 5-stage pipeline. Since there's only a bench with no prior experiments, I need to think about what predictors would work best. The current setup has branches resolving in the execute stage, which creates a 2-cycle penalty when mispredicted since the fetch and decode stages get flushed. The simplest approach would be a static predictor that assumes backward branches are taken.\n\nI'm weighing a few options: a basic backward-taken/forward-not-taken heuristic, a small BTB with 2-bit counters, or a return address stack. Given the tight LUT budget on the Tang Nano 20K (already at 9880/10000), I need something minimal but effective. The best angle seems to be combining JAL elimination—since JAL targets are known immediately from the immediate field—with static prediction for backward branches. This would catch most loop cases without much hardware overhead, letting the execute stage still correct any mispredictions. So with predecoding, we'd save 2 cycles per JAL since we eliminate both the flush_if and flush_id bubbles—the IF stage computes the target combinationally and fetches it next cycle, so by the time EX confirms the redirect, we're already at the right place. For conditional branches, I could use a simple static predictor that assumes backward branches are taken, letting the EX stage handle mispredicts normally. This is a straightforward early-resolution scheme with minimal hardware cost.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec181a45001gFxJToX2ncNnBa","sessionID":"ses_213e85f83ffeM04gWO9MsDQGrV","messageID":"msg_dec17c9e70011ZA57vBN0Qu7xv"}}
