{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777782528681,"sessionID":"ses_213e85f83ffeM04gWO9MsDQGrV","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015T18LTYbTaP8uVvQio8sZz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r1s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r1s2\ntitle: \"IF-stage JAL direct-jump + backward-taken static branch predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current 5-stage core has zero branch prediction: every taken\n  branch and every JAL resolves in EX and fires a redirect that\n  flushes IF/ID, costing 2 pipeline bubbles per control-transfer.\n  CoreMark spends a large fraction of its cycles in tight inner loops\n  (crclist, matrix_mul_matrix, state_machine transitions) and in\n  function-call glue (JAL/JALR pairs), so those 2-cycle bubbles add\n  up fast. A no-BTB predictor that uses only the freshly-fetched\n  instruction word itself can eliminate the bubbles for two very\n  common and cheaply identifiable cases — unconditional JAL (target\n  is a known function of PC+j_imm, so prediction is always correct)\n  and backward-taken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU (the classic\n  loop-back heuristic, ~85%+ accurate in practice for integer code)\n  — without adding any stateful predictor storage (no BHT, no BTB,\n  no RAS). That keeps the LUT/FF budget near baseline (currently\n  9880/10000 LUTs) while targeting the dominant CPI contributor.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add combinational predecode in if_stage.sv that inspects\n  io_imemData as it arrives and, for JAL and for BRANCH instructions\n  whose B-immediate is negative (sign bit = 1), overrides next_pc\n  with the predicted target (pc + j_imm for JAL, pc + b_imm for\n  backward branches) instead of pc+4. Carry a predicted_taken flag\n  plus predicted_target through IF/ID and ID/EX so the EX stage\n  can compare its resolved outcome against the prediction:\n    - correct prediction   -> no redirect, no bubble\n    - misprediction        -> redirect as today (flush_if/flush_id),\n                              target = resolved branch/jump target\n                              or pc+4 for fall-through\n  Forward branches default to not-taken (prediction == pc+4, same\n  as today), so those pay the existing 2-cycle bubble only when\n  actually taken. JALR is left unpredicted (requires a RAS or BTB\n  to do right; punt to a later hypothesis). This adds only a small\n  opcode compare (instr[6:0] vs 7'b1101111 / 7'b1100011), a\n  sign-bit check on the computed B-immediate, and a 3-input\n  next_pc mux in IF. The EX-stage redirect logic only changes to\n  XOR the predicted-vs-actual outcome before asserting redirect.\n  Net expected effect: CoreMark IPC rises from eliminating ~2\n  bubbles per hot-loop backward-branch iteration and per function\n  call's JAL, while Fmax stays within noise (the added IF logic is\n  a fixed-width decode + 20-bit add that parallelizes with the\n  existing pc+4 adder and should not extend the critical path past\n  the existing imem_addr -> pc register path). Worst-case Fmax\n  impact bounded by the j_imm adder, which is a single 32-bit\n  adder running in parallel with the existing pc+4 adder; the\n  predicted_target mux adds one 2:1 LUT layer. Expected net\n  improvement: ~6-10% fitness (mostly IPC, modest Fmax headwind).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add predecode of io_imemData: detect JAL (opcode 0x6F) and BRANCH (opcode 0x63) with negative B-immediate. Compute j_imm and b_imm locally. Override next_pc with pc+j_imm / pc+b_imm when predicted-taken, else pc+4. Output predicted_taken and predicted_target into the IF/ID bundle.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend if_id_t, id_ex_t, and ex_mem_t with predicted_taken (1 bit) and predicted_target (32 bits) fields so EX can compare its resolved branch/jump against the IF-stage prediction.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Pass predicted_taken and predicted_target through the ID/EX register unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute actual_taken and actual_target as today. Assert redirect only on misprediction: (actual_taken XOR predicted_taken) OR (actual_taken AND predicted_taken AND actual_target != predicted_target). On correct prediction for a backward taken branch or JAL, suppress redirect and keep pc_next = actual_target (which equals predicted_target) so RVFI pc_wdata stays correct. Misalign-fault path is unchanged (still traps, still suppresses redirect).\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"No semantic change — redirect drives flush_if/flush_id as today. Keep load-use stall and bus-stall logic untouched.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add directed tests: (1) tight backward BEQ loop completes in N cycles with zero redirect bubbles after the first iteration, (2) JAL retires without any IF/ID flush cycles, (3) mispredicted forward-taken branch still redirects correctly, (4) mispredicted backward-not-taken branch (rare) still redirects correctly, (5) RVFI pc_rdata/pc_wdata chain remains monotonic +1 in rvfi_order across a mix of predicted-correct and mispredicted branches.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r1s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r1s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777782528669,"end":1777782528680}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm formulating a hypothesis around IF-stage predecode for JAL instructions and backward-taken branches, which would eliminate the typical 2-cycle redirect bubbles for correctly predicted cases while still incurring the penalty for mispredictions that require EX-stage redirects. The approach involves combinationally decoding the instruction memory data in the IF stage to enable this early prediction.\n\nThe core mechanism extracts the opcode and immediate fields to predict JAL targets directly and apply static prediction for backward branches, marking each IF/ID bundle with the predicted target and a taken flag. The EX stage then validates these predictions and only triggers a redirect on misprediction. I'm weighing whether to implement both JAL and backward-taken prediction together or start with just JAL prediction since function calls are frequent in CoreMark and JAL has no misprediction risk. The tradeoff is that adding this predecode logic to the fetch path could impact timing closure, so I'm estimating around 8% improvement with medium confidence, though I need to verify the critical path won't degrade.\n\nThe main concern is that adding a predicted target mux alongside the existing redirect mux creates a 3-way selection that could marginally hurt Fmax, and extracting both B and J immediates requires combinational bit shuffling from the instruction encoding.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec1846a8001AVdgOZQA7jqUDX","sessionID":"ses_213e85f83ffeM04gWO9MsDQGrV","messageID":"msg_dec181ac8001qQAYXsjoEOUTmS"}}
