{"type":"text","timestamp":1777782535334,"sessionID":"ses_213e85f83ffeM04gWO9MsDQGrV","part":{"id":"prt_dec18a012001C9AMA6edjAP7A3","messageID":"msg_dec189ada001HjH2mrkmGAa24v","sessionID":"ses_213e85f83ffeM04gWO9MsDQGrV","type":"text","text":"Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r1s2.yaml`.\n\n**Hypothesis summary:** IF-stage predecode adds zero-state static branch prediction covering the two cheapest high-value cases — JAL (always correctly predicted from its j-immediate) and backward-taken conditional branches (loop-back heuristic). No BHT/BTB/RAS storage; just an opcode compare + immediate adder on the fetch path. EX stage suppresses redirect when prediction matched, keeping the existing 2-cycle bubble only for mispredicts.\n\n**Why \"predictor\" slot, why this angle:**\n- No predictor currently exists — every taken control transfer costs 2 bubbles.\n- CoreMark has dense JAL glue and inner loops; both cases hit frequently.\n- Zero stateful storage keeps LUT budget near baseline (9880/10000) and avoids Fmax risk from a BRAM-mapped BHT/BTB. The added logic parallelizes with the existing `pc+4` path.\n- Leaves the door open for a follow-up RAS or BTB hypothesis without conflict.\n\nExpected fitness: +8% (medium confidence) — IPC wins from dominant loop/call patterns, minor Fmax headwind from the 3-way next_pc mux and j_imm adder.","time":{"start":1777782530066,"end":1777782535332}}}
