{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777783502710,"sessionID":"ses_213d96018ffenZ3KaIfg9iR7Bw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Gs2oesWpTiPrr6qaboPT7P","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"list existing hypotheses"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"list existing hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"list existing hypotheses","time":{"start":1777783502698,"end":1777783502709}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm analyzing why the previous predictor attempt regressed so badly—adding logic to the PC register's combinational path cost 11.64% in performance. The critical insight is that prediction logic needs to stay off that critical path, either by registering the prediction or accepting a one-cycle redirect penalty instead. Now I'm thinking through a better approach that avoids this bottleneck.\n\nThe current design resolves branches in EX, creating two bubbles on taken branches. A registered BTB indexed by PC would let me do the lookup in parallel with fetch, then use the predicted target the next cycle—this trades a one-cycle redirect penalty for avoiding the combinational path entirely, which should actually save cycles compared to the current two-bubble cost.\n\nBut I'm running into a timing issue: the BRAM output is synchronous, so the prediction arrives too late to affect the PC in the same cycle. I could use a separate predicted_pc register that gets updated when the BTB hits, creating a mini-redirect on the next cycle, but that's getting complicated. Maybe a simpler approach like a Return Address Stack for JALR would be more practical, since unconditional jumps are less common in CoreMark anyway.\n\nActually, a better angle: use a branch history table with a registered prediction that fires at the ID stage instead of trying to redirect fetch early. The BHT lookup happens in IF, gets pipelined to ID, and then ID can immediately redirect IF with the predicted target—that's only 1 bubble instead of 2. The critical paths are manageable: the ID stage needs to decode, generate the immediate, look up the BHT, compute the target, and decide on redirect, but it all terminates at the PC register input, not propagating further downstream. This matches the lesson about registering predictions and absorbing a single-cycle redirect.\n\nFor the BHT itself, I'm thinking a 256-entry table of 2-bit saturating counters indexed by PC[9:2], with a combinational read in IF that gets registered into the IF/ID pipeline bundle, and a write port in EX when the branch resolves. Then in ID, if the instruction is a branch and the prediction says taken, I compute the target and fire the redirect. Alternatively, I could start simpler with static prediction—backward branches taken, forward branches not-taken—applied at ID stage, which gives the same 1-cycle penalty on misprediction without needing the BHT hardware yet. Either way, the redirect path from ID to the PC register adds another term to the mux but doesn't extend the critical path significantly since it terminates at a register.\n\nThe key insight is that the prediction comes from the *registered* IF/ID instruction, not combinationally from memory, so there's no Fmax hit. The ID-to-PC redirect already fits conceptually alongside the existing EX-to-PC redirect—just a 3-way mux instead of 2-way. ID's timing usually has slack, so adding a branch target adder (PC + imm) there shouldn't break anything. I need to track whether a branch was predicted taken through the ID/EX register so that in EX I can distinguish a correct prediction from a mispredict and only flush on mismatch.\n\nBut wait—I'm realizing the combinational path problem again. If ID reads from the combinational IF/ID output, decodes, and feeds back to the PC mux, that's still imem_data → PC register combinationally, which is the same bottleneck as before. The solution is to ensure the prediction signal itself comes from a register, not from combinational decode—either by pre-decoding branches in a separate registered stage or by simplifying the PC mux logic so any redirect stays fully registered.\n\nI'm now thinking a Branch Target Buffer in BRAM could work. The BTB would be a small 64-entry array storing valid bits, tags, and targets, written by EX when a branch commits. Since BRAM reads are synchronous, the BTB output arrives registered one cycle after presenting the PC index, so at cycle N+1 I'd have the registered BTB prediction for cycle N's PC. That prediction can then redirect the fetch for cycle N+2, giving a 1-bubble penalty on taken branches but keeping the PC mux input registered rather than combinational. The IF stage reads the BTB with the current PC, and next cycle the registered BTB output tells us where to fetch from.\n\nActually, let me step back and propose something more concrete and implementable given the time constraints. I'll design a 16-entry direct-mapped tagged BTB stored in a simple register array to avoid tool issues. Each entry holds a valid bit, 24-bit tag, and 31-bit target. The BTB read is combinational from the registered PC output, but I'll register that result into a prediction flop before using it. Since the BTB read comes from the registered PC, the prediction register captures a valid prediction for that cycle's PC, and the next cycle I can use that registered prediction to redirect the fetch.\n\nNow I'm working through the penalty structure. When the BTB hits correctly, there's a 1-cycle bubble because the prediction arrives too late to affect the current fetch—the PC has already selected PC+4 for the next cycle before the BTB prediction is registered. Let me trace through the timing more carefully to make sure I have this right.\n\nIf I want to avoid the critical path issue while still getting just 1 bubble, I can use a registered prediction that triggers a redirect on the following cycle. When a valid prediction is available and hasn't been used yet, I flush the IF/ID stage and redirect the PC to the predicted target, wasting just that one fetch of the fall-through address.\n\nNow I'll formalize this approach in YAML with the registered prediction output as the key optimization to maintain timing, expecting around 8% fitness gain.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec27770f001LBFmm75sIIuA2Y","sessionID":"ses_213d96018ffenZ3KaIfg9iR7Bw","messageID":"msg_dec26a032001hSlSyNtVwM10pa"}}
