{"type":"text","timestamp":1777783584226,"sessionID":"ses_213d96018ffenZ3KaIfg9iR7Bw","part":{"id":"prt_dec2822fb001mVk09MkWYgl2Qx","messageID":"msg_dec279230001fexgqQliIwbyAE","sessionID":"ses_213d96018ffenZ3KaIfg9iR7Bw","type":"text","text":"Now I understand the landscape. The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2) put the predict logic in the IF stage's combinational fetch loop (imem_data → predecode → PC), extending the fetch critical path. The lesson: \"register the prediction and absorb a 1-cycle redirect\" to avoid the Fmax cliff.\n\nMy approach: a small **registered BTB** that's indexed by PC (not by imem_data), so the lookup path doesn't go through the imem BRAM output. The prediction is flopped into a register and applied the following cycle as a 1-cycle-late redirect. This cleanly keeps the PC register's combinational cone to just the existing mux + the BTB register's Q output.","time":{"start":1777783546619,"end":1777783584225}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777783584236,"sessionID":"ses_213d96018ffenZ3KaIfg9iR7Bw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Ck5hMGcud7dSc5PhK27Y4L","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r2s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r2s2\ntitle: \"Registered 16-entry BTB indexed by PC (off the fetch BRAM critical path)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Branch prediction is still the biggest CPI lever on this core: every\n  taken BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/JAL/JALR resolves in EX and costs 2 pipeline\n  bubbles (flush IF + ID). CoreMark's inner loops (crc16, matrix_mul,\n  state_machine) plus function-call glue hit this tax on a large\n  fraction of cycles. The prior predictor attempt (hyp-003-r1s2,\n  -11.64%) proved the IPC win is real but put the predecode+adder on\n  the imem BRAM → PC register combinational cone, extending the fetch\n  loop critical path enough on GW2AR to wipe out the gain. The\n  LESSONS.md takeaway is explicit: prediction logic must stay off the\n  PC register's combinational cone — register the prediction and\n  absorb a 1-cycle redirect. A PC-indexed BTB satisfies this: the\n  lookup is driven by the PC register (not by imem_data), and its\n  output is flopped before reaching the PC mux.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a small 16-entry direct-mapped, tagged Branch Target Buffer\n  stored in flip-flops (not BRAM — avoids Yosys/GW2AR BRAM-inference\n  quirks and keeps the entry width flexible). Each entry is\n  {valid, tag[25:0], target[31:1]} = 58 bits × 16 = 928 FFs, well\n  inside the FF budget headroom (1858/??? used today).\n\n  Timing contract — this is the load-bearing part:\n    (1) BTB is READ with the CURRENT PC register value as index\n        (PC[5:2] for the 16-way set; PC[31:6] as the tag). The lookup\n        (16:1 mux + 26-bit tag equality) is combinational but its\n        output is FLOPPED into a btb_pred_q register at end of cycle.\n        Path: PC_reg → 4-level mux tree → xor/nor → FF D. Ends at a\n        flop, NOT at PC_reg. This is the critical change vs the prior\n        attempt — the imem BRAM is nowhere on this path.\n    (2) BTB is WRITTEN by EX stage when a branch/JAL/JALR resolves\n        taken, keyed by the branch PC already in the EX/MEM register.\n        Single write port, one entry per cycle.\n    (3) btb_pred_q is consumed one cycle later by IF stage: adds a\n        third input to the PC next-state mux\n        (redirect > btb_pred > PC+4). Since btb_pred_q is a register\n        output, this only adds one mux layer to PC_reg's combinational\n        cone. When btb_pred_q fires, the IF/ID bundle for the\n        wrong-path fetch just made is squashed to NOP via a new\n        flush_id cause — reusing the existing redirect-flush machinery.\n\n  Penalty model:\n    - Correctly-predicted taken branch: 1 bubble (the PC+4 fetch issued\n      one cycle before btb_pred_q could redirect is squashed). Down\n      from 2 bubbles today.\n    - Mispredict (wrong direction OR wrong target OR stale entry):\n      EX fires the usual redirect, flushes IF+ID, penalty stays at 2\n      bubbles — same as today. BTB is updated with the correct target.\n    - Untaken branches / no-BTB-hit: 0 penalty, PC+4 default.\n    - JAL/JALR: first execution trains the BTB (2-bubble miss, same as\n      today); subsequent calls to the same call site benefit. JALR to\n      rarely-repeated callsites stays at 2 bubbles.\n\n  A valid/taken counter bit is NOT added — the BTB's presence of a\n  valid entry itself acts as the taken predictor. Strongly-biased\n  branches and all JAL/JALR sites that retain their entry predict\n  taken; branches that resolve not-taken allocate no entry (EX only\n  writes on taken resolution), so they predict not-taken by default.\n  Aliasing between different-PC branches mapped to the same BTB index\n  is resolved by the tag check — on miscompare, no prediction fires.\n\n  Mispredict-direction case: a branch that previously resolved taken\n  (and installed a BTB entry) later resolves not-taken. BTB still hits\n  and predicts taken; EX's actual-taken=0 fires a redirect that\n  overrides btb_pred_q (priority: EX-redirect > btb_pred > PC+4). The\n  stale entry is INVALIDATED by EX on this \"took prediction but not\n  taken\" case to avoid persistent miss.\n\n  Expected IPC uplift: CoreMark is ~15% branches of which ~60% are\n  taken, ~5% are JAL/JALR — so ~10-12% of instructions are taken\n  control transfers. Saving 1 bubble per correctly-predicted transfer\n  at ~80% BTB hit-rate (hot loops + repeat-call function glue) ≈\n  0.09 cycles/inst saved. Against a current ~1.2 CPI that's ~7% IPC.\n  Fmax unchanged if the PC cone stays clean (enforced by the\n  register-the-prediction discipline above). Fitness expected ~+6%.\n\n  Risk / mitigations:\n    - LUT/FF budget: 928 FFs for BTB storage, plus ~100 LUTs for the\n      16:1 mux + tag compare + write decoder. Current LUT4 usage 9905\n      of 10000 target — this is tight. If synth blows budget, reduce\n      BTB to 8 entries (464 FFs, ~50 LUTs). Doing the 16-entry version\n      first to measure; fall back if nextpnr rejects.\n    - RVFI: prediction logic is PC-only and entirely pre-fetch; it\n      does NOT touch the retirement path. rvfi_order, rvfi_trap,\n      rvfi_pc_wdata still driven from the MEM/WB register exactly as\n      today. No contract risk.\n    - Formal: the unique-order / liveness / ill checks are unaffected\n      because retirement is unchanged. The pc_fwd property requires\n      pc_wdata_n == pc_rdata_{n+1} — still holds because mispredicts\n      flush and redirect, so the next retirement's pc_rdata is always\n      the previous retirement's pc_wdata.\n    - Invariant 6 (memory bounds): fetching at a mispredicted-to\n      address could in principle step outside [0, 0x100000). Mitigated\n      because the mispredicted fetch is squashed (flush_if) before it\n      produces an architectural side-effect, and imem reads at OOB\n      addrs are sim-side handled as 0 (which decodes to illegal but is\n      flushed before retirement).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/btb.sv\n    description: \"New 16-entry direct-mapped tagged BTB module. Combinational read from PC, registered prediction output {valid, target}. Synchronous write port driven by EX on taken-branch / JAL / JALR resolution. Flop-based storage (no BRAM). Exposes an invalidate port for the 'predicted taken but actual not-taken' stale-entry case.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend PC next-state mux to include btb_pred_q as a 3rd input (priority: EX redirect > BTB pred > PC+4). When btb_pred_q fires this cycle, force this cycle's IF/ID bundle to the NOP/invalid sentinel (same mechanism as existing flush). Add one cycle of latched 'pred_just_fired' to prevent re-applying the same prediction on consecutive cycles.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Emit BTB update signals: btb_update_valid (on any branch/JAL/JALR in EX), btb_update_pc (this instruction's PC), btb_update_target (resolved target), btb_update_taken (true for taken branch, always-true for JAL/JALR). Also emit btb_invalidate for the 'prediction was taken, actual was not-taken' case — uses existing mispredict detection, just routes an extra signal.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate btb module. Wire PC-register output to BTB read-index, btb_pred_q to if_stage's new prediction input, EX's update/invalidate signals to BTB write port. No change to RVFI port set or retirement path.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add pred_redirect cause to flush_if (treat a BTB-predicted redirect the same as an EX-redirect for wrong-path suppression). No new stall conditions — BTB never stalls the pipeline.\"\n  - file: test/test_btb.py\n    description: \"New cocotb unit test for the BTB module in isolation: write then read-hit, write then read-miss (tag mismatch), invalidate, write-conflict (two writes same cycle, latest wins), read of uninitialised entry returns invalid.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add integration tests: backward-BEQ hot-loop shows reduced cycles/iter vs baseline after BTB warms, JAL call site retains prediction across repeated calls, mispredict on direction flip correctly invalidates the BTB entry and reverts to not-taken default.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r2s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r2s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777783584222,"end":1777783584235}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I see the issue now—moving prediction into the IF stage combinationally extended the critical path, so instead I should register the prediction at the ID stage and let the redirect absorb a cycle delay, keeping the PC update path shorter.\n\nBut wait, registering the prediction means it arrives a cycle too late to help—by then the instruction is already in EX. The real problem is that the full decode-to-adder path is expensive, so maybe I can split it: use a lightweight pre-decode in IF that just identifies JAL and extracts the immediate, then register that early result to avoid the combinational chain.\n\nActually, the bottleneck was always the BRAM read itself. If I register imem_data before predecoding, I add a fetch cycle of latency. A better approach is a BTB—a small dedicated memory indexed by PC that stores predicted targets, completely bypassing the imem dependency. The path becomes PC → BTB lookup → PC mux, which is much tighter than going through instruction memory and decode.\n\nFor a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB, I'd store valid, tag, and target in registers—about 944 bits total. The read is combinational: PC[5:2] selects an entry, I compare the tag against PC[31:6], and if it hits, I use the predicted target. The PC mux then prioritizes mispredict correction, then BTB hit, then PC+4. The timing should work—tag comparison and muxing is maybe 15-20 gate levels. On a mispredict, I'd need to flush one or two bubbles since the BTB prediction takes effect the cycle after the branch is fetched, and the actual resolution happens when the branch reaches EX.\n\nNow I'm analyzing the critical path impact. Adding the BTB lookup—PC indexing into a 16-entry array, the tag comparison across 30 bits, and the final mux—introduces roughly 10 additional gate levels. At 148 MHz on the GW2A, that's potentially a 15-30% hit to Fmax. To avoid this, I should register the BTB output instead of using it combinationally, accepting one extra cycle of latency but keeping the critical path clean.\n\nWith a registered BTB prediction, the timing works out to one bubble on a correct prediction rather than two, which is still a win. The PC mux now just selects between the redirect target, the registered BTB prediction, or PC+4—all short paths. The BTB read itself terminates at the register, not at the PC register, so it's on a less critical path. I still need to handle flushing the wrong-path fetch when the prediction fires.\n\nI'm tracking whether I used the registered prediction this cycle to avoid reusing it, and mispredictions still get detected in EX with a 2-cycle penalty. For correct predictions, I'm down to 1 cycle. Since CoreMark has roughly 9% taken branches, saving a cycle on those gives me about 0.09 CPI improvement—roughly 7% IPC gain if frequency stays the same.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec2824c4001X7Bk2hiAaqJdMi","sessionID":"ses_213d96018ffenZ3KaIfg9iR7Bw","messageID":"msg_dec279230001fexgqQliIwbyAE"}}
