{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777785007772,"sessionID":"ses_213c30da2ffeGO1itZcKTbsuMW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01F3TVrzHdCM1VMsAXU8H3FC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r3s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r3s2\ntitle: \"Tiny 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS) with ID-stage speculative redirect\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  CoreMark is call/return dense — crc16, core_bench_matrix, core_bench_state\n  all run through small leaf functions, and every `ret` (JALR x0, x1, 0)\n  in this core costs TWO bubbles today (IF/ID both squashed when EX\n  resolves the JALR redirect). Prior predictor attempts failed for two\n  distinct reasons that point to a narrow design window:\n    * r1s2 (static BP at IF): logic on imem_data→PC_reg cone killed Fmax.\n    * r2s2 (16-entry BTB, ~928 FFs + ~100 LUTs): IPC win was ~7% but\n      area congestion on the near-full GW2AR (9905/10000 LUT4) erased it.\n  LESSONS.md explicitly suggests \"try 8-entry or tagless variants\". A\n  function-call RAS is the most area-efficient possible predictor: the\n  hit rate on returns is ~100% in single-threaded code with matching\n  call/ret discipline (CoreMark qualifies), it needs no tag compare, and\n  the predicted target is a stored 32-bit word rather than an adder\n  cone. Pattern-less call/ret imbalance is rare in CoreMark's hot loops,\n  so a 4-deep stack covers nearly all dynamic returns without ever\n  overflowing across a leaf call chain.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack that is READ and updated at the ID\n  stage, and emits an `id_redirect` that reloads PC one cycle earlier\n  than the EX-stage JALR resolution — saving exactly one bubble per\n  correctly predicted return.\n\n  Detection (purely combinational on IF/ID.instr, no regfile dependence):\n    * Push on \"call\":  opcode ∈ {JAL=0x6F, JALR=0x67} AND rd ∈ {x1, x5}.\n      Push value = in.pc + 4 (the normal link address).\n    * Pop  on \"return\": opcode = JALR AND funct3 = 0 AND rs1 ∈ {x1, x5}\n      AND rd = x0. This is the canonical `ret` pattern emitted by GCC\n      for RV32 (JALR also as tail-call goes through rd=x0 rs1=x6 etc.,\n      which we intentionally exclude to keep mispredicts away).\n    * Call-and-return (rd ∈ {1,5} AND rs1 ∈ {1,5} AND rd == rs1): the\n      RISC-V Unprivileged spec calling convention table says this is a\n      coroutine swap (pop then push). Handle simply as pop+push in the\n      same cycle.\n    * The push/pop is gated by `id_ex_w` being captured (i.e. not on\n      load-use bubble / dmem stall / flush_id). On flush caused by an\n      EX-stage mispredict we must NOT update the stack for the squashed\n      ID instruction — a simple `!flush_id && in.valid` gate.\n\n  Speculative redirect:\n    * On the POP arm, emit `id_redirect = 1`, `id_redirect_target =\n      ras[tos]`. This is a REGISTERED 32-bit read (no adder cone) —\n      the mux into PC is `{reset, ex_redirect, id_redirect, pc+4}` with\n      ex_redirect still highest priority so a same-cycle EX resolve of\n      an older instruction still wins over a newer ID pop. This keeps\n      the id_redirect path off the fetch-BRAM→PC cone that killed r1s2:\n      the RAS top is a flop output, and the ID-stage decode is already\n      a registered cycle after imem_data.\n    * Track the `predicted_target` and `predicted_valid` bits alongside\n      the JALR as it flows through EX/MEM. In EX, when the real JALR\n      target computes, compare `jump_target == predicted_target`:\n        - match  → suppress the EX redirect (we already redirected IF\n          from ID the cycle before; no extra flush needed).\n        - miss   → standard EX redirect with actual target; 2-bubble\n          penalty as today. Net cost of a misprediction = zero relative\n          to the un-predicted baseline.\n    * On ANY EX mispredict (misaligned JALR, branch mispredict), roll\n      back the RAS TOS pointer by `tos_snapshot` captured with the\n      oldest in-flight ID-predicted pop. For simplicity v1 stores just\n      one \"pending pop\" snapshot; multiple in-flight pops would need a\n      queue but CoreMark never has two returns within 1 cycle of each\n      other.\n\n  Storage budget (versus the 928-FF BTB that failed):\n    * 4×32-bit stack = 128 FFs.\n    * 2-bit TOS pointer = 2 FFs.\n    * Pending-pop snapshot (TOS + 1 valid bit) = 3 FFs.\n    * Decode logic ≈ 30 LUTs (rd/rs1 equality to {1,5}, opcode compare).\n    * ID-redirect mux in if_stage ≈ 32-bit 2:1 (id vs ex) + 1-bit\n      priority = ~35 LUTs.\n    * EX-stage match compare = 32-bit xor/or ≈ 10 LUTs.\n    Total budget ~130 FF, ~75 LUT — an order of magnitude smaller than\n    the BTB and zero tag-RAM, so GW2AR routing congestion should not\n    spike.\n\n  Expected IPC win on CoreMark:\n    * CoreMark at ITERATIONS=10 retires ~1.2M instructions per iteration\n      in its hot kernels; call/ret density in the matrix & state\n      kernels is ~5–8% of dynamic instructions (one ret per 12–20 ops).\n    * Each correctly-predicted return saves 1 cycle. At ~6% return rate\n      and ~100% RAS hit (matched call/ret), expected cycle reduction\n      ~5–6%, which composes multiplicatively with Fmax to become a\n      roughly +5% fitness improvement provided Fmax is preserved.\n    * Critical path is preserved: id_redirect_target is a flop read,\n      so the logic depth into PC is one 2:1 mux deeper than baseline.\n      The flush-priority mux in if_stage already selects between\n      redirect and pc+4; we add a single `id_redirect` wire with lower\n      priority than `ex_redirect`.\n\n  Correctness invariants (CLAUDE.md alignment):\n    * Inv. 1 (2-channel RVFI): unaffected — still single-issue, channel\n      1 stays tied off.\n    * Inv. 2 (trap = illegal): unaffected; decoder logic unchanged.\n    * Inv. 4 (unique rvfi_order): unaffected; a correctly-predicted\n      return reduces bubbles but does not change retirement order.\n    * Inv. 5 (liveness): on RAS empty pop, `id_redirect = 0` (no\n      prediction) — falls back to baseline 2-bubble JALR resolve. The\n      stack is reset to empty on core reset.\n    * Inv. 6 (mem bounds): RAS never writes memory.\n  Coverage is added in `test/test_ras.py` (cocotb): push/pop sequence,\n  stack overflow (5th push silently overwrites oldest — no correctness\n  risk, only a mispredict penalty), underflow (pop on empty = no\n  redirect), call-then-ret round-trip verified by EX-stage PC_wdata.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ras.sv\n    description: \"New module: 4-entry RAS with synchronous push/pop, TOS pointer, empty flag, rollback snapshot port for mispredict recovery.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Detect call (JAL/JALR with rd∈{1,5}) and return (JALR rs1∈{1,5}, rd=x0, funct3=0) combinationally. Drive RAS push/pop/push_data. Emit id_redirect + id_redirect_target from RAS top on return when RAS non-empty. Propagate predicted_target and predicted_valid into the ID/EX register for EX-stage verification.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend id_ex_t and ex_mem_t with `predicted_target [31:0]` and `predicted_valid` bits so the EX verifier sees the ID-stage prediction.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add id_redirect/id_redirect_target input with lower priority than ex redirect but higher than stall. PC mux becomes {reset, ex_redirect, id_redirect, !stall ? pc+4 : pc}; ensure id_redirect also squashes the IF/ID combinational payload to NOP so the wrong-path instruction does not enter ID.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"When a JALR resolves, compare jump_target to predicted_target. If match and predicted_valid, suppress the external redirect (still update pc_next for RVFI). If mismatch, drive redirect=1 with actual target AND issue ras_rollback to restore TOS snapshot. Misaligned JALR still traps as today.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate ras, wire ID/EX id_redirect paths, route EX rollback back to RAS. Channel-1 RVFI remains tied off.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add id_redirect as a flush_if trigger (squash the IF cycle driven by the soon-to-be-wrong pc+4). Treat it equivalent to ex redirect for flush semantics but it must NOT flush the ID register that originated the redirect itself.\"\n  - file: test/test_ras.py\n    description: \"New cocotb suite: verify RAS push/pop ordering, 4-deep overflow wraps without hanging (liveness), underflow is no-op, matched call/ret saves exactly one cycle relative to a baseline-equivalent run, mispredicted JALR (computed target ≠ RAS top) correctly flushes and rolls back TOS. Confirms rvfi_order still monotonic across predicted returns.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r3s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r3s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777785007758,"end":1777785007770}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm sketching out a Return Address Stack implementation for the instruction decode stage—a compact 4-entry design with minimal overhead that pushes return addresses on JAL/JALR instructions targeting x1 or x5, and pops them on pure returns where JALR reads from those same registers with x0 as the destination.\n\nThe speculative redirect happens at ID stage without impacting the fetch critical path, then EX stage verifies the prediction and flushes on mismatch. This saves roughly one cycle per correctly predicted return, which matters significantly in CoreMark's CRC kernel where returns cause 2-cycle bubbles today—potentially yielding around 5% IPC improvement if 10% of dynamic instructions are returns. The area footprint is tiny compared to the failed BTB attempt: just 128 flip-flops and ~50 LUTs versus the 928 FFs that killed that design.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec3dcd52001BxaBPOLzTm3XG9","sessionID":"ses_213c30da2ffeGO1itZcKTbsuMW","messageID":"msg_dec3dac6e0015LB1p9RFfhzl8O"}}
