{"type":"text","timestamp":1777785015541,"sessionID":"ses_213c30da2ffeGO1itZcKTbsuMW","part":{"id":"prt_dec3e73cc001CLEWFaUKKRXk0z","messageID":"msg_dec3e6edb001b6kU70YLpy4Lwd","sessionID":"ses_213c30da2ffeGO1itZcKTbsuMW","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis `hyp-20260503-003-r3s2.yaml` — a **4-entry Return Address Stack with ID-stage speculative redirect**.\n\nWhy this angle for the predictor slot:\n\n- **Prior predictor failures teach the design window**: r1s2 died because BP logic sat on the imem_data→PC_reg cone; r2s2 died because 928 FFs of BTB caused GW2AR routing pressure on a near-full die (9905/10000 LUTs). LESSONS.md explicitly recommends smaller/tagless variants.\n- **RAS is the smallest useful predictor**: ~130 FFs + ~75 LUTs total — an order of magnitude under the BTB — and it needs no tag compare, just a stored 32-bit word read from a flop.\n- **Critical-path clean**: prediction happens at ID (one cycle after imem_data), and the predicted target is a registered flop output, so the PC mux grows by one 2:1 priority level, not a fetch-cone adder chain.\n- **High hit rate on CoreMark**: call/ret in single-thread C is ~100% matched; 4 deep covers leaf chains comfortably. ~6% dynamic return rate × 1-cycle save ≈ ~5% IPC win without Fmax loss.\n- **Safe on mispredict**: TOS snapshot rollback on EX mismatch; misprediction cost equals the baseline 2-bubble JALR resolve (zero regression floor).","time":{"start":1777785009100,"end":1777785015537}}}
