{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777786116039,"sessionID":"ses_213b4018fffeXVi79ynWavpmfC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01PvikCjce6VjdgqBqZsEccM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r4s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r4s2\ntitle: \"Zero-storage JAL fast-path: resolve JAL redirect in ID via shared redirect wire\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  JAL is unconditional and fully determined at decode time — target = PC +\n  imm_j, no rs dependency, no branch condition. Today the pipeline pays\n  the full 2-cycle EX redirect penalty on every JAL (same cost as a\n  mispredicted branch): IF/ID is flushed, ID/EX is bubbled, PC reloads\n  from EX's redirect_target three cycles after the JAL's fetch.\n  CoreMark's call/return structure (list_ins/core_list_find/core_bench_*)\n  has ~3–5% dynamic JAL density; saving one cycle per JAL by resolving\n  the redirect in the ID stage — one cycle earlier than EX — recovers\n  ~3–5% of total execution cycles at effectively zero storage cost.\n  Prior predictor attempts (r1s2 JAL/backward-BEQ at IF, r2s2 16-entry\n  BTB, r3s2 4-entry RAS) all failed — either on the PC-register D-input\n  critical path (r1s2), on LUT budget on the near-full GW2AR fabric\n  (r2s2, 928 FFs), or on PC-select fanin growth combined with\n  snapshot/rollback state (r3s2). This hypothesis deliberately avoids\n  all three failure modes by adding ZERO storage (JAL is unconditional,\n  no rollback needed, no prediction table, no tag compare) and by\n  routing the ID-stage redirect through the EXISTING redirect wire via\n  a small priority mux — NOT by adding a new input to if_stage's PC\n  select. The decoder already produces is_jump (combinational); imm_gen\n  already produces imm_j (combinational). The new logic is just a\n  1-bit AND + a 32-bit adder + a 2:1 mux at the top-level redirect fan-in.\nhypothesis: |\n  Extract JAL's redirect one pipeline stage earlier (from EX into ID) and\n  route it through the same `redirect` / `redirect_target` wire if_stage\n  already consumes, so the PC register's D-input mux stays a 2:1 (no new\n  PC-select input — this is the r3s2 / r1s2 failure mode avoided).\n\n  Implementation:\n    1. In core.sv, add combinational signals computed from the IF/ID\n       bundle (if_id_w) and a small decode probe:\n         - id_is_jal     = (if_id_w.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111) & if_id_w.valid\n         - id_jal_imm    = {{11{instr[31]}}, instr[31], instr[19:12],\n                             instr[20], instr[30:21], 1'b0}   (J-type imm)\n         - id_jal_target = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm\n       This replicates a 7-bit opcode compare and one J-type imm decode\n       at the top level. imm_gen.sv already contains this exact formula;\n       we inline the JAL arm here to avoid feeding imm_gen's full output\n       mux into the redirect cone.\n    2. Arbitrate with EX's existing redirect at the top level:\n         redirect_combined        = ex_redirect | id_is_jal;\n         redirect_target_combined = ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target\n                                                : id_jal_target;\n       EX wins when both fire (EX redirect kills in-flight ID as usual\n       and the id_is_jal condition becomes stale next cycle via flush_id).\n       if_stage's PC D-input mux stays structurally 2:1 — the only\n       change is a 2:1 mux on redirect_target_combined fed into the\n       same existing wire.\n    3. Inside id_stage, kill the JAL's own ID/EX capture when it fires\n       id_is_jal so EX doesn't redundantly fire a second redirect for\n       the same instruction. Simplest: when id_is_jal fires, gate the\n       ID/EX register's valid bit to 0 on that cycle (the JAL converts\n       into an architectural NOP in EX — its rd=x1 write is preserved\n       by routing PC+4 into rd_wdata via a small MEM-stage mux that\n       already exists for is_jump). Alternative: leave the JAL alive\n       through EX, but mask its `redirect` output at EX so if_stage\n       doesn't see a second (identical) redirect one cycle after the\n       ID-stage one. The simpler path is to keep JAL fully in flight\n       (preserving rd_wdata = PC+4) and mask EX's redirect signal when\n       the instruction's own id_is_jal fired one cycle earlier — a\n       single-bit `jal_predicted_q` flag propagated alongside ID/EX.\n    4. Flush if_id in the cycle id_is_jal fires (reuse flush_if via\n       OR with id_is_jal) so the speculatively-fetched pc+4 becomes a\n       NOP, preventing a wrong-path instruction from reaching ID.\n\n  Critical-path argument:\n    - imem_data → opcode[6:0] compare + J-imm decode + 32-bit add → OR\n      into the existing redirect wire. This cone is shorter than the\n      existing ex_stage redirect cone (which is opcode + branch compare\n      on rs1/rs2 + target add + redirect mux). Since ex_stage is already\n      a well-balanced combinational block and redirect_combined is a\n      simple OR of ex_redirect (post ex_stage) with id_is_jal (the new\n      short cone), the new timing path should not become critical.\n    - The PC register D-input cone stays 2:1 mux (`redirect_combined\n      ? redirect_target_combined : pc + 4`). The redirect_target_combined\n      mux moves upstream, not onto the PC-mux's fanin — which is exactly\n      the r3s2 failure mode this hypothesis is designed to sidestep.\n\n  Area argument:\n    - Zero storage: no predictor table, no tags, no history counters,\n      no snapshot register. Only a 1-bit `jal_predicted_q` flag flowing\n      through ID/EX/MEM (~3 FFs across pipeline) to mask EX's redundant\n      redirect on already-folded JALs.\n    - Logic adds: ~7 LUTs for opcode compare, ~32 LUTs for J-imm + add\n      (a single 32-bit adder, same width as the one ex_stage already\n      has for branch targets — but this one is on a less-critical cone),\n      ~32 LUTs for the redirect_target 2:1 mux. Total ~70 LUTs vs\n      r2s2's ~100 + 928 FFs and r3s2's ~75 + 130 FFs. Well within\n      headroom even on the current 9905/10000 LUT4 fabric.\n\n  JALR explicitly excluded — its target depends on rs1 (regfile read +\n  forward), which is not available at IF/ID combinationally without\n  pulling the regfile + forward_unit cones into the new redirect path.\n  JALR stays in EX (RAS territory, r3s2, already tried). This\n  hypothesis targets JAL only — the cleaner, unconditional, no-data-\n  dependency cases — and leaves conditional branches to EX.\n\n  Expected fitness: CoreMark JAL density ~3–5% × 1 cycle saved = ~3–5%\n  cycle reduction → ~3–5% CoreMark iter/s improvement if Fmax is\n  preserved. Fmax risk is the primary concern; the zero-storage /\n  shared-redirect-wire design directly addresses the r1s2/r2s2/r3s2\n  failure modes.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Add id_is_jal / id_jal_target combinational signals from if_id_w plus a top-level 2:1 redirect_target mux (EX wins). OR id_is_jal into the flush_if input. Route the combined signals to if_stage via the existing redirect / redirect_target ports — no new if_stage port.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Propagate a 1-bit jal_predicted_q flag into ID/EX payload (via a new field in id_ex_t) indicating the JAL's redirect was already handled at ID; EX uses this to mask its own redundant redirect for the same instruction.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Mask the outgoing redirect signal when the in-flight instruction's ctrl.is_jump is set AND id_ex_w.jal_predicted_q is 1 — the ID-stage fast-path already fired redirect one cycle earlier. Other outputs (pc_next for RVFI, PC+4 into rd_wdata) stay identical so the JAL's rd=x1 write and the RVFI pc_wdata contract are unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add a 1-bit `jal_predicted` field to id_ex_t (and matching 0-default propagation through ex_mem_t/mem_wb_t if needed for RVFI consistency). Keeps struct-packed layout — cost is 3 FFs on the pipeline spine.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb unit test that exercises a tight JAL-heavy loop (JAL forward + JAL backward) and asserts the core completes the loop in (loop-body + 1*N_JAL) cycles rather than (loop-body + 2*N_JAL) cycles. Also verifies rvfi_order monotonicity, rvfi_pc_wdata correctness for each folded JAL, and that x1 (the link register) receives PC+4 on JAL-and-link encodings.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r4s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r4s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777786116026,"end":1777786116037}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_dec4ebcb3001R0oIULa402IXvW","sessionID":"ses_213b4018fffeXVi79ynWavpmfC","messageID":"msg_dec4eb4ad001wRmoR1j2rSILYv"}}
