{"type":"text","timestamp":1777786122354,"sessionID":"ses_213b4018fffeXVi79ynWavpmfC","part":{"id":"prt_dec4f5df1001Vydcldb1cblaFr","messageID":"msg_dec4f5812001kb7AcY4DvLEVup","sessionID":"ses_213b4018fffeXVi79ynWavpmfC","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written: `hyp-20260503-003-r4s2` — a zero-storage JAL fast-path predictor.\n\n**Approach summary:**\n- Resolve JAL redirect in ID stage (1 cycle earlier than EX) — saves 1 cycle per JAL\n- Zero storage: no table, no tags, no history, no snapshot/rollback (JAL is unconditional)\n- Route via **existing** `redirect`/`redirect_target` wire with a 2:1 priority mux (EX wins)\n- **Critically avoids** the r3s2 failure mode: PC register D-input mux stays 2:1 — no new PC-select fanin\n- ~70 LUTs + ~3 FFs total, vs r2s2's 928 FFs or r3s2's 130 FFs\n\n**How it sidesteps each prior failure:**\n- r1s2 (critical path on PC cone): new cone is shorter than existing ex_stage redirect cone, and registered through normal ID→IF delay\n- r2s2 (LUT area): zero storage table\n- r3s2 (PC-mux fanin growth): shares existing redirect wire instead of adding a new PC-select input\n\nConfidence marked `low` — given the track record of predictors on this near-full GW2AR fabric, the Fmax risk is real even with the explicit design-around. Expected delta: +3%.","time":{"start":1777786117617,"end":1777786122351}}}
