{"type":"text","timestamp":1777787215650,"sessionID":"ses_213a0ff71ffeCBtsJ1ZFQ1QRKP","part":{"id":"prt_dec5f8f86001tZC0xM1hxVouvf","messageID":"msg_dec5f014d0010enGOawpkCTdjy","sessionID":"ses_213a0ff71ffeCBtsJ1ZFQ1QRKP","type":"text","text":"Looking at the history, the clear winning pattern is r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%): resolve prediction one stage later than IF (at ID), share the existing `redirect`/`redirect_target` net, zero storage. Three prior predictor attempts (r1s2 static BP at IF, r2s2 BTB, r3s2 RAS) all failed by either loading the PC-mux cone, adding LUT area on near-full fabric, or both.\n\nThe natural extension: apply the same pattern to backward conditional branches (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) — which dominate CoreMark loop back-edges. The opcode space is disjoint from JAL, so both predictions can share one combined `id_predicted_taken_fire` wire and one 2:1 target adder (J-imm vs B-imm) without widening the PC-mux fanin.","time":{"start":1777787178886,"end":1777787215649}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777787215669,"sessionID":"ses_213a0ff71ffeCBtsJ1ZFQ1QRKP","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_0166QnuVFP5c9M1fz29MNHv5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r5s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r5s2\ntitle: \"Zero-storage backward-branch fast-path predictor at ID stage\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current best core (r4s2) won +17.73% by resolving JAL one stage\n  earlier than EX via a zero-storage fast-path at ID that folds onto the\n  existing `redirect`/`redirect_target` net. JAL dynamic density in\n  CoreMark is only ~3-5%, yet the single-cycle bubble it saves per JAL\n  cleared the Fmax noise floor. CoreMark's inner loops (crcu8, core_bench_*,\n  matrix_mul_const) are dominated by conditional backward branches\n  (BEQ/BNE), which we currently still pay 1 bubble for on every taken\n  loop iteration (EX-resolved). Dynamic backward-branch density is\n  roughly 10-15% in CoreMark with ~85-90% taken-rate on loop back-edges,\n  so a correctly-implemented static backward-taken predictor at ID can\n  save ~1.5-3x as many pipeline bubbles as JAL-only, with the same\n  zero-storage cost profile.\n\n  The three prior predictor failures teach us exactly what to avoid:\n    - r1s2 static BP at IF: loaded the PC-reg D-input cone with\n      predecode + adder + 3-way mux. FAIL.\n    - r2s2 16-entry BTB: ~928 FF + ~100 LUT on a 9905/10000 near-full\n      fabric, area/congestion erased IPC win. FAIL.\n    - r3s2 4-entry RAS: still added a 3rd input to the PC-select\n      priority mux for id_redirect. FAIL.\n    - r4s2 JAL fast-path: zero storage, fold onto existing redirect\n      net, PC mux stays 2:1. WIN (+17.73%).\n\n  The r4s2 pattern generalizes cleanly to conditional branches IF we\n  ensure (a) the PC mux stays 2:1, (b) no new storage is added, and\n  (c) the misprediction-recovery wire lands on EX's existing\n  redirect path (not a new one). This hypothesis tests that.\nhypothesis: |\n  Extend the r4s2 ID-stage fast-path to cover statically-predicted-taken\n  backward conditional branches (BRANCH opcode 0x63 with instr[31]=1).\n  Prediction policy is the classical \"backward-taken, forward-not-taken\"\n  heuristic which hits ~80-90% on CoreMark loop back-edges.\n\n  Mechanism (additions, all in core.sv + decoder-adjacent logic — NO\n  new modules, NO new flops, NO new tables):\n\n  1. At ID, detect BRANCH opcode AND instr[31]==1 (B-imm sign bit =\n     backward). Compute B-imm locally (replicate the imm_gen B-arm the\n     same way the r4s2 JAL path replicates the J-arm) and\n     id_branch_target = if_id_w.pc + b_imm.\n\n  2. Introduce a single combined fast-path fire signal:\n       id_predicted_taken_fire = (id_is_jal_fire) | (id_is_backward_branch_fire)\n     Since JAL opcode 0x6F and BRANCH opcode 0x63 are mutually\n     exclusive, only one can assert per cycle.\n\n  3. The target mux is a single 2:1 upstream of the PC reg D-input\n     (just like r4s2): redirect_target = ex_redirect ?\n     ex_redirect_target : id_predicted_target, where\n     id_predicted_target = id_is_jal ? id_jal_target : id_branch_target.\n     This keeps the PC-reg combinational cone unchanged structurally:\n     EX-wins vs ID-predicted, same as today.\n\n  4. Pass a bp_predicted_taken bit (1 wire) through ID/EX alongside the\n     existing jal_predicted bit. Rename jal_predicted to\n     predicted_taken and repurpose it to cover both JAL and branches,\n     OR keep them separate for clarity — either works; the former saves\n     1 FF.\n\n  5. EX-stage logic changes (all in redirect computation — the\n     existing ex_redirect wire absorbs both hit and miss cases):\n       - Hit (predicted_taken=1 && actual branch_taken=1): suppress EX\n         redirect (same as JAL today). pc_next = branch_target.\n       - Miss-to-not-taken (predicted_taken=1 && actual branch_taken=0):\n         fire EX redirect to (pc+4). Same wire, new target arm.\n         pc_next = pc+4.\n       - Never-predicted taken (predicted_taken=0 && actual\n         branch_taken=1): normal EX redirect to branch_target (today's\n         behavior for forward branches). Unchanged.\n       - Never-predicted not-taken: no redirect (unchanged).\n     This reuses EX's existing redirect net; no new redirect wire.\n\n  6. Hazard unit consumes ex_redirect only (same as r4s2) — the ID\n     fast-path does NOT feed flush_if/flush_id, because the branch\n     itself must be captured into id_ex to propagate its\n     predicted_taken bit. Wrong-path instrs fetched on mispredict are\n     killed by the EX redirect's flush_if when the miss resolves — same\n     2-cycle wrong-path cost as today's forward-branch mispredict path,\n     but applied only to the ~10-15% of branches where prediction was\n     wrong instead of the ~85% that today waste a bubble.\n\n  Why this should win (and specifically why it should not trip the\n  r1s2/r2s2/r3s2 failure modes):\n    - PC-reg D-input mux fanin unchanged (2:1, same as r4s2 win).\n    - Zero new storage (no tags, no tables, no counters, no RAS).\n    - Logic added: ~1 opcode compare (BRANCH), ~1 AND on instr[31],\n      ~1 32-bit add for B-imm target, ~1 2:1 mux on id_predicted_target\n      (J-imm-target vs B-imm-target), ~1 FF for predicted_taken in\n      ID/EX (reuse jal_predicted slot). Area cost is ~15-25 LUTs and\n      1 FF — well within the 9905-LUT budget's ~100-LUT headroom.\n    - Critical path: the new ID-side cone is opcode-compare + 32-bit\n      adder, similar depth to r4s2's JAL cone; still shorter than EX's\n      branch compare + misalign + target-select cone that already\n      bounds ex_redirect. So Fmax should be stable.\n    - IPC: CoreMark inner loops (crcu8, matrix multiply, core_state\n      scan) iterate via BEQ/BNE back-edges. Saving 1 bubble per correct\n      prediction × ~85% hit rate × ~10-15% dynamic density of backward\n      branches = roughly 1.0-1.3% cycles saved per percent backward-\n      taken density. Expected total IPC gain: ~6-10%.\n\n  This is the single most promising predictor angle given the proven\n  r4s2 pattern, and it's strictly additive: if it regresses we learn\n  where the conditional-branch cone exceeds JAL's, which tightens the\n  negative-knowledge lesson set.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 7\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Add id_branch_target computation (B-imm replica + pc adder) and id_is_backward_branch_fire signal. Combine with id_is_jal_fire into id_predicted_taken_fire. Widen id_predicted_target into a 2:1 mux (J-imm target vs B-imm target) feeding the existing redirect_target 2:1 mux. Rename the ID/EX-carried jal_predicted bit to predicted_taken (or add a parallel bp_predicted bit) and route it into id_stage.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Rename id_ex_t.jal_predicted to predicted_taken (carries both JAL and predicted-taken-branch cases), or add a sibling bp_predicted field — pick whichever keeps FF count minimal. Update comment block to describe the extended semantics.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Rename jal_predicted_in port to predicted_taken_in (or add bp_predicted_in) and wire it into reg_q.predicted_taken. No other logic changes.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend redirect logic to handle three cases: (a) predicted_taken && branch_taken -> suppress (same as today's jal_predicted suppression); (b) predicted_taken && !branch_taken for a BRANCH op -> fire redirect to pc+4 (misprediction recovery); (c) !predicted_taken && branch_taken -> normal redirect to branch_target. Update pc_next for the EX/MEM register to match the new semantics (pc+4 on mispredict-to-not-taken, branch_target on correctly-predicted-taken, unchanged otherwise). Keep jump_target handling for JAL/JALR unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add cocotb vectors that exercise: (1) a backward BEQ that is actually taken (fast-path hit, no bubble); (2) a backward BEQ that is actually not-taken (fast-path miss, EX redirects to pc+4); (3) a forward BEQ that is taken (no prediction, normal EX redirect); (4) a JAL immediately preceded/followed by backward BEQ (verify the disjoint-opcode combined-fire signal). Assert rvfi_order strictly +1 across all cases and pc_wdata matches architectural semantics.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r5s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r5s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777787215644,"end":1777787215666}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the results from recent predictor design attempts—each approach hit different bottlenecks, from PC critical path issues to area constraints and fanin growth problems.\n\nThe JAL fast-path breakthrough at +17.73% showed the winning pattern: resolve unconditional jumps early and reuse the existing redirect network. Now I'm considering what comes next in that same vein, weighing options like a minimal RAS for JALR returns, a zero-storage backward-branch predictor at ID stage, or speculative branch prediction using just the opcode. The challenge is that static backward-branch prediction at IF stage failed before due to PC timing, so any new approach needs to keep prediction logic off the critical path—likely by registering predictions rather than feeding them directly into the PC mux.\n\nThe r4s2 winner moved prediction to ID stage where we have a registered PC and decoded instruction. For BEQ, I'd apply the same pattern: detect backward branches by the sign bit of the B-immediate, fire a redirect to the predicted target, and pass a `bp_taken_predicted` flag through the pipeline so EX can suppress its own redirect if the prediction was correct. The hardware cost is minimal—just an opcode check, immediate sign extraction, and reusing the existing adder—and the PC mux is already 2:1 from the JAL path.\n\nSince both JAL and backward BEQ predict taken, I can merge them into a single \"ID predicted taken\" redirect path; only one will fire per cycle anyway. For conditional branches, I'm using a static backward-taken heuristic (roughly 80% accurate for loops), so forward BEQs stay predicted not-taken and don't fire a redirect. If the prediction is wrong, EX redirects to pc+4, absorbing one extra squashed instruction—the same cost as a mispredicted JAL. opcodes are disjoint, so no reason to restrict to just BEQ/BNE — checking for backward branches at the opcode level is equally cheap. I'm settling on a zero-storage backward-branch predictor at ID stage that mirrors r4s2's winning approach but extends it to all conditional branches. The main concern is the PC mux becoming 3-way (EX redirect, ID-JAL, ID-backward-branch), but since JAL and backward branches have different opcodes they can't fire simultaneously, so the target mux can safely multiplex between them.\n\nFor the target computation, I'd use a shared adder with the PC and a 2:1 mux selecting between the J-immediate and B-immediate — either two separate adders or a pre-mux on the immediate itself. Given that backward conditional branches are roughly 10-15% of dynamic instructions in CoreMark versus 3-5% for JALs, and r4s2 saw +17.73% from JAL-only, I'm estimating this could yield +6-8% IPC improvement with a similar small Fmax penalty, though there's medium confidence and some risk of hitting LUT limits. Time to write the YAML.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec5f930b0012GYREnj6mFvUlo","sessionID":"ses_213a0ff71ffeCBtsJ1ZFQ1QRKP","messageID":"msg_dec5f014d0010enGOawpkCTdjy"}}
