{"type":"text","timestamp":1777787222667,"sessionID":"ses_213a0ff71ffeCBtsJ1ZFQ1QRKP","part":{"id":"prt_dec6027ad001wNQGbqcfByblkM","messageID":"msg_dec601f74001gJjXWBluiuii93","sessionID":"ses_213a0ff71ffeCBtsJ1ZFQ1QRKP","type":"text","text":"Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r5s2.yaml`.\n\n**Hypothesis summary:** Extend the proven r4s2 zero-storage JAL fast-path pattern to statically-predicted-taken backward conditional branches. Core idea:\n\n- **Policy**: backward-taken / forward-not-taken (classic static BP; ~85% hit rate on CoreMark loop back-edges).\n- **Placement**: at ID stage — same stage as the r4s2 JAL win, avoiding r1s2's fatal PC-reg cone loading.\n- **Storage**: zero (no BTB, no RAS, no counters — avoids r2s2/r3s2 area/congestion failures on near-full GW2AR).\n- **PC-mux fanin**: unchanged at 2:1 — JAL and BRANCH opcodes are disjoint, so one combined `id_predicted_taken_fire` wire with a pre-mux on the immediate target adder feeds the existing redirect net.\n- **Misprediction recovery**: reuses EX's existing `ex_redirect` wire with a new target arm (pc+4 on predicted-taken-but-actually-not-taken).\n\nExpected +7% from saving ~1 bubble per correct prediction across ~10-15% dynamic backward-branch density at ~85% accuracy, while staying within the <100-LUT headroom budget.","time":{"start":1777787217837,"end":1777787222664}}}
