{"type":"text","timestamp":1777788340181,"sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","part":{"id":"prt_dec713e0e00184JjopdL4pTFzO","messageID":"msg_dec6f1c69001a3pIASHjXyYu05","sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","type":"text","text":"Looking at the predictor category history, the landscape is clear:\n- **r1s2** (static BP at IF): regressed -11% (PC-mux fanin growth)\n- **r2s2** (16-entry BTB): 0% (LUT budget exhausted)  \n- **r3s2** (4-entry RAS): 0% (PC-mux fanin from rollback)\n- **r4s2** (zero-storage JAL fast-path): **+17.73% WIN**\n- **r5s2** (backward-BEQ extension): broken (rename cascade in plumbing)\n\nThe pattern that wins: resolve control flow one stage earlier, share the *existing* redirect wire via upstream 2:1 mux, zero storage. r5s2 tried the right concept (extending to backward branches) but broke on implementation — specifically, renaming `jal_predicted` cascaded into missed downstream consumers.\n\nLet me check the log for additional context:","time":{"start":1777788337678,"end":1777788340174}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777788340192,"sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01WbpbyhKcAesYwvgBPPqpfo","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"List recent hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List recent hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List recent hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777788340171,"end":1777788340190}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the predictor options, the zero-storage JAL fast-path is clearly the winner at +17.73%, while the other approaches—static branch prediction, a small BTB, and a return address stack—all hit constraints that prevent them from delivering any gains.\n\nNow I'm exploring what comes next: JALR with register forwarding seems risky due to the long combinational path from decode through the regfile and adder back to the PC, while a simple target cache still requires storage. Branch target precomputation at the ID stage could work though—precomputing the branch target and latching it would let EX just do the comparison and mux selection, potentially shortening the redirect path. There's also the compressed loop predictor idea, which would cache just the last taken branch's PC and target as a single-entry predictor.\n\nThe real lesson from the failed r3s2 RAS attempt is that adding a new speculative redirect input to the PC mux creates fanin problems, but the winning r4s2 pattern reuses the existing redirect wire through an upstream mux. For JALR, the common case is `ret` (jalr x0, x1, 0), and since rs1 is read from the regfile at ID stage, we could theoretically compute the target there if we handle forwarding correctly—the challenge is detecting whether rs1 is stale because a write is happening this cycle.\n\nAlternatively, I could pre-compute branch targets at ID stage (where there's decode slack) and store them in the ID/EX register, letting EX just do the comparison and select the pre-computed target. This shifts the adder burden from EX's critical path to ID, but it costs 32 FFs in the pipeline register.\n\nLooking at the existing code, branch_target feeds directly into the redirect mux in EX, so moving it earlier could help timing. But the r4s2 lesson warns against adding storage and long wires just to move logic—I'd need to follow that winning pattern of zero storage and shared nets.\n\nFor JALR specifically, I'm considering whether a lightweight RAS or dedicated return path could help, but it would need to resolve early at ID without requiring operand forwarding complexity.\n\nThe real insight is that JAL never mispredicts, which is why r4s2 works—it just ORs into the existing redirect signal with a simple 2:1 target mux. So I should look for other instructions that never mispredict and can resolve that early, or focus on precomputing branch targets to shorten EX's critical path without adding new storage. Looking at the r4s2 pattern, it avoids the IF-stage bloat by computing the target at ID and feeding it through the existing redirect mux—no extra PC input needed. The r5s2 attempt at backward-BEQ prediction failed due to cascading renames breaking formal verification, but the core idea of static backward-taken prediction at ID should work if I'm careful about state naming. Rather than renaming fields across files, I could add a separate `branch_predicted_taken` field to keep the change localized and avoid breaking consumers.\n\nStepping back though, given that r4s2 already achieved a +17.73% win, the real question is what's worth the risk. Pre-computing redirect targets at ID for all control-flow instructions would shorten the EX cone by moving the target calculation earlier, but r4s1 showed that adding 32 FFs to the ID/EX pipeline can regress performance. Looking at how ex_stage.sv computes redirect_target as a mux between jump and branch targets, this computation runs in parallel with the ALU, so the latency savings might not justify the register overhead.\n\nI keep circling back to JALR optimizations—detecting return patterns or zero-register cases—but they either need storage for rollback or target such rare cases that the benefit is marginal. And the r1s2 lesson was clear: don't push JAL detection into the fetch path.\n\nThe r5s2 backward-branch prediction is the real opportunity. The architecture is sound—static prediction at ID for branches that loop backward—but the implementation failed because renaming `jal_predicted` cascaded through downstream consumers and broke the SBY signature. The core issue is structural: adding a new redirect arm in EX for mispredicted branches that were predicted taken but shouldn't be, which means touching multiple pipeline stages and redirect logic.\n\nDefining the EX redirect logic... Writing redirect logic...\n\nThe CoreMark matrix kernel likely has hot loop branches, so a 6-10% IPC improvement is realistic, though I need to weigh that against the Fmax cost of adding a 3:1 mux and extra redirect logic in EX. Precomputing the branch target at decode saves an adder but threads more state through the pipeline without real benefit. Instead, I should focus on a simpler approach: a 1-bit loop hint that predicts backward branches as taken at ID using the existing redirect mechanism, sharing the wire through a priority mux rather than adding new hardware. This mirrors the r4s2 pattern—just opcode detection, immediate computation, and a gated fire signal—keeping the implementation lean.\n\nExtending this to backward BEQ/BNE adds more complexity: I'd need backward-branch detection, another immediate adder, a 3-way mux for redirect targets, and logic in EX to handle mispredicts (redirecting to pc+4 if the branch wasn't actually taken). That's a meaningful amount of extra code and risk. I could also try enabling the fast path for JALR with immediate-only addressing, but that's too rare in CoreMark to matter. Let me focus on the actual hot loops—matrix multiply, CRC, and list operations—to see if the simpler JAL-only approach is enough.\n\nSince r5s2 broke due to plumbing issues rather than the core idea, I think the real lesson is to avoid renaming `jal_predicted` to something like `predicted_taken`, which cascades changes everywhere. Instead, I'll keep `jal_predicted` untouched and add a separate `branch_predicted_taken` field for backward branches. EX can handle both independently without the risk of breaking existing logic.\n\nActually, wait — that's still a structural change that touches multiple EX redirect paths. Let me reconsider with something more constrained: what if I just generalize `jal_predicted` to cover both JAL and predicted-taken backward branches, but only for BNE since that's the actual loop pattern? BEQ backward is rare, but BNE backward is how loops typically check \"continue while not equal.\" That narrows the scope significantly and avoids the cascading field additions.\n\nBut actually, to keep it simple and maximize coverage without overthinking the instruction mix, I should just predict all backward branches as taken regardless of the condition code. That's the cleanest approach — reuse the r4s2 redirect wire, add a single `branch_predicted_taken` field to id_ex, and call it done.\n\nLet me write this up as the hypothesis. Though I'm also wondering if there's a micro-optimization I'm missing — maybe something about moving JAL resolution into the stall computation, or registering the prediction to fire a cycle later? No, that last one would add a bubble and regress performance. And the stall gating feels risky.\n\nActually, I'm tempted to try something completely different: a single-entry Return Address Stack...\n\nDetecting JAL writes to x1 in the EX stage, latching PC+4 into one flop, then predicting JALR with x0 destination and x1 source as a return by reading that latched value back at ID. This is much simpler than r3s2's 4-entry design with snapshots and rollback — just one 33-bit register (32 bits of data plus a validity bit). The redirect logic stays the same, using the existing r4s2 wire pattern, and if the prediction misses, EX handles the correction normally.\n\nThe key difference is consolidating the redirect mux...\n\nCombining the logic...\n\nNow checking resource usage: 40 additional LUTs and 33 more FFs against the current 9484/10000 LUT budget. That's tight but feasible, though I'm wondering if r4s2 already has more headroom than r2s2 did, since r2s2 hit congestion issues at 9905/10000.\n\nThe PC-redirect mux chain would stay the same depth as r4s2 — just adding one extra 2:1 mux at the ID stage for ra_pred versus id_jal_target, which shouldn't create routing problems.\n\nBetween backward-branch prediction and a single-entry RAS for returns, the RAS feels like the safer bet. It's simpler to implement — just detect JALR x0, x1, 0 and store the return address in a flop — and avoids the complexity that tripped up r5s2.\n\nBut there's a critical issue with speculative execution: if I set jal_predicted=1 when firing the RAS prediction at ID, then EX will mask its redirect for that JALR. That means on a misprediction, I've already fetched 2 wrong instructions and still need EX to fire a redirect — worse than having no prediction at all. I need to either keep jal_predicted=0 and let EX always redirect (wasting a cycle on correct predictions), or verify the prediction at EX and only suppress the redirect when it matches, which requires comparing the actual target against ra_pred.\n\nThe real cost analysis: a correct prediction saves 2 cycles, but a misprediction costs the same as no prediction (2 bubble cycles after the wrong fetch path). So the net win depends on hit rate — if the RAS hit rate is above 50%, it's worth it. For CoreMark with a 1-entry RAS, the hit rate is probably too low since it only catches leaf-level returns.\n\nI'm going to step back and go with the simplest, safest approach: static backward-branch prediction at ID with zero storage overhead, implemented carefully to avoid the pitfalls I've been wrestling with.\n\nThe math works out: CoreMark has 7-10% conditional branch density, roughly half are backward branches in loops with 80-95% taken rates, giving about 5% of dynamic instructions covered at ~85% accuracy — that's roughly 8.5% IPC improvement from 2 cycles saved per hit.\n\nFor implementation, I'll add a new `branch_taken_pred` field separate from the existing `jal_predicted` to avoid the naming conflicts that caused issues before. I'll add a `br_pred_fire` wire at the core level that feeds into the redirect logic, and extend the ID fast target mux to handle this new prediction source. The EX stage computes whether the prediction was wrong and generates a redirect to PC+4 on misprediction.\n\nThe risk is adding a third mux arm to the redirect target and extra logic in EX, but this is cleaner than trying to squeeze more complex predictors into the area budget.\n\nI'm going with the static backward-taken policy at ID, keeping it compatible with r4s2's proven pattern. Writing up the hypothesis now.\n\nDrafting the YAML...\n\nSetting up implementation discipline: I'll add a separate `branch_pred_taken` field to avoid colliding with the existing JAL path, OR the new redirect signal into the existing wire, and use a priority chain so the PC mux stays 2:1. In EX, I'll compute misprediction as branch opcode XOR'd with actual outcome, firing a redirect to pc+4 on mispredicts while suppressing the EX redirect when the prediction was correct. Gating the ID prediction on no stall...\n\nImplementing the Fmax strategy: the new ID cone is just opcode decode plus immediate sign check plus the pc+imm adder—same complexity as the JAL path—and the EX misprediction XOR is minimal, so no critical path hit. The redirect priority chain uses two levels of 2:1 muxes at the core top, which is friendlier for LUT packing than a 3:1. With no BTB or history storage, I'm projecting a 5–10% IPC gain from backward-branch prediction density and hit rate at equal Fmax.\n\nNow I'm laying out the implementation: adding the branch_pred_taken bit to the pipeline, wiring the prediction signal through ID and EX stages, and building the misprediction logic to handle all three cases—correctly predicted taken, mispredicted taken-to-not-taken, and mispredicted not-taken-to-taken. The test harness covers backward loops, loop exits, forward branches that shouldn't be predicted, and misaligned traps to ensure correctness.\n\nI'm setting confidence low since predictors are historically tricky, but estimating a 7% fitness gain is reasonable if backward branches are as prevalent as JALs and the coverage is similar—though I'm being conservative compared to the 17% uplift we saw in r4s2.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec71442f001AZe7zBW7wOcLn2","sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","messageID":"msg_dec6f1c69001a3pIASHjXyYu05"}}
