{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777788438417,"sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01HF6ZFHhTUyhWtcFvtWq56k","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r6s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r6s2\ntitle: \"Zero-storage backward-branch prediction at ID, r4s2-pattern (additive, no rename)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  r4s2's zero-storage JAL fast-path (+17.73%) established the winning predictor\n  pattern on this fabric: resolve control flow one stage earlier (ID instead of\n  EX), feed the EXISTING redirect wire via an upstream 2:1 target mux, add zero\n  storage, no tags, no lookup. That covered ~3-5% of CoreMark dynamic\n  instructions.\n\n  The next natural target is backward conditional branches — CoreMark's hot\n  paths (matrix multiply inner loop, CRC update, list_search traversal) are\n  dominated by backward-taken BNE/BLT/BLTU loop back-edges. Static\n  backward-taken/forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction is 80-95% accurate on\n  these CoreMark kernels, covers another ~4-6% of dynamic instructions, and\n  saves 2 pipeline bubbles per hit.\n\n  r5s2 attempted this concept but failed implementation: it renamed\n  `jal_predicted` to `predicted_taken`, and a missed downstream consumer\n  cascaded into SBY's \"Status: passed / engine_0 did not produce any traces\"\n  signature + cover VCD crash (no_checks_generated). The architectural idea\n  is sound; the diff discipline was not. This hypothesis retries the concept\n  with strict additive plumbing (no renames) to eliminate the cascade-risk\n  class of failures entirely.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add zero-storage static backward-branch prediction at the ID stage, reusing\n  r4s2's exact redirect-wire topology.\n\n  ID-stage (combinational, mirrors the shape of r4s2's JAL cone):\n    - id_br_imm   = B-type sign-extend of if_id_w.instr\n    - id_is_back_branch = (opcode==1100011) & if_id_w.valid & instr[31]\n                          (instr[31] is the B-imm sign bit = backward)\n    - id_br_target = if_id_w.pc + id_br_imm\n    - id_br_target_aligned = (id_br_target[1:0] == 2'b00)\n    - id_br_pred_fire = id_is_back_branch & !stall_id & id_br_target_aligned\n                        & !id_is_jal_fire          // JAL wins ties, same rule as EX>ID\n\n  Core-level redirect plumbing (depth-preserving):\n    - redirect = ex_redirect | id_is_jal_fire | id_br_pred_fire\n    - redirect_target selected by priority chain of 2:1 muxes:\n        tmp_id_target = id_is_jal_fire ? id_jal_target : id_br_target\n        redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target : tmp_id_target\n      This keeps the if_stage PC-select mux structurally 2:1 (same as r4s2),\n      and the ID-side target mux is a shallow 2-level 2:1 chain rather than a\n      3:1 mux — friendlier for LUT4 packing on GW2AR and same logical depth.\n\n  ID/EX pipeline register (ADDITIVE — no rename):\n    - Keep `jal_predicted` exactly as r4s2 defined it. Do not touch its name,\n      width, or consumers.\n    - ADD a new 1-bit field `branch_pred_taken` to id_ex_t, next to\n      `jal_predicted`. Driven by id_br_pred_fire. Every other id_ex_t field\n      is unchanged.\n    - id_stage.sv gets ONE new input port `branch_pred_taken_in` that latches\n      into reg_q.branch_pred_taken. The existing `jal_predicted_in` port and\n      its latch are untouched.\n\n  EX-stage mispredict logic (additive, behind new field):\n    - mispredict_taken  = in.ctrl.is_branch &  in.branch_pred_taken & !branch_cond;\n        // we predicted taken, actual is not-taken: redirect to pc+4\n    - mispredict_ntaken = in.ctrl.is_branch & !in.branch_pred_taken &  branch_cond;\n        // we did NOT predict, branch is actually taken: redirect to branch_target\n        //   (this is the EXISTING behavior — pre-hypothesis redirect arm)\n    - new redirect expression:\n        redirect = ( (mispredict_taken | mispredict_ntaken)\n                    | (in.ctrl.is_jump & !in.jal_predicted) )\n                    & !misalign_fault;\n    - redirect_target mux:\n        redirect_target =\n          in.ctrl.is_jump      ? jump_target :\n          mispredict_taken     ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\n                                 branch_target;       // covers both the\n                                 // \"predicted-taken & taken -> no redirect\"\n                                 // case (redirect is deasserted) AND the\n                                 // mispredict_ntaken case naturally.\n    - pc_next in the EX/MEM flop follows the same case split so rvfi's\n      pc_fwd chain stays consistent:\n        predicted-taken & taken   -> branch_target (architectural next PC)\n        predicted-taken & !taken  -> pc+4          (architectural next PC)\n        predicted-not & taken     -> branch_target\n        predicted-not & !taken    -> pc+4\n      misalign_fault still forces pc_next=pc+4 and ctrl.is_illegal=1, unchanged.\n\n  Why this should pass where r5s2 broke:\n    - No rename. `jal_predicted` plumbing is byte-identical to r4s2; diff is\n      strictly additive. A missed-consumer cascade cannot happen because the\n      new field has exactly one producer (id_br_pred_fire) and one consumer\n      (ex_stage's branch mispredict calc) — the same closed surface as r4s2.\n    - EX's existing branch redirect arm (redirect on branch_cond & is_branch)\n      is replaced by the `mispredict_ntaken` expression, which reduces to the\n      original behavior whenever branch_pred_taken=0 — so uninstrumented\n      (forward) branches keep bit-identical semantics. No trap-discipline\n      changes; misalign path is untouched.\n    - The RVFI pc_wdata / pc_rdata chain follows pc_next which remains\n      architecturally correct in all four cases, so the unique / pc_fwd /\n      liveness checks in riscv-formal keep passing.\n\n  Why this should help Fmax/IPC on GW2AR:\n    - Cone shape at ID: opcode compare (7-bit) + imm[31] + B-imm adder +\n      2-bit aligned check + !stall_id AND — structurally identical to the\n      r4s2 JAL cone (whose Fmax impact on this fabric was measured as\n      positive net, else r4s2 wouldn't have won +17.73%).\n    - EX cone: one new XOR + two-way AND for mispredict_taken / ntaken, and\n      a 3:1 mux on redirect_target. branch_cond was already computed in EX\n      on r4s2; the new logic is in parallel with the ALU, not in series.\n    - Storage: one bit of new pipeline-register state (branch_pred_taken).\n      No arrays, no tags, no LUT-RAM. LUT4 budget: well within the ~500 LUT\n      headroom (9484/10000 currently used post-r4s2).\n    - IPC: CoreMark backward-branch density × BTFN hit rate × 2 bubble\n      cycles saved ≈ 4-6% × 0.85 × 2 ≈ 7-10%. Even at a conservative 50%\n      hit rate on mixed kernels, the floor is ~4-5%.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `branch_pred_taken` (1 bit) as a new field in id_ex_t, placed next to the existing `jal_predicted` field. Do NOT rename `jal_predicted`. All other typedefs unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add one new input port `branch_pred_taken_in` (1 bit). Latch it into reg_q.branch_pred_taken when !stall (same gate as all other id_ex fields). Leave `jal_predicted_in` and its latch byte-identical to r4s2. Reset clears branch_pred_taken to 0.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Compute combinational id_is_back_branch / id_br_imm / id_br_target / id_br_target_aligned / id_br_pred_fire from if_id_w (mirror the shape of the existing id_is_jal / id_jal_target block). Extend the redirect wire: redirect = ex_redirect | id_is_jal_fire | id_br_pred_fire. Extend redirect_target as a 2-stage 2:1 priority chain: (1) id-side mux id_is_jal_fire?id_jal_target:id_br_target, (2) ex-wins top-level mux. Wire id_br_pred_fire to the new id_stage.branch_pred_taken_in port. hazard_unit still consumes only ex_redirect (unchanged — same reasoning as r4s2's hazard_unit comment).\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace the branch redirect arm with mispredict detection: mispredict_taken = is_branch & in.branch_pred_taken & !branch_cond (predict-taken miss -> redirect pc+4). mispredict_ntaken = is_branch & !in.branch_pred_taken & branch_cond (equivalent to the pre-hypothesis taken-branch redirect). redirect = ((mispredict_taken | mispredict_ntaken) | (is_jump & !jal_predicted)) & !misalign_fault. redirect_target 3:1 mux: is_jump ? jump_target : mispredict_taken ? (pc+4) : branch_target. Update reg_q.pc_next case split to reflect all four predicted×actual combinations so the RVFI pc_fwd chain stays consistent. misalign_fault path, ctrl.is_illegal propagation, and jump-target misalign logic are all byte-identical.\"\n  - file: test/test_predictor.py\n    description: \"New cocotb smoke test exercising all four predicted×actual combinations on conditional branches: (a) backward-BNE loop taken+predicted (hit, save 2 cycles), (b) backward-BNE loop-exit predicted-taken-but-actual-not-taken (mispredict_taken fires EX redirect to pc+4), (c) forward-BEQ taken (not predicted, mispredict_ntaken fires EX redirect — pre-hypothesis behavior preserved), (d) forward-BEQ not-taken (no redirect). Plus a misaligned backward-branch target case to confirm ID prediction is gated off and EX's existing misalign trap still fires. Assert rvfi_order strictly monotonic +1 and every retirement's pc_rdata == previous pc_wdata across the full sequence.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r6s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r6s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777788438400,"end":1777788438414}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_dec7223eb001THijiWXpKvjFA3","sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","messageID":"msg_dec721c2c001Mo8xvqGT3qOoh4"}}
