{"type":"text","timestamp":1777788446350,"sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","part":{"id":"prt_dec72cde4001nc9vrT2tHRclM7","messageID":"msg_dec72c7d60016hyp0Vps0AKqJs","sessionID":"ses_21390e43effe7wZOUlHQmWt2vM","type":"text","text":"Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r6s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary of the hypothesis:**\n\n**Title:** Zero-storage backward-branch prediction at ID, r4s2-pattern (additive, no rename)\n\n**Core idea:** Replay r5s2's concept (extend the winning r4s2 JAL fast-path to backward conditional branches via BTFN static prediction) but with strict plumbing discipline to avoid r5s2's cascade failure mode.\n\n**Three defensive discipline choices drawn from r5s2's lesson:**\n1. **No renames** — keep `jal_predicted` byte-identical to r4s2; add a new `branch_pred_taken` field alongside it. This makes the diff purely additive with a closed producer/consumer surface.\n2. **Priority-chain 2:1 muxes** for `redirect_target` rather than a 3:1 — same logical depth, better LUT4 packing on GW2AR, keeps `if_stage`'s PC-select mux structurally 2:1 (same as r4s2).\n3. **EX's new redirect arms reduce to the pre-hypothesis behavior** whenever `branch_pred_taken=0`, so forward branches stay bit-identical — eliminates the risk of unintentionally perturbing the working JAL/JALR paths.\n\n**Expected fitness delta:** +6% (conservative given predictor track record: 4/5 past attempts regressed or broke; the one win was +17.73%). Confidence: **low** because the category is fragile on this fabric even when the architectural concept is sound.","time":{"start":1777788440036,"end":1777788446346}}}
