{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777790044768,"sessionID":"ses_213776e64ffe7ty052I3JicAbi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_0116yM6et4hcfXPde48AbHrs","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"List existing hypothesis files"},"output":"hyp-20260503-001-r7s0.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260503-001-r7s0.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777790044764,"end":1777790044766}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the predictor attempts, I can see a clear pattern: static approaches that add complexity to the PC path or increase storage requirements tend to fail due to resource constraints, but the JAL-only fast-path succeeded by keeping things minimal. I should focus on a hypothesis that maintains this simplicity while targeting the specific bottleneck.\n\nThe key insight is that r4s2 won by resolving unconditional jumps one stage earlier without expanding the redirect network. Conditional branches failed because they widened the misprediction arm in the EX stage. So I need to find another unconditional case that doesn't require forwarding or add extra muxing pressure.\n\nLet me check what the current JAL detection logic looks like...\n\nExamining the JAL fast-path implementation...\n\nThe JAL detection is already happening combinationally from the instruction memory output, feeding directly into the PC mux on the fetch critical path. So pushing it earlier won't help. I'm back to exploring other predictor strategies—maybe a tiny tagless branch target buffer with just 2-4 entries, though even 16 entries failed in r2s2.\n\nActually, here's a different angle: a 1-entry JALR predictor that just remembers the last return target. CoreMark has lots of function returns via JALR, and if I could predict those at ID by storing the previous target in a single 32-bit register, I'd save a cycle per return. The catch is that JALR targets depend on rs1, so I can't compute them at ID—but I can guess the target is the same as last time. When the prediction is wrong, EX resolves and redirects normally, though that misprediction path is what caused problems in r6s2.\n\nThe key insight is that EX already redirects on JALR anyway, so a wrong prediction at ID doesn't add extra cost—the wrong-path instruction gets flushed by EX's normal redirect. But I need to track whether the JALR was predicted at ID so EX knows whether to redirect based on a mismatch between predicted and actual target, which means adding a `jalr_predicted` flag through the pipeline. For JAL, the redirect at ID stage lets the fetch move to the target immediately, and since JAL prediction is always correct, suppressing the EX redirect avoids an unnecessary flush. But for JALR with a 1-entry predictor, if the prediction is wrong, suppressing EX redirect means we'd miss the correction entirely. I'd need to compare the predicted and actual targets in EX to conditionally redirect, which adds a 32-bit comparison into the critical path and hurts timing.\n\nThe simpler realization is that the current approach already optimizes the JAL path by using imem_data directly in the combinational logic, so there's not much room to improve there. I'm now thinking about whether pre-computing the predicted-not-taken path could reduce the misprediction window in EX.\n\nActually, a more practical idea: implement a minimal 1-entry return address stack for JALR returns. When a JAL with rd=x1 (call instruction) fires at ID, I snapshot pc+4 into a single 32-bit register. Then when a JALR with rs1=x1 and rd=x0 (return instruction) appears at ID, I predict its target from that stored address and redirect immediately. This is essentially a 1-entry RAS that catches the common call-return pattern. The challenge is handling mispredictions—I'd need to check the actual target in EX and redirect if it doesn't match the prediction, which means adding another input to the PC mux and managing the rollback path. The core issue is that a 32-bit compare in the critical path would likely hurt Fmax. I'm exploring alternatives: suppressing EX redirect based solely on the prediction bit risks correctness, and trying to selectively flush only mismatched instructions requires the same expensive comparison. Even a 1-entry RAS with matching logic runs into the same wall. I'm considering different angles — maybe treating JAL with rd=x0 as an unconditional branch hint, or snooping forwarded rs1 values for JALR to reduce misprediction bubbles, or even dual-issuing JAL with the next instruction — but each approach either adds complexity or doesn't meaningfully improve the baseline 2-bubble penalty from EX redirect. The timing concern is real—adding a 32-bit comparison on top of the jump target computation and ALU results would require several more LUT levels, which could push the critical path beyond what the FPGA can handle at target frequency. Looking at CoreMark's return patterns, if I could eliminate the 2-cycle bubble on 80-90% of returns, that'd be a solid 8-16% IPC gain, but only if Fmax stays intact. Given how fragile previous attempts have been, I'm skeptical this 1-entry RAS approach is worth the risk. The current Fmax headroom above target suggests I should look elsewhere—maybe simplifying the JAL fast-path's misalignment check to free up timing budget, or reconsidering what the actual CoreMark performance metric is showing.\n\nReviewing the past attempts more carefully: r4s2 succeeded by folding the redirect onto existing wires without structural changes, but r5s2's extension to backward branches failed due to a missed consumer in the renamed field, and r6s2 regressed 23% despite being formally correct because the widened EX mux hit Fmax hard. The pattern is clear—any predictor that adds a mispredict arm to already-registered branches kills performance on this fabric. For JALR specifically, since EX already handles redirects for jump targets, I could predict in ID and carry the prediction through id_ex without adding a new mispredict arm, which might avoid the toxicity that killed previous attempts.\n\nBut the core problem emerges: to suppress the EX redirect when JALR prediction is correct, I need a 32-bit compare in EX, and that compare becomes new critical path depth. The alternative of always firing the EX redirect means correct predictions don't save anything—the fetch still gets flushed by the EX redirect firing anyway. Without suppression, there's no gain. With suppression, I'm adding expensive logic to the critical path. The only way forward is to move the compare earlier, to ID, between the predicted target and something computable there. The r4s2 approach wins because it reuses the existing redirect path without adding new mux inputs, keeps the combinational logic minimal, and requires no extra storage—just opcode decoding and immediate extraction. To find another winning predictor, I need something equally deterministic and architecturally sound that resolves earlier in the pipeline. I'm exploring whether JALR with rd=x0 (pure indirect jumps used for returns) could be predicted by caching the last JAL destination, though a single-entry cache breaks on nested calls, and other patterns like LUI+JALR fusion or JAL with zero offset seem too rare or complex to justify the added logic.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the alignment check on JAL—since the immediate always has bit 0 fixed to zero and the PC is always 4-aligned in RV32I, the target's bit 0 is guaranteed zero. But bit 1 of the target depends on whether the immediate's bit 1 is set, so a misaligned JAL is still possible and the check can't be eliminated entirely. However, I could decouple the alignment check from the redirect-fire gate itself, letting the JAL fire speculatively while handling misalignment separately.\n\nGiven how cheap the alignment check is and how few real JALs are actually misaligned, I'm pivoting to a different optimization: predicting return instructions (JALR x0, x1, 0) using a simple 1-entry link-address register with a narrow misprediction check that avoids adding critical path delay.\n\nThe mechanism stores the return address in a flop whenever JAL with rd=x1 executes, then detects the RET pattern at decode and redirects to that stored address. In execute, I'd compare the actual target against the predicted one to catch mismatches, but that comparison adds to the redirect cone—the same timing bottleneck I keep running into. I'm going to propose it anyway, arguing the compare can fit because the EX redirect path already has significant depth from the ALU operations.\n\nActually, let me try a different approach: what if I optimize the existing JAL fast-path itself by simplifying the alignment check? Since the immediate's bit 0 is always zero and the PC's bit 0 is always zero, I only need to check bit 1 of the target, which reduces to just checking bit 21 of the instruction—a trivial gate that might save a LUT level on the critical path.\n\nBut that's probably not worth the effort since the instruction comes directly from memory. Let me focus on something more impactful instead.\n\nThe real opportunity is using a simple one-entry implicit return-address stack for JALR prediction at the ID stage, but only when there's no RAW hazard on rs1. Since rs1 can be read from the register file with write-first bypass, I can compute the JALR target at ID most of the time—the only problem is when rs1 is currently being produced in the EX stage, which would require a stall. The JAL fast-path works because JAL doesn't depend on rs1, but JALR does, so I need to handle that dependency carefully.\n\nActually, adding a separate combinational path from the regfile through an adder to compute the JALR target and feed it into the PC mux would create a deep combinational cone right in the fetch-to-PC critical path. Combined with the hazard detection logic needed to stall on EX-stage rs1 producers, this is probably net negative for timing given how tight the fabric already is.\n\nLet me reconsider what's actually feasible. I'm wondering if there's a combinational loop issue with how the current JAL fast-path checks validity—it gates on `if_id_w.valid`, which excludes the case where `id_is_jal_fire` is true, but I need to verify that doesn't create a feedback problem.\n\nTracing through the logic: `id_is_jal` depends on `if_id_w.valid`, which depends on `flush_if`, which comes from `ex_redirect` and `imem_stall` only—not from `id_is_jal_fire`. So there's no loop. And when an EX redirect fires the same cycle as a JAL at ID, the EX redirect takes priority by clearing `if_id_w.valid` first, which prevents `id_is_jal` from firing. That's the right behavior.\n\nNow I'm thinking about how to optimize the JAL fast-path further. The aligned gate adds latency, and I could potentially eliminate it by using the fact that IALIGN=32 makes misaligned JALs detectable from a single bit. Or I could parallelize the JAL decode with the immediate generation to shorten the critical path. But I'm also wondering if there's a bigger win—maybe combining the JAL prediction with improvements to the EX branch resolve path to free up routing for future optimizations.\n\nActually, let me step back and consider something more concrete: a tiny 4-entry branch cache at the IF stage that predicts conditional backward branches. The trick would be placing it behind the IF/ID boundary so it doesn't lengthen the fetch-to-PC cone—using the flopped PC as the lookup key and latching the prediction into a register for consumption at ID. But that's complicated because by the time the prediction is available, the instruction is already fetched, so it doesn't really help.\n\nMaybe I should just go with a 1-entry link register for JALR return prediction, even though it risks Fmax, since CoreMark has many returns. But wait—I need to re-examine what the previous attempt actually failed on. The r2s2 report mentioned that a 4-entry RAS delivered 0% fitness because the ID-stage speculative redirect added a new id_redirect input to the PC-select mux, which likely created a timing bottleneck.\n\nThe key insight is that r4s2 works by reusing the existing redirect wire instead of adding a new one. So if I build a RAS variant that shares that same redirect path—the one already used by the JAL fast-path—it should have much less impact than r3s2's approach. I'm thinking of a 1-entry implicit return address register: a 32-bit flop plus a valid bit, written when JAL fires with rd=x1, and fired on JALR x0, x1, 0 detection by checking the opcode and register fields. The redirect arbitration would prioritize EX over JAL over return, and the EX stage would verify the prediction by comparing the actual jump target against what was predicted.\n\nThe comparison itself is the bottleneck though. I'm exploring whether I can avoid it by tracking whether x1 has been dirtied—any write to x1 outside the JAL fast-path invalidates the link register, so if the link is still valid when JALR executes, the prediction must be correct. But nested calls break this: an inner JAL x1 would update both x1 and the link register, so the outer function's return would use the wrong address. I'd need to distinguish between non-JAL writes to x1 (invalidate) and nested JAL writes (update), but then the inner return fires first and consumes the inner address, leaving the outer function stranded. of the performance gain for outer returns. For CoreMark, deeper call chains do exist but many hot loops avoid deep recursion, so predicting inner returns is still worthwhile. I'm sketching out the design: a 32-bit link_q register with a valid bit that captures the return address when JAL writes to x1, detects the return pattern (JALR x0, x1, 0) at ID stage, and invalidates the prediction whenever x1 is written by any non-JAL instruction—this keeps the prediction safe while preserving the speedup for actual nested returns. The tricky part is threading the ret_predicted signal through the pipeline so EX knows to suppress its normal redirect when we've already predicted the return.\n\nNow I'm verifying that suppression works without needing a full comparison: if link_valid_q is set, it means link_q holds the current value of x1, and since we invalidate on any other x1 write, the JALR's actual target (x1 + 0) will match our predicted target, so the suppression is safe.\n\nBut I need to think through the pipeline timing more carefully—when the JALR reaches EX, there could be instructions in flight that write x1 after the JAL but before the JALR in program order, and I need to make sure our invalidation logic catches those cases to maintain the invariant that link_valid_q=1 guarantees x1 hasn't been modified. Now I'm working through a tricky case where a JAL at ID stage fires the fast-path while an earlier instruction in id_ex has the same destination register—the JAL's snapshot of the new link value should win over the invalidation from the older instruction. Finally, I'm tallying up the hardware cost: a 32-bit link register, a valid bit, pattern-matching logic for JALR-ret detection, mux logic for updates, invalidation detection on the rd field, and an extra bit in the pipeline to track whether a prediction fired.\n\nThe total footprint is tiny—around 33 flip-flops and maybe 30 LUTs—with no growth in the PC-mux or EX target-mux fanin since we're reusing existing redirect wires. The combinational depth on the redirect path stays flat because the ret-detect logic runs in parallel with the JAL detection, both feeding through an OR gate. Fmax risk is low, and given CoreMark's 10-15% return density with shallow call stacks in hot kernels, I'm estimating a 3-8% IPC win. This approach looks very promising, so I'm ready to write up the hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec8b4a30001MLoNt4OSnSms2Q","sessionID":"ses_213776e64ffe7ty052I3JicAbi","messageID":"msg_dec88925a001smXoVSfhDSnQVY"}}
