{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777790088059,"sessionID":"ses_213776e64ffe7ty052I3JicAbi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01984JRyMqV7oh2QffMDHJyB","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r7s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r7s2\ntitle: \"Implicit 1-entry RAS via dirty-x1 tracking: cone-free JALR-ret fast-path\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The r4s2 JAL-only ID fast-path won (+17.73%) by folding the redirect onto the existing\n  `redirect`/`redirect_target` wire — zero storage, no new PC-mux input, no new EX\n  target-mux arm. Subsequent predictor extensions (r5s2/r6s2 backward-branch BTFN,\n  r3s2 4-entry RAS) regressed because each added either a mispredict arm to EX\n  (widening the 2:1 target mux to 3:1) or a new id_redirect input to the PC-select\n  priority mux. CoreMark has ~8–12% return-instruction density via `jalr x0, x1, 0`\n  that the JAL-only path does not accelerate — each return still eats 2 bubbles.\n\n  The key insight: if we can prove at prediction time that the predicted target\n  EQUALS the actual JALR target, EX-redirect suppression becomes unconditional (like\n  jal_predicted), eliminating the need for a 32-bit target compare in EX's redirect\n  cone. That proof is available for free via a \"dirty x1\" tracker that invalidates\n  the cached link whenever any non-fast-path writer targets x1.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 1-entry \"implicit return-address register\" consisting of a 32-bit `link_q`\n  and a 1-bit `link_valid_q`, plus an ID-stage RET detect that shares the existing\n  redirect wire (no new PC-mux input). Correctness invariant: `link_valid_q=1`\n  implies architectural x1 equals `link_q` — so a prediction fired off `link_q` is\n  guaranteed to match the JALR's actual computed target, and EX redirect for the\n  predicted JALR can be unconditionally suppressed (no compare needed).\n\n  Mechanism:\n    1. `link_q <= pc+4; link_valid_q <= 1` on cycles where the existing JAL fast-path\n       fires AND the JAL's rd == 5'd1 (i.e. a CALL). Reuses id_is_jal_fire — zero new\n       combinational cone added to that wire.\n    2. `link_valid_q <= 0` on any cycle where id_ex captures an instruction with\n       rd==1 && ctrl.reg_write && !jal_predicted && !ret_predicted (i.e. any non-\n       CALL writer of x1 entering the pipeline). This maintains the invariant.\n    3. At ID, detect RET = `(instr[6:0]==7'b1100111) & (instr[11:7]==5'd0) &\n       (instr[19:15]==5'd1) & (instr[14:12]==3'd0) & (instr[31:20]==12'd0)`.\n       `is_ret_fire = is_ret & if_id_w.valid & !stall_id & link_valid_q &\n                      (link_q[1:0]==2'b00)`.\n    4. Arbitrate: `redirect = ex_redirect | id_is_jal_fire | is_ret_fire;`\n       `redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_tgt : id_is_jal_fire ? jal_tgt : link_q`.\n       Priority order (EX > JAL > RET) preserves r4s2's semantics.\n    5. Add `ret_predicted` bit to id_ex_t (parallel to jal_predicted). EX masks its\n       redirect with `!(in.jal_predicted | in.ret_predicted)` — unconditional\n       suppression, no 32-bit compare on the redirect cone.\n\n  Why this is different from r3s2 (4-entry RAS regression):\n    - r3s2 added a new `id_redirect` input to if_stage's PC-select priority mux.\n      This design reuses the existing `redirect` wire (like r4s2).\n    - r3s2's mispredict handling kept EX redirect armed (PC-select mux fanin grew).\n      This design relies on the dirty-x1 invariant to make suppression unconditional —\n      same shape as jal_predicted.\n    - r3s2 was 4-entry (130 FF / 75 LUT). This is 1-entry (33 FF + ~20 LUT for\n      compare + invalidation logic).\n\n  Why this is different from r5s2/r6s2 (BTFN regressions):\n    - BTFN added a 3:1 redirect_target mux in EX (need pc+4 arm for predicted-\n      taken-but-actual-not-taken). This design keeps EX's target mux 2:1 — JALR's\n      mispredict arm continues to route via the existing branch/jump cone only\n      when ret_predicted=0 (i.e. the fast-path didn't fire).\n    - BTFN's cone in ID required B-imm gen + 32-bit adder + funct3 legality gate.\n      This design's RET detection is a 20-bit equality check on the instruction\n      word (mostly single-LUT reduction), shorter than even the JAL opcode compare.\n\n  Expected IPC impact: CoreMark hot paths include ~8–12% returns; of those, the\n  inner-function returns between x1 dirties (the majority in shallow call chains,\n  and CoreMark's matrix/list kernels are ~1–2 deep in hot loops) get predicted.\n  Conservative estimate: 4–8% of returns predicted, saving 1 cycle each vs. the\n  current 2-cycle EX-redirect penalty → ~3–6% IPC win.\n\n  Expected Fmax impact: near-zero. The added cone on the existing `redirect` wire\n  is (instr[11:7]==0 && instr[19:15]==1 && instr[14:12]==0 && instr[31:20]==0 &&\n  instr[6:0]==0x67) & valid & !stall_id & link_valid_q & !link_q[1] — roughly one\n  6-LUT reduction in parallel with id_is_jal's existing cone. The OR merge with\n  id_is_jal_fire adds at most one level to the `redirect` net. The link_q update\n  is purely register-to-register (no path on the fetch-to-PC cone). `ret_predicted`\n  in id_ex feeds EX's redirect mask with the same profile as jal_predicted.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `ret_predicted` bit to id_ex_t struct (parallel to existing jal_predicted field) so the ret-fast-path fire can propagate through ID/EX to mask EX's would-be-redundant redirect.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Declare `link_q[31:0]` and `link_valid_q` flops. Add RET-pattern detect (`is_ret`, `is_ret_fire`) combinationally. Extend `redirect` to `ex_redirect | id_is_jal_fire | is_ret_fire` and `redirect_target` priority mux to include link_q as lowest-priority arm. Add clocked update: on id_is_jal_fire && rd==5'd1, snapshot link_q <= if_id_w.pc + 4 and set link_valid_q. On id_ex-capture of a non-JAL/non-RET instruction with rd==1 && reg_write, clear link_valid_q. Wire is_ret_fire into the id_stage port as `ret_predicted_in` alongside `jal_predicted_in`.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add `ret_predicted_in` input port (mirrors jal_predicted_in). Capture into reg_q.ret_predicted on non-stall cycles; clear on reset/flush.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend the redirect mask to `!(in.jal_predicted | in.ret_predicted)`: `redirect = (branch_taken || (in.ctrl.is_jump && !(in.jal_predicted | in.ret_predicted))) && !misalign_fault`. No change to redirect_target mux (stays 2:1 jump_target/branch_target). No change to EX's arithmetic cone.\"\n  - file: test/test_ret_predictor.py\n    description: \"Cocotb unit test: verify (1) JAL rd=x1 snapshots link_q=pc+4 and sets link_valid_q; (2) subsequent `jalr x0, x1, 0` at ID fires is_ret_fire, redirects fetch to link_q, and captures ret_predicted=1 in id_ex; (3) EX masks its JALR redirect on that instruction; (4) an intervening `addi x1, x1, k` clears link_valid_q and suppresses the fast-path; (5) misaligned link_q (link_q[1]=1) suppresses fire; (6) stall_id suppresses fire (re-evaluates next cycle); (7) EX redirect wins priority when both ex_redirect and is_ret_fire assert same cycle.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r7s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r7s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777790088054,"end":1777790088058}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm exploring an implicit return address stack approach using dirty-tracking instead of explicit management. The design uses 32-bit and 1-bit flops to store the link address and validity, updates them on JAL instructions with rd=x1, and invalidates the valid bit whenever any non-JAL instruction executes.\n\nAt the ID stage, I'll detect the RET pattern (JALR x0, x1, 0) and fire a redirect to the stored link address if it's valid and aligned, passing a prediction bit through the pipeline. In EX, I can safely suppress the normal JALR redirect when this prediction fires, since the invalidation invariant guarantees x1 matches the stored value at prediction time—no expensive 32-bit comparison needed. This reuses the existing redirect arbitration logic and costs roughly 33 flip-flops plus minimal LUT area.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec8b73ec001PQMAeKnGmL5mhj","sessionID":"ses_213776e64ffe7ty052I3JicAbi","messageID":"msg_dec8b56bd001ohHvA2yzD2biPB"}}
