{"type":"text","timestamp":1777790094027,"sessionID":"ses_213776e64ffe7ty052I3JicAbi","part":{"id":"prt_dec8bf99800158AbIhQRK6CTTG","messageID":"msg_dec8bf3b1001ZX8pi1MWM7YBgR","sessionID":"ses_213776e64ffe7ty052I3JicAbi","type":"text","text":"I've written the hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r7s2.yaml`.\n\n**Core idea**: 1-entry \"implicit RAS\" that shares the r4s2-winning pattern. The critical trick is the **dirty-x1 invariant**: `link_valid_q=1` ⇒ architectural x1 == link_q. That makes EX-redirect suppression unconditional (no 32-bit compare in EX), avoiding exactly the two failure modes from prior predictor attempts:\n\n- **r3s2 (4-entry RAS, regression)**: added new `id_redirect` input to PC-select mux. This design reuses the existing `redirect` wire like r4s2.\n- **r6s2 (BTFN backward branches, -23.51%)**: widened EX's redirect_target 2:1→3:1. This design keeps EX's target mux 2:1; `ret_predicted` just masks EX redirect with the same shape as jal_predicted.\n\n**Cost budget**: 33 FF + ~20 LUT (vs. r3s2's 130 FF / 75 LUT that delivered 0%).\n\n**IPC target**: CoreMark has ~8–12% returns; dirty-tracking lets us predict the inner-return subset (shallow call chains in hot kernels) — conservatively 3–6% IPC gain at 1 cycle saved per hit.","time":{"start":1777790089624,"end":1777790094026}}}
