{"type":"text","timestamp":1777792054136,"sessionID":"ses_2135add1dffeUKxS3GwWxQAvhl","part":{"id":"prt_deca92b04002w37S37u4QiU8AY","messageID":"msg_deca91f91001LP1TanCCb2I97K","sessionID":"ses_2135add1dffeUKxS3GwWxQAvhl","type":"text","text":"Now I'll write my predictor hypothesis. Key design choices:\n1. Preserve r4s2's winning recipe (unconditional, shared 2:1 redirect wire, no new PC-mux input, no EX mispredict arm)\n2. Avoid r7s0's tarpit: no id_ex_t struct rename (add only new top-level wires/flops, not fields in existing structs)\n3. Move the JAL 32-bit adder off the combinational ID→PC-D-in cone by pre-registering `jal_target` at IF","time":{"start":1777792002820,"end":1777792054136}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777792054140,"sessionID":"ses_2135add1dffeUKxS3GwWxQAvhl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01AZsiGC4ASF2crtgEP3RGbS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r8s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r8s2\ntitle: \"Pre-register JAL target at IF to lift the 32-bit adder off the ID redirect cone\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The r4s2 JAL fast-path is the one predictor that won on this fabric\n  (+17.73%). Every subsequent predictor variant regressed because it\n  violated at least one of the winning constraints: no new PC-mux\n  input (r1s2), no storage+tag array pulling LUT area (r2s2), no new\n  ID-side fire-term with a misprediction arm widening the EX redirect\n  mux past 2:1 (r6s2, r7s2), no id_ex_t struct rename (r7s0).\n\n  What r4s2 did NOT eliminate, though, is a 32-bit adder sitting on\n  the ID→PC-D-in combinational cone. In core.sv today:\n\n      id_jal_target  = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm;         // <-- 32b adder\n      redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_target : id_jal_target;\n      // if_stage: PC_D = redirect ? redirect_target : pc+4;\n\n  On each cycle where a JAL is in ID, the PC register's D-input cone\n  passes through PC_reg → if_id_w.pc → 32-bit carry-chain add → 2:1\n  mux (ex_redirect select) → 2:1 mux (redirect select) → PC_D. The\n  carry chain dominates this arm. On near-full GW2AR (9484/10000\n  LUT4), congestion-amplified routing around the carry chain is\n  exactly the sort of thing that nudges Fmax down — and r4s2's win\n  confirms Fmax-side gains are available on the fetch-redirect net.\n\n  Crucially, the adder's operands both resolve to flop outputs at the\n  clock edge starting cycle N: PC_reg is already flopped; J_imm is a\n  bit-permutation of imem_data which at cycle N is the Gowin BRAM\n  output (clock-to-Q of the BRAM, not a combinational chain). So the\n  adder can be RELOCATED to compute `jal_target_next = pc + J_imm`\n  during cycle N-1 (when the JAL is still in IF) and registered into\n  a new `jal_target_q` flop on the N-1→N edge. At cycle N the JAL is\n  in ID and `jal_target_q` is a ready flop output — feeding the\n  redirect_target mux with ZERO adder levels in the ID→PC cone.\n\n  IPC is UNCHANGED (redirect still fires on the same cycle as r4s2,\n  1 fetch bubble per taken JAL). The win, if any, is pure Fmax from\n  shortening the ID→PC critical arm by one 32-bit carry chain.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add IF-stage JAL predecode with registered target. Specifically:\n\n  1. In `rtl/if_stage.sv`, add two new output ports:\n        output logic        jal_pred_q,\n        output logic [31:0] jal_target_q\n     Compute combinationally inside if_stage:\n        jal_imm_pd     = {{11{imem_data[31]}}, imem_data[31],\n                          imem_data[19:12],   imem_data[20],\n                          imem_data[30:21],   1'b0};\n        jal_pred_next  = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111) && !flush && !stall;\n        jal_target_nxt = pc + jal_imm_pd;   // <-- the 32-bit adder\n     Register both into new flops (`jal_pred_q`, `jal_target_q`) on the\n     clock edge, clearing on reset or redirect.\n\n  2. In `rtl/core.sv`, replace the current ID-stage fast-path\n     computation:\n        id_jal_imm     = {...};                 // delete\n        id_is_jal      = (if_id_w.instr[6:0] == 7'b1101111) & if_id_w.valid;\n        id_jal_target  = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm;   // <-- adder on cone\n        id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00);\n     with the pre-registered version:\n        id_is_jal      = jal_pred_q;            // flop output\n        id_jal_target  = jal_target_q;          // flop output\n        id_jal_aligned = (jal_target_q[1:0] == 2'b00);   // bit-compare only\n\n  3. The downstream wires are UNCHANGED:\n        id_is_jal_fire  = id_is_jal & !stall_id & id_jal_aligned;\n        redirect        = ex_redirect | id_is_jal_fire;\n        redirect_target = ex_redirect ? ex_redirect_target : id_jal_target;\n     So the PC-select mux stays 2:1, the redirect wire is still the\n     same one, and EX still masks its own redundant redirect via the\n     existing `jal_predicted` bit in id_ex_t (r7s0-safe: NO struct\n     rename, NO new id_ex_t field — we're only moving where the\n     combinational adder lives, not changing any packed-struct\n     layout).\n\n  4. The `jal_target_q` flop loads every cycle the IF stage advances\n     (i.e., !stall), using imem_data as-if-it-were-a-JAL. The\n     `jal_pred_q` flop qualifies it. On redirect or flush or reset,\n     `jal_pred_q` clears to 0 (so a wrong-path pre-decoded JAL from\n     a squashed fetch cannot fire a rogue redirect). This is a 33 FF\n     addition (32 target bits + 1 valid bit), about 0.3% of the\n     current FF budget (1861) — negligible vs. the r2s2 BTB's 928 FFs\n     that still netted ~0%.\n\n  Why this should win, not regress:\n\n  - No new PC-mux input. The IF PC-select mux is still `redirect ?\n    redirect_target : pc+4`. (r1s2/r3s2/r7s2 all died on widening\n    this to 3+:1.)\n  - No widened EX redirect_target mux. The existing EX redirect arm\n    stays untouched; JAL retires in EX with `jal_predicted=1`, EX\n    suppresses its own redundant redirect, same as r4s2. (r6s2 died\n    on widening this to 3:1 for a mispredict arm.)\n  - No misprediction arm. JAL is unconditional — the prediction is\n    always correct. (r6s2/r7s2 tarpit.)\n  - No id_ex_t edit. The `jal_predicted` field remains as r4s2 set\n    it. (r7s0 tarpit.)\n  - No tags, no CAM, no BTB storage. Just two flops local to if_stage.\n    (r2s2 area tarpit.)\n  - The IF-side cone that GAINS the adder is: PC_reg (flop) →\n    imem-BRAM-read (clock-to-Q, ~3-4 ns on GW2AR) → J_imm\n    bit-permute (~0.2 ns, no carry) → 32-bit add (PC_reg + J_imm,\n    ~2.5 ns on GW2AR carry chain) → jal_target_q flop D-input. The\n    BRAM path is the dominant delay (it's also how imem_data reaches\n    the decoder + imm_gen cone feeding the id_ex register D-input).\n    The extra +J_imm adder is parallel with the existing decoder +\n    imm_gen + ctrl-sig fanout that already lives in the IF/ID→id_ex\n    setup budget, so if the id_ex register is setup-limited by\n    imem_data+decoder+imm_gen (the most common IF-side critical\n    path), the new adder is NOT on the worst arm of that cone.\n  - The ID-side cone that LOSES the adder is: PC_reg → if_id_w.pc\n    (comb) → +J_imm adder (carry chain) → 2:1 mux → 2:1 mux → PC_D.\n    Removing the adder here collapses that arm to: jal_target_q\n    (flop) → 2:1 mux → 2:1 mux → PC_D. That's a clean 1-LUT-level\n    reduction on the ID→PC-D cone. If this was an active Fmax\n    constraint after r4s2, this hypothesis captures the slack.\n\n  Equivalence proof (for formal / cosim):\n  - At cycle N-1, if IF stage sees imem_data=JAL at PC=P_jal with\n    !flush && !stall, then at cycle N: jal_pred_q=1,\n    jal_target_q = P_jal + J_imm.\n  - At cycle N, id_stage sees the JAL in if_id_w (since IF/ID is\n    combinational through if_stage's output). The old fast-path\n    computed id_jal_target = if_id_w.pc + id_jal_imm = P_jal +\n    J_imm. The new path reads jal_target_q = P_jal + J_imm. Same\n    value, same cycle.\n  - Squash conditions (reset, redirect, flush) clear jal_pred_q\n    to prevent wrong-path firing, mirroring if_stage's existing\n    `out.valid = !flush` guard that already zeroes if_id_w.valid\n    (which the old fast-path ANDed into id_is_jal).\n\n  Expected gain: small but positive — ~2-4% fitness. If ID→PC cone\n  was NOT the active Fmax limiter, gain ~0%. If it was, the Fmax\n  win lands cleanly. Risk: if the new IF-side adder path ends up\n  longer than the current decoder+imm_gen setup path, it could\n  tip IF-side critical — but PC_reg is already flopped and J_imm\n  assembly is a bit-permute with no carry, so the only carry chain\n  added is in parallel with the existing imm_gen carry chains\n  (J-type imm vs. I/S/B/U-type imm — imm_gen already has a case\n  mux over all imm forms; the J-type arm is the deepest, so\n  adding a SECOND J-type computation in parallel should not\n  extend it further — both complete in roughly the same time).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add two new outputs: jal_pred_q (1 bit) and jal_target_q (32 bits). Internally compute jal_imm_pd (J-type immediate from imem_data bits), jal_target_nxt = pc + jal_imm_pd, jal_pred_next = (imem_data[6:0]==7'b1101111) && !flush && !stall. Register both into new flops, clearing on reset or redirect (so a squashed wrong-path JAL predecode cannot fire in the next cycle). Existing if_id_t output (pc/instr/valid) unchanged. PC-update always_ff unchanged. No change to IO contract on top-level — these are new internal ports consumed only by core.sv.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Replace the ID-stage JAL fast-path combinational computation with consumption of the new flopped outputs from if_stage. Delete id_jal_imm assignment, change id_jal_target / id_is_jal / id_jal_aligned to read from u_if.jal_target_q and u_if.jal_pred_q. The redirect / redirect_target / id_is_jal_fire expressions downstream stay bit-identical. No change to any other module instantiation, hazard_unit/forward_unit wiring, or RVFI generation. id_ex_t.jal_predicted bit continues to be driven by id_is_jal_fire via id_stage (unchanged).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb test that exercises (a) a JAL followed immediately by another JAL — the predecode flop must latch the second JAL correctly the cycle after the first JAL's redirect, (b) a JAL in a flush cycle (redirect from EX branch mispredict on same edge) — jal_pred_q must NOT fire on the wrong-path JAL, (c) a JAL whose target is misaligned — id_jal_aligned must still gate id_is_jal_fire to 0 (EX trap path handles the misaligned JAL via misalign_fault as before). Also verify rvfi_order still increments monotonically across JAL-heavy sequences with no gaps or duplicates.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r8s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r8s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777792054135,"end":1777792054139}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I've identified the pattern, so I'm moving forward with my hypothesis using the IF-stage registered JAL predecode as the predictor slot.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deca9323c001p6VELeVTSwnjoP","sessionID":"ses_2135add1dffeUKxS3GwWxQAvhl","messageID":"msg_deca91f91001LP1TanCCb2I97K"}}
