{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777792803482,"sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","part":{"id":"prt_decb56296001y54yN9OwFOs5Az","messageID":"msg_decb54245001sGcU7ulnRhfDGq","sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","snapshot":"42cf8aaa8177ab1e0cdc49de9d85ca998dd45d78","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777792946129,"sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_017ddt7DgQWg78aF3fcEe11Y","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/rtl/core.sv","offset":110,"limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/rtl/core.sv</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n110:   // resolved one pipeline stage earlier than EX. See hypothesis\n111:   // \"Zero-storage JAL fast-path\" — the PC register's D-input mux stays\n112:   // 2:1; we only add a small 2:1 on the redirect-target upstream of it.\n113:   logic        id_is_jal;\n114:   logic [31:0] id_jal_imm;\n115:   logic [31:0] id_jal_target;\n116:   logic        id_jal_aligned;\n117:   logic        id_is_jal_fire;\n118: \n119:   // Combined redirect wire fed into if_stage. EX wins on any conflict\n120:   // (EX's in-flight instruction is architecturally older, and the\n121:   // hazard_unit's flush_if/flush_id already consume ex_redirect so the\n122:   // JAL in IF/ID will be observed as invalid this cycle anyway).\n123:   logic        redirect;\n124:   logic [31:0] redirect_target;\n125: \n126:   // regfile interface (driven by ID + WB stages)\n127:   logic [4:0]  rs1_addr_w;\n128:   logic [4:0]  rs2_addr_w;\n129:   logic [31:0] rs1_data_w;\n130:   logic [31:0] rs2_data_w;\n131:   logic        wb_w_en;\n132:   logic [4:0]  wb_w_addr;\n133:   logic [31:0] wb_w_data;\n134: \n135:   // ── ID-stage JAL fast-path combinational logic ────────────────────────\n136:   // JAL is unconditional and fully determined at decode: target = PC +\n137:   // imm_j, no rs dependency, no branch condition. We replicate the\n138:   // J-type imm arm of imm_gen here (rather than feeding imm_gen's full\n139:   // output mux into the redirect cone) so the new path is just\n\n(Showing lines 110-139 of 341. Use offset=140 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"  // resolved one pipeline stage earlier than EX. See hypothesis\n  // \"Zero-storage JAL fast-path\" — the PC register's D-input mux stays\n  // 2:1; we only add a small 2:1 on the redirect-target upstream of it.\n  logic        id_is_jal;\n  logic [31:0] id_jal_imm;\n  logic [31:0] id_jal_target;\n  logic        id_jal_aligned;\n  logic        id_is_jal_fire;\n\n  // Combined redirect wire fed into if_stage. EX wins on any conflict\n  // (EX's in-flight instruction is architecturally older, and the\n  // hazard_unit's flush_if/flush_id already consume ex_redirect so the\n  // JAL in IF/ID will be observed as invalid this cycle anyway).\n  logic        redirect;\n  logic [31:0] redirect_target;\n\n  // regfile interface (driven by ID + WB stages)\n  logic [4:0]  rs1_addr_w;\n  logic [4:0]  rs2_addr_w;\n  logic [31:0] rs1_data_w;","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/rtl/core.sv","time":{"start":1777792946105,"end":1777792946126}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the predictor performance data from these benchmark runs, I'm noticing that the static branch predictor shows a significant performance hit at -11.64%, while both the BTB and RAS implementations report zero impact—which suggests they're either not being exercised much in this workload or the fabric constraints aren't being triggered. I should focus my hypothesis on what's actually causing the static predictor's degradation and whether the other predictors might have latent issues that aren't surfacing yet.\n\nThe JAL fast-path approach is clearly the winner at +17.73% because it avoids storage overhead entirely by reusing existing redirect infrastructure, but I'm now exploring whether I can extend this pattern to handle JALR in specific cases—though pulling the regfile cone for rs1 dependency would likely kill the timing benefit. I'm also considering a next-PC register bypass approach, but I need to think through whether that creates new critical paths or conflicts with the existing redirect multiplexer constraints. I'm exploring whether JALR with rs1=x0 could resolve at ID by checking the instruction bits directly, since that case semantically becomes a JAL—but this optimization is probably rare in CoreMark anyway. I'm also wondering if there's a way to retire JAL instructions earlier than the normal 4-cycle pipeline, though I'm not sure that's feasible.\n\nLooking back at the constraints: I have about 516 LUT4s left in my budget, so a small predictor is still possible. The BTB approach from r2s2 didn't help despite being architecturally sound, so I'm thinking much smaller—maybe just a single-entry loop back-edge cache that tracks the last taken branch target.\n\nBut that runs into the same redirect-path sharing issue that caused the r6s2 regression. I've also considered predicting store-hazard forwarding, but that's not really a predictor. The ID-stage fast-path for unconditional branches like `BEQ x0, x0` is already handled by the JAL pseudo-instruction mapping. I'm exploring a minimal 4-entry saturating counter table indexed by PC bits, read from the flopped PC register at ID stage so it doesn't load the critical path, with the prediction consumed alongside the existing JAL fast-path.\n\nThe problem is that adding a second redirect arm for predicted-taken branches widens the ID cone and causes the same -23.51% regression we saw before. So instead of predicting, maybe I should focus on reducing the cost of a mispredict—currently 2 bubbles when the branch resolves at EX. If I could resolve the condition at ID instead, that saves a bubble, but operands aren't available until the regfile or forwarding paths deliver them, which would require adding a new forwarding path back to ID. For branches that read directly from the regfile without needing forwarding, I could theoretically resolve at ID, but detecting which ones need forwarding and adding the compare logic would bloat the ID critical path.\n\nI've ruled out store-unit stride prefetching as too expensive, and the link-register variant already regressed in r8s2. Given the hard constraints on not widening id_ex_t or the redirect multiplexer, I need to find something that actually fits.\n\nThere's an interesting edge case: when both operands of a BEQ are the same register (rs1_addr == rs2_addr), the branch is always taken—it's semantically a JAL. A simple 5-bit address compare at ID could catch this for free and convert it into a fast unconditional path. But GCC already emits these as `j` pseudo-instructions using JAL, not BEQ, so this wouldn't help CoreMark.\n\nNow exploring whether a return address predictor could work without the area penalties that killed the dirty-x1 RAS attempt. The core problem is that any second predictor arm either widens redirect_target or appends to id_ex_t, both of which regressed performance. A RAS would need to detect JAL returns at WB instead of ID, avoid sharing the redirect mux, and somehow not add a second predictor arm—but that seems to contradict the whole design. Looking at whether there's a truly novel prediction angle that doesn't hit these architectural constraints.\n\nConsidering load-use prediction as an alternative domain, though zero-detect bypass would require complex rollback logic. Most other ideas either duplicate what the existing JAL fast-path already does naturally, or push into fmax territory like precomputing targets or merging the alignment check into the decoder itself.\n\nActually, I realize the alignment check can be simplified dramatically: since PC is always 4-aligned by hardware (maintained through reset and +4 increments, with redirects validated), the JAL target's alignment depends only on the immediate's lower bits, which are hardcoded in the instruction encoding—specifically, `id_jal_aligned` reduces to just checking a single bit from the instruction rather than computing a full comparison. This is a small optimization but it does tighten the JAL fast-path's critical path.\n\nHowever, the adder for computing `id_jal_target` still runs in parallel since it feeds the actual redirect target, so while the alignment gate gets faster, the overall critical cone to the PC mux is still dominated by that 32-bit addition. so maybe it's acceptable since it's specifically about the JAL predictor cone. Let me reconsider the framing — this is really about tightening the JAL fast-path by replacing the adder-output alignment check with a direct instruction-bit check, which keeps it squarely in the predictor category. On GW2AR, the gate from `!instr[21]` might not even be the critical path, so Fmax gains could be zero, but the logic is strictly simpler so it shouldn't regress. This feels safer than the other predictor ideas since it doesn't touch `id_ex_t`, doesn't widen `redirect_target`, and doesn't add new PC-mux inputs. I'm also wondering if there are other similar simplifications in the JAL fast-path — the 7-bit opcode compare is hard to reduce, and partial opcode checks risk false positives. Let me think about an alternate approach instead.\n\nWhat if I remove the alignment gate entirely and let EX handle misalignment? If JAL always fires the fast-path redirect at ID, and the target is misaligned, the JAL propagates through ID/EX and EX's misalign_fault path sets `is_illegal` and redirects PC linearly. But since the PC was already redirected to the misaligned target, IF is now fetching from a misaligned address, which triggers another misaligned trap — this cascades awkwardly, so I should skip this approach.\n\nI'm also considering whether a static sign-bit branch predictor that resolves at EX instead of ID could work, but the speedup only comes from earlier PC redirect, which would still need to happen at ID or IF anyway.\n\nAnother angle: computing branch conditions at ID using regfile read data directly, but this creates forwarding hazards if preceding instructions haven't written back yet. We'd need either stalling (loses IPC) or ID-level forwarding (complex), and past experiments show ID-side branch resolution regressed performance significantly.\n\nSo I'm settling on the simplest fix: tighten the JAL fast-path alignment check to `!instr[21]` instead of the full target address check. But I need to verify these are actually equivalent — the original check was `id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00`, which only matches the new form when `pc[1:0] == 2'b00`. If PC could be 2-aligned but not 4-aligned, there's a mismatch I need to think through.\n\nTracing through the PC flow: reset gives aligned PC, then either we redirect (which is suppressed on misalignment faults) or advance by 4, so PC should always stay aligned. When we do redirect from a JAL, it only fires if `id_jal_aligned=1`, meaning the target is 4-aligned, and since the immediate has `imm_j[1:0]=2'b00` when `instr[21]=0`, the target's lower bits match the PC's lower bits.\n\nBy induction, the invariant holds—PC stays aligned throughout execution. The question is whether Yosys already optimizes this away or if removing the adder-dependent check actually saves gate depth. The fitness gain from r4s2 was +17.73%, but that's the full fast-path benefit; the actual delta from this specific change is probably 1-3%, possibly even 0% if the optimizer already caught it.\n\nI'm torn on confidence here—the logic is sound but the practical gain is unclear. Let me think about whether there's a more aggressive predictor move that could actually move the needle.\n\nThe pattern is clear: only zero-storage predictors survive, only JAL works, everything else regresses. What if JAL could fire one cycle earlier, at IF instead of ID? The challenge is that r1s2 tried combinational IF-stage prediction and regressed despite the theory being sound—it added too much logic to the critical path. But what if I could do it cleaner, without the extra adders and muxes that r1s2 added? The current PC mux is already 2:1; could I transform it into something that detects JAL combinationally and routes the target directly without bloating the path?\n\nActually, stepping back—the current JAL fast-path fires at ID with one bubble between the JAL and its target instruction. Moving to IF would eliminate that bubble entirely. But both r1s2 and r8s2 tried IF-stage variants and both regressed, so the fmax hit isn't worth it. I'm going to stick with tightening the existing alignment check instead—minimal risk, minimal reward, but safe.\n\nThough one more angle: I could simplify the JAL detection logic itself by checking just the unique bit pattern of the JAL opcode rather than doing a full comparison, which might reduce the select cone feeding into the PC mux.\n\nBut wait, if I only check bits [6:2] and skip [1:0], I'd accidentally fire on illegal compressed-like encodings where those lower bits aren't 2'b11. The full 7-bit opcode check is necessary to avoid that false positive.\n\nActually, there's a more interesting optimization: instead of computing the full 32-bit JAL target in the adder and then checking if the lower 2 bits are zero, I could just look at bit 21 of the instruction directly—that bit determines whether the target is 4-byte aligned. This would cut the adder out of the critical path entirely, which is a real win.\n\nThe adder itself is still needed to compute the actual target address, but removing it from the redirect signal's dependency chain could save a couple LUT levels, especially on hardware with carry-chain latency like the GW2AR.\n\nNow I'm weighing whether to also propose eliminating the alignment check entirely and letting misaligned JALs trap in the execute stage instead. That would remove even the instruction bit check, but it changes behavior—the ID stage would redirect to a misaligned address, fetch from it, and trigger cascading misalignment traps rather than catching it early. Let me trace through what happens in each case to see if the tradeoff is worth it.\n\nIf I remove the alignment gate and always fire the ID fast-path redirect, the PC gets set to a misaligned target before the execute stage can trap it. By the time the misalignment fault is detected and the instruction is marked illegal, the next cycle's fetch is already reading from that misaligned address. This breaks riscv-formal's PC forwarding check—the retired instruction says the next PC should be pc+4, but the actual next fetch came from a misaligned address. So I can't remove the alignment gate without breaking formal verification.\n\nI could try tightening `id_jal_aligned` to a pure logic check, but the SBY flow is extremely sensitive to any changes in the fetch-redirect cone—even minor restructures have caused formal to fail before. The safer approach might be to register the JAL-aligned signal from IF to ID, computing it directly from the instruction bits rather than relying on the adder output. But that still leaves the target computation running at ID, which creates its own issues. I'm exploring whether there's a completely orthogonal solution that avoids touching the redirect path altogether.\n\nActually, I could pre-decode the JAL signals at IF using the raw instruction data, then flop that hint into ID as a gate for the redirect logic. But looking at the actual datapath, `if_id_w.instr` is already just a direct passthrough of `imem_data` (with flush logic), so there's no real critical path benefit to moving the detection earlier. Given that, I think I should just accept the risk and go with the simplest change: `id_jal_aligned = !if_id_w.instr[21]`. It's local, logically sound, and the cleanest way forward. The hardware loop counter approach is too risky with state management and pipeline complexity. I'm confident in sticking with the JAL alignment simplification—it's a minimal logic change that should yield a modest 1–3% Fmax gain if the redirect path is near-critical, though the actual impact could be negligible given fabric uncertainty. I'll set the confidence to low and estimate a 2% delta, then write up the YAML proposal.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decb78a3b001oc63174UL2Oesu","sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","messageID":"msg_decb54245001sGcU7ulnRhfDGq"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777792946346,"sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","part":{"id":"prt_decb78323001dH3VPbpq8HTuCY","messageID":"msg_decb54245001sGcU7ulnRhfDGq","sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons carefully, the predictor landscape is harsh:\n- r4s2 (**+17.73%** JAL fast-path at ID) is the only winner — zero-storage, shares existing redirect net, 2:1 mux stays 2:1\n- r5s2, r6s2, r7s2, r8s2 all regressed or broke trying to extend r4s2 (adding predictor arms, widening redirect_target past 2:1, moving adders to IF)\n- r8s0 proved even purely-local restructuring of the fetch-redirect cone can hit the `no_checks_generated` SBY tarpit\n- r7s0 proved id_ex_t edits are formal-unsafe\n\nSo the only \"safe\" predictor move is to *tighten* the existing JAL fast-path without widening id_ex_t or redirect_target. Let me check the critical cone for opportunity.","time":{"start":1777792942883,"end":1777792946343}}}
