{"type":"text","timestamp":1777792982714,"sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","part":{"id":"prt_decb7b72d0017ffEcDTTiWsVdQ","messageID":"msg_decb79100001j9iFz4RRnCfopn","sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","type":"text","text":"My analysis of the critical cone:\n\nCurrent `id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)` — this forces a 32-bit adder output into the `redirect` (PC-mux select) cone. But given:\n- J-type imm has hardcoded `imm[0]=1'b0` and `imm[1]=instr[21]` (from the imm construction)\n- PC[1:0]=2'b00 is a hardware invariant (reset → all redirect paths are alignment-gated)\n\nThen `id_jal_target[1:0] = pc[1:0] + imm[1:0] = 2'b00 + {instr[21], 1'b0}`, so `id_jal_target[1:0]==2'b00` ⟺ `instr[21]==0`. The alignment check can be rewritten as `!instr[21]` — a single bit test off the raw instruction word, removing the adder from the `redirect` select cone entirely (the adder still feeds `redirect_target` data, which is parallel-timed with the select).\n\nThis is a pure logic simplification — same truth table given the invariant — and structurally the smallest possible edit to the r4s2 fast-path. It doesn't widen `redirect_target` past 2:1, doesn't touch `id_ex_t`, doesn't add a predictor arm, doesn't flop anything. The risk is the r8s0 formal tarpit on fetch-redirect cone edits, but this is a gate-signal simplification (not a `redirect_target` restructure like r8s0).","time":{"start":1777792956205,"end":1777792982713}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777792982729,"sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01AyWswgyz39C1DdoFT6c5J9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r9s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r9s2\ntitle: \"Strip JAL-target adder from redirect-select cone via direct instr[21] alignment test\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The r4s2 JAL fast-path (+17.73%) is the only predictor move that has\n  ever won on this core. Every attempted extension has regressed (r5s2\n  BEQ-backward broken, r6s2 BTFN -23.5%, r7s2 RAS -50%, r8s2 IF-stage\n  predecode -13.25%) because each adds either a second ID-side predictor\n  arm, a widened redirect_target mux, or an extra IF-side carry chain.\n  The remaining lever is NOT \"extend the predictor to more opcodes\" but\n  \"tighten the existing winning cone\". On GW2AR the r4s2 cone feeds two\n  consumers off the same id_jal_target 32-bit adder: (a) id_jal_target\n  itself drives the redirect_target 2:1 data mux (necessary), and (b)\n  id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00) drives the redirect\n  SELECT gate via id_is_jal_fire. Consumer (b) is the PC-register\n  D-input select cone, which on a near-full fabric (9484/10000 LUT4)\n  sits close to Fmax-critical; forcing a 32-bit adder's low-output\n  comparison into the select cone stacks carry-chain latency onto a\n  signal that should be pure combinational opcode+stall gating.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00) with\n  id_jal_aligned = !if_id_w.instr[21]. The two expressions are\n  provably equivalent under the hardware invariant PC[1:0]==2'b00:\n\n    - J-type imm construction has imm[0] hardcoded to 1'b0 and\n      imm[1] = instr[21]  (see core.sv:144 id_jal_imm).\n    - PC[1:0]==2'b00 holds by induction from reset (RESET_PC=0) and\n      is preserved by every redirect source: ex_redirect is gated on\n      !misalign_fault (target 4-aligned); id_is_jal_fire is gated on\n      the same id_jal_aligned being validated; pc+4 preserves 4-align.\n    - Therefore id_jal_target[1:0] = pc[1:0] + imm[1:0]\n                                   = 2'b00 + {instr[21], 1'b0}\n                                   = {instr[21], 1'b0}\n    - So (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00) iff (instr[21] == 1'b0),\n      which is !instr[21].\n\n  After the substitution, the critical cone for the `redirect` PC-mux\n  select signal becomes:\n\n    imem_data → instr[21]  (single wire, no logic)\n              → id_jal_aligned  (1 inverter)\n              → id_is_jal_fire  (AND with id_is_jal & !stall_id)\n              → redirect        (OR with ex_redirect)\n              → PC D-input mux select\n\n  The 32-bit id_jal_target adder STAYS (still drives redirect_target\n  data) but is now purely parallel to the select cone rather than\n  stacked inside it. id_jal_target is only read when the redirect_target\n  mux selects the JAL arm, and that data-path timing is independent of\n  the select-signal timing — this is the same shape r4s2 originally\n  framed as \"PC register's D-input mux stays 2:1\" but with the adder\n  fully off the select cone.\n\n  This change:\n    - does NOT widen redirect_target past 2:1 (same JAL vs EX arms)\n    - does NOT append to id_ex_t (no struct edits — r7s0 tarpit avoided)\n    - does NOT add a second ID-side predictor arm (r6s2 tarpit avoided)\n    - does NOT flop the target into IF (r8s2 tarpit avoided)\n    - does NOT touch regfile reset, MEM load-data cone, or JAL-link\n      mux (r4s0/r5s0/r5s1/r6s0/r6s1 tarpits avoided)\n    - does NOT touch `redirect_target`'s mux topology (r8s0 tarpit — the\n      edit here is on the gate signal `id_jal_aligned` only)\n\n  The expected Fmax gain is modest (1–3%) because we don't know\n  a priori whether the PC-mux select cone was the binding path on\n  GW2AR; if it wasn't, Yosys's arithmetic CSE might already have\n  lowered the adder's low-bit comparison close to a single LUT4, in\n  which case the delta approaches 0%. But the direction of effect is\n  structurally positive: removing a 32-bit carry-chain dependency from\n  a select signal cannot extend that signal's Fmax — at worst it is\n  already shorter and the change is a no-op, at best it shaves a\n  Gowin LUT4 level from the fetch-redirect critical net.\n\n  Implementation is exactly one line in core.sv. No test edits needed\n  — riscv-formal already checks JAL trap discipline on misaligned\n  targets via rvfi_pc_fwd, which this change preserves byte-for-byte\n  under the PC-alignment invariant.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: |\n      Replace the assignment `assign id_jal_aligned = (id_jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00);`\n      with `assign id_jal_aligned = !if_id_w.instr[21];`. Update the\n      surrounding comment block to note the PC[1:0]=2'b00 invariant and\n      why the instruction-bit form is equivalent. No other signals,\n      structs, or module ports change.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r9s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r9s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777792982709,"end":1777792982727}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm ready to write up the hypothesis now. My approach is to replace the JAL alignment check with a simpler bit extraction from the instruction, which should remove the 32-bit adder from the critical path for the PC multiplexer selection.\n\nThe key insight is that since PC is always 4-byte aligned and the immediate's lowest bit is hardcoded to zero, the alignment result depends only on instruction bit 21. This keeps the adder in the data path for computing the actual target address, but removes it from the timing-critical gate that decides whether to redirect at all.\n\nI'm aware this touches the fetch-redirect timing cone, which is tricky for formal verification, but the change is surgical—just replacing one gate signal, not restructuring the PC update logic. I'm estimating a modest 2% Fmax gain if this path was actually critical, though confidence is low given the formal verification risks and uncertainty about whether GW2AR even has this as a bottleneck.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_decb7c09d001lGuIBwPLskAG6B","sessionID":"ses_2134abeb0ffeyPZh47WsaheTu0","messageID":"msg_decb79100001j9iFz4RRnCfopn"}}
